description: This 1988 Porsche 911 Turbo cabriolet is a factory M505 slant nose example that was acquired by the current owner in 2007. It is powered by a turbocharged 3.3-liter flat-six paired with a four-speed manual transaxle and is finished in Guards Red over Champagne special leather. The car is equipped with a power-operated black soft top, a limited-slip differential, 17″ BBS wheels, air conditioning, a roll bar, a three-spoke steering wheel, and heated and power-adjustable seats. Work performed in preparation for the sale included adjusting the valves, recharging the air conditioning system, and replacing the oil cooler fan, spark plugs, and valve cover gaskets. This M505 930 Turbo is offered on dealer consignment with a Porsche Certificate of Authenticity, an owner’s manual, service records, a car cover, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The car is finished in Guards Red and is equipped with factory flachbau bodywork (M505), a package that featured pop-up headlights, vented front fenders, side strakes, and extended side sills. Additional equipment includes a black convertible soft top, fog lights, and twin exhaust outlets. The right windshield washer nozzle was replaced and the convertible top was repaired in preparation for the sale. Imperfections are highlighted in a document shown in the gallery below, which also includes photos of paint meter readings.

The 17″ BBS wheels are mounted with 225/45 front and 265/40 rear Michelin Pilot Sport tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel cross-drilled and ventilated discs. The brake hoses were replaced and the brake fluid was flushed in preparation for the sale.

The heated and power-adjustable front seats are upholstered in Champagne special leather and are complemented by a color-coordinated center console, carpeting, and door panels. Amenities include air conditioning, an analog clock, and power windows. A roll bar, metal pedals, Pioneer and JVC stereos, and an amplifier have been added, and the seller notes that an aftermarket alarm system is installed. The driver’s seat switch was replaced in 2023.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a central tachometer with a 6,700-rpm redline as well as a 170-mph speedometer and gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, oil level, fuel level, and boost pressure. The six-digit odometer shows 44k miles, approximately 4k of which were added under current ownership. The odometer drive gear was replaced in 2020, and total mileage is unknown.

The turbocharged 3.3-liter flat-six was factory rated at 282 horsepower and 278 lb-ft of torque. The battery was replaced in 2021. Service in preparation for the sale included performing an oil change, adjusting the valves, servicing the air conditioning system, and replacing the oil cooler fan, spark plugs, and valve cover gaskets.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. The clutch disc was replaced in 2018.
The Porsche Certificate of Authenticity lists colors, optional equipment, and a production completion date of December 2, 1987.
The Carfax report is free of accidents and other damage.
The car was designated a Gross Polluter by the State of California in 2016, and it last passed a California emissions test in June 2024.

This 2023 Porsche 718 Cayman GT4 RS is an Arctic Gray-finished example that has 58 miles and was optioned with the $13k Weissach Package. Powered by a 4.0-liter flat-six paired with a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle, that car has black and Deep Sea Blue upholstery, the Light Design Package, the Chrono Package, a front-axle lift system, 20″ forged magnesium wheels, a Bose sound system, carbon-fiber full bucket seats, carbon-fiber interior trim, a fire extinguisher, Porsche Communication Management, navigation, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This 718 Cayman GT4 RS was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024 and is now offered with an accident-free Carfax report and a clean Florida title.

The 718 GT4 RS features lightweight rear glass, vented front fenders, additional upper intakes, and a larger swan-neck rear wing when compared with the contemporary 718 GT4. Weissach Package-equipped cars are denoted by titanium tailpipes as well as exposed carbon-fiber weave on the hood, intakes, side mirror housings, and wing. This example is finished in Arctic Gray and is fitted with bi-xenon headlights, power-folding side mirrors, ParkAssist rear parking sensors, carbon-fiber window triangles, and integrated dual exhaust outlets exiting through the rear diffuser.

The 20″ forged magnesium wheels are mounted with staggered-width Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires. A front-axle lift system was optioned from the factory, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel dimpled and ventilated discs.

The carbon-fiber full bucket seats are upholstered in black leather with Deep Sea Blue Race-Tex inserts, “Weissach RS” headrest embroidery, blue seatbelts, and color-contrasting stitching that extends to the dashboard, center console, steering column, and door panels. Appointments include carbon-fiber trim, dual-zone automatic climate control, carbon-fiber illuminated door sill guards, a Bose sound system, Shark Blue door pulls, a fire extinguisher, and PCM infotainment with navigation. The optional Light Design Package added LED lighting in the overhead console, door handles, door storage compartments, footwells, and vanity mirrors.

The Race-Tex-wrapped steering wheel features a yellow centering stripe and fronts a central tachometer with a 9k-rpm redline flanked by a 200-mph speedometer and a configurable digital display. The optional Chrono Package added a stopwatch atop the dashboard. The digital odometer indicates 58 miles.
The mid-mounted 4.0L flat-six resides beneath a carbon-fiber cover in the rear cargo area and was factory rated at 493 horsepower and 331 lb-ft of torque.

Power is routed to the rear wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle, and the car is equipped with Porsche Torque Vectoring (PTV) and a mechanically locking differential. Additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery.
The Carfax report lists at least one open recall.
listing_details: Black Leather & Deep Sea Blue Race-Tex Upholstery

description: This 2021 BMW R nineT Pure underwent modifications at Angel Motoworks (formerly BAAK USA) of Los Angeles that included fitting a custom two-into-two exhaust system, LED lights, and a leather tank pouch in addition to tuning the engine, powder-coating the valve covers, and removing the airbox and rear fender. The bike is finished in gray and is powered by an 1,170cc opposed twin paired with a six-speed transmission and enclosed driveshaft. This R nineT is now offered at no reserve with service records and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The motorcycle is finished in gray and has been modified with a fender-eliminator and license-plate bracket kit, LED turn signals, an LED brake light, aluminum mirrors, and a black leather tank pouch. The bike has a two-up seat and a side stand.

Black-finished 17″ alloy wheels wear ZR-rated Michelin tires. Suspension consists of a 43mm conventional fork in addition to a monoshock attached to the Paralever single-sided swingarm. Braking is from Brembo calipers mounted over a pair of floating 320mm discs up front as well as a BMW-branded caliper fitted over a 265mm rotor at the rear, and the motorcycle is equipped with BMW Motorrad ABS.
The aluminum one-piece handlebar fronts a 140-mph speedometer with a built-in digital display that contains an odometer showing 8k miles, 7,500 of which were ridden by the seller.

The air-cooled 1,170cc opposed-twin factory-rated output was 110 horsepower and features an oil cooler, oil-cooled cylinder heads, fuel injection, and four valves per cylinder. A custom two-into-two exhaust system with a crossover pipe has been fitted, and additional modifications include powder-coating the valve covers black, removing the air box, and performing tuning work. An oil change and valve clearance check was carried out in September 2023.
Power is sent to the rear wheel via a six-speed transmission and an enclosed driveshaft.
Engine number A72B12A51206378 is shown above. The engine number listed on the California title document, A728B12A51206378, adds an “8” between the “2” and “B.”

This 1988 Mercedes-Benz 560SL remained registered with its previous owner for 27 years before being sold on BaT in June 2021, and it now shows 43k miles. Subsequent work included paintless dent removal, refinishing the pinstripes, applying a ceramic coating to the exterior, recharging the air conditioning system, and servicing the transmission and differential. The convertible soft top, heater control valve, EHA valve, fuel pumps and accumulator, belts, tie rod assemblies, spark plugs, and ignition wires were also replaced. Finished in Smoke Silver over Burgundy leather upholstery, the car is powered by a 5.5-liter V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission. It also has a body-colored removable hardtop, fog lights, power windows, a Pioneer CD stereo, and automatic climate control. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this R107 is now offered with a window sticker, manufacturer’s literature, service records, a wind deflector, a car cover, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Wisconsin title.

Smoke Silver Metallic paint finishes the exterior, which is complemented by a color-matched removable hardtop and a black convertible soft top that was replaced in June 2022. Additional details include quad headlights, fog lights, a power antenna, and chrome-accented bumpers and trim. Under previous ownership, paintless dent removal was performed on the right door, and the pinstripes were refinished. A ceramic coating was applied to the exterior in June 2023. Delamination is noted at the bottom corners of the windshield, and close-up photos of paint chips and imperfections are viewable in the gallery below.

The car rides on Gullideckel 15″ wheels fitted with Bridgestone Turanza tires that show 2017 production codes, and a full-size spare is located in the trunk. The car was factory equipped with power steering, a fully independent suspension, and power-assisted four-wheel disc brakes. The tie rod assemblies were replaced, the steering box was adjusted, and an alignment was performed in July 2021.

The cabin is upholstered in Burgundy leather (277) with color-coordinated door panels and carpets, complemented by burl wood accents on the center console and dash. Amenities include a power-adjustable passenger-side mirror, cruise control, power windows, central locking, an outside temperature gauge, automatic climate control, Lloyd Floor mats, and a Pioneer CD stereo linked with Pioneer speakers on the rear parcel shelf. The heater control mono valve was replaced under previous ownership, and the air conditioning system was most recently recharged in 2024. There are cracks in the left door sill trim, and a section of black felt has been installed on the back of the left seat.

A four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a 170-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, an inoperative clock, and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, fuel economy, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 43k miles.

The 5.5-liter M117 V8 features Bosch fuel injection and was factory rated at 227 horsepower and 279 lb-ft of torque. Replacement catalytic converters and exhaust components were installed in 2020, and service between 2021 and 2023 included replacing the EHA valve, spark plugs, ignition wires, accessory drive belts, and the fuel pumps, filter, and accumulator. An oil change was performed in May 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a limited-slip differential, both of which were serviced in July 2021.

The window sticker lists initial delivery to Gurley Leep Buick of Mishawaka, Indiana as well as factory colors, equipment, and a total suggested retail price of $62,430. Manufacturer’s literature, service records, a wind deflector, and a car cover are included in the sale.

The original window sticker indicates initial delivery to Gurley Leep Buick of Mishawaka, Indiana, detailing the factory colors, equipment, and a total suggested retail price of $62,430. The sale includes manufacturer’s literature, service records, a wind deflector, and a car cover.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1972 Chevrolet C10 Cheyenne pickup was purchased new by the seller’s father at Grant Bishop Chevrolet of Los Gatos, California, and has remained under their care since. Power is provided by a 350ci V8 mated to a three-speed automatic transmission, and the truck is finished in Dark Olive over green vinyl upholstery. A color-keyed camper shell and aftermarket exhaust system components have been added, and additional equipment includes 15″ Rally wheels, power steering, a tow ball, air conditioning, and an AM radio. This C10 pickup is now offered by the seller on behalf of their father with manufacturer’s literature, initial purchase documentation, service records, and a clean California title in the name of the owner’s trust.

The truck left the factory finished in Dark Olive, and records provided in the gallery indicate that it was repainted in April 1995. A color-keyed camper shell has been added, and it features sliding side windows and fold-down cots while carpeting lines the floor of the cargo bed. Additional exterior details include a chrome grille and bumpers, dual side mirrors, and bodyside moldings with woodgrain inlays as well as a tow ball accompanied by a seven-pin trailer hookup.

The 15″ Rally wheels feature green-painted centers and chrome accents, and they are mounted with 235/70 Uniroyal Tiger Paw GTS tires. The truck is equipped with power steering, and braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The cabin houses a bench seat upholstered in green vinyl as well as color-coordinated door panels with woodgrain trim. Air conditioning was optioned from the factory, and other equipment includes an AM radio, a fire extinguisher, crank-operated windows, and a green vinyl floor mat. The door panel armrests are worn and photos provided in the gallery show deterioration of the driver-door weather seal. The air conditioning system does not blow cold.

The two-spoke steering wheel is cracked in the center and wears an aftermarket wrap. Instrumentation consists of a 100-mph speedometer and gauges for fuel level, amperage, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The five-digit odometer shows 57k miles. True mileage is unknown.

The 350ci V8 was factory rated at 175 horsepower and 290 lb-ft of torque. Aftermarket exhaust headers have been installed, and they feed into a dual exhaust system with Flowmaster mufflers. An aftermarket horn shown in photos has been removed.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a three-speed Turbo Hydramatic automatic transmission.
The SPID label, shown above, lists factory colors and options.
Initial purchase documentation will accompany the truck along with manufacturer’s literature and service records.

This 2012 Porsche 911 Carrera S cabriolet was ordered new by the seller’s father, who specified Basalt Black Metallic paintwork over a two-tone Black and Platinum Grey leather interior. The car was optioned with the Premium Package Plus and a Burmester sound system as well as a switchable sport exhaust system, ParkAssist, Voice Control, Power Steering Plus, and a multifunction steering wheel. Power is from a 3.8-liter flat-six linked with a seven-speed manual transaxle, a limited-slip differential, and Porsche Torque Vectoring. Work within the last year has included replacing the battery, lower oil sump, spark plugs, alarm module, and brake fluid. This 991.1 has 49k miles following its acquisition by the seller approximately two years ago, and it is now offered with records, a window sticker, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Washington title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in Basalt Black Metallic and features bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, front and rear parking sensors, LED taillights, and a speed-activated rear spoiler. The seller notes that a parking-lot incident approximately 11 years ago resulted in repainting the rear fascia. The front valance shows a pair of scrapes on the lower lip. Rock chips are also noted up front, and the replacement windshield has a rock chip in the lower-center area.

The 20″ Carrera S alloy wheels have full-color center caps and are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires. Braking is handled by red-painted Porsche-branded calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated discs. The car is equipped with Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM). The brake fluid was flushed in July 2024.

The Black and Platinum Grey leather interior features the Premium Package Plus, which included heated and ventilated 14-way adjustable sport seats. Other options include a Burmester sound system, Voice Control, and Porsche crests for the front-seat headrests. The outer driver’s seat bolsters show signs of wear. The alarm module was updated in June 2023.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel frames a gray-dial tachometer with a 7,600-rpm redline as well as a 200-mph speedometer, a digital display, and gauges for oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 49k miles, approximately 1,600 of which were added under current ownership.

The 3.8-liter flat-six was factory rated at 400 horsepower and 325 lb-ft of torque. The lower-engine oil sump and seals were replaced and an oil change was performed in July 2024, and the spark plugs were replaced at that time. The battery and lid struts were replaced in June 2023.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential with Porsche Torque Vectoring. The car was optioned with a switchable sport exhaust system that can be controlled via a button in the center console.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Porsche North Scottsdale in Phoenix, Arizona, as well as factory colors, equipment, and a total price of $129,210.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or damage.
listing_details: Black And Platinum Gray Leather Upholstery

description: This 2003 BMW Sport Wagon left the factory as a 540i with an automatic gearbox and was modified in 2015 with the installation of a 4.9-liter V8, a six-speed manual transmission, and a limited-slip differential sourced from an E39 M5. It is finished in Black Sapphire Metallic and is equipped with an M5-style front bumper cover and side mirrors along with angel eyes headlights, European-specification taillights, 18″ Style 65 wheels, an M5-sourced steering box, StopTech front brakes, Ground Control front coilovers, Koni rear shocks, and aftermarket sway bars. The car was acquired by the current owner on BaT in March 2019 and the cabin was later retrimmed in brown leather. Other details include a dual-mode exhaust system, aftermarket engine management software, a UUC Motorwerks short shifter, an X5-sourced infotainment system, and aftermarket speakers. This M5-style E39 Sport Wagon is offered in New York on dealer consignment at no reserve with an owner’s manual, service records, a Carfax report, and a clean Minnesota title.

Finished in Black Sapphire Metallic, the car has an M5-style front bumper cover and side mirrors along with aftermarket angel eyes headlights, clear side markers, European-specification taillights, and quad exhaust outlets. Other features include an electric sunroof, a rear window wiper, fog lights, headlight washers, tinted windows, and roof rails. Damage to the car is noted in a 2007 entry on the Carfax report. The hood, fenders, bumpers, and side mirrors were repainted in 2019, and areas of touch-up paint are noted. The tailgate struts were replaced in 2023. A cover is missing from the front bumper cover, there is chipped paint on the rear bumper cover, and an area of corrosion is noted on the lower tailgate.

The 18″ Style 65 wheels are mounted with 275/35 Michelin Pilot Sport A/S 3+ tires. An M5-sourced steering box is said to be installed, and the car has been further modified with StopTech front brakes, Ground Control front coilovers, Koni rear shocks, a Dinan front sway bar, an Eibach rear sway bar, and polyurethane sway bar bushings.

The cabin was retrimmed in brown leather with contrasting stitching in 2019. It features E39 M5 components including a steering wheel, rearview mirror, and front seats, while other details include a ZHP shift knob, a European-specification lower dash, and an infotainment system sourced from a 2014 BMW X5. An aftermarket sound system is installed along with a UUC Motorwerks Evo3 short shifter with a Double Shear Selector Rod (DSSR). A Sport button has been added to the center stack, and the alarm system has been disabled. The left seatbelt retractor was rebuilt in 2023.

Black-dial instrumentation includes an M-branded 185-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a variable redline along with gauges for coolant temperature, oil temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 119k miles, approximately 13k of which were added under current ownership.

The 4.9-liter S62 V8 is said to have been sourced from a 2002 E39 M5 and installed in 2015 along with an E39 M5-sourced six-speed manual transmission and limited-slip differential. Aftermarket engine management software is said to be installed. M5-sourced rear axles have reportedly been added, and the differential front mount has been reinforced. The car has a dual-mode exhaust system. Work in 2023 is said to have included replacing the driveshaft CV joint, exhaust cut-out motor, and air conditioning belt.
Additional photos of the undercarriage are provided in the image gallery below.
The Carfax report notes the aforementioned accident.

This 1985 Porsche 911 Carrera coupe is powered by a 3.2-liter flat-six paired with a 915 five-speed manual transaxle and is finished in black over black leather. Equipment includes sport shocks, 16″ Fuchs alloy wheels, a power-operated sunroof, a power-adjustable driver seat, air conditioning, cruise control, and a Porshe Classic stereo with navigation. The current owner purchased the car in 2018 and subsequent work included resealing the engine, reprogramming the ECU, repairing the sunroof, and replacing the clutch, engine temperature sensor, idle contact switch, fuel injectors, headliner, and seats. This Carrera coupe shows 95k miles and is offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner with a Porsche Production Specification Certificate, an owner’s manual, a tool kit, service records, a Carfax report, and a clean Washington title in the owner’s name.

The car was refinished under previous ownership in black and features fog lights, headlight washers, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, a power-operated sunroof, and black rear bumperettes. The Carfax report notes a theft and recovery in February 2012 as well as a damage report indicating that the car hit a sign. The front hood struts were replaced under current ownership.

The 16″ Fuchs alloy wheels are mounted with 205/55 front and 225/50 rear Continental ExtremeContact tires. The car was optioned with sport shocks, and braking is handled by four-wheel discs. Work in 2021 included replacing the front rotors, brake pads, wheel seals, and tie rods. Blemishes are visible on the finish of the wheels.

The replacement front bucket seats and individual rear seats are upholstered in black leather. Appointments include air conditioning, cruise control, power windows, central locking, and a Porsche Classic stereo with navigation. Work under current ownership included repairing the sunroof and replacing the blower motor, driver-side passenger window switch, window seals, and headliner. The power-adjustable controls for the passenger seat are inoperative.

The leather-wrapped MOMO Prototipo steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a central tachometer with a 6,300-rpm redline as well as a 170-mph speedometer, a Quarz clock, and gauges for oil level, oil pressure, oil temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 95k miles, approximately 15k of which were added under current ownership. The fuel level sender was replaced in 2022.

The 3.2-liter M930/21 flat-six was factory rated at 202 horsepower and 185 lb-ft of torque and features a Dansk muffler. Work under current ownership included resealing the engine, reprogramming the ECU, and replacing the cylinder head temperature sensor, idle contact switch, distributor rotor and cap, and fuel injectors. An oil return line was replaced and an oil change was performed in preparation for the sale. Results from a compression test are presented in the gallery.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Type 915 five-speed manual transaxle. The clutch disc was replaced in 2020.
The Porsche Production Specification Certificate lists a production completion date of October 22, 1984, along with colors and options.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned theft, recovery, and damage report in February 2012 and lists history in New York and Washington from the initial entry in April 1992.
Interested to see what Car and Driver thought about the 911 Carrera when it was new? Click here to check out their February 1984 Road Test.

This 1967 Chevrolet Camaro coupe was modified in the late 1990s and is equipped with a 472ci big block Chevrolet V8 that is backed by a two-speed automatic transmission and a Dana 60 rear end. Further modifications include a nitrous oxide system, a Crane camshaft, KB pistons, and Hooker headers in addition to tubbed rear wheel wells, 15″ Budnik wheels, Strange axles, and a Flaming River steering rack. The bodywork is finished in blue with white stripes and mounted to a fabricated chassis. A fuel cell and components for the nitrous oxide system are located in the trunk, and the interior houses a roll cage and fixed-back bucket seats equipped with safety harnesses as well as a Grant steering wheel, AutoMeter instrumentation, a Hurst shifter, and a fire extinguisher. Acquired by the seller in 2006, this Pro Street Camaro is now offered with a seller-provided build sheet, spare rear wheels, and a New Jersey title in the seller’s name.

The bodywork is finished in metallic blue with white stripes and has been fitted over a fabricated steel chassis. Features include a removable hood and fenders, a rear spoiler, a non-functional bolt-on drag chute, and a chrome ladder bar. Areas of bubbling paint are noted.

Budnik 15″ wheels are mounted with 28×7.5″ Mickey Thompson tires up front and 33×18.5″ Hoosier Quick Time Pro Street tires. The car is equipped with Strange front and Wilwood rear calipers, a dual master cylinder with a proportioning valve, Strange 38-spline axles, and a Flaming River steering rack.

The cockpit is lined with black carpets and outfitted with a roll cage and fixed-back bucket seats trimmed in black and gray upholstery. Additional features include Simpson safety harnesses, a fire extinguisher, and a Hurst shifter.

The Grant steering wheel fronts an AutoMeter 160-mph speedometer and 10k-rpm tachometer. A fuel-pressure gauge is mounted on the cowl, and auxiliary readouts are housed in the dashboard and glovebox. The five-digit odometer shows 3,200 miles, approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.
The seller notes that the 472ci big block Chevrolet V8 was installed in 2000 and later equipped with a nitrous oxide system in addition to the following components:
The trunk houses a fuel cell, battery, and bottle for the nitrous oxide system.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a two-speed Powerglide automatic transmission and a Dana 60 rear end. A TCI Auto transbrake and a 4,500-stall torque converter are also fitted.
The New Jersey title carries a “Not the Actual Mileage” notation.

This 1972 Chevrolet K5 Blazer 4×4 was purchased by the owner in 2018 and subsequently refurbished with work that included refinishing the body in Olive Green with a white removable hardtop as well as rebuilding the 350ci V8. A three-speed automatic transmission is accompanied by a dual-range transfer case, both of which were reportedly overhauled and connected to rebuilt differentials via custom-fabricated driveshafts. The interior is trimmed in Olive, and additional equipment includes an AM radio, a center console, a 4″ lift kit, power-assisted steering and brakes, and Warn locking front hubs as well as an Edelbrock intake manifold, a Holley carburetor, a COMP Cams camshaft, and Dart cylinder heads. This K5 Blazer is now offered on dealer consignment in Arizona with a spare set of four polished Mickey Thompson wheels and an Idaho title.

The truck was refinished in Dark Olive Green following rust repair in the rocker panels during the refurbishment. The removable hardtop was refinished in white, and additional details include woodgrain tailgate and bodyside trim, dual side mirrors, and chrome bumpers. The seller states the frame was stripped and powder-coated black.

White-painted 15″ wheels are mounted with 33×12.5″ BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A tires, and the truck is also pictured with an included set of four polished Mickey Thompson wheels. The seller states that the Warn front hubs were rebuilt, a Skyjacker 4″ lift was installed, a later-model K5 Blazer sway bar was installed, the steering box mounting area was reinforced, and the steering gearbox and pump were rebuilt during the refurbishment.

The cabin features front bucket seats upholstered in Olive vinyl with houndstooth cloth inserts. Interior appointments include a body-color dash panel, a center console, faux woodgrain door panel accents, and a push-button radio. The seller notes the seat foam was replaced and the seats were reupholstered during the refurbishment.

The two-spoke steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer alongside gauges for fuel level, battery charge, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The five-digit odometer shows 44k miles, approximately 1k of which were added under current ownership.

The 350ci V8 was reportedly machined and rebuilt using forged pistons, Dart cast-iron cylinder heads, a COMP Cams hydraulic roller camshaft, and roller rocker arms. Additional equipment includes an Edelbrock aluminum intake manifold, a Holley four-barrel carburetor, MSD ignition components, and coated cast-iron exhaust manifolds that flow into a ceramic-coated exhaust system with a Flowmaster muffler.

Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels through a TH350 three-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case, both of which were rebuilt during the refurbishment along with the front and rear differentials according to the seller. The front driveshaft has been lengthened and rebuilt, and the rear driveshaft is a custom-fabricated unit with a CV joint at the transfer case.

This 2004 Mercedes-Benz SL500 is finished in Brilliant Silver Metallic over Ash leather and is powered by a 5.0-liter V8 paired with a seven-speed automatic transmission. The car spent time in Georgia and Florida and now has under 46k miles. Features include a power-folding hardtop with a panoramic glass roof as well as the AMG Sport Package, bi-xenon headlights, chrome 18″ Alphard wheels, heated power-adjustable seats, a Bose sound system, and COMAND with navigation. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this R230 is now offered with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Florida title.

The car is finished in Brilliant Silver Metallic (744) and is equipped with a power-folding convertible hardtop with a panoramic glass roof as well as bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, dual exhaust outlets, fender air vents, and the AMG Sport Package, which added revised bumper covers and aerodynamic side skirts.
This is a relist after the vehicle was previously sold on BaT in July 2024 and the sale was not completed due to extenuating circumstances. This was not due to any fault with the vehicle.

Chrome-finished 18″ Alphard alloy wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact DWS06 Plus tires installed in preparation for the sale. The car features Active Body Control (ABC) suspension as well as an Electronic Stability Program (ESP) and Automatic Slip Control (ASR).

The heated power-adjustable seats are upholstered in Ash leather and complemented by burl walnut wood trim. Equipment includes dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, a Bose sound system, and COMAND with navigation. The selling dealer states delaminating display screens were replaced in preparation for the sale and black Mercedes-branded floormats were installed.
The wood- and leather-rimmed steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates under 46k miles.

The 5.0-liter M113 V8 was factory rated at 302 horsepower and 339 lb-ft of torque. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission. The batteries were changed in March 2024.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1995 Porsche 911 Carrera coupe was first delivered to Harper’s Porsche in Knoxville, Tennessee. It was purchased new by its current owner, and it has 56k miles following registration history in the state. Finished in Guards Red over Cashmere leather, the car is powered by a 3.6-liter flat-six paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes Bilstein coilovers, aftermarket sway bars, 17″ Cup II wheels, a power-operated sunroof, power-adjustable front seats, cruise control, a cassette stereo, and air conditioning. This 993 Carrera coupe is now offered on dealer consignment with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, a tool kit, an air compressor, and a clean Tennessee title.

The car is finished in Guards Red and features headlight washers, fog lights, power-adjustable mirrors, a power-operated sunroof, a speed-activated rear spoiler, and dual exhaust outlets. Wiring for trailer brake lights has been added. The Carfax report indicates that an accident occurred in October 2002, and damage is noted in an October 2020 entry. The rear bumper was repainted and a taillight was replaced in 2002, per the selling dealer. Photos in the gallery depict finish imperfections.

Silver-finished 17″ Cup II wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport tires. Braking is handled by Porsche-branded calipers over cross-drilled rotors at all four corners. Bilstein coilovers have been added, and additional suspension modifications include aftermarket sway bars, adjustable drop links, and monoball camber plates.

The power-adjustable front seats are upholstered in Cashmere leather and complemented by a color-coordinated center console, door panels, and carpeting. Amenities include cruise control, a CR-1 cassette stereo, and power windows. Wear is evident on the driver’s seat and on the shift knob. The air conditioning system’s blower was replaced in 2022.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a central tachometer with a 6,800-rpm redline, a 180-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, oil level, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 56k miles.
The air-cooled 3.6L flat-six was factory rated at 270 horsepower and 243 lb-ft of torque. The battery was replaced in August 2022, and the oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a six-speed manual transaxle. The transaxle was rebuilt and the clutch was replaced at 50k miles in March 2009.

The window sticker lists initial delivery to Harper’s Porsche in Knoxville, Tennessee, along with factory equipment, colors, and a total price of $63,147. The sale also includes service records, a tool kit, and an air compressor.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned accident and damage report. It also indicates that a duplicate title was issued in September 2019, though the seller states that this is an error.
Interested to see what Car and Driver thought about the 911 Carrera when it was new? Click here to check out their June 1994 Road Test.

This 1981 Rolls-Royce Corniche convertible has remained registered in Florida since it was acquired by the current owner in 1995, and it now shows 8k miles. Finished in Willow Gold and Walnut over beige Connolly leather upholstery with brown piping, the car is powered by a 6.75-liter V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. Further equipment includes 15″ steel wheels, a power-operated beige soft top, a matching top boot, power-adjustable front seats, power windows, automatic climate control, and a push-button Blaupunkt radio linked with a Pioneer cassette player. Work performed in preparation for the sale included replacing the thermostat, and the right-rear brake caliper, front calipers, brake hoses, and tires were recently replaced. This Corniche convertible is now offered in Michigan on dealer consignment with manufacturer’s build sheets, owner’s manuals, a tool kit, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Florida title.

Willow Gold and Walnut paint finish the exterior, and features include a stainless-steel Doric-inspired grille with a Spirit of Ecstasy ornament as well as a power-operated beige soft top, a color-coordinated top boot, and quad round headlights.

The 15″ steel wheels feature trim rings and Rolls-Royce logo hubcaps, and they are mounted with 235/70 Vogue Tyre Custom Built Radial whitewall tires that show 2022 production codes. Factory equipment includes a four-wheel independent suspension with coil springs, anti-roll bars, telescopic dampers, and a hydraulic self-leveling system. The front brake calipers, right-rear caliper, and brake hoses were recently replaced.

The power-adjustable front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in beige Connolly leather with dark brown piping, while burl wood trim accents the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Interior appointments include power windows, automatic climate control, and a push-button Blaupunkt radio linked with a Pioneer cassette player.

A two-spoke steering wheel frames an 85-mph speedometer alongside a warning lamp panel and a combination gauge for amperage, coolant temperature, fuel level, and oil pressure. The six-digit odometer shows 8k miles, approximately 4k of which were added under current ownership.

The 6.75-liter V8 features an aluminum-silicon alloy block and aluminum cylinder heads along with Bosch K-Jetronic fuel injection. Service in 2023 included recharging the air conditioning system and replacing the drive belts, fuel pump, and fuel filter. An oil change was performed in January 2024, and the thermostat was replaced in preparation for the sale.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission. The transmission was serviced in February 2023.
Manufacturer’s literature, build sheets, a tool kit, and a 2024 service invoice are included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1971 Triumph TR6 was refurbished under prior ownership and was acquired by the current owner on BaT in September 2019. The car is powered by a 302ci Ford V8 linked to a Tremec T5 five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential, and it is finished in light blue over black upholstery. Additional equipment includes an Edelbrock carburetor, a Griffin radiator, a Centerforce clutch, 16″ Konig wheels, Wilwood front disc brakes, a black soft top, and a Clarion stereo. This TR6 is offered on dealer consignment with service records and New Hampshire registration.

The body was reportedly sand-blasted and rust was repaired before the car was repainted light blue under prior ownership. Equipment includes a front spoiler, chrome bumpers, and dual exhaust outlets. The seller notes separation between the right-rear window and the black vinyl soft top.

The 16″ Konig Rewind wheels are mounted with Falken tires, and the front tires are said to rub when the steering wheel is fully turned. Braking is from Wilwood discs up front, drums out back, and a Master Brakes master cylinder with a Wilwood proportioning valve.

The heated bucket seats were reportedly sourced from a Mazda Miata, and they are trimmed in black leather. Additional equipment includes a Clarion stereo head unit, a wood shift knob, and a Mr. Roadster gas pedal with a Lokar cable. The transmission tunnel has been widened, which reduced the size of the pedal box.

The Moto-Lita wood-rimmed steering wheel fronts a wood dashboard with AutoMeter gauges. The digital odometer shows 1,700 miles, approximately 200 of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 302ci Ford V8 crate engine was installed under prior ownership, and it is reportedly equipped with aluminum cylinder heads, an Edelbrock carburetor and fuel pump, a Griffin radiator, and a Dynomax Turbo exhaust system. The fuel lines were replaced under current ownership.

The Tremec five-speed manual transmission is said to feature a Centerforce clutch, a Wilwood master clutch cylinder, and a Tilton hydraulic throw-out bearing. Additional equipment includes aftermarket axles and a limited-slip rear differential. The frame was reinforced under prior ownership.
The car does not have a title, as it is registered in a state that does not issue titles for a vehicle of its age. It is being sold on its registration.

This 1991 BMW 325iX sedan is a Canadian-market example that is powered by a 2.5-liter M20 inline-six paired with a four-speed automatic transmission and is finished in Sterling Silver Metallic over Indigo leather.  Equipment includes an all-wheel drive system, 15″ basketweave alloy wheels, fog lights, a sunroof, heated front seats, a MOMO steering wheel, cruise control, and a CD stereo. The car has remained registered in British Columbia since new and was acquired by the seller in 2022.  Subsequent work performed involved replacing suspension components as well as the water pump, timing belt, drive belts, fuel pump, and fuel filter. Now showing 205k kilometers (~127k miles), this E30 sedan is now offered in Canada with an owner’s manual, service records for work performed under current ownership, US and Canadian Carfax reports, and British Columbia registration in the seller’s name.

The 325iX features flared wheel arches and side skirts to accommodate a 9mm wider track and more deeply offset wheels when compared with the standard 325i. This example is finished in Sterling Silver Metallic (244) and features aluminum trim, quad headlights, fog lights, a sunroof, a decklid spoiler, an antenna, and iX-specific body-color rocker panel and wheel-arch extensions. Blemishes include bubbles in the paint on the left front fender, cracks in the front and rear bumper covers, and paint blemishes on various body panels. The Carfax Canada report lists incidences of theft in April 1994 and again in September 1999, and also notes multiple collision reports from December 1992 through November 2006.

Silver 15″ basketweave alloy wheels are mounted with 195/60 Maxtrek Relamax 4s tires. Braking is handled by ventilated front and solid rear discs with a Bosch ABS system that was revised for use in the iX. The shocks and struts were replaced in November 2022.

The heated front seats are upholstered in Indigo leather and are joined by color-coordinated door panels and carpets. A heater, an onboard computer, cruise control, BMW-branded floor mats, and a Kenwood CD stereo are additional details. The seller notes the air conditioning system does not work and that the low coolant light remains illuminated.

The MOMO Prototipo steering wheel frames a 240-km/h speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for instant fuel economy, fuel level, and coolant temperature. The six-digit odometer shows 205k kilometers (~127k miles), approximately 20k of which have been added under current ownership.

The 2.5-liter M20B25 inline-six was factory rated at 168 horsepower and 164 lb-ft of torque. The water pump, timing belt, and drive belts were replaced in March 2024, and the fuel pump and fuel filter were replaced in July 2024.

Power is sent to all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission, an open front differential, and viscous-coupling center and rear differentials. A replacement muffler was fitted in March 2024, and rust is noted behind the right rear wheel opening.
The US Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage. A Carfax Canada report is provided in the gallery and shows the aforementioned collision and theft reports from 1992 through 2006.
The car does not have a title and is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada.

This 1973 Toyota Land Cruiser FJ40 was acquired by the current owner in 2020 and subsequently refurbished, with work including disassembling the body, replacing panels, repainting the truck in blue, and re-trimming the cabin in black vinyl. Body-color bedliner material was applied to the underbody, underside of the hood, headliner, and cab floors. The 4.2-liter inline-six was resealed and is fitted with a Weber carburetor, a Downey exhaust header, powder-coated equipment, and replacement ignition components, and it is linked with an overhauled four-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Further equipment includes rear jump seats, 15″ wagon wheels, front disc brakes, Rancho shocks, a steering stabilizer, and two cab heaters. This FJ40 was listed on BaT in March 2024 and is now offered again on dealer consignment with a clean Rhode Island title.

The truck was disassembled and stripped before rust repairs were performed and replacement floors, quarter, and tub panels were fitted during the refurbishment. It was subsequently repainted in blue, and the removable hardtop features a white roof. The liftgate mechanism was overhauled and replacement glass, weatherstripping, door hardware, and window regulators were installed.

White 15″ wagon wheels are mounted with 31×10.50″ Toyo Open Country A/T tires, and a matching spare is fitted to the rear swing-away carrier. The truck rides on Rancho shocks and is equipped with manually locking front hubs and an Old Man Emu steering stabilizer.

The front bucket seats and inward-facing rear jump seats were reupholstered in black vinyl during the refurbishment, at which point the front heater assembly was rebuilt and the rear heater received a replacement coil and seals. Body-color bedliner material was applied to the floors, and a roll cage and cargo floor liner are installed.

The instrument cluster was refurbished and features a 100-mph speedometer and gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, amperage, and fuel level. The odometer shows 39k miles, and total mileage is unknown.

The 4.2-liter F inline-six is said to be from a 1978 example and is fitted with a Weber 32/36 carburetor and a ceramic-coated Downey exhaust header. The engine is said to have been resealed during the refurbishment, at which point a powder-coated intake manifold, valve cover, and thermostat housing were installed along with a replacement thermostat, alternator, water pump, and ignition components. Fluid services were performed, and the wiring harness is said to have been refurbished.

The frame is said to have been media-blasted before being refinished, and body-color bedliner material was applied to the underbody. The four-speed manual transmission routes power to the rear or all four wheels through a dual-range transfer case, the latter of which is said to have been overhauled along with the differentials. The clutch, pressure plate, flywheel, and release bearings were replaced, according to the selling dealer, and a stainless-steel exhaust system is installed.
Photos showing the truck during various stages of the refurbishment can be seen in the gallery below.

This 2001 Ferrari 360 Spider was initially delivered to Ferrari San Francisco in Mill Valley, California, and was acquired by the current owner on BaT in November 2022. The car is powered by a 3.6-liter V8 paired with a six-speed manual transaxle and is finished in Grigio Alloy over Classic Gray leather. Equipment includes a limited-slip differential, a Tubi exhaust system, 18″ two-piece BBS alloy wheels, a black convertible soft top, a Challenge-style rear grille, power-adjustable seats, a gated shifter, a Ferrari-branded stereo, a commemorative dashboard plaque, and automatic climate control. The tires were replaced in May 2019, a timing belt service was performed in May 2020, and the clutch was replaced along with installation of a Tubi exhaust in July 2021. This 360 Spider has 21k miles and is now offered on dealer consignment in Washington State with service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New Mexico title.

The Pininfarina-designed aluminum body is finished in Grigio Alloy (750) and features xenon headlights, a power-retractable black convertible soft top, a Challenge-style rear grille, and quad exhaust outlets exiting through the rear fascia. The front bumper cover has been refinished, and a crack is noted in the left rear quarter panel along with a scuff underneath the car.

Two-piece 18″ BBS alloy wheels are mounted with Hankook Ventus V12 Evo2 tires that were installed in May 2019. Stopping power is provided by black Ferrari-branded calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated rotors at each corner. The lower ball joints were replaced in July 2021.

The cockpit features power-adjustable seats upholstered in Classic Gray leather along with matching door panel inserts and carpets. Amenities include a gated shifter, a Ferrari-branded stereo, aluminum pedal covers, and automatic climate control. A fire extinguisher has been installed, and sticky buttons have been refinished. The dashboard is equipped with an optional commemorative plaque.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 220-mph speedometer and a tachometer with an 8,500-rpm redline as well as a digital fuel level readout and gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 21k miles, approximately 500 of which were added under current ownership.

The mid-mounted 3.6-liter Tipo F131 V8 features a flat-plane crankshaft, dry-sump lubrication, dual overhead camshafts, and five valves per cylinder. Factory-rated output was 395 horsepower and 275 lb-ft of torque. Engine belts and idler bearings were replaced and wiring for a battery tender was installed in May 2020. The battery was replaced in 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. A Tubi exhaust system has been installed, and the clutch assembly was replaced in July 2021.
The Carfax report is free of accidents and other reported damage.

This 2002 Porsche Boxster S is finished in Speed Yellow over black full leather and is powered by a 3.2-liter flat-six paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. Work in the last year is said to have included installing an LN Engineering IMS bearing and replacing the clutch, air-oil separator, rear main seal, water pump, alternator, starter, ignition coils, and spark plugs and tube seals. The car is finished in Speed Yellow and features a power-operated black soft top. Additional features include a speed-activated rear spoiler, side air intakes, and body-color roll hoops. Photos of paint meter readings are provided in the gallery below, and the soft top rear window is foggy.

Aftermarket 18″ black wheels feature lighter outer rims and are mounted with 245/40 front and 275/35 rear Kumho Ecsta PS91 tires. Braking is handled by four-piston Porsche-branded calipers fitted over cross-drilled rotors at all four corners. A brake fluid flush was reportedly performed within the last year.

The cabin features replacement seats upholstered in black leather that extends to the dashboard and door panels. Other interior appointments include a Bose sound system, cruise control, automatic climate control, and a JVC stereo with Bluetooth connectivity.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a central tachometer, a 180-mph speedometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates under 88k miles.

The mid-mounted 3.2L flat-six was factory rated at 250 horsepower and 225 lb-ft of torque. The selling dealer notes that the IMS bearing was replaced in 2024 with an LN Engineering kit, and other work completed in the last year reportedly included replacing the air-oil separator, alternator, water pump, starter, rear main seal, ignition coils, and spark plugs and tube seals.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle, the clutch components for which were reportedly replaced in 2024. A sport exhaust system was optioned from the factory.

This 1954 MG TF was acquired by the seller in 2019, and subsequent work included a repaint, a rebuild of the dual SU carburetors, and replacement of the rear axle, clutch, and starter. The car is powered by a 1,250cc XPAG inline-four paired with a four-speed manual transmission and is finished in Primrose over black. Equipment includes a Fawn soft top, 15″ wire wheels, chrome bumpers, running boards, rear-hinged doors, fender-mounted mirrors, driving lights, seat belts, side curtains, a tonneau cover, and a Moto-Lita steering wheel. This TF is now offered with the owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, a car cover, a tool kit, and Connecticut registration in the name of the seller’s spouse.

The car is finished in Primrose and was repainted in 2022. Equipment includes a Fawn soft top, chrome bumpers with a front badge bar, wind wings, running boards, rear-hinged doors, fender-mounted mirrors, driving lights, side curtains, a tonneau cover, and a folding windshield. Body filler on the firewall was addressed during the repaint.
The 15″ wire wheels with knock-off hubs are mounted with 165HR15 Vresdestein Sprint Classic tires, and a spare is affixed to the rear. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel drums.

The cabin features low-back bucket seats trimmed in black that are complemented by a color-coordinated dash pad and door panels. Additional equipment includes lap belts, a burled walnut dash, a dash-mounted rearview mirror, and a passenger grab handle.

The wood-rimmed Moto-Lita steering wheel fronts Jaeger instrumentation consisting of a 105-mph speedometer with an inset clock, a tachometer, and a combination gauge for coolant temperature, oil pressure, and amperage. The five-digit odometer shows 13k miles, approximately 500 of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown. The tachometer cable was replaced in 2024. The clock is inoperative and the low fuel light is disconnected.

The 1,250cc XPAG inline-four is equipped with dual SU carburetors for a factory rating of 57 horsepower. A replacement gear reduction starter was installed in 2022 and the carburetors were rebuilt in 2024. Oil leaks are noted.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission, which was removed and inspected in 2022. A replacement clutch and rear axle were also installed at that time, while 4.55:1 gears and a replacement differential cage were installed in 2023.
The car does not have a title, as it is registered in a state that does not issue titles for a vehicle of its age. It is being sold on its Connecticut registration.

This 2011 Maserati GranTurismo convertible is finished in silver over Nero leather and is powered by a 4.7-liter F136 V8 paired with a six-speed automatic gearbox. Equipment includes 20″ Astro Anthracite wheels, a black canvas soft top, bi-xenon headlights, heated power-adjustable front seats, navigation, a Bose sound system, parking sensors, and dual-zone automatic climate control. The car has spent time in Oregon, California, Connecticut, and Pennsylvania and now has 33k miles. Acquired by the selling dealer in April 2024, this GranTurismo convertible is now offered with manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Pennsylvania title.

The car is finished in silver and features a black convertible soft top, adaptive bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, fender porthole vents, front and rear parking sensors, LED taillights, and dual exhaust outlets. Clear paint protection film covers the front bumper cover, hood, and fenders, and the Carfax report notes that the windshield was replaced in August 2019.

The 20″ Astro Anthracite alloy wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact Sport 02 tires said to have been installed in preparation for the sale. Braking is handled by red-finished calipers over cross-drilled and vented rotors at each corner. The brake fluid was changed in preparation for the sale.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats upholstered in Nero leather with red stitching. Interior amenities include an infotainment system with navigation as well as an 11-speaker Bose surround-sound system, cruise control, dual-zone automatic climate control, and driver’s seat-position memory settings. An automatically deploying rollbar system was standard. The selling dealer notes sticky switchgear throughout the interior.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel features shift paddles and frames a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 33k miles.

Designed in collaboration with Ferrari, the 4.7-liter F136 V8 featured dual overhead camshafts per cylinder bank, four valves per cylinder, and variable valve timing for a factory rating of 433 horsepower and 361 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a ZF six-speed automatic gearbox.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2006 AM General M1165 HMMWV was originally designed for use by the US military and is powered by a 6.5-liter turbodiesel V8 mated to a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Finished in drab camouflage, the truck has a soft top and doors with zip-up windows in addition to an air intake snorkel, a pintle hitch, LED headlights, 16.5″ two-piece steel wheels, 37″ military-specification tires, inboard disc brakes, portal axles, and front and rear limited-slip differentials. The cabin is outfitted with four cloth-trimmed bucket seats and air conditioning. This Humvee is offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner in Georgia with a clean Florida title.

The M1165 variant of the HMMWV was developed as an Expanded Capacity command and control vehicle for the US military. This example is finished in drab camouflage and has a soft top and doors with zip-up windows as well as an air intake snorkel, a pintle hitch, LED headlights, rear mud flaps, and D-ring hold-down and lift anchors. The rear window was replaced in preparation for the sale according to the seller, who notes that the side markers need to be replaced.

The 16.5″ two-piece steel wheels are mounted with 37×12.50″ Goodyear Wrangler MT/R tires. Braking is handled by inboard-mounted front and rear discs, and the truck features four-wheel independent suspension. The brakes were serviced in preparation for the sale according to the selling dealer.
The cabin is outfitted with air conditioning and front and rear bucket seats trimmed in green cloth upholstery.

Instrumentation includes a 60-mph speedometer, an air filter restriction readout, and gauges for oil pressure, fuel level, coolant temperature, and voltage. A tachometer is located overhead and indicates 244 engine hours. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 48 miles. Total mileage is unknown.

The 6.5-liter turbodiesel V8 produced 190 horsepower and 380 lb-ft of torque when new, which is sent to all four wheels through a four-speed 4L80E automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, portal axles, and front and rear Torsen limited-slip differentials. The belt tensioner pulley needs to be replaced.
Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery below.
The data plate shown above displays the serial number 226121, which is listed as the VIN on the Florida title.

This 1999 Ford Mustang SVT Cobra convertible was originally purchased in May 1999 by the first owner, with whom it has since remained in Arizona since new. Now showing 117k miles, the car is finished in Rio Red Tinted Clearcoat over Dark Charcoal leather and is powered by a 4.6-liter DOHC V8 linked with a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. Equipment includes a black convertible soft top, 17″ painted five-spoke wheels, an independent rear suspension, a vented hood, a rear spoiler, articulated front sport seats, a Mach 460 AM/FM/cassette stereo, remote keyless entry, cruise control, and power windows, mirrors, and locks. This SVT Cobra convertible is now offered on dealer consignment at no reserve with an SVT certificate of authenticity, a window sticker, manufacturer’s literature, a car cover, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Arizona title.

The Cobra was distinguished from the contemporary SN95 Mustang by circular front fog lights, tri-color taillights, and a revised front fascia and vented hood. This example is finished in Rio Red Tinted Clearcoat, and additional equipment includes a power-retractable black soft top, a raised rear spoiler, dual polished exhaust outlets, and SVT and Cobra badging.

The 17″ painted five-spoke wheels have curb marks and are mounted with 245/45 Continental ExtremeContact DWS06 Plus tires said to have recently been installed. SVT-specific suspension components consist of linear-rate springs, gas-pressurized front struts and rear shocks, and an independent rear suspension. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes with Cobra-branded calipers up front.

The cabin features articulated front sport seats trimmed in Dark Charcoal leather. Equipment includes a Mach 460 AM/FM/cassette stereo, a leather-wrapped shift knob, remote keyless entry, cruise control, air conditioning, and power windows, mirrors, and locks. The driver’s seat outer bolster is worn and covered with black tape.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel is mounted to a tilting column and frames white instrument dials including a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,800-rpm redline as well as gauges for fuel level, coolant temperature, voltage, and oil pressure. The cruise control set/accelerate button is worn. The digital odometer indicates under 117k miles.
The 4.6-liter DOHC V8 was factory rated at 320 horsepower and 317 lb-ft of torque.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a Tremec T-45 five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. The selling dealer states that the clutch was recently replaced.
A Ford Special Vehicle Team certificate of authenticity is included in the sale along with a window sticker, a car cover, and manufacturer’s literature.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1965 Chevrolet Chevelle Malibu Sport Coupe was refurbished and modified during previous ownership and fitted with a Z16-specification aluminum 396ci V8 that is linked with a Tremec five-speed manual transmission and a PosiTraction differential. The car was placed on a rotisserie and the bodywork has been refinished in silver during the build, while the cabin was outfitted in red vinyl upholstery with SS-style trim. Additional work included boxing and painting the frame, smoothing the firewall, and installing a Vintage Air climate control system, a retro-look digital stereo, and long-tube headers. Further details include power-assisted steering and four-wheel disc brakes, tubular upper and lower control arms, Hotchkis rear suspension components, 17″ American Racing wheels, and an aluminum radiator with electric fans. This Chevelle Malibu is now offered by the selling dealer with build documentation and a clean Tennessee title.

The car was placed on a rotisserie during the build, and the body was refinished in the Mercedes-Benz shade of Brilliant Silver according to the selling dealer. Replacement glass was installed along with SS and 396 badging, and additional exterior details include a cowl induction hood, polished window trim, and dual side-view mirrors.

American Racing 17″ Torq Thrust-style wheels are mounted with Sumitomo tires. Braking is via power-assisted four-wheel discs and the car is also equipped with power-assisted steering in addition to front and rear sway bars, tubular upper and lower front control arms, and Hotchkis rear suspension components.

The front bucket seats and rear bench were reupholstered in red vinyl during the refurbishment, and they are joined by matching door panels. Appointments include a Vintage Air climate control system, a retro-look digital stereo, SS-style trim, and a Hurst shifter mounted in the center console.

A wood-rimmed two-spoke steering wheel is mounted to a tilting column and frames replacement SS-style instrumentation that includes a 120-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and a combination display. The five-digit odometer shows 47 miles, which is said to represent the mileage accumulated since the completion of the build. Total mileage is unknown.

The aluminum 396ci V8 is said to have been overhauled and assembled to Z16 specification during the build. The engine is equipped with a solid lifter camshaft, an aluminum radiator, dual electric fans, a Front Runner accessory drive system, and long-tube headers connected to an X-pipe midsection and MagnaFlow mufflers. Billet hood hinges were installed and the firewall was smoothed.

Power is sent to the rear wheels via a Tremec five-speed manual transmission and a 12-bolt rear end with a PosiTraction differential and a TA cover. The frame was boxed, smoothed, and painted and houses the brake and fuel lines. Additional underbody images are provided in the gallery below.
A binder documenting the refurbishment is included in the sale.

This 2010 Chevrolet Corvette ZR1 spent time in Missouri, California, and Massachusetts before it was sold on BaT in July 2021, and it was acquired by the seller on BaT in January 2023. Powered by a supercharged 6.2-liter LS9 V8 paired with a six-speed manual gearbox, the car is finished in Cyber Gray Metallic over black leather and microsuede upholstery. It has been modified with an Akrapovič exhaust system, a Lingenfelter Performance Engineering (LPE) 710 HP engine package kit and engine control unit (ECU) tune, and Caravaggio Corvettes carbon-fiber components including a Modena steering wheel and Daytona Race seats. Additional equipment includes the 3ZR Premium Equipment Group, a limited-slip differential, 19″ and 20″ multi-spoke wheels, Brembo ceramic-composite brakes, xenon headlights, a Bose sound system, navigation, a head-up display, and Keyless Access. This C6 ZR1 indicates 11k miles and is offered with a clean Carfax report and a clean Wisconsin title in the seller’s name.

The C6 ZR1 featured a hydro-formed aluminum chassis paired with composite and carbon-fiber bodywork, and this example is finished in Cyber Gray Metallic. Exterior details include an exposed carbon-fiber roof, xenon headlights, and a clear engine cover. XPEL clear paint protection film was installed on the front bumper, hood, front fenders, and rocker panels in 2017. A previous owner noted a scratch on the left side of the rear spoiler.

Staggered-diameter 19″ and 20″ multi-spoke alloy wheels were mounted with 285/30 front and 335/25 rear Michelin Pilot Super Sport tires in September 2021. Braking is handled by Brembo ceramic-composite discs at each corner, and the car is equipped with Magnetic Ride Control.

A pair of black leather and microsuede-upholstered carbon-fiber Caravaggio Corvettes Daytona Race seats were installed under previous ownership along with a re-wrapped shift knob and parking brake lever. Factory appointments include dual-zone automatic climate control, a head-up display, and Keyless Access with push-button start, while the optional 3ZR Premium Equipment Group added Bose audio, navigation, and a power-telescoping steering column.

The Caravaggio Corvettes Modena steering wheel features carbon fiber along the top of the rim as well as revised thumb grips. Instrumentation includes a 220-mph speedometer, a ZR1-branded tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, boost pressure, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 11k miles, approximately 300 of which were added under current ownership.

The supercharged 6.2-liter LS9 V8 was modified with a Lingenfelter Performance Engineering (LPE) engine control unit (ECU) tune in addition to an LPE 710 HP engine package kit, which included a revised air-intake system, supercharger pulley, cast-aluminum supercharger front cover assembly, 160-degree thermostat, and idler bearing assembly, and drive belt. The accessory and supercharger drive belts were replaced under previous ownership.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a rear-mounted six-speed manual gearbox and a limited-slip differential. An Akrapovič exhaust system with 115mm titanium tips was installed under previous ownership.

This 1979 Yamaha RD400 Daytona Special is finished in white with red and black stripes and is powered by a 398cc two-stroke parallel twin paired with a six-speed transmission. It is equipped with a kick starter, a two-up seat, a pair of Mikuni carburetors, a two-into-two exhaust system, cast aluminum wheels, front and rear disc brakes, and both side and center stands. This RD400 was acquired by the seller in March 2023 and is now offered with service records, spare parts, and a clean Arizona title in the seller’s name.

The motorcycle is finished in white with red and black stripes over a black frame. Features include a 4.4-gallon fuel tank, a two-up seat, tool kit storage, a black-painted rear fender, street lighting, folding passenger foot pegs, and both center and side stands. The front fender has been touched up, and the rear fender has been repainted. The taillight lens, mirrors, and battery tie-down strap were replaced in January 2024.

Seven-spoke 18″ cast-alloy wheels are finished in black and silver and were mounted with IRC tires in January 2024. Suspension consists of a 35mm telescopic fork as well as a pair of adjustable shocks mounted to the black powder-coated swingarm. Braking is provided by a single 267mm disc at each end.

The chrome handlebar fronts a a 120-mph speedometer and a matching tachometer with an 9k-rpm redline as well as indicator lamps for high beam, turn signals, oil pressure, and neutral gear selection, the latter of which is noted to be inoperative. The five-digit odometer shows 12k miles, a handful of which were ridden by the seller.

The 398cc two-stroke parallel twin was rated at 44 horsepower when new and features Autolube oil injection, reed-valve induction, a CD ignition module, a kick-start lever, and a chrome low-mounted dual exhaust system. Work in June 2024 consisted of replacing the stator, battery, and coils in addition to rewiring the charging system, rebuilding and tuning the carburetors, and flushing the fuel tank.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed transmission and a drive chain.

This 1968 Ford Thunderbird hardtop coupe is finished in yellow over black vinyl and powered by a 429ci “Thunder Jet” V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes hideaway headlights, sequential taillights, power steering, power front disc brakes, 15″ wheels, crank windows, a Philco AM radio, and a dual exhaust system with bullet-style mufflers. The car was acquired by the seller in 2019 and subsequent work consisted of replacing the turn signal relay, battery, and interior lights. This Thunderbird coupe is offered with the manufacturer’s literature, a car cover, a battery tender, spare parts, a historical Wisconsin title, and Rhode Island registration.

The car left the factory finished in yellow and was repainted under prior ownership. Exterior details include pinstriping, a driver-side mirror, sequential taillights, bright side moldings, chrome bumpers, and polished exhaust finishers. The hideaway headlights were reportedly rebuilt under prior ownership.

The steel 15″ wheels wear factory covers and are wrapped in Uniroyal whitewall tires. The car is equipped with power steering and braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. The brakes are said to have been serviced approximately five years ago.

The front and rear bench are upholstered in black vinyl joined by a matching dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Woodgrain trim lines the dashboard and steering wheel and interior elements include a left mirror adjuster, crank windows, and a Philco AM radio. The turn signal relay and interior light bulbs were replaced under current ownership. The analog clock does not work.

The two-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of a 120-mph speedometer and gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, alternator charge, and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 70k miles, approximately 2,500 of which were added under current ownership.
The 429ci “Thunderjet” V8 is fed via a four-barrel carburetor. Work since 2023 is said to consist of replacing the battery and performing an oil change.

Power is delivered to the rear wheels via a three-speed automatic transmission. A dual exhaust system with bullet-style mufflers has been fitted, and the fuel tank is said to have been replaced under prior ownership.
Decoding the data plate reveals the following details:
The car does not have a current title, as it is registered in a state that does not issue titles for vehicles of its age. It is being sold on its Rhode Island registration.

This 1987 Porsche 911 Carrera Targa shows 60k miles following registration history in New York and New Jersey. Powered by a 3.2-liter flat-six paired with a G50 five-speed manual transaxle, the car is finished in black over black leather upholstery. It has been fitted with a Fabspeed exhaust system and a Bluetooth-capable Blaupunk Bremen stereo, and additional equipment includes 16″ Fuchs alloy wheels, a black removable targa roof panel, front and rear spoilers, cruise control, power windows, central locking, a heated power-adjustable driver’s seat, and air conditioning. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this Carrera Targa is offered with an owner’s manual, a stamped service booklet, spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in black and was optioned with front and rear spoilers. Additional exterior details include a black removable targa roof panel, integrated fog lights, H4 headlights, and heated power-adjustable side mirrors, the latter of which wear leather covers. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

The 16″ Fuchs alloy wheels have black centers and are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport tires that have 2019 date codes. A front strut tower brace is fitted, and braking is handled by four-wheel discs.

The cabin features front seats upholstered in black leather. A Blaupunkt Bremen stereo with Bluetooth connectivity has been installed, and additional amenities include a heated power-adjustable driver’s seat, cruise control, a Rennline seat-mounted cup holder, a Rennline magnetic phone mount, air conditioning, and power windows and locks.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a central tachometer with a 6,300-rpm redline as well as a 170-mph speedometer, a Quarz clock, and gauges for oil level, oil pressure, oil temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 60k miles.
The 3.2-liter M930/25 flat-six features Bosch Motronic engine management and was factory rated at 217 horsepower and 195 lb-ft of torque. A Fabspeed exhaust system has been added.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a G50 five-speed manual transaxle.
Decoding the option sticker reveals the following information:
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage from its first entry in January 1989.

This 1996 Chevrolet C1500 Silverado pickup is powered by a 5.7-liter V8 linked with a five-speed manual transmission. The truck shows 49k miles and is finished in two-tone Emerald Green Metallic and Light Autumn Wood Metallic over beige cloth upholstery. Features include a cowl-induction hood, Lund fiberglass running boards, a tonneau cover, a receiver hitch, 15″ Prime aluminum wheels, a cassette stereo, cruise control, and air conditioning. This GMT400 pickup is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with an accident-free Carfax report and a clean Missouri title.

The truck is finished in two-tone Emerald Green Metallic and Light Autumn Wood Metallic and features a Fleetside bed and a cowl-induction hood as well as a fiberglass tonneau cover, a windshield visor, cab marker lights, tinted windows, Lund fiberglass running boards, a receiver hitch, and chrome bumpers.

The silver-finished 15″ Prime aluminum wheels are mounted with 275/60 Cooper Cobra white-letter tires that were fitted in August 2023. Braking is provided by anti-lock power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The extended cab cabin features a 60/40 split-bench seat with a fold-down center console upholstered in beige cloth. Interior amenities include a cassette stereo, cruise control, power windows, remote keyless entry, and air conditioning.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for voltage, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 49k miles.
The 5.7-liter V8 was factory rated at 250 horsepower and 335 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage and lists at least one open recall.
listing_details: Two-Tone Emerald Green Metallic & Light Autumnwood Paint

description: This 1965 Pontiac LeMans convertible was initially delivered to Lane Buick-Pontiac of Fairfield, California, and an owner of 18 years sold the car on BaT in October 2021. A 350ci V8 was installed under previous ownership along with a four-speed manual transmission, and the car is refinished in white over blue cloth. Additional equipment includes a power-operated blue soft top, a four-barrel Holley carburetor, 14″ steel wheels, power steering and brakes, a Hurst shifter, and a push-button AM radio. This LeMans was acquired by the selling dealer in 2022 and is now offered with PHS documentation, a reproduction window sticker, service records, and a clean Virginia title.

Originally finished in Teal Turquoise, the car was repainted white in 2004, at which time the power-operated blue soft top was replaced. Additional details include dual side mirrors, LeMans badging, and dual exhaust outlets. The headlight and taillight bezels were re-chromed under previous ownership, and the trunk floor, body mounts, and soft top motor have been replaced. Rust repair has been performed to the rear wheel wells.

The 14″ wheels are wrapped in 205/70 white-letter BFGoodrich Radial T/A tires that were mounted in 2018, and a full-size spare is mounted in the trunk. Stopping power is provided by power-assisted drum brakes at all four corners. The power steering pump was replaced in 2013, while the shocks and front control arm bushings were replaced in 2015.
