The cabin features front bucket seats and a rear bench upholstered in blue cloth with a matching dashboard pad, door panels, and replacement carpets. A push-button AM radio and a locking glovebox are housed in the body-color lower dashboard, and additional equipment includes lap belts for the front occupants, a Hurst shifter, vent windows, and a removable center console. The driver’s door does not open smoothly and the right-rear window requires assistance to roll up.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel features a Pontiac-logo center cap and fronts a 120-mph speedometer and auxiliary gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 49k miles, a few of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 350ci V8 was reportedly sourced from a 1969 Pontiac and fitted with a Holley four-barrel carburetor, an Edelbrock intake manifold, and Pontiac-branded valve covers. A replacement heater core was fitted in 2015, while the fuel pump and battery were replaced in 2019.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission. The clutch was replaced and the transmission was overhauled with a replacement 1st gear, bearings, and synchronizers in 2004.
The trim tag decodes as follows:
Pontiac Historic Services documentation, a reproduction window sticker, service records, and an owner’ manual are included in the sale.

This 2008 BMW X5 3.0si remained registered with the original owner until the selling dealer’s acquisition in May 2024 and now has 34k miles. The truck is finished in Space Gray Metallic over black leatherette upholstery and is powered by a 3.0-liter inline-six that drives all four wheels through a six-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes adaptive xenon headlights, a panoramic sunroof, Style 210 wheels, power-adjustable front seats, third-row seats, cruise control, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This E70 X5 is now offered at no reserve with the owner’s manual, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean New York title.

The truck is finished in Space Gray Metallic (A52) and features adaptive xenon headlights, fog lights, a panoramic sunroof, running boards, roof rails, and a rear window wiper. The left fender badging is missing.

The 18″ Style 210 alloy wheels are mounted with 225/55 Hankook Ventus S1 evo2 tires. Stopping power is provided by disc brakes at all four corners, and the truck is equipped with a self-leveling suspension.

The seating surfaces and door panels are upholstered with black leatherette, and burl walnut wood trim accents the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Amenities include power-adjustable front seats, driver-seat position memory, third-row seats, cruise control, dual-zone automatic climate control, and iDrive infotainment.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel fronts a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline as well as gauges for fuel level and instant fuel economy. The digital odometer indicates 34k miles, approximately 300 of which were added under current ownership.

The 3.0-liter N52B30 inline-six features double VANOS variable valve timing and was factory rated at 260 horsepower and 225 lb-ft of torque. Power is delivered to all four wheels through a six-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage and lists at least one open recall.

This 1990 Nissan 300ZX 2+2 coupe is finished in Yellow Pearglow over Charcoal leather and is powered by a 3.0-liter V6 paired with a five-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes a limited-slip differential, 16″ Turbo alloy wheels, removable roof panels, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, an aftermarket cassette stereo, a Bose sound system, automatic climate control, and cruise control. The car was acquired by the current owner in 2024 and now shows 43k miles. This Z32 is offered in Illinois by the seller on behalf of the owner at no reserve with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Ohio title.

The car is finished in Yellow Pearglow and features removable glass T-top roof panels. Additional equipment includes integrated fog lights, painted mirror caps, a power-telescoping antenna, a rear window wiper, and quad exhaust outlets. A scratch is noted on a quarter panel, and close-up photos of the paintwork and trim are presented in the gallery.

The 16″ Turbo alloy wheels are mounted with 225/50 Falken Ziex ZE950 A/S tires with 2022 date codes. The car is equipped with independent multi-link suspension. Stopping power is provided by anti-lock four-wheel vented disc brakes.

The 2+2 cabin features seats upholstered in Charcoal leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, center console, and door panels. Interior features include a power-adjustable driver’s seat, rear seats, an aftermarket cassette stereo, a Bose sound system, automatic climate control, and cruise control.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 43k miles, approximately 400 of which were added under current ownership.
The 3.0-liter VG30DE V6 was factory rated at 222 horsepower and 198 lb-ft of torque. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential.
Corrosion is present on underside components, additional photos of which are provided in the gallery.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage from the first entry in 1992.
The current owner signed and dated the Ohio title in July 2024.

This 1967 Porsche 911 coupe is a non-running project with no engine or transmission. The floors, rear panel, and rear quarter panels have been removed, and the shell rolls on 15″ ventilated steel wheels with polished hubcaps. The project was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, and the sale includes spare quarter panels, seats, and door panels. This SWB 911 coupe is now offered in New York at no reserve with a clean Connecticut title.

The car came finished from the factory in Aga Blue (6608), and the rear panel and both quarter panels have been removed. The front fenders are finished in gray primer, while the doors, roof, and hood have been painted dark blue. Rust, dents, and areas of prior repairs are viewable in the gallery. A replacement pair of quarter panels accompany the vehicle.

The 15″ ventilated steel wheels feature polished hubcaps and are mounted with a mixed set of tires. The car was factory equipped with an independent front suspension including an anti-sway bar, longitudinal torsion bar, upper struts, and lower wishbones. The rear semi-trailing arm setup features a transverse torsion bar.

The floors have been removed, and the interior retains a dashboard, a four-spoke steering wheel, and VDO instrumentation, including a central 8k-rpm tachometer, a 150-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and gauges for fuel level, oil level, oil temperature, and oil pressure. The five-digit odometer shows 51k miles.

A pair of black vinyl seats upholstered in black leatherette with houndstooth cloth inserts accompanies the vehicle, along with door panels and rear seats. One of the front seats has rodent damage and is missing the headrest.
No drivetrain is included in the sale.
There is rust on the underside, additional photos of which are provided in the gallery.

This 1976 Alfa Romeo Alfetta GT is said to have been sold new in California, and it was registered in Colorado before it was acquired and relocated to California by the seller in 2010. The car is powered by a replacement mechanically fuel-injected 2.0-liter inline-four, and it has been modified with a “Velocissima” body kit, a revised suspension, Recaro front bucket seats, a Momo steering wheel and shifter, and Euro-style bumpers. Finished in yellow over black and grey upholstery, the car is further equipped with a five-speed manual transaxle, 14″ alloy wheels, yellow fog lights, and a Dual CD stereo head unit. This Alfetta is a running project that is now offered with a repair manual, manufacturer’s literature, Alfa Romeo-branded bags, three keys, spare parts, and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

A set of Euro-style bumpers and a “Velocissima” body kit and rear spoiler were installed on the yellow-finished body following the seller’s acquisition. Additional details include yellow fog lights, Alfa Corsa graphics, side mirrors, and twin exhaust outlets. The rear valance was trimmed under previous ownership. There are mounting holes near the door mirrors, bubbling is shown in the center of the hood, and additional photos of paint imperfections are viewable in the gallery below.

Silver-finished 14″ alloy wheels wear Alfa Romeo center caps and are wrapped in Delinte tires. The suspension has been reportedly modified with a Shankle setup. The seller notes that the shock absorbers and suspension bushings would benefit from replacement. A set of Koni shock absorbers and replacement rubber suspension components are included in the sale.

The Recaro front bucket seats are trimmed in black vinyl with gray inserts and are complemented by black door panels and carpets. Interior appointments include a padded dashboard cover, a yellow Momo shift knob, Alfa Romeo-logo floor mats, a Dual CD stereo, a rear roll bar, and a fire extinguisher. Stains are noted on the right-front seat, and the door panels are secured with screws.

The three-spoke Momo steering wheel fronts a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline. Centrally mounted instrumentation consists of an inoperative 150-mph speedometer as well as gauges for oil pressure, fuel level, and coolant temperature. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 85k miles, and the total mileage is unknown. A replacement speedometer cable will accompany the car.

The replacement 2.0-liter inline-four features mechanical fuel injection, and it was reportedly overhauled approximately 5k miles ago. The rear fuel pump and the fuel lines are said to have recently been replaced. The seller notes a slow electrical draw, a battery cut-off switch has been installed, and the battery has been replaced in preparation for sale. The car most recently passed a California emissions test in November 2021.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a rear-mounted five-speed manual transaxle. There is a hole in the center resonator, and a replacement center exhaust section is included in the sale.
The car is registered as Planned Non-Operation in the state of California.

This 1971 Volkswagen Beetle has been modified in the style of a Baja Bug and was acquired by the seller in 2019. The body has been finished in tan and features fiberglass body panels, tubular bumpers, side rails, a winch, and a receiver hitch, while the interior has been fitted with suspension seats, a bolt-in roll cage, an EMPI trigger shifter, and a CNC Brakes single-lever turning brake system. The car has been fitted with four-wheel disc brakes and the suspension has been modified with boxed rear trailing arms, custom-fabricated chromoly lifted front spindles, and Fox Racing remote-reservoir shocks. Power comes from a replacement single-port air-cooled 1.6L flat-four paired with a Rancho Performance Pro Street four-speed manual transaxle. This Baja Bug is now offered with a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The car has been repainted in tan and is fitted with a Baja-style front valance and fenders as well as tubular bumpers, side rails, and mirror mounts. Additional exterior details consist of off-road lighting, a winch, pop-out rear quarter windows, a receiver hitch, and a rear skid plate.

Aftermarket 15″ wide-five alloy wheels are mounted with General Grabber tires measuring 205/75 up front and 30×9.5″ out back. The suspension has been lifted and features aftermarket boxed rear trailing arms, custom-fabricated chromoly lifted front spindles, and Fox Racing remote-reservoir shocks. The brakes have been converted to disc with two-piston front calipers over drilled rotors up front.  The brakes were bled in preparation for the sale.

Inside, the rear seat has been removed and a bolt-in roll cage has been fitted along with a pair of suspension seats trimmed in black vinyl and cloth upholstery. Sound-deadening material has been applied to the firewall, and additional interior elements include a keyed push-button ignition, lap belts, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, an Optima Red Top battery, an EMPI trigger shifter, and a CNC Brakes single-lever turning brake system. The wiring harness and battery were reportedly replaced under current ownership. The headliner has tears and there is no radio installed, though speakers are mounted in the rear cargo area.

Instrumentation includes a replacement 90-mph speedometer, a Sunpro tachometer, and a VDO fuel level gauge. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 3k miles, approximately 1k of which have been added under current ownership. True mileage is unknown.

The replacement single-port air-cooled 1.6L flat-four is equipped with Bosch ignition components and an EMPI off-road exhaust system. Work performed in preparation for the sale reportedly included an oil change, valve adjustment, and fan belt replacement.

Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a Rancho Performance Pro Street four-speed manual transaxle equipped with a Super diff and a heavy-duty aluminum side cover. The seller states CB Performance transaxle mounts and Type 2 axles have been installed.
listing_details: Four-Wheel Disc Brakes w/Drilled Front Rotors

description: This 2012 Ariel Atom is a track-dedicated Spec:RaceAtom (SRA) example that is powered by a 2.4-liter K24 inline-four paired with a manual transaxle. The chassis is finished in black, and additional details include black, yellow, and clear bodywork as well as a digital dashboard display, Wilwood brakes, QA1 adjustable dampers, Kirkey bucket seats, a fire-suppression system, and 15″ wheels with competition tires. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this Atom SRA is now offered in Michigan with a spare set of wheels and tires, recent service records, and a bill of sale.

The Atom features a powder-coated tubular space-frame chassis with an integrated roll bar. Details consist of black, white, and clear bodywork accented by Honda Racing, number 67, Hoosier, and Spec:RaceAtom graphics. Equipment includes dual side mirrors, rain lights, rear brake lights, and a master electrical cutoff switch. The selling dealer notes chips in the body panels.

The 15″ alloy wheels are wrapped in 205/50 front and 225/55 rear Toyo Proxes tires that were fitted in 2022. The car is equipped with QA1 adjustable dampers with coilover springs, and stopping power is provided by four-piston Wilwood calipers paired with slotted rotors. Service in 2024 included replacing the brake fluid reservoir, flushing the brake fluid, and replacing two brake pads.

The cockpit features fixed-back Kirkey seats with Sabelt harnesses. Additional equipment includes a Genesis restraint net, a Wilwood pedal set and brake bias controller, and Longacre roll bar padding.

The MOMO steering wheel is trimmed in microsuede and mounted to a quick-release hub. A Race Technology DASH2 digital display is housed in an aluminum surround and is linked to a data and video logging system. The digital odometer indicates 2k miles.

The 2.4-liter Honda K24 inline-four sends power to the rear wheels through a manual transaxle. Equipment includes a Keihin ECU, Spal electric cooling fans, and a MagnaFlow muffler. Work in 2024 involved changing the oil and replacing a fuel hose.
Additional chassis and suspension photos can be viewed in the gallery below.
A spare set of wheels mounted with Hoosier tires will accompany the car along with recent service records.
The seller cannot locate a chassis number on the car. This car does not have a title and is not legal to register for street use. It is being offered on a bill of sale.

This 1931 Buick Series 60 Eight is a Model 67 sedan that was donated to the seller, The National Museum of Transportation in St. Louis, Missouri, in 2022. The car is finished in dark blue over tan cloth upholstery, and power comes from a 273ci straight-eight paired with a three-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes four-wheel mechanical drum brakes, 19″ wood-spoke wheels, front and rear bumpers, cowl lamps, rear-hinged rear doors, a heater, and a rear cabin robe bar and footrest. This Buick Model 8-67 is now offered with a clean Missouri title in the seller’s name.

Buick built a total of 30,665 Model 8-67 sedans for the 1931 model year. This example is finished in dark blue with red pinstriping and features a bright radiator surround and bumpers as well as cowl lamps, cowl vents, running boards, rear-hinged rear doors, and a single taillight. Imperfections in the finish can be seen in the gallery.

Black-painted wood-spoke wheels feature red pinstriping and Buick-branded center caps, and they are mounted with 6.00–19 Lester bias-ply tires. A matching spare rim and tire are stowed out back. The Buick Series 60 Eight rode on a 118″ wheelbase and featured solid axles with front and rear semi-elliptical leaf springs. Stopping power is provided by mechanical drums at all four corners.

The cabin features front and rear benches trimmed in tan tufted cloth along with a color-coordinated headliner, door panels, and rear carpets. A black rubber mat lines the front floors, and additional equipment includes woodgrain dash and window trim, a heater, a rear footrest, and a robe bar mounted on the front seatback.

The four-spoke steering wheel fronts a painted steel dash housing a 90-mph barrel speedometer and gauges for oil pressure, water temperature, fuel level, and amperage. The five-digit odometer shows 45k miles, a few of which were added under the seller’s ownership. Total mileage is unknown.
The 273ci straight-eight features five main bearings and a Marvel carburetor, and it was factory rated at 90 horsepower. The water pump was reportedly serviced in 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a three-speed manual transmission.
The car is titled using the reproduction VIN tag shown above.

This 1954 Chevrolet Bel Air convertible was modified under previous ownership and is powered by a 350ci V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. Other work included refinishing the body in blue over gray leather upholstery, installing a Heidts Mustang II front suspension, a four-link rear suspension, a RideTech Air Ride system, Packard-style tail lights, and remote door poppers as well as shaving the hood, trunk, and door handles, and smoothing the firewall and inner fenders. The car is also equipped with a dark charcoal convertible top, 15″ wheels with chrome hubcaps, power steering, power-assisted front disc brakes, a Flowmaster dual exhaust system, a CD stereo, and Vintage Air air conditioning. The carburetor, air conditioning compressor, fuel pressure regulator, battery, and spark plugs are said to have been replaced in 2024. Previously listed on BaT in April 2024, this Bel Air is now offered at no reserve by the selling dealer in Texas with a clean Louisiana title.

The car is finished in blue and features a dark charcoal convertible soft top, a chrome front bumper, a painted rear bumper, Packard-style tail lights, a shaved hood and trunk, and shaved door handles with remote poppers.

The 15″ steel wheels wear chrome hubcaps and Auburn whitewall tires measuring 205/75. A Heidts Mustang II front suspension, a four-link rear suspension, and a RideTech Air Ride system are fitted. Braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums, and the car is equipped with power steering. The air ride system is said to have been rebuilt in preparation for the sale.

The seating surfaces are upholstered in gray leather, and interior appointments include an air suspension controller, a Sony CD stereo, aftermarket speakers, cupholders, lap belts, and Vintage Air air conditioning.

The billet leather-wrapped steering wheel sits ahead of white Dakota Digital gauges. The digital odometer shows 2k miles, approximately 150 of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 350ci V8 was installed under previous ownership and features an Edelbrock four-barrel carburetor, coated exhaust headers, a Flowmaster dual exhaust system, an aluminum radiator, and a bright brake master cylinder and booster, alternator, air conditioning compressor, pulleys, and mounting brackets. The firewall and inner fenders were smoothed and the battery was relocated to the rear of the vehicle. Service in preparation for the sale included replacing the carburetor, air conditioning compressor, spark plugs, fuel pressure regulator, and battery.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a TH350 three-speed automatic transmission. The selling dealer states a dry-ice cleaning was performed followed by application of POR-15 coating.

This 2006 Porsche Cayenne Turbo S remained within the original owner’s family until the selling dealer’s acquisition in 2024 and now has 48k miles. The truck is powered by a paired with a six-speed Tiptronic S automatic transmission and is finished in Titanium Metallic over black leather. Equipment includes all-wheel drive with a variable center differential, bi-xenon headlights, ParkAssist, 20″ Cayenne SportDesign alloy wheels, heated power-adjustable front seats, Porsche Communication Management, navigation, a Bose sound system, dual-zone automatic climate control, and cruise control. This Cayenne Turbo S is now offered with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.
The truck is finished in Titanium Metallic and features bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, front and rear parking sensors, quad exhaust outlets, and a rear window wiper.

The 20″ Cayenne SportDesign alloy wheels are mounted with 295/45 Yokohama Parada tires that are said to have been fitted in preparation for the sale. The truck is equipped with an air suspension and Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM). Stopping power is from Porsche-branded calipers over ventilated rotors at each corner.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats upholstered in black leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Amenities include Porsche Communication Management, navigation, a Bose sound system, dual-zone automatic climate control, and cruise control.

The multi-function leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 180-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil temperature, coolant temperature, fuel level, and boost pressure. The digital odometer indicates 48k miles.

The twin-turbocharged 4.5-liter V8 was factory rated at 520 horsepower and 530 lb-ft of torque. The ignition coils and coolant reservoir were replaced in February 2022 and an oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
Power is routed to all four wheels through a six-speed Tiptronic S automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, a variable center differential, and Porsche Traction Management.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2016 Land Rover Range Rover Supercharged was registered in Florida and South Carolina until 2024, and it has 56k miles. Finished in Mariana Black Metallic over Ivory and Ebony leather, it was optioned with 22″ wheels, the Vision Assist Package, which included blind-spot monitoring and a surround camera system, and the Driver Assistance Package, which featured a head-up display and a suite of active parking aids. Heated and ventilated front seats, heated rear seats, InControl touchscreen infotainment, and a Meridian sound system are additional elements. Power comes from a supercharged 5.0-liter V8 linked with an eight-speed automatic transmission. The selling dealer serviced the electronic air suspension and replaced brake components and the tires in preparation for the sale. This Range Rover Supercharged is offered in New York with owner’s manuals, two keys, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Montana title.
The metallic black finish is contrasted by Atlas trim, and the vehicle has LED signature lighting, adaptive xenon headlamps, soft-close doors, power-folding mirrors, and a powered Gesture tailgate.

The 22″ split-spoke wheels are mounted with Continental CrossContact LX Sport tires that show 2023 production date codes. Additional equipment includes selectable Terrain Response 2 driving modes, Adaptive Dynamics continously variable damping, and Dynamic Response hydraulic roll control. The control arms, brake rotors and pads, and front air shocks were replaced in 2024.

The heated and ventilated front seats are trimmed in Ivory Oxford leather, while Ebony leather and Grand Black wood trim accent the cabin, which has a sliding panoramic roof, a Meridian surround sound system, an 8″ touchscreen, configurable mood lighting, solar-attenuating privacy glass, three-zone automatic climate control, and heated rear seats.

The heated steering wheel has paddle shifters and is mounted on a power-adjustable column, and the driver is aided by a heated windshield, a head-up display, a surround camera system, blind-spot monitors, parking sensors, Parallel Parking, Parking Exit, Perpendicular Parking, 360° Park Distance Control, and All Terrain Progress Control, which is an off-road cruise control system for low speeds. The odometer indicates 56k miles.

The supercharged 5.0-liter V8 was factory rated at 510 horsepower and 461 lb-ft of torque, and it sends power to all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case with an electronic locking center differential. An oil change was completed in preparation for the sale.
Additional photographs of the underside are shown in the gallery below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2001 Ducati MH900e is number 1,519 of 2,000 produced, and this example was purchased new by its current owner. Now indicating 686 kilometers (~426 miles), the motorcycle is finished in red with silver graphics. Power is provided by a 904cc desmodromic L-twin paired with a six-speed transmission, and equipment includes Marelli electronic fuel injection, a Showa adjustable fork, a Paioli shock, triple disc brakes, and five-spoke 17″ Antera wheels along with a front fairing, a solo seat, clip-on handlebars, side mirrors, and a side stand. This MH900e is offered by the seller on behalf of the owner with a display plaque, a paddock stand, a shipping crate, and a clean Pennsylvania title in the owner’s name.

The MH900e was designed by Pierre Terblanche as an homage to Mike Hailwood’s 1978 Isle of Man TT-winning Ducati 900 SS, and each example left the factory finished in red with silver graphics over a color-coordinated trellis frame. Additional features include a black vinyl-upholstered solo seat, an integrated front fairing, a clear windscreen, dual mirrors, and a side stand.

Five-spoke 17″ Antera wheels wear 120/65 front and 170/60 rear Michelin Pilot Sport tires. Suspension consists of an inverted 43mm Showa fork as well as a Paioli shock attached to the tubular single-sided swingarm. Braking components include dual 320mm rotors with four-piston Brembo calipers up front and a 220mm rotor with a two-piston Brembo caliper at the rear.

Clip-on handlebars are mounted below the upper triple clamp, which fronts a chrome-ringed 10k-rpm tachometer and a digital display that shows menu options and a speedometer. The digital odometer indicates 686 kilometers (~426 miles).
A plate on the fuel tank cover denotes this motorcycle as #1519 of 2,000 MH900evoluzione units produced. An Eric Bostrom signature is visible on the fuel tank cover.

The air-cooled 904cc L-twin features an oil cooler, Marelli fuel injection, a desmodromic valvetrain, and satin black exhaust head pipes with a chrome heat shield. Factory-rated output was 75 horsepower and 56 lb-ft of torque. The battery was changed in July 2024.
Power is routed to the rear wheel through a dry clutch, a six-speed transmission, and a drive chain.

A display plaque will accompany the motorcycle along with a paddock stand, factory literature, and various accessories. Close-up photos of a numbered factory shipping crate can be viewed in the gallery below.

This 1998 Alfa Romeo 156 is a right-hand-drive example that was imported from Japan to the US in 2024 following the selling dealer’s acquisition. It is powered by a 2.5-liter Busso V6 paired with a six-speed manual transaxle and is finished in red over black leather. Equipment includes 17″ alloy wheels, headlight washers, fog lights, automatic climate control, a Pioneer head unit, faux carbon fiber interior trim, and power windows, locks, and mirrors. This Alfa Romeo 156 shows 102k kilometers (~64k miles) and is now offered at no reserve by the selling dealer with manufacturer’s literature, import documents, a removed head unit and CD changer, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Washington title.

The car is finished in red and features headlight washers, fog lights, power-adjustable mirrors, bright front door handles, and a single polished exhaust outlet. Scratches are evident on the rocker panels.
Silver-finished 17″ alloy wheels are mounted with 215/45 Bridgestone Regno tires. Braking is handled by power-assisted discs at all four corners.

The front bucket seats are upholstered in black leather with embossed Alfa Romeo logos in each seatback along with MOMO logos embossed into the sides of the headrests. A dashcam and a Pioneer head unit have been retrofitted, and appointments include automatic climate control, faux carbon fiber trim, aluminum pedals, and Alfa Romeo-branded floor mats.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 260-km/h speedometer and a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline. An analog clock and additional readouts for monitoring coolant temperature and fuel level and mounted in the center stack. The digital odometer shows 102k kilometers (~64k miles), approximately 2k of which have been added by the selling dealer.
The 2.5-liter Busso V6 features four valves per cylinder and was factory rated at 187 horsepower.
Power is delivered to the front wheels via a six-speed manual transaxle.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1972 International Harvester Scout II was repainted dark red under prior ownership, and it is powered by a 345ci V8. Equipment includes a Dana 20 dual-range transfer case, round headlights, a three-slot grille, front vent windows, an aftermarket front bumper, a roll bar, a receiver hitch, power steering, a body lift, manually locking front hubs, front disc brakes, aftermarket wheels, front bucket seats, and a folding rear bench. The truck was acquired by the seller in 2017 and was subsequently fitted with a three-speed automatic 727 transmission, a “steer straight” steering brace, and a replacement tailgate. This Scout II is now offered with service records, spare parts, a car cover, and a clean Ohio title in the seller’s name.

The truck was repainted in a Mercedes-Benz shade of Saturnrot Pearl under prior ownership, and a replacement tailgate was installed and refinished to match the body since the seller’s acquisition. A replacement windshield, mirrors, and aftermarket front bumper were also installed. The seller notes prior metal replacement in the front, rear, and bed. The left side of the hood is bent, there are scratches and dings, and rust on the bedrails is shown in the gallery. Replacement bedrail strips are included in the sale.

The aftermarket black-finished wheels are mounted with 28” Dominator Sport A/T tires. The truck is equipped with manually locking front hubs and power steering, and a body lift has been fitted. Stopping power is provided by front discs and rear drums. The front calipers, rotors, shocks, rear drums, and rear wheel cylinders were reportedly replaced under current ownership, and a “steer straight” steering brace was installed.

The cabin houses front bucket seats and a folding rear bench trimmed in Jet Black vinyl. A textured bedliner material has been applied to the interior, and a GRC roll bar has been added along with shoulder belts, a center console with cupholders, and a Bluetooth speaker. There is a tear on the driver’s seat, the radio is not hooked up, and the heater and air conditioning are inoperative. The seller states that the right window is hard to roll down, the passenger door lock requires a new rubber stopper, and the interior drvier’s door handle is inoperative.

The three-spoke steering wheel fronts a horizontal 120-mph speedometer and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, amperage, and fuel level. A Sunpro tachometer is mounted to the steering column and a three-gauge pod is housed below the dash. The five-digit odometer shows 84k miles, approximately 250 of which were added under current ownership. An aftermarket fuel level gauge was added and the speedometer cable was replaced under current ownership.

The 345ci V8 was factory rated at 197 horsepower and 309 lb-ft of torque. The seller notes the carburetor has been rebuilt, though it requires adjustment. A replacement fuel pump was also installed under current ownership.

A rebuilt three-speed 727 automatic transmission was installed in place of the factory manual gearbox in 2021, and power is routed to the rear or all four wheels through a Dana 20 two-speed transfer case. The U-joints, axles, and driveshafts were reportedly replaced under current ownership. Leaks are noted from the transfer case.

This 1966 Lotus Cortina MK1 was used as a race car in Arizona and California from the early 1970s until the mid-2010s. It is powered by a replacement 1,558cc Lotus Twin-Cam four and equipped with a four-speed manual gearbox, limited-slip differential, Fuel Safe fuel cell, front strut tower brace, and 13″ Panasport wheels. The selling dealer acquired the car in early 2024 and subsequent service included changing the fluids, adjusting the carburetors, and replacing the brake master cylinder. This Lotus Cortina is now offered with a spare set of wheels, a bolt-in roll bar, service records, an SCCA log book, and a clean California title.
The car is finished in white and green and the selling dealer notes that it was recently repainted. Close-up photos of the paint, trim, and badges can be found in the gallery.

Silver 13″ Panasport wheels are mounted with 185/60 Avon Turbospeed CR28 tires, and a set of factory steel wheels and hubcaps are included. Service in preparation for the sale included replacing the brake master cylinder, bleeding the fluid, and adjusting the brake bias.
The cabin is upholstered in black vinyl with matching carpets and features lap seatbelts, a three-spoke wood-rim steering wheel, and a wood shift knob. The heater controls are disconnected.

Instrumentation includes a 140-mph speedometer, a 6,500-rpm-redline tachometer, and gauges for oil pressure, water temperature, voltage, and fuel level. Toggle switches to control the fuel pump and fan have been added to a radio blanking plate.

The replacement 1,558cc Lotus twin-cam inline-four was installed circa 2019 and is equipped with twin Weber side draft carburetors. Service in February 2024 included changing the fluids and adjusting the carburetors. An electric radiator fan and aftermarket front strut tower brace are installed.
A Fuel Safe cell is mounted in the trunk along with a pump, filter, and battery.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential.
A removed bolt-in roll bar is included in the sale along with a spare fuel tank.
Factory books, period literature, and a SCCA log book are also included.

This 2014 Chevrolet Corvette Stingray convertible is powered by a replacement 6.2-liter LT1 V8 fitted with a Procharger D-1SC supercharger and intercooler, a TSP camshaft, a revised rotating assembly, an MSD Atomic intake manifold, Kooks long-tube exhaust headers, and a Corsa Performance cat-back exhaust system.  Finished in Arctic White over Black leather, the car is equipped with a six-speed automatic gearbox, a limited-slip differential, the 3LT Preferred Equipment Group, black 19″ and 20″ split-spoke alloy wheels, xenon headlights, a black convertible soft top, a carbon-fiber hood insert, and a rear spoiler. The cabin is outfitted with heated and ventilated bucket seats, a head-up display, a Bose sound system, and MyLink infotainment. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2023, this C7 Stingray is now offered in Georgia with a clean Texas title.

The car is finished in Arctic White and features xenon headlights, a black convertible soft top, a vented carbon-fiber hood, a carbon-fiber hood insert, a rear spoiler, power-adjustable mirrors, and quadruple exhaust outlets. A 2015 Carfax report entry lists “minor damage” to the rear of the vehicle.

Black-finished 19″ and 20″ split-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Kumho Ecsta front and Nitto Motivo rear tires. The car is equipped with an Active Handling System with all-speed traction control. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel slotted and ventilated rotors.

The heated and ventilated bucket seats are upholstered in black leather. Interior features include a head-up display, a Bose sound system, automatic climate control, cruise control, keyless entry, and a touchscreen infotainment system.

The multifunction steering wheel frames a 205-mph speedometer and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level as well as a center digital display with an integrated tachometer and virtual gauges. The digital odometer indicates 29k miles.

The 6.2-liter LT1 V8 was reportedly replaced and rebuilt under prior ownership and fitted with a Procharger D-1SC supercharger and intercooler, a TSP camshaft, a revised rotating assembly, an MSD Atomic intake manifold, Kooks long-tube exhaust headers, and a Corsa Performance cat-back exhaust system. Additional work under prior ownership is said to consist of replacing the following:
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed automatic gearbox and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned accident in 2015.

This Norton VR880 Sprint Special is one of fewer than 50 examples that were built during the 1990s by Kenny Dreer of Vintage Rebuilds in Clackamas, Oregon. The remanufactured bike is based on a 1974 Commando 850 that was provided by the seller, and it utilizes approximately 80% all-new parts. The motorcycle is powered by a modified 880cc parallel twin equipped with a Mega Cycle camshaft, a Boyer-Bransden electronic ignition system, and dual Keihin flat-slide carburetors, and it is one of fewer than 10 examples that were built with hand-hammered aluminum bodywork by Evan Wilcox. Additional equipment includes a four-speed transmission, a Gates primary belt drive, an electric starter, a modified Roadholder fork, Progressive Suspension shocks, alloy rims, triple disc brakes, a racing-style seat, custom-bent 1.5″ headpipes, and chrome reverse-cone megaphone mufflers. This VR880 Sprint Special was delivered to the seller in September 1999 and is now offered with the original purchase agreement, dynamometer results, service records, a copy of the September 1999 issue of Cycle World magazine in which the model is featured, and a clean South Carolina title in the seller’s name.

Aluminum bodywork hand-formed by Evan Wilcox wears black Norton graphics with red and black stripes and is mounted over a braced and black powder-coasted Isolastic frame. Features include a black racing-style seat with a rear cowl as well as a black-finished front fender, rear-set foot controls, and a center stand.

Wire-spoke wheels measuring 19″ front and 18″ rear are mounted with Avon RoadRider MK II tires. Suspension is handled by a Roadholder fork with modified Honda CBR600F3 cartridges and alloy sliders as well as a pair of preload-adjustable Progressive Suspension shocks mounted to the swingarm. Brakes were sourced from Kosman Engineering out of San Francisco, California, and consist of dual floating drilled rotors with custom hubs and single-piston GMA calipers up front and a single version at the rear. A piston-type damper spans the lower steering stem and the left frame downtube.

A chrome handlebar equipped with bar-end mirrors fronts a 120-mph VDO speedometer, a matching adjustable tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline, and a Lucas ammeter inset atop the chrome headlight bucket. The digital odometer indicates 11k miles. Total mileage is unknown.

The 829cc OHV parallel twin was fitted with with bored cylinders and custom-made 79mm JE Pistons which increased displacement to 880cc. The cylinder heads were ported, the crankshaft was lightened and balanced, and a strengthened re-cast left-side crankcase was utilized. Additional equipment includes dual 35mm Keihin FCR pumper carburetors, Kibblewhite valves, guides, springs, and retainers, a Mega Cycle 6000-series camshaft, alloy connecting rods, a Boyer-Bransden electronic ignition system, a Dyna dual-output coil, and custom-bent 1.5″ headpipes flowing into a pair of upswept reverse-cone megaphone mufflers. The bike was returned to Dreer for the installment of an electric starter, and the starter ring gear was replaced in preparation for the sale.

Power is sent to the rear wheel through a Gates primary belt drive, a four-speed transmission with right-side shifting, and a drive chain. The three-piece cush-drive sprocket was sourced from aerospace manufacturer Sertco Industries of Okemah, Oklahoma.

This 2015 Porsche Cayenne Diesel is finished in Moonlight Blue Metallic over Agate Grey standard leather and is powered by a 3.0-liter turbodiesel V6 linked with an eight-speed Tiptronic S automatic transmission and a locking center differential. It is equipped with the Sport Chrono, Premium, Infotainment, and Dark Walnut Interior packages as well as Adaptive Cruise Control, 19″ Cayenne Turbo wheels, a panoramic sunroof, heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats, a Bose surround-sound system, PCM with navigation, and xenon headlights with PDLS. The SUV remained with its original owner in California until 2024, and it now has 128k miles. This Cayenne Diesel is now offered in Virginia at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a clean Ohio title.

The vehicle is finished in Moonlight Blue Metallic and features xenon headlights with the Porsche Dynamic Light System (PDLS) as well as a panoramic sunroof, a receiver hitch, front and rear ParkAssist, aluminum-look roof rails, and LED taillights. Exterior blemishes are pointed out in the photo gallery below.

The 19″ Cayenne Turbo alloy wheels are mounted with 265/50 Michelin Pilot Sport All Season 4 tires. Stopping power is provided by six-piston front and four-piston rear brake calipers over ventilated rotors at each corner.

The heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats and the rear bench have debossed Porsche crests on the headrests and are upholstered in Agate Grey leather complemented by dark walnut wood trim. Amenities include Adaptive Cruise Control with Porsche Active Safe (PAS) as well as Porsche Entry & Drive, a Bose surround-sound system, Lane Change Assist (LCA), and dual-zone automatic climate control.

The heated leather- and wood-rimmed sport steering wheel features shift paddles and frames a central tachometer, a 175-mph speedometer, a configurable digital display, and gauges for oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The Sport Chrono Package added a stopwatch atop the dashboard. The digital odometer indicates 128k miles.

The 3.0-liter turbodiesel V6 was factory rated at 240 horsepower and 406 lb-ft of torque. The Carfax report notes drive belt replacement in July 2023, and work in preparation for the sale is said to have included changing the oil and replacing the exhaust temperature sensor.
Power is sent to all four wheels through an eight-speed Tiptronic S automatic transmission and a locking center differential.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1958 Morgan Plus 4 four-passenger roadster was sold new by Fergus Imported Cars of New York City. It is said to have remained under single ownership for over 40 years before changing hands in 2021 and being acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. Finished in black over red leather, the car is powered by a 1,991cc inline-four paired with a four-speed manual transmission, and equipment includes a black soft top, 15″ wire wheels, a rear-mounted spare, fender-mounted side mirrors, fog lights, seatbelts, removable side curtains, a heater, and chrome bumpers. This Plus 4 is now offered by the selling dealer with a clean Pennsylvania title.

The car was repainted black approximately 25 years ago, with more recent paintwork noted on the rear fenders. Additional features include a black soft top, running boards, a leather hood strap, fender-mounted side mirrors, Lucas fog lights, wind wings, side curtains, and chrome bumpers.

The 15″ wire wheels with knock-off hubs were installed in 2023 and are mounted with 185SR15 Michelin XZX tires, and a spare is affixed to the rear. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel drum brakes that were reportedly serviced in 2023.
The four-passenger cabin features seating trimmed in red leather. Additional equipment includes a wood dashboard, seatbelts, a cabin heater, and a dash-mounted rearview mirror.

The banjo-style steering wheel fronts Smiths instrumentation including a 6k-rpm tachometer, a 110-mph speedometer, and a combination gauge for oil pressure, fuel level, coolant temperature, and amperage. The five-digit odometer shows 70k miles, approximately 50 of which were added under current ownership. The coolant temperature gauge was repaired in preparation for the sale.
The Triumph-sourced 1,991cc inline-four is fitted with dual Zenith carburetors and was factory rated at 100 horsepower. A tune-up is said to have been performed in 2023.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission.
Number 3969 displayed on the plate shown above corresponds with the VIN listed on the Pennsylvania title.

This 1997 BMW M3 is a left-hand-drive European-specification coupe that was first sold in Japan, and it was acquired and imported to the US in 2024 by the selling dealer. Finished in Estoril Blue Metallic over M-Cross cloth and anthracite Amaretta upholstery, the car has been fitted with 18″ BBS wheels, Bilstein coilovers, an aftermarket intake and front splitters, chrome trunk trim and kidney grilles, aftermarket rear exhaust components, Hella xenon headlights, and a ZHP shift knob. Powered by a 3.2-liter inline-six linked with a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential, the car is also equipped with manually adjustable Vader front sport seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, and an aftermarket Pioneer stereo head unit. This E36 M3 coupe has 75k kilometers (~47k miles) and is now offered by the selling dealer in Virginia with manufacturer’s literature, import document copies, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Tennessee title.

Estoril Blue Metallic paint finishes the exterior, and modifications include aftermarket front splitters, Hella xenon headlights, and a chrome-finished trunk finisher and kidney grilles. Additional details include fog lights, clear front corner markers, a sunroof, dual exhaust outlets, and factory aerodynamic bumpers, side sills, and mirrors. The selling dealer reports that the hood has been repainted.

Silver-finished 18″ BBS wheels are mounted with older 225/40 front and 255/35 rear Michelin Pilot Sport tires. The car rides on Bilstein coilovers, and braking is handled by ventilated discs at each corner.

The cabin houses manually adjustable Vader sport seats trimmed in M-Cross cloth with anthracite Amaretta bolsters as well as matching door panel inserts and fold-down rear seats. A ZHP shift knob and a Pioneer stereo head unit have been added, and additional details consist of dual-zone automatic climate control, an auto-dimming rearview mirror, and power windows, mirrors, and locks. There are dead pixels in the onboard computer display.

A leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a 280-km/h speedometer, a tachometer with a 7,400-rpm redline, and supplementary gauges. The digital odometer indicates 75k kilometers (~47k miles), approximately 100 of which were added under current ownership.

The 3.2-liter S50B32 inline-six is equipped with individual throttle bodies as well as double VANOS variable valve timing, and it was factory rated at 321 horsepower and 258 lb-ft of torque. An aftermarket intake has been installed, and the selling dealer states that the oil was changed and the fuel pump was replaced in preparation for the sale.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. Aftermarket rear exhaust components were installed under previous ownership, and additional photos of the underside are viewable in the gallery below.
Japanese-language manufacturer’s literature and import document copies are included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1997 BMW M3 is a left-hand-drive European-specification coupe that was first sold in Japan, and it was acquired and imported to the US in 2024 by the selling dealer. Finished in Estoril Blue Metallic over M-Cross cloth and anthracite Amaretta upholstery, the car has been fitted with 18″ BBS wheels, Bilstein coilovers, an aftermarket intake and front splitters, chrome trunk trim and kidney grilles, aftermarket rear exhaust components, Hella xenon headlights, and a ZHP shift knob. Powered by a 3.2-liter inline-six linked with a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential, the car is also equipped with manually adjustable Vader front sport seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, and an aftermarket Pioneer stereo head unit. This E36 M3 coupe has 75k kilometers (~47k miles) and is now offered by the selling dealer in Virginia with manufacturer’s literature, import document copies, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Tennessee title.

Estoril Blue Metallic paint finishes the exterior, and modifications include aftermarket front splitters, Hella xenon headlights, and a chrome-finished trunk finisher and kidney grilles. Additional details include fog lights, clear front corner markers, a sunroof, dual exhaust outlets, and factory aerodynamic bumpers, side sills, and mirrors. The selling dealer reports that the hood has been repainted.

Silver-finished 18″ BBS wheels are mounted with older 225/40 front and 255/35 rear Michelin Pilot Sport tires. The car rides on Bilstein coilovers, and braking is handled by ventilated discs at each corner.

The cabin houses manually adjustable Vader sport seats trimmed in M-Cross cloth with anthracite Amaretta bolsters as well as matching door panel inserts and fold-down rear seats. A ZHP shift knob and a Pioneer stereo head unit have been added, and additional details consist of dual-zone automatic climate control, an auto-dimming rearview mirror, and power windows, mirrors, and locks. There are dead pixels in the onboard computer display.

A leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a 280-km/h speedometer, a tachometer with a 7,400-rpm redline, and supplementary gauges. The digital odometer indicates 75k kilometers (~47k miles), approximately 100 of which were added under current ownership.

The 3.2-liter S50B32 inline-six is equipped with individual throttle bodies as well as double VANOS variable valve timing, and it was factory rated at 321 horsepower and 258 lb-ft of torque. An aftermarket intake has been installed, and the selling dealer states that the oil was changed and the fuel pump was replaced in preparation for the sale.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. Aftermarket rear exhaust components were installed under previous ownership, and additional photos of the underside are viewable in the gallery below.
Japanese-language manufacturer’s literature and import document copies are included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2005 Chrysler PT Cruiser GT convertible spent time with one owner in Alabama before the selling dealer’s 2024 acquisition, and it now has 8k miles. A turbocharged 2.4-liter inline-four sends power to the front wheels through a four-speed automatic transaxle with a manual-shift mode. Finished in Inferno Red Crystal Pearl over Pearl Beige leather upholstery, the car is equipped with a sport suspension, chrome-finished 17″ wheels, a power-operated beige soft top, fog lights, heated front seats, air conditioning, and a factory stereo with an in-dash CD changer. This PT Cruiser convertible is now offered by the selling dealer with manufacturer’s literature, two keys with remote fobs, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Inferno Red Crystal Pearl and features a power-operated beige soft top with a glass rear window as well as a body-color roll bar, fog lights, bright badges and door handles, chrome wheel arch moldings, and a single exhaust outlet with a polished tip.

Chrome-finished 17″ alloy wheels wear 205/50 Goodyear Eagle RS-A tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel anti-lock discs, and the car is equipped with a sport suspension, a front stabilizer bar, and traction control.

The heated front seats and the split-folding rear bench seat are upholstered in Pearl Beige leather with gray inserts. Body-matched red trim accents the two-tone dashboard, and appointments include air conditioning, cruise control, a satin silver-finished gear selector knob, an under-seat storage drawer, power windows, locks, and mirrors, and a factory AM/FM stereo with an in-dash CD changer.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 140-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates under 8k miles.
The turbocharged 2.4-liter “High Output” inline-four was factory rated at 215 horsepower and 245 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the front wheels through a four-speed automatic transaxle with an Autostick manual-shifting mode.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 1985 Land Rover 90 is a left-hand-drive example that was fitted with a Cummins R2.8 turbodiesel inline-four and a replacement five-speed manual transmission and dual-range transfer case under previous ownership. Finished in gray over black leather, it is equipped with an Alisport intercooler and radiator as well as a Spectre air intake, 16″ steel wheels, Fox front shocks, Bilstein rear shocks, Old Man Emu springs, and LED headlights. Other features include inward-facing jump seats, an Alpine head unit, aftermarket speakers, and air conditioning. The truck was imported to the US under previous ownership and was acquired by the seller on BaT in February 2023. This Land Rover 90 is offered with a Carfax report and a clean Georgia title in the seller’s name.

The truck is said to have been repaired and repainted in its current shade of gray under previous ownership. Exterior features include LED headlights, black fender flares, sliding rear windows, and windshield vents. Checker-plate trim was installed under current ownership.

Black-finished 16″ steel wheels wear 255/85 Bighorn Maxxis tires, and a matching spare is secured to the rear. The truck rides on a lifted suspension with Old Man Emu coil springs and Fox shocks up front and Bilstein shocks out back. Stopping power is provided by front discs and rear drums. 30mm wheel spacers are installed.

The cabin features front bucket seats and inward-facing jump seats that have been reupholstered in black Exmoor Trim leather. Work under previous ownership included installing a custom-fabricated rear bulkhead delete bar, applying Dynamat sound deadening material to the cab floor, and modifying the lower dash to accommodate a Ministry of Defender heating and air conditioning system. A Focal amplifier, BLAM speakers, JL Audio subwoofers, and an Alpine head unit with Apple CarPlay were added under current ownership along with carpet and a rubber mat in the cargo area.

Instrumentation includes a 120-mph speedometer, auxiliary gauges, and a Murphy digital display. The six digit-mechanical odometer shows 19k miles, approximately 5k of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown. The coolant temperature gauge does not work.

The Cummins R2.8 turbodiesel inline-four crate engine was installed under previous ownership along with a replacement R380 five-speed manual transmission and LT230 dual-range transfer case. The engine has been fitted with a Spectre air intake as well as an Alisport intercooler and radiator with an electric puller fan. A Tom Wood’s custom rear driveshaft and a Britpart exhaust system are installed. The fuse box was upgraded under current ownership according to the seller, and an oil change was performed in June 2024.
Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2016 Jeep Grand Cherokee SRT Night is a black-over-black example powered by a 6.4-liter Hemi V8 linked to an eight-speed automatic transmission, a Quadra-Trac active on-demand four-wheel-drive system, and an electronic limited-slip rear differential. It remained registered to its original owner until 2024 and was later acquired by the selling dealer. The vehicle has a Bilstein active-damping suspension, 20″ alloy wheels, Brembo disc brakes, a panoramic sunroof, heated and ventilated front seats, a heated second-row bench, a Harman Kardon sound system, and a suite of electronic driving aids. This Grand Cherokee SRT has 5k miles and is offered with a clean Carfax report and a clean New Jersey title.

SRT Night vehicles feature gloss-black trim, and this one is finished in Brilliant Black Crystal Pearl. Exterior equipment includes a panoramic sunroof, a power-operated tailgate, a receiver hitch, bi-xenon headlights, LED taillights, parking sensors, and dual exhaust outlets. Photos of paint meter readings are provided in the image gallery below.

Black Satin-finished 20″ alloy wheels are wrapped in 295/45 Pirelli Scorpion Verde All Season tires. The SRT rides on a Bilstein active-damping suspension and braking is handled by gloss red Brembo calipers over a ventilated disc at each corner. There are scuffs on the wheels.

The heated and ventilated front seats and heated split-folding rear bench are upholstered in black Laguna leather with SRT logos debossed in the front backrests. Carbon-fiber trim accents the dashboard and door panels, and additional appointments include remote start, keyless Enter-N-Go, push-button ignition, dual-zone automatic climate control, a rearview camera, navigation, and an 8.4″ Uconnect infotainment system linked to a 19-speaker Harman Kardon sound system.

The heated steering wheel features paddle shifters and is mounted on a power tilting and telescoping column. Instrumentation consists of a central digital tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline flanked by a 180-mph speedometer and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 5k miles. Adaptive cruise control and blind-spot and cross-path detection were standard equipment.
The 6.4-liter Hemi V8 was factory rated at 475 horsepower and 470 lb-ft of torque. The fuel injection system was flushed in April 2021.
Power is delivered to all four wheels via an eight-speed automatic transmission, a Quadra-Trac active on-demand four-wheel-drive system, and an electronic limited-slip rear differential.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The New Jersey title is a duplicate.

This 1987 Rolls-Royce Silver Spur spent time in the US Virgin Islands and was imported to the contiguous US in 2001 before being exported to Canada in 2009, where it was reportedly acquired by the selling dealer in 2022 before it was brought back to the US in 2024. Now showing 22k miles, the car is finished in white with a color-coordinated vinyl roof over white leather and powered by 6.75-liter V8 paired with three-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes a self-leveling suspension and 15″ steel wheels with polished hubcaps as well as power-adjustable front seats, automatic climate control, a Pioneer CD/cassette stereo, and folding rear table trays. This Silver Spur is offered by the selling dealer with a clean Carfax report and a clean Washington title.
The car is finished in White (9510235) with gold pinstriping and features a white vinyl roof, a gold Spirit of Ecstasy grille ornament, bright trim, and window tint film.

The 15″ steel wheels wear polished covers with painted accents and are wrapped in 225/75 Toyo Eclipse narrow-whitewall tires. The Silver Spur features a hydropneumatic self-leveling suspension, the shock absorbers for which are said to have been recently replaced. Braking is handled by discs at each corner. The Rolls-Royce emblem is missing from the left front wheel cover.

The power-adjustable front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in white leather with tan piping while burl wood trim accents the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Appointments include front seat position memory settings, automatic climate control, cruise control, power windows, folding rear table trays, and a Pioneer CD/cassette stereo. The courtesy lights are non-functional.
The two-spoke steering wheel fronts a Jaeger 140-mph speedometer and gauges for oil pressure, voltage, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 22k miles.
The 6.75-liter L410 V8 features Bosch fuel injection and was factory rated at 220 horsepower.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a GM THM400 three-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage from an initial entry in March 2001.

This 1990 Freightliner Unimog FLU419 is a former US military vehicle that is said to have been previously owned by a fire department before being purchased by the seller in 2023. The truck is finished in red and has been fitted with a rear cargo bed featuring bedside storage lockers. The cab houses bucket seats trimmed in black vinyl, and power comes from a 5.7-liter Mercedes-Benz diesel inline-six mated to a manual gearbox and a dual-range transfer case. Further equipment includes portal axles, locking differentials, 20″ steel wheels, four-wheel disc brakes, and power-assisted steering along with an air intake snorkel, a front brush guard, a receiver hitch, and a rear bumper with a retractable step. Previously listed on BaT in April 2024, this Freightliner Unimog is now offered with a US Army service manual and a clean Georgia title in the seller’s name listing the truck as a 1990 Freightliner FLA086.

The Unimog 419 was classified as a Small Emplacement Excavator and was used by the US Army as an engineering vehicle. This example was repainted in red under previous ownership and features a rear cargo bed with bedside storage lockers. The front bumper incorporates a brush guard along with a roller fairlead for a winch, while the rear bumper features a pull-out step and is accompanied by a receiver hitch. Further details include an air intake snorkel, vent windows, and side steps.

The 20″ six-lug steel wheels are finished in black and wear Mercedes-Benz center caps. They are mounted with 335/80 Continental MPT 81 tires, and a spare is stored in the bed. The truck is equipped with power-assisted steering, and braking is handled by discs at all four corners.

The cab is equipped with low-back bucket seats trimmed in black vinyl upholstery along with a color-matched engine cover and door panels. Controls for the gearbox and transfer case are located between the seats.

A two-spoke steering wheel frames a 65-mph VDO speedometer and auxiliary gauges, and a Ricker Instrument Company inclinometer is fitted atop the instrument panel. The six-digit odometer shows 2,200 miles, while an engine hour meter mounted in the engine bay shows 914 hours of runtime. Total mileage is unknown. The tachometer does not work.

The 5.7-liter Mercedes-Benz OM352 diesel inline-six was factory rated at 110 horsepower. It is linked to a four-speed manual gearbox with a high/low range and a splitter, offering sixteen forward gears and eight reverse gears.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a dual-range transfer case, locking differentials, and portal axles. Corrosion beneath the battery box can be seen in the gallery.
The chassis plate shown above lists a February 1990 build date.
listing_details: Rear Cargo Bed w/ Storage Lockers

description: This 1985 Toyota Land Cruiser HJ47 pickup is said to have spent time in Costa Rica before being imported to the US in 2021 and later refurbished by Elite Land Cruisers of Buckhead, Georgia. The truck is finished in green over beige vinyl upholstery and is powered by a 4.0-liter diesel inline-six linked with a four-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Equipment includes a headache rack, 15″ steel wheels, manually locking front hubs, Vintage Air climate control, and brown vinyl floor liners. Acquired by the current owner in 2022, this HJ47 is offered on dealer consignment in Wisconsin with a clean Florida title.
The truck is finished in green with a white roof and is equipped with a steel front bumper, a headache rack, a drop-down tailgate, and fender-mounted indicators.

This is a relist after the vehicle was previously sold on BaT in June 2024 and the winning bidder failed to follow through with their commitment to purchase. This was not due to any fault with the vehicle. The winner’s participation on BaT has been restricted.
The 15″ steel wheels are wrapped in 33×10.50″ BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A KO2 tires. The front axle is equipped with Warn manually locking hubs, and braking is handled by four-wheel drums.
The split bench seat is trimmed in beige vinyl that extends to the dashboard and door panels. Brown vinyl liners protect the footwells, and Vintage Air climate control is said to have been added.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 160-km/h speedometer as well as gauges for oil pressure, fuel level, coolant temperature, and amperage. The five-digit odometer shows 2,500 kilometers (~1,500 miles), approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 4.0-liter 2H diesel inline-six is said to have been rebuilt as part of the refurbishment, which also included replacing the wiring harness according to the seller. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.

Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels through a four-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case. The selling dealer notes that the frame was powder-coated and the driveline was rebuilt during the refurbishment. A Rush Racing exhaust is installed.

This 2002 Mitsubishi Montero Limited is finished in Glacier White with Sudan Beige lower cladding over tan leather and is powered by a 3.5-liter V6 mated to a five-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Further equipment includes a locking center differential, a limited-slip rear differential, 16″ alloy wheels, a sunroof, a receiver hitch, heated front seats, an Infinity CD stereo, third-row seating, and the Premium Package, which added automatic climate control, middle-row climate control, and power-adjustable front seats. The truck was first registered in Louisiana and later spent time in Georgia, where it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. This Montero has 82k miles and is now offered with a Carfax report and a Louisiana title.

The truck is finished in Glacier White with Sudan Beige lower cladding, bumper covers, and wheel arch flares. Additional features include a glass sunroof, roof rails, fog lights, a power-operated antenna, rear window tint film, and a receiver hitch.
The 16″ alloy wheels are mounted with 265/70 Zeetex HT1000 tires, and a covered spared is affixed to the swing-out tailgate. Braking is provided by four-wheel ventilated discs.

The heated and power-adjustable front bucket seats and a split second-row bench are upholstered in tan leather, while woodgrain trim accents the dashboard. Amenities include automatic climate control, cruise control, middle-row climate control, fold-away third-row seating, and an Infinity CD stereo.

The wood- and leather-trimmed steering wheel frames a 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 82k miles, approximately 500 of which have been added by the selling dealer.
The 3.5-liter 6G74 V6 features multiport fuel injection and was factory rated at 200 horsepower and 235 lb-ft of torque. The fluids were reportedly changed in preparation for the sale.

Power is delivered to the rear or all four wheels through a five-speed Sportronic automatic transmission, an Active Trac dual-range transfer case, a locking center differential, and a limited-slip rear differential.
The Carfax report lists at least one open recall and notes that the truck was registered in a county that was declared a flood disaster area by FEMA in September 2005.

This 2022 Ford F-250 XLT 4×4 is a Crew Cab pickup that was converted by Sherrod into their Signature Edition model prior to its initial purchase. It is powered by a 6.7-liter Power Stroke turbodiesel V8 linked with a 10-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a 3.31:1 electronically locking rear differential. The truck is finished in Agate Black Metallic over black quilted leather, and equipment includes the FX4 Off-Road, XLT Premium, and High-Capacity Trailer Tow packages as well as a 6″ suspension lift, underbody skid plates, Magnaflow exhaust, 22″ Fuel wheels, a spray-in bedliner, a tonneau cover, a panoramic sunroof, surround cameras, heated front seats, and SYNC 3 touchscreen infotainment. The current owner purchased the truck in 2023 and has since added approximately 2k of the 9k miles. This P558 Super Duty is now offered on dealer consignment with the owner’s manual, a conversion build sheet, two key fobs, a damage-free Carfax report, and a clean Texas title in the owner’s name.

The truck is finished in Agate Black Metallic (UM), and exterior equipment includes a panoramic sunroof, painted fender flares, fog lights, side steps, a keyless entry keypad, a sliding rear window, a hard folding tonneau cover, a spray-in bedliner, rear parking sensors, and Signature Edition graphics.

Black-finished 22″ Fuel Off-Road Contra wheels are mounted with 37×12.50″ Amp M/T A Terrain Attack tires. The truck is equipped with the optional FX4 Off-Road and High-Capacity Trailer Tow packages, and the Sherrod Signature Edition added these additional items:

The heated front bucket seats are upholstered in quilted black leather with Sherrod-embroidered headrests. Interior features include a power-adjustable driver’s seat, rear under-seat storage, air conditioning, cruise control, SYNC 3 touchscreen infotainment, surround cameras, trailer back-up assist, and BLIS blind-spot monitoring with cross-traffic alerts.

The multifunction steering wheel fronts a 100-mph speedometer and a tachometer as well as a central digital display and auxiliary gauges showing oil pressure, coolant temperature, fuel level, and boost pressure. The digital odometer indicates 9k miles, approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership.
The 6.7-liter Power Stroke turbodiesel V8 was factory rated at 475 horsepower and 1,050 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in December 2022.

Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels through a 10-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a 3.31:1 electronically locking rear differential. A Magnaflow exhaust system was fitted as part of the Signature Edition.
The Sherrod build sheet lists standard features of the F-250 Signature Edition as well as a conversion value of $18,810 on top of the truck’s MSRP of $70,375.
The Carfax report lists an open manufacturer recall.

attributes.value: F-250 Super Duty Sherrod Signature Edition XLT Crew Cab 4×4

description: This 2011 Lexus LS460 L is a US-market example that is said to have been utilized by the US Embassy in Japan until it was brought back to the US in February 2024. It is finished in Obsidian over black leather and is equipped with the Rear-Seat Upgrade Package, heated and ventilated front and rear seats, a power-reclining right-rear seat, adaptive air suspension, 18″ nine-spoke wheels, a Mark Levinson audio system, four-zone climate control, and a DVD Rear-Seat Entertainment System. Power is provided by a 4.6-liter V8 linked with an eight-speed automatic transmission. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this LS460 L indicates 36k miles and is now offered at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a clean Virginia title.

The car is finished in Obsidian (212) and features adaptive HID headlights, a sunroof, front and rear parking sensors, rain-sensing windshield wipers, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, a powered trunk lid, and LED taillights.

The 18″ nine-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with 235/50 Hankook Ventus S1 Noble 2 Plus tires. The car is equipped with height-adjustable Adaptive Variable Air Suspension with electronically modulated damping as well as Vehicle Dynamics Integrated Management (VDIM) and traction control. Braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs.

The cabin features heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats upholstered in black leather, and wood trim adorns the dashboard, door panels, and front and rear consoles. Amenities include a back-up camera, a Mark Levinson audio system, navigation, cruise control, and four-zone climate control. The left-rear seat bottom has indentations. The infotainment system language is in Japanese.

This example was specified with heated and ventilated power-adjustable outboard rear seats with massage functions and memory settings as well as a power-reclining right-rear seat, an Alcantara headliner, powered rear sunshades, and a central DVD Rear-Seat Entertainment System (RSES) with a 9″ screen.

The heated wood- and leather-trimmed steering wheel fronts a 160-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The instrument cluster was replaced upon reentry to the United States. The digital odometer indicates 36k miles.
The 4.6-liter DOHC 1UR-FSE V8 was factory rated at 380 horsepower and 367 lb-ft of torque.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage since an initial entry in February 2024.

This 1972 Chevrolet K10 4×4 pickup is powered by a 383ci stroker V8 that was installed under previous ownership and outfitted with an Edelbrock aluminum intake manifold and cylinder heads as well as a 750 CFM Holley carburetor. The truck was refinished in dark olive and white following the seller’s 2019 acquisition and is equipped with a four-speed manual transmission, a dual-range transfer case, a Ford 9″ Positraction rear differential, power steering, and four-wheel disc brakes. Additional features include 15″ Eagle Alloy wheels, a fiberglass tonneau cover, black vinyl and houndstooth cloth upholstery, air conditioning, and a wood-rimmed Grant GT steering wheel. This K10 is offered with a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The seller reports that the body was stripped to bare metal, bodywork and rust repair was performed, a repaint in dark olive with a white upper cab was carried out, and the trim was replaced under current ownership. Exterior details include a Fleetside bed with a green spray-in bedliner and a hinged fiberglass tonneau cover as well as chrome bumpers, dual side mirrors, a sliding rear window, a receiver hitch, and Cheyenne badging. Scratches are noted on the grille surround.

The 15″ Eagle Alloy wheels were mounted with 33×12.5″ BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A KO2 tires in 2020. The truck is equipped with manually locking front hubs, power steering, and power-assisted four-wheel disc brakes. The seller states that the power steering pump, steering stabilizer, and shock absorbers were replaced in 2020.
The bench seat is upholstered in black vinyl with houndstooth cloth inserts, and the interior features air conditioning. An AM/FM stereo is fitted, though no speakers are installed.

A wood-rimmed Grant GT steering wheel is mounted to a tilting column and fronts a column-mounted 8k-rpm tachometer, a 100-mph speedometer, and gauges for fuel level, amperage, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. Auxiliary instruments are positioned beneath the dash. The five-digit odometer shows 22k miles, approximately 7k of which were added under current ownership. The seller notes that the total mileage is unknown.

A 383ci stroker V8 was installed under previous ownership and is said to be fitted with an aftermarket camshaft, a 750 CFM Holley carburetor, and an Edelbrock Performer RPM intake manifold, aluminum cylinder heads, and electric fuel pump. The seller notes that an MSD ignition control box was installed in 2020 and that an Optima battery was fitted and fluid services were performed in 2024.

Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels through a four-speed SM465 manual transmission, a dual-range NP208 transfer case, and a Ford 9″ Positraction rear differential with 3.55:1 gearing. The dual exhaust system was fitted with Flowmaster resonators and mufflers in 2022.

This 2001 BMW R1100RT is finished in Pacific Blue and is powered by a 1,085cc opposed twin that routes power through a five-speed transmission and an enclosed driveshaft. It has been fitted with an LED headlight and heated grips, and it also features hard-sided panniers, a luggage rack, rider and passenger seats, 17″ front and 18″ rear alloy wheels, both center and side stands, triple anti-lock disc brakes, oil-cooled cylinder heads, fuel injection, a Telelever front end, and a Paralever single-sided swingarm. This R1100RT was acquired by the seller in 2019 and is now offered at no reserve with a tool kit, a bike cover, and a clean Colorado title in the seller’s name.

The bike is finished in Pacific Blue, and features include a LED headlight, black rider and passenger seats, a clear button-activated adjustable windscreen, BMW-branded hard-sided panniers, folding passenger foot pegs, integrated mirrors, a 6.6-gallon fuel tank, and both center and side stands. Scratches on the valve covers and scuffs in the paint are noted to have been incurred under prior ownership.

The 17″ front and 18″ rear three-spoke alloy wheels were mounted with a 120/70 front Continental ContiMotion and a 160/80 rear Metzeler Roadtec in September 2020. The front tire was damaged during a ride in July 2024 and is in need of replacement. Suspension consists of a Telelever front end as well as a single-sided Paralever swingarm with a monoshock. Anti-lock braking is provided by multi-piston calipers fitted over dual discs up front and a single disc out back. The fork seals were replaced in October 2019. The seller reports a squeaking noise emanating from the front wheel during low-speed braking.

Individual handlebars mounted to the top triple clamp feature heated grips and are mounted aft of instrumentation consisting of a 150-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7,500-rpm redline as well as a row of indicators and a digital display for oil temperature and fuel level.
