The six-digit odometer shows 6k miles, approximately 2k of which have been ridden by the seller.

The 1,085cc opposed twin features Bosch Motronic electronic fuel injection, a two-into-one exhaust system, four valves per cylinder, oil-cooled cylinder heads, and an electric starter. The fluids were last changed in 2020 and the battery was replaced in 2024.
Power is routed to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and an enclosed driveshaft.
A tool kit, an owner’s manual, oil and additives, a pair of BMW-branded hard-sided panniers, and keys will accompany the bike.

This 2005 Porsche 911 Turbo S coupe was specified in Black over black full leather, and it was optioned with the Turbo Aerokit, heated front sport seats, a sport shifter, and Porsche Communication Management (PCM) with navigation. The car is powered by a twin-turbocharged 3.6L flat-six that drives all four wheels via a six-speed manual transaxle, and it has been modified with an AWE Tuning exhaust system, adjustable coilover suspension, billet diverter valves, aftermarket intake tubes, and a K40 radar detector. Additional features include the a sunroof, bi-xenon headlights, integrated fog lights, 18″ Sport Techno wheels, Porsche Ceramic Composite Brakes (PCCB), a Bose sound system, a remote six-disc CD changer, and automatic climate control. This 996 Turbo S coupe has 46k miles, and it is now offered in Georgia on dealer consignment at no reserve with the owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, a car cover, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Mississippi title.

The car is finished in Black (041), and features include a sunroof, xenon headlights, fog lights as well as wider rear bodywork, rear air intakes, and revised bumper covers in comparison to the contemporary Carrera. The car is also fitted with the Turbo Aerokit, which added revised lower side sills, front and rear lower spoilers, and a bi-plane rear wing. The front lip spoiler was replaced in May 2017. A two-stage paint correction was performed in preparation for the sale, and photos depicting paint-meter readings are provided in the gallery. The selling dealer notes that the key fob does not unlock the doors

The 18″ Sport Techno wheels wear Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires that show date codes from 2021 and 2023. The car has been fitted with an adjustable coilover suspension, and it is equipped with Porsche Stability Management (PSM) and an automatic brake differential. Braking is from Porsche Ceramic Composite Brakes (PCCB) featuring yellow-painted six-piston front and four-piston rear calipers.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front sport seats upholstered in black leather that extends to the dashboard and door panels. Equipment includes a sport shifter, driver-seat memory settings, a Bose sound system, a remote six-disc CD changer, Porsche Communication Management with navigation, and automatic climate control. A K40 radar detector has been installed. The driver’s seat left bolster shows signs of wear, and the rearview mirror is cloudy.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer, a central tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 46k miles, approximately approx 6k of which were added under current ownership.

The twin-turbocharged 3.6L Mezger flat-six included the Turbo Power Kit as standard, which included revised engine management software and larger turbochargers and intercoolers for a factory rating of 444 horsepower and 457 lb-ft of torque. Modifications include billet diverter valves, aftermarket intake tubes, and a K&N air filter. The radiator was replaced in February 2020, and an oil change was performed in June 2024.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle. An AWE Tuning exhaust system has been fitted.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The Mississippi title is listed as a replacement.

This 1971 Triumph was modified prior to the seller’s acquisition and is powered by a 2.0-liter in-line six linked with a four-speed manual transmission. The car is equipped with a Monza-style exhaust as well as a GT6-style hood and has been refinished in red. Equipment includes a black soft top, 13″ Minilite-style wheels, front disc brakes, and chrome bumpers in addition to a wood veneer dashboard, a wood shift knob, and black vinyl upholstery. The seller purchased the car in 2022, and subsequent work involved replacing the top, window seals, valve cover gasket, water pump, master cylinder, and battery. This modified Triumph is now offered at no reserve with a tonneau cover and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

This car was refinished in its current shade of red and equipped with a GT6-style hood and Spitfire 1500 badges at some point under prior ownership. The seller notes that the black soft top, front wheel arch trim, and seals for the windows and doors were replaced under current ownership. Exterior details include a black top boot and tonneau cover, a driver-side mirror, chrome bumpers, and quad exhaust outlets. The seller reports blemishes in the finish and that the front window trim needs to be replaced.

The 13″ Minilite-style wheels are mounted with 175/70 Summit Ultramax All Season tires that show 2024 date codes. Stopping power is provided by front discs and rear drums, and the master cylinder was replaced under current ownership.

The cabin houses bucket seats with black vinyl upholstery complemented by color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Appointments include a wood-veneer dashboard, a wood shift knob, and a heater. The radio is missing, and the seller states that the seat foam is crumbling and requires replacement.

Instrumentation includes a 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges. The ignition switch was replaced following the seller’s acquisition. The five-digit odometer shows 58k miles, approximately 1k of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The seller notes that the 2.0-liter inline-six was installed under prior ownership. Work performed following the seller’s acquisition is said to include replacing the water pump and aluminum housing, fuel pump, starter solenoid, valve cover gasket, and battery.

Power is routed to the rear wheels through a replacement four-speed manual transmission. The differential seal and U-joints were replaced under current ownership, according to the seller, and the Monza exhaust and driveshaft were refurbished.

This 1999 Jeep Cherokee SE is finished in Stone White over Agate cloth upholstery and is powered by a 4.0-liter inline-six mated to a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. The truck has 21k miles and was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. Features include front disc brakes, 15″ five-spoke wheels, power-adjustable side mirrors, air conditioning, power windows, an AM/FM stereo, and front bucket seats. This XJ Cherokee is now offered with a clean Carfax report and a clean New Jersey title.
The truck is finished in Stone White with a black grille, bumper covers, and wheel arch flares. Additional equipment includes a rear window wiper, 4×4 graphics, and power-adjustable side mirrors.

The 15″ five-spoke wheels are mounted with 215/75 Goodyear Wrangler SR-A tires. Stopping power is provided by front discs and rear drums with ABS. The truck came equipped from the factory with power steering.
The cabin features reclining front bucket seats and a rear bench trimmed in Agate cloth. Amenities include air conditioning, power windows, a locking glovebox, and an AM/FM stereo.
The steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, voltage, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 21k miles.
The PowerTech 4.0-liter inline-six was factory rated at 190 horsepower and 225 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in June 2024.
Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels via a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. The truck features a Command-Trac four-wheel drive system.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2013 Fiat 500C is a Gucci Edition example that is finished in Bianco over Nero and Bianco leather with “Guccissima” prints and red and green striping. Power is provided by a 1.4-liter MultiAir inline-four paired with a six-speed automatic transaxle and Gucci-specific details include a black Cabrio soft top with green and red striping as well as a unique shift knob, door panels, signature doorsill plates, chrome badges, and color-keyed 15″ wheels with GG hubcaps. The car is further equipped with rear parking sensors, heated front seats, automatic climate control, hands-free communication, and a CD stereo. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this 500C Gucci Edition has 32k kilometers (~20k miles) and is offered in Canada at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a British Columbia registration.

This example is finished in Bianco (PW3) and Gucci-specific details include a black Cabrio soft top with green and red striping, a bright center hood trim piece, chrome Gucci signature badges, and bright mirror caps. Additional features include a polished exhaust finisher, bright rear bumper trim, tinted windows, and fog lights.

Color-keyed 15″ alloy wheels wear GG center caps and are mounted with Firestone Firehawk tires. The car is equipped with a sport-tuned suspension, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes.

The heated front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in Nero and Bianco leather with “Guccissima” prints, red and green striping, and GG embossed front headrests. Interior elements include a Gucci-branded shift knob and doorsill plates as well as automatic climate control, cruise control, Blue&Me hands-free communication, and a CD stereo.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel frames a digital speedometer, tachometer, and supplementary gauges for coolant temperature, fuel level, and fuel economy. The digital odometer shows 32k kilometers (~20k miles), approximately 500 of which were added under current ownership.

The 1.4-liter MultiAir inline-four was factoryrated at 101 horsepower and 98 lb-ft of torque. Recent work is said to consist of replacing the spark plugs and ignition coils. Power is sent to the front wheels via a six-speed automatic transaxle.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada
listing_details: Black Soft Top w/Red & Green Stripes

description: This 2008 Lexus GS460 is finished in Mercury Metallic over light gray leather and is powered by a 4.6-liter V8 paired with an eight-speed automatic transmission, and now has 19k miles. Equipment includes 17″ alloy wheels, a sunroof, adaptive HID headlights, fog lights, a rear lip spoiler, and front and rear parking sensors in addition to heated, ventilated, and power-adjustable front seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, a powered rear sunshade, a CD/cassette stereo, and a 7″ touchscreen infotainment system with a rearview camera and navigation. The car was first registered in California and later spent time in New Jersey where it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. This GS460 is now offered at no reserve with a first aid kit, a battery tender, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Mercury Metallic (1F2) and features a power-operated glass sunroof. Additional details include adaptive HID headlights, fog lights, a rear lip spoiler, power-adjustable and folding side mirrors, front and rear parking sensors, and dual polished exhaust outlets. The selling dealer notes that the front bumper cover was repainted under prior ownership, and moisture is evident in the left inner headlight. Paint imperfections are shown up close in the gallery along with body panel VIN stickers and paint-meter readings.

Chrome-finished 17″ alloy wheels are mounted with 225/50 Goodyear Assurance Comfortred Touring tires with 2016 date codes. The car is equipped with an Adaptive Variable Suspension (AVS) system, and braking is provided by ventilated discs at all four corners.

The heated, ventilated, and power-adjustable front seats and a rear bench seat are upholstered in light gray leather and are joined by wood trim that accents the center console and door panels. Amenities include front seat position memory, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, a powered rear sunshade, a CD/cassette stereo, and a 7″ touchscreen infotainment system with a rearview camera and navigation.

The wood- and leather-trimmed steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges. The digital odometer indicates 19k miles, approximately 100 of which have been added by the selling dealer.

The 4.6-liter 1UR-FSE V8 features variable valve timing and was factory rated at 342 horsepower and 339 lb-ft of torque. A battery tender has been retrofitted, and the oil was changed and the hood support struts were reportedly replaced in preparation for the sale.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2008 Tesla Roadster is #48 of the first 100 produced, which were sold as the Signature 100 Edition. This car was the recipient of nearly $26k in service by Gruber Motor Company of Phoenix, Arizona, in February 2024, the process of which included a “Level 2” battery pull, a “Level 2 Full Rebuild” on the PEM, rebuilding the switchpack, reupholstering the seats and door panels, converting the headlights to LEDs, and replacing the battery coolant pumps. The car features a 1.5-series battery pack powering a three-phase AC induction motor paired with a single-speed transmission, and it is finished in Twilight Blue over black leather. Equipment includes a removable roof panel, a black removable soft top, 16″ and 17″ forged aluminum wheels, and heated sport seats. The car has spent time in California and Pennsylvania and now has 52k miles. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this Roadster is now offered in New York with service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Pennsylvania title.

The Tesla Roadster was based on the aluminum tub from the contemporary Lotus Elise, with which it shared its windshield and windshield frame. The remainder of the carbon-fiber body panels were unique to the Tesla, and it utilized a 2″ longer wheelbase than the Elise. This example is finished in Twilight Blue and features a removable roof panel, a black removable soft top, an exterior charging port, an integrated rear spoiler, and LED taillights. The front bumper cover was replaced in July 2011, and work in February 2024 included removing clear paint protection film, performing paint correction, and rebuilding the headlights and converting them to LEDs. Scrapes and peeling clearcoat are visible on the front bumper cover.

Silver-finished 16″ front and 17″ rear forged aluminum wheels are mounted with Yokohama Advan Neova tires measuring 175/55 and 225/45, respectively. The car is equipped with traction control as well as front and rear independent wishbone suspension with co-axial coil springs and telescopic dampers. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel discs with a regenerative braking system. The rear brake pads were replaced in February 2024.

The heated sport seats and door panel inserts were reupholstered in black leather in February 2024 by Gruber Motor Company. Appointments include a JVC stereo, cruise control, and air conditioning. Records indicate that the switchpack was rebuilt in February 2024.
A plaque between the headrests identifies this example as #48 of the first 100 Tesla Roadster models produced.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a 150-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 13k-rpm redline. A configurable multifunction LCD screen is mounted to the left of the steering column. The digital odometer indicates 52k miles.

A 53-kilowatt-hour battery pack powers a three-phase, 375-volt AC induction motor featuring a hand-wound stator. Factory-rated output was 248 horsepower and 200 lb-ft of torque. Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a single-speed transmission. Work in February 2024 included a “Level 2” battery pull, a “Level 2 Full Rebuild” on the power electronics module (PEM), and replacing the battery coolant pumps.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1973 Toyota Land Cruiser FJ40 was acquired by the seller in 2010 and was subsequently modified and refurbished. It was fitted with a 6.0-liter LQ9 Vortec V8 and an H55F five-speed manual transmission, the dual-range transfer case was rebuilt, and an Auburn limited-slip rear differential was installed. The truck was repainted green, and the interior was refreshed with replacement seats, a Vintage Air climate control system, Dakota Digital gauges, a Grant steering wheel, a Tuffy center console, power windows, and a Metal Tech 4×4 roll cage. Riding on a lifted suspension with Fox shocks and Old Man Emu springs over 17″ aftermarket wheels and four-wheel disc brakes, the truck is also equipped with aftermarket bumpers, an air-intake snorkel, a Rigid Industries light bar, and a Warn winch. This FJ40 is offered with service records and a clean New York title in the seller’s name.

During the refurbishment, a hardtop, windshield frame, and doors from a 1980 FJ40 were fitted, the bumpers, side mirrors, headlights, windshield, and side windows were replaced, and the truck was repainted green. Additional equipment includes a Rigid Industries light bar, LED headlights, an air-intake snorkel, and a Warn winch.

The 17″ black-finished aftermarket wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A KO2 tires. The truck is equipped with a 4″ suspension lift, Fox shocks, Old Man Emu springs, manually locking front hubs, and four-wheel disc brakes. Additional work during the refurbishment included rebuilding the front brake calipers, performing a power steering conversion, and replacing the body mounts and suspension bushings.

The front bucket seats and rear bench are trimmed in black upholstery and were installed under current ownership, at which time the dash pad and carpets were also replaced. Appointments include Vintage Air climate control, a Sony CD stereo, Rockford Fosgate speakers, power windows, a Tuffy center console, and a Metal Tech 4×4 roll cage.

The Grant steering wheel is mounted to a tilting column and frames Dakota Digital instrumentation including a 120-mph speedometer and supplementary gauges. The digital odometer shows 1,800 miles. Total mileage is unknown.
The 6.0-liter LQ9 Vortec V8 is said to have been sourced from a 2003 Cadillac Escalade. The following components were also replaced during the refurbishment:

During the build, the H55F five-speed manual transmission was installed, the dual-range transfer case was rebuilt, the Auburn limited-slip rear differential was fitted, a Nitro rear differential cover and 4.11:1 Yukon gears were installed, the driveshaft U-joints were replaced, and the frame was refinished.

This 2023 Porsche 911 GT3 RS was specified from the factory with the Tribute to Carrera RS Package featuring Python Green 20″ and 21″ magnesium wheels and exterior graphics along with unique interior elements and a suite of accessories. It was ordered new by the current owner through Porsche Hunt Valley in Cockeysville, Maryland, and now has 1,200 miles. Power is supplied by a 4.0-liter flat-six that drives the rear wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle and an electronically locking differential, while the Weissach Package reduces weight by utilizing a carbon-composite roof panel, front lid, anti-roll bars, and interior trim. The car is further equipped with a front axle lift system and carbon-ceramic brakes along with LED-Matrix Design headlights, Exclusive Design taillights, carbon-fiber bucket seats, and a Bose surround sound system. This Tribute to Carrera RS 992 GT3 RS is now offered in Maryland by the seller on behalf of the owner with a window sticker, manufacturer’s literature, accessories, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Montana title.

The Tribute to Carrera RS Package was released for the US market in 2023 as an homage to the 1973 911 Carrera RS 2.7 that debuted 50 years prior. The package specified white paint accented by Python Green mirror caps, GT3 RS side graphics, model badging, and rear wing accents along with CFRP panels finished in exposed carbon-fiber weave from the Weissach Package.

As in the standard GT3 RS, the car features lightweight glass, vented front fenders, and a carbon-fiber-reinforced plastic (CFRP) front trunk lid, roof panel, and rear swan-neck-hinged wing with drag-reduction (DRS) functionality. It is further equipped with LED-Matrix Design headlights with PDLS+, Exclusive Design taillights, a rear fog light, and rear ParkAssist. Paint protection film was applied to the hood, front bumper, fenders, doors, mirrors, and rear wing in 2023.

The forged lightweight magnesium 20″ and 21″ GT3 center-lock wheels are finished in Python Green and mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires measuring 275/35 up front and 335/30 out back. Stopping power is provided by Porsche Ceramic Composite Brakes (PCCB) with gloss black–finished calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated discs at each corner. The car is equipped with a front-axle lift system, rear-axle steering, and the Weissach Package, which added carbon-fiber front and rear anti-roll bars and coupling rods.

The carbon-fiber bucket seats are trimmed in black leather with Race-Tex inserts, “Weissach RS” embroidery on the headrests, and Tribute to Carrera RS tailoring with Python Green stitching that extends to the dash, center console, knee pads, and door panels. Carbon-fiber trim accents the cabin as well as the illuminated door sill guards, while the carpets are protected by Porsche-branded floor mats with leather edging and deviated stitching. Further appointments include Porsche Communication Management infotainment with navigation in addition to a Bose surround-sound system, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, an ambient lighting system, and auto-dimming mirrors.

The GT3 sports steering wheel features a vehicle configuration dial and frames a central tachometer with a 9k-rpm redline as well as a digital speed readout and configurable TFT screens. The digital odometer indicates 1,200 miles. The shift paddles were replaced in April 2024.
An Andreas Preuninger signature appears in the front trunk.

The 4.0-liter flat-six features direct fuel injection, VarioCam variable valve timing, dry-sump lubrication, and individual throttle bodies. It was rated at 518 horsepower and 342 lb-ft of torque. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle and an electronically locking differential. A stainless-steel sport exhaust system was fitted as standard, and the car was optioned with an extended range fuel tank. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
The window sticker shows initial delivery to Porsche Hunt Valley and lists factory colors, equipment, and a total price of $339,190.
Each 2023 Porsche 911 GT3 RS ordered with the Tribute to Carrera RS Package was accompanied by a collection of accessories including:
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

description: This 2019 Porsche 911 Speedster is #1,716 of 1,948 examples produced for the model year and was purchased new by the current owner at Porsche Redwood City in California. Having 12 miles, it is powered by a 4.0-liter flat-six paired with a six-speed manual transaxle and is finished in GT Silver Metallic. The car was optioned with 20″ GT3 center-lock alloy wheels, carbon-ceramic brakes, a limited-slip differential, a front-axle lift system, a black soft top, and a carbon-fiber twin-hump convertible-top cover panel. The cockpit features the Chrono and Light Design Packages, extended black leather with red deviated stitching, carbon-fiber trim, a Bose surround sound system, and carbon-fiber full bucket seats. This 911 Speedster is now offered by the seller on behalf of the owner with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean California title in the current owner’s name.

The Speedster shares styling cues with the 991 GT3 including a similar front splitter and bumper covers, while features unique to the Speedster consist of a shorter windshield, a manually retractable black soft top, and a body-color carbon-fiber twin-hump convertible-top cover panel. This example is finished in GT Silver Metallic and has xenon headlights, a speed-activated rear spoiler, body-color side skirts, carbon-fiber mirror caps, and dual exhaust outlets.

Center-locking 20″ forged alloy wheels are mounted with staggered-width Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel cross-drilled Porsche Ceramic Composite Brakes with yellow Porsche-branded calipers. Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM), Porsche Stability Management (PSM), and rear-axle steering were standard on the Speedster, and this example was optioned with a front-axle lift system.

The interior was optioned with black leather extending from the carbon-fiber full bucket seats to the dashboard, center console, steering column, door panel inserts, inner door sill guards, sun visors, and air vent surrounds, with red deviated stitching throughout. Carbon-fiber trim adorns the cabin, and additional amenities include the Light Design Package, illuminated carbon-fiber door sill guards, Porsche Communication Management with navigation, dual-zone automatic climate control, a Bose surround sound system, aluminum pedals, a fire extinguisher, cruise control, “Speedster” headrest embroidery, and a Porsche crest on the center armrest.
A serialized plaque located between the seats denotes this example as #1,716 of 1,948 Speedsters produced.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped GT sports steering wheel features a red centering stripe and deviated stitching. Instrumentation consists of a central tachometer with a 9k-rpm redline flanked by a 225-mph speedometer and gauges for oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The Chrono Package added a stopwatch atop the dashboard. The digital odometer indicates 12 miles.

The naturally aspirated, GT3-sourced 4.0L flat-six features VarioCam Plus valve timing and was updated for the Speedster with revised individual throttle bodies and high-pressure fuel injectors. Factory rated power output was 502 horsepower and 346 lb-ft of torque.

Power is sent to the rear wheels via a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. The car is equipped with an optional 23.7-gallon extended-range fuel tank. Additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery.

The window sticker shows initial delivery to Porsche Redwood City in California, along with factory colors, options, and a total price of $301,440. The owner’s manual, a binder documenting the car, and two painted-to-match keys with a leather key pouch are also included in the sale.
The Carfax report lists at least one open recall.
The California title carries a “title only” notation.
The car is registered as Planned Non-Operation in the state of California.

This 1971 Mercedes-Benz 280SL underwent a refurbishment under previous ownership in California circa 2019, and it sold on BaT in November 2022. Work under previous ownership included rebuilding the 2.8-liter inline-six, installing a six-speed S&SG manual transmission, replacing the tan soft top, refreshing the tan interior, and servicing the braking and fueling systems. The car is finished in green, and additional equipment includes a body-color hardtop, 14″ steel wheels with covers, VDO gauges, an AM/FM radio, Coco floor mats, and PerTronix electronic ignition. Acquired by the current owner in 2022, this W113 SL is offered in California on dealer consignment with the owner’s manual, a tool roll, and a Montana title.

The car was refinished in green under previous ownership and is equipped with a removable body-color hardtop in addition to a replacement tan soft top that was installed in 2019. The left front fender is said to have been repaired and the inboard front fender tips are noted to be missing. The forward portions of the car show signs of bodywork, and paint chips and evidence of surface preparation in the finish are present on various body panels. The rear floor pan was refinished in 2019, and dents on the left quarter panel and trunk lid were repaired that same year.

Black 14″ steel wheels wear polished covers with body-color centers, and they were mounted with Vredestein Sprint Classic tires in 2019. Bilstein front shocks were also installed at that time. Braking is provided by power-assisted four-wheel discs.

Interior work under previous ownership included reupholstering the bucket seats in tan, adjusting the door and door windows, servicing the driver’s window regulator, and replacing the air conditioning compressor. Appointments include tan carpeting covered by Jaspe Coco mats as well as an analog clock and a push-button AM/FM radio.

A two-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of VDO instrumentation that includes a 140-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and vertical auxiliary gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 69k miles, and the clock and speedometer were serviced in 2019 by Palo Alto Speedometer in California. Total mileage is unknown.

The fuel-injected 2.8L inline-six was rebuilt in 2020, and work included hot tanking the block in addition to boring and honing the cylinders. The cylinder head was overhauled with replacement valves and guides, and the engine block and cylinder head were resurfaced before being reassembled. A PerTronix electronic ignition is installed.

The factory four-speed automatic transmission was replaced with a six-speed S&SG manual transmission in 2020. The flywheel, clutch components, and pedals were replaced as part of the transmission replacement. Rust perforation is noted on the front crossmember.
A previously issued California title lists an odometer brand of “exceeds mechanical limits.”

This 1987 Ferrari Testarossa was purchased by the current owner in 1992, and it now shows 22k miles following registration history in California. It is powered by a 4.9-liter flat-12 paired with a five-speed manual transaxle and is finished in Rosso Corsa over Nero Connolly leather upholstery. Equipment includes a limited-slip differential, 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels, pop-up headlights, air conditioning, power windows, a cassette stereo, and a gated shifter. This Testarossa is offered on dealer consignment with service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The Pininfarina-designed body is finished in Rosso Corsa and features pop-up headlights, fog lights, an asymmetrical cooling duct beneath the left fog lamp, side intake strakes, black-finished rocker panels, and quad exhaust outlets.
Silver 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich g-Force Sport tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs.

The cockpit is trimmed in Nero Connolly leather upholstery over the seats, door panels, and lower dashboard. Interior amenities include a Kenwood cassette stereo, motorized seat belts, and a gated shifter located on the center console alongside controls for the air conditioning, rear window defroster, and power windows.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames Veglia instrumentation including a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,800-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil pressure and coolant temperature. A clock and auxiliary gauges for fuel level and oil temperature are housed in the center stack. The six-digit odometer shows 22k miles, approximately 11k of which were added under current ownership.
The 4.9-liter flat-12 was factory rated at 380 horsepower and 354 lb-ft of torque. A timing belt service is said to have been completed in 2015 at approximately 2k miles ago.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential.

The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage. An entry in April 2015 states that the car was designated a gross polluter in California, although the car has since passed California emissions inspections.

This 1969 MGC roadster was refurbished in 1991 under previous ownership and was purchased by the seller in 1992, who has since added approximately 28k miles. It is powered by a 2.9-liter inline-six paired with a four-speed manual transmission and is finished in red over black leather upholstery. Equipment includes a black convertible top, a domed hood, a roll bar, dual SU carburetors, an electronic distributor, front disc brakes, 15″ wire wheels with knock-off hubs, safety harnesses, and a heater. This MGC roadster is now offered at no reserve with a workshop manual, partial service records, a tool kit, and a clean Wisconsin title in the seller’s name.

The car was previously refinished in red, and exterior equipment includes a black folding soft top, a domed hood, a front air dam, a door-mounted driver-side mirror, an aftermarket roll bar, a single exhaust outlet, and chrome-finished side moldings, window trim, and bumpers with overriders. Paint chips, faded paint, and dents around the exterior are shown up close in photos provided below.

The 15″ wire wheels feature knock-off hubs and show wear, and they are mounted with 195/60 Fuzion HRi tires. The car was factory equipped with rack-and-pinion steering as well as torsion bars, anti-roll bars, and telescopic shock absorbers. Stopping power is provided by front discs and rear drums. The seller notes the front brakes occasionally make noise.
The cabin features two seats upholstered in black leather with red piping, and interior appointments include safety harnesses, a padded dashboard, a heater, and a carpeted rear parcel shelf.

The four-spoke steering wheel frames Smiths instrumentation including a 140-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 5,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 32k miles, approximately 28k of which were added under current ownership.

The 2.9-liter inline-six was factory equipped with dual SU carburetors and an oil cooler, and an aftermarket electronic distributor has been fitted. Factory-rated output was 145 horsepower and 174 lb-ft of torque. Replacement engine gaskets were installed and the engine was repainted in 2018.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission with overdrive. The fuel system was reportedly refurbished in 2015, and the clutch components were replaced in 2018.
The attached identification plate seen above shows the car number. The VIN on the Wisconsin title lists the letter “I” as the fourth character instead of the number “1”.

This 1964 Austin-Healey 3000 BJ7 Mk II is a 2+2 convertible that was acquired by the seller in 1965 in Pittsburgh. The car is powered by a 2.9-liter inline-six that was rebuilt approximately 25 years ago and which is linked to a four-speed manual transmission with overdrive. Following the rebuild the car was placed in long-term storage, and the car disassembled and refurbished between August 2017 and October 2018. Finished in green over tan leather upholstery, it has chrome-plated bumpers with overriders as well as 15″ wire wheels, front disc brakes, stainless-steel exhaust components, a tan soft top, a hood scoop, dual side mirrors, a Smiths heater, and a Pioneer stereo. This 3000 BJ7 is now offered at no reserve with a front-end cover and a clean Ohio title in the seller’s name.

The seller reports that the car was fully disassembled during the refurbishment before it was repainted in the current shade of green. Exterior details include a tan convertible soft top, a hood scoop, dual fender-mounted side mirrors, red 3000 Mk II badging, dual polished exhaust outlets, and chrome bumpers with overriders. The radio antenna is disconnected and a black front-end cover is included in the sale. The antenna is broken.

Silver-finished 15” wire wheels secured by two-eared knock-offs are mounted with 165-series Monarch radial tires that were mounted approximately 20 years ago. A spare wheel with a mismatched tire is located in the trunk, and braking is provided by front discs and rear drums.

The 2+2 seating was re-trimmed in tan leather while dark tan upholstery accents the dashboard and door panels. Appointments include a Smiths heater, a dash-mounted rearview mirror, an aftermarket Pioneer stereo, front lap belts, and a passenger grab handle. Portions of the seat upholstery is loose and shows creasing.

The banjo-style steering wheel sits ahead of Smiths instrumentation that includes a 120-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 79k miles, approximately 70k of which were added under current ownership.

The 2.9-liter inline-six was rebuilt between 1997 and 2000 according to the seller, who notes the dual SU carburetors were installed at that time and PerTronix electronic ignition was added. Approximately 50 miles have been added since the rebuild. The car is difficult to start when cold, and the removed carburetors are included in the sale.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission with an electrically actuated overdrive unit. A dual stainless-steel exhaust system has been installed. A rattle is audible in the exhaust video in the gallery below.

This 1999 Chevrolet Tahoe LT is a two-door example that was initially delivered to Van Chevrolet in Carrollton, Texas, and it was purchased by the seller in 2021 following registration history in that state since new. Powered by a 5.7-liter V8 mated to a four-speed automatic transmission, the truck is finished in two-tone Light Pewter Metallic and Gunmetal Gray over gray leather upholstery. It was optioned with the Z71 Off-Road Package and the Sports Appearance Package, and equipment includes AutoTrac full-time four-wheel drive, a locking rear differential, rear barn doors, roof rails, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, power windows and locks, a CD/cassette stereo, keyless entry, cruise control, and air conditioning. Work completed under current ownership has included replacing the tires, valve cover gaskets intake manifold gasket, and transfer case control module. This GMT400 Tahoe is offered at no reserve with a window sticker, service records, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean Texas title in the seller’s name.

This two-door example is finished in two-tone Light Pewter Metallic (11U) and Gunmetal Gray, and it is equipped with the Sports Appearance Package, which added a Dark Argent-colored grille, wheel flares, rubber strips on the front and rear bumpers, a front air dam, and sports decals. Additional features include front tow hooks, roof rails, a receiver hitch, and rear barn doors. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

The 16″ twist five-spoke aluminum wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A K02 tires that were mounted in 2021. Braking is handled by front discs and rear drums. Front and rear Bilstein shocks are equipped as part of the Z71 Off-Road Package.

The cabin features seating surfaces trimmed in gray leather, and amenities include a power-adjustable driver’s seat, a folding three-passenger rear bench, power windows and locks, keyless entry, a CD/cassette stereo, cruise control, and air conditioning.

The four-spoke steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, voltage, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The six-digit odometer shows 140k miles, approximately 1k of which were added under current ownership. The instrument cluster was replaced in June 2024. Total mileage is unknown.

The 5.7-liter Vortec V8 was factory-rated at 255 horsepower and 330 lb-ft of torque. The truck is equipped with the Skid Plate Package as part of the Z71 Off-Road Package, which included shield plates for the engine, front differential, and transfer case. The oil pan gasket was replaced in August 2019, and work in 2024 has included changing the coolant and oil and replacing the valve cover gaskets and intake manifold gasket.

Power is sent to all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission with overdrive and an AutoTrac four-wheel-drive system. The truck is equipped with a locking rear differential. The transfer case control module was replaced in 2024.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Van Chevrolet in Carrollton, Texas, as well as factory colors, equipment, and a total vehicle price of $35,275.
The Carfax report lists at least one open recall.

description: This 1985 BMW M635CSi is a black-on-black European-market example that was imported to the US in June 1985 and remained with its original owner in California until the current owner acquired the car on BaT in July 2021. Power is provided by a 3.5-liter M88/3 inline-six mated to a five-speed manual transmission, and the car is equipped with a limited-slip differential, 17″ BBS wheels, a power sunroof, front and rear spoilers, air conditioning, power-adjustable front seats, and an Alpine CD stereo. This E24 M635CSi shows 168k miles and is now offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner with manufacturer’s literature, period brochures, import documents, service records dating to 1984, a tool kit, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean California title in the owner’s name.

The car is finished in black (086) with white pinstripes and features a power-operated sunroof, fog lights, bright trim, both front and decklid spoilers, and twin center-exit exhaust outlets. Photos provided in the gallery show cracked fog and marker light lenses as well as dents below the right-rear window and blemishes around the front of the car. The silver trim on the front spoiler was refinished in preparation for the sale.

Multi-piece 17″ BBS wheels are mounted with 235/45 Pirelli P-Zero tires. The M635CSi was factory-equipped with a lowered sport suspension and a 26-mm front sway bar, and aftermarket rear shocks have been installed. Anti-lock braking is provided by power-assisted four-wheel discs. The sway bar bushings were replaced in January 2024, and the seller notes the brake pads were replaced in preparation for the sale.

The power-adjustable front comfort seats have been reupholstered in black leather, and they are joined by color-coordinated door panels and carpeting. An Alpine CD stereo has been installed, and amenities include air conditioning, power-operated windows and locks, an onboard computer, and an M-branded leather-wrapped shift knob. The steering wheel and dashboard were reconditioned under current ownership. The clock is inoperative.

The M-Tech 1 steering wheel frames a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as a 160-mph speedometer and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The six-digit odometer shows 168k miles, approximately 4k of which were added under current ownership. The instrument cluster was removed and reinstalled to facilitate the replacement of the light bulbs in September 2022.

The 3.5-liter DOHC M88/3 inline-six is equipped with individual throttle bodies and differs from the US-market S38B35 by featuring a single-row timing chain, exhaust headers, and a piston and head combination that results in a higher 10.5:1 compression ratio. Factory-rated output was 282 horsepower and 252 lb-ft of torque. A fuel hose was replaced in April 2022, and work in March 2024 involved replacing the ignition cap and rotor along with the spark plugs.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. The transmission fluid was changed in April 2022.

Documents related to the car’s import can be viewed in the gallery and are included in the sale. Manufacturer’s literature, period brochures, and service records dating to 1984 will also accompany the car.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage and lists history in California beginning in 1986.
The car has been designated a gross polluter by the state of California, however, the car since passed a California emissions test in March 2024.

This Chevy Junior go-kart was manufactured by Rupp Industries of Mansfield, Ohio, and is based on the design of the 1965 Chevrolet Monza SS show car. It features white fiberglass bodywork mounted over a tubular steel frame, and it is powered by a 3.5 horsepower Tecumseh single-cylinder engine fitted at the rear and linked with a centrifugal clutch and a drive chain. Features include 5″ Rupp turbine wheels, a single seat trimmed in black vinyl, and a three-spoke steering wheel. This Rupp Monza Junior was acquired by the seller roughly 14 years ago, and it is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve in Gainesville, Georgia, on a bill of sale.

The original Monza kart design was custom-built at the GM Tech Center for Bill Mitchell’s stepson and Chuck Jordan’s son. Their popularity inspired General Motors to contract Rupp to produce a run of karts for commercial sale based on an existing Rupp chassis. Rupp later marketed the kart as both the Monza Junior and Chevy Junior. This example has been finished in white, and additional features include a “Chevy Junior” plate, Chevrolet scripts, and faux taillights with red quad reflectors.
The 5″ Rupp turbine wheels feature polished lips and are mounted with Goodyear tires. Stopping power is provided by a single mechanically operated rear drum.
The cockpit features a black vinyl seat, a three-spoke steering wheel with polished accents, and a simulated instrument cluster.
The pull-start Tecumseh single was factory rated at 3.5 horsepower, which is routed to the rear wheels through a centrifugal clutch and a drive chain.
The manufacturer’s plaque is affixed to the body and shows serial number 29516.

This 1976 Chevrolet Corvette coupe was acquired by the seller in 2018 and subsequently underwent a cosmetic and mechanical refurbishment. Work is said to have included fitting the 454ci V8, overhauling the four-speed manual transmission, repainting the exterior red, and replacing suspension components. Additional equipment includes Hooker headers and side pipes, a Ron Davis radiator, 15″ Race Star wheels, removable roof panels, a raised cowl hood, and a Bluetooth-capable stereo. This C3 Corvette coupe is offered with an additional set of wheels and a clean New York title in the seller’s name.

The car was repainted red and a raised cowl hood was installed under current ownership. Equipment includes pop-up headlights, a power antenna, and removable roof panels. An area of paint is missing on the front bumper.

Chrome 15″ Race Star wheels are mounted with Mickey Thompson Sportsman S/T tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs. The seller states the suspension was overhauled under current ownership.
The cabin features bucket seats upholstered in gray leather. Equipment includes a Bluetooth-capable stereo and power windows. The heater does not work.

The four-spoke steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and a column-mounted water temperature gauge. An analog clock and auxiliary gauges are mounted in the center stack. The odometer does not work. Total mileage is unknown.

The 454 V8 was installed in 2020, and additional work at that time is said to have included installing Hooker headers and side pipes, a Ron Davis radiator, and MSD ignition components as well as replacing the water pump, fuel pump, alternator, and serpentine belts. An oil change was performed in April 2024.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transmission and a Positraction differential. The seller states the transmission was overhauled under current ownership.
An additional set of wheels are included in the sale.
The seller signed and dated the title in November 2021.

This 1968 Ford Mustang GT convertible was first delivered to Loucks Motors Limited of Ponoka, Alberta, Canada, and is powered by a 390ci V8 paired with a four-speed manual transmission. The car is refinished in red over black vinyl and equipped with a Traction-Lok differential, a white convertible soft top, 14″ steel wheels, power-assisted front disc brakes, power steering, GT side stripes, fog lights, hood vents, front bucket seats, an AM/FM/cassette stereo, a center console, and a Hurst shifter. This Mustang GT convertible was acquired by the selling dealer in 2008 and is now offered with a Deluxe Marti Report photocopy, a boot cover, and an Ohio title.

The car was delivered in Gulfstream Aqua and is said to have been refinished in its current shade of red with white accents in 2000. Features include a replacement white convertible soft top, a black boot cover, a GT fuel cap, fog lights, hood vents, quad exhaust outlets, and bright bumpers.
The 14″ steel wheels are mounted with Goodyear Eagle ST tires measuring 215/70. The car is equipped with power steering and braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The cabin features front bucket seats and a rear bench upholstered in black vinyl, and appointments include an AM/FM/cassette stereo, a Hurst shifter, a heater, and a center console with storage and cupholders.

The steering wheel is mounted on a tilting column and frames a 120-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and auxiliary gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and amperage. The five-digit odometer shows 56k miles, approximately 3k of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.
The 390ci Thunderbird Special V8 was factory rated at 325 horsepower and equipped with a four-barrel carburetor.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transmission and a Traction-Lok differential.
A photocopy of the Deluxe Marti Report shows initial delivery to Loucks Motors Limited of Ponoka, Alberta, Canada, and lists factory options and production statistics.
The Ohio title carries a “Non-Actual: Warning Odometer Discrepancy” notation.

This 2000 Jeep Wrangler Sahara remained registered in Florida until 2024 and now has 54k miles. The truck is finished in black over Dark Green and Camel cloth upholstery and is powered by a 4.0-liter inline-six linked with a three-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range Command-Trac transfer case. Features include a tan Quadratec soft top, full metal doors, 15″ Canyon aluminum wheels, a Rough Country steering stabilizer, fog lights, air conditioning, a fold-and-tumble rear seat, power steering, high-back front bucket seats, an AM/FM/CD stereo, and a roll bar. The selling dealer acquired the truck in 2024 and has since replaced the spark plugs, tires, rear drum brakes, and rear wheel cylinders. This TJ Wrangler is now offered in Virginia with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Arizona title.

The truck is finished in black and features a tan Quadratec soft top that was fitted by the selling dealer. Additional exterior details include full metal doors, sill protectors, fog lights, dual side mirrors, and a swing-out tailgate.

The 15″ Canyon aluminum wheels are fitted with 31×10.5″ Sailun Terramax All-Terrain tires that were installed in preparation for the sale, and a full-size spare is mounted to a swing-out rear carrier. Stopping power is provided by front discs and rear drums. The truck came factory equipped with a Quadra-Coil multi-link suspension with live solid axles. A Rough Country steering stabilizer was installed and the rear drum brakes and rear wheel cylinders were replaced in preparation for the sale as well.

The cabin features high-back front bucket seats upholstered in Dark Green and Camel cloth with color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Amenities include a fold-and-tumble rear seat, a roll bar, a mini-floor console with a cup holder, air conditioning, an AM/FM/CD stereo, and a locking glovebox.
The steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for fuel level, battery voltage, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The digital odometer indicates 54k miles.
The 4.0-liter Power Tech inline-six was rated at 181 horsepower and 222 lb-ft when new. The spark plugs were replaced and an oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.

Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range Command-Trac transfer case. A transmission service was carried out in preparation for the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

description: This 1982 Mercedes-Benz 300CD Turbo was purchased by the seller from its long-term prior owner in 2024, and it now shows 186k miles. The car is powered by a 3.0-liter turbodiesel inline-five paired with a four-speed automatic transmission and is finished in Champagne Metallic over Palomino leather upholstery. Features include a sunroof, 14″ Bundt alloy wheels, a cassette stereo, cruise control, air conditioning, and automatic climate control. This W123 300CD Turbo is offered with manufacturer’s literature, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The car was finished from the factory in Champagne Metallic (473) and was refinished in 2002. Exterior details include a sunroof, fog lights, dual side mirrors, a power antenna, and bright trim. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.
Silver-finished 14″ Bundt alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Harmony tires. Stopping power is provided by disc brakes at each corner.

The front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in Palomino leather, and interior features include power windows, a cassette stereo, cruise control, and automatic climate control. The air conditioning system was recharged in preparation for the sale.

Instrumentation consists of an 85-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 186k miles, approximately 200 of which were added under current ownership.
The 3.0-liter turbodiesel inline-five was factory-rated at 119 horsepower and 170 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission. The transmission was reportedly rebuilt approximately 20 years ago.
Service records and documentation that is said to cover the car’s history since new are included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1997 Porsche Boxster has 43k miles following an IMS bearing and clutch replacement in September 2021. It is powered by a 2.5-liter flat-six paired with a five-speed manual transaxle and is finished in Arctic Silver Metallic over black leather. Features include a black soft top, 16″ alloy wheels, a speed-activated rear spoiler, a Becker Porsche CR-210 cassette stereo, a Sony CD changer, cruise control, and automatic climate control. This 986 Boxster is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with the owner’s manual, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Minnesota title.
The car is finished in Arctic Silver Metallic and features a black soft top, and additional features include a speed-activated rear spoiler, side air intakes, and roll hoops.
The 16″ alloy wheels are mounted with Bridgestone Potenza S02A S-04 Pole Position tires. Braking is handled by four-piston Porsche-branded calipers fitted over vented rotors at all four corners.

The cabin features seats upholstered in black leather, while Porsche-branded floor mats line the footwells. Additional features include a Becker Porsche CR-210 cassette stereo, a remote Sony CD changer, cruise control, and automatic climate control. A satellite radio receiver has been installed in lower portion of the center console.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a central tachometer, a 160-mph speedometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 43k miles.

The mid-mounted 2.5-liter M96 flat-six was factory rated at 201 horsepower and 181 lb-ft of torque. The IMS bearing was replaced in September 2021, and additional work at that time included replacing the rear crankshaft seal, the water pump, and the spark plugs. The oxygen sensors were replaced in October 2021, the mass air flow sensor and the fuel pressure regulator were replaced in June 2022, and wiring was repaired in November 2022.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle. The clutch assembly was replaced in September 2021.

This 1981 Toyota Pickup is a 4×2 example that is powered by a 2.2-liter diesel inline-four linked with a five-speed manual transmission. The truck was acquired by the seller in 2018 and subsequently refurbished mechanically and cosmetically. Finished in beige over two-tone vinyl upholstery, it is equipped with 14″ steel wheels, power brakes, a sliding rear window, and a tubular rear bumper with a receiver hitch. Previously listed on BaT in February 2023, this diesel pickup is now offered at no reserve in Canada with British Columbia registration in the seller’s name.

The truck was disassembled and sandblasted before it was refinished under current ownership according to the seller, who reports that the bottom of the cab and bed were zinc-plated during the work. Exterior details include a tubular rear bumper, anodized rear window trim, a telescoping antenna, a sliding rear window, vent windows, bed tie-down points, rear mud flaps, and a receiver hitch. The seller states stainless-steel trim has been applied to the top of the cabin and the sides of the windshield, and that the truck wears British Columbia Collector plates. The listing photos are from 2023.

This is a relist after the vehicle was previously sold on BaT in July 2024 and the winning bidder failed to follow through with their commitment to purchase. This was not due to any fault with the vehicle. The winner’s participation on BaT has been restricted and their buyer’s fee was not refunded.

Silver-painted 14″ steel wheels are mounted with 205/75 Hankook Optimo H724 tires. The truck is equipped with KYB shock absorbers, and the power-assisted brake system was overhauled during the refurbishment.

The split bench seat is trimmed in two-tone vinyl and accompanied by color-coordinated door panels and brown carpets. Equipment consists of a heater, manual crank windows, and a push-button AM radio that the seller states does not produce sound.

A two-spoke steering wheel fronts a 140-km/h speedometer and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The six-digit odometer shows 199k kilometers (~124k miles), approximately 1k of which have been added under current ownership. The Carfax report shows a mileage inconsistency in June 2012, and true mileage is unknown.
The 2.2-liter SOHC diesel inline-four was rated at 62 horsepower and 93 lb-ft of torque when new.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission. A shifter bushing was replaced in preparation for the sale along with the fuel sending unit. Additional underbody photos are provided in the gallery.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned mileage inconsistency in 2012.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada.

This 1970 Oldsmobile 442 convertible was initially delivered to Krouse Oldsmobile of Cherry Hill, New Jersey, and it is powered by a 455ci Rocket V8 that was overhauled in 2021. Power is routed through a three-speed automatic transmission and a heavy-duty performance rear axle with 3.23:1 gearing. Finished in blue with a power-operated white soft top and matching stripes, the car is equipped with ram-air induction, 14″ Super Stock III wheels, power steering, front disc brakes, and a dual exhaust system, while the cabin is trimmed in blue vinyl upholstery and fitted with power windows, a center console, a Custom Sport steering wheel, and a push-button AM/FM radio. Acquired by the seller in 2020, this 442 convertible is offered with a window sticker and a Massachusetts title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in Twilight Blue with a power-operated white soft top, and white stripes accent the ram-air hood, trunk lid, and bodysides. Additional details include a white boot cover, sport mirrors, chrome bumpers, quad headlights, and dual exhaust outlets with trumpet-style finishers.

Body-color 14″ Super Stock III wheels are mounted with 225/70 BFGoodrich Radial T/A white-letter tires, and a matching spare is stowed in the trunk. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is provided by power-assisted front disc and rear drum brakes.

The front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in blue button-tufted vinyl and are joined by woodgrain trim on the dashboard, center console, and doors. Interior appointments include a floor-mounted shifter, power-operated windows, deluxe lap belts, and a push-button AM/FM radio. The air conditioning does not blow cold.

The Custom Sport steering wheel sits on a tilting column and fronts a 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer, an analog clock, and supplementary readouts. The five-digit odometer shows 25k miles, approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 455ci Rocket V8 is said to have been overhauled in 2021, and it breathes through a four-barrel carburetor and ram-air induction. Approximately 2k miles are said to have been added since the engine overhaul.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a three-speed Turbo-Hydramatic automatic transmission and a heavy-duty performance rear axle with 3.23:1 gearing.
A window sticker lists initial delivery to Krouse Oldsmobile of Cherry Hill, New Jersey, along with factory equipment and options.
The current Massachusetts title lists an Odometer Discrepancy brand.

This 2007 Honda VFR800 Interceptor is a 25th Anniversary Special commemorating a quarter-century of Interceptor production, and it was purchased new by the seller in 2009. Powered by a liquid-cooled 781cc DOHC V4 mated to a six-speed transmission, the bike wears full-fairing bodywork finished in white and blue with red accents. Equipment consists of 17″ alloy wheels, linked triple-disc brakes, an HMAS cartridge fork, a Pro Arm single-sided swingarm, and dual under-seat mufflers as well as an integrated windscreen, clip-on handlebars, two-up seating, and both side and center stands. The bike has been kept off the road since 2020, and its odometer indicates 2,700 miles. This VFR800 is now offered at no reserve with a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The fully faired bodywork is finished in the 25th Anniversary livery of Pearl Fadeless White and Pearl Spencer Blue with red stripes, and it is mounted over an aluminum twin-spar frame. Features include a 5.8-gallon fuel tank with commemorative graphics along with an integrated windscreen, fairing-mounted mirrors, both center and side stands, folding passenger foot pegs, and a black vinyl-upholstered two-up seat. Photos showing scratches on the back of the tank are provided in the gallery below.

Five-spoke 17″ cast-alloy wheels wear Bridgestone tires, and braking is provided by a linked system with dual 296mm discs and three-piston Nissin calipers up front along with a single 256mm-disc version at the rear. Adjustable suspension consists of a 43mm Honda Multi-Action System (HMAS) cartridge-style fork as well as a Pro-Link monoshock and linkage mounted to the aluminum Pro Arm single-sided swingarm. Rust on the fork is noted by the seller.

Clip-on handlebars are mounted above the upper triple clamp, and the instrument panel ahead houses a centrally mounted tachometer with an 11,800-rpm redline. An LCD screen is located on each side, displaying a digital speedometer on the left and a fuel gauge on the right along with readouts for ancillary functions. The digital odometer indicates 2,700 miles, all of which were ridden under current ownership.

The liquid-cooled 781cc DOHC V4 is equipped with VTEC variable valve timing, programmed fuel injection, and digital ignition as well as a four-into-one-into-two exhaust system with dual-outlet mufflers under the tail section. Factory-rated output was 110 horsepower and 61 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a hydraulically actuated clutch, a six-speed transmission, and a drive chain.
The motorcycle is currently registered as Planned Non-Operation in the state of California.

This 2022 Combat Motors P51 Combat Fighter is powered by a fuel-injected 132ci V-twin paired with a five-speed transmission. Features include a billet monocoque chassis, carbon-fiber trim, a solo seat, BST carbon-fiber wheels, a girder fork, adjustable Race Tech monoshocks, Beringer triple disc brakes, and sight-glass covers for the airbox, fuel tank, and cam chest. The bike was purchased new by the seller in 2022, and it now shows 137 miles. This P51 is now offered with a certificate of origin and a clean Texas title in the seller’s name.

The bike features exposed frame and chassis components wearing their raw-aluminum finishes as well as a carbon-fiber belly pan, heat shield, and fenders. Additional equipment includes an aluminum backbone frame that houses 3.75 gallons of fuel as well as a side stand, a multi-element round headlight, LED front indicators integrated into the fork legs, and rear lighting integrated into a solo seat upholstered in brown leather.

BST carbon-fiber wheels measuring 19″ up front and 17″ at the rear are mounted with Pirelli 120/70 Gran Turismo and Pirelli 240/45 Diablo Rosso tires, respectively. Suspension consists of an aluminum girder fork, a triangulated aluminum swingarm, and adjustable Race Tech monoshocks at both ends. Braking components include dual Beringer Aerotec 4D twin-disc rotors with radial-mounted three-piston calipers up front in addition to a slotted wave rotor with a radial-mounted caliper at the rear.

The clubman-style handlebar is equipped with toggle-switchgear and a single bar-end mirror. Instrumentation consists of a Motogadget 8k-rpm tachometer with inset LED indicators and a multifunction liquid-crystal display. The digital odometer indicates 137 miles.

The air-cooled 132ci V-twin features machined 6061 aluminum crankcases, dual S&S Cycle throttle bodies, Delphi electronic fuel injection, an oil cooler, and sight-glass covers for the oil tank, intake, and camshaft gears and belts. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.

This 1984 Porsche 911 Carrera coupe was optioned with the M491 “Turbo Look” package, which added front and rear spoilers as well as wider rear bodywork. Finished in black over black leather upholstery, the car is powered by a 3.2-liter flat-six paired with a 915 five-speed manual transaxle and an optional limited-slip differential. Equipment includes 16″ Fuchs alloy wheels with body-color centers as well as a power-operated sunroof, front sport seats, cruise control, a MOMO Steering Wheel, air conditioning, and a Porsche Classic Communication Management (PCCM) head unit. The car was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024 following registration history in Illinois and Indiana, and work performed in preparation for the sale included adjusting the valves and replacing drive belts, brake hoses, rear brake pads, and shifter bushings. This Carrera coupe is offered in California with a Porsche Certificate of Authenticity, manufacturer’s literature, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Indiana title.

The M491 option was first introduced in 1984 and features front and rear spoilers from the contemporary 911 Turbo as well as wider front and rear fenders. The car is finished in black and features a power-operated sunroof, a rear window wiper, and heated power-adjustable side mirrors. The right fender and left quarter panel have been refinished and paint touch-ups have been applied to the front bumper cover and left quarter panel. There are paint chips on the forward-facing surfaces, and close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

The 16″ Fuchs alloy wheels feature body-color centers and anodized lips and are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport tires. The M491 package included Turbo-specification brakes, anti-roll bars, trailing arms, and torsion bars as well as Turbo brake calipers with drilled rotors. The brake fluid was changed and the brake hoses and rear brake pads were replaced in 2024.
The cabin features front sport seats upholstered in black leather. Amenities include cruise control, air conditioning, power windows, and a Porsche Classic Communication Management head unit.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped MOMO steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a central tachometer with a 6,300-rpm redline as well as a 170-mph speedometer, a Quarz clock, and gauges for oil level, oil pressure, oil temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 104k miles. The Carfax report indicates that a Not Actual Mileage title was issued in Illinois in April 1991, which the selling dealer attributes to a clerical error. Total mileage is unknown. The removed factory three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel is included in the sale.

The 3.2-liter M930/21 flat-six was factory rated at 200 horsepower and 185 lb-ft of torque, and a top-end rebuild was performed in 2007. The valves and throttle linkage were adjusted, the oil was changed, and the oil level sender gasket and drive belts were replaced in June 2024. Documentation of the rebuild is provided in the image gallery below.

Engine stamping *64E03605* is presented above and matches the number listed on the Porsche Certificate of Authenticity. Transaxle stamping 74510308 is shown in the gallery below and also matches the Certificate of Authenticity.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Type 915 five-speed manual transaxle and an optional limited-slip differential. The clutch was replaced in 2007, and the shifter bushings were replaced in 2024.
The Porsche Certificate of Authenticity shows factory colors, equipment, and a production completion date of March 15, 1984. Manufacturer’s literature and service records will accompany the sale.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned April 1991 Not Actual Miles title
Head over to our friends at Car and Driver to check out their February 1984 Road Test for the 911 Carrera.

This 2008 Volkswagen R32 is one of 5,000 units produced for the model year, and it is finished in Candy White over Anthracite leather. Power is from a 3.2-liter VR6 that drives all four wheels through a six-speed DSG automatic transaxle and a 4MOTION all-wheel-drive system, and other equipment includes a sunroof, bi-xenon headlights, 18″ Niche wheels, heated front sport seats, navigation, an in-dash CD changer, cruise control, and automatic climate control. This Mk5 R32 has 35k miles and is now offered by the selling dealer in New York with the owner’s manual and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Candy White (LB9A) and features bi-xenon headlights, power-adjustable side mirrors, a glass sunroof, a rear spoiler, a rear window wiper, and dual central exhaust outlets. The Carfax report lists “minor damage” in a September 2018 entry, which the selling dealer attributes to scrapes beneath the front valance.

The 18″ Niche wheels show curb marks and are mounted with Continental tires. The car is equipped with an Electronic Stabilization Program (ESP) and Anti-Slip Regulation (ASR). Stopping power is provided by disc brakes with blue-finished calipers at all four corners.

The heated front sport seats and split-folding rear bench are upholstered in Anthracite leather, while machined aluminum trim accents the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Amenities include an in-dash CD changer, aluminum pedals, power front-seat lumbar adjustment, dual-zone automatic climate control, and touchscreen infotainment with navigation.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel carries a pair of paddle shifters and fronts a 180-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 35k miles.
A serialized badge on the steering wheel denotes the car as #937 of the 5,000 Mk5 R32 units produced.
The 3.2-liter VR6 was factory rated at 250 horsepower with 236 lb-ft of torque.
Power is delivered to all four wheels through a six-speed DSG automatic transaxle, an Electronic Differential Lock, and a 4MOTION all-wheel-drive system.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage.

This 2016 Porsche 911 GT3 RS was purchased new by the current owner at Carlsen Porsche of Redwood City, California, and it was previously offered on BaT in June 2023. It is finished in GT Silver Metallic over black leather and Alcantara upholstery with red deviated stitching ordered through Porsche’s Special Wishes program. Power is provided by a 4.0-liter flat-six paired with a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle, and modifications include an Akrapovič Evolution Race Line titanium exhaust system, EVOMSit engine software, TechArt and MA Carbon carbon-fiber components, a European-market Porsche Club Sport roll cage, an integrated Escort Max 360 Ci radar detector, and Apple CarPlay with a rearview camera. The car is also equipped with a rear wing, a front-axle lift system, dynamic LED headlights, Porsche Active Suspension Management, Porsche Ceramic Composite Brakes, Porsche Torque Vectoring Plus, center-lock alloy wheels, the Sport Chrono Package, carbon-fiber-backed seats, and the Sound Package Plus. This 991.1 GT3 RS has 21 miles and is offered by the seller on behalf of the owner with a window sticker, a binder of documents, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

Developed as a track-focused variant of the GT3, the RS is equipped with a magnesium roof panel, a rear wing, a carbon-fiber trunk lid and front fenders, and aluminum doors. This example is finished in GT Silver Metallic, and it features LED headlights with the Porsche Dynamic Light System in addition to LED taillights with clear lenses. Exterior TechArt and MA Carbon carbon-fiber components include the front splitter, decklid cover, rear window visor, rear diffuser, side mirror supports, front fender vent inserts, rear quarter panel air intake vents, wing supports and end pieces, and side skirts. Clear paint protection film has reportedly been applied to the hood, front splitter, forward lighting, bumpers, fenders, side skirts, and quarter panels.

Staggered-diameter center-lock alloy wheels wear an optional satin black finish and are mounted with 265/35-20 front and 325/30-21 rear Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires. Standard GT3 RS equipment included rear-axle steering, Porsche Active Suspension Management, and Porsche Torque Vectoring Plus. The car was factory-optioned with a front-axle lift system as well as Porsche Ceramic Composite Brakes featuring yellow-painted calipers.

The carbon fiber-backed seats are trimmed in black leather and Alcantara, while red deviated stitching on the leather-covered dash, steering column, door panels, and GT3 RS headrest embroidery was specified through the Custom Tailoring Option under Porsche’s Special Wishes Program (CXX). A body-color European-market Porsche Club Sport roll cage has been fitted, and further appointments include the Sport Chrono Package, PCM with navigation, a rearview camera, the Sound Package Plus, the Light Design Package, an electronic logbook, a six-disc CD changer, Guards Red seat belts, Porsche Bluetooth handset, a fire extinguisher, and illuminated carbon fiber sill guards along with Apple CarPlay and SiriusXM satellite radio connectivity. An Escort 360 CI radar detector was installed and integrated to display alerts on the factory gauge cluster.

The steering wheel features MA Carbon carbon-fiber trim along with an optional thicker rim, and it fronts a 225-mph speedometer, a central GT3 RS-branded tachometer, a configurable LCD screen, and gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 21 miles.

The 4.0-liter flat-six has been modified with an Akrapovič Evolution Race Line titanium exhaust system and EVOMSit engine software. The battery and spark plugs were replaced in April 2021, at which time fluid changes were performed.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle with Porsche Torque Vectoring Plus.

The included window sticker displays initial delivery to Carlsen Porsche of Redwood City, California, and it lists factory colors, standard equipment, and over $50k of optional equipment along with a total price of $230,365. A binder of documents will also accompany the car.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage, displays at least one open recall, and lists history in California.

This 1975 Honda CB750 was purchased new by the current owner at Fay Myers Motor Co. of Denver, Colorado, and it now shows 14k miles. Powered by a 736cc SOHC inline-four paired with a five-speed transmission, the motorcycle is finished in Light Ruby Red with black, gold, and white stripes. It also features a kick starter, an electric starter, a quartet of Keihin carburetors, a four-into-two exhaust system, a front disc brake, wire-spoke wheels, a two-up seat with a passenger grab strap, and a side stand. This CB750K5 is offered at no reserve on dealer consignment with a tool kit, an owner’s manual, a maintenance checklist, a service guide, and a clean Colorado title.

The bike is finished in Light Ruby Red, and black, gold, and white stripes accent the 4.5-gallon fuel tank. Additional details include a rear grab bar, chrome-finished fenders, dual mirrors, a black vinyl-upholstered two-up seat with a passenger grab strap, and a side stand.

Wire-spoke wheels measuring 19″ up front and 18″ out back are wrapped in IRC Formula tires. Suspension consists of a conventional fork with black rubber gaiters in addition to a pair of partially shrouded shocks attached to the swingarm. Braking is handled by a front disc and a rear drum.

The chrome-finished handlebar is affixed to the upper triple clamp via a riser, the upper portion of which houses a quartet of indicator lights. Instrumentation consists of a Nippon Denso 150-mph speedometer and a matching tachometer. The five-digit odometer shows 14k miles.

The 736cc SOHC inline-four is equipped with a kick starter, an electric starter, four Keihin carburetors, and a four-into-two exhaust system. Factory-rated output was 67 horsepower. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and a drive chain.
A tool kit, an owner’s manual, a maintenance checklist, and a service guide are included in the sale.
listing_details: Red Paint w/Black, Gold & White Stripes

description: This 1992 Toyota Land Cruiser Prado EX LJ78 is a four-door right-hand-drive wagon that was imported to the US in 2022 and sold by the selling dealer to the current owner.
