It is finished in silver and blue over gray cloth and is powered by a 2.4-liter turbodiesel inline-four linked with a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Equipment includes a Toyota Electronic Modulated Suspension adaptive suspension, aftermarket 15″ wheels, front disc brakes, a sunroof, running boards, side steps, air conditioning, and a double-DIN Pioneer head unit. This J70 Prado shows 156k kilometers (~97k miles) and is now offered on dealer consignment with a clean New Jersey title.

The truck is finished in silver and blue and features a sunroof, chrome bumpers, running boards, window rain guards, side steps, and a rear window wiper. Offroad Express graphics have been applied to the lower rear doors. Paint chips and scuffs are noted on the exterior.

Aftermarket 15″ wheels are mounted with 265/70 Yokohama Geolandar A/T tires, and braking is provided by anti-lock front discs and rear drums. The truck came equipped from the factory with a Toyota Electronic Modulated Suspension adaptive suspension.

The right-hand-drive cabin features seats upholstered in two-tone gray cloth, and interior equipment includes an altimeter, a thermometer, air conditioning, and an aftermarket Pioneer head unit said to be equipped with Apply CarPlay and Bluetooth. Stickers and graphics adorn the glovebox door.

Instrumentation consists of a 170-km/h speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for oil pressure, voltage, fuel level, and coolant temperature. The six-digit odometer shows 156k kilometers (~97k miles), approximately 4k of which were added under current ownership.

The 2.4-liter turbodiesel 2L-TE inline-four was factory rated at 95 horsepower and 177 lb-ft of torque. Work in May 2022 reportedly included replacing the water pump, timing belt, head gaskets, and intake and exhaust gaskets, while an aluminum radiator was installed in November of that year. The cylinder head and exhaust were replaced in 2023, and the oil was changed in June 2024.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case.

attributes.value: Land Cruiser Prado EX LJ78 Turbodiesel

description: This 2001 Ford Excursion XLT is powered by a 7.3-liter Power Stroke turbodiesel V8 linked with a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. The truck is finished in Toreador Red Metallic over Medium Graphite cloth, and features include 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels, Mile Marker manual locking front hubs, cross-drilled and slotted brake rotors, KYX running boards, roof rails, an aftermarket remote start system, a backup camera, air conditioning, Pioneer door speakers, and an Alpine touchscreen head unit with wireless Apple CarPlay and Android Auto. The seller purchased the truck in 2023 and has since added approximately 36k of the 137k miles shown. This Excursion is now offered with service records, spare keys, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Ohio title.

The truck is finished in Toreador Red Metallic and is equipped with gray lower-bodywork, KYX running boards, roof rails, a receiver hitch, a backup camera, a split tailgate, and a rear window wiper. Rust is visible near the right rear window, and additional blemishes around the body are shown in the gallery below.

Polished 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with 265/75 Ironman All Country tires that were fitted in November 2023. Mile Marker manual locking hubs are equipped up front, and braking is handled by four-wheel discs with cross-drilled and slotted rotors all around that were installed in March 2024.

The interior features three rows of seating trimmed in Medium Graphite cloth with color-coordinated door panels and carpets. An Alpine touchscreen head unit with wireless Apple CarPlay and Android Auto and Pioneer door speakers are installed and additional amenities include cruise control, air conditioning, and an aftermarket remote start system.

The two-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel wears a cover and frames instrumentation that features LED lighting comprised of a 100-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 3,500-rpm redline and gauges for oil pressure, voltage, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 137k miles, approximately 36k of which were added under current ownership.
The 7.3-liter Power Stroke turbodiesel V8 was factory rated at 250 horsepower and 505 lb-ft of torque.
Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels via a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Areas of corrosion are visible on the underside.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage. A gap in entries can be seen between June 2003 and December 2020.
There is currently a lien on the truck, and the seller’s lender will need to be paid off before the title can be transferred to the next owner.
listing_details: Mile Marker Manual Locking Front Hubs

description: This 2015 Mercedes-Benz C63 AMG Coupe was purchased new by the seller at Mercedes-Benz Boundary in Vancouver, British Columbia, with the Edition 507 package that included upgraded engine components, a vented aluminum hood, carbon-fiber interior trim, forged AMG 19″ wheels, and upgraded brakes. Finished in Polar White over white leather and black Alcantara upholstery, it also has bi-xenon headlights, active corner illumination, a panoramic sunroof, COMAND infotainment with navigation, heated front seats, and a Harman Kardon sound system. Power comes from a 6.2-liter V8 paired with a seven-speed AMG Speedshift MCT transmission. The car has 3,500 kilometers (~2,200 miles), fewer than 150 of which were added since it was previously listed on BaT in September 2022. This C63 AMG is now offered at no reserve in Canada with manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carfax report, and British Columbia registration.

The body features AMG-specific bumper covers and hood vents as well as an Edition 507 gloss black rear spoiler and mirror caps. Additional details include a panoramic sunroof, active corner illumination, bi-xenon headlights, parking sensors, a rear diffuser, and quadruple exhaust outlets.
AMG 19″ forged wheels are mounted with 235/35 front and 255/30 rear Continental ContiSportContact tires. Red AMG-branded brake calipers are fitted over drilled and slotted rotors at all four corners.

The heated and power-adjustable front seats are upholstered in Designo white leather with black Alcantara inserts, and carbon-fiber trim accents the cabin, which has front seat position memory, Keyless Go, dual-zone automatic climate control, Harman Kardon audio, an auto-dimming rearview mirror, COMAND infotainment with navigation, and Edition 507 badging.
An Alcantara-wrapped steering wheel frames a 320-km/h speedometer, a tachometer, auxiliary gauges, and an LCD screen. The digital odometer indicates 3,500 kilometers (~2,200 miles).

The 6.2-liter M156 V8 was factory rated at 507 horsepower and 450 lb-ft of torque in Edition 507 trim, and it sends power to the rear wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission. The ignition coil for cylinder seven was replaced in preparation for the sale.
Additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada.

This 1989 Mercedes-Benz 560SEL has remained registered in Washington since new, and it is powered by a 5.5-liter M117 V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission. The car is finished in Midnight Blue over Palomino leather upholstery, and equipment includes a limited-slip differential, 15″ Gullideckel alloy wheels, a sunroof, heated power-adjustable front seats, heated rear seats, automatic climate control, and cruise control. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this W126 560SEL is offered in Oregon with a clean Carfax report and a clean Washington title.

The car is finished in Midnight Blue (904) and features a power-operated sunroof, a power antenna, dual exhaust outlets, headlight wipers, and bright window and bumper trim. Touch-up paint has been applied to scratches on the front and rear bumper covers, and close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

Silver 15″ Gullideckel alloy wheels are mounted with Westlake Radial tires. The car was equipped from the factory with a self-leveling hydraulic rear suspension. Braking is handled by power-assisted four-wheel discs with ABS.

The interior features seating surfaces upholstered in Palomino leather along with a color-coordinated center console, door panels, and carpets. Appointments include heated power-adjustable front seats, heated rear seats, a cassette stereo, automatic climate control, and cruise control. Wear is noted on the seat bolsters.

The four-spoke steering wheel frames a 170-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as an analog clock and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, fuel level, and instant fuel economy. The six-digit odometer shows 87k miles.
The 5.5-liter M117 V8 was factory-rated at 238 horsepower and 287 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2000 Chevrolet Metro is a three-door hatchback coupe that remained registered in Pennsylvania with its original owner until it was acquired by the selling dealer in June 2024 and now has 44k miles. It is finished in Bright Blue Metallic over two-tone gray cloth and is powered by a 1.0-liter inline-three paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes 13″ steel wheels, front disc brakes, and a rear window defroster in addition to air conditioning, a fold-down rear bench seat, and an AM/FM stereo. An oil change was performed and the tires were replaced in preparation for the sale. This Metro is now offered at no reserve by the selling dealer with manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Pennsylvania title.

The Metro was offered as both a four-door sedan and three-door coupe hatchback for the 2000 model year, and the body of this example is finished in Bright Blue Metallic. Details include black front and rear bumpers, side moldings, chrome-finished door edge protectors, a retractable antenna mounted on the A-pillar, and a rear window defroster.

The 13″ steel wheels wear full covers and were mounted with 155/80 Ironman iMove PT tires in preparation for the sale. The car is equipped with a Macpherson strut independent suspension system as well as front and rear sway bars. Braking is handled by front discs and rear drums.

The front bucket seats and rear bench seat are upholstered in two-tone gray cloth and are joined by color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Appointments include air conditioning, an AM/FM stereo, and manual-crank windows.
The four-spoke steering wheel frames a 90-mph speedometer and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The six-digit odometer shows 44k miles.

The 1.0-liter inline-three features electronic fuel injection and was factory rated at 55 horsepower and 58 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale. Power is delivered to the front wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle.
Manufacturer’s literature is included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1965 Oldsmobile 442 convertible is powered by a 400ci V8 linked to a three-speed Turbo Hydra-Matic automatic transmission and is finished in red with a power-operated white soft top over red vinyl upholstery. Equipment includes Super Sport 15″ wheels, red-line tires, power steering, power-assisted drum brakes, dual exhaust, front bucket seats, and Sunpro auxiliary gauges. The vehicle was refurbished at some point prior to 2018, and the current owner purchased the car in 2021. Subsequent service is said to have involved overhauling the brakes and replacing the voltage regulator, tires, points, fuel sending unit, windshield, and tailpipes. This 442 is now offered at no reserve on dealer consignment with a set of hubcaps, a trickle charger, and a clean Florida title.

Oldsmobile produced 3,468 Cutlass convertibles with the 442 performance package for 1965. Finished from the factory in Target Red with a black convertible top (R-1), this car has been repainted in red and fitted with a power-operated white convertible top. Equipment includes a red top boot, quad headlights, chrome bumpers, bright trim, 442 badging, a driver-side mirror, and reverse lights. The windshield and windshield molding reportedly were replaced in 2022. The seller notes that much of the exterior anodized and stainless trim has not been refurbished and exhibits pitting.

Super Sport 15″ wheels are mounted with 205/70 BFGoodrich Silvertown Radial double-red-line tires. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is provided by power-assisted drums at all four corners. In April 2021, the tires are said to have been replaced along with the brake master cylinder, rear shoes, hardware, and wheel cylinders.

The cabin features front bucket seats and a rear bench that have been reupholstered in red vinyl and are accented by coordinating door panels and replacement red carpeting. Appointments include lap belts, patterned-metal dash trim, a heater, and a locking glovebox. The retro-style aftermarket stereo in the dashboard is inoperative.

The two-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of a sweeping 120-mph speedometer and a fuel-level gauge. A Sunpro tachometer is attached to the steering column near Sunpro gauges for coolant temperature, voltage, and oil pressure. The five-digit odometer shows 13k miles, approximately 850 of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 400ci V8 is equipped with a four-barrel carburetor and was factory rated at 345 horsepower and 440 lb-ft of torque. The voltage regulator was replaced in 2021, and work in 2022 included replacing the points and the fuel sending unit, adjusting the timing and the carburetor, and flushing the radiator.

Power is routed to the rear wheels through a three-speed Turbo Hydra-Matic automatic transmission. The dual exhaust system’s tailpipes and hangars were replaced in 2022, according to the selling dealer.
Decoding the body tag reveals the following information:

This 1961 Chevrolet Corvette is powered by a fuel-injected 283ci V8 paired with a four-speed manual transmission and is refinished in red over black vinyl. The car underwent a refurbishment in 2002, and features include a removable hardtop, a power-retractable black soft top, a Positraction limited-slip differential, 15″ steel wheels, power windows, a heater, and a Wonder Bar AM radio. This C1 Corvette was acquired by the current owner in 2024 is now offered in Maryland on dealer consignment with an owner’s guide, a sales brochure, NCRS guides, refurbishment and historical photos, and a clean Pennsylvania title.

The car is refinished in red with white coves and features a matching removable hardtop as well as a power-retractable black soft top. Additional features include quad headlights and polished bumpers and trim.
The 15″ steel wheels feature simulated knock-off spinner covers and are mounted with wide whitewall tires. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel drums.

The cabin was refurbished and features two bucket seats upholstered in Black vinyl. Interior equipment includes a dash-mounted rearview mirror, power windows, a heater, a Wonder Bar AM radio, and an analog clock.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 5,300-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature, amperage, oil pressure, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 2,800 miles, though it was previously reset and total mileage is unknown.
The 283ci V8 was factory equipped with Rochester mechanical fuel injection for a rating of 275 horsepower when new.

The stamping on the engine pad is shown above. The CR suffix is consistent with a 283ci V8 rated at 275 horsepower and designated for a 1961 Corvette with Rochester mechanical fuel injection and a manual transmission.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission and a Positraction limited-slip differential.
An owner’s guide, a sales brochure, and NCRS guides are included in the sale.
listing_details: 15″ Steel Wheels w/Simulated Knock-Off Spinner Covers

description: This 2006 BMW M3 coupe was ordered with the Competition Package and is modified with a CSL-style trunk lid, Eventuri carbon-fiber intake, MAP sensor conversion kit, sway bars, and ECU and TCU tunes. The car is finished in Titanium Silver Metallic over black Nappa leather and is powered by a 3.2-liter inline-six linked with a six-speed SMG sequential transmission and a limited-slip differential. Other features comprise a PureTech Sweden rear chassis brace, 19″ Style 163M wheels, CPI headers, and a Rogue Engineering exhaust system. The current owner purchased the car in 2018 and has since added approximately 16k of the under 83k indicated miles. This E46 M3 was listed on BaT in June 2024 and is now offered again on dealer consignment with a clean Carfax report and a clean Arizona title.

The car is finished in Titanium Silver Metallic and features matte Shadowline trim as well as a CSL-style trunk lid, a glass sunroof, xenon headlights, carbon-fiber front splitters, rain-sensing windshield wipers, LED tail lights, and quad exhaust outlets.

The 19″ M cross-spoke Style 163M alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires. The car was factory equipped with Dynamic Stability Control (DSC), and suspension modifications include adjustable front end links, 30.88mm front and 22.5mm rear sway bars, ECS Tuning wheel spacers, and Turner Motorsport greaseable control arm monoball bushings and sealed monoball rear trailing arm bushings. Braking is provided by four-wheel ventilated discs, and the ZCP Competition Package added an upgraded steering rack and larger cross-drilled brake rotors. The front lower control arms are said to have been replaced.

The power-adjustable front sport seats are upholstered in black Nappa leather complemented by BMW Individual carbon-fiber trim on the dashboard. A PureTech Sweden rear chassis brace is mounted in the trunk area, and interior amenities include cruise control, a Harman Kardon sound system, automatic climate control, an aftermarket infotainment screen, and a center armrest delete kit. The Carfax report notes that the left and right airbags were replaced in January 2019.

The microsuede-wrapped steering wheel features M-color stitching and a yellow centering stripe and is modified with aftermarket shift paddles. Instrumentation consists of a 185-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a variable redline along with gauges for coolant temperature, oil temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates under 83k miles, approximately 16k of which were added under current ownership.

The 3.2-liter S54 inline-six sends power to the rear wheels through a six-speed SMG sequential transmission and a limited-slip differential. Engine and transmission modifications include the following:
A metal belly pan is also installed.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1961 Chevrolet Corvette is powered by a fuel-injected 283ci V8 paired with a four-speed manual transmission and is refinished in red over black vinyl. The car underwent a refurbishment in 2002, and features include a removable hardtop, a power-retractable black soft top, a Positraction limited-slip differential, 15″ steel wheels, power windows, a heater, and a Wonder Bar AM radio. This C1 Corvette was acquired by the current owner in 2024 is now offered in Maryland on dealer consignment with an owner’s guide, a sales brochure, NCRS guides, refurbishment and historical photos, and a clean Pennsylvania title.

The car is refinished in red with white coves and features a matching removable hardtop as well as a power-retractable black soft top. Additional features include quad headlights and polished bumpers and trim.
The 15″ steel wheels feature simulated knock-off spinner covers and are mounted with wide whitewall tires. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel drums.

The cabin was refurbished and features two bucket seats upholstered in Black vinyl. Interior equipment includes a dash-mounted rearview mirror, power windows, a heater, a Wonder Bar AM radio, and an analog clock.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 5,300-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature, amperage, oil pressure, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 2,800 miles, though it was previously reset and total mileage is unknown.
The 283ci V8 was factory equipped with Rochester mechanical fuel injection for a rating of 275 horsepower when new.

The stamping on the engine pad is shown above. The CR suffix is consistent with a 283ci V8 rated at 275 horsepower and designated for a 1961 Corvette with Rochester mechanical fuel injection and a manual transmission.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission and a Positraction limited-slip differential.
An owner’s guide, a sales brochure, and NCRS guides are included in the sale.
listing_details: 15″ Steel Wheels w/Simulated Knock-Off Spinner Covers

description: This 1988 Mercedes-Benz 300E was a former stereo competition car that was sold on BaT in March 2020. It is finished in black metallic over gray MB-Tex upholstery, and power comes from a 3.0-liter inline-six paired with a four-speed automatic transmission. Modifications include an AMG body kit, AMG wheels, a lowered suspension, and an aftermarket Alpine and a/d/s stereo system. A brake overhaul was performed under current ownership along with suspension, steering, and ignition work. This modified W124 is now offered on dealer consignment at no reserve in Florida with a clean Carfax report and a clean Montana title.

Finished in metallic black, the car is fitted with an AMG body kit consisting of a three-piece rear spoiler, rocker panel extensions, and bumper covers. The headlights, fog lights, and taillights feature LED lighting, and an under-body LED light kit was removed under current ownership. There are blemishes and dents on the exterior, the trunk lid paint has faded, and the lower rear valance is cracked.

AMG 17″ Monoblock wheels wear 225/45 Michelin Pilot Sport All Season tires that have 2023 date codes. The suspension is modified with lowering springs and front and rear sway bars. New Bilstein dampers are fitted in 2023, and additional work performed under current ownership included replacing the brake pads and rotors, the brake fluid, the stabilizer bar links, and the idler arm.

The interior is trimmed in gray MB-Tex with matching door panels and carpets. Amenities include cruise control, automatic climate control, and an electric sunroof. AMG-logo floor mats, an LED interior light system, and an aftermarket Alpine stereo system with a/d/s speakers. The subwoofer in the trunk does not work. The ABS warning light is illuminated, the power adjustments for the front seats work intermittently, and the air conditioning was recharged twice in 2023.

The airbag steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation consisting of a 160-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for temperature, oil pressure, fuel level, and fuel economy. The six-digit odometer shows 72k miles and was repaired under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 3.0-liter M103 inline-six is equipped with a tubular exhaust header, and a strut tower brace spans the rear of the engine compartment. Work since 2021 has included replacing the mass air flow sensor, alternator, distributor cap, spark plugs and wires, and the fuel filter.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission. A Magnaflow muffler is fitted and no catalytic converter is installed.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 2004 Mercedes-Benz SL55 AMG spent time in South Carolina and Illinois prior to the seller’s September 2022 purchase, and it now has 45k miles. The car is finished in Pewter Metallic over Charcoal leather and is powered by a supercharged 5.4-liter V8 paired with a five-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes a power-retractable hardtop, bi-xenon headlights, 18″ AMG five-spoke alloy wheels, heated multi-contour seats, a Bose sound system, and COMAND with navigation. This R230 is offered with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Florida title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in Pewter Metallic (723) and features a power-folding convertible hardtop, and AMG bodywork including a revised front spoiler, side skirts, and quad exhaust outlets. Other equipment includes bi-xenon headlights with washers, fog lights, and fender air vents. A trunk compartment hydraulic cylinder and a convertible pump were replaced in September 2023.

This is a relist after the vehicle was previously sold on BaT in July 2024 and the winning bidder failed to follow through with their commitment to purchase. This was not due to any fault with the vehicle. The winner’s participation on BaT has been restricted and their buyer’s fee was not refunded.

The 18″ AMG five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Super Sport tires that were installed in April 2021. The car features Active Body Control (ABC) suspension as well as an Electronic Stability Program (ESP), Automatic Slip Control (ASR), revised suspension settings, and an AMG High Performance Braking System with cross-drilled rotors.

The heated multi-contour seats are trimmed in Charcoal leather, and burl walnut wood accents the center console and door panels. Amenities include dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, a Bose sound system, and COMAND with navigation. the upper-left bolster on the driver’s seat was re-dyed and the trunk lid vinyl was repaired in May 2021. A piece of cracked plastic is noted in the trunk.

The leather-trimmed steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 45k approximately 5k of which were added under current ownership. The seller notes a distortion on one of the digital screens.

The supercharged 5.4-liter M113 V8 was factory rated at 493 horsepower and 516 lb-ft of torque. The alarm horn was replaced in August 2021, the spark plugs and valve cover gaskets were replaced in October 2021, and the supercharger drive belt as well as the electric change-over valve and relay were replaced in December 2021.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed automatic transmission.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to John Sisson Motors in Washington, Pennsylvania, along with factory colors, standard features, optional equipment, and a total price of $124,020.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 2001 Porsche Boxster S is finished in Zanzibar Red over black full supple leather and is powered by a 3.2-liter flat-six paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. It has remained on the East Coast since new and now has 63k miles. Equipment includes the Sport Touring and Power Seat packages as well as a black soft top, 18″ Turbo-look wheels, xenon headlights, a speed-activated rear spoiler, cruise control, a Bluetooth-capable Alpine CD stereo, and a Hi-Fi sound system with DSP. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this 986 Boxster S is now offered with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Zanzibar Red and features a black soft top with a replacement rear window. Additional features include xenon headlights, a speed-activated rear spoiler, side air intake scoops, roll hoops, and clear front side markers. The seller notes wear on the soft top fabric, a patched tear in the top rear window, and blemishes in the finish as depicted in the photo gallery along with photos of paint meter readings.

The 18″ Turbo-look wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Super Sport front and Michelin Pilot Sport 4S rear tires measuring 225/40 and 265/35, respectively. Braking is handled by four-piston Porsche-branded calipers fitted over cross-drilled rotors at all four corners.

The cabin features power-adjustable seats upholstered in black supple leather, and color-coordinated leather extends to the dashboard and door panels. Features include driver seat-position memory settings, a wind deflector, cruise control, automatic climate control, a Bluetooth-capable Alpine CD stereo, and a Hi-Fi sound system with Digital Sound Processing (DSP). The seller states that the instrument binnacle leather upholstery has been replaced, and a climate control screen was replaced in preparation for the sale. The center console hinge is missing.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a central tachometer, a 180-mph speedometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 63k miles.

The mid-mounted 3.2L flat-six was factory rated at 250 horsepower and 225 lb-ft of torque. Records indicate that the IMS bearing was replaced in September 2013 at 35k miles at which time the rear main seal was also replaced. The oil was most recently changed in June 2023.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a six-speed manual transaxle. The clutch components were replaced along with the flywheel and pilot bearing in September 2013 at 35k miles.

The window sticker notes initial delivery to Leith Incorporated in Cary, North Carolina, and lists factory equipment, colors, options, and a total price of $61,252. The owner’s manual, tools, and service records are also included in the sale.
The Carfax report notes at least one recall.
Head over to our friends at Car and Driver to check out their January 2000 Road Test for the 986 Boxster S.

This 1973 BMW R75/5 is a long-wheelbase (LWB) example that was acquired by the seller in November 2019, reportedly from the spouse of its original owner. It subsequently earned a Vintage Award at the June 2022 BMW MOA Rally in Springfield, Missouri, which celebrated the 50th anniversary of the /5. The bike finished in blue with white pinstripes and is powered by a 745cc opposed twin paired with a four-speed transmission. Equipment includes an enclosed driveshaft, an electric starter, a chrome dual exhaust system, dual Bing carburetors, 19″ front and 18″ rear wire-spoke wheels, panniers, and a black vinyl-upholstered two-up seat. This R75/5 LWB is offered with an owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, a tool kit, and a clean Michigan title in the seller’s name.

The bike is finished in Blue Metallic (539), and equipment includes a grab bar, a left-side lift-assist handle, both center and side stands, panniers, dual mirrors, and a black vinyl-upholstered two-up seat.

Wire-spoke wheels with alloy rims were mounted with 3.25-19″ front and 4.00-18″ rear Metzeler Block C5 tires in November 2019 at which time the rims were polished and the spokes were replaced. Stopping power is provided by front and rear drums. Suspension consists of a leading-axle fork as well as dual shocks mounted to the swingarm on the left and the final-drive enclosure on the right. The fork seals were replaced in November 2022. The increase in wheelbase was a mid-year change by BMW, with LWB models identifiable by the 50mm (~2″) welded-in section just forward of the swingarm flange where it bolts to the rear drive.

The handlebar is mounted to the upper triple clamp via a pair of risers that frame the adjustment knob for a steering damper. The headlight nacelle houses a MotoMeter combination gauge, which contains a 120-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,800-rpm redline. The five-digit odometer shows 3,500 miles, approximately 3k of which were ridden by the seller.

The 745cc opposed twin features an electric starter, a chrome dual exhaust system with a crossover tube, and dual Bing carburetors. Factory-rated output was 50 horsepower and 44 lb-ft of torque. The pushrod tube seals were replaced in August 2022 and the oil was last changed in May 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a four-speed transmission and a driveshaft enclosed within the right leg of the swingarm.
The number 4004938 stamped on the engine case matches with the numbers stamped on the frame and steering headstock tag.
The Michigan title carries a “Duplicate” notation under the Brand or Legend section.
listing_details: Dual Chrome Exhaust System w/Crossover Pipe

description: This 1980 Honda CR250R Elsinore was acquired in 2021 by the seller who carried out a refurbishment in 2024 that included rebuilding the 248cc two-stroke single, overhauling the wheels and hand controls, fitting a Mikuni carburetor, reupholstering the seat, and replacing the side panels, drive chain, sprockets, and hardware. The bike is finished in Tahitian Red, and equipment includes a five-speed transmission, 21″ and 18″ alloy wire-spoke wheels, a black-finished upswept expansion-chamber exhaust, high-mounted fenders, preload-adjustable shocks, and drum brakes. This CR250R is now offered at no reserve in Ohio for off-road use only with a bill of sale.

The bike is finished in Tahitian Red and features include a red-finished frame, a blue solo seat, side number plates, and high-mounted fenders. The seat was recovered and the side panels and hardware were replaced in 2024.

The 21″ and 18″ alloy wire-spoke wheels wear 3.00″ front and 5.00″ rear IPC knobby tires, and the rims, spokes and tires were replaced in July 2024. Suspension consists of a leading-axle telescopic fork as well as dual preload-adjustable shocks mounted to the swingarm. Braking is provided by drums at both ends.

The replacement black handlebar features an engine stop switch on the left. The grips, engine stop switch, and hand controls were replaced in 2024. No instrumentation is present, therefore total mileage is unknown.
The 248cc two-stroke single features a kick starter and a black high-mount exhaust system. It was rebuilt in July 2024 with work that included:
Power is routed to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission. The drive chain and sprockets were replaced in 2024.
The bike does not have a title or registration. It is being sold on a bill of sale only.

This 1987 Porsche 944S is powered by a 2.5-liter inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transaxle and is finished in Diamond Blue Metallic over black leather upholstery. Equipment includes 15″ phone-dial alloy wheels, a detachable roof panel, pop-up headlights, fog lights, power-adjustable front seats, cruise control, an aftermarket head unit, and air conditioning. The car was purchased by the seller in 2020, and subsequent work is said to have included rebuilding the cylinder head and replacing the timing belt, timing belt tensioner, coolant hoses, coolant reservoir, motor mounts, dampers, control arm bushings, steering rack boots, and outer tie rods. This 944S is offered with manufacturer’s literature, service records, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean North Carolina title in the seller’s name.

The car was finished from the factory in Diamond Blue Metallic and was refinished under previous ownership. Exterior details include pop-up headlights, a detachable roof panel, a rear spoiler, and fog lights. Paint touch-ups have been applied to the left fender and paint chips are noted around the body. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

Silver 15″ phone-dial alloy wheels are mounted with Fuzion tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel power-assisted ventilated discs. The seller states that the dampers, control arm bushings, sway bar bushings, steering rack boots, and outer tie rods were replaced under current ownership.

The cabin features power-adjustable seats upholstered in black leather along with a color-coordinated center console and door panels. Amenities include cruise control, air conditioning, an alarm system, power windows, and an aftermarket head unit. The cargo cover does not retract and the turn signal stalk does not return to the center.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 170-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges. The six-digit odometer shows 106k miles, approximately 300 of which were added under current ownership. The Carfax report shows a history of Not Actual Miles-branded titles starting in November 2012. Total mileage is unknown.

The 2.5-liter M44/40 inline-four features Bosch engine management and was factory rated at 188 horsepower and 170 lb-ft of torque. Work performed since 2020 is said to have included rebuilding the cylinder head and replacing the timing belt, timing belt tensioner, coolant hoses, coolant reservoir, motor mounts, crank sensor, oil pressure sender, oxygen sensor, and knock sensor.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle. The clutch cylinders and throw-out bearing were replaced under current ownership, per the seller.
Decoding the option sticker reveals the following information:
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned history of Not Actual Miles-branded titles beginning in November 2012.

This 1998 Mercedes-Benz E320 wagon is finished in Aspen Green Metallic with pinstripes over tan leather, and it is powered by a 3.2-liter V6 paired with a five-speed automatic transmission. Features include a sunroof, 16″ 10-hole wheels, power-adjustable front seats, a rear-facing third-row bench, a roof rack, cruise control, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This S210 E320 wagon is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with literature, a first-aid kit, a damage-free Carfax report, and a clean New York title.

The car is finished in Aspen Green Metallic (891) and is equipped with a power-operated glass sunroof, fog lights, a roof rack, an eccentric-sweeping monoblade wiper, power side mirrors, a power tailgate, a rear window wiper, roof rails, and bright trim.

The 16″ 10-hole light alloy wheels are mounted with a mixture of Michelin Defender and Michelin Premier tires. The S210 wagon was factory equipped with a self-leveling rear suspension. The car is equipped with Automatic Slip Control (ASR) . Stopping power is provided by four-wheel ventilated discs.
The cabin features power-adjustable front seats upholstered in tan leather, and amenities include front-seat position memory, cruise control, and dual-zone automatic climate control.
The rear-facing bench seat stows flat into the cargo area floor.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a 7k-rpm tachometer as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer shows 38k miles, although the Carfax report lists a potential odometer rollback in a November 2010 entry. Total mileage is unknown.
The 3.2-liter M112 V6 was factory rated at 221 horsepower and 232 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed automatic transmission. Additional photographs of the underside are shown in the gallery below.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned potential odometer rollback.

This 1973 Norton Commando 750 Roadster was refurbished in Vancouver, British Columbia, before it was imported to the United States circa 2013, and it resided in Washington prior to its 2019 acquisition by the seller. Finished in black with gold graphics, the motorcycle is powered by an overbored 745cc air-cooled parallel twin paired with a four-speed transmission that was rebuilt by Colorado Norton Works. It is also equipped with a single Mikuni carburetor, Boyer Bransden electronic ignition, a Colorado Norton Works single-coil conversion and three-phase alternator system, an overhauled front disc brake, Ikon rear shocks, a Roadholder telescopic fork with Teflon-lined bushings and Lansdowne adjustable dampers, and laced wheels with shouldered rims as well as a two-up seat, amber turn signals, and both center and side stands. This Commando is offered at no reserve with workshop manuals, spare parts, service and parts invoices, and a Washington title in the seller’s name.

The motorcycle is finished in black with gold graphics. Features include a chrome-plated headlight shell, amber turn signals, a combined stoplight and taillight, a black vinyl-upholstered two-up seat with a passenger grab strap, and folding passenger foot pegs along with both center and side stands. A portion of the gallery photos were taken in July 2023.

The laced wheels feature stainless-steel spokes, replacement wheel bearings, and shouldered rims measuring 19″ up front and 18″ out back, and they are mounted with Bridgestone Battlax BT45 tires. The Roadholder telescopic fork has been fitted with Cosentino Engineering Teflon-lined bushings under current ownership along with Lansdowne dampers, which enable adjustment of compression and rebound damping. An aftermarket one-piece rear axle has been installed, and rear suspension is provided by a pair of Ikon shocks attached to the swingarm.

The seller notes that the front brake disc was resurfaced and drilled under current ownership, and additional front brake work involved installing an Andover Norton 13mm front brake master cylinder and Ferodo brake pads were installed as well as rebuilding the Norton-Lockheed front brake caliper with replacement seals and pistons. A drum brake provides stopping power at the rear.

The chrome-finished handlebar frames a Smiths 150-mph speedometer and a matching tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline. The five-digit odometer shows 46k miles, approximately 600 of which were ridden under current ownership.

The overbored 745cc air-cooled parallel twin was rebuilt under previous ownership, with reported work having included boring the cylinders to accept .060″-oversized pistons and fitting the cylinder head with replacement valves, guides, spark plug and exhaust thread inserts, and seals as well as installing a single Mikuni carburetor, a Boyer Bransden electronic ignition system, and a Colorado Norton Works single-coil conversion, three-phase alternator system, and ARP barrel and head bolt kits. The oil tank was modified by Colorado Norton Works in 2014.

Power is transferred to the rear wheel through a four-speed transmission with a right-side shifter as well as a drive chain. The transmission was rebuilt by Colorado Norton Works in 2015, and the bike has been fitted with a Colorado Norton Works clutch.
The number 221643 stamped on the engine case matches the number stamped on the headstock plate, a photo of which is provided in the gallery.
The Washington title carries an Antique brand.

This 1975 Bricklin SV-1 is said to have remained in Canada with its first owner before being acquired by the seller’s father in 1996. It is finished in red over a tan interior and powered by a 351ci Windsor V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. The car is equipped with air-actuated gullwing doors, pop-up headlights, 15″ Turbo Mag aluminum wheels, power-assisted front disc brakes, a dual exhaust system, air conditioning, and a factory radio. This SV-1 shows 5k miles and is offered by the seller on behalf of their mother with a service manual, a parts catalog, appraisal reports, historical photos, awards, spare parts, and Ontario registration.

The SV-1 features acrylic resin body panels bonded to a fiberglass substrate, which are mounted on a steel frame with an integrated rollover structure. A claimed 2,100 examples were produced for the 1975 model year, and this one was repainted in its current shade of red around 1995. Design cues include pop-up headlights, impact bumpers, and gullwing doors that have been converted to air actuation. Crazing on the hood and areas of touch-up paint are noted by the seller.

Machine-finished 15″ Turbo Mag aluminum wheels are wrapped in BFGoodrich Radial T/A white-letter tires that were mounted in 2022. Power steering was equipped as standard along with power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The bucket seats are covered in two-tone tan vinyl and suede microfiber cloth, and they are accompanied by a color-coordinated dashboard and door panels. Equipment includes a factory radio, a three-spoke President steering wheel, air conditioning, and a rear defroster.

VDO instrumentation includes a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer, while gauges for voltage, coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level are located in the center stack. The five-digit odometer shows 5k miles, approximately 3k of which were added under current ownership.
The Ford-supplied 351ci Windsor V8 was factory rated at 175 horsepower and 286 lb-ft of torque. The seller notes that the alternator was replaced in 2022 and the carburetor was rebuilt in 2023.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Ford FMX three-speed automatic transmission. The exhaust butterfly has been removed.
Historical photos are provided in the gallery below.
The vehicle is being sold on its Ontario registration, which serves as the ownership document in Ontario, Canada. The sale does not include a title.

This 2015 Land Rover Range Rover Autobiography LWB was registered in Texas before it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024 and now has 47k miles. Finished in Aruba Premium Metallic over Pimento and Ebony leather, it is powered by a supercharged 5.0-liter V8 linked with an eight-speed automatic transmission, a two-speed transfer case, and a locking rear differential. Equipment includes heated and ventilated seats, Executive Class rear seating, a rear-seat entertainment system, a Meridian 3D Surround-Sound system, adaptive cruise control, surround-view cameras, and soft-close doors. The truck also has 21″ wheels, a panoramic roof, power running boards, four-zone automatic climate control, and an 8″ touchscreen with navigation. This Range Rover is offered by the selling dealer in Wisconsin with an owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Texas title.

Finished in Aruba Premium Metallic with a color-matched roof, the vehicle has adaptive xenon headlights, rain-sensing windshield wipers, and heated, power-adjustable, and auto-dimming mirrors along with a panoramic roof, a power-operated tailgate, and power running boards. Blemishes on the tailgate are shown in the gallery below.

Ten-spoke 21″ wheels are mounted with 275/45 Yokohama Geolandar tires. Equipment includes an electronic air suspension with variable ride height as well as Terrain Response 2, Adaptive Dynamics stability control, Hill Descent Control (HDC), Electronic Traction Control (ETC), and ventilated disc brakes at each corner.

The four-passenger cabin houses heated, ventilated, and massaging front seats trimmed in Pimento leather complemented by Ebony upholstery on the upper dash. The second row features heated, ventilated, and power-reclining Executive Class seats in addition to an entertainment system with 10.2″ screens. Gloss-black trim accents the interior, and additional appointments include an 8″ touchscreen with navigation as well as a 29-speaker Meridian 3D Surround-Sound system, four-zone automatic climate control, adaptive cruise control, surround-view cameras, soft-close doors, and coolers in the front and rear consoles. Parts of the headliner are loose.
The heated steering wheel features paddle shifters and frames a configurable digital instrument cluster with an 8k-rpm tachometer and a 180-mph speedometer. The digital odometer indicates 47k miles.

The supercharged 5.0-liter V8 was factory rated at 510 horsepower and 461 lb-ft of torque. Power is sent to all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission, a two-speed electronically controlled transfer case, and a locking rear differential.
Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1996 Toyota Land Cruiser has been modified with a Slee Off Road suspension lift kit, front and rear ARB air-locker differentials, 17″ Method Race wheels wrapped in 37″ tires, an ARB front bumper, a winch, a Slee Off Road rear bumper, and aftermarket seating. It was refinished in white and is powered by a 4.5L 1FZ-FE inline-six linked with a rebuilt four-speed automatic transmission and dual-range transfer case along with a locking center differential. The truck was acquired by the selling dealer in 2023, and the engine is said to have been subsequently overhauled. This FZJ80 is offered in California at no reserve with build invoices, an accident-free Carfax report, and a Texas title.

The rig was refinished in white under current ownership and has been modified with an ARB front bumper with a brush guard and driving lights as well as a winch, a snorkel, a roof basket, rock sliders, a rearview camera, and a Slee Off Road rear bumper with a ladder and dual swing-outs carrying jerry cans and a spare tire. The vehicle also features a sunroof, power-adjustable side mirrors, and a rear window wiper.

The 17″ Method Race wheels are mounted with 37×12.5″ Cooper Discoverer STT Pro tires. The suspension has been modified with a Slee Off Road lift kit as well as an Old Man Emu steering stabilizer and dampers. Stopping power is handled by four-wheel discs with ABS, and the brakes were serviced under current ownership. The selling dealer states that a replacement power steering gearbox and axles have been installed and the hubs were rebuilt.

The aftermarket Singer Design-inspired front bucket seats and a rear bench are upholstered in tan fabric, and an ARB fridge/freezer is stored on a slide-out bracket in the rear cargo area. Additional equipment includes air conditioning, a digital clock, all-weather floor mats, and an Alpine head unit linked to Infinity door speakers. Additional work is said to have involved replacing the headliner and carpeting as well as the A-pillar trim and door panel inserts.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 130-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and supplementary gauges. The six-digit odometer shows 306k miles, approximately 350 of which were added under current ownership. The Carfax report lists a mileage inconsistency in November 2023, with a note that it “may just be a clerical error.”

The 4.5L 1FZ-FE inline-six was factory rated at 212 horsepower and 275 lb-ft of torque and was reportedly overhauled under current ownership. An air compressor has been mounted in the engine bay, and the oil and spark plugs were changed in November 2023. Additional service is said to have involved installing a replacement alternator, air conditioning compressor, and intake and exhaust manifolds. Photos taken during the engine work can be seen in the gallery. The truck has not passed a California emissions test.

Power is routed to all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case that were rebuilt in March 2022 by Snider Transmission in La Porte, Texas. The truck has a locking center differential, and the selling dealer notes aftermarket gear sets have been added along with front and rear ARB air-locker differentials. The transfer case and differentials were recently serviced.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned mileage inconsistency.
listing_details: Slee Off Road Suspension Lift Kit

description: This 1985 Stutz Bearcat is one of a claimed seven Series IV examples produced between 1979 and 1987 and is said to have spent 18 years in a museum collection before it was purchased by the selling dealer in 2023. The car is finished in two-tone silver and black and features simulated side exhaust pipes, removable roof panels, a targa bar, and a power-operated rear soft top. Inside, the power-adjustable front seats are trimmed in gray upholstery and accompanied by gold-plated interior trim, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, air conditioning, and an Alpine CD stereo. Power comes from a 5.0L V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission, and further equipment includes power steering, power-assisted front disc brakes, and 15″ chrome wire wheels. This Stutz Bearcat is now offered with a top boot, a jack, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Oregon title.

The Stutz marque was revived in the late 1960s with the Virgil Exner–designed Blackhawk. The later Bearcat convertible model was based on contemporary General Motors A platform running gear and produced from 1979 through 1987. This example was built using the chassis and powertrain from a 1983 Oldsmobile Delta 88 Royale and features hand-built coachwork by Carrozzeria Saturn of Torino, Italy.

The car is finished in silver and black and features bumper-mounted headlights and driving lamps, simulated exhaust pipes that emerge from the front fenders, removable roof panels, a targa bar, and a power-operated rear soft top. A black top boot is included in the sale.

The 15″ chrome wire wheels feature faux knock-off hubs and are mounted with 215/75 Milestar whitewall tires. A spare is stowed under a vinyl cover on the rear decklid. The car is equipped with power steering, while braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The cabin features power-adjustable front bucket seats and a rear bench trimmed in gray upholstery with black piping along with a color-matched dashpad, center console, and door panels. A plaque with the original owner’s name is affixed to the glovebox door, and burl wood trim with gold-plated accents are present on the dash, center console, and doors. Additional equipment includes an Alpine CD stereo, air conditioning, and power windows.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel features gold-plated spokes as well as a Stutz horn button. It frames a horizontal-sweep 85-mph speedometer and a fuel gauge. The five-digit odometer shows 96k miles, less than 100 of which have been added by the selling dealer.
The 5.0-liter V8 is equipped with a four-barrel carburetor. An oil change was performed in 2024.
A plaque engraved with the names of the coachbuilders who built the body is affixed to the radiator fan shroud.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a three-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report lists the car as a 1983 Oldsmobile Delta 88 Royale and notes that it was designated a gross polluter twice by the state of California in 1999.
The car is titled as a 1985 Stutz Delta convertible.

This 2004 Chevrolet Corvette coupe is said to have remained in storage for approximately 10 years before the selling dealer’s recent acquisition, and it now has under 16k miles. The car is powered by a 5.7-liter LS1 V8 paired with a four-speed automatic gearbox and is finished in Torch Red over black and Torch Red leather. Equipment includes two removable roof panels, 17″ and 18″ polished five-spoke wheels, a limited-slip differential, dual-zone automatic climate control, a Bose sound system, and traction control. The selling dealer states that the battery was replaced, the alternator was rebuilt, and the oil was changed in 2024. This C5 coupe is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Missouri title.
The car is finished in Torch Red and features a removable glass roof panel, a removable body-color roof panel, pop-up headlights, fog lights, and quad exhaust outlets.

Polished five-spoke wheels measure 17″ in diameter up front and 18″ out back and are mounted with Goodyear Eagle F1 GS tires measuring 245/45 and 275/40, respectively. The car is equipped with traction control, and braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs.

The cabin features two bucket seats trimmed in black and Torch Red leather. Amenities include dual-zone automatic climate control, a CD stereo, a Bose sound system, cruise control, rubber floor mats, and driver’s seat-position memory settings. The selling dealer notes that the right window is intermittently inoperative.

The steering wheel wears an aftermarket red and black wrap and frames a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates under 16k miles.
The 5.7-liter LS1 V8 was factory rated at 350 horsepower and 360 lb-ft of torque. The selling dealer states that the battery was replaced, the alternator was rebuilt, and the oil was changed in 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic gearbox and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The car has not been registered since 2019.

This 1972 BMW 3.0CSi was completed on October 17, 1972, and delivered new to BMW of Italy in Palazzolo. The car was relocated in 1995 to the Netherlands, where a refurbishment was completed in 2017 by Oldenzaal Classics, and it was imported to the US by its current owner in 2022. Finished in Polaris Silver over blue leather upholstery, it has a stainless-steel exhaust system, four-wheel disc brakes, 14″ Alpina wheels, power windows, a Blaupunkt cassette player, and a Nardi steering wheel. Power comes from a fuel-injected 3.0L inline-six paired with a four-speed manual transmission. Service in June 2023 involved replacing the water pump, cooling fan, and left-front rubber brake hose. This E9 coupe was previously listed on BaT in September 2023, and it is now offered on dealer consignment in Pennsylvania with an owner’s manual, refurbishment records, and a clean Montana title.

The Karmann-built body was repainted in its factory Polaris Silver during the project, and the windshield, rocker covers, fender grilles, headlights, emblems, rubber bumper moldings, and body seals were replaced. Dual mirrors, a rear fog light, and a retractable antenna are additional elements.

Silver 14″ Alpina wheels are mounted with 205/70 Vredestein Sprint Classic tires that show 2016 production date codes. Lowered suspension is noted, and rebuilds of the brake master cylinder and brake calipers are said to have been completed during the refurbishment. A replacement left-front brake hose was installed in June 2023, at which time the brake fluid was flushed.

The front bucket seats and contoured rear bench were reupholstered in blue leather during the refurbishment, which also involved replacing the carpets, while the car’s door cards and headliner were retained. Additional equipment includes power windows, a Blaupunkt cassette player, a heater, a rear window defroster, and wood accents on the dashboard and doors.

A Nardi wood-rimmed steering wheel frames a 240-km/h speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, a combination gauge, and a clock. The five-digit odometer is said to have rolled over once and shows 54k kilometers (~34k miles), approximately 300 of which were added under current ownership.
The 3.0-liter M30B30 inline-six features an aluminum cylinder head and Bosch D-Jetronic fuel injection. Service in June 2023 involved replacing the water pump, cooling fan, and fan clutch.

Power is sent to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transmission. A stainless-steel exhaust system was installed during the refurbishment, and the underside was coated with Dinitrol anti-rust treatment.

This 1998 Lexus GS400 was registered with a single owner in Washington and Arizona from new until 2024, and it now indicates 79k miles. Powered by a 4.0-liter DOHC V8 paired with a five-speed automatic transmission, the car is finished in Black Onyx over Ivory leather. It is equipped with a power sunroof, a decklid spoiler, fog lights, four-wheel double-wishbone suspension, chrome-finished 17″ wheels, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, heated and power-adjustable front seats, and a Nakamichi-Lexus cassette stereo linked to an in-dash CD changer. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this GS400 is offered at no reserve in Florida with a clean Carfax report and a clean Washington title.
The car is finished in Black Onyx (202) with contrasting pinstripes. Exterior details include a decklid spoiler, a power sunroof, fog lights with yellow-tinted bulbs, and dual exhaust outlets.

Chrome-finished 17″ wheels are mounted with Primewell PZ-900 tires. The car rides on a four-wheel double-wishbone suspension with front and rear stabilizer bars, and it is equipped with electronic vehicle skid control, brake assist, speed-sensing progressive steering, and four-wheel anti-lock disc brakes.

The heated and power-adjustable front bucket seats and the rear bench seat are trimmed in Ivory leather. Woodgrain trim accents the center console and door panels, and appointments include dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, Lexus-branded front floor mats, driver-seat position memory settings, and a Lexus-Nakamichi AM/FM/cassette stereo along with a CD changer housed within the glove compartment.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel with E-shift controls frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline, and auxiliary gauges. The digital odometer indicates 79k miles.

The 4.0-liter 1UZ-FE V8 engine features dual overhead camshafts per cylinder bank with VVT-i variable valve timing, and it produced 300 horsepower and 310 lb-ft of torque when new. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed automatic transmission. The selling dealer states that the fluids were serviced in preparation for the sale.
Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery below.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists history in Washington and Arizona.

This 1994 Volkswagen Kombi was refurbished in Brazil before being imported to the US by the selling dealer in March 2023. It is finished in white with orange vinyl wrapping on the lower half over black patterned upholstery and powered by an air-cooled 1.6L flat-four paired with a four-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes 17″ aftermarket wheels, rack-and-pinion power steering, front disc brakes, right-side barn doors, a roof rack, three rows of bench seating, and an aftermarket head unit. This Brazilian-market Type 2 is now offered with a clean Florida title.

The body is finished in white and features an orange vinyl wrap applied to the lower half of the bus. Exterior details include black bumpers and trim, quarter vent windows, right-side barn doors, a roof rack, and a top-hinged rear hatch door.

Aftermarket 17” wheels are mounted with 205/50 Continental ContPremiumContact 2 tires. The bus has been converted to rack-and-pinion power steering, and stopping power is provided by front disc and rear drum brakes.

The front cabin houses a split bench seat trimmed in black vinyl with patterned inserts. Interior elements include an aftermarket shifter, a 12-volt charging outlet, and an aftermarket head unit linked to speakers in the rear cargo area and front kick panel.
Instruentation includes a 140-km/h speedometer with an inset five-digit mechanical odometer that shows 30k kilometers (~19k miles). True mileage is unknown.
The rear cabin features two rows of bench seating trimmed in matching upholstery.
The air-cooled 1.6L (UG) flat-four is equipped with dual Solex carburetors and electronic ignition.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transaxle.

This 2003 Jaguar XJR was registered in Maryland and New York before it was acquired by the current owner in 2019, and it now has 31k miles. Powered by a supercharged 4.0-liter V8 paired with a five-speed automatic transmission, the car is finished in Quartz over Oatmeal leather. Equipment includes a sunroof, fog lights, rear parking sensors, 18″ Asteroid alloy wheels, heated front and rear seats, power-adjustable front seats, wood veneer interior trim, navigation, an Alpine sound system, a CD stereo, and cruise control. This XJR is now offered at no reserve in Florida by the seller on behalf of the owner with manufacturer’s literature, two keys with fobs, a car cover, partial service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New York title in the owner’s name.

The car is finished in Quartz and features a sunroof, quad headlights, fog lights, a power antenna, rear parking sensors, a chrome “leaper” hood ornament, and dual exhaust tips. Indents are noted on the right-rear door.

The 18″ Asteroid alloy wheels are mounted with 255/40 Sumitomo HTR A/S P03 tires that were installed in 2022. The XJR was fitted with a sport-tuned suspension, stability control, and speed-sensitive power steering as standard, and stopping is handled by four-wheel antilock disc brakes. The brake fluid was flushed in March 2023.

The cabin features seating surfaces upholstered in Oatmeal leather, and wood veneers accent the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Amenities include heated power-adjustable front seats, heated rear seating, wood veneer trim, cruise control, automatic climate control, DVD-based navigation, and an Alpine sound system with a trunk-mounted CD changer. There is a crack in the base of the J-gate shifter and shrinking leather is noted on the center armrest cupholder cover.

The wood- and leather-trimmed steering wheel frames a 170-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 31k miles, just over 2k of which were added under current ownership.
The supercharged 4.0-liter AJ V8 was factory rated at 370 horsepower and 387 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed and the fuel pump was replaced in preparation for the sale.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a five-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1955 Chevrolet 210 two-door sedan underwent a refurbishment that was completed in 2002 and is powered by a 402ci V8 linked with a Muncie M22 four-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes a COMP Cams camshaft, Hedman headers, an Edelbrock intake manifold, a Holley carburetor, and a Moser Engineering 12-bolt rear end with 4.11 gears. The body was refinished in maroon and white, and the bench seats were re-trimmed in red and white cloth. The car also has 15″ American Racing wheels, front disc brakes, and traction bars in addition to a Hurst shifter and a retro-style stereo linked to a trunk-mounted CD changer. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2018, this 210 is now offered with a Massachusetts title.
The car was refinished in maroon and white during the refurbishment and features a hood ornament, electric windshield wipers, dual side mirrors, and chrome bumpers and trim.

American Racing 15″ wheels are mounted with 225/60 front and 245/60 rear BFGoodrich Radial T/A tires. The car has front disc brakes, rack-and-pinion steering, Lakewood traction bars, and rear air shocks.

The cabin houses a split-back front bench and rear bench upholstered in red and white cloth. Interior appointments include a Hust shifter, a locking glovebox, and lap belts. A retro-style head unit is linked to a CD changer housed in the trunk.

The Grant steering wheel is fitted, and an AutoMeter 8k-rpm tachometer is secured to the Ididit steering column. Aftermarket instrumentation includes a 110-mph speedometer with readouts for temperature and fuel level, and a trio of gauges is mounted under the dashboard. The five-digit odometer shows 10k miles. Total mileage is unknown.

The seller notes that the 396ci was sourced from a 1966 Chevrolet Impala SS and bored .030″ over before it was installed as part of the refurbishment. Equipment includes a COMP Cams camshaft, Hedman headers, an Edelbrock intake manifold, a Holley carburetor, MSD ignition, and a Be Cool radiator. A Pete Jackson gear drive and electric fuel pump were equipped in 2009. An aluminum fuel tank is located below the trunk floor.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Muncie M22 four-speed manual transmission and a Moser Engineering 12-bolt rear end with 4.11 gears. A Flowmaster exhaust is fitted.
The Massachusetts title carries an odometer discrepancy brand.

This Backdraft Racing roadster was acquired new by the current owner in 2002 and is powered by a 302ci V8 paired with a Tremec T5 five-speed manual transmission. The fiberglass body is finished in silver with black center stripes and features quick-jack bumperettes, a single roll hoop, and dual side-exit exhaust outlets, while the interior is trimmed in black vinyl upholstery and incorporates Stewart-Warner instrumentation, tinted sunvisors, racing harnesses, and a battery cut-off switch. Additional details include 15″ Halibrand-style wheels, independent suspension, an Edelbrock carburetor and intake manifold, and MSD ignition components. This Cobra replica is now offered on dealer consignment with a transferrable New York registration describing it as a 1965 Ford.

The fiberglass body is mounted to a reinforced steel box frame and is finished in silver with black center stripes. Exterior details include quick-jack bumperettes, a hood scoop, fender vents, a bullet-style side mirror, wind wings, a single roll hoop, a Le Mans-style fuel filler, and dual side-exit exhaust outlets with perforated heat shields.

Halibrand-style 15″ wheels wear faux knock-off spinners and are mounted with 235/60 front and 295/50 rear Goodyear Eagle GTII white letter tires. The car is equipped with rack-and-pinion steering, adjustable coilovers, and four-wheel independent suspension sourced from an E36 BMW. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes.

The fixed-back bucket seats are trimmed in black vinyl upholstery and are joined by a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpeting. Interior elements include a dashboard-mounted rearview mirror, tinted sunvisors, racing harnesses, and a battery cut-off switch.

Stewart-Warner instrumentation includes a reverse-sweep 180-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and supplementary readouts for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, battery voltage, and fuel level. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 14k miles, all of which were added during current ownership.

The 302ci V8 is equipped with an Edelbrock Performer intake manifold, an Edelbrock carburetor, MSD ignition components, and a Cobra-branded air filter cover and valve covers. An oil change was performed in 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Tremec T5 five-speed manual transmission.

An identification tag affixed to the firewall identifies this car as a Backdraft Roadster that was assembled by TR-Tec in South Africa with a VIN of AA9BMAAHVX1CN1661. The car is registered as a 1965 Ford Convertible by VIN ICN1661 in New York. The car does not have a title, as it is registered in a state that does not issue titles for a vehicle of its age. It is being sold on its registration.

This 2010 Honda Ridgeline RTL remained registered with its initial owner in California until May 2024, and it now has 28k miles. It is finished in Taffeta White over gray leather and is powered by a 3.5-liter V6 mated to a five-speed automatic transaxle and a VTM-4 four-wheel-drive system. The truck is equipped with 18″ alloy wheels, a sunroof, a rearview camera, a receiver hitch, heated front seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, navigation, and a six-disc CD changer. Service in preparation for the sale included changing the oil and replacing the battery and brake pads. Acquired by the selling dealer in May 2024, this Ridgeline is now offered at no reserve with manufacturer’s literature and a clean California title.

The Ridgeline features unibody construction and an integrated cargo bed with in-bed storage. This example is finished in Taffeta White and has a power-operated sunroof, a dual-action tailgate, a power-sliding rear window, a receiver hitch, fog lights, heated power side mirrors, and a rearview camera. The Carfax report lists damage to the rear in November 2017. Paint oxidization is noted on various panels, and close-up photos of the paintwork, trim, and body panel VIN stickers are presented in the gallery.
The 18″ alloy wheels are wrapped in 245/60 Michelin Primacy Tour A/S tires. Service in June 2024 included flushing the brake fluid, resurfacing the rotors, and replacing the pads.

The heated front seats and a fold-away rear bench are upholstered in gray leather. Amenities include a 10-way power-adjustable driver’s seat, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, navigation, and a six-disc CD changer.

A leather-wrapped multi-function steering wheel frames a 140-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 28k miles, approximately 300 of which were added under current ownership.

The 3.5-liter V6 features VTEC variable valve timing, and it was factory rated at 250 horsepower and 247 lb-ft of torque. Service in June 2024 included changing the oil and replacing the battery and air filter.
Power is delivered to all four wheels via a five-speed automatic transaxle and a VTM-4 four-wheel-drive system. Additional underside photos are viewable in the gallery.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage entry.

This 1985 Porsche 928S was initially delivered through Rusnak Porsche in Pasadena, California, and was acquired by the current owner in 1987. The car is powered by a 5.0-liter V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transaxle and is finished in Guards Red (80K) over black leather. Equipment includes four-wheel disc brakes, 16″ polished alloy wheels, pop-up headlights, a sunroof, a rear spoiler, power-adjustable front seats, air conditioning, and power windows. Work in 2023 included servicing the engine and transaxle, rebuilding the torque tube and steering rack, and overhauling the air conditioning system. This 928S is offered by the seller on behalf of their spouse with service records, an accident-free Carfax report, and a British Columbia registration.

The car is finished in Guards Red (80K) and features pop-up headlights with washers as well as fog lights, power-adjustable side mirrors, body-color side skirts, a steel sunroof, a rear window wiper, and a rear spoiler. Stitched repairs to the cracked front chin spoiler are depicted in the gallery.
Polished 16″ seven-hole alloy wheels are mounted with 225/50 Bridgestone Potenza tires. Braking is handled by power-assisted discs at each corner. The power steering rack was rebuilt in 2023.

The power-adjustable front bucket and folding individual rear seats are trimmed in black leather. Appointments include air conditioning, cruise control, and power windows. The hatch release mechanism was recently serviced and the Blaupunkt cassette stereo does not work.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 170-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as supplementary gauges for coolant temperature, fuel level, oil pressure, and voltage. The six-digit odometer shows 40k miles, approximately 25k of which were added under current ownership. The Carfax report notes a mileage inconsistency in March 1992, which is thought to be a clerical error related to a mile/kilometer conversion when the car moved to Canada. The combination gauge for voltage and oil pressure was replaced in 2023.

The 5.0-liter V8 was factory rated at 288 horsepower and 302 lb-ft of torque. Work in July 2023 included powdercoating the engine parts, replating the engine hardware, resurfacing the cylinder heads, overhauling the air conditioning system, and installing the following replacement components:
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a rear-mounted four-speed automatic transaxle. The torque tube was rebuilt and the torque converter bearings were replaced in 2023.
In-process photos of the 2023 engine-out service are presented in the gallery.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage, notes the aforementioned mileage inconsistency, and lists history in California and British Columbia Canada from the initial entry in March 1992.
The car does not have a title as it is registered in a province that does not issue titles for vehicles. It is being sold on its transferrable British Columbia registration.

This 1941 Graham Hollywood Model 109 is a non-running project that was disassembled by its previous owner of 64 years before it was purchased by the selling dealer in 2024. Body panels wear gray primer, and the car retains a General Motors-sourced inline-six and a three-speed manual transmission. A collection of spare parts is included in the sale and features grille and external trim pieces, headlights, gauges, seats, and a radiator. This Graham Hollywood project is now offered at no reserve in Ulster Park, New York, with a clean Indiana title.

The Hollywood featured front-end styling by John Tjaarda, while bodywork from the cowl aft was produced using body dies from the Cord 810/812, which Graham-Paige had acquired from the Hupp Motor Car Corporation in early 1940. Production for Hollywood models and the similar Hupmobile Skylark was limited to five months before Graham retooled in September 1940 to focus on defense contracts. This example was reportedly sandblasted before being finished in primer under previous ownership. Areas of rust are presented in the gallery below.
Steel wheels are finished in gray, and they wear older whitewall tires.
The cabin is stripped, and areas of the floorboards have been cut out. Corrosion on the cabin and trunk floors can be seen in the gallery.
The banjo-style steering wheel is mounted ahead of the steel dash, which is absent its instruments. A Camaro-branded wood shift knob tops the floor shifter.
The factory 217.8ci L-head inline-six with water-cooled centrifugal supercharger was replaced with a General Motors-sourced inline-six under previous ownership.
A three-speed manual transmission is retained.
Spare parts including exterior brightwork, headlights, gauges, seats, and mechanical components are included in the sale and are further detailed in the gallery.

This 2007 Mercedes-Benz CL600 is finished in Obsidian Black Metallic over Cognac Brown and Black Exclusive Nappa leather and is powered by a twin-turbocharged 5.5-liter V12 paired with a replacement.five-speed automatic transmission. Features include 20″ AMG five-spoke wheels, a power sunroof, bi-xenon headlights, Distronic adaptive cruise control, Parktronic, Night View Assist, Keyless Go, heated and ventilated dynamic multi-contour front seats, burl walnut wood trim, a rearview camera, a Harman Kardon LOGIC7 sound system, dual-zone automatic climate control, and COMAND infotainment with navigation. The car remained registered in California prior to the selling dealer’s acquisition, and it has 110k miles. This C216 is now offered in New York at no reserve with a VMI report and a clean California title.

The car is finished in Obsidian Black Metallic (197) and features a pillarless roof design with fully retracting side windows. Additional exterior equipment includes bi-xenon headlights with Active Curve Illumination as well as fog lights, a glass power sunroof, rain-sensing windshield wipers, and heated side mirrors. The Carfax report notes damage in April 2017 and September 2019 entries, which resulted in the bumper covers being refinished, per the selling dealer. An AMG badge has been added to the trunk lid.

The 20″ AMG five-spoke wheels are mounted with Laufenn S Fit, Fullway HP-108, and Pirelli P Zero tires. One of the wheels was reportedly replaced in preparation for the sale. Stopping power is provided by disc brakes with ventilated rotors at each corner. The car is equipped with an Electronic Stability Program and an Active Body Control suspension.
