Graphite Diamond Turned 19" Multi-Spoke Alloy Wheels
Clean US and Canadian Carfax Reports

description: This 1973 AMC Javelin is a running-and-driving project that was purchased by the previous owner in 1980 and was acquired by the owning dealer in July 2024. The car has been refinished in black with purple accents over multi-color upholstery, and power is supplied by a 360ci V8 mated to a three-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes Pierre Cardin badging, Cragar wheels, whitewall tires, power steering, front disc brakes, headers, and side-exit exhaust pipes. The brakes were overhauled in preparation for the sale, and the car has not been regularly driven since 2022. This Javelin project is now offered by the seller on behalf of the owning dealer with 1980-dated registration paperwork and a clean Massachusetts title.

The car has been repainted in black with purple accents over each wheel. Additional exterior elements include aftermarket headlamps, “426 Hemi” grille badging, a driver-side mirror, side-exhaust pipes, bright trim, and chrome bumpers with rubber overriders. Pierre Cardin badging is affixed to both front fenders. The seller states that the driver door has been replaced. Checked paint, rust-through, and other imperfections are pictured in the gallery below, and evidence of unpainted body work is visible on the passenger side of the vehicle.

Bright-finished Cragar 15″ wheels are mounted with American Classic whitewall tires; the wheels exhibit corrosion. The seller states that the master cylinder was replaced in 2023 and that the rear wheel cylinders and brake shoes were replaced in July 2024 and the front brake calipers were rebuilt.

The cabin is equipped with front bucket seats and a rear bench trimmed in black upholstery with purple, orange, white, and gray stripes, a theme that carries over to the door panels and the headliner. Appointments include Pierre Cardin logos, a center console, a horseshoe-style shift lever, a push-button radio, a heater, woodgrain accents, and bright doorsill trim. A stain on the passenger seat is shown in the gallery, and rust is evident in the trunk compartment.
A three-spoke steering wheel fronts a 120-mph speedometer and auxiliary gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 51k miles, less than 10 of which were added by the seller; true mileage is unknown.

The 360ci V8 was rated by the factory to produce 175 horsepower with the aid of a two-barrel carburetor. The engine has been fitted with Edelbrock chrome valve covers, a chrome air cleaner, and exhaust headers. The oil was changed most recently in 2023.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission. Corrosion is noted on underbody components, and a portion of the driver-side exhaust piping is absent.

A chassis-number plate pictured in the gallery corresponds with a 1973 Javelin hardtop coupe equipped with a 360ci V8, a two-barrel carburetor, and a floor-shifted three-speed automatic transmission. The information plate shown above—attached to the replacement driver-side door—reveals the following production details:

This 1970 Chevrolet Nova SS is a black-over-black coupe that was initially delivered to John Logan Chevrolet of Brampton, Ontario. A cosmetic and mechanical refurbishment was commissioned by the reported second owner circa 2012, and it was recently acquired by the selling dealer. The car is powered by a replacement 396ci L78 V8 linked with a Muncie four-speed manual transmission and a PosiTraction limited-slip differential, and it rides on 14″ steel wheels with chrome hubcaps. Equipment includes power-assisted front disc brakes, a Hurst shifter, a four-barrel carburetor, a dual-snorkel air cleaner, and a cabin heater. This Nova SS coupe is offered by the selling dealer with a reproduction window sticker, an NCRS Shipping Data Report, GM of Canada correspondence, and a clean Pennsylvania title.
The car was finished from the factory in Tuxedo Black (19), and the SS package added a revised hood and grille, a black taillight panel, and a dual exhaust system.
Black 14″ steel wheels wear chrome hubcaps and are mounted with reproduction Firestone Wide Oval white-letter tires. Braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.
The cabin houses bench seating that was reupholstered in black vinyl during the refurbishment. Amenities include a Hurst shifter, front vent windows, and a heater. The radio does not work.
The SS-branded steering wheel fronts a horizontal-sweep 120-mph speedometer and a fuel-level gauge. The five-digit odometer shows 55k miles. Total mileage is unknown.
The replacement 396ci V8 is said to have been installed in 1971 and is equipped with a dual-snorkel air cleaner and a four-barrel carburetor.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a Muncie M21 close-ratio four-speed manual transmission and a PosiTraction limited-slip differential with 4.10:1 gears.

The reproduction window sticker lists initial delivery to John Logan Chevrolet of Brampton, Ontario, Canada, along with factory equipment, and a total suggested retail price of $4,073. An NCRS Shipping Data Report and a GM of Canada build sheet are also included in the sale.

This 1994 BMW R100GS is finished in black with a yellow brush guard and powered by an air-cooled 980cc opposed twin mated to a five-speed transmission and an enclosed driveshaft. A Parabellum clear windscreen has been added, and the bike is further equipped with a black and yellow vinyl two-up seat, hand guards, BMW hard-sided panniers, and wire-spoke wheels with Akront rims as well as a Paralever single-sided swingarm, a front disc brake, a pair of Bing carburetors, and a two-into-one exhaust system. Acquired by the seller in 2023, this R100GS is now offered at no reserve with a rider’s manual, a tool roll, spare parts, two additional two-up seats, the removed clear windscreen, and a clean South Carolina title in the seller’s name.

The 5.8-gallon fuel tank, front fairing, and fenders are finished in black, while the front brush guard is finished in yellow. The bike is equipped with a Parabellum clear windscreen, a black and yellow vinyl two-up seat, removable hard-sided BMW panniers, a rear grab bar, a rear cargo rack, folding passenger foot pegs, and both center and side stands.

Wire-spoke wheels with Akront rims measuring 21″ up front and 17″ out back are mounted with Metzeler tires that have production-date codes from 2018 and 2019. Suspension consists of a telescopic fork with yellow-finished lowers and black accordion gaiters as well as a monoshock fitted to the Paralever single-sided swingarm. Braking is handled by a single Brembo caliper mounted over a cross-drilled disc up front and a drum out back. The brake fluid was flushed in April 2023.

The cross-braced handlebar is equipped with black hand guards and a pair of round mirrors, and it sits aft of MotoMeter instrumentation that consists of a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline as well as a 120-mph speedometer, and a central array of indicator lights. The five-digit odometer shows 19k miles, approximately 1k of which were ridden by the seller.

The air-cooled 980cc OHV opposed twin features dual Bing carburetors, a two-into-one high-mount exhaust system, two valves per cylinder, an oil cooler, and an electric starter. Factory-rated output was 60 horsepower and 55 lb-ft of torque. Work in April 2023 involved changing the oil, adjusting the timing, valves, and carburetor floats, and replacing the carburetor bowl gaskets and fuel filters. The seller notes an oil leak from the push rod seals.
Power is routed to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and an enclosed driveshaft, both of which received a fluid change in April 2023.
Two spare two-up seats and the removed clear windscreen are included in the sale along with a rider’s manual, a tool roll, a poster, and spare parts.

This 1969 Chevrolet Corvette coupe is powered by a 350ci V8 linked with a four-speed manual transmission, and it was refinished in red before the selling dealer’s recent acquisition. Equipment includes removable roof panels, a domed hood, simulated side-exit exhaust pipes, and flip-up headlights as well as 15″ Rally wheels, four-wheel disc brakes, power steering, and chrome bumpers. The cabin is trimmed in black vinyl upholstery and outfitted with a Hurst shifter, a cassette stereo, Astro Ventilation, and a center console. Additional equipment includes long-tube headers, Flowmaster-style mufflers, and a chrome air cleaner. This C3 coupe is offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with a clean New Jersey title.

The car left the factory finished in Fathom Green and was repainted in the current shade of red under prior ownership. Details include a domed hood, flip-up headlights, fender vents, simulated side-exit exhaust pipes, removable roof panels, and dual exhaust outlets. Close-up photos of the paint, trim, and imperfections are provided in the gallery.

The 15″ Rally wheels wear chrome trim rings and center caps and are mounted with BFGoodrich Radial T/A white-letter tires. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is handled by power-assisted four-wheel discs. The brake pads were replaced in June 2024, according to the selling dealer.

The bucket seats are upholstered in black vinyl and joined by color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Amenities include headrests, a heater, a cassette stereo, a Hurst shifter, Astro Ventilation, aftermarket speakers, and lap belts. The door weather seals are worn and cracked, the passenger seat upholstery is ripped, and close-up photos of the condition of the cabin are provided in the gallery.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 5,350-rpm redline, while auxiliary gauges for fuel level, battery charge, oil pressure, and coolant temperature are mounted in the center stack. The five-digit odometer shows 40k miles.

The 350ci V8 was factory equipped with a four-barrel Rochester carburetor and was rated at 300 horsepower when new. Fluid services are said to have been performed in June 2024. Long-tube headers feed a dual exhaust system with an X-pipe and Flowmaster-style mufflers, and the exhaust system has been painted.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission.
Decoding the trim tag reveals the following details:

This 2000 Land Rover Discovery II SE was purchased new by the current owner and now has 137k miles. It underwent a cosmetic refurbishment in 2023 that included repainting the truck red and replacing the bumpers, badges, and trim. Powered by a 4.0-liter V8 linked with a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case, the truck is also equipped with 18″ alloy wheels, a 1.5″ suspension lift, Active Cornering Enhancement (ACE), a receiver hitch, Bahama Beige leather upholstery, dual sunroofs, heated power-adjustable front seats, and automatic climate control. This Discovery II is offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, and a clean North Carolina title in the owner’s name.

The truck left the factory finished in Rutland Red and it was repainted in 2023, at which time the cowl panel, A- and C-pillar trim, bumpers, and badges are said to have been replaced. Equipment includes a rear-mounted spare tire, a receiver hitch, a steel rear bumper, and dual sunroofs. An accident with “very minor damage” is shown on the Carfax report in February 2016, which the seller states left a dent below the left taillight. A crack is noted on the front bumper cover.

The 18″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A KO2 tires. The truck is equipped with a 1.5″ suspension lift and Active Cornering Enhancement (ACE) hydraulic anti-roll system. Stopping power is handled by four-wheel disc brakes.

The heated power-adjustable front bucket seats and the rear bench are trimmed in Bahama Beige leather with black piping. Amenities include automatic climate control, a CD/cassette stereo, and power windows. Wear is noted on the door panels and seats.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 135-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 137k miles, all of which were added under current ownership. A crack is noted on the gauge bezel.
The 4.0-liter V8 was factory rated at 188 horsepower and 251 lb-ft of torque.
Power is routed to all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case.
The window sticker lists factory colors, equipment, and options as well as a total price of $41,125.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned accident.

This Chevrolet Corvette coupe was converted for racing use over 25 years ago and acquired by the current owner in Oregon in 2016. The car is finished in red with NART-style livery over a race-prepped interior and is powered by a modified 427ci V8 paired with an M22 four-speed manual transmission and a 3.55:1 rear differential. Equipment includes Torq Thrust–style 15″ wheels, four-wheel disc brakes, a side-exit exhaust system, a front spoiler, removable roof panels, adjustable front coilovers, a fuel cell, an MSD ignition system, and a roll cage as well as a fire-suppression system, a Hurst shifter, and a Kirkey Racing seat with a four-point harness. A mechanical overhaul was carried out in 2017, and an inspection and a compression test were performed in preparation for the sale. This C3 race car was sold on BaT in October 2023 and subsequently relisted in November 2023, and is now offered again on dealer consignment in Oregon with racing logbooks, recent service records, spare parts, and a bill of sale.

The body was modified under previous ownership over 25 years ago in the style of the 1968 L88 RED/NART car that competed in the 1973 24 Hours of Le Mans. Equipment includes custom fixed headlight covers and grilles, removable roof panels, a custom side mirror, a side-exit exhaust system, a lower front spoiler, and front and rear tow loops.

White-finished Torq Thrust-style 15″ alloy wheels feature polished lips and wear staggered-width Hoosier T.D. R racing tires. The aftermarket steering rack was rebuilt in 2018, and the rear leaf spring and U-joints were replaced. The front suspension features aftermarket control arms and adjustable coilovers, and braking is handled by four-wheel discs with SSBC Force 10 front calipers and custom air ducting.

The removable hardtop conceals a full roll cage, and the driver is provided with a Kirkey high-back aluminum racing seat along with a Hurst shifter and a three-spoke steering wheel with a quick-release hub. Additional equipment includes a fire-suppression system, an electrical system master cut-off switch, an oversized mirror, and custom door panels.

The custom dashboard houses an AutoMeter Phantom 10k-rpm tachometer and additional AutoMeter auxiliary gauges for fuel and oil pressure along with water temperature. Neither a speedometer nor odometer are installed, and the total chassis mileage is unknown.

The 427ci V8 was rebuilt before being installed in 2018 and is equipped with a Dart Machinery block, 6.00″ lightweight connecting rods, a lightweight crankshaft, a custom oil pan, and a mechanical oil pump as well as Canfield cylinder heads, an Edelbrock intake manifold, a Holley carburetor, an MSD ignition system, an aluminum radiator with an electric fan, a fuel cell, and a custom exhaust system with Hooker headers. Compression test photos are provided in the gallery below.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a Muncie M22 four-speed manual transmission and a 3.55:1 rear differential that was rebuilt in June 2018. The clutch was replaced in August 2018.
Vehicle log books are included in the sale along with literature and records.
The race car is not legal for road use, has not been registered for the street, and carries no title or registration. It is being sold on a bill of sale.

This 2012 Volkswagen Eos was initially sold in California, moved to Washington D.C. in 2021, and was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. It is finished in Reflex Silver Metallic over Titan Black vinyl and is powered by a turbocharged 2.0-liter inline four linked with a six-speed DSG automatic transaxle and an electronically locking differential. Equipment includes a power-retractable hardtop with an integrated panoramic sunroof as well as four-wheel disc brakes, 17″ alloy wheels, heated front seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, and a CD stereo. Work in preparation for the sale consisted of changing the oil and replacing the left front window regulator. This Eos has 77k miles and is offered at no reserve by the selling dealer in Florida with a clean Carfax report and a clean District of Columbia title.

The car is finished in Reflex Silver Metallic and features a power-retractable hardtop with an integrated power sunroof. Exterior details include fog lights, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, and twin exhaust outlets. Paint meter readings from around the car are presented in the gallery.
Silver-finished 17″ alloy wheels are mounted with 235/45 Hankook Ventus V2 tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs with ABS. Scuffs are visible on the wheels.

The heated front seats and contoured rear bench are upholstered in Titan Black vinyl. Appointments include a power-adjustable driver seat, dual-zone automatic climate control, a removable wind deflector, and a CD stereo with an in-dash six-disc changer. The left front window regulator was replaced under current ownership and all-weather floor mats are included in the sale.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel frames a central digital display flanked by a 180-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and supplementary gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The odometer indicates 77k miles miles.
The turbocharged 2.0-liter inline-four was factory rated at 200 horsepower and 207 lb-ft of torque and features direct fuel injection. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the front wheels through a six-speed DSG automatic transaxle and an electronically locking differential.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists history in California, Washington D.C., and Maryland.

This 1974 BMW R90/6 was acquired from its original owner in 1976 by the seller, who has ridden it approximately 90k miles, and it has been modified with a Keihan stainless-steel exhaust system, a Dyna electronic ignition module, a stainless-steel front brake hose, first-oversize pistons, and an LED headlight. It is finished in black with white pinstripes and is powered by an 898cc opposed twin paired with a five-speed transmission. Additional equipment includes an enclosed driveshaft, an electric starter, a rear cargo rack, an engine guard, dual Bing carburetors, 19″ front and 18″ rear wire-spoke wheels, a front disc brake, panniers, dual mirrors, an analog clock, and a black vinyl-upholstered two-up seat. This R90/6 is now offered with an owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, a tool kit, and a clean Texas title in the seller’s name.

The bike was refinished in black during the 2015 refurbishment, and an LED headlight was fitted and the headlight harness replaced in April 2024. Equipment includes a left-side lift-assist handle, both center and side stands, panniers, dual mirrors, an analog clock, and a black vinyl-upholstered two-up seat. The seller notes a tear in the seat cover and a scratch on the engine guard.

Wire-spoke wheels measure 19″ front and 18″ rear and are mounted with 3.25″ and 4.00 Continental tires, respectively. and stopping power is provided by a single front disc and a rear drum. Suspension consists of a leading-axle fork as well as dual Progressive Suspension shocks mounted to the swingarm on the left and the final-drive enclosure on the right. The fork seals were replaced and the front brake caliper rebuilt in February 2018, while a stainless-steel front brake hose and a replacement master cylinder were fitted in April 2024.

The handlebar is mounted to the upper triple clamp via risers that frame an adjustment knob for the hydraulic steering damper. The dash panel houses a replacement MotoMeter 140-mph speedometer and a matching tachometer with a 7,100-rpm redline as well as indicator lights for brake failure, neutral gear selection, generator, oil pressure, and turn signals. The five-digit odometer shows 12k miles, though the seller has ridden over 90k miles. Total mileage is unknown.

The 898cc opposed twin has been fitted with first-oversize pistons, a Keihan stainless-steel dual exhaust system with a crossover tube, and a Dyna electronic ignition system. The battery and air filter were replaced in April 2024 and the oil was changed at that time.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and a driveshaft enclosed within the right leg of the swingarm. An easy-pull clutch device has been fitted.
The number 4931968 stamped on the engine case matches with the numbers stamped on the frame and steering headstock tag, photos of which can be viewed in the gallery.
A tool kit, an owner’s manual, a security cable, a repair manual, and records, are included in the sale.

This 2012 Land Rover Range Rover Supercharged is powered by a supercharged 5.0-liter AJ133 V8 that drives all four wheels through a six-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and locking center and rear differentials. Finished in Santorini Black over Ivory leather and optioned with the Silver package, the truck is equipped with 20″ Style 11 alloy wheels, adjustable air suspension, the Terrain Response system, Hill Descent Control, adaptive Xenon headlights, a 360-degree camera system, and a sunroof. Inside, the power-adjustable, heated, and ventilated front seats are accompanied by power-adjustable rear seats, Harman Kardon audio, navigation, a rear-seat entertainment system, and quad-zone automatic climate control. Work in 2024 consisted of flushing the brake fluid and replacing the front struts, brake rotors, and brake pads. Acquired by the selling dealer in June 2024, this Range Rover Supercharged has 73k miles and is now offered in California with owner’s manuals, floor mats, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Arizona title.

The truck is finished in Santorini Black and was optioned with the Silver package’s adaptive xenon headlights and 360-degree camera system. Additional exterior details include fog lights, headlight washers, a sunroof, tinted rear windows, a rear window wiper, and parking sensors.

Silver-finished 20″ Style 11 alloy wheels are mounted with 255/50 Hankook Dynapro HP2 tires that have 2018 production-date codes. The truck is equipped with adjustable air suspension, a Terrain Response system, and Hill Descent Control. Braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs with ABS. February 2024 service consisted of flushing the brake fluid and replacing the front brake pads and rotors, and the selling dealer reports replacing the front air-suspension struts in preparation for the sale.

The front seats are upholstered in Ivory leather with contrasting piping, and they feature heating, ventilation, power adjustment, and position memory. The door panels and power-adjustable rear bench are trimmed to match, and additional appointments include Grand Black Lacquer trim, keyless entry, push-button ignition, an analog clock, navigation, a 19-speaker Harman Kardon sound system, and four-zone automatic climate control as well as a rear-seat entertainment system.

The leather- and wood-trimmed multifunction steering wheel frames a 12.3″ digital instrument cluster that displays an 8k-rpm tachometer, a 155-mph speedometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level, while the Silver package added blind-spot monitoring. The digital odometer indicates 73k miles, approximately 20 of which were added under current ownership.
The supercharged 5.0-liter AJ133 V8 was factory rated at 510 horsepower and 461 lb-ft of torque. The oil was most recently changed in May 2023.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a six-speed ZF automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case as well as locking center and rear differentials.
The Carfax report is free of accident or damage entries.

This 1978 Mercedes-Benz 300D is said to have remained registered with its second owner in New Jersey from 2003 until the selling dealer’s acquisition in 2024, and it now shows 37k miles. Finished in Medium Red over Bamboo MB-Tex upholstery, the car is powered by a 3.0-liter diesel inline-five paired with a four-speed automatic transmission. Further equipment includes 14″ wheels with color-matching covers as well as a sunroof, cruise control, air conditioning, and a Becker Europa II AM/FM radio. The selling dealer acquired the car in 2024, and work in preparation for the sale is said to have included a valve adjustment, fluid and filter changes, and replacing the valve cover gasket, auxiliary water pump, drive belts, tires, and air conditioning compressor, receiver drier, and servo. This W123 300D is now offered at no reserve with a window sticker, manufacturer’s literature, a service booklet, and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Medium Red and features an optional power-operated sunroof, fog lights, dual side mirrors, a power antenna, and bright trim. The selling dealer reports that paintwork was performed on the right quarter panel and trunk lid under previous ownership. Additional photos of the paint meter readings are viewable in the gallery below.

The 14″ wheels feature color-matching covers and are mounted with 195/70  Hankook Kinergy ST tires that were installed following the selling dealer’s acquisition. Stopping power is provided by disc brakes at each corner. The brake fluid was flushed in preparation for the sale.

The front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in Bamboo MB-Tex, and Zebrano veneer trim accents the dashboard and center console. Interior amenities include power windows, cruise control, air conditioning, and a Becker Europa II AM/FM radio. A set of sisal floor mats is included in the sale.

Instrumentation consists of a 115-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 37k miles, approximately 150 of which were added under current ownership.

The 3.0-liter OM617 diesel inline-five was factory rated at 77 horsepower and 115 lb-ft of torque. The oil and coolant were changed in preparation for the sale, and the selling dealer states that a valve adjustment was performed and the valve cover gasket, auxiliary water pump, drive belts, fuel filters, and air conditioning compressor, receiver drier, and servo were replaced at that time.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a four-speed automatic transmission. The engine and transmission mounts have been replaced, according to the selling dealer.

The window sticker lists initial delivery to Autohafen Inc. of Chicago Heights, Illinois along with factory colors, equipment, and a total suggested retail price of $18,523. Manufacturer’s literature and a service booklet are included in the sale.

This 1970 Ford Bronco Sport was initially delivered to Lee Motor Company, Inc. of Wilson, North Carolina, and is powered by a 170ci inline-six driving the rear or all four wheels through a three-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case. It is finished in Chrome Yellow with a white removable hardtop over Parchment Rosette vinyl. Equipment includes 15″ steel wheels, manually locking front hubs, drum brakes, a Jet Star air conditioning unit, an AM radio, and front lap belts. This Bronco is now offered by the selling dealer with an Elite Marti report and a clean North Carolina title.

The truck is one of 220 examples for the model year that left the factory finished in Chrome Yellow (G). Exterior details include a white removable hardtop and a polished grille, bumpers, and trim in addition to

Steel 15” wheels wear chrome hubcaps and are mounted with 235/75 Goodyear Wrangler Radial tires. A full-size spare is mounted in the rear cargo area. The truck is equipped with manually locking front hubs as well as unassisted drum brakes and steering.

The front bucket seats and rear bench are trimmed in Parchment Rosette vinyl and are joined by a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and sunvisors. Interior elements include a Jet Star air conditioning unit, an AM radio, and front lap belts.

Instrumentation includes a 100-mph speedometer encircled by auxiliary gauges for voltage, fuel level, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 84k miles, and true mileage is unknown.
The 170ci inline-six was factory rated at 105 horsepower and 156 lb-ft of torque.
rear or all four wheels through a three-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case.
The Elite Marti report lists factory equipment and production information as well as a build date of May 25, 1970.

This 1948 Chevrolet Fleetmaster station wagon was acquired by the current owner on BaT in May 2023 and was subsequently refurbished in a project that involved replacing rusted sheet metal, refinishing the bodywork in burgundy, refreshing the wood components, reupholstering the interior, and replacing the clutch. Equipment includes three rows of bench seating, a heater, a black vinyl roof covering, body-color 16″ wheels, hubcaps, whitewall tires, and a rear-mounted spare. Power is supplied by a 216.5ci inline-six paired with a column-shifted three-speed manual transmission. This Fleetmaster woodie wagon is now offered in Florida by the seller on behalf of the owner with refurbishment photos and a Montana title under the owner’s LLC.

The steel body panels underwent rust repairs and other bodywork before being refinished in burgundy under current ownership, and the wood components were refurbished. Exterior details include a black vinyl roof covering, a split windshield, bumper overriders, a two-piece rear bumper, and a single taillight.
Burgundy-painted 16″ steel wheels with trim rings and Chevrolet-stamped hubcaps are mounted with whitewall tires. A matching spare is attached to the drop-down tailgate.

The three rows of bench seating have been retrimmed in tan upholstery, and the tan carpeting was replaced during the refurbishment. Appointments include a wooden roof, door panels, and pillars as well as an ashtray in the center of the dash and a Super Deluxe heater/defroster.

A two-spoke steering wheel with a horn ring sits ahead of a 100-mph speedometer alongside rectangular auxiliary gauges. A clock is located on the opposite side of the dash. The five-digit odometer shows 24k miles, less than 10 of which have been added under current ownership; true mileage is unknown.
The 216.5ci inline-six is fed by a replacement carburetor with a black air-cleaner assembly. The engine gaskets were reportedly replaced during the aforementioned refurbishment.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a column-shifted three-speed manual transmission. The clutch was replaced during the refurbishment.
Decoding the Fisher data plate reveals the following information:
Additional refurbishment photos are provided in the gallery below.
The Montana title lists a “not actual” odometer brand for mileage.

This 1992 Mercedes-Benz 500E is said to have remained under the care of its original owner until 2022, and it was purchased by the seller later that same year. It is powered by a 5.0-liter M119 V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission and is finished in Black Pearl Metallic over gray leather upholstery. The car has been fitted with 18″ Carlsson wheels, European-specification headlights, and H&R lowering springs as well as an aftermarket rearview mirror with integrated front and rear cameras and a Kenwood head unit with Bluetooth connectivity. Additional equipment includes a power sunroof, fog lights, Automatic Slip Control, automatic climate control, heated power-adjustable front seats, and cruise control. This W124 500E is offered with a spare set of wheels, partial service records, manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carax report, and a clean Texas title in the seller’s name.

The 500E was assembled by Porsche and featured wheel arch flares, revised bodywork, and a lower ride height when compared to other W124 models. This example is finished in Black Pearl Metallic (199) and features gray lower cladding. Additional exterior features include European-specification headlights with wipers, integrated fog lights, a retractable antenna, and a power sunroof. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

The 18″ Carlsson wheels feature silver centers and polished lips, and they are fitted with Continental ExtremeContact Sport tires that have 2022 and 2023 date codes. The car is equipped with Automatic Slip Control (ASR), and braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs. Koni shocks have been added up front as well as H&R springs at all four corners. The seller states that the brake fluid was changed and the tie rods and parking brake spring were replaced under current ownership.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats upholstered in gray leather along with a color-coordinated lower dashboard, door panels, and carpeting. An aftermarket rearview mirror with integrated front and rear cameras has been fitted, and additional amenities include automatic climate control, a Kenwood head unit with Bluetooth connectivity, aftermarket speakers, a trunk-mounted JL Audio subwoofer, a Viper alarm system, and cruise control. The headliner has been replaced, per the seller, who notes cracks in the center console trim.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline, an analog clock, and gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 121k miles, approximately 16k of which were added under current ownership.

The 5.0-liter M119 DOHC V8 was factory-rated at 322 horsepower and 354 lb-ft of torque. The air conditioning compressor, evaporator, and expansion valve were reportedly replaced under current ownerhsip in addition to the engine wiring harness, valve cover gaskets, hood insulation, exhaust system, and drive belts.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission. The transmission fluid was changed in 2022.
A spare set of  16″ eight-hole alloy wheels wrapped in Michelin Premier tires with 2021 date codes will accompany the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
There is currently a lien on the car, and the seller’s lender will need to be paid off before the title can be transferred to the new owner.

This 2001 BMW M5 was purchased by the current owner’s late husband in 2003, and it has remained registered in Florida since new. The car is powered by a 4.9-liter V8 paired with a six-speed manual transmission and is finished in Silverstone Metallic over Silverstone and black Nappa leather upholstery. Equipment includes 18″ Style 65 wheels, a limited-slip differential, a sunroof, xenon headlights, fog lights, heated power-adjustable front seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, and navigation. Work performed in 2023 included servicing the VANOS system and replacing the timing chain and guides, valve cover gaskets, water pump, thermostat, power steering hoses, oil pan gasket, spark plugs, drive belts, engine mounts, transmission mount, differential mount, oxygen sensor, and differential seals. This E39 M5 is offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner service records, manufacturer’s literature, and a clean Florida title in the owner’s name.

The car is finished in Silverstone Metallic (425) with Shadowline trim and features aftermarket DjAuto xenon headlights with washers, fog lamps, rear parking sensors, a glass sunroof, a trunk lid spoiler, rain-sensing wipers, and quad exhaust outlets. A June 2024 entry on the Carfax report lists “minor damage” to the front of the car, which the seller attributes to the replacement of the front bumper cover. There is a ding in the right rear quarter panel, cracking on the door molding, and corrosion near the fuel filler cover. Close-up photographs of the exterior blemishes and trim are shown in the gallery below.

Chrome Shadow 18″ Style 65 wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact tires. The car features Dynamic Stability Control (DSC) with All Season Traction and braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs measuring 13.6″ and 12.9″ front and rear, respectively. The front and rear ABS sensors, front lower control arms, front and rear struts, and sway bar links were replaced in 2023.

The cabin features Silverstone and black Nappa leather covering the heated power-adjustable front sport seats, door panel inserts, center console, and lower dashboard. Amenities include dual-zone automatic climate control, an illuminated shift knob, cruise control, and navigation, the latter of which has a blemished display.

The multi-function leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts an M-branded 185-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a variable redline, along with gauges for coolant temperature, oil temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer shows 76k miles, approximately 25k of which were added under current ownership. A potential odometer rollback is noted in a November 2016 entry on the Carfax report, which the seller states was the result of a clerical error.

The 4.9-liter S62 V8 is equipped with individual throttle bodies and double-VANOS continuously variable valve timing. It was factory rated at 394 horsepower at 6,600 rpm and 369 lb-ft of torque at 3,800 rpm. Work performed since 2023 has included servicing the VANOS system and replacing the timing chain, timing chain tensioner, timing chain guides, valve cover gaskets, water pump, thermostat, power steering hoses, oil pan gasket, drive belts, drive belt tensioner, engine mounts, oxygen sensor, and spark plugs.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Getrag six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. The transmission mount, differential mount, and differential seals were replaced in 2023.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned June 2024 damage and potential odometer rollback.

This E39 M5 is offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner service records, manufacturer’s literature, and a clean Florida title in the owner’s name.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Getrag six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. The transmission mount, differential mount, and differential seals were replaced in 2023.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned June 2024 damage and potential odometer rollback.

This 1969 Morgan 4/4 is a right-hand-drive example that was imported to the US in 1982 by an American citizen who acquired the car while living in London. It was relocated to Texas under prior ownership and was acquired by the seller in 2024. Power is provided by a 1.6-liter inline-four that is equipped with a Weber carburetor and backed by a four-speed manual transmission. Work in preparation for the sale involved cleaning the carburetor, performing electrical repairs, refurbishing the distributor and fuel pump, and replacing the battery, water pump, and thermostat. Finished in cream over black upholstery, the car is equipped with a black tonneau cover, 15″ wire-spoke wheels, front disc brakes, a badge bar, a luggage rack, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, and a wood dashboard. This 4/4 is now offered at no reserve with an uninstalled soft top, side curtains, and a Texas title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in cream and equipped with a front badge bar, a rear luggage rack, wind wings, fender-mounted mirrors, and chrome bumpers. An uninstalled black soft top will accompany the car along with a matching tonneau cover and top boot. Areas of corrosion and touched-up paint are noted, and the wood in the sills is deteriorating.

Wire-spoke 15″ wheels are secured with Morgan-branded knock-offs and are wrapped in bias-ply tires, which the seller states need to be replaced. A spare is mounted out back. Stopping power is provided by front disc and rear drum brakes.

The right-hand-drive cockpit houses a pair of front bucket seats and a rear bench trimmed in black. Wear on the upholstery is shown in the gallery below. A storage cubby is located on the left side of the wood dash panel. The heater has been removed, and components will accompany the car.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel sits ahead of a 110-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary readouts. The seller states that the tachometer reads higher than the actual rpm and that some gauges are inaccurate. The five-digit odometer shows 94k miles, approximately 150 of which were added under current ownership.

The 1.6-liter inline-four is equipped with a Weber Brevettato 32 DFM carburetor and a K&N air cleaner assembly. Service in preparation for the sale reportedly involved changing fluids, cleaning the carburetor, adjusting the valves, repairing electrical components, refurbishing the distributor and fuel pump, and replacing the battery, water pump, and thermostat.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission. The seller notes that the differential oil was changed and the clutch hydraulics were rebuilt in preparation for the sale.
Documentation, partial service records, an uninstalled soft top, and side curtains will accompany the car.

This 1979 Porsche 928 is said to have spent time in storage from 2004 to 2017 before being acquired in 2019 by Casey Putsch of Genius Garage Racing, who initiated a refurbishment that involved an interior re-trim and mechanical work. It was purchased by the current owner in 2022, and subsequent work performed included repairing the instrument cluster and servicing the air conditioning system as well as replacing the power steering pump, thermostat, and various brake and clutch components. The car is finished in black metallic over black leatherette with Pasha velour inserts and is powered by a 4.5-liter V8 paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. Further equipment includes 16″ phone-dial alloy wheels, pop-up headlights, fog lights, cruise control, and a push-button AM/FM stereo. This 928 is now offered on dealer consignment in Michigan with an owner’s manual, partial service records, and a Nevada title.

Finished from the factory Black Metallic (708), the car was repainted under prior ownership. Details include pop-up headlights with washers in addition to fog lights, power-adjustable mirrors, a locking fuel filler cap, and a rear window wiper. The taillights were refurbished and the left headlight bulb was replaced under current ownership. Various seals and trim pieces are recommended to be replaced.

The 16″ phone-dial alloy wheels are mounted with 225/50 Continental Extreme Contact Sport tires with 2017 date codes. Braking is handled by power-assisted discs at each corner with red-finished calipers fitted up front. The power steering pump and brake pads and rotors were replaced, the brake master cylinder and booster were rebuilt, and the brake hard lines were refurbished under current ownership. The selling dealer recommends replacing the wheel center caps.

The front bucket seats and folding rear seats are upholstered in black leatherette with replacement Pasha velour inserts, which extend to portions of the door panels. A replacement dash cap was retrofitted, and further appointments include air conditioning, cruise control, an analog clock, and a push-button AM/FM stereo. Work performed since 2022 has reportedly involved refurbishing the radio, replacing the ignition cylinder, repairing the climate control panel, and installing a rear-view mirror.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 170-mph speedometer, a 7,600-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature, fuel level, oil pressure, and voltage. The six-digit odometer shows 33k miles, approximately 200 of which have been added under current ownership. The instrument cluster was repaired and calibrated by North Hollywood Speedometer in California under current ownership. True mileage is unknown.

The 4.5-liter V8 was factory rated at 219 horsepower and 254 lb-ft of torque. The water pump and timing components were replaced in 2017, and work performed since 2022 involved refurbishing the air conditioning system in addition to replacing the battery, thermostat, air intake hoses, and an alternator cable. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a rear-mounted five-speed manual transaxle. The transmission fluid was changed, the master cylinder, clutch release and pilot bearings were replaced, the flywheel was machined, and the right axle was rebuilt under current ownership.
Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery below.
An owner’s manual and partial service records are included in the sale.

This 2004 Mazda Mazdaspeed MX-5 Miata has 63k miles following registration history in Florida, Arizona, and California, and it was purchased by the seller from the late original owner’s family in July 2020. Modifications include a Flyin’ Miata cat-back exhaust system, a Hard Dog roll bar, a short-throw shifter, an aftermarket shift knob, and revised differential gearing. The car is finished in Titanium Gray Metallic over black and red cloth upholstery, and it is powered by a turbocharged 1.8-liter inline-four paired with a six-speed manual transmission. Additional equipment includes 17″ Racing Hart alloy wheels, Bilstein dampers, a black soft top, fog lights, a decklid spoiler, a leather-wrapped Nardi steering wheel, a Bose sound system, and air conditioning. This Mazdaspeed NB Miata is now offered at no reserve with service records and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

This example is finished in Titanium Gray Metallic and features a black soft top, a heated glass rear window, fog lights, a front air dam, extended rocker panel trim, a power antenna, and painted mirror caps. Mazdaspeed-specific features include revised front and rear bumper covers, front and rear under spoilers, a color-matched rear lip spoiler, and Mazdaspeed badging. A Hard Dog roll bar has been added. The Carfax report indicates that a January 2010 accident resulted in damage to the front. The passenger-side mirror is loose, and close-up photos in the gallery detail cracks on the soft top, a dent on the front bumper cover, and finish imperfections on the body.

Silver 17″ Racing Hart alloy wheels were reportedly powdercoated in March 2024 and are mounted with Kuhmo Ecsta tires. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes with ABS, and the factory-lowered suspension features Mazdaspeed-tuned sway bars, springs, and Bilstein dampers.

The cabin features bucket seats trimmed in black and red cloth along with color-coordinated door panels. Amenities include air conditioning, a Bose sound system, a CD stereo, power windows, a short-throw shifter, and an aftermarket shift knob.

The leather-wrapped Nardi steering wheel frames a 150-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 63k miles, approximately 8k of which were added under current ownership.

The turbocharged 1.8-liter inline-four was factory rated at 178 horsepower and 166 lb-ft of torque. A Flyin’ Miata cat-back exhaust system has been added, and the catalytic converter has been replaced. Work in March 2020 included replacing the timing belt, water pump, valve cover gasket, thermostat, front crankshaft seal, and camshaft seals. MAP and knock sensors were replaced in April 2022.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential, the latter of which was fitted with 3.6:1 gearing in February 2021.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned accident.
The car most recently passed a California emissions test in June 2024.

This 1995 Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme convertible is finished in Bright Red over Graphite Pearl leather and powered by a 3.4-liter DOHC V6 paired with a four-speed automatic transaxle. Now showing 46k kilometers (~29k miles), the car features a power-operated black soft top, five-spoke 16″ alloy wheels, four-wheel antilock disc brakes, a touring suspension, a power-adjustable driver seat, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, a CD/cassette stereo, and power windows, locks, and mirrors. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this Cutlass Supreme convertible is offered at no reserve in British Columbia, Canada, with a clean Carfax report and Alberta registration.
The car is finished in Bright Red and features a power-operated black soft top, a top boot, fog lights, a power antenna, power-adjustable side mirrors, and quad exhaust outlets.
Five-spoke 16″ aluminum wheels are mounted with General Altimax RT tires. The car rides on a touring suspension, and braking is handled by antilock discs at all four corners.

The front bucket seats and rear bench are trimmed in Graphite Pearl leather. Amenities include a power-adjustable driver seat, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, a CD/cassette stereo, and power windows and locks.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel frames a 190-km/h speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 46k kilometers (~29k miles), approximately 100 of which were added by the selling dealer.
The 3.4-liter DOHC V6 was factory rated at 210 horsepower and 215 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the front wheels through a four-speed automatic transaxle.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.
The car does not have a title and is being sold on its Alberta registration, which serves as the ownership document in Alberta, Canada.

This 2014 Land Rover Range Rover Sport Supercharged was ordered with the Dynamic Package, which featured an increased top-speed limiter, 21″ wheels, red-finished brake calipers, aluminum pedals, and a 12.3″ digital instrument cluster. It was also optioned with the Vision & Convenience Package and the Front Climate Comfort & Visibility Package, which featured heated and ventilated front seats. Power comes from a supercharged 5.0-liter V8 that drives all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission. Electronic air suspension and an active locking rear differential are additional elements. Registered in California since new, this Range Rover Sport Supercharged has 46k miles and is offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a clean California title.

The truck is finished in Corris Gray Metallic with gloss-black accents, and it has adaptive xenon headlights, a sliding panoramic roof, and a power-operated tailgate. Paint touch-ups are noted on the rear bumper.

This is a relist after the vehicle was previously sold on BaT in July 2024 and the winning bidder failed to follow through with their commitment to purchase. This was not due to any fault with the vehicle. The winner’s participation on BaT has been restricted and their buyer’s fee was not refunded.

The 21″ Style 15 alloy wheels wear 275/45 Yokohama Geolandar X-CV tires with 2020 date codes. Additional equipment includes adjustable air suspension, Adaptive Dynamics continuously variable damping, and selectable Terrain Response driving modes. The brake pads were replaced and the rotors were resurfaced in July 2024.

The heated and ventilated front seats are trimmed in tan Oxford leather with contrast stitching, while Ebony leather and textured aluminum trim accent the cabin, which has an eight-speaker sound system, touchscreen infotainment, a center-console cooler box, heated rear seats, and soft-close doors.

The heated steering wheel is mounted on a power-adjustable column, and the driver is aided by a heated windshield, a surround camera system, blind-spot monitors, and Park Assist. The odometer indicates 46k miles.

Factory rated at 510 horsepower and 461 lb-ft of torque, the supercharged 5.0-liter V8 sends power to all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case with a locking center differential, and a Dynamic Active rear locking differential. The engine oil was changed in July 2024.
Additional photographs of the underside are shown in the gallery below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
