description: This 1937 Chevrolet Sedan street rod was refurbished and modified under previous ownership and is powered by a 383ci Chevrolet V8 equipped with an Edelbrock four-barrel carburetor, an electronic ignition, and a 3″ dual exhaust system with ceramic-coated headers. The car is finished in red and white and is also equipped with a four-speed automatic transmission, independent front suspension, rack-and-pinion steering, four-wheel disc brakes, 17″ Foose wheels, and a 10-bolt rear end. The interior is upholstered in red, white, and gray vinyl and features Corbeau Sport front seats, Vintage Air climate control, and an Alpine CD receiver. This Chevrolet street rod was acquired by the seller in 2022 and is now offered with service records, show placards and awards, and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The body is finished in Medium Garnet Red over Snow White Pearl with an integrated gray gradient. A gray waistline stripe is outlined with red and gold pinstriping and leads to a 3D air-brushed design at the rear with additional red, gold, and gray pinstripes. Features include a center-hinged hood with louvered side panels, running boards with black rubber treads, and doors with shaved handles and remote-actuated electric poppers. Additional details include blue dot tri-bar headlights, recessed front and rear turn signals, peep mirrors, and a hideaway/flip-down license plate bracket at the rear.

Foose 17″ polished Nitrous wheels are mounted with Falken Ziex ZE950 tires showing 2015 date codes. The car rides on a custom aftermarket chassis with Mustang II-style independent suspension and coilover shocks up front, along with 2″ dropped spindles and power-assisted rack-and-pinion steering. Leaf springs and tube shocks are utilized at the rear. Braking is provided by power-assisted four-wheel discs.

The cabin features Corbeau Sport front seats and rear bench seats trimmed in tri-tone vinyl consisting of Garnet Red with pleated white and Gray Flannel MB-Tex inserts as well as matching door panels and color-coordinated British wool carpets. Additional interior details include Vintage Air climate control, an Alpine CD receiver, a separate Alpine amplifier, Kicker speakers, and lap belts.

A red-leather-wrapped Lecarra steering wheel fronts a body-color dash with milled aluminum instrument and and glovebox panels. VDO instrumentation consists of a 120-mph speedometer flanked by fuel level, charging, oil pressure, and coolant-temperature gauges. A clock is inset on the glovebox door, and an adjustable tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline is clamped to the tilt steering column. The five-digit odometer shows 54k miles, approximately 500 of which were added by the seller. True mileage is unknown.

The 383ci Chevrolet stroker V8 is equipped with an Edelbrock four-barrel carburetor, a Walker Radiator Works radiator and fan assembly, an MSD distributor, and a 3″ dual exhaust system with ceramic-coated headers, Magnaflow mufflers, and chrome-tipped rear exits. Underhood dress-up pieces include polished aluminum valve and air cleaner covers and a chrome alternator cover.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a 700R4 four-speed automatic overdrive transmission and a 10-bolt rear end sourced from a 1970 Monte Carlo. The final gear ratio is 3.08:1.
The car is titled in California using the Washington Assigned Identification Number WA94180426.
listing_details: Red & White Paint w/Gray, Red & Gold Accents

description: This 1977 Alfa Romeo Alfetta was reportedly sold new in California, and refurbishment work carried out between 2006 and 2017 consisted of repainting the Olandese Blu exterior, refreshing the matching interior, and rebuilding the SPICA fuel injection in addition to sorting the electrical system and removing emissions-control equipment. Tubular exhaust headers, custom steel bumpers, and 15″ Rota wheels have been fitted along with a vintage-style digital radio, aftermarket air conditioning, and a 1975-specification grille. Powered by a 2.0L twin-cam inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transaxle, the car is further equipped with four-wheel disc brakes, polyurethane suspension bushings, and a woodgrain steering wheel and interior trim. Purchased by its current owner on BaT in October 2017, this Alfetta is now offered at no reserve by the seller on behalf of the owner with the removed heater and wheels as well as a clean Illinois title in the owner’s name.

The car was factory-finished in Olandese Blu (343) and repainted in 2006. Modified 1967 Camaro bumpers have been fitted, as have a 1975-specification Alfetta front grille and headlight assemblies. Additional exterior details include dual side mirrors, a Centro Stile fender badge, C-pillar vents, and a downturned exhaust outlet. Bubbled paint near the left front wheel arch is noted by the seller, and photos showing pitted door-handle chrome, chipped paint, and other blemishes in the finish are provided in the gallery below.

Rota 15″ alloy wheels with Alfa Romeo-logo center caps are wrapped in 205/60 Sumitomo HTR A/S P01 tires, and the suspension was rebuilt with polyurethane bushings under prior ownership. Braking is provided by four-wheel discs with inboard rears, and the system is said to have been serviced within the last year.

The interior was reportedly refreshed in the mid-2010s, and the replacement front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in blue cloth. Matching door panels were fitted, and additional appointments include woodgrain trim, a vintage-styled digital radio, and three-point seatbelts as well as aftermarket air conditioning in place of the stock heater. Faded carpet and a loose radio fit are noted by the seller, and a cracked dashboard is depicted in the gallery.

The replacement three-spoke steering wheel frames a refurbished 140-mph speedometer and 7,500-rpm tachometer along with a clock and gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 33k miles and has reportedly rolled over, with approximately 600 miles added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 2.0-liter inline-four is equipped with a SPICA fuel-injection system that was rebuilt circa 2006. Tubular exhaust headers have been installed, all emissions-control equipment has been removed, and the car’s electrical system was sorted in 2017.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a rear-mounted, five-speed manual transaxle. The clutch was replaced circa 2006, the underside of the car is said to have been treated with Formula 3000 rust inhibitor in the mid-2010s, and the exhaust system and driveshaft flex joints were reportedly replaced under current ownership.
The removed wheels and heater assembly are included in the sale.

This 1969 Chevrolet Camaro SS convertible was purchased in Ontario by the seller in circa 2011, and a subsequent refurbishment in 2015 included a repaint in Butternut Yellow and reupholstering the interior in vinyl and houndstooth cloth upholstery. It is powered by a replacement 396ci Turbo-Jet V8 paired with a four-speed manual transmission. Features include a 2.73:1 Positraction differential, a replacement black convertible soft top, 14″ steel wheels with hubcaps, power-assisted steering, retractable headlights, an Enduro-style front bumper, an AM/FM radio, Deluxe interior trim, power windows, and a cabin heater. This Camaro SS convertible is now offered in Canada with transferable Ontario registration in the seller’s name.

The body is said to have been removed from the frame and refinished in Butternut Yellow during the refurbishment approximately a decade ago. An Endura-style front bumper has been added, while additional exterior details include a replacement black convertible soft top, retractable headlights, and chrome trim.

The body-color 14″ steel wheels wear hubcaps and are mounted with 215/70 Goodyear Polyglas tires. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The cabin features front bucket seats and a rear bench reupholstered in black vinyl with houndstooth inserts. Power windows have been retrofitted, and the car was optioned from the factory with Deluxe interior trim. Interior appointments include an AM/FM radio, woodgrain dashboard accents, and a cabin heater.

The three-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of a 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and a fuel-level gauge. The five-digit odometer shows 31k miles, approximately 300 of which were added by the seller. Total mileage is unknown.

The car was originally optioned with the L35-code 396ci Turbo Jet V8 rated at 325 horsepower and equipped with a four-barrel carburetor. The replacement 396ci Turbo-Jet L35 V8 was installed in 2010 per the seller.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission and an optional 2.73:1 Positraction differential.
Decoding the Fisher body tag reveals the following information:
The car does not have a title, as it is registered in a country that does not issue vehicle titles. It is being sold on its Ontario provincial registration.

This 1964 Mercedes-Benz 230SL is powered by a replacement 2.8-liter inline-six paired with a four-speed manual transmission and is finished in Light Ivory over Bamboo MB-Tex. Equipment includes a brown convertible top, a removable hardtop, 14″ Bundt alloy wheels, and a heater. The selling dealer acquired the car in 2023, and it had previously been registered with the same owner since 1990. Work since October 2023 has reportedly included refinishing the wood trim as well as replacing the carpets and tires. This W113 SL is now offered at no reserve with a clean California title.

The W113 SL was designed by Friedrich Geiger, Béla Barényi, and Paul Bracq and was introduced to the public at the 1963 Geneva Motor Show. This example is finished in Light Ivory (670) and features a brown soft top, a removable hardtop, a driver-side mirror, and European-specification headlights.

The 14″ Bundt alloy wheels are mounted with 195/70 Kumho Solus tires that show 2023 date codes. Braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. A brake fluid flush was performed in October 2023. Curb rash is present on the wheels.

The cabin houses bucket seats upholstered in Bamboo MB-Tex that extends to the door panels. The seller states that the wood trim was refinished in April 2024, the door panels have been redyed, and the carpets were replaced in preparation for the sale. Interior appointments include an analog clock, a floor-mounted gear shifter, a Kenwood cassette stereo, and a heater. Wear is present on the steering wheel and trim.

The two-spoke steering wheel features a chrome horn ring and frames a 140-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 73k miles, a handful of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.
The 2.8-liter inline-six was installed in place of the original 2.3-liter unit under previous ownership.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission.

This 2005 Aston Martin DB9 has 19k miles following registration history in Colorado, Nevada, Texas, and Illinois. It is finished in Tungsten Silver over Iron Ore Red leather, and it is powered by a 5.9-liter V12 paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. The car is equipped with a limited-slip differential, 19″ 10-spoke alloy wheels, rear parking sensors, heated power-adjustable seats, a navigation system, a Linn sound system, cruise control, and automatic climate control. This DB9 is now offered by the selling dealer with shop manuals, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Pennsylvania title.

The DB9 featured a mix of aluminum and composite body panels installed over an extruded aluminum spaceframe. This example is finished in Tungsten Silver and features a Tungsten grille, hood vents, fender vents, rear parking sensors, LED taillights, and dual exhaust outlets.

The 19″ 10-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Bridgestone Potenza rubber up front and Hankook Ventus V12 Evo tires out back. The car is equipped with adaptive dampers, and braking is handled by four-wheel slotted and ventilated steel rotors.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats trimmed in Iron Ore Red leather. Amenities include a retractable navigation screen, a CD stereo, a Linn sound system, cruise control, and automatic climate control.
The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 220-mph speedometer, a reverse-sweep tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 19k miles.
The 5.9-liter DOHC V12 was factory rated at 450 horsepower and 420 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.

This 1937 Buick Series 80 Roadmaster is a Model 81 trunk-back sedan that underwent a cosmetic refurbishment under previous ownership that included a repaint in metallic gray as well as the installation of replacement tan cloth upholstery. Power comes from a 320ci straight-eight paired with a three-speed manual transmission, and equipment includes dual side-mount spare wheels, yellow-lens driving lamps, rear-hinged rear doors, an AM radio, a heater, a rear footrest, and a robe cord. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale. This Series 80 Roadmaster was purchased by the selling dealer in 2024 and is now offered with a clean Massachusetts title.

The Buick lineup was restyled for 1937 and featured squared-off fender ends, a split grille with horizontal chrome bars, and streamlined headlight buckets and fender-mounted driving lamps. A total of 14,637 Model 81 trunk-back sedans were produced for the model year. This example was delivered from the factory in Imperial Black (500) and was repainted in metallic gray under previous ownership. Equipment includes yellow-lens driving lamps, Roadmaster-branded hood vents, an antenna, dual side-view mirrors, running boards, dual taillights, and a glass-lens Buco-Buick brake lamp mounted on the trunk lid.

The red-painted wheels feature chrome hubcaps and trim rings, and they are mounted with 7.00-16 Lester whitewall bias-ply tires. Spare wheels in body-color covers are stowed in the front fenders. The Model 81 rode on a 131″ wheelbase and featured a coil-sprung independent front suspension along with a live rear axle with leaf springs. Stopping power is provided by hydraulic drums at all four corners.

The cabin was reupholstered in tan cloth under previous ownership, and it features front and rear benches along with a color-coordinated headliner, door panels, and carpets. Additional equipment includes an AM radio, a heater, a locking glovebox door with an inset clock, woodgrain dash and window trim, a rear cabin footrest, a robe cord, and a rear fold-down armrest.

The three-spoke banjo-style steering wheel features a chrome horn ring, and it frames a 120-mph speedometer and auxiliary gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 49k miles, approximately 100 of which were added by the selling dealer. Total mileage is unknown.
The 320ci straight-eight features five main bearings and a Carter carburetor for a factory rating of 130 horsepower. An oil change was performed in 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a floor-shifted three-speed manual transmission.

This 1956 Austin-Healey BN2 Roadster is one of 640 factory-built 100M “Le Mans” specification cars produced between 1955 and 1956, and it is finished in Old English White and red with a black soft top over black leather. It was completed on October 13, 1955, as a North American-market example, and it was sold by B.C. Importers of Miami, Florida in October 1959 to a long-term owner of 39 years. The replacement 2,660cc inline-four was rebuilt in 2019 with an aluminum cylinder head from Denis Welch, forged 8.5:1-compression Arias pistons, a ground and re-hardened camshaft from Elgin, and a high-volume oil pump. Power is sent to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transmission with overdrive. The car was listed on BaT in March 2020 and January 2021. Work performed since November 2022 included rebuilding the carburetors as well as replacing the clutch, resealing the front of the transmission, and replacing the pinion gear, oil pan, rear main seal, timing and valve cover gaskets, and ignition components, after which the car was listed on BaT in May 2024. This 100M is now offered in Arizona by the selling dealer with a 100M “Le Mans” Registry Certificate of Membership, a British Motor Industry Heritage Trust certificate, a 1959 sales invoice, service records, and a clean Michigan title.

The car was refinished in Old English White with contrasting red lower bodywork during previous ownership, and replacement bumpers and overriders have been installed. The 100M-specific louvered hood is secured with a leather strap, and additional details include a black soft top, a tilt-down windshield, early-style smooth rear fenders, and replacement chrome bumpers with overriders. Close-up photos of the trim and finish are provided in the gallery, and a semi-circular crack on the shroud aft of the cockpit is noted.

Silver-finished 15″ wire wheels are secured by two-eared knockoffs and wear 165-series Vredestein Sprint Classic tires. A matching spare wheel with a Dunlop SP 4N tire is secured in the trunk. Braking is handled by four-wheel drums, and the suspension and brakes were overhauled in 2018.

The two-place cockpit features black leather upholstery with red piping over the seats and driveline tunnel that is complemented by red carpeting, door panels, and trunk lining. Additional features include a banjo-spoke steering wheel, a dashboard-mounted rear-view mirror, Sisal floor mats, and a 100M registry placard affixed to the body-color dashboard.
Smiths instrumentation includes a 120-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, a fuel gauge, and a combination oil pressure and water-temperature gauge. The five-digit odometer shows 63k miles.

The 2,660cc inline-four features a replacement block that was sleeved, line-bored, and hot-tanked during the 2019 rebuild. An aluminum cylinder head and uprated bolts from Denis Welch were fitted, and the factory pistons were replaced with forged alloy versions from Arias with an 8.5:1 compression ratio. The camshaft is a reground and re-hardened Elgin component made to 6707 M specifications, and the rotating assembly is said to have been balanced during the build. Markings on the twin SU carburetors and distributor are pictured in the previous listing for the car along with a summary document of the engine rebuild. Work performed since November 2022 consisted of rebuilding the carburetors, a valve adjustment, installing an aluminum oil pan, and replacing the rear main seal, timing and valve cover gaskets, heater hoses, two freeze plugs, and the ignition points, rotor, condenser, and wires.

Power is sent to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transmission with an electrically actuated overdrive unit. The floors were reportedly replaced under previous ownership and dents are pictured at various points along the frame rails. Work performed between November 2022 and January 2023 included resealing the front of the transmission, repairing overdrive shaft leaks, and replacing the clutch disc, pressure plate, pilot bushing, release bearing, and pinion gear.

The 100M “Le Mans” Registry Certificate of Membership was issued in September 2019 and lists the chassis, engine, and body numbers. Additional documentation includes a British Motor Industry Heritage Trust certificate, 1959 invoices, 100M “Le Mans” articles, and recent service invoices.
listing_details: Old English White and Red Paint

description: This 1993 Ferrari 512 TR is one of 408 examples delivered to North America between 1992 and 1994. It was purchased by its current owner in July 2007, and it shows 39k miles following registration history in Oregon and California. Finished in Rosso Corsa over Beige Connolly leather, the car is powered by a 4.9-liter flat-12 paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes a limited-slip differential, a Tubi Style exhaust system, Fabspeed high-flow catalytic converters, 18″ five-spoke alloy wheels, pop-up headlights, air conditioning, power windows, a CD stereo, and a gated shifter. This 512 TR is now offered on dealer consignment with the owner’s manual, service records, awards, a car cover, spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The Pininfarina-designed 512 TR was introduced as the updated successor to the Testarossa in 1991, with revisions that included restyled bumper covers as well as revised wheels and lighting. This example is finished in Rosso Corsa and features pop-up headlights, side intake strakes, body-color rocker panels, and quad exhaust outlets. Euro-style fog lights have been added.

Silver 18″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Kumho Ecsta MX tires. Cross-drilled brake rotors are stationed at all four corners. The brake fluid was flushed in March 2024. The sale includes a spare set of 18″ Y-spoke wheels, and they are shod with Michelin tires.

The cockpit is trimmed in beige Connolly leather upholstery over the seats, door panels, and lower dashboard. Interior amenities include a CD stereo, motorized seat belts, and a gated shifter located on the center console alongside controls for the air conditioning and power windows.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames Veglia instrumentation including a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7,200-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil pressure and coolant temperature. A clock and auxiliary gauges for fuel level and oil temperature are housed in the center stack. The six-digit odometer shows 39k miles, approximately 21k of which were added under current ownership.

The 4.9-liter DOHC flat-12 received updates over the version used in the Testarossa including Nikasil cylinder liners, a redesigned intake system, and Bosch engine management. Output was rated at 421 horsepower and 362 lb-ft of torque when new. A Tubi Style exhaust system and Fabspeed high-flow catalytic converters have been added. A belt service was reportedly performed in April 2021, and the oil and coolant were changed in March 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. The transaxle fluid was changed in March 2024.

The car won a Ferrari Club of America Premio di Platino award in 2015. The sale includes the spare set of 18″ Y-spoke wheels as well as awards, removed factory muffler and catalytic converter components, Schedoni luggage, a car cover, and service records.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The car most recently passed a California emissions test in May 2021, however, the catalytic converters installed are not CARB-compliant.
listing_details: Tubi Style Exhaust w/Fabspeed High-Flow Catalytic Converters

description: This 2007 Chevrolet Corvette Z06 is powered by a 7.0-liter LS7 V8 paired with a six-speed manual gearbox and is finished in Victory Red over Ebony leather. The car has remained registered in California since it was new and now has under 7k miles. Equipment includes the 2LZ Preferred Equipment Group, a limited-slip differential, 18″ and 19″ multi-spoke wheels, xenon headlights, a head-up display, heated seats, push-button start, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, and a Bose sound system. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this C6 Z06 is now offered with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The C6 featured a hydro-formed aluminum chassis paired with composite and carbon-fiber bodywork. This car is finished in Victory Red and features black front and rear spoilers as well as xenon headlights, fog lights, Z06 fender badging, and polished quad exhaust outlets.

Staggered-diameter 18″ and 19″ multi-spoke wheels are mounted with Goodyear Eagle F1 Supercar tires measuring 275/35 and 325/30, respectively. Braking is handled by red-finished Corvette-branded calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated discs at each corner.

The cabin houses heated bucket seats upholstered in Ebony leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, center console, door panels, and carpets. Interior amenities include a power-adjustable driver’s seat with memory settings as well as Keyless Access, push-button start, a head-up display, a CD stereo, cruise control, dual-zone automatic climate control, and a Bose sound system.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates under 7k miles.
The 7.0-liter LS7 V8 features a dry-sump lubrication system and was factory rated at 505 horsepower and 470 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual gearbox and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2010 Mercedes-Benz S550 4MATIC remained with its original owner between Florida and New York before the selling dealer’s acquisition in 2023, and it was sold on BaT in December 2023. It is finished in Diamond White Metallic over Savanna and Cashmere leather and is powered by a 5.5-liter V8 that drives all four wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission. It features the Sport Package, 19″ five-spoke AMG wheels, bi-xenon headlights, a panoramic sunroof, Parktronic, soft-close doors, Keyless-Go, COMAND with navigation, and heated and ventilated power-adjustable dynamic front seats. This W221 S550 has 17k miles and is now offered on dealer consignment in Wisconsin with manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Illinois title.

The car is finished in Diamond White Metallic (799) and features AMG-styled bodywork including a revised front spoiler and side skirts. Additional equipment includes bi-xenon headlights, a panoramic sunroof, Active Curve Illumination, Parktronic, soft-close doors, a power-operated trunk lid, dual exhaust outlets, and auto-dimming side-view mirrors with integrated signal lighting. The Carfax report notes that the car was involved in an accident with another motor vehicle in January 2014, and the rear sustained “minor damage” in December 2017. There are blemishes on the left mirror cap.

The 19″ five-spoke AMG wheels are mounted with Continental ContiProContact tires measuring 255/40 all around. The car is equipped with Airmatic semi-active suspension, and braking is handled by four-wheel vented disc brakes with cross-drilled front rotors. There are blemishes on the right-front wheel.

The cabin features heated and ventilated dynamic power-adjustable front seats upholstered in Savanna and Cashmere leather complemented by burl walnut wood trim. Amenities include dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, Keyless-Go, a back-up camera, a Harman Kardon sound system, and COMAND infotainment with navigation.
The wood- and leather-rimmed steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 17k miles.
The 5.5-liter M273 V8 was factory rated at 382 horsepower and 391 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report notes the aforementioned damage reports and lists history in Florida and New York.

This 1962 Century Resorter is a 17′ mahogany-hulled runabout that is powered by a replacement inboard 400ci GM V8 mated to a jet drive. The boat was purchased in 1982 by the seller’s father, who subsequently performed a refurbishment that included replacing the engine, rebuilding the Buehler jet drive, reupholstering the interior in red and white vinyl, and applying a West System epoxy overlay to the bottom. The boat features a two-piece windshield, a spotlight, a transom-mounted stepping board, running lights, and deck-mounted cleats. This Resorter is now offered at no reserve by the seller on behalf of his father’s estate with a single-axle trailer, a boat cover, spare parts, and Minnesota registrations for the boat and trailer.

Work carried out on the 17′ mahogany hull included replacing damaged boards, applying a West System overlay, and stripping and reapplying the topside varnish and bottom paint. The boat is equipped with running lights, a spotlight, a two-piece windshield, and gunwale-mounted step plates.

The cabin features two rows of bench seats that were reupholstered in red and white vinyl under current ownership. Appointments include a replacement gray carpet, a dash-mounted rearview mirror, a fire extinguisher, and storage cubbies to port and starboard.

A four-spoke steering wheel fronts an upholstered dash that houses instrumentation consisting of a tachometer and gauges for engine temperature, oil pressure, and battery amperage. An aftermarket speedometer has been fitted to the left of the steering wheel. The hour meter shows 833 hours, though total runtime is unknown due to the replacement engine. The fuel level gauge is not functional.
The replacement 400ci GM V8 was installed under current ownership in 1989. The fuel tank was flushed in preparation for the sale.
The boat is equipped with a Buehler jet drive. The seller notes that there is a leak where the jet drive mounts to the boat.
The single-axle trailer is equipped with a rolling tongue jack, a manual winch, rollers, carpeted bunks, surge brakes, and street lighting.
The seller cannot locate a hull identification number on the boat, and one is not listed on the registration.
The boat and trailer do not have titles as they are registered in a state that does not require a title for vehicles of their type. They are being sold on their registrations.

This 1971 Ford F-250 Custom is a 4×4 pickup delivered new to Hughson Ford of San Francisco, California, and it is said to have remained with two owners in northern California until its 2024 acquisition by the selling dealer. A 360ci V8 is linked to a four-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case. The truck is finished in Candyapple Red and Wimbledon White and it is equipped with manually locking front hubs, a receiver hitch, 16″ steel wheels, Western-style mirrors, a black vinyl-upholstered bench seat, a cassette stereo, and a heater. This bumpside F-250 is now offered by the selling dealer in North Carolina with a Deluxe Marti report and a clean California title.

The truck is finished in Candyapple Red and Wimbledon White and features a Styleside bed as well as Western-style mirrors, a diamond-plate rear step bumper, and a receiver hitch. Wear is visible in the truck bed, dents are noted above the right-hand fuel door and on the left front fender, and the red portions portions of the body show evidence of paintwork.

White-painted 16″ steel wheels wear Falken Wildpeak M/T tires measuring 255/85 that were reportedly mounted in preparation for the sale. The truck is equipped with manually locking front hubs and manual steering, and braking is provided by unassisted drums at each corner.

The bench seat was reupholstered in black vinyl in preparation for the sale, and the steering wheel and dash pad were replaced. A Kenwood cassette stereo is fitted along with lap belts and a heater. The factory floor mats are worn and the rearview mirror is damaged.
Instrumentation consists of a sweeping 100-mph speedometer, an ammeter, and gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 81k miles.

The 360ci V8 was factory rated at 215 horsepower and 327 lb-ft of torque. An ignition tune-up was reportedly completed in preparation for the sale along with rebuilding the carburetor and replacing the valve cover gaskets. Rust is noted on the underside of the hood.
Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels via a four-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Corrosion is visible on underside surfaces.
The warranty tag is shown above and indicates a serial number of F26YRL28121, which matches the frame stamping shown in the gallery and the VIN on the California title.
The Deluxe Marti report displays factory colors and options as well as a build date of March 29, 1971.

This 2012 Porsche Cayenne S is finished in white over Light Tartufo and Umber leather and is powered by a 4.8-liter V8 linked with an eight-speed Tiptronic S automatic transmission and a locking center differential. It is modified with a Eurowise Performance 3″ lift kit and tubular front bumper bar with Hella driving lights as well as 18″ OZ Racing Rally Raid wheels. Other equipment includes the Premium Plus and Walnut Interior packages as well as a panoramic sunroof, heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats, a Bose surround-sound system, PCM with navigation, and xenon headlights with PDLS. The vehicle has spent time in Florida, Texas, Georgia, and New York and now has 90k miles. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this Cayenne S is now offered at no reserve with a clean Florida title.

The SUV is finished in white with high-gloss black trim and features xenon headlights with the Porsche Dynamic Light System (PDLS) as well as a panoramic sunroof, a receiver hitch, front and rear ParkAssist, and LED taillights. A Eurowise Performance tubular front bumper bar is equipped with Hella driving lights. The Carfax report notes that the rear of the vehicle sustained “minor damage” in September 2015 with no additional information provided. The seller notes scratches on the rear hatch and rear bumper cover.

Bronze 18″ OZ Racing Rally Raid wheels are mounted with 275/65 Falken Wildpeak A/T AT3W tires. The vehicle is equipped with a Eurowise Performance 3″ lift kit, an adjustable air suspension, and Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM). Stopping power is provided by six-piston front and four-piston rear brake calipers over ventilated rotors at each corner.

The cabin features heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats and a heated rear bench upholstered in Light Tartufo leather complemented by a two-tone Umber and Light Tartufo dashboard and door panels. Amenities include a back-up camera, a Bose surround-sound system, Porsche Entry & Drive, Lane Change Assist (LCA), power rear sunshades, dual-zone automatic climate control, and Porsche Communication Management (PCM) with navigation. WeatherTech floor liners are included in the sale.

The heated wood- and leather-rimmed steering wheel features shifter switches and frames a 175-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,800-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 90k miles.
The 4.8-liter V8 features VarioCam Plus and was factory rated at 400 horsepower and 369 lb-ft of torque. The seller states that the water pump was replaced and the oil was changed in July 2024.
Power is sent to all four wheels through an eight-speed Tiptronic S automatic transmission and a locking center differential.
The Carfax report notes the aforementioned damage entry.

This 2017 Jeep Wrangler Unlimited Sport was purchased by the current owner in January 2018 and now has 46k miles. The truck is finished in black over black leather upholstery, and it is powered by a 3.6-liter V6 linked to a five-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Additional equipment includes 20″ Moto Metal wheels, a removable hardtop, aftermarket bumpers, air conditioning, and a Pioneer touchscreen stereo. This JK Wrangler Unlimited is offered by the seller in Texas on behalf of the current owner with the owner’s manual, two sets of keys, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New Mexico title in the owner’s name.

The truck is finished in black, and equipment includes a removable hardtop, a receiver hitch, LED auxiliary lights, and an aftermarket grille, rock rails, bumpers, and fender flares. The seller states the winch goes out but not in.
The 20″ Moto Metal wheels are mounted with 37×13.5″ Nitto Trail Grappler M/T tires. Braking is handled by discs at each corner. The truck is equipped with dual Rough Country steering stabilizers.
The front bucket seats and rear bench are trimmed in black leather with diamond-stitch inserts. Appointments include a Pioneer touchscreen stereo, aftermarket audio components, and air conditioning.
Instrumentation includes a 100-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline as well as auxiliary gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 46k miles.
The 3.6-liter Pentastar V6 was factory rated at 285 horsepower and 260 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a five-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2001 Honda S2000 has 14k miles, and it is finished in Silverstone Metallic over black leather. Power is supplied by a 2.0-liter VTEC inline-four linked with a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential, and features include 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels, a black convertible soft top, xenon headlights, air conditioning, a CD stereo, and cruise control. This AP1 S2000 is now offered by the selling dealer with a clean Carfax report and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Silverstone Metallic (NH-630M) and features a power-operated black soft top with a plastic rear window. Additional exterior features include xenon headlights, roll hoops, and dual exhaust outlets.

Factory 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact DWS 06 Plus tires, which were fitted in April 2022. The car features double-wishbone suspension and four-wheel disc brakes.

The cabin features seats upholstered in black leather with color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Amenities include push-button ignition, air conditioning, cruise control, a CD stereo, a wind deflector, and an aluminum shift knob.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a digital speedometer and a bar-style tachometer with an 8,900-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 14k miles.
The 2.0-liter VTEC F20C inline-four was factory rated at 240 horsepower and 153 lb-ft of torque. The battery was replaced in September 2021.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.
Head over to our friends at Car and Driver to check out their August 1999 Road Test for the S2000.

This 2006 Subaru Legacy GT Limited was purchased new by the seller from Manchester Subaru in Bedford, New Hampshire, and was subsequently brought to Canada and modified. It is powered by a turbocharged and intercooled 2.5-liter flat-four that is said to have been fitted with an AVO turbocharger, intercooler, and fuel pump as well as Deatschwerks fuel injectors, a COBB Tuning V2 Accessport, and aftermarket exhaust components. Power is delivered to all four wheels via a five-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip rear differential, and the car is finished in Brilliant Silver Metallic over black leather. Additional equipment includes 17″ Rays alloy wheels, an aftermarket front grille, heated and power-adjustable front seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, a short-throw shifter, and a six-disc CD changer. This modified Legacy GT has 151k miles, and is now offered in Canada with service records, a collection of magazines, three keys, spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and New Brunswick registration in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in Brilliant Silver Metallic (39D), and an aftermarket front grille has been installed. Additional details include a hood scoop, projector-style headlights, fog lights, and heated and power-adjustable side mirrors with integrated signal indicators. The seller notes that touch-up paint has been applied to blemishes on various body panels, and the right rear door handle was replaced and does not match the body color.

Silver-finished 17″ Rays Gram Lights wheels are mounted with 215/45 Bridgestone Potenza RE980AS tires. Koni adjustable struts are said to be retrofitted, and braking is provided by discs at all four corners.

The heated and power-adjustable front bucket seats are upholstered in black leather and are joined by silver-finished trim that accents the dashboard, center console, and door panels. A short-throw shifter is said to have been retrofitted, and appointments include dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, an auto-dimming rearview mirror with Homelink, and an in-dash six-disc CD changer linked with aftermarket speakers. Wear is evident on various interior surfaces.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges. Additional readouts for monitoring boost pressure, oil pressure, and oil temperature are mounted in the center stack. The digital odometer indicates 151k miles, all of which have been added under current ownership.

The turbocharged and intercooled 2.5-liter flat-four has been reportedly modified with an AVO 380 turbocharger, top-mount intercooler, and fuel pump in addition to Deatschwerks 850cc fuel injectors. The car is equipped with a Lachute tune using a COBB Tuning V2 Accessport, and dynamometer test results can be viewed in the gallery below. The timing belt and tensioner were replaced in January 2020, and the seller notes that the check engine light illuminates intermittently.

Power is sent to all four wheels via a five-speed manual transaxle, an all-wheel-drive system, and a limited-slip rear differential. A Lachute performance exhaust system is fitted that utilizes the factory mufflers.
Service records, rubberized floor liners, a collection of magazines, three keys, and spare parts are included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of any accidents or other reported damage.
The car does not have a title and is being sold on its New Brunswick registration, which serves as the ownership document in New Brunswick, Canada.

This 1987 BMW 325i convertible spent time in New York, New Jersey, and North Carolina before it was purchased by the seller in 2009, and it is powered by a 2.5-liter inline-six paired with a replacement five-speed manual gearbox that was installed in 2010. Refinished in gray over a black and red interior, the car also features a limited-slip differential, a replacement black soft top, 14″ OZ wheels, and an aftermarket cassette stereo. Service under current ownership is said to have involved converting the air conditioning system to utilize R134a refrigerant as well as replacing the timing belt, water pump, clutch, suspension components, and more as detailed below. This E30 convertible is offered at no reserve with a seller-provided maintenance log and a clean Pennsylvania title in the seller’s name.

The car was repainted in gray in 2005, while a replacement black soft top was installed in 2018 and the windshield was replaced within the past year. Additional exterior details include a power antenna, body-color mirror caps, white pinstripes, and quadruple headlights. Photos show dents on the right-rear quarter panel and the doors.

OZ 14″ alloy wheels are mounted with 195/70 Kumho Solus TA11 tires. The car is equipped with an independent suspension and power-assisted four-wheel disc brakes with ventilated front rotors. The seller states that the front wheel hub assemblies were replaced in 2019 along with the front struts and rear shock absorbers, while the front brake pads, coil springs, and spring insulators were changed in 2024.

According to the seller, the black cloth-upholstered and heated Corbeau front bucket seats were fitted in 2018, at which time the air conditioning system was converted to utilize R134a refrigerant. The rear bench seat is trimmed in red and black, and color-coordinated trim is visible throughout the cabin. Appointments include an onboard computer, cruise control, and a Sony cassette stereo along with power windows, door locks, and mirrors. The seller notes that the driver-side door lock needs to be rebuilt but that the locking mechanisms for the vehicle work otherwise.

The three-spoke steering wheel wears an aftermarket wrap and frames a 150-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges. The six-digit odometer shows 151k miles, though the seller does not believe it is accurate and the odometer gears were replaced in 2024. Total mileage is unknown.

The 2.5-liter M20 inline-six features Bosch fuel injection and was factory rated at 168 horsepower and 164 lb-ft of torque. Maintenance under current ownership is said to have included installing a replacement oxygen sensor in 2014 and a replacement radiator in 2017, changing the ignition wires in 2018, and fitting replacement radiator hoses and rebuilding the stater motor in 2020, while service within the past year reportedly involved replacing the following components:
The seller notes hesitation under acceleration when the engine is cold.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a replacement five-speed manual gearbox that was installed in 2010 as well as a factory-optional limited-slip differential. The seller states that the clutch, pressure plate, and throwout bearing were replaced in 2016, a replacement differential mount and rear subframe mounts were fitted in 2017, and the clutch slave cylinder was changed in 2020.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists history in New York, New Jersey, North Carolina, and Pennsylvania.

This 1945 Allis-Chalmers WC tractor was refurbished under prior ownership and purchased by the seller in 2023. The tractor is finished in orange with matching wheels, and power is from a gasoline-fueled 201ci inline-four paired with a four-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes a silver exhaust stack, headlights, rear half fenders, a side-mounted belt pulley, a pin hitch, and a rear power take-off.  This Model WC is now offered at no reserve in Wisconsin with a bill of sale.

The Allis-Chalmers WC tractor was introduced in 1933, and designer Brooks Stevens oversaw styling updates that debuted in 1938. This “styled” example is said to have been refinished in orange under prior ownership and has streamlined sheet metal compared to pre-1938 models. Details include a mesh grille, a silver exhaust stack, headlights, rear half fenders, and Allis-Chalmers graphics.

The steel wheels are painted orange up front, while the rear wheels have silver rims with orange centers. They are mounted with 5.50-16″ Super Hi-Rib front and 12.4-28″ Armstrong Hi-Traction Lug rear tires. Braking is handled by independent rear drums, and the tractor is equipped with a narrow–track front axle. The seller notes leaks in the front axle assembly and rear hubs.

The operator’s station features a steel seat suspended on a flat spring. Controls include a hand throttle, a transmission output shaft disconnect lever, a foot pedal for the engine clutch, a shifter, and dual levers for the individual rear brakes.

The three-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of a body-color instrument panel that houses an ammeter, and a coolant temperature gauge is recessed within the engine cover. The tractor is not equipped with an hour meter, therefore total runtime is unknown.
The gasoline-fueled 201ci inline-four sends power to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission.
The tractor is equipped with a pin hitch, a rear power take-off shaft, and a side-mounted accessory belt pulley.

This 1976 Porsche 911 is a RoW coupe that was acquired by the seller’s father in 1991, and it is powered by a 2.7-liter flat-six mated to a five-speed manual transaxle. The car is finished in Guards Red over black leatherette upholstery, and equipment includes 15″ cookie-cutter alloy wheels, fog lights, body-color bumpers, front bucket seats, air conditioning, and a heated rear window. The engine was rebuilt in 2014, while more recent work since 2023 involved replacing the tires, recharging the air conditioning system, and replacing the fuel pump and ignition components. This mid-year 911 is now offered by the seller on behalf of their father with service records and a clean Alabama title.

The car was finished from the factory in Guards Red (027) and features US-spec headlight trim rings, fog lights, and body-color impact bumpers. The front windshield seal was replaced in 2024. There is a dent on the left rear quarter panel, the exterior passenger door handle is broken, and the left fog light needs replacement.

The 15″ cookie-cutter alloy wheels were mounted with 205/60 BFGoodrich Advantage Control tires in 2023. A space-saver spare is stored in the front trunk. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel ventilated disc brakes.

Black leatherette upholstery covers the front bucket seats, folding rear seats, and side panels. Appointments include opening rear-quarter windows, an analog clock, air conditioning, a heated rear window, an aftermarket shift knob, and a CD stereo. The air conditioning system was recharged with R134a refrigerant in 2023. The seller notes that the radio and speakers could use tuning.

The three-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of VDO instrumentation that consists of a 150-mph speedometer, a centrally mounted tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, oil level, oil temperature, and oil pressure. The five-digit odometer is inoperative and shows 60k miles, with 100 miles of which are said to have been added since the 2014 engine rebuild. Total mileage is unknown. The fuel level gauge is not accurate.

The 2.7-liter flat-six features Bosch K-Jetronic fuel injection and was rebuilt in 2014. The CDI ignition control box was replaced in 2015, the fuel pump and lines were replaced in 2023, and work in 2024 consisted of replacing the spark plugs, ignition wires, and distributor cap and rotor. The seller states that the car smokes after sitting for approximately a week, and the hood cannot stay up on its own. Replacement hood struts will accompany the car.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle.

This 1981 Chevrolet Corvette was reportedly acquired new by the owner’s father and was inherited by the seller in 2014. Subsequent work consisted of rebuilding the engine, overhauling the transmission, and replacing the clutch and suspension and brake components. Power is provided by a 350ci L81 V8 paired with a four-speed manual transmission and the car is finished in beige over camel leather upholstery. Equipment includes a Positraction differential, 15″ eight-slot alloy wheels, removable glass roof panels, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, an Alpine CD stereo, power windows, and air conditioning. This C3 Corvette is now offered on dealer consignment with a roof panel carrier, an engine dynamometer sheet, recent service records, and a clean Washington state title.

The car is finished in beige and features removable glass T-top roof panels, pop-up headlights, side marker lights, fender air vents, sport mirrors, and quad taillights. The rear panel has been fitted with grommets to hold the T-top roof panels.

The 15″ eight-slot alloy wheels are mounted with 225/70 R15 BFGoodrich Radial T/A white-letter tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel power-assisted discs. Work in 2023 is said to consist of replacing the power booster and brake master cylinder.

The cabin features bucket seats trimmed in camel leather along with a color-matching dash, center console, door panels, and carpeting. Interior amenities include a power-adjustable driver’s seat, power windows, a tilting steering column, air conditioning, and an Alpine CD stereo with Bluetooth capability and a microphone.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames an 85-mph speedometer and a 7k-rpm tachometer. Gauges for coolant temperature, oil temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level are located in the center stack. The five-digit odometer shows 43k miles, although a 2015 Carfax service entry notes 132k miles.
The 350ci L81 V8 was rebuilt in January 2014 at Preston’s Automotive in Redmond, Washington. An engine build invoice and a 2014 engine dynamometer result sheet are displayed in the gallery.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission and a Positraction differential. The transmission is said to have been rebuilt and a replacement clutch was fitted in 2014.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 1981 Triumph TR8 convertible has been refinished in blue metallic over tan leather and is powered by a 3.5-liter V8 linked with a five-speed manual transmission and a Quaife differential. It is equipped with a MegaSquirt 3 ECU, a MagnaFlow exhaust system, Spax adjustable dampers, four-wheel disc brakes, power steering, 15″ Rota wheels, a tan soft top and top boot, pop-up headlights, LED exterior lights, a RetroSound vintage-look stereo, and Rockford Fosgate speakers. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this TR8 convertible is offered in Oregon with manufacturer’s literature, service records, and a black hardtop with a rolling stand as well as a clean Carfax report and a Washington title.

The car was finished from the factory in Argent Silver Metallic (MCB) and repainted blue metallic under previous ownership. Exterior details include a tan convertible soft top and a forward-hinged hood with functional louvers as well as a front spoiler, Euro-style bumpers, and LED pop-up headlights, fog lights, and taillights. The selling dealer notes fisheyes in the paint on the trunk lid.

The 15″ Rota wheels are mounted with 205/50 Kumho Ecsta PA31 tires. The car was factory equipped with power-assisted rack-and-pinion steering as well as anti-roll bars and an independent front suspension. Spax adjustable dampers have been fitted along with larger disc brakes and Wilwood calipers up front and discs in the rear.

The replacement bucket seats are upholstered in tan leather, and color-coordinated upholstery covers the center console and door panels. Interior appointments include three-point seatbelts, CocoMats floor mats, a locking glovebox, a cabin heater, a rear parcel shelf, a RetroSound vintage-look stereo, and Rockford Fosgate speakers. The air conditioning system has been removed.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames Smiths instrumentation consisting of a 140-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, an analog clock, and gauges for coolant temperature, voltage, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 87k miles. The selling dealer notes that the total mileage is unknown.

The fuel-injected 3.5-liter Rover V8 features an electronic ignition and was rebuilt in 2017. Additional equipment includes a Rover intake manifold, a MegaSquirt 3 ECU, LS2 ignition coils, and aftermarket exhaust headers.

Power is routed to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission that has been fitted with a Centerforce clutch as well as a Quaife differential. The car is equipped with a MagnaFlow dual exhaust system.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.
The “not the actual mileage” box is checked on the current Washington title.

This 2011 Rolls-Royce Ghost is finished in black over tan leather upholstery and is powered by a 6.6-liter V12 paired with an eight-speed automatic transmission. It is equipped with a panoramic sunroof, soft-close doors, electronic variable damping, and 20″ wheels with self-leveling center caps along with heated, ventilated, and power-adjustable front and rear seats. Other features include a 16-speaker sound system, a 10.2″ navigation display, a rear-seat entertainment system, a rear beverage compartment, a surround camera system, a head-up display, night vision, and active cruise control. The car was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024 and now has 26k miles. This Ghost is offered with recent service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Arizona title.

The car is finished in black and has been fitted with a silver vinyl wrap that covers part of the front valance, hood, and windshield surround. Exterior features include a power-retractable Spirit of Ecstasy ornament, a panoramic sunroof, soft-close doors, tinted windows, parking sensors, and auto-leveling xenon headlights with high-beam assist. The windshield was replaced in 2022.

Fitted with self-leveling center caps, the 20″ wheels are mounted with 255/45 front and 285/40 rear Pirelli P Zero tires. The four-wheel disc brakes feature a four-channel anti-lock system, and the car is equipped with electronic Variable Damping Control (VDC) and self-leveling air springs with anti-roll stabilization. The brake fluid was flushed in November 2023.

The heated, ventilated, and power-adjustable front and rear seats are trimmed in tan leather with Rolls-Royce headrest logos, and they are complemented by wood trim on the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Amenities include a massaging front seats, 16-speaker audio system, four-zone climate control, and a 10.2″ navigation display.

Accessed via electronically regulated coach doors with power closing assistance and umbrella holders, the rear cabin features massaging seats, an entertainment system with screens, fold-out tray tables, and a beverage compartment between the seats.

A leather-trimmed steering wheel faces the driver, and white-dial instrumentation includes a 160-mph speedometer, a reverse-sweep power reserve meter, gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature, and a digital display. The odometer indicates 26k miles. The driver is aided by night vision, a surround camera system, a head-up display, and active cruise control.

Factory rated at 563 horsepower and 575 lb-ft of torque, the 48-valve aluminum 6.6-liter V12 sends power to the rear wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission. Service in November 2023 included an oil change and replacement of the battery, cabin filter, and spark plugs.
Additional photographs of the underside are shown in the gallery below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2023 Chevrolet Corvette Z06 convertible is a 70th Anniversary Edition example that was optioned from the factory with the Z07 Performance Package, the 3LZ Equipment Group, carbon-fiber interior trim, and the Carbon Fiber Aero Package, which added a carbon-fiber high wing, front dive planes, and ground effects. Finished in White Pearl Metallic Tricoat with Satin Matrix Gray racing stripes over Ceramic White and Jet Black leather upholstery, it is powered by a 5.5-liter LT6 V8 paired with an eight-speed dual-clutch automatic transaxle. The car has an electronic limited-slip differential, a front-axle lift system, a power-retractable hardtop, LED headlights, 20″ and 21″ forged aluminum wheels, a Z07 suspension, and Brembo carbon-ceramic brakes as well as heated and ventilated power-adjustable Competition Sport bucket seats, a Bose sound system, front and rear cameras, and a touchscreen infotainment system. Purchased new by the seller at Stingray Chevrolet of Plant City, Florida, and previously listed on BaT in June 2024, this C8 Z06 has 9 miles and is offered again with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a build sheet, spare parts, two keys, and a clean Wisconsin title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in White Pearl Metallic Tricoat with Satin Matrix Gray racing stripes and the Carbon Fiber Aero Package, which added a carbon-fiber high wing, front dive planes, and ground effects. Exterior details include a power-retractable hardtop, LED headlights, 70th Anniversary badging, side air intakes, and rear parking sensors. Driver-assist systems include rear cross-traffic alert, blind-spot monitoring, and front and rear cameras.

The 20″ and 21″ forged aluminum wheels feature a red accent stripe as well as 70th Anniversary Edition center caps and are mounted with 275/30 front and 345/25 rear Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2R tires. Stopping power is provided by red-painted Brembo calipers fitted over ventilated carbon-ceramic rotors at each corner. The car is equipped with a front-axle lift system and a Z07 suspension.

The heated, ventilated, and power-adjustable Competition Sport bucket seats are trimmed in Ceramic White and Jet Black leather with Corvette logos on the headrests, Torch Red seatbelts, and red stitching that extends to the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Carbon-fiber trim accents the cabin, and additional appointments include a head-up display, the Stealth Interior Trim Package, a Bose sound system, remote start, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, and an 8″ touchscreen with Chevrolet Infotainment 3.

The heated carbon-fiber- and microsuede-trimmed steering wheel frames a multifunction display that includes a central tachometer and auxiliary readouts for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 9 miles.

The mid-mounted 5.5-liter LT6 V8 features a flat-plane crankshaft and was factory rated at 670 horsepower and 460 lb-ft of torque. The car came equipped from the factory with a performance exhaust with driver-selectable modes. Power is routed to the rear wheels via a Tremec TR-9080 eight-speed dual-clutch automatic transaxle and an electronic limited-slip differential.

The window sticker lists initial delivery to Stingray Chevrolet of Plant City, Florida, along with factory colors, equipment, options, and a total vehicle price of $165,605. A build sheet, spare parts, and two keys are included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

description: This 1975 Pontiac Firebird Trans Am is powered by a high-output 455ci V8 linked with a four-speed manual transmission and a Safe-T-Track limited-slip differential and is finished in Buccaneer Red with a black and orange Trans Am hood decal. Equipment includes 15″ honeycomb-style wheels, power front disc brakes and steering, front and rear spoilers, a Shaker hood, and fender air extractors. The cabin is trimmed in black vinyl upholstery and fitted with a Kenwood cassette stereo, a Hurst shifter, engine-turned dashboard trim, and air conditioning. Acquired by the current owner in 2024, this Trans Am is offered in Delaware on dealer consignment with a clean Texas title.

The car is finished in Buccaneer Red (75) with an orange and black Trans Am decal on the hood. Exterior equipment includes a front air dam, front fender air extractors, a Shaker hood, a rear spoiler, and body-color mirror caps. Close-up photos of the paint, finish, and imperfections are provided in the gallery.

Silver-finished 15″ honeycomb-style wheels are mounted with 235/70 Cooper Cobra Radial G/T tires. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The seating surfaces are trimmed in black vinyl, which extends to the dashboard and door panels. Amenities include a Hurst shifter, a period Kenwood cassette stereo, and air conditioning. The dashboard is cracked and the passenger seat bottom is torn.

The leather-wrapped Formula steering wheel sits ahead of an engine-turned instrument panel housing a 100-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, an analog clock, and gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and voltage. The five-digit odometer shows 35k miles, approximately 200 of which were added under current ownership.
The 455ci L75 V8 was factory rated at 200 horsepower and 330 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission and a Safe-T-Track limited-slip differential. Long-tube headers flow to a dual exhaust system.
Decoding the trim tag reveals the following information:

This 1975 AMC Pacer is finished in green apple over brown upholstery with patterned inserts and is powered by a 258ci inline-six paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. Chrome bumpers are fitted along with power steering, chrome 14″ moon-style wheels, front disc brakes, a locking fuel cap, and a heater. The car spent time in Arkansas before being acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. This Pacer is now offered in Kansas at no reserve with a clean Arkansas title.

The car is finished in green apple and details include a fender-mounted antenna, a locking fuel cap, a polished exhaust finisher, chrome door handles, and chrome bumpers with rubber guards. The reverse lights do not work, and areas of corrosion and paint blemishes are displayed in the gallery.
Chrome 14″ moon-style wheels are wrapped in 185/70 Doral SDL-Sport tires. The car is equipped with power-assisted steering and braking is handled by front discs and rear drums.
The seating surfaces are trimmed brown vinyl with patterned cloth inserts. Equipment includes hand-crank windows, a locking glovebox, and a heater. The radio is inoperative.

A two-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of a 90-mph speedometer, a fuel-level gauge, and a gear indicator for the column-mounted shifter. The five-digit odometer shows 48k miles, approximately 50 of which were added by the seller.
The 258ci inline-six is equipped with a single-barrel carburetor and was factory rated at 100 horsepower. The seller notes that the power steering system leaks fluid.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission. Corrosion is visible on underbody components including the driver’s area floorboard.
listing_details: Brown Leather Upholstery with Patterned Inserts

description: This 1983 Honda V45 Interceptor is said to have remained with a single owner in California from new until the seller’s October 2022 acquisition. Finished in a white, blue, and red livery, the motorcycle is equipped with a liquid-cooled 748cc DOHC V4 mated to a five-speed transmission. Equipment includes a quarter fairing, a lower cowl, a tinted windscreen, a two-up seat, a TRAC anti-dive fork, dual two-into-two exhausts, chrome engine guards, triple disc brakes, staggered-diameter D.I.D alloy wheels, rear-set foot controls, and both side and center stands. Maintenance under current ownership is said to have involved replacing the battery and the carburetor crossover tubes as well as cleaning the four Keihin carburetors. This VF750F shows 9k miles and is offered at no reserve with an owner’s manual, a service manual, a tool kit, a period brochure, and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The bodywork is finished in a white, blue, and red livery and mounted over a silver-finished double-cradle boxed steel frame. Equipment includes a quarter fairing, a tinted windscreen, a two-up seat, rear-set foot controls, passenger grab handles, chrome engine guards, dual mirrors, folding passenger foot pegs, and both center and side stands as well as a 5.8-gallon fuel tank with a recessed integrated petcock control.

Six-spoke ComCast alloy wheels measuring 16″ up front and 18″ out back are mounted with Dunlop tires. Suspension consists of a telescopic TRAC anti-dive fork in addition to a monoshock attached to the swingarm. The triple disc brakes feature twin-piston sliding calipers and slotted rotors.

Black-finished clip-on handlebars are mounted above the upper triple clamp, and the instrument panel ahead houses a 150-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 10,500-rpm redline, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 9k miles, approximately 20 of which were ridden by the seller.

The liquid-cooled 748cc DOHC V4 is equipped with an electric starter, dual radiators, electric cooling fans, and twin two-into-one exhausts with megaphone-style mufflers. Factory-rated output was 86 horsepower and 46 lb-ft of torque. Maintenance in preparation for the sale reportedly included changing the oil, replacing the battery and the carburetor crossover tubes, and cleaning the four 30mm Keihin carburetors. Photos showing the condition of the camshaft lobes can be viewed in the gallery below.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a hydraulically actuated clutch, a five-speed transmission, and a drive chain.
A tool kit is included in the sale along with an owner’s manual, a service manual, and a period brochure.

This 1997 Jeep Grand Cherokee Orvis Edition example reportedly spent time with a single owner prior to the seller’s acquisition in 2024. Finished in Moss Green over green and tan leather upholstery, the truck is powered by a 5.2-liter V8 linked with a four-speed automatic transmission and a Quadra-Trac Full-Time 4WD transfer case. Equipment includes a power sunroof, a receiver hitch, 16″ alloy wheels, anti-lock brakes, air conditioning, cruise control, power accessories, an Infinity Gold speaker system, and a CD/cassette stereo. This Grand Cherokee is now offered at no reserve in Canada with the manufacturer’s literature, service records, a Canadian Carfax report, and a British Columbia registration.

The Orvis trim package was created in partnership with the Vermont-based apparel and sporting goods company, and this example is finished in Moss Green with two-tone pinstripes along with Orvis and gold-tone badging. Exterior details include fog lights, dual power-adjustable mirrors, roof-rack crossbars, tinted rear windows, a rear window wiper, and a hitch receiver. The seller notes that the rear window wiper requires adjustment.

Machined alloy 16″ wheels with green-finished accents are mounted with 225/70 General Altimax RT tires. Orvis Edition examples were equipped with the Up Country Suspension Group, which also added tow hooks and skid plates. Braking is provided by four-wheel discs with ABS. The seller notes that the brakes squeal intermittently and that the front bump stops have fallen out.

The power-adjustable front seats as well as the split-folding rear bench are upholstered in Dark Green leather with Champagne trim and Roan Red piping. Woodgrain panels with Orvis branding accent the cabin, which is further appointed with automatic climate control, Orvis-branded carpeted floor mats, power windows and locks, an Infinity Gold speaker system, and a CD/cassette stereo. The seller notes that the right front power door lock does not work at times and the blower motor fan is loud when operating.

The three-spoke steering wheel is equipped with cruise-control buttons and it frames a 120-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, voltage, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The oil pressure gauge works intermittently. The digital odometer indicates 57k kilometers (~35k miles), approximately 170 of which were added under current ownership. A potential odometer rollback is listed in a 2011 Carfax report entry.
The 5.2-liter V8 was factory rated at 220 horsepower and 300 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in April 2024. The seller recommends that an engine tune-up service be performed.
Power is routed to all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a Quadra-Trac dual-range transfer case
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists the aforementioned potential odometer rollback.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada

This 1997 Porsche Boxster spent time in New York and was sold by the selling dealer on BaT in November 2022 before being reacquired in 2024. Now showing 49k miles, it is finished in black over black leather and is powered by a 2.5-liter flat-six paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes a black soft top, 17″ Carrera-look alloy wheels, a speed-activated rear spoiler, automatic climate control, power windows, and a Kenwood stereo. Work in October 2023 included an IMS bearing service and replacing the rear main seal and clutch. This 986 Boxster is offered by the selling dealer with spare parts, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New York title.

The car is finished in black with a black soft top. Exterior details include heated power-adjustable side mirrors, side air intakes, roll hoops, and a speed-activated rear spoiler. Close-up photos presented in the gallery show wear on the soft top, scratches on the underside of the front bumper cover, and paint meter readings from around the car.

Carrera-look 17″ twist-spoke alloy wheels with black centers wear full-color Porsche crest center caps and are mounted with 205/50 front and 225/40 rear General G-Max tires. Braking is handled by four-piston Porsche-branded calipers fitted over a ventilated rotor at each corner.

The power-adjustable bucket seats are upholstered in black leather complemented by a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Appointments include automatic climate control, power windows, stainless-steel sill plates, and a Bluetooth-capable Kenwood stereo.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a central tachometer, a 160-mph speedometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 49k miles.

The mid-mounted 2.5-liter M96 flat-six was factory rated at 201 horsepower and 181 lb-ft of torque. Work in October 2023 consisted of changing the oil and replacing the IMS bearing and rear main seal.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle. The clutch was replaced in October 2023.
