The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists history in New York and Arizona.

This 1927 Erskine Model 50 coupe was reportedly sold new in California, and it was purchased by the seller’s father and grandfather in 1966 before undergoing a refurbishment that was performed between 1979 and 2004. The car is finished in metallic blue over gray cloth upholstery, and power comes from a Continental 146ci inline-six paired with a three-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes an electric starter, four-wheel mechanical drum brakes, 20″ wood-spoke wheels, a spare rim, a Boyce MotoMeter radiator cap, wind wings, and a rumble seat. This Erskine Model 50 is now offered by the seller on behalf of his father with an owner’s manual, literature, and a clean California title in the seller’s father’s name that lists the car as a 1927 Studebaker.

Studebaker Corporation president Albert Russel Erskine sought to develop a short-wheelbase, entry-level model to expand the company’s footprint in European markets. His eponymous marque was launched at the Grand Palais in Paris, France, in 1927, and featured coupe, sedan, and touring models with styling by Raymond Dietrich. Marketed as ” The Little Aristocrat,” Erskine models were offered through 1930, when the marque was absorbed by Studebaker. This example has been repainted blue and features front and rear bumpers, a Boyce MotoMeter radiator cap, running boards, wind wings, a black roof panel, and a single taillight. Imperfections in the finish are noted by the seller.

The wood-spoke wheels feature body-color hubs and rims, and they are mounted with 4.75-5.00–20 Firestone bias-ply tires. A black-painted spare rim with a Pullmore tire is mounted out back. The Model 50 rode on a 108″ wheelbase and featured solid axles with semi-elliptical leaf springs. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel mechanical drum brakes.
The cabin features a bench seat trimmed in gray cloth along with a color-matched headliner, door panels, and carpets.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel fronts a painted steel dash housing a Stewart-Warner 75-mph barrel speedometer and gauges for amperage, oil pressure, fuel level, and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 66k miles, approximately 1k of which were added under current ownership.
The rumble seat features matching gray cloth upholstery.

The 146ci inline-six was built for Erskine by the Continental Motors Company, and it was factory rated at 40 horsepower. An electric starter was installed prior to 1966, and the ignition points and distributor were serviced in 2019.
The car is titled by its engine number 8F13104.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a three-speed manual transmission.

This 2021 Mercedes-Benz Sprinter 2500 4×4 was outfitted as a camper by Winnebago Industries before it was acquired by the seller in 2022. The van is finished in gray over black vinyl upholstery and is powered by a 3.0-liter turbodiesel V6 mated to a seven-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Equipment includes swiveling front seats, a suspended Power Lift bed platform, a kitchenette, a wet bath, privacy shades, and a workspace with a removable work surface as well as a Canyon Adventure Vans storage system, 17″ Method alloy wheels, roof-mounted solar panel and air conditioning units, and a power-operated awning. A full-size spare, a ladder, a locking storage box, and bike racks are fitted to the rear barn doors. This Sprinter has 31k miles and is now offered with an accident-free Carfax report and a clean South Carolina title.

The extended-height body is finished in gray with Revel graphics. The van features a sliding side door, rear barn doors, a power-operated awning, a roof rack, a roof-mounted air conditioner, rooftop solar panels, running boards, a receiver step, front and rear parking sensors, and shore hookups for water and power. A ladder, a locking storage box, and bike racks are mounted to the rear doors.

Method 17″ wheels are mounted with 245/70 BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A KO2 tires, and a matching spare is mounted to the rear ladder. The truck was factory-equipped with electronic stability and traction control, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes.

The power-adjustable front seats are upholstered in black vinyl, and carbon-look trim accents the dashboard and doors. Appointments include air conditioning, Weathertech floor liners, cruise control, and a factory audio system.

The multifunction steering wheel frames a 130-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and a central information display. The digital odometer indicates 31k miles, approximately 10k of which were added under current ownership.

The living quarters are outfitted with a sink, a microwave, a Nova Kool refrigerator, storage cabinets, and a countertop with a cutting board. A bench seat and a swiveling table are fitted behind the driver’s seat, and a system panel with controls for the heater, solar charger, power systems, and holding tanks. A wet bath with a cassette toilet sits behind a sliding door.

The rear compartment features a Canyon Adventure Vans GLSS storage and seating system as well as an upgraded Luxe6 cool gel memory foam mattress, a Power Lift bed platform, a swiveling table, a water tank control panel, a storage bag, and a partition screen.
The 3.0-liter BlueTec turbodiesel V6 was factory rated at 188 horsepower and 325 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case.

The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage as well as at least one manufacturer recall. There is a lien on the truck, and the seller’s lender will need to be paid off before the title can be transferred to the buyer.

This 2005 Chrysler Crossfire Limited Roadster has 40k miles following registration history in Pennsylvania. Finished in Blaze Red Crystal Pearl Coat over Dark Slate Gray leather, the car is powered by a 3.2-liter V6 paired with a six-speed manual transmission. Features include a black convertible soft top, staggered-diameter seven-spoke alloy wheels, a speed-activated rear spoiler, fog lights, heated power-adjustable seats, a Sony CD stereo, dual-zone climate control, and cruise control. This Crossfire is now offered in Florida by the selling dealer at no reserve with the owner’s manual and a Pennsylvania title.

The Crossfire shared its platform with the Mercedes-Benz R170 SLK, and this example is finished in Blaze Red Crystal Pearl Coat. It is equipped with a power-operated black soft top that stows beneath a body-color top boot. Additional exterior details include a speed-activated rear spoiler, projector headlights, fog lights, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, a straked hood, fender vents, and dual center exhaust outlets. The Carfax report lists “minor damage” to the rear in a September 2018 entry, and the selling dealer indicates that the rear bumper cover was repainted under prior ownership. Photos showing paint-meter readings are included in the gallery.

The 18″ and 19″ seven-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact DWS 06 tires. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes. The car is equipped with a touring suspension, electronic stability control, and traction control.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable seats trimmed in Dark Slate Gray leather, while silver-color trim accents the center stack. Amenities include a Sony CD stereo, dual-zone climate control, and cruise control.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 40k miles.

The SOHC 3.2-liter M112 V6 was sourced from Mercedes-Benz and was rated at 215 horsepower and 229 lb-ft of torque. The thermostat was replaced in December 2021, the air and cabin filters were replaced in July 2023, and the oil was changed in July 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transmission.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage.
listing_details: Blaze Red Crystal Pearl Coat Paint

description: This 1964 MGB Roadster was campaigned as an E/P racer in the Corinthian Vintage Auto Racing (CVAR) circuit from 1997 to 2020 and was acquired by the seller as a non-running project in 2022. The replacement 1.8-liter inline-four was installed under current ownership and features County pistons, a 719 camshaft, a Vernier cam gear, a mildly ported cylinder head, dual SU carburetors, and an LCB header. The car is finished in blue with white stripes and additional equipment includes a four-speed manual transmission, a modified suspension, front disc brakes, 14″ alloy wheels, Nitto NT-01 tires, a low-profile polycarbonate windshield, a roll cage, a fixed-back racing seat, a five-point harness, an electrical cut-off switch, and a fuel cell. This MGB is offered at no reserve with a 2024 CVAR log book and a clean Texas title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in blue with black accents and white over-the-top stripes and numbers. Exterior details include early-style “pull” door handles, front and rear tow points, deleted headlights, hood pins, a low-profile tinted polycarbonate windscreen, and a bullet-style driver mirror. Blemishes in the paint and repaired race damage are viewable in the gallery.

Polished 14″ slotted aluminum wheels are mounted with 205/55 Nitto NT-01 tires that are recommended for competition use only. The suspension is modified with heavy-duty front springs, drop spindles, front and rear sway bars, and a Panhard bar. Braking is provided by front discs and rear drums.

The stripped cockpit houses a single fixed-back racing seat upholstered in black vinyl and cloth. Appointments include a roll cage, a Speedway Motors five-point harness, a convex rearview mirror, and an electrical cut-off switch. The pictured fire extinguisher does not accompany the car.
The steering wheel fronts an 8k-rpm tachometer and auxiliary gauges. The 120-mph speedometer and the five-digit odometer are disconnected and true mileage is unknown.
The trunk houses a fuel cell, a Holley electric fuel pump, and the mechanism for the electrical cut-off switch.

The replacement 1.8-liter inline-four was installed under current ownership. The cylinders are bored .020 over and the cylinder head received mild porting work, a three-angle valve job, and dual race valve springs. Additional features include County pistons, a 719 camshaft, a Vernier cam gear, twin SU carburetors, K&N air cleaners, and an LCB header. The seller states the compression is approximately 10:1 and conventional premium fuel can be used.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through an aluminum flywheel, a four-speed manual transmission, and an open differential with 4.30:1 gearing.

This 2013 BMW M3 convertible is a Jerez Black Metallic-finished example that has 42k miles and was optioned from the factory with the Premium Package. Powered by a 4.0-liter V8 paired with a seven-speed dual-clutch transmission, the car has a Dinan exhaust system, Palladium Silver and black Novillo leather upholstery, 19″ forged Style 220 wheels, a limited-slip differential, adaptive xenon headlights, a retractable hardtop, rear parking sensors, heated power-adjustable front seats, iDrive with navigation, dual-zone automatic climate control, and cruise control. This E93 M3 was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024 and is now offered with a clean Carfax report and a clean California title.
The car is finished in Jerez Black Metallic and has a retractable hardtop and adaptive xenon headlights as well as rain-sensing wipers, rear parking sensors, and quadruple exhaust outlets.

Forged 19″ Style 220 wheels are mounted with 245/35 front and 265/35 rear Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires showing 2021 date codes. The car features Dynamic Stability Control (DSC), and braking is handled by four-wheel vented and cross-drilled discs measuring 14.2″ and 13.8″ front and rear, respectively.

The heated power-adjustable front sport seats are upholstered in Palladium Silver and black Novillo leather, and Carbon Structure Leather trim accents the dashboard and doors. Appointments include iDrive with navigation, Comfort Access keyless entry, a CD stereo, dual-zone automatic climate control, M3-branded floor mats, and cruise control. The driver’s seat outer bolster is worn.

The multi-function leather-wrapped steering wheel features paddle shifters along with tri-color stitching and frames an M-branded tachometer, a 200-mph speedometer, a central information display, and gauges for oil temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 42k miles, approximately 1,200 of which were added under current ownership.

The 4.0-liter S65 V8 features double-VANOS variable valve timing and was factory rated at 414 horsepower and 295 lb-ft of torque. The car passed an emissions inspection in August 2023, and an oil change was performed in May 2024.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed M-DCT dual-clutch transmission and a Variable M Differential Lock. A Dinan exhaust system has been fitted, and additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
listing_details: Palladium Silver and Black Novillo Leather Upholstery

description: This 1954 Sunbeam Alpine is powered by a 2,267cc inline-four paired with a floor-shifted four-speed manual transmission, and it underwent a cosmetic refurbishment circa 2004 that included a repaint in metallic gray over a reupholstered red leather interior. The car was purchased by the current owner in January 2020, and subsequent service has involved machining the cylinder head, rebuilding the generator and the heater box, repairing and polishing the beltline trim, and replacing the clutch assembly, water pump, voltage regulator, wheel cylinders, engine mounts, tachometer cable, and tires. Additional equipment includes a black convertible top, 16″ ventilated steel wheels, hubcaps, four-wheel drum brakes, independent front suspension, Lucas driving lamps, a spotlight, and a USB charger port. This Alpine Mk I is now offered on dealer consignment with service records from current ownership, detachable side windows, a tonneau cover, tire-changing tools, a can of paint, owner’s and workshop manuals, a parts catalog, Alpine literature, and a Pennsylvania title in the owner’s name.

The hand-fabricated Mulliners body was refinished in metallic gray under previous ownership. Exterior details include chrome bumpers with overriders, amber-lens Lucas driving lamps, an 18″ badge bar, a louvered hood, fender-mounted dual side mirrors, and chrome external trunk hinges. The stainless-steel beltline trim was repaired and polished in May 2021. Paint cracks on the lower-left trunk lid are shown in the seller’s walk-around video provided below.

Body-color 16″ ventilated steel wheels wearing chrome hubcaps with Sunbeam crests are mounted with Coker Classic tires showing 2018 date codes, and a spare is stowed in a hatch below the trunk. Suspension consists of independent coil springs up front, semi-elliptic leaf springs out back, and Armstrong lever-type shocks at all four corners. Stopping power is provided by twin leading-shoe finned drum brakes that had all six wheel cylinders replaced in August 2023.
The car is fitted with a black canvas soft top. Detachable sliding side windows and a black canvas tonneau cover are included in the sale.

The seats are trimmed in red leather that extends to the dash pad, door panels, center armrest, cockpit collar, and shifter boot. The tan carpeting is overlaid with brown and tan Coco-type mats. The heater box was rebuilt and repainted in May 2021, and additional interior details include a dash-mounted rearview mirror and a USB charger port that was installed in July 2020.

The ivory-colored banjo-style steering wheel fronts an arching 120-mph AC speedometer set in a body-color dash and flanked by gauges for fuel level, coolant temperature, amperage, and oil pressure. A 6k-rpm AC tachometer is mounted centrally on the bottom edge of the dash. The five-digit odometer shows 11k miles, approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership. True mileage is unknown.

The 2,267cc inline-four was rated at 80 horsepower when new and features a high-compression cylinder head that was resurfaced in July 2020. Additional equipment includes a downdraft carburetor, an Arthur Gould Rebuilders water pump, and replacement engine mounts. The generator was rebuilt in June 2024, and the oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a replacement clutch and a four-speed manual transmission that was rebuilt in June 2023.

In addition to the aforementioned detachable side windows and black canvas tonneau cover, the car is accompanied by the owner’s service records, a pint can of touch-up paint, tire-changing tools, owner’s and workshop manuals, a parts catalog, and additional Alpine literature.
The Pennsylvania title carries an “Antique Vehicle” brand.

This 1971 Harley-Davidson MSR-100 Baja was manufactured for AMF/Harley-Davidson by the company’s Italian subsidiary, Aermacchi. It was acquired by the seller in 2016 and was subsequently refurbish in a project that culminated in 2018. The bike is powered by a 98cc two-stroke single paired with a five-speed transmission and is finished in gloss-black accented by a matte-black center panel, white stripes, and decals. Features include a Torque Engineering exhaust system, a 120-mph speedometer, 21″ and 18″ wheels, a right-side shifter, a Ceriani fork, and dual rear shocks. This MSR-100 is now offered at no reserve in Michigan for off-road use only with a sales brochure and a bill of sale.

The 2.5-gallon fuel tank with knee indents is finished in black with orange, white, and gray AMF/Harley-Davidson graphics as well as a matte-black center panel and white stripes. The bike is equipped with a black frame that uses the engine as a stressed member as well as a black solo seat and silver-finished fenders.

Chrome rims measuring 21″ up front and 18″ at the rear are laced to hubs with drum brakes and wrapped in Shinko Golden Boy enduro-style tires. Suspension is provided by a Ceriani fork as well as a swingarm mounted with dual chrome shocks.

An aluminum adjustment knob for a friction-plate steering damper in the steering stem sits ahead of a chrome cross-braced handlebar. A 120-mph Harley-Davidson-branded VDO speedometer contains an inset five-digit odometer showing three miles. Total mileage is unknown.

The 98cc two-stroke single is equipped with an alloy cylinder and cylinder head as well as a 24mm Dell’Orto carburetor and a Torque Engineering high-mounted exhaust system. Output was rated at 12 horsepower and 9 lb-ft of torque when new. Power is sent to the rear wheel through a wide-ratio five-speed transmission that is shifted on the right as well as a drive chain.
The bike does not have a title or registration and it is being sold on a bill of sale only.
listing_details: Gloss-Black w/Matte-Black Center Panel, White Stripes, & Decals

description: This 1957 Ford Thunderbird is finished in Willow Green over matching vinyl and features with a black vinyl hardtop with porthole windows. Power is powered by a 312ci V8 paired with a three-speed Fordomatic automatic transmission. The car is equipped with 14″ wire wheels, a power-adjustable bench seat, power windows, a retro-style radio, and a heater. The car was refurbished—reportedly in 2020—and acquired by the owner in 2023. It is now offered on the owner’s behalf in with a clean South Carolina title.

The car has been repainted in the factory Willow Green. The porthole hardtop originally matched the body but was trimmed in black vinyl. The car is not equipped with a soft top, but is equipped with a Thunderbird hood emblem, shaped and chromed front and rear bumpers, fender vents, bumper-mounted auxiliary parking lights, a fixed antenna, and slanted tail fins. Fender skirts are included in the sale.
The 14″ wire wheels are mounted with Firestone whitewall tires, and stopping power is supplied by drum brakes at each corner.

The interior was overhauled during previous ownership. The power-adjustable bench seat is upholstered in Willow and Cumberland Green vinyl and is accompanied by a color-coordinated dashboard and door panels. Amenities include a heater, a modern retro-style radio, an analog clock, a floor-mounted shifter, manual windows, and a locking glovebox.
The three-spoke steering wheel frames a centrally mounted 140-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 62k miles.
The D-code 312ci Y-block V8 is topped with a four-barrel carburetor and was factory rated at 245 horsepower.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Fordomatic three-speed automatic transmission.
Decoding the data plate reveals the following production information:

This 1989 Chevrolet G20 was converted to four-wheel drive by the Pathfinder Equipment Company in California under prior ownership, and it is powered by a replacement 350ci V8 mated to a four-speed automatic transmission. Finished in gold over color-coordinated vinyl upholstery, the van is equipped with 20″ steel wheels wearing 35″ tires along with Skyjacker steering dampers, vinyl side graphics, rear window louvers, window tint, a second-row bench seat, and an Alpine touch-screen head unit. This G20 4×4 is now offered at no reserve with additional wheels and tires, spare parts, and a clean Montana title in the seller’s name.
The van is finished in gold with red, white, and black vinyl side graphics along with a sliding side door, tinted windows, and rear window louvers.

White-finished 20″ steel wheels wear 35×12.50″ Firestone Destination X/T tires. A set of turbine-style wheels with BFGoodrich Mud-Terrain tires is included in the sale. Braking is by front discs and rear drums, and dual Skyjacker steering dampers are fitted.
The individual front seats are upholstered in patterned gold vinyl, and a color-coordinated second-row bench is fitted along with tan carpets, center cupholders, and an Alpine touch-screen head unit.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames an 85-mph speedometer and auxiliary gauges. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 29k miles. Odometer readings of 95k, 104k, and 118k miles are shown on the Carfax report from 2008-2016 along with a potential odometer rollover in 2023. True mileage is unknown.

The van was factory-equipped with a 305ci V8 which was replaced with a 350ci crate engine in 2017. The oil was most recently changed in March 2023. An aftermarket exhaust system is fitted and the catalytic converter has been removed.

Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and solid front and rear axles. The transfer case and differentials were serviced in March 2023.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and the aforementioned potential odometer rollover.

This 1961 Heinkel 103 A1 was acquired by the seller in 2012 as a disassembled project, and a subsequent two-year refurbishment included rebuilding the engine, replacing the wiring harness, replacing the nosepiece, painting the frame and bodywork, and reupholstering the seat and backrest in red vinyl with black piping. It has been modified with turn signals and an HID headlight. The scooter is powered by a 175cc four-stroke single paired with a four-speed manual transmission, and additional features include an electric starter, a locking storage compartment, a 12-volt electrical system, a rear cargo rack, a clear windshield, a bar-end mirror, and a center stand. This 103 A1 is now offered at no reserve with a refurbished PAV 40 trailer, an owner’s manual, a service manual, and a Utah title in the seller’s name.

Work during the refurbishment included refinishing the frame in white, replacing the nosepiece and other body components, repairing the rear fender, and refinishing the bodywork in Jet Black with red pinstripes. The wiring loom along with the rubber gaskets and seals were replaced, a custom trailer hitch was fabricated, and turn signals and an HID headlight were fitted during the refurbishment. The aluminum was polished and other metal components were chrome-plated at that time. Equipment includes a locking storage compartment under the two-up seat, a clear windscreen, a luggage rack, and a backrest. Photos of the refurbishment process can be viewed in the gallery. The seller notes that the seat lock does not fully latch due to wear.

Steel 10″ wheels, including the rear-mounted spare, were powder-coated in Candy Apple Red and mounted with Michelin Reggae tires. The front shock was rebuilt and the rear shock was replaced during the refurbishment. Braking is handled by drums at both ends, and the shoes were replaced during the refurbishment.

The handlebar is fitted with a bar-end mirror, and it is covered by a color-coordinating shroud that houses a VDO 80-mph speedometer. The five-digit odometer shows 3k miles, approximately 800 of which were ridden by the seller. Total mileage is unknown. The gauge cluster was rebuilt and teflon control cables were fitted during the refurbishment.

The air-cooled 175cc four-stroke single is equipped with an electric starter, a 12-volt electrical system, and an exhaust system that is concealed under the rear bodywork. Work during the refurbishment included:
The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a four-speed manual transmission that is shifted from the left handgrip. The seller reports difficulty when shifting into second gear.

The PAV 40 trailer’s fiberglass bodywork was refinished in black, and the steel wheel was powder-coated Candy Apple Red during the refurbishment. The trailer is equipped with side and rear lighting, and it was rewired during the refurbishment.
An owner’s manual and a service manual are included in the sale.
The Utah title is listed as a “Corrected Title.”

This closed-cockpit race car was built by Howe Racing for Trans Am TA2-series racing events and was acquired by the current owner in 2023. It is powered by a Katech 6.2-liter LS3 V8 linked to a G-Force 101 four-speed manual transmission, and the Camaro-silhouette fiberglass bodywork is finished in a blue racing livery with red and white graphics. Equipment includes a tubular steel frame, a roll cage, a RaceTech seat, a fire-suppression system, a Wilwood pedal box, and Bassett 15″ steel wheels. The car has participated in multiple Trans Am TA2, Historic Sportscar Racing, and SpeedTour events since 2017. This Trans Am racer is now offered by the seller on behalf of the owner in Texas with spare parts and a bill of sale.

The Five Star Race Car Bodies bodywork is finished in blue with red and white graphics, sponsor decals, and number 69 on the roof and sides. Exterior details include a removable hood, a front splitter, front and side brake cooling ducts, a plexiglass windshield and rear window, dual mirrors, a carbon-fiber wing, and a single right-side exhaust outlet. The seller notes blemishes on the body.

Bassett 15″ steel wheels are mounted with 275/695 Pirelli P Zero racing slicks, and the car is equipped with Sweet Manufacturing rack-and-pinion steering. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs with PFC calipers and ventilated rotors, and cooling ducts are located on the front fascia and side panels. A set of four Penske adjustable coilover shocks with remote reservoirs is included in the sale. Service in 2023 reportedly involved replacing the brake pads and rotors as well as a brake cooling fan.

The race-prepared cockpit houses a single RaceTech carbon-fiber seat, a Sabelt multi-point harness, a Simpson restraint net, and a roll cage in addition to a Wilwood pedal box and brake bias adjuster, a Long shifter, and an ESS fire-suppression system.

The MOMO flat-bottom steering wheel is mounted on a quick-release hub and sits ahead of an AiM digital instrumentation display and a switch panel for controlling vehicle systems. The car is not equipped with an odometer, and total mileage is unknown.

The 6.2-liter LS3 V8 was built by Katech of Clinton Township, Michigan, and is equipped with a rear-mounted fuel cell, an SLP airbox cover, Jones Racing Products pulleys, Beyea exhaust headers, and an aluminum radiator with an electric cooling fan.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a G-Force 101 four-speed manual transmission. The drive shaft was serviced in 2023 per the seller, and additional underside photos are provided in the gallery.
This car does not have a title and is not legal to register for street use. It is being offered on a bill of sale.

This 2010 Audi Q5 was registered with one owner in Georgia through May 2024, and it has 71k miles. Finished in Brilliant Black over black leather upholstery, it was optioned with a panoramic sunroof, a Bluetooth hands-free system, and heated front seats. Power comes from a 3.2-liter V6 paired with a six-speed automatic transmission and Quattro all-wheel drive. This Q5 is offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with a window sticker, owner’s manuals, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Georgia title.
Exterior equipment includes an aluminum hood and tailgate, LED taillights, and a roof rack.

The 18″ wheels are mounted with 235/60 Pirelli Scorpion Zero tires. Servotronic speed-sensitive power steering, 320mm ventilated front brake rotors, and Electronic Differential Lock traction control are additional elements.

The heated and power-adjustable front seats are trimmed in black leather, and wood trim accents the cabin, which has a panoramic sunroof, a Bluetooth hands-free system, three-zone climate control, and an Audi Concert stereo with an Audi Music Interface cable.
The odometer indicates 71k miles.
The aluminum 3.2-liter V6 was factory rated at 270 horsepower and 243 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was completed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to all four wheels via a Tiptronic six-speed automatic transmission and a rear-biased Quattro all-wheel-drive system with a Torsen center differential.
The window sticker lists factory colors, equipment, and a total price of $41,315.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1980 Mercedes-Benz 500SL is a European-market example finished in Astral Silver Metallic that was imported to the US before it was acquired by the seller’s uncle in 1990. It is powered by a 5.0-liter M117 V8 mated to a four-speed automatic transmission and equipped with a color-keyed removable hardtop, a rear spoiler, 16″ RIAL basketweave alloy wheels, power windows, and heated front bucket seats upholstered in black leather as well as air conditioning, cruise control, and a Blaupunkt stereo. The seller’s parents acquired the car in 2023, and work since has included repairing the odometer and replacing the tires and battery. This Euro R107 is now offered by the seller on behalf of their parents with service records dating to 1991 and a clean California title.

The car left the factory finished in Astral Silver Metallic and features a color-keyed removable hardtop as well as both front and rear spoilers. Additional exterior details include fog lights, dual side mirrors, a power antenna, and twin polished exhaust outlets. The car is not equipped with a soft top. The bottom edge of the front spoiler is damaged.

Silver-finished RIAL 16″ basketweave alloy wheels were mounted with 225/50 Michelin Pilot Sport All Season tires in May 2024. Braking is handled by power-assisted four-wheel discs. The seller notes that the tie rods are loose.

The heated front bucket seats and the two-place rear bench are trimmed in black leather, and they are joined by color-coordinated door panels and carpeting. A Blaupunkt Berlin SQR 83 head unit and speakers have been added, and the cabin is further appointed with air conditioning, cruise control, power windows, and wood trim pieces.

The four-spoke steering wheel frames a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline and an inset analog clock as well as a 160-mph speedometer and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, fuel economy, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 7k miles, approximately 200 miles were added by the current owner. The odometer had frozen under previous ownership and was repaired in April 2024, therefore true mileage is unknown.

The 5.0-liter M117 SOHC V8 features Bosch K-Jetronic fuel injection and was modified to meet California emissions standards in 1991. Adjustments were made to the ignition system and the battery was replaced in March 2024. The air conditioning system was partially recharged and an oil change was most recently carried out in April 2024. A note from that service visit describes smoke at start-up and the presence of vacuum leaks.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission.

This 1983 Honda CX650 Turbo was purchased new by the seller’s father and was passed to the seller in 1998. It is powered by a turbocharged and liquid-cooled 647cc V-twin mated to a five-speed transmission and an enclosed driveshaft and is finished in white with blue and red graphics. The bike is equipped with electronic fuel injection, a dual exhaust system, air-adjustable suspension, triple disc brakes, ComStar alloy wheels, a smoked windscreen, a digital boost gauge, and a black two-up seat. Work in 2018 included overhauling the electrical system, fork, and brakes, and replacing the battery, spark plugs, tires, and engine gaskets. This CX650 Turbo is offered with a bike cover, an owner’s manual, a shop manual, a tool kit, and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The bodywork is finished in white with blue and red graphics. Features include a smoked windscreen, integrated front turn signals, fairing-mounted mirrors, a black two-up seat, a rear grab handle, and both center and side stands.

ComStar “Boomerang” alloy wheels measuring 18″ up front and 17″ out back were mounted with Avon RoadRider tires in 2018. Air-adjustable suspension consists of a 37mm Showa fork with TRAC anti-dive control as well as a Showa monoshock attached to the Pro-Link swingarm. Braking is handled by dual front disc brakes and a single rear disc. Service in 2018 included replacing the fork seals and disassembling and cleaning the brake master cylinders and calipers.

The shrouded handlebar is mounted aft of instrumentation consisting of a 150-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 9k-rpm redline as well as a digital clock and gauges for boost pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 34k miles.

The longitudinally mounted, turbocharged, and liquid-cooled 647cc V-twin was factory rated at 100 horsepower and 68 lb-ft of torque and features electronic fuel injection and ignition. Service in 2018 included polishing and refinishing the valve covers and radiator grilles, adjusting the valves, replacing the battery, spark plugs, and various seals and gaskets as well as the stator, voltage regulator, and ignition modules with components sourced from a 1986 Honda Banshee. Wear is visible on the finish of the mufflers.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a multi-plate wet clutch, a five-speed transmission, and an enclosed driveshaft.
An owner’s manual and tool kit accompany the motorcycle.

This 2020 Mercedes-AMG S63 coupe has 9k miles and was optioned from the factory with the Driver Assistance, Warmth and Comfort, AMG Exterior Night, and Premium packages. Finished in Magnetite Black Metallic over black and red Exclusive leather upholstery, it is powered by a twin-turbocharged 4.0-liter V8 that drives all four wheels through a nine-speed automatic transmission and a 4MATIC+ all-wheel-drive system. The car has dynamic LED headlights, carbon-fiber exterior and interior accents, OLED taillights, 20″ AMG forged Y-spoke wheels, Distronic Plus adaptive cruise control, a surround view system, a Burmester sound system, heated and ventilated active multicontour front seats with massaging elements, heated rear seats, and a panoramic fixed roof panel with Magic Sky Control. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this C217 S63 AMG coupe is now offered with a clean Carfax report and a clean Texas title.

The car is finished in Magnetite Black Metallic with carbon-fiber accents, and additional exterior details include a panoramic fixed roof panel with Magic Sky Control, dynamic LED headlights OLED taillights, pillarless side windows, front and rear parking sensors, soft-close doors, bright trim, and quad exhaust outlets.

The 20″ AMG forged Y-spoke wheels are mounted with staggered-width Hankook tires. The car is equipped with an AMG Adaptive Sport Suspension with Airmatic self-leveling, and stopping power is provided by red AMG-branded calipers over cross-drilled and slotted discs.

The cabin is upholstered in red and black Exclusive leather and features carbon-fiber trim on the dashboard and door panels. Interior appointments include heated and ventilated active multicontour front seats with position memory and massaging elements, AMG illuminated door sill plates, heated rear seats, a surround view system, a Burmester sound system, ambient lighting, Keyless-Go, Distronic Plus adaptive cruise control, a head-up display, and COMAND infotainment with navigation.

The heated AMG performance steering wheel with Dinamica side grips and carbon-fiber trim fronts paddle shifters and frames a configurable 12.3″ digital instrument cluster. The digital odometer indicates 9k miles.
The twin-turbocharged 4.0-liter V8 was factory rated at 603 horsepower and 664 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in March 2024.
Power is sent to all four wheels through an AMG Speedshift MCT nine-speed automatic transmission and a 4MATIC+ all-wheel-drive system. Additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

description: This 1983 Honda City Turbo II was imported from to the US from Japan in 2018 and previously sold on BaT in January 2019 and again in January 2022 before it was acquired by the seller in 2023. The car is powered by a turbocharged 1.2-liter inline-four linked with a five-speed manual transaxle and finished in silver with red decals over blue and gray cloth. Equipment includes 13″ multi-spoke wheels with Volk Racing aero covers as well as air conditioning, a dashboard cooler, an Alpine AM radio, and a BOSS Bluetooth stereo. This City Turbo II is offered with a Pennsylvania title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in silver and features wider fender flares than the standard City model as well as a hood bulge to accommodate the intercooler. Additional exterior details include an asymmetric grille, yellow fog lights, side vents, window visors, and mud guards. Replacement decals were applied to the body and the right front fender received rust repairs and a repaint under previous ownership. Peeling paint is present on the mirror caps.
The 13″ multi-spoke wheels wear Volk Racing aero covers and are mounted with Federal Super Steel 595 tires that were manufactured in 2018. Braking is handled by front discs and rear drums.

The right-hand-drive cabin houses front bucket seats and a rear bench trimmed in blue cloth with gray centers that extend to the door panel inserts. The dashboard features a built-in cooler, and additional appointments include air conditioning, an Alpine AM radio, and a BOSS Audio Systems Bluetooth stereo. A hole is noted in the upholstery on the driver seat outer bolster.

The three-spoke steering wheel fronts a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as a digital speedometer and turbo gauge and analog readouts for coolant temperature and fuel level. The five-digit odometer has rolled over and shows 311 kilometers (~193 miles). The seller notes that approximately 11k kilometers (~7k miles) were driven under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The turbocharged and intercooled 1.2-liter inline-four is equipped with multi-port fuel injection and was factory rated at 108 horsepower and 118 lb-ft of torque. The seller reports that an idle-hunting issue was resolved under current ownership. The oil was most recently changed in April 2024.
Power is sent to the front wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle. The car is equipped with a straight-pipe exhaust.
The Pennsylvania title carries an “Antique Vehicle” brand.

description: This 2001 Lexus ES300 remained registered to its original owner until 2024, and it was acquired by the selling dealer in June of that year. Finished in Diamond White Pearl over Dark Ivory leather upholstery, the car is powered by a 3.0-liter V6 paired with a four-speed automatic transaxle. Equipment includes chromed 16″ alloy wheels, anti-lock disc brakes, a glass sunroof, automatic climate control, a factory cassette stereo, and power accessories. In December 2022, the oil was changed, the coolant was flushed, and the tires, front brake pads, and intake-manifold and valve-cover gaskets were replaced. This ES300 has 41k miles and is now offered at no reserve in Georgia with owner’s manuals, two keys, a clean Carfax report, and a Georgia title.

The car is finished in Diamond White Pearl (051) with gray lower-body panels and bumper covers. Exterior details include fog lights, a powered glass sunroof, power-adjustable mirrors, and goldtone badging. Photos showing paint-meter readings are provided in the gallery below.

Chrome-plated 16″ six-spoke wheels are wrapped in 205/60 Kumho Solus TA11 tires that have 2022 production-date codes. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs with ABS. The front brake pads were replaced in December 2022, and the fluid was flushed at that time.

The front bucket seats as well as the rear bench are upholstered in Dark Ivory leather. The door panels are trimmed to match, and the cabin is further appointed with woodgrain trim, automatic climate control, power windows and locks, and a digital clock as well as a rear window defroster, cruise control, Lexus-branded carpeted floor mats, and a factory stereo with a cassette player.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 140-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 41k miles, approximately 15 of which were added under current ownership.

The four-cam 3.0-liter V6 is equipped with continuously variable valve timing and was factory rated at 210 horsepower and 220 lb-ft of torque. In December 2022, the oil was changed and the valve-cover and intake-manifold gaskets were replaced.
Power is sent to the front wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accident or damage entries.

This 1957 Chevrolet 210 two-door sedan is powered by a fuel-injected 502ci big block V8 and finished in Elkhart Blue over black leather. The modifications were carried out in 2022 and also included installing a Turbo 400 automatic transmission, a limited-slip rear end, a dual exhaust system, front disc brakes, tubular front A-arms, 17″ and 18″ Ridler wheels, power rack-and-pinion steering, TMI seats, Vintage Air climate control, a modern retro-style stereo, and Dakota Digital gauges. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this big block 210 is now offered with a clean Florida title.

Originally Imperial Ivory, the car was repainted in Elkhart Blue in 2022. Bel Air and Fuel Injection badging was also applied. Close-up photos of the paint, glass, and brightwork can be viewed in the gallery.

Five-spoke 17″ and 18″ Ridler wheels are mounted with 225/45 Doral front and 245/50 Goodyear Eagle F1 rear tires. Modifications include power rack-and-pinion steering, front disc brakes, tubular front A-arms, KYB front shocks, and Calvert Racing rear shocks.

The cabin was overhauled during the build and is now equipped with black leather TMI seats, a leather-trimmed center console, Vintage Air climate control, a modern retro-style stereo, and aftermarket speakers.
The two-spoke steering wheel features a chrome horn ring and frames Dakota Digital gauges. The digital odometer shows around 830 miles.
The 502ci big block V8 was installed in 2022 and is equipped with FiTech fuel injection, aluminum Edelbrock cylinder heads, a dual exhaust system, and an aluminum radiator with electric fans.
The car has been fitted with a three-speed Turbo 400 automatic transmission and a limited-slip rear end.
Decoding the trim tag reveals the following information:

This Ford T-bucket was built by Al Mathon of Hicksville, New York, and is powered by a 700ci V16 constructed from two Chevrolet small-block V8s. Breathing through two Holley four-barrel carburetors, the powerplant features a single crankshaft and is backed by an automatic transmission. The car is fitted with fiberglass bodywork and rides on a custom frame equipped with a tubular front axle, front disc brakes, and rear coilovers. Additional equipment includes a front wing, polished exhaust headers, Weld Racing 15” alloy wheels, a custom steering wheel, Stewart-Warner instrumentation, and black leather upholstery. Acquired several years ago by the Petersen Automotive Museum of Los Angeles, California, this V16-powered hot rod is now offered at no reserve with a California title.

Al Mathon was a welder and instructor from Long Island who built this roadster and its engine with his son. The V16 was constructed by cutting and welding two 350ci Chevrolet V8 engine blocks back-to-front to form a single unit with nine main bearings. Cylinder heads were combined in a similar fashion, and each side features a finned valve cover emblazoned with “Mathon V16.” Two crankshafts were joined with a 45-degree offset into a single unit, as were two camshafts, so that each revolution delivers eight sequential power strokes. Induction is through dual Holley four-barrel carburetors, and two sets of exhaust headers run in parallel on each side, exiting in front of the rear wheels.

The fiberglass body is finished in black, and it is mounted to a custom-fabricated tubular steel frame that has been painted to match. Exterior details include a front wing, a grille guard, and chrome headlight buckets. The seller notes that the mounting gasket for the right-side LED taillight is misaligned.

Staggered-width Weld Racing 15” alloy wheels are mounted with 135-series Firestone F-560 tires up front and 33×21.5” Mickey Thompson Sportsman units out back. The tubular front axle features a transverse leaf spring and radius rods, while the live rear axle is equipped with adjustable coilovers. Braking is handled by vented discs up front and drums out back.
The cockpit is trimmed in black leather with white accents, and black carpets line the floor. The dashboard fascia has been painted to match the body, and a Lokar shifter has been installed.

The custom steering wheel is mounted to an Ididit tilting column, and Stewart-Warner instrumentation consists of a 160-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary gauges. The six-digit odometer shows 13 miles, and total mileage is unknown.
The distributor was custom-fabricated and is connected to a Mallory HyFire ignition box. Dual electric fans are mounted to a polished radiator.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission. Corrosion is noted on the engine and underbody components, which can be viewed in the gallery.
The car is titled in California as a 1923 Ford using the VIN T8765521.

This 1983 Toyota Celica Supra is an L-Type example finished in Silver Gray Metallic and Dark Gray Metallic over Black leather upholstery, and it currently shows 106k miles. A 2.8-liter inline-six sends power to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes a power sunroof, 14″ aluminum alloy wheels, power windows and locks, automatic climate control, and a factory cassette stereo with a graphic equalizer. This A60 Celica Supra is now offered by the seller on behalf of the owner at no reserve with manufacturer’s literature, a workshop manual, a Carscore report, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Massachusetts title.

The car is finished in Silver Gray Metallic and Dark Gray Metallic. It is equipped with pop-up headlights, integrated fog lights, a power-operated sunroof, and a rear window wiper. Rust is noted in the rear wheel arches, the windshield is chipped, the power antenna is broken, and paint chips and blemishes are visible around the car. Additional detail is shown in a seller-provided Carscore report.
The 14″ aluminum-alloy wheels are mounted with Bridgestone Turanza tires measuring 195/70. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is provided by power-assisted four-wheel vented discs.

The seats are upholstered in black leather, and amenities include cruise control, automatic climate control, power windows and locks, and a factory cassette stereo with a graphic equalizer. Repair tape is visible on the driver seat bolster.

The two-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames an 85-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for voltage, coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 106k miles.

The 2.8-liter DOHC 5M-GE inline-six features electronic fuel injection and was factory rated at 150 horsepower and 159 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in March 2023 at which time the rear main seal was replaced. Additional oil leaks are noted on the associated service invoice and the hood support struts have failed.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a five-speed manual transmission. Rust is visible on the undercarriage.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

description: This 2002 Chevrolet Corvette Z06 was acquired by the current owner in 2009 and now has 31k miles. The car is powered by a 5.7-liter LS6 V8 linked to a six-speed manual gearbox and a limited-slip differential. The car is finished in Quicksilver Metallic over Torch Red and black leather and is equipped with 17″ aftermarket wheels, the Memory Package, pop-up headlights, dual-zone climate control, cruise control, a head-up display, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, a Bose sound system, and a CD stereo. This C5 Z06 is now offered on dealer consignment at no reserve with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean New York title.

The C5 Z06 was only offered as a fixed-roof coupe for increased chassis stiffness and featured a quad-exit titanium exhaust system, mesh grille inserts, and weight-saving measures such as thinner glass and reduced sound deadening when compared to the standard C5. This example is finished in Quicksilver Metallic and features pop-up headlights, Z06 fender badges, and rear brake vents. Paint protection film was applied to the hood, door guards, and turn signals in 2013.

The chrome-finished 17″ aftermarket wheels are mounted with 265/40 front and 295/35 rear Goodyear Eagle F1 tires. The Z06 suspension featured a larger front stabilizer bar, increased damping, and a higher spring rate than the standard Corvette. The car is equipped with active handling and traction control systems, speed-sensitive rack-and-pinion power steering, and ventilated disc brakes at all four corners. Replacement brake rotors and pads were installed within the past two years, and the removed factory wheels are included in the sale per the selling dealer.

The cabin features two seats upholstered in Torch Red and black leather. Amenities include a six-way power-adjustable driver’s seat, a head-up display, dual-zone automatic climate control, an onboard computer, cruise control, electrochromic mirrors, and a Bose sound system with an in-dash CD player.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline along with gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 31k miles, approximately 2,200 of which were added under current ownership. A mileage inconsistency is noted in an April 2009 Carfax report entry.

The 5.7-liter LS6 V8 was based upon the contemporary LS1 and features a refined aluminum block, a higher-lift camshaft, a 10.5:1 compression ratio, and increased air and oil flow. Factory-rated output for the 2002 model year was 405 horsepower and 400 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in April 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual gearbox and a limited-slip differential.
The window sticker notes initial delivery to Planker Chevrolet of West Babylon, New York, and lists factory colors, options, and a total vehicle price of $51,535.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage and lists the aforementioned mileage inconsistency.
Interested to see what Car and Driver thought about the Corvette Z06 when it was new? Click here to check out their August 2001 Road Test.

This 1964 Volvo 1800S is powered by a 1.8-liter inline-four that has been equipped with a single carburetor and is mated to a four-speed manual transmission. The car was refinished in red and fitted with revised front bodywork prior to the owner’s 2023 acquisition. Additional features include 15″ wire-spoke wheels, front disc brakes, an AM/FM radio, flow-through ventilation, a heater, front bucket seats, and black leather upholstery. This 1800S is now offered in Rhode Island at no reserve by the seller on behalf of the owner with a clean North Carolina title in the owner’s name.

The car left the factory finished in Cherry Red (46), and it was repainted and fitted with revised front bodywork at some point under prior ownership. Details include chrome trim, a driver-side mirror, and front vent windows. The antenna is missing.

Wire-spoke 15″ wheels show rust and are mounted with Yokohama Avid Ascend GT tires. The car is equipped with an independent front suspension, and stopping power is provided by front disc and rear drum brakes.
The front bucket seats and rear bench are trimmed in black leather, and interior appointments include a padded dashboard, a rear parcel shelf, an AM/FM radio, flow-through ventilation, and a heater.

The woodgrain-rimmed steering wheel frames Smiths instrumentation consisting of an inoperative 120-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and vertical gauges for coolant and oil temperatures. Centrally mounted auxiliary readouts for fuel level and oil pressure are joined by an analog clock. The five-digit odometer does not work and currently shows 13k miles. Total mileage is unknown.
The 1.8-liter B18B inline-four has been equipped with a single carburetor in place of the dual units fitted from the factory.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission. Rust on the undercarriage is noted.

This 1980 Jeep J-10 is a Sportside pickup that was acquired by the selling dealer in 2022 and subsequently fitted with Holley Sniper fuel injection. Additional work performed involved repainting the bumpers, overhauling the brakes, and replacing the body seals, power steering pump, battery, starter, transmission oil pan gasket, and various cooling components. The truck is finished in blue over blue cloth upholstery and is powered by a 258ci inline-six mated to a three-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Additional equipment includes 15″ steel wheels, 33″ tires, power steering, power-assisted front disc brakes, manually locking front hubs, and a bed-mounted roll bar in addition to air conditioning, a B&M shifter, and a Sony cassette stereo. This J10 pickup is now offered by the selling dealer in Georgia with an invoice for work performed under current ownership and a clean Texas title.

The truck is finished in blue and was repainted under previous ownership. Details include a Sportside bed, dual side mirrors, a sliding rear window, a bed-mounted roll bar, wood bed rails, and a receiver hitch. The front and rear bumpers were repainted under current ownership, at which time the window and door seals were replaced.

White-finished 15″ steel wheels are mounted with 33×12.5″ Kenda Klevar A/T 2 tires. Multiple lug nuts are missing and the finish is failing on the wheels. The front axle is equipped with manually locking hubs, and braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. Work performed under current ownership involved replacing the power steering pump, front brake pads and rotors, and rear brake wheel cylinders, shoes, and drums.

The front bucket seats are upholstered in faded blue cloth and are joined by color-coordinated door panels. A B&M shifter and a Sony cassette stereo have been retrofitted, and air conditioning, a digital clock, a locking glove compartment, and a passenger grab handle are further details.

The three-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of an engine-turned instrument bezel that consists of an 85-mph speedometer and auxiliary gauges for fuel level, coolant temperature, oil pressure, and amperage. A Holley EFI module is mounted to the left climate control duct. The five-digit odometer shows 57k miles, approximately 150 of which have been added by the selling dealer.

The 258ci inline-six was fitted with Holley Sniper electronic fuel injection in 2024. Additional work performed involved replacing various coolant gaskets as well as the radiator, thermostat, starter, and battery.
Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. The transmission oil pan gasket was replaced in 2024.

This 1996 Ford Taurus LX wagon is a Canadian-market example that remained with one family until it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2023. The car is finished in Silver Frost Metallic over gray cloth upholstery, and it is powered by a 3.0-liter Duratec V6 paired with a four-speed automatic transaxle. Additional equipment includes 15″ aluminum wheels, four-wheel disc brakes, a keyless entry keypad, automatic climate control, power windows and locks, a cassette stereo, and a multi-disc CD changer. This Taurus wagon shows 72k kilometers (~45k miles) is offered by the selling dealer in Canada at no reserve with a clean US Carfax report and British Columbia registration.

The car is finished in Silver Frost Metallic and features body-color mirrors, door handles, and bodyside moldings. Additional exterior features include a retractable antenna, a keyless entry keypad, and a rear liftgate with flip-up glass.
The  15″ aluminum wheels are mounted with Uniroyal Tiger Paw tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs.

The seating surfaces are upholstered in gray cloth and amenities include power windows, locks, and mirrors as well as a power-adjustable driver seat, automatic climate control, and a cassette stereo linked to a CD changer.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 200-km/h speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 72k kilometers (~45k miles).

The 3.0-liter Duratec V6 features dual overhead cams and four valves per cylinder which lead to a factory-rated output of 201 horsepower and 207 lb-ft of torque. The selling dealer states the battery was replaced, a coolant flush was performed, and the transmission was serviced in preparation for the sale
Power is delivered to the front wheels via a four-speed automatic transaxle.
The US Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The vehicle is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada. The sale does not include a title.

This 1978 Bultaco Pursang 370 is said to have been raced in Southern California before being acquired in 2016 by the seller, who completed a refurbishment of the bike in 2024. Work at that time included overhauling the 363cc two-stroke single’s top end, repainting the frame and bodywork, reupholstering the seat, rebuilding the wheels and fork, and replacing the remote-reservoir shocks, wheel spokes, hand controls, drive chain, and sprockets. Equipment includes a five-speed transmission, a side stand, a cross-braced handlebar, yellow front and side number plates, drum brakes, and a high-mount exhaust system. This Mk11 Pursang 370 is now offered in Tennessee for off-road use only with refurbishment records and images, a Bell helmet, goggles, a riding jersey, a mouth guard, an owner’s manual, spare parts, and a bill of sale.

The frame, swingarm, fiberglass bodywork, and accessories were stripped and repainted in blue with silver, red, and yellow accents during the refurbishment, and the seat was reupholstered, the fuel tank internally sealed, and the petcocks replaced at that time. Equipment includes high-mount fenders, a right-side side stand, yellow side and front number plates, and serrated foot pegs.

The 21″ front and 18″ rear alloy rims were overhauled with new bearings, seals, and stainless-steel spokes and mounted with knobby tires during the refurbishment. The leading-axle fork was overhauled at that time, and a pair of reproduction remote-reservoir Betor shocks were fitted. The swingarm bushings, seals, and bolt were replaced. Braking is from drums at both ends.

A black cross-braced handlebar is secured to the upper triple clamp, and the brake, clutch and throttle cables along with the Magura throttle, grips, and kill switch were replaced in 2024. The bike did not come with an odometer or other instrumentation, therefore total mileage is unknown. The seller estimates having ridden approximately 20 hours.

The 363cc two-stroke single was factory rated at 41 horsepower and is equipped with a kick starter along with a high-exit expansion-chamber exhaust system. The bottom end was overhauled in 2016, and work during the 2024 refurbishment included rebuilding the top end and carburetor, replacing or zinc-coating hardware as needed, and replacing the seals, gaskets, o-rings, reed valves, intake spacer, air filter, and air filter housing.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission. The drive chain and sprockets were replaced during the refurbishment.
listing_details: Blue Paint w/Silver, Red, & Yellow Accents

description: This 2001 Ford Mustang GT convertible has 21k miles, and was specified in Oxford White Clearcoat over Medium Parchment leather. The car is powered by a 4.6-liter V8 paired with a five-speed manual transmission, and equipment includes a limited-slip differential, a tan convertible soft top, 17″ five-spoke Premium aluminum wheels, a hood scoop, a rear spoiler, fog lights, articulated front sport seats, remote keyless entry, air conditioning, cruise control, a Mach 460 sound system, and a CD changer. This New Edge Mustang is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Oxford White Clearcoat, and features include a power-operated tan convertible top, a hood scoop, a rear spoiler, fog lights, power-adjustable side mirrors, polished dual exhaust outlets, and a Mustang script-debossed rear bumper cover. Photos depicting paint-meter readings are provided in the gallery.
The 17″ five-spoke Premium aluminum wheels are mounted with Sumitomo HTR P02 tires. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel discs.

The cabin features articulated front sport seats trimmed in Medium Parchment leather. Amenities include remote keyless entry, air conditioning, power accessories, a Mach 460 sound system, a CD changer, and cruise control.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 150-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, coolant temperature, voltage, and oil pressure. The digital odometer indicates 21k miles.
The 4.6-liter SOHC V8 was factory rated at 260 horsepower and 302 lb-ft of torque. The battery and engine oil were replaced in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a Traction-Lok limited-slip differential. Corrosion is noted on various underside components.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 1986 Mercedes-Benz 500SEL is a European-specification example that is powered by a 5.0-liter M117 V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission and is finished in Signal Red over black leather. Equipment includes 15″ Gullideckel alloy wheels, four-wheel disc brakes, fog lights, heated power-adjustable front and rear seats, a Becker cassette stereo, an Alpine CD changer, automatic climate control, and cruise control. The car was acquired by the current owner in 2017 and it now shows 57k miles. This W126 500SEL is offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner with the owner’s manual, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Maryland title in the owner’s name.
The car is finished in Signal Red with gray lower cladding and features fog lights, a sunroof, a power antenna, dual exhaust outlets, European-style bumpers, and bright window and bumper trim.
The 15″ Gullideckel alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Premier A/S tires. Braking is handled by power-assisted four-wheel discs.

The heated power-adjustable front seats and rear bench are upholstered in black leather. Appointments include a Becker cassette stereo, automatic climate control, cruise control, and a trunk-mounted Alpine CD changer linked to a steering column-mounted display.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, an analog clock, and supplementary gauges. The six-digit odometer shows 57k miles, approximately 1k of which were added under current ownership.
The 5.0-liter M117 V8 was factory rated at 245 horsepower and 295 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage up to the most recent entry in May 2023.

This 2023 Mercedes-AMG G63 is a Canadian-market example that is finished in G Manufaktur China Blue and was optioned from the factory with the AMG Night Package and the G Manufaktur Interior Package Plus. Powered by a twin-turbocharged 4.0-liter V8 linked with a nine-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case, the truck has 2,100 miles and is further equipped with Platinum White Nappa leather upholstery, three locking differentials, 22″ matte black AMG forged cross-spoke wheels, a sunroof, LED lighting, parking sensors, heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats, heated rear seats, a Burmester surround sound system, tri-zone automatic climate control, adaptive cruise control, carbon-fiber interior trim, and COMAND infotainment with navigation. Acquired by the owner in 2024, this W463 G63 is now offered by the seller on behalf of the owner, a retail dealer, with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and British Columbia registration.

The truck is finished in G Manufaktur China Blue with black trim and a power sunroof, a front brush guard, a receiver hitch, LED lighting, Active Parking Assist sensors, rain-sensing windshield wipers, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, running boards, black bumpers and fender extensions, and dual exhaust outlets ahead of each rear wheel.

Matte black 22″ AMG forged cross-spoke wheels are mounted with 285/40 Pirelli Scorpion tires. Braking is provided by red-painted calipers fitted over cross-drilled discs at each corner. The truck came equipped from the factory with adaptive damping.

The heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats are trimmed in Platinum White Nappa leather with AMG logos on the backrests and diamond-stitched inserts that extend to the door panels. Carbon-fiber trim accents the cabin, and additional appointments include heated rear seats, front-seat position memory settings, a Dinamica headliner, a Burmester surround sound system, Apple CarPlay, Android Auto, Blind Spot Assist, tri-zone automatic climate control, adaptive cruise control, AMG illuminated door sill plates, COMAND infotainment with navigation, and “G manufaktur” script on the passenger grab handle.

The heated carbon-fiber- and Dinamica-trimmed steering wheel frames a 12.3″ configurable digital instrument cluster. The digital odometer indicates 2,100 miles, all of which were added under current ownership.
The twin-turbocharged 4.0-liter V8 was factory rated at 577 horsepower and 627 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in August 2023.

Power is sent to all four wheels through an AMG Speedshift TCT nine-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and locking differentials at the front, center, and rear. Additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada.

description: This 1984 Ford Mustang SVO is said to have remained with a single owner until the selling dealer’s acquisition in 2024. Powered by a turbocharged 2.3-liter inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transmission, the car is finished in red over charcoal cloth upholstery. Modifications include a Ford Motorsport A231 camshaft and “big valve” cylinder head as well as a Super Turbo muffler, a Saleen G-bar, subframe connectors, urethane sway bar bushings, an 8.8″ rear axle with a Ford Motorsport 3.73:1 differential. Additional equipment includes 16″ alloy wheels, power-assisted four-wheel disc brakes, and a Clarion CD stereo. This Mustang SVO is now offered at no reserve in Washington state with the owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, and a clean Oregon title.

Ford’s Special Vehicle Operations gave the Mustang SVO a biplane rear spoiler and revised front-end styling as well as thinner rocker panels and an offset hood scoop to feed the top-mount intercooler. This example was repainted in red under prior ownership and features fog lights, polished exhaust finishers, and black trim. Exterior blemishes are displayed in the gallery.

The 16″ alloy wheels are mounted with older 225/50 Toyo Proxes tires. The SVO was equipped from the factory with power steering and adjustable Koni dampers. Modifications include subframe connectors, a Saleen G-bar, and urethane sway bar bushings. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is handled by power-assisted four-wheel discs.

The cabin features seating surfaces upholstered in charcoal cloth with matching door panels. Amenities include articulated front sport seats, a premium sound system, a Clarion CD stereo, a tilting steering column, a digital clock, intermittent wipers, power windows, and power locks. Interior blemishes are displayed in the gallery. The air conditioning does not work.

The three-spoke sport steering wheel frames an 85-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 5,800-rpm redline as well as gauges for boost pressure, coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 47k miles.
The turbocharged 2.3-liter inline-four was reportedly fitted with a Ford Motorsport A231 camshaft and “big valve” cylinder head.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and an 8.8″ rear axle with a Ford Motorsport 3.73:1 differential. A revised clutch, pressure plate, and BBK clutch cable are said to have been installed. A Super Turbo muffler is fitted.
A spare radio, Koni shocks, brake calipers, fog light covers, service records, and drive belt accompany the vehicle.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 1965 BMW R27 is said to have been modified for land-speed racing under prior ownership with work that included fitting an R50S piston, replacement valves, and Excel alloy rims, and it has been refinished in Dover White with black pinstripes. Power is from a 247cc vertical single paired with a four-speed transmission, and features include a driveshaft, a black Denfeld saddle, a chrome low-rise handlebar, bar-end turn signals, an Earles fork, a center stand, and a Bing carburetor. The bike was imported through Butler & Smith in New York City in 1964 and spent time in California and Washington from 2015 until it was acquired by the seller in 2023. This R27 is now offered at no reserve with manufacturer’s literature, service records, and a clean South Carolina title in the seller’s name.

The bike was refinished in Dover White with black hand-painted pinstripes reportedly more than 15 years ago. It features a black Denfeld solo saddle, bar-end turn signals, black rubber knee grips, a cargo rack, and a center stand.

Rebuilt wire-spoke wheels with 18″ Excel alloy rims wear Avon RoadRider tires. Suspension is provided by an Earles fork as well as preload-adjustable shocks mounted to the swingarm on the left and the final-drive housing on the right. Braking is handled by front and rear drums.

The chrome low-rise handlebar fronts a 90-mph speedometer and a pair of indicator lights. The five-digit odometer shows 2,100 miles, approximately 200 of which were ridden under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 247cc vertical single is said to have been modified with an R50S piston and replacement valves under prior ownership. It features a Bing carburetor and was factory rated at 18 horsepower. The valves were adjusted, the cylinder head bolts torqued, and the fluids changed by the seller in July 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a four-speed transmission as well as a driveshaft enclosed within the right leg of the swingarm.
The headstock plate indicates that this bike is an R27 with serial number 382225, and the matching numbers stamped on the frame and engine case can be viewed in the gallery.

This 1978 Pontiac Firebird Trans Am was refurbished under prior ownership and work consisted of repainting the body, retrimming the interior, and rebuilding the engine. Finished in Starlight Black over Carmine vinyl upholstery, the car is powered by a 400ci V8 linked with a three-speed automatic transmission and a Safe-T-Track limited-slip differential. The car has been fitted with an Edelbrock intake manifold and cylinder heads, Hedman exhaust headers, and a Hooker Aero Chamber muffler, and equipment includes a shaker hood, 15″ Cragar SS wheels, power steering, power front disc brakes, and an AM/FM radio. The selling dealer acquired the car in June 2024. This Firebird Trans Am is now offered with service records and a clean New York title.

The car was repainted in Starlight Black circa 2018, and exterior equipment includes Firebird hood graphics on the shaker hood as well as a front spoiler, a rear spoiler, painted mirror caps, and polished quad exhaust outlets.

The 15″ Cragar SS wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich Radial T/A white-letter tires measuring 245/60 up front and 255/60 out back. The vehicle is equipped with power steering, and stopping power is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The front bucket seats and rear bench were retrimmed in Carmine vinyl upholstery, which extends to the center console, door panels, and carpets. Amenities include an engine-turned dash fascia, a full-length center console, an AM/FM radio, and a heater.

The leather-wrapped Formula steering wheel fronts a 100-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, an analog clock, and a fuel-level gauge. The five-digit odometer shows 85k miles, a handful of which were added under current ownership.
The 400ci V8 was rebuilt in 2018 and is said to have been fitted with Butler Performance engine internals as well as Edelbrock Performer aluminum cylinder heads and Hedman exhaust headers.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission and a Safe-T-Track limited-slip differential. A Hooker Aero Chamber muffler has been fitted.

This 1991 Mercedes-Benz 300E 4MATIC has remained registered in Colorado since new and now shows 94k miles. It is powered by a 3.0-liter M103 inline-six that drives all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission, and it is finished in Smoke Silver Metallic over beige leather upholstery. Equipment includes 15″ Gullideckel alloy wheels, a sunroof, power-adjustable front seats, a cassette stereo, air conditioning, and cruise control. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2023, this W124 300E is offered at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a clean Colorado title.

The car is finished in Smoke Silver Metallic (702) with black bumper trim and darker lower cladding. Features include a sunroof, headlight wipers and washers, fog lights, a power antenna, and a mono-blade windshield wiper. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.
Silver 15″ Gullideckel alloy wheels are mounted with Arctic Claw Winter XSI tires. Braking is handled by ventilated front and solid rear disc brakes with ABS.

The cabin features seating upholstered in beige leather along with wood trim and a color-coordinated lower dashboard, center console, door panels, and carpets. Interior appointments include power-adjustable front seats, a cassette stereo, air conditioning, a passenger airbag, and cruise control.

The four-spoke steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer as well as an analog clock and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 94k miles, approximately 600 of which were added by the selling dealer.
The 3.0-liter M103 inline-six was factory-rated at 177 horsepower and 188 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a 4MATIC all-wheel-drive system.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1986 Chevrolet Corvette coupe has 2,800 miles and is powered by a 5.7-liter L98 V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission. The car is finished in Dark Red Metallic over gray cloth upholstery. Additional equipment includes the Z51 Performance Handling Package, a limited-slip differential, 16″ turbine-style alloy wheels, a removable painted roof panel, a Delco-Bose sound system, automatic climate control, and pop-up headlights. This C4 coupe is now offered by the selling dealer with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a Pennsylvania title.
The car is finished in Dark Red Metallic and features pop-up headlights, fog lamps, a removable painted roof panel, heated side mirrors, and quad exhaust outlets.

The 16″ turbine-style alloy wheels are mounted with 245/50 Cooper Zeon RS3-G1 tires. The car is equipped with an independent front and five-link rear suspension as well as front and rear stabilizer bars. Stopping power is provided by anti-lock four-wheel disc brakes. The Z51 Performance Handling Package added a heavy-duty suspension with Bilstein dampers.

The cabin features sport bucket seats upholstered in gray cloth along with matching carpets and door panels. Amenities include a Delco-Bose sound system, automatic climate control, cruise control, and an onboard computer.

The two-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a digital instrument panel that includes a speedometer, a tachometer, and a fuel-level display as well as numeric readouts for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, and fuel economy. The six-digit odometer shows 2,800 miles.
