The 5.7-liter L98 V8 is equipped with Tuned Port Injection and was factory rated at 230 horsepower and 330 lb-ft of torque. The Z51 Performance Handling Package added a heavy-duty radiator, an auxiliary cooling fan, and an engine oil cooler.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a limited-slip differential.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Simpson Chevrolet of Zelienople, Pennsylvania, along with factory equipment, options, and a total suggested retail price of $29,217.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1968 Ford F-250 is powered by a 360ci V8 linked to a four-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case, and it is finished in green over black upholstery. Equipment includes a Workmate drop-in camper shell, 16″ Mickey Thompson wheels, a Warn winch, a receiver hitch, side steps, and a Pioneer CD stereo. The truck was acquired by the seller in 2000, and work under current ownership is said to have included repainting the bed, overhauling the transmission, rebuilding the carburetor, and replacing clutch components along with the rear driveshaft, radiator, and thermostat. This F-250 is offered at no reserve with service records and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The truck is finished in green, and the seller states the bed was repainted under current ownership. Equipment includes a Workmate drop-in camper shell with exterior storage compartments as well as a Warn winch, a chrome front bumper, a receiver hitch, and side steps.
The 16″ Mickey Thompson wheels are mounted with Toyo tires. The truck is equipped with manually locking front hubs, and braking is provided by drums at each corner.
The bench seat is trimmed in black cloth and vinyl. Appointments include a heater, a Pioneer CD stereo, and wind-up windows.

The steering wheel frames a sweeping 100-mph speedometer, a column-mounted tachometer, and auxiliary gauges. The speedometer was replaced in May 2020 and currently reads 34k miles. Total mileage is unknown.

The 360ci V8 was factory rated at 215 horsepower and 327 lb-ft of torque. The carburetor was rebuilt in May 2024, and additional work under current ownership included performing wiring repairs, installing a dual exhaust system, and replacing the radiator, thermostat, spark plugs, ignition wires, and various hoses.

Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels through a four-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case. The seller states the transmission was overhauled and the clutch and throwout bearing were replaced under current ownership. The rear driveshaft was replaced in May 2024.

This 2007 Mercedes-Benz SL550 was specified in Aegean Blue Metallic over beige leather, and it is powered by a 5.5-liter V8 paired with a seven-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes a power-folding hardtop, a panoramic glass roof, bi-xenon headlights, 18″ split five-spoke wheels, Keyless Go, heated and ventilated seats, a Bose sound system, and COMAND with navigation. This R230 has 51k miles, and it is now offered in Pennsylvania by the selling dealer with the owner’s manual, service records, and a clean Missouri title.

The car is finished in Aegean Blue Metallic (946) and features a power-folding convertible hardtop, a panoramic glass roof, bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, dual exhaust outlets, and fender air vents. Protective film has been installed on the front end. The Carfax report lists accident damage in a June 2022 entry. The underside of the front bumper cover shows signs of scraping.

The 18″ split five-spoke wheels show signs of curb rash and are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact tires. The car features Active Body Control (ABC) suspension as well as an Electronic Stability Program (ESP) and Automatic Slip Control (ASR). The ABC struts were replaced in April 2019, and the rear brake pads and rotors were replaced in October 2023.

The cabin features heated, ventilated, and massaging multi-contour seats that are upholstered in beige leather, while wood trim accents the center console and door panels. Amenities include seat position memory settings, dual-zone automatic climate control, a wind deflector, cruise control, Keyless Go, a Bose sound system, a remote six-disc CD changer, and COMAND with navigation. An inner door handle was replaced in February 2024.
The leather- and wood-rimmed steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 51k miles.
The 5.5-liter M273 V8 was factory rated at 382 horsepower and 391 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in October 2023, and the battery was replaced in February 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage.

This 1995 Mercedes-Benz E320 cabriolet is powered by a 3.2-liter M104 inline-six paired with a four-speed automatic transmission, and it is finished in Polar White over Parchment leather. Equipment includes a black convertible soft top, silver 15″ Alamak alloy wheels, heated power-adjustable front seats, a cassette stereo, automatic climate control, and cruise control. The convertible top hydraulic system is said to have been overhauled in preparation for the sale. This A124 E320 shows 114k miles and is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with a stamped maintenance booklet, tools, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New York title.

The car is finished in Polar White (149) with gray lower cladding and features a power-operated black convertible soft top, headlight wipers, a power-telescoping antenna, bright trim, asymmetrical side mirrors, and a single eccentric-sweep windshield wiper. The convertible top hydraulic system is said to have been overhauled in preparation for the sale. Photographs of paint-meter readings are shown in the gallery below.
Silver 15″ Alamak alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Premier A/S tires. The car is equipped with Acceleration Slip Control (ASR), and braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats upholstered in Parchment leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, center console, door panels, and carpets. Burl wood accents the dash, center stack, and doors, while amenities include a cassette stereo, automatic climate control, and cruise control. The seating surfaces show signs of wear.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline as well as an analog clock and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 114k miles.

The 3.2-liter M104 inline-six features four valves per cylinder and was factory rated at 217 horsepower and 229 lb-ft of torque. The seller notes that the wiring harness has been replaced with a synthetic unit.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or damage.
The New York title is listed as a duplicate.

This 1932 Ford roadster is powered by a 239ci flathead V8 paired with a three-speed manual transmission and finished in metallic green over white tuck-and-roll vinyl. Equipment includes a white removable hardtop, a dropped front axle, hydraulic drum brakes, electric door poppers, Edelbrock cylinder heads, and triple Stromberg 97 carburetors. The car was reportedly built circa 1952 and the selling dealer acquired it in 2024. Service in preparation for the sale included changing the oil, rebuilding the brake master cylinder, and replacing the wheel cylinders, fan belt, spark plugs, and battery. This 32 Ford is now offered with spare parts and a clean Washington title.

The car is finished in metallic green and is equipped with a white removable hardtop and electric door poppers. The rumble seat and hood are missing and were reportedly stolen at a car show in the mid-1990s. There is paint loss on the cowl and rust in the rockers. An unpainted spare hood is included in the sale.

The 15″ steel wheels are painted to match the body and wear chrome dog-dish hubcaps. The tires are US Royal Super Safety 4-ply whitewalls. The car is equipped with a 4″ dropped front axle and four-wheel hydraulic drum brakes. Service in preparation for the sale included rebuilding the brake master cylinder and replacing the wheel cylinders.
The cabin is upholstered in white tuck-and-roll vinyl with turquoise carpets and matching sheet metal.

The three-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of a 100-mph speedometer and gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, charging status, and temperature. The five-digit odometer shows around 3k miles, though the total mileage is unknown.

The 239ci flathead V8 is equipped with Edelbrock cylinder heads, an Edelbrock intake manifold, and triple Stromberg 97 carburetors. Service in preparation for the sale included changing the oil and replacing the fan belt, spark plugs, and battery.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a column-shifted three-speed manual transmission.
A white soft top with side curtains, a spare windshield, a cover, an unpainted hood, literature, and prior registration documents will accompany the car.

This 1974 Honda CB360 spent time in long-term storage in Iowa before the seller’s acquisition from the spouse of the reported original owner in 2020. Subsequent recommision work included overhauling the Keihin carburetors, flushing the fuel tank, changing the oil, and replacing the battery, spark plugs, fuel lines, and tires. The bike is powered by a 356cc parallel twin paired with a six-speed transmission and is finished in Candy Orange. Equipment includes kick and electric starters, drum brakes, 18″ wire-spoke wheels, chrome fenders, street lighting, a two-up seat, a passenger backrest, rear crash bars, and a luggage rack. This CB360 shows 4,300 miles and is offered at no reserve with an owner’s manual, tool kit, handwritten service notes, and a clean Minnesota title in the seller’s name.

The 2.9-gallon fuel tank and side covers are finished in Candy Orange. The backrest adjusts and slides to accommodate either the driver or passenger, and exterior details include chrome fenders, street lighting, a black two-up seat, folding passenger foot pegs, chrome rear crash bars, a luggage rack, and both center and side stands.
Chrome-steel 18″ rims are laced to drum-brake hubs and were mounted with IRC Grand High Speed tires in 2021. Suspension consists of a telescopic fork as well as dual shocks mounted to the swingarm.

The chrome handlebar carries dual mirrors and is mounted aft of Nippon Seiki instrumentation consisting of a 110-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 9,200-rpm redline. A bank of indicator lights is located between the gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 4,300 miles, approximately 200 of which were ridden under current ownership. The ignition cylinder was relocated to the handlebar under previous ownership.

The 356cc parallel twin was factory rated at 34 horsepower and features dual Keihin carburetors, a chrome two-into-two exhaust system, and both kick and electric starters. Service in 2021 included rebuilding and synching the carburetors, flushing the fuel tank, changing the oil, adjusting the valves, setting the timing, and replacing the fuel lines and spark plugs. A Motobatt battery was installed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a six-speed transmission and a drive chain with a black upper guard.
A tool kit and owner’s manual accompany the motorcycle.

This Meyers Manx is a Signature Series example that was ordered by the seller’s family in 1999, and it rides on a custom-fabricated tubular steel chassis with an integrated roll bar and an independent rear suspension. Finished in red, the car is powered by a 1.6-liter flat-four equipped with dual carburetors and mated to a four-speed manual transaxle. Porsche bucket seats are trimmed in black leather with Tartan cloth inserts, and other highlights include 15” steel wheels, diamond-plate aluminum floors, a Vintage Speed shifter, a Woody’s Custom Shop digital media receiver, VDO instrumentation, and three-point seatbelts. This Manx is now offered on dealer consignment with a clean Michigan title listing the car as a 1967 Volkswagen.

Initially finished in yellow, the fiberglass body shell was repainted in red before it was mounted to a custom-fabricated tubular steel chassis with an integrated roll cage. Exterior details include a black front bumper, driving lights, chrome headlight buckets, wind wings, and black taillight bezels surrounding the period Beetle-style taillights.

Cream-finished 15” steel wheels wear baby-moon hubcaps and are mounted with 30.0×7.0” Mickey Thompson Baja Pro tires. The car is equipped with an independent rear suspension, and braking is handled by four-wheel drums.

The fixed-back bucket seats were sourced from a Porsche 914 and are trimmed in black leather with Tartan cloth inserts. Removable tan cloth covers will accompany the car. The floors are constructed from diamond-plate aluminum, and additional appointments include a Vintage Speed shifter, a Woody’s Custom Shop digital media receiver, a roller accelerator, side pockets, and three-point seatbelts.

The Grant GT steering wheel fronts a gold engine-turned instrument panel housing a VDO 120-mph speedometer and gauges for oil pressure, cylinder head temperature, alternator output, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 1,300 miles.

The 1.6-liter flat-four was sourced from GEX International of Booneville, Arkansas, and features dual carburetors and EMPI finned valve covers. Approximately 200 miles are said to have been added since the engine was installed in 2016 at Auto Europe of Birmingham, Michigan. The polished muffler is dented.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transaxle. Bedliner material has been applied to portions of the underbody.

A Meyers Manx identification tag indicates that the car is number 50 of 100 examples produced for the Signature Series. A second plaque riveted to the body shows the number 117427716, which is consistent with a Volkswagen Beetle produced for the 1967 model year and matches the VIN listed on the Michigan title, which describes the car as a 1967 Volkswagen.
listing_details: Tubular Steel Chassis w/Integrated Roll Bar

description: This 1970 Chevrolet K5 Blazer is powered by a 6.0-liter LS2 V8 linked and a Tremec six-speed manual transmission that were sourced from a Chevrolet SSR and installed after the current owner’s 2021 acquisition. It rides on a lowered suspension with QA1 rear coilovers along with 19″ and 20″ SSR wheels that are mounted over four-wheel disc brakes. The exterior was refinished in dark green with woodgrain trim, and the matching hardtop was fitted with a Legacy sliding ragtop sunroof. The cabin was fitted with heated and ventilated front bucket seats and a contoured rear bench from a Kia Stinger along with a full-length roll cage, Vintage Air climate control, power windows, Dakota Digital instrumentation, and an Alpine touchscreen head unit. This modified K5 Blazer is offered on dealer consignment in Delaware with a clean New Jersey title.

The truck was repainted in dark green and the matching hardtop has been fitted with a Legacy sliding ragtop sunroof. Additional details include a Fesler windshield, aftermarket headlights, dual side mirrors, and woodgrain trim accenting the bodysides and tailgate.

Chrome 19″ and 20″ SSR wheels are mounted with 255/45 front and 295/40 rear Continental ExtremeContact DWS06 tires. The truck rides on a lowered suspension with QA1 coilovers out back, and braking is handled by four-wheel discs.

The front bucket seats and contoured rear bench were sourced from a Kia Stinger, and they have been reupholstered in tan leather. A color-coordinated dash pad and door panels were installed during the build along with black carpets. Amenities include heated and ventilated front seats, power windows, Vintage Air climate control, a full-length roll cage, USB ports, and an Alpine touchscreen head unit linked with aftermarket speakers.

The aftermarket wood-rimmed steering wheel frames a Dakota Digital instrument cluster with a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, an analog clock, and readouts for voltage, fuel level, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The replacement odometer shows 1,900 miles, and the total mileage is unknown.

The 6.0-liter LS2 V8 is said to have been sourced from a Chevrolet SSR and was installed in 2023. A custom engine cover and a polished intake pipe are installed. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.

Power is routed to the rear wheels through a Tremec six-speed manual transmission and a 14-bolt rear axle with a limited-slip rear differential. The dual exhaust system features Flowmaster mufflers and terminates with turn-downs ahead of the rear axle.

This 2005 Honda Rune is a limited-production motorcycle based on the contemporary Valkyrie, and it is powered by 1,832cc SOHC flat-six paired with a five-speed transmission. The bike is finished in Double Clear Coat Black with chrome accents, and features include a digital instrument display, LED taillights, a black Corbin two-up seat, a trailing-link fork, a Unit Pro-Link linkage and monoshock, a single-sided swingarm, an enclosed driveshaft, optional chrome-finished 18″ and 17″ five-spoke wheels, triple Nissin disc brakes, electronic fuel injection, and a six-into-two exhaust system. The seller purchased the bike approximately 11 years ago, and it now has 9k miles. This Rune is offered with  literature and a clean Texas title in the seller’s name.

The bike is finished in Double Clear Coat Black and features an aluminum twin-spar frame, a black Corbin two-up seat, a 6.1-gallon fuel tank, a chrome engine guard, and a side stand. The lighting package is comprised of dual headlights housed in a triangular color-keyed bucket with a chrome visor in addition to chrome turn signals and a pair of vertical LED taillight strips incorporated into the rear fender.

Five-spoke aluminum wheels measuring 18″ up front and 17″ out back are finished in chrome, a $2k option, and are mounted with Dunlop Sportmax Roadsmart tires. Suspension consists of a chrome trailing-link fork along with a single-sided swingarm attached to a Unit Pro-Link linkage and remote-reservoir monoshock. Braking is handled by dual Nissin three-piston calipers mounted over cross-drilled rotors up front as well as a two-piston Nissin caliper and a cross-drilled rotor at the rear.

The chrome set-back handlebar carries matching controls, grips, and mirrors as well as a Formotion Products clock and ambient temperature gauge. A digital screen housed in a chrome console atop the fuel tank displays a speedometer, a fuel-level readout, and a pair of trip meters. The digital odometer indicates 9k miles.

The liquid-cooled 1,832cc SOHC flat-six features two valves per cylinder, electronic fuel injection, and a chrome six-into-two exhaust system. Factory-rated output was 118 horsepower. The battery was replaced in May 2024, and an oil-filler cap with an integrated oil temperature gauge has been installed.
Power is transferred to the rear wheel through a hydraulically actuated clutch, a five-speed transmission, and a driveshaft enclosed within the swingarm.
Manufacturer’s literature and keys will accompany the bike.

This 2023 Dodge Challenger SRT Demon 170 is #1,066 of approximately 3,300 examples built for the model year and is finished in F8 Green over black Alcantara and Laguna leather. The car is equipped with the Premium Group equipment package, Air-Catcher HID headlights, an Air-Grabber hood, flared quarter panels, four-piston Brembo brake calipers, 18″ front and 17″ rear forged aluminum wheels, heated and ventilated front seats, dual-zone climate control, and a Harman Kardon sound system. The car is powered by a supercharged 6.2-liter Hemi High-Output V8 producing up to 1,025 horsepower and 945 lb-ft of torque, which is sent to the rear wheels via a TorqueFlite eight-speed automatic transmission and a limited-slip differential. Acquired by the selling dealer in November 2023, this SRT Demon 170 has 20 miles and is now offered with a window sticker, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Michigan title.

Dodge released seven different Last Call special editions for the 2023 model year to celebrate the end of production of the Charger and Challenger, and the Demon 170 was the final special edition variant. This example is finished in F8 Green (PFQ) and features an Air-Grabber hood with a satin black graphic and “Alcohol Injected” lettering on the hood-scoop bezel. Other exterior details include a front splitter that has retained its yellow scuff guards, Air-Catcher HID headlights, flared rear quarter panels, dual exhaust outlets, and an SRT Performance rear spoiler with an integrated rearview camera.

Black 18″ front and 17″ rear forged aluminum wheels are mounted with Mickey Thompson tires. Stopping power is provided by black four-piston Brembo calipers with yellow SRT lettering over ventilated discs. The Demon 170 is equipped with an edition-specific Drag Mode suspension with adaptive-damping shocks as well as launch control, a line lock, and a revised transbrake.

The heated and ventilated front seats and the rear bench are upholstered in black Alcantara and Laguna leather complemented by carbon-fiber trim on the dashboard and center console. The optional Premium Group adds a suede headliner, a premium-stitched dash panel, a blind spot monitoring system, rear cross-path detection, and an 18-speaker Harman Kardon audio system with a trunk-mounted subwoofer. Other amenities include remote start, dual-zone climate control, and UConnect infotainment with navigation, Android Auto, and Apple CarPlay capability. Demon 170 models left the factory with a reduced amount of sound-deadening materials compared to the standard Challenger.
A plaque below the passenger air vent identifies this Demon 170 as #1,066.

Shift paddles are affixed to the rear of the Alcantara-wrapped multifunction steering wheel, which frames a red 220-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and a 7″ configurable digital display. The digital odometer indicates 20 miles.

The 6.2-liter Hemi High-Output V8 is equipped with a 3.0-liter supercharger with a 3.02″ pulley and a 105mm throttle body in addition to revised fueling system components, Nitride-coated intake valves, copper-lead bearings, and upgraded cylinder head studs when compared to the previous Demon model. The horsepower rating adjusts automatically based on the ethanol percentage in the fuel, and output ranges from 900 horsepower and 810 lb-ft of torque with conventional E10 fuel to 1,025 horsepower and 945 lb-ft of torque when using E85. The engine is also equipped with an SRT Power Chiller, which utilizes the air conditioning refrigerant to cool the air entering the intake ports.
A “Last Call” plaque is affixed under the hood near the driver-side headlight.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a TorqueFlite eight-speed automatic transmission and a 3.09:1 limited-slip differential with a strengthened housing and a 240mm ring gear. The Demon 170 also features an improved rear prop shaft and 43-spline rear half shafts.
The window sticker notes initial delivery to Crown Chrysler Dodge Jeep Ram in Holland, Michigan, and lists factory equipment, colors, options, and a total price of $123,041.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1989 Porsche 944 Turbo is powered by a turbocharged 2.5-liter inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transaxle and is finished in Guards Red over beige leather. Equipment includes the M030 sport suspension package, 16″ Club Sport alloy wheels, a limited-slip differential, pop-up headlights, fog lights, power-adjustable front seats, a sunroof, an alarm system, cruise control, and air conditioning. The car was initially sold in North Carolina and was purchased by the seller in September 2019. This 944 Turbo now shows 29k miles, and it is offered with initial purchase documents, the owner’s manual, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean North Carolina title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in Guards Red and features a tilting sunroof with a removable panel as well as pop-up headlights, fog lights, a rear window wiper, and a rear spoiler. The front bumper is said to have been refinished.

The 16″ Club Sport alloy wheels are mounted with Bridgestone Potenza RE-11 tires. The car is equipped with the M030 sport suspension package that includes adjustable Koni shocks, height-adjustable front spring perches, and larger sway bars. The seller notes the brake fluid was flushed prior to sale.

The cabin features power-adjustable front seats and split-folding rear seats upholstered in beige leather along with a color-coordinated lower dashboard, center console, door panel inserts, and carpeting. Amenities include driver seat power lumbar support, an alarm system, cruise control, power windows and locks, dual front airbags, and an air conditioning system that has been converted to utilize R134a refrigerant. The AC system was recharged in preparation for the sale. The radio has been removed.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 180-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature, turbo boost pressure, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 29k miles, approximately 150 of which were added under current ownership.

The turbocharged 2.5-liter inline-four was factory rated at 247 horsepower and 258 lb-ft of torque. The timing belt, a balance belt, the belt tensioner rollers, a balance shaft gear, and the water pump were replaced in July 2018. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. The clutch master cylinder and slave cylinder were replaced in June 2019, the muffler was replaced in February 2022, and the transmission fluid were replaced in preparation for the sale.
Decoding the option sticker reveals the following information:
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 1971 Honda Z50A Mini Trail was refurbished under previous ownership and was acquired by the seller in 2015. Finished in Mexican Yellow with white accents, the bike is powered by a 49cc single paired with a three-speed semi-automatic transmission. Features include a Keihin carburetor, an upswept exhaust, a kick starter, drum brakes, 8″ steel wheels, chrome fenders, trail lighting, twist-lock handlebars, and a black vinyl seat. This Z50A Mini Trail is offered at no reserve in New York with a bill of sale.

The frame, fork, and bodywork were stripped to bare metal during the aforementioned refurbishment and were refinished in Mexican Yellow with white accents. Details include chrome fenders, trail lighting, a height-adjustable black vinyl seat, and a side stand.
Multi-piece 8″ steel wheels wear Golden Boy tires. An inverted fork with black gaiters comprises the bike’s only suspension. Braking is handled by front and rear drums.
The twist-lock folding handlebars carry a twist-grip throttle on the right and a run switch on the left. No instrumentation is present, therefore total mileage is unknown.

The rebuilt 49cc four-stroke single was bored 0.5mm over and a valve job was performed before the engine was reassembled with a replacement piston and valves. Features include a Keihin carburetor, a kick starter, and an upswept exhaust system with chrome heat shields.
Power is routed to the rear wheel through a three-speed semi-automatic transmission and a drive chain with a chrome guard.

This 1968 Mercedes-Benz 280SL is a Euro-market example that is powered by a 2.8-liter inline-six paired with a four-speed manual transmission and is finished in white over black upholstery. Equipment includes a black convertible top, a removable hardtop, power steering, 14″ steel wheels with painted covers, a cassette stereo, and a heater. This W113 SL is now offered in California by the selling dealer at no reserve with partial service records and a clean Colorado title.

The W113 SL was designed by Friedrich Geiger, Béla Barényi, and Paul Bracq and was introduced to the public at the 1963 Geneva Motor Show. This example is finished in white and features a black soft top, a removable hardtop, fog lights, a retractable antenna, a driver-side mirror, and European-specification headlights. Tears in the soft top, dents, peeling paint, chips, and other blemishes are shown up close in the gallery.

The 14″ steel wheels feature covers with painted centers and are mounted with 195/75 Peerless Presidential Touring tires up front and and 185R14 Michelin Rainforce MX4 rubber out back. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is provided by power-assisted four-wheel discs.

The cabin houses bucket seats upholstered in black along with matching carpets and door panels. Interior appointments include a cassette stereo, an analog clock, a floor-mounted gear shifter, and a heater. The seller notes that the driver’s window occasionally sticks.

The two-spoke steering wheel features a chrome horn ring and frames a 140-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 43k miles, and total mileage is unknown.
The 2.8-liter M130 inline-six was factory equipped with Bosch fuel injection and was rated at 195 horsepower and 195 lb-ft of torque when new. The hood insulation pad is missing.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission.

This 1999 Chevrolet Tahoe LT is powered by a replacement 5.7-liter V8 that was overhauled in preparation for the sale and is linked with a four-speed automatic transmission, an AutoTrac four-wheel-drive system, and a locking rear differential. The truck is finished in Victory Red over gray leather and features the Trailering and Comfort and Security packages, five-spoke 17″ alloy wheels, Bilstein shock absorbers, heated and power-adjustable front seats, air conditioning, and an AM/FM/cassette stereo. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2023, this GMT400 Tahoe now shows 201k miles and is offered at no reserve with recent service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Oregon title.

This four-door example is finished in Victory Red (74U) and features front tow hooks, chrome bumpers and Westin tubular side steps, heated side mirrors, a cab visor, window visors, roof rails, rear barn doors, and a receiver hitch and trailer wiring harness.

This is a relist after the vehicle was previously sold on BaT in May 2024 and the winning bidder was unable to follow through with their commitment to purchase due to circumstances outside of their control. This was not due to any fault with the vehicle and the winner’s buyer’s fee was refunded.

Five-spoke 17″ alloy wheels from a later model are mounted with 265/70 Goodyear Wrangler SR-A tires. The truck is equipped with front and rear 46mm high-pressure gas shocks as part of the Comfort and Security Package, and braking is handled by front discs and rear drums.

The heated and power-adjustable front seats and folding rear bench are trimmed in gray leather and joined by a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Appointments include keyless entry, Homelink, front and rear cabin air conditioning, cruise control, an AM/FM/cassette stereo, and power windows, mirrors, and locks. The carpets are stained.

The airbag steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, voltage, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The six-digit odometer shows 201k miles, approximately 500 of which were added by the selling dealer.

A replacement 5.7-liter Vortec V8 was rebuilt and installed in March 2024. The overhaul involved installing remanufactured cylinder heads, honing the cylinders, polishing the crankshaft, and replacing the rear main seal, camshaft and bearings, main and connecting rod bearings, piston rings, rocker arms, push rods, and intake manifold gaskets. Additional work consisted of installing a high-volume oil pump and changing the timing chain and gears, spark plugs, ignition wires, and distributor cap and rotor as well as performing fluid changes.

Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission with overdrive as well as an AutoTrac four-wheel-drive system and a locking rear differential with 3.73:1 gearing.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 1998 Bentley Continental T is one of 14 North American Regional Special Edition (RSE) examples produced for the model year. The car is powered by a turbocharged 6.75-liter V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission and is finished in Blue Sequin Mica over blue and tan leather. Equipment includes a self-leveling rear suspension, 18″ chrome-plated five-spoke wheels, four-wheel disc brakes, power-adjustable side mirrors, an Alpine navigation system, heated power-adjustable front bucket seats, and dual-zone automatic climate control. The current owner purchased the car in 2022 and has since added approximately 2k of the 54k miles. This Continental T is now offered on dealer consignment with a clean New York title.

The Mulliner Park Ward-built body is finished in Blue Sequin Mica, and exterior details include quad headlights, flared wheel arches, polished headlight surrounds, and power-adjustable side mirrors. Some of the selling dealer’s photos date to November 2023.

The 18″ chrome-plated five-spoke wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport A/S 3+ tires measuring 285/40, and braking is handled by anti-lock discs at each corner. The car came equipped from the factory with a self-leveling rear suspension.

The heated power-adjustable front bucket seats are trimmed in tan and blue leather with burl walnut veneer dashboard and door panel accents. Amenities include an Alpine navigation system, front-seat position memory settings, push-button start, drilled alloy pedals, and dual-zone automatic climate control.

The leather-wrapped four-spoke steering wheel frames a 170-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 4,500-rpm redline, while gauges housed in the center stack display turbo boost, oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, voltage, fuel level, and outside temperature. The digital odometer indicates 54k miles, approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership.
Power is from a turbocharged 6.75-liter V8.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a 4L80-E four-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.
listing_details: Royal Blue Carpet and Dashboard Upholstery

description: This 1990 BMW 325i convertible is powered by a 2.5-liter inline-six paired with a four-speed automatic transmission and is finished in black over matching leatherette upholstery. The car is equipped with a black soft top, 14″ basketweave wheels, fog lights, heated front sport seats, a Pioneer CD stereo, an onboard computer, and air conditioning. The car spent time in several states before the current owner’s acquisition in 2016, and it now shows 143k miles. This E30 convertible is now offered at no reserve by the seller on behalf of the owner with a service manual, spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title in the owner’s name.

The car is finished in black and features a matching convertible soft top that is said to have been replaced. Equipment includes fog lights, painted mirror caps, tinted side windows, a power antenna, and twin exhaust outlets. The seller reports that both doors appear to have been repainted. Bubbles are visible in the paint on the right door, blemishes are shown under the left-side mirror, there is a dent in the hood, a scuff is noted on the right corner of the front bumper, and additional photos of the exterior condition are viewable in the gallery below.
The 14″ basketweave wheels are mounted with 195/65 Vredestein Sportrac 5 tires. The car is equipped with an independent suspension and power-assisted four-wheel disc brakes with vented front rotors.

The cabin features heated front sport seats and the rear bench are trimmed in black leatherette upholstery. Interior amenities include air conditioning, an onboard computer, a Pioneer CD stereo, BMW-branded floor mats, and power windows, locks, and side mirrors. An area of discoloration is visible on the bottom of the right-front seat, the cruise control is inoperative, and the ambient air temperature sensor does not work.

The four-spoke steering wheel fronts a 150-mph speedometer and a 7k-rpm tachometer as well as gauges for coolant temperature, fuel level, and instant fuel economy. The six-digit odometer shows 143k approximately 25,000 of which were added under current ownership. Wear is visible on the steering wheel.
The 2.5-liter M20 inline-six features Bosch fuel injection and was factory rated at 168 horsepower and 164 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed at approximately 142k miles.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission.
A service manual, a replacement trunk roundel, a spare center console and taillight, and two speakers are included in the sale.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists history in California, Illinois, Georgia, and Texas from an initial entry in August 1993.
The current California title was signed and dated in July 2023.

This 2016 Porsche Cayman GT4 is finished in Racing Yellow over black leather and Alcantara and is powered by a 3.8-liter flat-six linked with a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. Equipment includes body-color interior trim and stitching as well as hardback sport seats, satin black 20″ GT4 wheels, a rear wing, and bi-xenon headlights with PDLS. The car has spent time in multiple states and now has under 4,300 miles. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this 981 Cayman GT4 is now offered with a clean Carfax report and a clean Kentucky title.

This example is finished in Racing Yellow and equipped with bi-xenon headlights in black with the Porsche Dynamic Light System (PDLS) as well as side air intakes, revised front and rear bumper covers, GT4 badging, central dual exhaust outlets, and a rear wing with black supports and endplate graphics.

Satin black 20″ GT4 alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires with date codes from 2015. Braking is handled by four-wheel cross-drilled and ventilated discs with red-painted Porsche-branded calipers. The GT4 utilized front suspension components from the 991.1 GT3 as well as a specially tuned multi-link rear setup, Porsche Stability Management (PSM), Porsche Torque Vectoring (PTV), and PASM adaptive dampers.

The cockpit features hardback sport seats upholstered in black leather and Alcantara with Racing Yellow stitching and GT4-script headrest embroidery. The car was also ordered with Racing Yellow interior trim and seatbelts as well as a fire extinguisher mounted in the passenger footwell.

The three-spoke sport steering wheel features a yellow centering stripe and frames a GT4-branded central tachometer with a 7,600-rpm redline as well as a 200-mph speedometer and a digital display. The digital odometer indicates under 4,300 miles.
The rear cargo area covers the mid-mounted 3.8L flat-six, which was shared with the contemporary 991 Carrera S and was factory rated at 385 horsepower and 309 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2008 Ducati Monster S4R S is #159 of 400 Tricolore examples produced, and it is finished in Italy’s national colors. Powered by a 998cc Testastretta L-twin paired with a six-speed transmission, the bike is equipped with carbon-fiber trim, adjustable Öhlins suspension, Brembo brake calipers, a tinted windscreen, 17″ Marchesini wheels, frame and fork sliders, a black Sargent seat with red piping and a painted tail cowl, and a two-into-two exhaust system with carbon-fiber Termignoni mufflers. Purchased by the seller on BaT in April 2023, this Monster S4RS has 11k miles and is now offered in Nevada with literature and a clean Florida title in the seller’s name.

All Monster Tricolore examples feature a red, white, and green-painted tank and a matching rear cowl mounted over a Fabio Taglioni-designed tubular steel trellis frame. Features include a tinted windscreen, rear-set foot controls, a carbon-fiber front fender and accents, frame and fork sliders, a black Sargent seat with red piping, and a side stand. The seller notes the bike was dropped on the right side in July 2023 which resulted in scuffs and scrapes on engine slider, foot peg, rear brake lever and exhaust pipe heat guard, photos of which can be viewed in the gallery.

The 17″ Marchesini ten-spoke wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Power 2CT tires. Braking is handled by Brembo calipers mounted over twin 320mm discs up front and a single inboard disc at the rear. The fully-adjustable Öhlins suspension includes a 43mm inverted front fork with titanium nitride-plated legs as well as a monoshock connected to the aluminum single-sided swingarm via a progressive linkage.

The silver-finished alloy handlebar is secured aft of an instrument panel housing a white-dial 160-mph speedometer, a matching tachometer, and a bank of indicator lights. The digital odometer indicates 11k miles.
A plaque affixed to the left side of the engine denotes the bike as #159 of 400 S4R S Tricolores produced.

The liquid-cooled 998cc Testastretta L-twin features a desmodromic valvetrain, an oil cooler, an electric starter, and a two-into-two exhaust system with slip-on Termignoni carbon fiber mufflers. Work performed in February 2023 included replacing the timing belts, installing a K&N air filter, flushing the coolant, and changing the oil. The throttle position sensor was changed in December 2023.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a multi-plate dry clutch, a six-speed transmission, and a drive chain. The clutch master cylinder was flushed in February 2023.
Manufacturer’s literature, keys, and a rear stand will accompany the motorcycle.

This 1938 American Bantam Model 60 Speedster is a disassembled project that was reportedly sold new in Connecticut to the captain of the destroyer that the seller’s father served on during World War II. It was gifted by him to the seller’s family in 1948 and was used as a summer car before it spent several decades in storage. The car retains a 45ci inline-four that is said to have been rebuilt in the 2010s as well as a three-speed manual transmission. The fenders were finished in primer in preparation for the sale. This American Bantam project is now offered at no reserve in New Bern, North Carolina, with parts, parts invoices, literature, and a bill of sale.

The American Austin Car Company was founded in 1929 in Butler, Pennsylvania, and built an American version of the British Austin Seven until filing for bankruptcy in 1934. The company was revived the following year by former Austin salesman Roy Evans, who commissioned designer Alexis de Sakhnoffsky to restyle the Seven into the American Bantam before production resumed in 1937. This example is said to have been delivered from the factory in black, and it was repainted using yellow lacquer in the 1970s. The fenders were were coated in primer in 2024. Parts, including a grille, headlights with Stablite lenses, a windshield frame, and taillights can be seen in the gallery. The bumpers are missing along with the convertible frame and top.

The steel wheels were sandblasted and primed in 2008 before they were powder-coated black. They are mounted with BFGoodrich Silvertown whitewall bias-ply tires that were ordered from Coker Tire and installed approximately 10 years ago. Included Bantam-branded chrome hubcaps and trim rings can be seen in the gallery. The cable-actuated four-wheel drum brakes were reportedly serviced and adjusted in the 2010s, and replacement wheel bearings and grease seals were installed at that time.

The floors in the stripped cabin were reportedly coated with fiberglass and painted with POR-15 during the 2010s. A three-spoke steering wheel is fitted along with a Bantam-branded combination gauge. Bucket seat shells are included in the sale and can be seen in the gallery along with removed red upholstery sections, an ignition switch and key, rubber pedal covers, and the removed speedometer, which includes a five-digit odometer showing 13k miles.

The 45ci inline-four was fitted with replacement head studs and rod bolts from American Racing Products in the 2010s  as well as grease seals, spark plugs, ignition points, and a Tillotson carburetor. The cylinder head and intake manifold were resurfaced, and the radiator was also re-cored at that time. A replacement six-volt battery was installed in 2023, and the starter was rebuilt in 2024. The seller notes that the radiator mounting brackets will require repairs.

The car retains its floor-shifted three-speed manual transmission and rear axle as well as front transverse and rear semi-elliptical leaf springs. The underside was coated with POR-15 during the 2010s, while the fuel tank was cleaned and coated with epoxy.
The car does not have a title and is being sold as a project on a bill of sale.

This 1997 Jaguar XK8 coupe has 72k miles, and it is finished in Sapphire Metallic over Cream leather upholstery. Powered by a 4.0-liter V8 linked with a five-speed automatic transmission, the car is equipped with 17″ alloy wheels, anti-lock disc brakes, fog lights, tinted windows, burl wood interior trim, heated power-adjustable front seats, automatic climate control, cruise control, and a cassette stereo linked with a trunk-mounted CD changer. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this XK8 coupe is now offered at no reserve in Florida with a driver’s handbook, a clean Carfax report, and a Pennsylvania title.

Sapphire Metallic (JGE) paint finishes the exterior, and equipment includes fog lights, power-adjustable side mirrors, a retractable antenna, tinted windows, and chrome-finished dual exhaust outlets. There are scrapes on the underside of the front bumper cover.

The 17″ alloy wheels are wrapped in 245/50 Pirelli P Zero Asimmetrico front and Pirelli Cinturato P7 rear tires. The car is equipped with traction and stability control, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel ventilated disc brakes.

The heated power-adjustable front bucket seats are upholstered in Cream leather. that extends to the center console and door panel inserts. Wood veneer trim accents the cabin, and additional appointments include driver’s seat memory settings, cruise control, automatic climate control, and a cassette stereo linked with a trunk-mounted six-disc CD changer.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 170-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,750-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 72k miles.
The 4.0-liter AJ V8 was factory-rated at 290 horsepower and 290 lb-ft of torque, which is sent to the rear wheels through a ZF five-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The current Pennsylvania title lists a “Classic” brand.

This 2002 Porsche Boxster S has 4k miles and remained with its previous owner in Illinois from 2005 until 2024. It is finished in Speed Yellow over black partial leather and is powered by a 3.2-liter flat-six paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. Features include the Sport Package, a black soft top, factory 18″ Turbo-look wheels, a speed-activated rear spoiler, xenon headlights, heated power-adjustable seats, and a Hi-Fi sound system. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this 986 Boxster S is now offered in New Jersey at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a clean Illinois title.

The car is finished in Speed Yellow (12H) and features a power-operated black soft top. Additional exterior details comprise xenon headlights, a speed-activated rear spoiler, side air intakes, and roll hoops.

Factory 18″ Turbo-look wheels are mounted with older Dunlop tires. Braking is handled by red four-piston Porsche-branded calipers fitted over cross-drilled rotors at all four corners, and the car is equipped with Porsche Stability Management (PSM).

The cabin features heated power-adjustable seats upholstered in black leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Features include driver’s seat-position memory settings, a wind deflector, a Hi-Fi sound system, cruise control, and automatic climate control. The Carfax report notes ignition switch and window motor replacement in July 2024.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a central tachometer, a 180-mph speedometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates just under 4k miles.
The mid-mounted 3.2L flat-six was factory rated at 250 horsepower and 225 lb-ft of torque. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle.
Decoding the option sticker reveals the following information:
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage, and it notes at least one recall.
Interested to see what Car and Driver thought about the 986 Boxster S when it was new? Click here to check out their January 2000 Road Test.

This 1998 Ferrari F355 Berlinetta shows 19k miles following registration history in Washington and California, and it was purchased by its current owner in June 2003. An engine-out belt service was performed in March 2024. The car is finished in Titanium Silver over blue Connolly leather, and it is powered by a 3.5-liter DOHC V8 linked with a paddle-shifted six-speed F1 gearbox. Features include a Tubi Style muffler, 18″ five-spoke magnesium wheels, pop-up headlights, a Challenge-style rear grille, a Kenwood stereo, and automatic climate control. This F355 Berlinetta is now offered on dealer consignment with the owner’s manual, service records, a tool kit, luggage, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title

The Pininfarina-designed body is finished in Titanium Silver, and styling elements include pop-up headlights, integrated front fog lights, an integrated rear decklid spoiler, quad exhaust outlets, a vented engine cover, a Challenge-style rear grille, and air intakes on the doors and rocker panels. The right headlight lifter motor was replaced earlier this year.

The 18″ five-spoke magnesium wheels are mounted with Pirelli P Zero tires. Ferrari-branded brake calipers are mounted over ventilated discs at each corner. The brake and power steering fluids were changed in March 2024.

The cabin features sport seats trimmed in blue Connolly leather, and matching leather extends to the center console, door panel inserts, and dashboard. Amenities include automatic climate control, a Kenwood stereo, and drilled aluminum pedals. The air conditioning system was recharged in March 2024.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel is equipped with paddle shifters and frames a 200-mph speedometer, a 10k-rpm tachometer, a gauge for coolant temperature, and a digital gear indicator. Ancillary instruments in the center stack include an analog clock and gauges for fuel level and oil pressure. The six-digit odometer shows 19k miles, approximately 3k of which were added under current ownership.

The mid-mounted 3.5-liter DOHC V8 features five valves per cylinder and dry-sump lubrication for a factory-rated output of 375 horsepower and 268 lb-ft of torque. A Tubi Style muffler has been fitted. An engine-out belt service was completed in March 2024, and additional work included oil and coolant exchanges and replacing the battery, fuel filter, camshaft seals, air filters, spark plugs, and trunk and engine lid struts.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through an electrohydraulically operated six-speed F1 gearbox. The transaxle fluid was changed in March 2024.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.
The car most recently passed a California emissions test in February 2024, however, the Tubi Style muffler installed is not CARB-compliant.

This 1948 Willys-Overland sedan delivery is a non-running project truck that is said to have been stored on blocks in a Quonset hut in North Dakota for more than 35 years before being purchased out of Montana by the seller’s late uncle in 2014. Subsequent work involved sourcing a custom frame from Art Morrison Enterprises, stripping the body, installing a 6.2-liter LS3 V8 and a 4L65-E four-speed automatic transmission, adapting Strange Engineering independent front and rear suspension, fitting 1930s Dodge gauges, strengthening the fenders and the hood, and sourcing Detroit Steel Wheel 20″ artillery-style wheels, Wilwood brakes, Vintage Air climate control, and custom valve covers. This Willys project is now offered at no reserve by the seller with a binder of build records and various parts as well as power-of-attorney documentation and a Nebraska title in the uncle’s name.

The body was removed from the frame and stripped using an acid-dipping process before being mounted to a custom-ordered frame from Art Morrison Enterprises. Fabrication work performed by No Coast Custom and Rod Shop of Lincoln, Nebraska, included reinforcing the fenders and the hood with double walls. Other equipment includes swing-out rear doors, So-Cal Speed Shop dual side mirrors, custom front and rear bumpers, custom headlights and taillights, refurbished hood latches, Detroit Speed windshield wipers, and replacement glass.

Detroit Steel Wheel Co. Ambassador/Artillery 20″ wheels with chrome hubcaps are mounted with 245/40 Nexen N5000 Plus tires in the front and 295/40 Nexen Roadian HP tires in the rear. A Strange Engineering independent front suspension includes adjustable coilovers and an anti-roll bar, while the Strange Engineering four-link rear suspension utilizes coilovers and a Panhard bar. Power-assisted steering is based on an Opel-sourced rack and pinion. Wilwood disc brakes at each corner are augmented by a Wilwood ProSpindle kit.

The bucket seats have been stripped of upholstery, and the floors were modified. Parts were purchased and preparations made for the vehicle to have six-way-power-adjustable seats as well as power windows, power door locks, and Vintage Air climate control.
A 1934 Dodge gauge surround and 1933 Dodge gauges are installed in a fabricated dashboard. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 65k miles, and true mileage is unknown.

The 6.2-liter LS3 V8 was purchased from Friesen Chevrolet of Sutton, Nebraska, in 2015. Other equipment includes custom valve covers, a custom wiring harness, Billet Specialities pulleys and engine mounts, an AFCO radiator, exhaust headers, and a custom fuel cell.
A 4L65-E Supermatic four-speed automatic transmission is paired with a Strange Engineering rear end with 31-spline axles.

A sketch of the intended finished project—produced by No Coast Custom and Rod Shop—is shown above. More than 100 pages of receipts are pictured in the gallery below and said to exceed $140,000; a video of the seller’s uncle describing the build and the receipts is provided below.

The Nebraska Department of Motor Vehicles has assigned a VIN to the vehicle, which no longer has a factory-applied identification plate. The title cites the number on the tag shown above (which is not attached to the vehicle) and lists the Year as 2015, the Make as “Asmbld Vehicle”, the Model as “1948 Willys Sedan Dlvry”, and the color as an abbreviation for black. The title also bears a Notice that reads: “This vehicle may be subject to an undisclosed interest bond number 150209″.

This 1993 Chevrolet Corvette convertible was initially delivered to Grey Chevrolet in Port Orchard, Washington, and it has remained in that state under the care of its original owner and their family until 2023. Indicating 32k miles, the car is equipped with the 40th Anniversary Appearance Package and is finished in Ruby Red Metallic over matching leather upholstery. It is powered by a 5.7-liter LT1 V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission, and equipment includes 17″ sawblade alloy wheels, a limited-slip differential, Selective Ride and Handling, a ruby red convertible soft top, a removable hardtop, fog lights, power-adjustable sport seats, a Bose CD/cassette stereo, and automatic climate control. Acquired by the selling dealer in April 2023, this 40th Anniversary C4 convertible is offered in Oregon at no reserve with a window sticker, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Washington title.

The car is finished in 40th Anniversary-exclusive Ruby Red Metallic (68) and features a ruby red convertible soft top, a removable hardtop, 40th Anniversary fender badging, pop-up headlights, integrated fog lights, a Corvette-branded front plate cover, quad taillights, and dual polished exhaust outlets. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

Polished 17″ sawblade alloy wheels are fitted with Continental ExtremeContact tires that were mounted in 2023. The car is equipped with Selective Ride and Handling as well as traction control. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel ventilated discs with ABS.

The cabin features power-adjustable sport bucket seats trimmed in Ruby Red leather with 40th Anniversary logos embroidered on the headrests as well as matching door panel inserts and carpets. Amenities include a Bose CD/cassette stereo, automatic climate control, a digital clock, and cruise control.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a central digital speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, and battery voltage. The digital odometer indicates 32k miles, approximately 100 of which were added by the selling dealer.
The 5.7-liter LT1 V8 features multi-port fuel injection and was factory rated at 300 horsepower and 340 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a limited-slip differential.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Grey Chevrolet in Port Orchard, Washington, as well as factory colors, equipment, and a total vehicle price of $48,944.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1966 Jaguar XKE Series I coupe is powered by a 4.2-liter inline-six linked to a four-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential and is finished in Carmen Red over black leather. The car is equipped with enclosed headlights, 15″ wire-spoke steel wheels, power-assisted disc brakes, triple windshield wipers, an AM/FM radio, and a heater. The current owner purchased the car in 2013, and work in 2023 involved rebuilding the carburetors, cleaning the fuel system, and replacing the brake master cylinder, battery, and spark plugs. This XKE Series I coupe is now offered on dealer consignment with a Jaguar Heritage Trust Certificate, the owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, and a clean Indiana title.

The Series I E-Types were equipped with covered headlights and taillights mounted above the chrome rear bumpers. This example is finished in Carmen Red, and additional equipment includes enclosed headlights, a louvered clamshell hood, wraparound chrome bumpers, bright trim, fender-mounted mirrors, triple windshield wipers, a side-hinged rear hatch, and dual exhaust outlets.

The 15″ wire wheels are secured by two-eared knock-offs and are mounted with Michelin X tires measuring 185R15. Braking is provided by four-wheel discs with inboard-mounted rear rotors. The brake master cylinder was replaced in 2023.

The cabin features bucket seats that have been reupholstered in black leather along with color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Interior appointments include black vinyl dash trim, a sliding rearview mirror, an AM/FM radio, and a heater.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel frames a Smiths 160-mph speedometer and 6k-rpm tachometer, while auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, fuel level, and amperage are located in the center of the dashboard. The five-digit odometer shows 69k miles, less than 1k of which were added under current ownership.

The 4.2-liter inline-six features triple SU carburetors and was factory rated at 265 horsepower and 283 lb-ft of torque. A replacement fuel tank was installed in 2014 and Pertronix electronic ignition was added in 2016. Work in 2023 included rebuilding the carburetors, cleaning the fuel system, and replacing the battery and spark plugs.
The cylinder head stamp reads 7E5425-9, and a photo of the corresponding engine block stamping is provided in the gallery.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a full-synchromesh four-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential.
The Jaguar Heritage Trust Production Record Trace certificate shows the original colors and drivetrain numbers as well as the build and dispatch dates.

This 1959 Chevrolet is a stepside Apache 3200 “big window” pickup that was assembled in Los Angeles, California. It is powered by a 235.5ci inline-six mated to a floor-shifted four-speed manual transmission, and it has power-assisted front disc brakes, a wood-lined bed, aftermarket gauges, and a heater and defroster. This Task Force pickup was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024 and is now offered at no reserve with a conditional Georgia title.

The truck was delivered in Frontier Beige, and it has been repainted black with color-coordinated bumpers. Features include a wraparound rear window, dual mirrors, a wood-lined bed, quad headlights, and quarter vent windows. Corrosion on the cab is shown in the gallery and video below.
The beige-painted 15″ steel wheels are wrapped in 235/75 Hankook Optimo HT tires. Stopping power is provided by power-assisted front disc brakes, and the truck rides on a 123″ wheelbase.
The bench seat has been trimmed in two-tone vinyl, and additional appointments include a heater and defroster, chrome hardware and knobs, and seat belts.
The three-spoke steering wheel fronts a replacement cluster. The five-digit odometer has been reset, and total mileage is unknown. The wipers and horn do not work.
The truck is powered by a 235.5ci inline-six. The truck has a 12-volt electrical system and an alternator.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission.
The Georgia title carries a notation reading “Conditional title — May not reflect all liens or other encumbrances.”

This 2019 Ural Gear Up is equipped with a factory sidecar and powered by a 749cc opposed twin mated with a four-speed transmission with a reverse gear and selectable two-wheel drive. It is finished in matte green over tan upholstery and is equipped with an IMZ leading-link fork, preload-adjustable shocks, Brembo disc brakes, 19″ alloy rims, and both kick and electric starters, and the sidecar features an optionally driven wheel, a luggage rack, front and rear guards, auxiliary lighting, a jerry can, and a spare wheel and mounted tire. This Gear Up was acquired by the seller in 2023 and is now offered with a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The bodywork is finished in matte green over a black frame. Equipment includes rubber fuel tank knee bolsters, a five-gallon fuel tank, a tan solo saddle, a rear luggage rack, an engine guard, folding passenger foot pegs, passenger grab handles, and outboard turn signals.

The 19″ wire-spoke wheels with black aluminum rims are wrapped in 4.00″ Duro tires all around. Preload-adjustable suspension consists of an IMZ leading-link fork, dual Sachs shocks mounted to the swingarm, and a matching Sachs shock mounted to the sidecar’s single-sided swingarm. The disc braking system includes a cross-drilled rotor at each wheel as well as Brembo calipers, the front of which has four pistons.
The factory-equipped sidecar features a tan vinyl-upholstered seat, a clear windscreen, auxiliary lights, a side step, luggage racks, and fender-mounted lights.
A 100-mph speedometer with a digital menu display sits above the headlight bucket. The digital odometer indicates 120 miles, 50 of which have been ridden by the seller.
The air-cooled 749cc opposed twin is rated at 41 horsepower and features electronic fuel injection, kick and electric starters, and a dual exhaust system with a crossover pipe.
Power is sent to the primary or both rear wheels through a four-speed transmission with a reverse gear.

This 1981 Chevrolet Corvette is powered by a 350ci L81 V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission and is finished in gray metallic over gray leather upholstery. The car is equipped with an Edelbrock intake manifold, Flowmaster mufflers, long-tube exhaust headers, a Positraction differential, 15″ eight-slot alloy wheels, removable glass roof panels, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, an aftermarket pop-out head unit, cruise control, power windows, and air conditioning. The selling dealer acquired the car in 2024 and recent work consisted of replacing the calipers and brake pads. This C3 Corvette is now offered at no reserve with a roof panel carrier and a Maryland title.

The car is finished in metallic gray and is said to have been repainted under prior ownership. Exterior details include removable glass T-top roof panels, pop-up headlights, side marker lights, fender air vents, sport mirrors, polished exhaust finishers, and quad taillights. A June 2005 Carfax entry notes damage to the front left of the vehicle.

The 15″ eight-slot alloy wheels are mounted with 245/60 Bfgoodrich Radial T/A white-letter tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel power-assisted discs. The brake pads and calipers are said to have been replaced recently.

The twin bucket seats are trimmed in gray leather along with a color-matching dash, center console, door panels, and carpeting. Woodgrain trim lines the center console, center stack, and instrument cluster, and interior amenities include a power-adjustable driver’s seat, a pop-out aftermarket head unit, cruise control, power windows, a tilting steering column, and air conditioning.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel frames an 85-mph speedometer and a 7k-rpm tachometer. Gauges for coolant temperature, oil temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level are located in the center stack. The five-digit odometer shows 15k miles, approximately 150 of which were added under current ownership. The Carfax report indicates a mileage entry of 89k in 2007, and the total miles are unknown.

The 350ci L81 V8 is said to have been rebuilt circa 2015 and is fitted with an Edelbrock Performer intake manifold, an HEI distributor, and long-tube exhaust headers. An oil change was performed recently.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission and a Positraction differential. Flowmaster chambered mufflers have been fitted. The transmission fluid was changed recently.
The Carfax report shows an accident report and lists the aforementioned odometer rollover.
The Maryland title lists a “Duplicate or Corrected” notation.

This 2010 Porsche Panamera S is finished in Carbon Grey Metallic over Luxor Beige full leather and is powered by a 4.8-liter V8 paired with a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch automatic transmission. Equipment includes the Sport Chrono Plus and Walnut Interior packages as well as 22″ Gianelle wheels, an aftermarket exhaust system, heated and adaptive power-adjustable front sport seats, a Bose sound system, and Porsche Dynamic Chassis Control with Porsche Torque Vectoring Plus. The car has remained registered in California since new and now has 93k miles. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this Panamera S is now offered at no reserve with an accident-free Carfax report and a clean California title.

The car is finished in Carbon Grey Metallic (M9Z) and is equipped with xenon headlights, a sunroof, front and rear ParkAssist, a speed-activated rear spoiler, and quad exhaust outlets. The headlight lenses are damaged and other blemishes are visible around the body.

The 22″ Gianelle Dilijan wheels are mounted with Lexani LX-Twenty tires measuring 265/30 up front and 295/25 out back. The left-rear tire has sidewall damage and multiple wheels have curb marks. The car was ordered with an adaptive air suspension, Power Steering Plus, and Porsche Dynamic Chassis Control (PDCC) with Porsche Torque Vectoring Plus (PTV+). Stopping power is provided by red calipers over slotted and ventilated discs at each corner. Air suspension repairs are noted on the Carfax report in July 2017 along with ABS sensor, lower control arm, and sway bar bushing replacement in December 2017.

The cabin features seating surfaces upholstered in Luxor Beige leather that extends to the dashboard, center consoles, and door panels. Additional appointments include heated and adaptive power-adjustable front sport seats as well as walnut wood trim, a Bose sound system, dual-zone automatic climate control, and Porsche Communication Management (PCM).

The heated leather-wrapped steering wheel has a pair of shifter switches and fronts a central tachometer with a 6,600-rpm redline, a 200-mph speedometer, and a configurable display as well as gauges for oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 93k miles. Instrument panel repairs are noted on the Carfax report in September 2010.

The 4.8-liter V8 was factory rated at 400 horsepower and 369 lb-ft of torque. Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch automatic transmission. An aftermarket exhaust system is installed.
The Carfax report notes at least one recall.
The car most recently passed a California emissions inspection in 2021.

This 1978 Ford Ranchero GT Brougham was reportedly purchased new by an acquaintance of the owner and was acquired by the owner in 1999. Subsequent work consisted of repainting the vehicle in 2005 and servicing the fuel system in 2022. Finished in Champagne Metallic with white GT stripes over brown vinyl upholstery, the vehicle is powered by a 351ci V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes power steering, power front disc brakes, Magnum 500-style wheels, the Brougham Decor Group, a Pioneer cassette stereo, cruise control, and air conditioning. This Ranchero is now offered on dealer consignment at no reserve in Yucca Valley, California, with manufacturer’s literature, service records, and a clean California title.
The vehicle was repainted in Champagne Metallic circa 2005 and details include white GT stripes, quad headlights, rubber bumper guards, chrome bumpers, side markers, and dual sport mirrors.
The Magnum 500-style 14″ wheels wear bright trim rings and are wrapped in 225/70 Futura GLS Super Sport white-letter tires. Work in 2012 consisted of replacing the shocks and servicing the brakes.

The bucket seats are trimmed in brown vinyl upholstery joined by a color-coordinated dashboard pad and door panels. Equipment includes the Brougham Decor Group, a Pioneer cassette stereo, cruise control, air conditioning, three-point seatbelts, and clear rubber floormats. There are tears in both seat covers.

The two-spoke steering wheel fronts an 85-mph speedometer, a tachometer, an analog clock, and auxiliary gauges. The odometer indicates 60k miles, approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership.

The 351ci V8 was factory rated at 149 horsepower and 275 lb-ft of torque. Work in 2022 consisted of servicing the fuel system, tuning the carburetor, and replacing the battery. The vehicle most recently passed a Smog Check in July 2024.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels via a three-speed Ford FMX automatic transmission.
The vehicle is registered as Planned Non-operation in the state of California and may be subject to fees.
listing_details: Champagne Metallic Paint w/White GT Stripes

description: This 1981 Volkswagen Jetta coupe was modified in the 1980s and 90s by a prior owner, who reportedly used the European Jetta GTi as inspiration. A 2.0-liter Audi 3A block was mated to a solid-lifter cylinder head and a G-grind camshaft, and it was paired with a Rabbit GTI five-speed manual transaxle. Additional modifications include a Leistritz exhaust system, H&R coilovers, 15″ BBS RM wheels, and 16V brake components in addition to European bumpers, Hella horns, König front seats, and a MOMO steering wheel. Finished in Mexico Beige over a tan and brown interior, the car is further equipped with a sunroof, a power antenna, and an Audiobahn cassette stereo. Previously registered in California, the vehicle was purchased by its current owner in 2003 and relocated to Washington State. The timing belt was replaced in 2021, and the oil was changed in preparation for the sale. Showing 15k miles, this Jetta is now offered on dealer consignment in Oregon with parts and service records, spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Washington title.

The car is finished in Mexico Beige with black trim and body-side moldings. Volkswagen European-specification bumpers and Hella E-code headlights have been fitted, and additional exterior details include a sunroof, a power antenna, a heated rear window, and GLI and 2.0 badging. Close-up photos of the finish are provided in the gallery below.

This is a relist after the vehicle was previously sold on BaT in July 2024 and the winning bidder failed to follow through with their commitment to purchase. This was not due to any fault with the vehicle. The winner’s participation on BaT has been restricted and their buyer’s fee was not refunded.

Silver-finished 15″ BBS RM alloy wheels are wrapped in 195/45 Toyo Extensa HP II tires. The suspension has been modified with H&R Street Performance coilovers along with a Neuspeed front chassis brace and rear sway bar, and Scirocco 16V braking components have been fitted along with a cross-drilled rotor at each corner.

König bolstered front seats are upholstered in tan leather, and the door panels and rear bench are trimmed to match. Additional appointments include an Audiobahn AM/FM/cassette stereo connected to Concord speakers as well as a heater and defroster, MOMO pedal covers, a Wolfsburg-logo leather shift knob, and a bank of auxiliary switches added to the center console.

The MOMO steering wheel wears a brown leather wrap and features a Wolfsburg-logo horn button. It frames a VDO 85-mph speedometer, a coolant-temperature gauge, and a MotoMeter 7k-rpm tachometer with an inset fuel-level gauge. Additional VDO gauges for vacuum, temperature, and pressure are housed in the center console. The six-digit odometer shows 15k miles.

The 2.0-liter inline-four was assembled in 1988-89 using a replacement Audi 80 3A block, a Volkswagen JH solid-lifter cylinder head that was ported and polished, and a G-grind camshaft. An ABD Racing Big-Bore intake system, Setrab 13-row oil cooler, dual downpipe, and Leistritz no-catalyst exhaust system have been installed, as have braided stainless-steel lines, a Neuspeed strut-tower brace, and chrome-plated valve and belt covers. The timing belt was replaced in 2021, and the oil was most recently changed in May 2024. Cylinder compression was measured at that time, and the results can be viewed in the gallery.
Power is routed to the front wheels through a replacement Rabbit GTI five-speed manual transaxle.
A color-matching Zender front valance and side skirts are included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accident or damage entries.

This 1970 Plymouth GTX hardtop is one of 7,748 examples produced for the model year, and it is said to have been refurbished around 1999, when a replacement overbored 440ci V8 was installed and the car was repainted in orange with black accents over orange vinyl upholstery. Other equipment includes a three-speed automatic transmission, a Sure-Grip differential, 3.90:1 rear-end gearing, widened rear wheels, an Air Grabber hood, a Holley carburetor, an Edelbrock intake manifold, an aluminum radiator, an auxiliary electric cooling fan, MSD ignition parts, Hooker headers, dual exhaust, power steering, front bucket seats, a center console, aftermarket auxiliary gauges, and an AM radio. This GTX was purchased by the seller in 2021 and is now offered with a spare hood and a clean Florida title in the seller’s name.

Finished from the factory in Deep Burnt Orange metallic (FK5), the car was repainted during the aforementioned refurbishment. Black stripes adorn the hood and the body sides, and the tail panel also has black accents. Other features include quad headlights, chrome bumpers, GTX badging, dual side mirrors, and dual exhaust outlets. An Air Grabber hood is currently installed, and a domed hood painted to match the car will accompany the vehicle and is pictured in the gallery below. The seller notes chips in the paint. The headlights and taillamps do not work, and the hood-mounted turn-signal indicators have been removed.

Rallye-style 15″ wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich Radial T/A tires; the rear wheels measure 10″ wide. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is provided by unassisted drums at each corner.

The front bucket seats and the rear bench are trimmed in orange vinyl, and woodgrain trim accents the dashboard and the door panels. Interior equipment includes front-seat shoulder belts, rear lap belts, a center console, an AM radio, and a heater. The lights on the center console are inoperable.

The three-spoke steering wheel has a horn ring and fronts a 150-mph speedometer and gauges for fuel level, coolant temperature, oil pressure, and amperage. An AutoMeter Phantom tachometer with a shift light is installed adjacent to the speedometer, and two aftermarket gauges for water temperature are positioned ahead of the shifter and accompanied by an aftermarket gauge for oil pressure. The five-digit odometer shows 38k miles, approximately 500 of which were added under current ownership; true mileage is unknown.

The 440ci V8 is said to have been installed by Koffel’s Place around 1999 and was bored .030″ over for a total displacement of 446ci. The engine is augmented by B1 Heads cylinder heads and valve covers, a Holley carburetor, an Edelbrock Performer RPM intake manifold, an MSD Ignition 6AL digital ignition controller, an MSD Pro-Billet Distributor, a Jacobs Electronics Ultra Coil, a BeCool aluminum radiator, an auxiliary electric cooling fan, and Hooker Super Competition headers. The belts, spark plugs, and plug wires were replaced in 2021, and the fluids were changed most recently in 2023, according to the seller.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a rebuilt TorqueFlite three-speed automatic transmission and a Sure-Grip limited-slip differential with 3.90:1 gearing. Corrosion is noted on underbody components.
Decoding the fender tag shown above reveals the following information:

This 2009 Mercedes-Benz CLK550 cabriolet was first delivered to Motorcars Acquisition in Bedford, Ohio, and it has 46k miles. Finished in black over matching leather, the car is powered by a 5.5-liter V8 paired with a seven-speed automatic transmission.
