Features include the Premium Package, a power-operated black soft top, bi-xenon headlights, 18″ split-spoke AMG aluminum alloy wheels, heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats, a six-disc CD changer, a Bose sound system, Keyless-Go, navigation, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This A209 CLK550 is now offered in Connecticut by the selling dealer at no reserve with a window sticker, owner’s manuals, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Kentucky title.

The CLK550 came equipped from the factory with an AMG front air dam, rear apron, rear trunk spoiler, and side skirts. The car is finished in black (040) and features a power-operated black convertible top, bi-xenon headlights, cornering illumination, rain-sensing windshield wipers, power-adjustable heated side mirrors, and twin polished exhaust outlets. Separation is present on the soft top.

The 18″ split-spoke AMG aluminum alloy wheels are mounted with Continental ContiSportContact tires. Close-up photos of scrapes on the wheels are included in the gallery. The car is equipped with an Electronic Stability Program (ESP) as well as an independent front and multilink rear sport suspension. Stopping power is provided by four-piston front and two-piston rear calipers.

The cabin features heated and ventilated 10-way power-adjustable front seats trimmed in black leather, which extends to the door panels. Interior amenities include burl walnut trim, front seat position memory, a glovebox-mounted six-disc CD changer, Keyless-Go, a Bose sound system, cruise control, COMAND with navigation, and dual-zone automatic climate control. Photos included in the gallery detail a broken speaker grille as well as separation on the seats.

The leather-wrapped four-spoke steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a central 160-mph speedometer with an inset digital display along with a 7k-rpm tachometer, an analog clock, and readouts for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 46k miles.
The 5.5-liter M273 DOHC 32-valve V8 was factory rated at 382 horsepower and 391 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a seven-speed automatic transmission with Touch Shift.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Motorcars Acquisition in Bedford, Ohio, along with factory equipment, colors, and a total retail price of $73,615.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.

This 1988 Dodge Daytona spent time in Ohio through the selling dealers acquisition in 2024. Finished in Twilight Blue Pearl over Twilight Blue cloth upholstery, it is powered by a turbocharged 2.2-liter inline-four paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. The car is equipped with four-wheel disc brakes, 15″ alloy wheels, pop-up headlights, a rear spoiler, “Enthusiast” front seats, an 18-way power-adjustable driver seat, air conditioning, crank windows, and a trip computer. Work in preparation for the sale consisted of changing the oil, recharging the air conditioning refrigerant, overhauling the front brakes, and replacing the power steering pump, valve cover gasket, and hatchback struts. This Daytona Pacifica is offered at no reserve by the selling dealer with an owner’s manual, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean Ohio title.

The car is finished in Twilight Blue Pearl and features black body moldings with a red pinstripe. Exterior details include pop-up headlights, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, a rear spoiler, tinted taillights, and a single oval exhaust outlet. Checked paint is noted on the hood and roof.

Polished 15″ alloy wheels are wrapped in Sailun Atrezzo tires with 2021 and 2022 date codes. The car features an independent front suspension, a solid rear axle, and rack-and-pinion steering. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs. The front brakes were overhauled in preparation for the sale.

The bolstered “Enthusiast” front bucket seats and folding individual rear seats are trimmed in Twilight Blue cloth with patterned inserts. Appointments include an 18-way power-adjustable driver seat, air conditioning, crank windows, a retractable cargo cover, and carpeted floor mats. The factory cassette stereo and Infinity sound system do not work. The hatch struts were replaced under current ownership.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 125-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as supplementary gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, voltage, and fuel level. A trip computer and a boost gauge are housed in the center stack. The six-digit odometer shows 15k miles.

The turbocharged 2.2-liter inline-four was factory rated at 146 horsepower and 170 lb-ft of torque. Work in preparation for the sale consisted of changing the oil, recharging the air conditioning refrigerant, and replacing the power steering pump and valve cover gasket.
Power is delivered to the front wheels via a three-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists history in Ohio from the initial entry in May 1988.

This 1988 Ford Thunderbird Turbo Coupe was modified under prior ownership in the style of Bill Elliott’s 1980s NASCAR race car. It was then used in a NASCAR commercial prior to its acquisition by the selling dealer in 2024 and listing on BaT in April 2024. Finished in silver under a Coors livery wrap, the car retains much of its Medium Gray leather street car interior sans door panels and has been fitted with a window net, a rear spoiler, a front air dam, coilover suspension, and gold 15″ Bassett wheels with racing slicks. It is powered by a turbocharged 2.3-liter inline-four mated with a five-speed manual transmission and a Traction-Lok limited-slip differential, and additional equipment includes tinted windows, a Grant steering wheel, electronic climate control, and a cassette stereo with a graphic equalizer. This modified Turbo Coupe shows 174k miles and is now offered at no reserve in Lauderhill, Florida, for off-road use only with service records and a bill of sale.

Finished in Silver Clearcoat Metallic (9Z), the car has been wrapped in a replica of Bill Elliott’s Melling Racing #9 Coors livery. The side mirrors have been removed, and lighting components are not visible. A rear spoiler and front air dam have been added, with the latter item showing damage. The fenders have been cut to clear the tires, and the windows have been tinted. Imperfections are noted in the wrap.

Gold 15″ Bassett wheels are mounted with a mix of Goodyear Eagle and Hoosier slick tires, some of which show cracking. Aftermarket adjustable coilovers have been installed along with adjustable camber plates, and braking is from discs all around.

The interior retains front and rear seats upholstered in Medium Gray leather, while the door panels have been removed. Other factory equipment includes air conditioning, power lumbar support for the driver, and a cassette stereo with a graphic equalizer.

The Grant steering wheel fronts a 95-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, amperage, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 174k miles, approximately 10 of which were added under current ownership. A Bosch boost pressure gauge has been added beneath the dash.
The turbocharged 2.3-liter inline-four was factory rated at 190 horsepower when paired with a five-speed manual transmission. A Champion aluminum radiator is fitted.
Additional underside photos are presented below.
The Carfax report shows no accidents and notes that the car was designated a gross polluter by the state of California in 2005.
The sale does not include a title, as the car is being sold for off-road use only on a bill of sale.

This 1978 Ford F-250 Ranger XLT 4×4 pickup reportedly spent time with a single owner in Montana until the seller’s acquisition in 2024. Recent work consisted of rebuilding the carburetor and replacing the fuel pump. Power is provided by a 400ci V8 linked with a four-speed manual transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a rear limited-slip differential and the truck is finished in two-tone silver metallic and candyapple red over red cloth upholstery. A factory white camper shell is fitted and equipment includes a receiver hitch, cab clearance lights, power steering, power front disc brakes, white 16″ steel wheels, manually locking front hubs, an AM/FM stereo, a Realistic CB radio, and air conditioning. This F-250 Ranger XLT shows 75k miles and is now offered with a Deluxe Marti report, a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, and a clean Montana title in the seller’s name.

The truck is finished in two-tone silver metallic and candyapple red and features a Styleside bed as well as dual towing mirrors, a factory camper shell, a receiver hitch, a sliding rear window, a lockable tool stowage box, a chrome front bumper, cab clearance lights, rear stone guards, and bright bodyside moldings with vinyl inserts. The seller notes that the truck was keyed on the dealership lot and the upper passenger door and box sides were repainted. Paint and body blemishes are displayed in the gallery.

White 16″ steel wheels are mounted with 285/75 Bighorn Maxxis M/T tires. The truck is equipped with manually locking front hubs and power steering, and braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. A spare tire is mounted on the under-frame slide-out carrier.

The bench seat is trimmed in red cloth upholstery joined by a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Woodgrain trim lines the dashboard and upper door panels, and interior amenities include air conditioning, an AM/FM stereo, a Realistic CB radio, a trailer brake controller, and rubber floor mats.

The two-spoke steering wheel frames an 85-mph speedometer as well as gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, battery charge status, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 75k miles, approximately 200 of which were added under current ownership.
The 400ci V8 was factory rated at 169 horsepower. Recent work consisted of rebuilding the carburetor and replacing the fuel pump. An oil change was performed most recently in September 2023.

Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a four-speed manual transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a rear limited-slip differential. The rear differential was serviced in September 2023.

The Deluxe Marti Report lists factory colors, options, and production statistics. The manufacturer’s literature, initial sales paperwork, Ownercard, service records, and spare wheels and tires accompany the truck.

This 1982 Porsche 911 Turbo is said to have been ordered new by a German owner and subsequently sent to RUF Automobile GmbH for conversion to BTR Lightweight specification. The car was reportedly sold upon completion to a Japanese collector and remained in Japan until it was purchased by the selling dealer and imported to the US in 2023. Finished in Grand Prix White over black cloth, the car is powered by a turbocharged Type 930/60 flat-six that was modified by RUF to a displacement of 3.4 liters and is mated to a RUF five-speed manual transaxle. Additional features include RUF valances, modified Bilstein suspension, cross-drilled and ventilated disc brakes, staggered-width Fuchs-style alloy wheels, a quad-outlet exhaust system, a manual boost controller, an oil cooler, a sunroof, air conditioning, and a Blaupunkt cassette player. Since its acquisition by the current owner on BaT in November 2023, RUF badging, door sill trim, pedals, and floor mats have been added, the Recaro front seats were fitted with houndstooth inserts, the wheels were refinished, a Porsche Classic Communication Management stereo linked to Kicker speakers was added, and the headlights were replaced. This RUF-modified 930 is now offered in San Diego, California, with a set of removed Cup-style side mirrors, RUF documentation, service invoices, magazine articles featuring the car, a tool kit, an air compressor, import documents, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Montana title.

RUF began offering modified versions of the Porsche 930 in 1977 before being granted German manufacturing status in 1981 and introducing the BTR, or Gruppe B Turbo RUF, in 1983 as the first model to carry a RUF VIN. In addition to the BTRs constructed from bodies-in-white, RUF offered conversions of customer-supplied Porsches to various states of BTR specification.

The selling dealer notes the car was purchased direct from the Porsche factory (code COO Germany and code 1120010 Porsche factory for delivery partner). It is believed that the base cars produced in white for delivery to RUF Automobile GmbH, Pfaffenhausen, Germany carried unique two-digit commission codes from 01-46, and the commission number for this particular example is 33. The car left the Porsche factory finished in Grand Prix White and was optioned with a power-operated sunroof and a tinted windshield.

According to the selling dealer, this example was converted to BTR Lightweight specifications when new. The bodywork included removal of the front and rear valences and the inner front and rear steel substructure, bracing and brackets, and the installation of RUF specific, lightweight replacement items and accounts for nearly 200lb in weight reduction. The RUF front valance has an integrated spoiler and oil cooler opening flanked by brake-cooling inlets, and the RUF rear valance is vented.

Paintwork has been performed on the hood, front valance, rocker panels, and wheel arches, and imperfections shown in the photo gallery below include touched-up areas on the left-rear fender and blemishes on the decklid and right-rear fender. A pair of RUF Cup-style side mirrors are said to have been removed in favor of standard mirrors during the car’s time in Japan and are included in the sale, and replacement H4 headlights have been installed.

Fuchs-style 16″ alloy wheels were stripped, refinished, and fitted with hand-painted center caps, and they are wrapped in 205/55 front and 225/50 rear Pirelli P Zero Rosso tires that show date codes from 2022 and 2023. The suspension was modified by RUF and features Bilstein shock absorbers all around. Stopping is handled by four-piston calipers acting upon slotted and ventilated disc brakes all around, and the system was refreshed in 2023.

RUF originally installed lightweight Recaro seats in models they modified. The cabin houses a pair of Recaro Idealsitz SR seats trimmed in black cloth upholstery with houndstooth inserts, and the seat backs were reupholstered. Legacy Autosport in Camarillo, California installed a Porsche PCCM stereo and Kicker speakers, and RUF pedals, sill plates, and floor mats were also installed. Additional features include color-matched carpeting, power windows, air conditioning, a Blaupunkt cassette player, and a manual boost controller located in front of the rear seats.

The three-spoke steering wheel features a RUF horn pad and sits ahead of a RUF-branded 8k-rpm tachometer and 300-km/h speedometer as well as auxiliary gauges for fuel level, oil level, oil temperature, oil pressure, and boost pressure. The six-digit odometer shows 84k kilometers (~52k miles), and the current title lists an odometer reading of 83,321 miles.

RUF BTR-specification modifications to the Type 930/60 flat-six included a displacement increase to 3.4 liters via a widened bore and the installation of RUF-specific pistons, cylinder heads, and camshafts. A higher-capacity intercooler was also fitted, while boost pressure was increased over that of the factory 911 Turbo. Output claimed by RUF was 374 horsepower and 354 lb-ft of torque. An engine-out service including the replacement of seals is said to have been performed after the car’s arrival in the US.
Approximately $15k worth of service was performed between August and November 2023, with a further ~$15k spent since the current owner’s acquisition.

Power is sent to the rear wheels via a five-speed manual transmission that was reportedly fitted during the RUF conversion and is said to have been overhauled in 2000. The exhaust system was removed, stripped and re-powder coated in special high temperature material.

A letter provided by RUF in September 2023 lists the BTR engine modifications as well as the RUF bodywork, instruments, and suspension. Two Japanese-language magazine articles featuring the car are included in the gallery, as are English translations provided by the selling dealer.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other issues and lists the purchase and titling of the car in 2023.

This 2013 Chevrolet Corvette 427 convertible is one of 2,552 examples produced for the single model year and was optioned with the 1SC Package, the 427 Heritage Package, and a six-speed manual gearbox, which is paired with a 7.0-liter LS7 V8. Finished in Torch Red over Ebony upholstery, the car has 9k miles and is equipped with a limited-slip differential, 19″ and 20″ multi-spoke alloy wheels, a black convertible soft top, xenon headlights, a head-up display, heated power-adjustable seats, and Keyless Access. This C6 427 was acquired by the owner in 2023 and is now offered on dealer consignment with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, two keys, a clean Carfax report, and a clean North Carolina title.

The car is finished in Torch Red and has a power-retractable black soft top. Additional details include xenon headlights, fog lights, Z06-style carbon-fiber fenders, a carbon-fiber hood, satin black hood stripes, and polished quad exhaust outlets. The front spoiler has scratches, and the quarter panel vents have chips.

The 19″ and 20″ multi-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with staggered-width Michelin tires. Braking is handled by red-finished Corvette-branded calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated discs at each corner. The right-rear wheel has curb damage.

The heated power-adjustable bucket seats are upholstered in Ebony leather with microsuede inserts, Corvette logos on the headrests, and red stitching that extends to the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Carpeted floor mats line the footwells, and additional appointments include Keyless Access, push-button start, a head-up display, a CD stereo, a Bose sound system, cruise control, and automatic climate control.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 9k miles, approximately 600 of which were added under current ownership.
The 7.0-liter LS7 V8 features a dry-sump lubrication system and was factory rated at 505 horsepower and 470 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual gearbox and a limited-slip differential. An oil change was performed in 2024.

The window sticker lists initial delivery to Lawrence Chevrolet of Mechanicsburg, Pennsylvania, along with factory colors, equipment, options, and a total vehicle price of $88,600. The owner’s manual and two keys are also included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1950 Ford F-47 is a Canadian-market pickup that is finished in two-tone green and black over brown upholstery and is powered by a 239ci flathead V8 paired with a three-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes wood bed stakes, a wood-lined bed floor, lap belts, a 12-volt electrical system, driving lights, 16″ steel wheels, a Holley carburetor, and a heater. The truck was refurbished in the late 1990s and was acquired by the current owner approximately a decade ago. This F-47 pickup is now offered on dealer consignment in Texas with transferrable New York registration.

The truck was repainted in green with black fenders in the late 1990s, and equipment includes running boards, a wood-lined bed floor, wood bed stakes, black bumpers, driving lights, and quarter vent windows. Bullet hole-style decals have been added to the left front fender and driver’s door. Chips and other blemishes around the body can be seen in the gallery.

The 16″ black-painted steel wheels wear chrome trim rings and Ford-branded hubcaps, and they are mounted with 6.5-16 Tornel tires. Braking is handled by drums at each corner. The master cylinder and wheel cylinders were reportedly replaced in preparation for the sale.
The cabin features a bench seat upholstered in brown, along with body-color metal surfaces. Lap belts are fitted for two occupants, and the truck is equipped with a heater.

The three-spoke steering wheel fronts a 100-mph speedometer and gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, battery voltage, and coolant temperature. An aftermarket gauge is fitted below the dash. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 2,500 miles, and total mileage is unknown.

The 239ci flathead V8 was factory rated at 100 horsepower and features a block heater as well as a 12-volt electrical conversion with an alternator in place of the factory generator. The Holley 94 carburetor was rebuilt and an oil change performed in preparation for the sale.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a three-speed manual transmission.

This 2009 Cadillac CTS-V sedan was initially delivered to Ocean Cadillac in Miami Beach, Florida, and was acquired by the selling dealer from the original owner in 2024. Finished in Black Raven over Ebony leather and microsuede upholstery, it is powered by a supercharged 6.2-liter LSA V8 mated to a six-speed automatic transmission and a limited-slip differential. The car was modified with painted gray graphics by Lip-Ship Performance, and additional equipment includes 19″ wheels, Brembo disc brakes, adaptive HID headlights, an Ultraview sunroof, heated and ventilated power-adjustable Recaro front seats, a Bose sound system, navigation, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This CTS-V sedan has 26k miles and is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with a window sticker and a clean Florida title.

The car is finished in Black Raven and features painted gray graphics across the hood, bodysides, and trunk. Additional equipment includes adaptive HID headlights, fog lights, mesh grille inserts, an Ultraview sunroof, tinted windows, LED taillights, a rear spoiler, parking sensors, and polished exhaust outlets.

Polished 19″ Y-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Falken Azenis FK510 tires that are said to have been installed within the last 500 miles. The disc brakes are equipped with silver V-branded Brembo calipers, and the sport suspension features Magnetic Ride Control.

The heated and ventilated power-adjustable Recaro front seats and rear bench are upholstered in Ebony leather and microsuede and are complemented by a black upper dashboard and carpets. Equipment includes dual-zone automatic climate control, V-branded floor mats, push-button start, keyless access, cruise control, navigation, and a Bose sound system.

The multifunction microsuede-trimmed steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,200-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature, boost pressure, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 26k miles.
The supercharged 6.2-liter LSA V8 was factory rated at 556 horsepower and 551 lb-ft of torque. Service in 2024 included changing the oil and replacing the battery.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a six-speed automatic transmission and a limited-slip differential. A Corsa exhaust system is installed.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Ocean Cadillac of Miami Beach, Florida, along with factory colors, equipment, and a total vehicle price of $68,840.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage. The sale will be processed by a retail Michigan dealer.

This 1963 Porsche 356B is one of approximately 310 Carrera 2 GS examples built on the T6 platform between 1962 and 1964 and is among 27 built with a retractable sunroof. Completed on April 1, 1963, the car was initially designated as a company car and is believed to have been driven by Porsche public relations manager Baron Huschke von Hanstein before being sold to its first private owner in the mid-1960s. After two changes of hand in Germany, it was sold to a New York owner in the 1970s, and at the end of the decade, moved to the UK, where it underwent a refurbishment between the late 1990s and 2000s. Following completion of the project, the car was featured on the cover of Classic Porsche magazine in 2013 and was later purchased by its current owner in California in 2018. Wearing a repaint in its factory shade of Light Ivory, it is powered by a replacement 1,966cc Type 587 four-cam flat-four that features a plain-bearing crankshaft, dry-sump lubrication, and dual-throat Solex carburetors. Additional equipment includes a four-speed manual transaxle, four-wheel annular disc brakes, Koni shock absorbers, a camber compensator, silver-painted 15” wheels, an Eberspacher gas heater, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, and a Blaupunkt radio. This Carrera 2 sunroof coupe is now offered on dealer consignment with a copy of its Kardex, historical documentation, invoices, a tool kit, a battery charger, and a clean California title.

The Carrera variant was introduced in 1955 with power from a derivation of the four-cam engine designed by Dr. Ernst Furhmann for use in Porsche’s competition efforts. In 1957, the Carrera offerings were divided into the GT and GS, or de Luxe, models, with the latter more luxuriously equipped for comfortable road use. Launched in late 1961 on the T6 platform, the Carrera 2 brought about a further displacement increase to two liters as well as the first production use of Porsche’s annular disc brakes.

This example is said to have received a repaint in its original shade of Light Ivory during the refurbishment performed in the 2000s by Roger Bray Restoration in Exeter, UK. Various chips are noted on areas of the finish. Features include a retractable sunroof, body-color bumpers without guards, a driver-side mirror, a fender-mounted antenna, twin decklid grilles, and a rear apron through which dual exhaust outlets pass.

Silver-painted wheels wear Porsche-crest hubcaps and are wrapped in 185/70R15 Avon Radial tires, as is a matching spare secured in the front compartment. Annular disc brakes incorporate calipers positioned on the inner edge of the rotors allowing for a larger disc diameter. A replacement dual-circuit master cylinder was installed in 2016, and the brakes are said to have been adjusted in preparation for the sale.

The cabin houses a pair of bucket seats trimmed in black leatherette with Pepita cloth inserts, while black leatherette covers the fold-down rear seats and door panels. Additional features include charcoal square-weave carpeting, black rubber floor mats, front shoulder belts, a lockable glovebox, a passenger-side grab handle, and a Blaupunkt push-button radio. An Eberspacher gas heater is situated in the front compartment.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel sits ahead of a body-color dash fascia housing green-letter VDO instrumentation including an 8k-rpm tachometer, a 250-km/h speedometer, and a combination gauge monitoring oil temperature and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 27k kilometers (~17k miles), approximately 1k of which have been added under current ownership. Additional instruments include a MotoMeter outside/inside thermometer and a clock.

The Type 587/1 flat-four carried over the quad overhead camshafts, plain-bearing crankshaft, dry-sump lubrication, and dual-throat Solex carburetors of the previous version of Fuhrmanm’s powerplant, but featured a longer stroke for a displacement increase to 1,966cc. This example’s engine is a replacement that is said to have been overhauled during the refurbishment performed in the 2000s. The cam lobes were replaced in 2016, and the oil thermostat was replaced in 2019, while the dynamo was rebuilt in 2023. Work performed in preparation for the sale is said to have included adjustment of the carburetors and an oil change.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a dual-mount Type 741 four-speed manual transaxle.

The Kardex lists the original colors and describes the original handler as “Werkseigener Wagen,” or “factory-owned car,” and lists the first owner as “Presse.” Correspondence from Porsche Great Britain shown in the gallery below also notes that the car was originally owned by the factory.

This 2009 Chevrolet Corvette ZR1 is finished in black over Ebony leather and has 881 miles following history in Georgia, South Carolina, Arizona, and Montana. It is powered by a supercharged 6.2-liter LS9 V8 linked with a six-speed manual gearbox and a limited-slip differential, and it was ordered with the 3ZR Premium Equipment Group. Other equipment includes chrome 19″ and 20″ multi-spoke wheels, Brembo ceramic-composite brakes, xenon headlights, a Bose sound system, navigation, a head-up display, heated power-adjustable seats, and Keyless Access. Purchased by the seller in June 2022, this C6 ZR1 is now offered in Vermont with a build sheet, the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Montana title in the name of the seller’s LLC.

The C6 featured a hydro-formed aluminum chassis paired with composite and carbon-fiber bodywork. This example is one of a reported 368 ZR1 examples finished in black (41U) for the model year, and it features xenon headlights, an exposed carbon-fiber roof, a clear engine cover, polished quad exhaust outlets, and a carbon-fiber front splitter and side skirts.

Staggered-diameter 19″ and 20″ multi-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport tires with date codes from 2008. The car is equipped with Magnetic Ride Control, and braking is handled by Brembo ceramic-composite discs at each corner.

The cabin houses power-adjustable bucket seats upholstered in Ebony leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, center console, door panels, and carpets. The car was optioned with the 3ZR Premium Equipment Group, which added heated seats with position memory settings for the driver along with a power-adjustable steering column, steering wheel audio controls, a Bose sound system, navigation, and a CD stereo. Additional amenities include Keyless Access, push-button start, a head-up display, cruise control, and dual-zone automatic climate control.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 220-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, boost, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 881 miles, approximately 200 of which were added under current ownership.
The supercharged and intercooled 6.2-liter LS9 V8 features a dry-sump lubrication system and was factory rated at 638 horsepower and 604 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual gearbox and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1960 Chris-Craft Conqueror is a 42′ wood-hulled cruiser that was purchased by the seller in 1991 and is powered by twin 7.2-liter Chrysler 440 V8s paired with Morse forward-reverse transmissions. The boat’s topsides are painted in black, and the bottom is finished in red antifouling paint with a white bootstripe. Additional features include a Westerbeke genset, a Furuno chart plotter, dual tachometers, rear bronze propellors, an aft cabin, a forward V-berth, and a head. Big Woody is now offered with an Ohio title in the seller’s name.
The 42′ wood hull’s topsides are painted in black, and the bottom is finished with red antifouling paint with a white bootstripe. The deck and transom are finished with varnish.

The wheelhouse features a helm mounted aft of a dash that houses forward-reverse controls as well as instrumentation including a Furuno chart plotter, dual tachometers, and gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, and voltage. The four-digit hour meter shows 5,700 hours, and total runtime is unknown.
The boat has an aft cabin and forward V-berth.
The head is equipped with a foot-operated toilet and a sink.
Power is from twin 7.2-liter Chrysler 440 V8s to the rear bronze propellors through Morse forward-reverse transmissions. The boat is equipped with a Westerbeke genset.
The boat is titled by the number CBA40046, though the seller is unable to find a matching number on the boat’s hull.

This 1995 Ducati 916 is one of 300 examples produced in the Senna Edition, all of which combine a Strada-specification 916cc desmodromic L-twin with the rear subframe, brakes, and carbon-fiber trim of the SP model. The bike is finished in a two-tone Senna scheme and features a six-speed transmission, three-spoke 17″ Brembo wheels, clip-on handlebars, an adjustable Showa fork, an Öhlins piggyback monoshock, triple Brembo disc brakes, a carbon-fiber front fender, an integrated windscreen, a black vinyl Monoposto seat, Termignoni carbon-fiber mufflers, Weber-Marelli electronic fuel injection, carbon-fiber heel guards, and a side stand. The seller purchased the bike last year and has since added a handful of the 765 kilometers (~475 miles) shown. This 916 is now offered in Canada with its paddock stand, a bike cover, the removed exhaust components, tools, literature, and British Columbia registration.

The Massimo Tamburini-designed bodywork is finished in a two-tone scheme with silver and red graphics, and it is mounted over a trellis frame. Features include an integrated windscreen, a black vinyl Monoposto seat, a carbon-fiber front fender, fairing-mounted mirrors, carbon-fiber heel guards, a 4.4-gallon fuel tank, and a side stand.

Red three-spoke 17″ Brembo wheels are mounted with Michelin tires. Suspension consists of an adjustable Showa 43mm inverted fork as well as an Öhlins piggyback monoshock mounted to the single-sided swingarm. Brembo braking components include dual 320mm discs and four-piston calipers up front as well as a 220mm disc and a two-piston caliper at the rear.

Clip-on handlebars are secured below the upper triple clamp, which has a mounting point for the piston-style steering damper. Instrumentation consists of a 300 km/h speedometer, a 13k-rpm tachometer, a coolant temperature gauge, and an array of indicator lights. The five-digit odometer shows 765 kilometers (~475 miles), a handful of which were ridden under current ownership.
The top triple clamp bears a serialized plaque listing the bike as #071 of the Senna Edition units produced for the model year.

The liquid-cooled 916cc L-twin features Weber-Marelli electronic fuel injection, four desmodromically actuated valves per cylinder, and a dual exhaust system with under-tail Termignoni carbon-fiber mufflers. Factory-rated output was 114 horsepower and 66 lb-ft of torque. The seller notes that the timing belts were replaced and fluids services were performed in Spring 2024.
Power is routed to the rear wheel through a dry clutch, a six-speed transmission, and a drive chain.
A tool kit, manufacturer’s literature, a paddock stand, removed exhaust components, and a cover will accompany the bike.
The bike is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada.

This Mini Monster go-kart is a Grave Digger model manufactured in the 1990s by the Carter Brothers Manufacturing Co. of Brundidge, Alabama. Features include plastic bodywork finished in black over a green tubular steel frame, and power comes from a 6.5-horsepower Tecumseh single with a torque converter and chain drive. Other equipment includes front and rear bumpers, drum brakes, a three-spoke steering wheel, exterior lighting, and 8″ wheels. This Carter Brothers go-kart was purchased by the seller in 2024 and is now offered at no reserve in Plymouth, Indiana, with a bill of sale.

The plastic body is finished in black and features green flames over the hood and fenders as well as Grave Digger graphics along the side panels. Additional features include a plastic windshield, headlights with red lenses, a faux grille, side steps, and silver front and rear bumpers. Imperfections on the bumpers and decals, as well as corrosion on the side steps, are shown in the gallery.
The 8″ wheels wear Kenda Bear Claw tires. Stopping power is provided by drum brakes mounted at the rear wheels.

The cockpit features a single black seat and a three-spoke steering wheel trimmed in black vinyl that sits aft of the foot pedals with green and red covers. Features include a lap belt, a turn-key electric starter, a manual choke, and a toggle switch on the right side for exterior lights. The green frame and floor pan are visible below.

The 6.5-horsepower Tecumseh OHV single is linked to a torque converter and sends power to the rear wheels via chain drive. Work under current ownership includes replacing the spark plug and engine oil. The 12-volt battery has also been replaced.
Rust is visible on the underside frame and hardware.
The manufacturer’s label shows the model and serial numbers.
listing_details: Black Plastic Bodywork w/Grave Digger Graphics

description: This 1995 Land Rover Defender 90 is a left-hand-drive example that was initially delivered to Italy before it was acquired by the seller and imported to the US in 2022. It is finished in Alpine White with County graphics over black vinyl and powered by a 2.5-liter 300Tdi turbodiesel inline-four linked to a five-speed manual transmission, a dual-range transfer case, a locking center differential, and a limited-slip rear differential. Equipment includes front disc brakes, white 16″ Rostyle wheels, LED exterior lighting, tubular side steps, a folding rear step, and inward-facing rear bench seats. This Defender 90 shows 334k kilometers (~208k miles) and is offered with a British Motor Industry Heritage Trust certificate, service records, spare synthetic wood flooring, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Arizona title in the seller’s name.

The truck is finished in Alpine White (456) with County graphics and features LED lighting, windshield vents, alpine windows, black wheel arch flares, tubular side steps, a folding rear step, and a tow ball. The seller notes that doors were aligned under current ownership. The rear window wiper is disconnected.

White 16″ Rostyle wheels are mounted with 235/70 BFGoorich All-Terrain T/A KO2 tires, and a spare is affixed to the swing-away rear tire carrier. Braking is handled by front discs and rear drums. The seller states that the brake booster, ball joints, tie rod ends, and power steering pump and hoses were replaced in 2022.

The front bucket seats are upholstered in black vinyl, and interior appointments include a locking center console and a cabin heater. The seller notes that the right window crank was replaced under current ownership. The headliner is sagging.

The two-spoke steering wheel fronts a 150-km/h speedometer and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 334k kilometers (~208k miles), approximately 10k of which were added under current ownership.
The cargo area features inward-facing bench seats, synthetic wood flooring, sliding side windows, and cargo divider bars.

The 2.5-liter 300Tdi turbodiesel inline-four was factory rated at 111 horsepower and 195 lb-ft of torque. The crankshaft and cooling hoses were reportedly replaced in 2022, and the rear main seal, timing belt, and engine oil were changed in October 2023.
Power is routed to all four wheels through a five-speed manual transmission, a dual-range transfer case, a locking center differential, and a limited-slip rear differential.
The British Motor Industry Heritage Trust certificate lists an April 25, 1995 build date along with factory colors, serial numbers, and initial delivery to Rover Italia Spa.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage and shows history in Texas and Arizona from an initial entry in November 2022.

A reproduction warranty tag has been been installed, and the fender apron stamping is shown in the gallery below and lists VIN sequence 5R09C140457.
