A key code card and two keys will accompany the motorcycle along with a Honda-branded battery charger and tester.

This 1977 Ford Bronco underwent a refurbishment under previous ownership that involved the installation of a reproduction steel body, a repaint in Azure Gray Metallic, and a rebuild of the 302ci V8. Shifting is through a replacement three-speed automatic transmission paired with a dual-range transfer case, and the engine has been fitted with a Holley Sniper electronic fuel injection system and a Ford Performance intake manifold. The truck rides on a lifted suspension and is further equipped with a Borgeson power steering box, power-assisted front disc brakes, Mile Marker front hubs, 15″ Mickey Thompson aluminum wheels, and a Rampage black vinyl soft top. On the inside, the high-back bucket seats are upholstered in black vinyl and are joined by a six-point roll cage, a cabin heater, and a locking center console. This modified Bronco was acquired by the selling dealer in March 2024 and is now offered with a clean Pennslyvania title.

The truck was fitted with a replacement steel body and finished in Ford Azure Gray Metallic as part of the aforementioned refurbishment under prior ownership. A Rampage black vinyl soft top and black-finished bumpers were also added along with replacement lighting, glass, badging, and trim.

Mickey Thompson 15″ aluminum wheels are mounted with 33×12.5″ Mickey Thompson Baja Legend EXP tires. The truck rides on a 2.5″ lifted suspension and has been fitted with a Borgeson power steering conversion kit, a Skyjacker steering stabilizer, Mile Marker manually locking front hubs, and power-assisted front disc brakes.

The high-back bucket seats and fold-and-tumble rear bench seat are upholstered in black vinyl. A six-point roll cage has been installed, and further details include a cabin heater, three-point seatbelts, black front carpets, and a bedliner-coated cargo area. A locking center console was installed under current ownership and is said to be equipped with a Bluetooth-capable head unit and speakers.

A leather-wrapped steering wheel sits ahead of a 100-mph speedometer and auxiliary gauges for voltage, fuel level, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. A Holley EFI module is mounted in the glove compartment. The five-digit odometer shows 50 miles, and total mileage is unknown.

The replacement 302ci V8 is said to have been rebuilt before it was installed under prior ownership. A COMP Cam camshaft is said to have been installed and the engine is further equipped with a Holley Sniper fuel injection system and a Ford Performance intake manifold. An aluminum radiator has been retrofitted, and an oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.

Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels via a replacement three-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. A dual exhaust system has been installed, and the driveshafts and axle joints were reportedly replaced under prior ownership.

This 2005 Mercedes-Benz E320 sedan has 17k miles, and it was specified in Everest Green Metallic with a panoramic sunroof over a Stone MB-Tex interior. The car is powered by a 3.2-liter V6 paired with a five-speed automatic transmission, and additional features include 16″ multi-spoke alloy wheels, power-adjustable front seats, a concealed CD stereo, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This E320 sedan is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve in New Jersey with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The car is finished in Everest Green Metallic (816) and features a glass panorama sunroof and fog lights. A paint correction was performed and a ceramic coating was applied to the bodywork in preparation for the sale.
The 16″ multi-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Toyo Eclipse tires. Stopping power is provided by ventilated discs at each corner.

The cabin features power-adjustable front seats upholstered in Stone MB-Tex. Interior features include a concealed CD stereo, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, and COMAND infotainment.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as an analog clock and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 17k miles.
The 3.2-liter M112 V6 was factory rated at 221 horsepower and 232 lb-ft of torque. Work in preparation for the sale has included an oil change, a coolant flush, and replacing the air filters.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a five-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or damage.

This 2015 Volkswagen Touareg Executive TDI is finished in Sand Gold Metallic (LC1Y) over Terracotta Brown Vienna leather and is powered by a 3.0-liter turbodiesel V6 that drives all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission and a 4MOTION permanent four-wheel-drive system. Equipment includes the Driver Assistance Package, 20″ Montauk alloy wheels, a panoramic sunroof, a power-operated tailgate, adaptive xenon headlights, Park Distance Control, heated power-adjustable front seats, heated rear seats, a Surround-View camera system, adaptive cruise control, Dynaudio sound system, and touchscreen infotainment with navigation. The truck has 67k miles and is said to have remained under the care of a single owner. This 7P Touareg is now offered in Wisconsin by the selling dealer at no reserve with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, and a clean Montana title.

The truck is finished in Sand Gold Metallic (LC1Y) and features a panoramic sunroof, a power-operated tailgate, a receiver hitch, adaptive xenon headlights, fog lights, roof rails, Park Distance Control parking sensors, and a rear window wiper. The Carfax report notes damage in a May 2021 entry, and the left front fender has been refinished. Photos depicting paint-meter readings as well as detailed photos of exterior blemishes are provided in the gallery.

The 20″ Montauk alloy wheels show signs of curb rash and are mounted with Pirelli Scorpion tire. Stopping power is provided by ventilated discs at each corner. The brake pads and the front rotors were replaced in March 2023.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats and heated rear seats trimmed in Terracotta Brown Vienna leather. Amenities include a Surround-View camera system, a rearview camera, a Dynaudio sound system, keyless entry, Climatronic dual-zone automatic climate control, rear window sunshades, and touchscreen infotainment with navigation. Driver assistance features include Lane Assist, Lane Keep Assist, Lane Change Assist, Lane Departure warning, Forward Collision Warning, and adaptive cruise control.

The heated multifunction steering wheel frames instrumentation consisting of a 180-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 67k miles.

The 3.0-liter turbodiesel V6 was factory rated at 240 horsepower and 406 lb-ft of torque. A TDI recall proof of completion sticker can be viewed in the gallery. The catalytic converters were replaced in March 2023.
Power is sent to all four wheels through an Aisin eight-speed automatic transmission and a 4MOTION permanent four-wheel-drive system.
The window sticker lists factory colors, standard features, options, and a total price of $65,845.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage.

This 1987 Honda XL600R was acquired by the seller in April 2024, reportedly from its second owner, and it is powered by a  589cc SOHC single paired with a five-speed transmission. It is finished in a white, blue, and red paint scheme, and equipment includes 21″ and 17″ alloy rims, a kick starter, a compression-release valve, twin Keihin carburetors, a high-mount exhaust system, electronic ignition, a front disc brake, an air-adjustable fork, adjustable Pro-Link rear suspension, a blue two-up seat, a cross-braced handlebar, a skid plate, and a side stand. This XL600R is now offered at no reserve with a clean Colorado title in the seller’s name.

The bike is finished in white with blue and red graphics, and it features a white frame, a blue vinyl two-up seat, a rear parcel rack, a headlight, a taillight, a headlight fairing, a cross-braced handlebar, a single mirror, high-mounted plastic fenders, a skid plate, a 3.2-gallon fuel tank, a side stand, and a toolbox mounted behind the left side panel. The bike is not equipped with turn signals.

Wire-spoke wheels with D.I.D alloy rims measuring 21″ up front and 17″ out back are mounted with Dunlop D606 knobby tires. Suspension consists of an air-adjustable leading-axle fork with blue gaiters as well as a rebound-adjustable monoshock attached to the Pro-Link linkage and swingarm. Braking is handled by a front disc and a rear drum.

Instrumentation consists of a 105-mph speedometer that displays recommended shift points and a resettable trip meter in addition to a bank of indicator lights. The odometer shows 10k miles, approximately 50 of which were ridden by the seller.

The air-cooled 589cc SOHC single features a hemispherical combustion chamber with four radial valves as well as electronic ignition, a kick starter, a compression-release valve, 28mm Keihin carburetors, and a black dual-header exhaust system that terminates with a high-mount muffler. Factory-rated output was 45 horsepower. The carburetors were cleaned, the spark plugs replaced, and the oil changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is delivered to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and a drive chain.
listing_details: White Paint w/Red, White & Blue Graphics

description: This 2016 Ferrari 488 Spider has 8k miles and was ordered with approximately $63k in options, some of which include carbon-fiber exterior and interior accents in addition to Goldrake racing seats, which are upholstered in Beige Tradizione leather. Powered by a twin-turbocharged 3.9-liter V8 paired with a seven-speed F1 dual-clutch automatic transaxle, the car is finished in Nero and is further equipped with 20″ split-spoke alloy wheels, ceramic-composite brakes, an SCM-E magnetorheological damping system, a retractable hardtop, Scuderia Ferrari fender shields, a sport exhaust system, rear parking sensors, front and rear cameras, a passenger display, and navigation. This 488 Spider was acquired by the selling dealer in 2020 and is now offered in California with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a battery tender, a tool kit, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Arizona title.

The car is finished in Nero and has carbon-fiber B-pillar trim and side air splitters. Additional details include a retractable hardtop, Scuderia Ferrari fender shields, xenon headlights, rear parking sensors, a vented deck lid, and Italian flags on either side of the car. The underside of the front spoiler has scrapes.

Black-finished 20″ split-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with staggered-width Federal tires. The car is equipped with an SCM-E magnetorheological suspension control system. Braking is provided by red-finished multi-piston calipers over ceramic-composite discs at each corner.

The Goldrake racing seats are upholstered in Beige Tradizione leather with Cavallino Rampante logos on the headrests, Nero stitching, and black center stripes. Carbon-fiber trim accents the cabin, and additional appointments include carpeted floor mats, drilled aluminum pedals, a wind deflector, dual-zone automatic climate control, navigation, front and rear cameras, and a passenger display.

The leather- and carbon-fiber-trimmed steering wheel sits ahead of column-mounted paddle shifters and features an engine-start button, a manettino driving-mode selector, shift lights, and additional controls. Instrumentation consists of a central 10k-rpm tachometer flanked by multifunction displays. The digital odometer indicates 8k miles, approximately 6k of which were added under current ownership.
The twin-turbocharged 3.9-liter V8 was factory rated at 661 horsepower and 561 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in May 2024.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed F1 dual-clutch automatic transaxle. The car is equipped with a sport exhaust system. Additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery.
The window sticker shows initial delivery to Scottsdale Ferrari of Phoenix, Arizona, along with factory colors, equipment, options, and a total suggested retail price of $339,595.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The car has not passed a California emissions test.

This 2021 Tesla Model S Plaid is finished in Deep Blue Metallic over light gray upholstery and is powered by three-phase AC induction motors driving all four wheels. Equipment includes a panoramic glass roof, Plaid-specific bodywork, 21″ Arachnid wheels, and an adaptive air suspension in addition to woodgrain interior trim, heated and ventilated front seats, heated rear seats, a yoke steering wheel, a 17″ center touchscreen, and a 22-speaker audio system. Purchased new by the owner in New York, This Model S Plaid has 2,000 miles and is offered on dealer consignment with a charging cable, manufacturer’s literature, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New York title in the name of an LLC.

The Model S Plaid debuted in 2021 and was the first Tesla produced with three electric motors. This example is finished in Deep Blue Metallic, and exterior features include a panoramic glass roof, model-specific bodywork, and LED headlights along with heated and power-folding side mirrors, retracting door handles, and front and rear parking sensors. The car’s Sentry Mode uses various external cameras to record activity around the vehicle once a proximity alert is triggered.

Optional 21″ Arachnid wheels are wrapped in Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires measuring 265/35 up front and 295/30 out back. Four-wheel disc brakes are paired with black Tesla-branded calipers all around, and energy is recouped through a regenerative braking system. An adaptive air suspension was standard equipment.

Light gray synthetic leather covers the heated, ventilated, and power-adjustable front seats in addition to the heated outboard rear seats. Additional interior amenities consist of 17″ front and 9.4″ rear displays, an in-cabin gaming system, tri-zone automatic climate control, navigation, and a 22-speaker audio system.
A yoke-style steering wheel fronts a configurable digital information screen, and the odometer indicates 2k miles. Woodgrain trim lines the dashboard, center console, and door panels.
The single front motor and dual rear motors drive all four wheels and combine for a factory-rated output of 1,020 horsepower and 1,050 lb-ft of torque.
Additional underside images are provided in the gallery below. A charging cord and its accompanying carrying case are included in the sale.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists history with a single owner in New York.

This 2000 Dodge Viper GTS shows 12k miles, and it was specified in Viper Black over black leather. Power is provided by an 8.0-liter V10 paired with a six-speed manual transmission, and equipment includes a limited-slip differential, 18″ polished aluminum-alloy wheels, projector-style headlights, air conditioning, and an Alpine CD stereo. This Viper GTS is now offered by the selling dealer in Florida with spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Michigan title.
The car is finished in Viper Black and features projector-style headlights, fog lights, a vented hood, and dual center-exit exhaust outlets.
The 18″ polished aluminum-alloy wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs.

The cabin features bucket seats upholstered in black leather along with a color-matching dashboard, center console, door panels, and shift knob. Additional equipment includes a CD stereo, adjustable pedals, power windows, dual airbags, an aftermarket shift knob, and chrome-finished climate control knobs and sill guards. The air conditioning system was recharged in July 2022.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline. Auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, fuel level, and voltage are mounted atop the center stack. Chrome-finished gauge trim has been added. The six-digit odometer shows 12k miles.
The 8.0-liter OHV V10 was factory rated at 450 horsepower and 490 lb-ft of torque. The battery was replaced in May 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Tremec T-56 six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.

This 2017 Land Rover Range Rover HSE Td6 Diesel is a Firenze Red Metallic-finished example that was registered in California, Texas, and North Carolina before it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, and it now has 21k miles. Power is provided by a 3.0-liter turbodiesel V6 linked with an eight-speed automatic transmission and a two-speed electronically controlled transfer case. Features include the Four-Zone Climate Comfort Pack, xenon headlights, a panoramic roof, 20″ split-spoke Style 502 wheels, Tan and Espresso leather upholstery, heated and ventilated front seats, heated and ventilated rear seats, a Meridian surround sound system, and a 10″ touchscreen with navigation. This Range Rover HSE Td6 Diesel is now offered in Wisconsin with a clean Carfax report and a clean North Carolina title.

The truck is finished in Firenze Red Metallic with a color-matched roof, and exterior features include a panoramic roof, xenon headlights, fog lights, rain-sensing windshield wipers, heated power-adjustable auto-dimming mirrors, front and rear parking sensors, dual exhaust outlets, and a power-operated tailgate. The front bumper cover was repainted under previous ownership.

The 20″ split-spoke Style 502 wheels are mounted with 255/55 Goodyear Eagle F1AT tires that show 2017 production codes. Equipment includes an electronic air suspension with variable ride height as well as Adaptive Dynamics stability control, Hill Descent Control (HDC), Electronic Traction Control (ETC), and [color]-finish brake calipers over ventilated discs at each corner. The selling dealer states that the brake pads were replaced in preparation for the sale.

The seating surfaces are upholstered in Tan leather, and Espresso leather extends from the upper dashboard to the lower door panels. Interior amenities include heated and ventilated front seats, heated and ventilated reclining rear seats, all-weather floor mats, a Meridian surround sound system, and a 10″ touchscreen with navigation. The optional Four-Zone Climate Comfort Pack added massage functionality for the front seats, adjustable front seat bolsters, four-way power-adjustable rear seats, a cooler compartment in the front center console, four-zone climate control, and solar attenuating windshield glass.

The heated multifunction steering wheel features paddle shifters and frames a configurable digital instrument cluster with a 6k-rpm tachometer and a 150-mph speedometer. The digital odometer indicates 21k miles.
The 3.0-liter turbodiesel V6 was factory rated at 254 horsepower and 443 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission and a two-speed electronically controlled transfer case.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

attributes.value: Rover Range Rover HSE Td6 Diesel

description: This 1970 Honda CL175 Scrambler was purchased by the seller in 2020, reportedly following time with two previous owners in Washington State. Finished in Candy Orange, it is powered by a four-stroke 174cc parallel twin paired with a five-speed transmission. Equipment includes a chrome high-mount exhaust system, a kick starter, dual Keihin carburetors, 19″ and 18″ wire-spoke wheels, and drum brakes as well as trail lighting, a steering damper, high-mounted fenders, a side stand, and a black vinyl-upholstered two-up seat. The seller reports vapor-blasting the carburetors in 2022 along with resealing the forks, changing the engine oil, and replacing the battery, front tire, petcock, fuel line, and hand levers. This CL175K3A is now offered at no reserve with a tool kit and a Washington title in the seller’s name.

The bike is finished in Candy Orange and is equipped with a 2.5-gallon fuel tank that was internally sealed under prior ownership. Additional bike details include high-mounted fenders, front and rear lighting, folding passenger foot pegs, a side stand, and a black vinyl-upholstered two-up seat. Photos showing a ding in the right side of the tank are provided in the gallery below.

Wire-spoke wheels with 19″ front and 18″ rear chromed steel rims wear a 2.75″ Shinko tire up front that was mounted in 2022 along with an older 3.50″ Cheng Shin tire out back. Suspension consists of a telescopic leading-axle fork that was resealed by the seller as well as dual preload-adjustable Showa shocks mounted to the swingarm. Braking is handled by front and rear drums, with the former featuring twin leading shoes.

The chrome cross-braced handlebar carries a single mirror and replacement levers, and it is secured ahead of a steering-damper adjuster. Nippon Seiki instrumentation consists of a 110-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 10,500-rpm redline. The five-digit odometer shows 1,700 miles, approximately 25 of which were ridden under current ownership.

The four-stroke 174cc parallel twin is equipped with a kick starter, dual Keihin carburetors, and a chrome high-mounted exhaust system with a shielded muffler and runners. Factory-rated output was 20 horsepower and 11 lb-ft of torque. The seller reports vapor-blasting the carburetors in 2022 as well as changing the oil and replacing the battery, petcock, and fuel line.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and a drive chain.
A tool kit will accompany the motorcycle.
The motorcycle’s Washington title carries a Classic brand.

This Porsche 356 replica was reportedly assembled by Vintage Speedsters of Hawaiian Gardens, California, circa 2014 and was acquired in 2017 by the seller, who added approximately 15k of its 20k miles shown. It is powered by an air-cooled 1,915cc flat-four paired with a four-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes 15″ wide-five alloy wheels, front disc brakes, aluminum drum covers, dual EMPI carburetors, a 009-style distributor, and a sidewinder-style center-exit exhaust system with heater boxes in addition to a wood-rimmed steering wheel, Coco mats, a wind deflector, Crow Enterprizes lap belts, and a hidden Bluetooth stereo system. This 356 replica is now offered with service records and a clean California title in the seller’s name describing it as a 1963 SPCN.

The fiberglass body is mounted over a modified Volkswagen Beetle chassis and is finished in Mexico Blue with black #9 racing numbers and graphics. Exterior details include a black soft top and side curtains leather hood straps, driving lights, mesh headlight grilles, gold-finished Porsche and Carrera badging, Spyder-style mirrors, a reproduction Reutter badge on the right fender, a GT-style louvered decklid, and beehive taillights. An additional pair of glass side windows are included in the sale. Paint chips are present on the front end.
Wide-five 15×5.5″ alloy wheels are mounted with 185/65 Pirelli P4 tires. Stopping power is provided by front disc and rear drum brakes with spun aluminum drum covers.

The cockpit houses a pair of fixed-back bucket seats trimmed in black vinyl upholstery that extends to the dash pad, door panels, shifter boot, and rear parcel shelf. The parking brake handle is mounted below the dashboard, and additional interior elements include black square-weave carpeting, Coco mats, a wind deflector, Crow Enterprizes latch-and-link lap belts, an adjustable height rearview mirror, and a hidden Bluetooth stereo linked to 5.25″ and 6×9″ speakers, a subwoofer and Rockford Fosgate amplifiers.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel wears a Porsche crest horn button and frames a central tachometer flanked by a 130-mph speedometer and a combination gauge monitoring engine temperature and fuel level. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 20k miles, approximately 15k of which have been added under current ownership.

The air-cooled 1,915cc flat-four is said to be equipped with an Engle 110 camshaft in addition to dual EMPI carburetors, a 009-style distributor, and a sidewinder-style center-exit exhaust system with heater boxes. An oil change and valve adjustment were performed in May 2024. An oil leak is present.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transaxle that has reportedly been modified with a “Freeway Flyer” gearset with a 3.88:1 ring and pinion.

The chassis number 5210842 shown above is consistent with a 1963 Volkswagen Beetle and matches the VIN on the current California title which describes the car as a 1963 Specially Constructed Vehicle (SPCN).

This 1963 Triumph TR4 was modified as a race car in the mid-1960s and has been campaigned in SCCA events over the years. Power is supplied by a 2,138cc inline-four mated with a four-speed manual transmission with overdrive and close-ratio gears along with a Southwick rear axle conversion with a Detroit locker with 4.10:1 gearing. It is finished in white with blue and red stripes over a race-prepped interior housing a roll cage, a single racing seat with harnesses, AutoMeter gauges, and a Grant GT steering wheel. Additional equipment includes aftermarket 15″ wheels, an aluminum radiator, an Accusump oil accumulator and oil cooler, a fuel cell, adjustable coilovers, and four-wheel disc brakes with dual master cylinders. The car was acquired by the current owner in 2016 and has been converted to left-hand drive since it was previously listed on BaT in December 2018. This TR4 is now offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner in Pennsylvania with fiberglass body panels, an SCCA log book, and a bill of sale.

The Giovanni Michelotti-designed body was repainted white with blue and red stripes and #37 livery in 2017. The bumpers, headlights, and windshield have been removed, while additional equipment includes a fender-mounted left mirror, hood and trunk pins, DZUS fasteners, and an electrical cutoff switch. Fiberglass body panels accompany the vehicle.

The 15″ aftermarket wheels are mounted with 205/60 Hoosier Speedsters tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs utilizing Tilton dual master cylinders, TR4A front calipers and rotors, Saab 9000 rear rotors and Wilwood four-piston calipers, and a Tilton proportioning valve. The front suspension incorporates adjustable upper A-arms, Koni shocks, aftermarket springs, a sway bar, and Delrin bushings while the four-link rear setup features heim joints, Koni adjustable coilovers, and a panhard bar.

The cabin has been stripped and houses an eight-point roll cage with door bars surrounding an aluminum racing seat with harnesses. A fire suppression system is installed. The car was converted to left-hand drive since the last auction.

The Grant GT steering wheel frames a custom dash housing AutoMeter gauges including a tachometer and auxiliary instrumentation. There is no speedometer or odometer installed and total mileage is unknown.

The 2,138cc inline four was reportedly built in January 2018 with a Moldex steel crankshaft, forged pistons, Carrillo rods, a racing camshaft, and a reworked cylinder head. The nine-quart oiling system uses a three-quart Accusump and an oil cooler ducted through one of the headlamp openings. Cooling is through a Griffin aluminum radiator supplemented by driver-controlled electric fans. An eight-gallon fuel cell is located in the trunk, and twin electric fuel pumps supply the dual SU carburetors.

Power is routed to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission that features a later ribbed case and overdrive in all four gears. An aluminum flywheel is joined by a Tilton pressure plate and custom hydraulic throw-out bearing. The Southwick rear axle conversion incorporates a Detroit locker with a 4.10:1 final drive ratio.
There is no chassis number on the vehicle, and it is not registered, titled, or legal for road use. It is being sold on a bill of sale.

This 1978 Kawasaki Z1-R underwent a one-year refurbishment that was completed in April 2019, only two weeks before the 14th annual Quail Motorcycle Gathering in Carmel, California, where it placed second in the Japanese class. The bike is powered by a 1,015cc inline-four paired with a five-speed transmission and is finished in silver over a black double-cradle frame. Equipment includes a quarter-fairing, a stepped two-up seat with a rear cowl, 18″ cast alloy wheels, triple disc brakes, quad Mikuni carburetors, an electric starter, and a chrome four-into-two-into-one exhaust system with a reverse-cone megaphone muffler. This D1 Z1-R was acquired by the seller in September 2020 and is now offered with a clean Wyoming title in the seller’s name.

The bike features a fiberglass quarter-fairing, a steel 3.4-gallon fuel tank and front fender, and an ABS plastic ducktail cowl and side panels that were refinished in Metallic Stardust Silver with blue and black pinstriping during the refurbishment. Additional equipment includes a black-painted double-cradle frame and a stepped two-up seat with a grab strap as well as a tinted windscreen, a chrome lift-assist handle, folding passenger foot pegs, and both center and side stands.

Seven-spoke 18″ cast alloy wheels are finished in black with bright edges and mounted with Phoenix E70P front and Dunlop Gold Seal K87 Mark II rear tires. Suspension is handled by a 36mm telescopic fork as well as a pair of preload-adjustable shocks mounted to a swingarm that pivots on needle bearings. Braking is provided by dual 296mm drilled discs up front and a single 290mm drilled disc at the rear. All three brake calipers and both master cylinders were rebuilt during the refurbishment.

A chrome handlebar equipped with a pair of black-finished mirrors fronts a dash panel housing a 160-mph Nippon Denso speedometer, a matching tachometer with an 8,500-rpm redline, a fuel-level gauge, an ammeter, and a vertical bank of warning lamps. The five-digit odometer shows 18 miles, though true mileage is unknown.

The 1,015cc DOHC inline-four was factory rated at 90 horsepower and is equipped with four 28mm VM-series Mikuni carburetors, an electric starter, and a chrome four-into-two-into-one exhaust system with a reverse-cone megaphone muffler. An overhaul of the engine during the refurbishment included replacing and honing the cylinders, replacing the piston rings, and fitting a replacement wiring harness from another Z1-R. Re-chroming the exhaust system was a process that is said to have involved cutting the pipes into pieces and rewelding them using the same process as the factory.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and a drive chain.
The bike is accompanied by an owner’s manual and a Kawasaki tool kit that are stowed in the tail section as well as an emergency kick-start lever that is secured by a bracket to the seat pan.

This 1972 Oldsmobile Cutlass convertible is said to have been purchased new by the current owner’s father-in-law, and it was fitted with a remanufactured 350ci V8 in 2012. Power is routed through a three-speed automatic transmission, and the car was repainted in white in 2017. Equipment includes a replacement white soft top, 14″ Super Stock III wheels, sport mirrors, and chrome bumpers. The cabin was refreshed in 2016 and outfitted with white vinyl upholstery as well as an AM/FM radio, a Custom Sport steering wheel, woodgrain trim, and air conditioning. This Cutlass Supreme convertible is offered on dealer consignment with service records and a clean Florida title.

The exterior finish was stripped and rust repairs were performed before the car was repainted in white with black pinstriping in 2017. A replacement white convertible top was installed in July 2016, and exterior details include chrome bumpers, a split grille, quad headlights, and dual sport mirrors.
Body-color 14″ Super Stock III wheels feature chrome accents and are mounted with BFGoodrich Radial T/A white-letter tires. Braking is provided by power-assisted front disc and rear drum brakes.

The front bucket seats were reupholstered in white vinyl in 2016, at which point the carpets, armrests, and sun visors were replaced and the dashboard and center console were refurbished. Woodgrain trim accents the cabin, and interior appointments include an AM/FM radio, replacement speakers, and an air conditioning system that was converted to utilize R134a refrigerant.

The Custom Sport steering wheel fronts a 120-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and a fuel level gauge. The five-digit odometer shows 98k miles, nearly all of which were added under the current family’s ownership.

A remanufactured 350ci V8 was installed in May 2012. and the starter, exhaust components, and valve cover gaskets were replaced and the positive battery cable was repaired in 2019. A replacement battery was installed in 2024. An exhaust leak is noted.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a three-speed Turbo-Hydramatic automatic transmission. The transmission pan gasket was replaced in 2019.
Decoding the data plate reveals the following production information:

This 2006 Jeep Wrangler SE was first delivered to Dodge of Winter Haven in Florida, and it has 32k miles following registration history in the state. It remained in the care of its original owner until it was purchased by the seller’s parents in 2008, and it was acquired by the seller in 2024. Finished in Midnight Blue over dark slate gray vinyl, the truck is powered by a 2.4-liter inline-four linked with a six-speed manual transmission and a dual-range Command-Trac transfer case. Equipment includes chrome-finished tubular bumpers and side step bars as well as 15″ Ravine aluminum wheels, a soft top, metal half doors, air conditioning, a fold-and-tumble rear bench, power steering, high-back front bucket seats, a roll bar, and a Bluetooth-capable Alpine stereo. This TJ Wrangler is now offered with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Florida title in the seller’s name.

The truck is finished in Midnight Blue, and exterior equipment includes metal half doors,   dual side mirrors, a swing-out tailgate, and chrome-finished tubular bumpers and side step bars. The replacement soft top was reportedly fitted about a year ago. Close-up photos of finish imperfections are included in the gallery.

The 15″ Ravine aluminum wheels are fitted with Cooper Discoverer RTX tires, and a full-size spare is mounted to a swing-out rear carrier. Curb marks and corrosion are present on the wheels. Stopping power is provided by front discs and rear drums. The truck came factory equipped with a Quadra-Coil multi-link suspension with live solid axles. The rear bump stops were reportedly replaced in preparation for the sale.

The cabin features high-back front bucket seats upholstered in dark slate gray vinyl with color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Amenities include a fold-and-tumble rear bench, a roll bar, a mini-floor console with a cup holder, air conditioning, a locking glovebox, and an Alpine CD stereo with Bluetooth connectivity.

The steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, voltage, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The digital odometer indicates 32k miles, approximately 100 of which were added under current ownership.
The 2.4-liter inline-four was rated at 147 horsepower and 165 lb-ft when new. The battery was replaced in preparation for the sale.

Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a six-speed manual transmission and a dual-range Command-Trac transfer case. The clutch interlock switch was reportedly replaced in June 2024. Corrosion is evident on the underbody.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Dodge of Winter Haven in Florida, along with factory equipment, colors, and a total price of $19,945.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.
listing_details: Chrome-Finished Tubular Bumpers & Side Step Bars
High-Back Front Bucket Seats & Fold-And-Tumble Rear Bench

description: This 1956 Chevrolet Corvette was refurbished prior to the current owner’s 2014 acquisition and is powered by a 265ci V8 with dual-quad carburetors that is backed by a two-speed Powerglide automatic transmission. Finished in green with white coves, the car has a tan soft top, 15″ wheels, windshield washers, power windows, a heater, bucket seats, beige vinyl upholstery, and a rearview mirror mounted atop the twin-cowl dash. This C1 is now offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner at no reserve with a clean Texas title in the name of the owner’s business.

The car is finished in green with white coves and has a tan soft top. Features include a wrap-around windshield with washers in addition to split chrome bumpers and dual exhaust outlets that exit through the rear bumper uprights.

Steel 15″ wheels wear covers with faux knock-off spinners and are wrapped in BFGoodrich whitewall tires. The car came equipped from the factory with an independent front suspension and semi-elliptical rear leaf springs. Braking is handled by drums at each corner.

The cabin houses twin bucket seats trimmed in beige vinyl along with a color-coordinated twin-cowl dash, carpets, and door panels. Amenities include power windows, a heater, a floor-mounted shifter, a clock, and a dash-mounted rearview mirror.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 140-mph speedometer, and center-mounted instrumentation consists of a tachometer, an ammeter, and gauges for fuel level, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The five-digit odometer shows 4,500 miles, approximately 100 of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.
The 265ci V8 is equipped with two four-barrel carburetors and was factory rated at 225 horsepower.

The engine stamping is shown above. The FG suffix is consistent with a 265ci V8 rated at 225 horsepower and designated for a 1956 Corvette with two four-barrel carburetors and an automatic transmission.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a two-speed Powerglide automatic transmission.

This 2006 Porsche 911 Carrera cabriolet remained registered in California through the seller’s acquisition on BaT in April 2023, and it now has 244k miles. Finished in Carrara White over Sand Beige leather, the car is powered by a 3.6-liter flat-six paired with a five-speed Tiptronic S automatic transaxle. Equipment includes a Cocoa soft top, 19” Carrera Classic wheels, bi-xenon headlights, heated and power-adjustable seats, PCM with navigation, Bose high-end sound, a wind deflector, and automatic climate control. Work in 2023 reportedly included replacing the motor mounts, starter, right-rear window regulator, front tires, and climate control buttons. This 997.1 cabriolet is now offered at no reserve with a binder of service records, a Carfax report, and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in Carrara White (B9A) and equipment includes a Cocoa convertible soft top, bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, dual exhaust outlets with polished finishers, and a speed-activated rear spoiler. The Carfax report lists damages to the front and rear in November 2006 and April 2016, respectively, and the front and rear bumper covers were refinished under previous ownership. Paint protection film has been applied to the front end and mirror caps. A scrape is noted on the right side of the front bumper cover, and there is an indent in the left-rear bumperette.

The 19” Carrera Classic wheels show curb marks and are mounted with staggered-width Michelin Pilot Sport 4S front and Bridgestone Potenza rear tires, the front of which were reportedly replaced in June 2023. Braking is handled by four-piston monoblock calipers over vented and cross-drilled discs and the car is equipped with Porsche Stability Management (PSM), an automatic brake differential (ABD), and Anti Slip Regulation (ASR).

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats upholstered in Sand Beige leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Amenities include driver-seat position memory, Porsche Communication Management with navigation, a trunk-mounted CD changer, the Bose High End Sound Package, a wind deflector, automatic climate control, and cruise control. The right-rear window regulator and climate control buttons were replaced in early 2023.

The steering wheel frames a central tachometer and a 200-mph speedometer along with gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 244k miles, approximately 4,200 of which were added under current ownership. The rain-sensing function for the windshield wipers is inoperative, and a message is shown on the instrument cluster readout.

The 3.6-liter M96 flat-six was factory rated at 325 horsepower and 273 lb-ft of torque, which is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed Tiptronic S automatic transaxle. Maintenance under previous ownership included replacing the air oil separator and water pump in 2019, the spark plugs and air filters in November 2021, and the starter and motor mounts in May 2023. An oil change was performed in December 2023. The car most recently passed a California emissions test in January 2023.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned damages in 2006 and 2016 along with history in California.

This 2010 Mercedes-Benz GL450 is powered by a 4.7-liter V8 linked with a seven-speed automatic transmission and a 4MATIC all-wheel-drive system, and it is finished in Obsidian Black over black leather. Equipment includes 20″ twin five-spoke wheels, Airmatic air suspension, a sunroof, fog lights, running boards, Parktronic parking sensors, heated power-adjustable front seats, a Harman Kardon LOGIC7 sound system, cruise control, automatic climate control, Keyless Go, and COMAND infotainment with navigation. This X164 GL450 has 29k miles and is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve in Wisconsin with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Nevada title.

The truck is finished in Obsidian Black (197) and features a power sunroof, a power-operated liftgate, fog lights, power-operated rear quarter windows, Parktronic front and rear parking sensors, and a rear window wiper.

The 20″ twin five-spoke wheels are mounted with Michelin Premier LTX tires. The truck is equipped with an Airmatic dual-control semi-active air suspension system, and braking is handled by disc brakes at all four corners. The front air struts were replaced by the selling dealer.

The heated power-adjustable front seats are trimmed in black leather, while burl walnut wood accents the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Amenities include driver-seat position memory settings, third-row seating, ambient lighting, a rearview camera, a Harman Kardon LOGIC7 sound system, cruise control, automatic climate control, Keyless Go, and COMAND infotainment with navigation.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel frames a central multifunction display, a 160-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, an analog clock, and a fuel-level gauge. The digital odometer indicates 29k miles.
The 4.7-liter DOHC V8 was factory rated at 335 horsepower and 339 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission and a 4MATIC all-wheel-drive system. Additional photographs of the underside are shown in the gallery below.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Mercedes-Benz of Honolulu, Hawaii, as well as factory colors, equipment, and a total retail price of $73,755.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or damage.

This 1968 Chevrolet Corvair 500 Sport Coupe was modified as a race car approximately eight years ago under prior ownership and was later used in NASA-sanctioned track days as well as VDCA and SVRA events. The car was purchased by the seller on BaT in August 2022. Power is from a flat-six that has been increased in displacement to 3.0 liters and paired with a close-ratio four-speed manual gearbox. The car is finished in yellow with black stripes and features a roll cage with door bars, front and rear spoilers, a trunk-mounted fuel cell, Kirkey fixed-back bucket seats, front and rear sway bars, uprated springs, and 15” Aero wheels. This Corvair race car is now offered at no reserve in Kentucky with a clean Michigan title in the seller’s name.

Finished from the factory in Ermine White (C), the car was repainted its current shade of yellow with black stripes during the build. The bumpers, trim, side windows, and inner taillights have been removed, and #76 roundels have been added to the quarter panels and hood. Additional modifications include rear window straps, Lexan rear quarter windows, hood pins, front and rear lip spoilers, a custom air duct on the rear decklid, an intake grille in the lower front end for the oil cooler, and brake cooling ducts in place of the inner headlights.

Black-painted 15” Aero wheels feature yellow pinstripes and are mounted with 225/50 Toyo Proxes R888R tires. Braking is via front discs and rear drums. The car is reportedly fitted with uprated springs along with Crown front and rear sway bars with custom mounts and links.

The stripped cabin is finished in off-white and houses a full roll cage with door bars as well as two black fabric-upholstered Kirkey fixed-back bucket seats. Equipment includes a wide-angle multi-pane rearview mirror, a window net, fire extinguisher and brake balance valve mounted between the seats, and Simpson multi-point harnesses, which expired in June 2022.

The three-spoke steering wheel with a quick-release sits ahead of a custom instrument panel housing an 8k-rpm Sunpro tachometer and auxiliary displays for cylinder head temperature, oil temperature, and air/fuel ratio. The center stack features toggle switches for vehicle functions. No odometer is fitted, thus total mileage is unknown.

The front trunk contains a Jaz Products fuel cell, a Holley electric fuel pump, lines from the front-mounted oil cooler, and ducting for the front brakes. The Optima battery was installed by the seller.

The replacement flat-six reportedly displaces 3.0 liters and was built in 2006 by LeVair Performance, during which time it was fitted with tri-ported heads. The engine was upgraded by the seller in 2021 with parts sourced from Auto-Bohn engines of Lowell, Michigan, that included custom cylinders, 92mm Wiseco pistons, Offenhauser-branded valve covers, angle-ported exhaust tubes with Porsche-spec exhaust manifolds, an aftermarket dual exhaust system, and an electronic distributor. A replacement carburetor was installed under current ownership and is said to need tuning prior to track use. Additional modifications are said to include the following components:
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transaxle with close-ratio third and fourth gears.

This 1989 Ford Ranger XLT is a SuperCab pickup powered by a 2.9-liter V6 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission and is finished in Scarlet Red over Scarlet Red cloth upholstery. Features include 14″ 10-hole alloy wheels, power-assisted front disc brakes, power steering, fog lights, tow mirrors, cruise control, air conditioning, and a cassette stereo. The car has been registered in Iowa since new, and service following the selling dealer’s recent acquisition included recharging the air conditioning system and replacing the battery, air filter, front wheel bearings, front brake pads and rotors, and rear axle bearings and seals. This Ranger now shows 75k miles and is offered at no reserve with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Iowa title.

The truck is finished in Scarlet Red (EN) with contrasting lower-body trim and features fog lights, tow mirrors, bed rails, a drop-in bedliner, and chrome bumpers. There is a scratch in the lower right door and a dent in the upper-right bedside, and the right-rear wheel arch is dented and has been repainted in black.

The 14″ 10-hole alloy wheels are mounted with Hankook Kinergy ST tires measuring 215/70, and braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. The truck is equipped with power steering. Service in May 2024 reportedly included replacing the front brake pads and rotors, the front wheel bearings, and the rear axle bearings and seals.
The bench seat is upholstered in Scarlet Red cloth, and interior appointments include air conditioning, cruise control, a fold-down center armrest, rear jump seats, and a cassette stereo.
Instrumentation consists of an 85-mph speedometer and a tachometer along with auxiliary gauges for voltage, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 75k miles.

The truck is powered by a 2.9-liter V6, which drives the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission. Noted work in May 2024 included replacing the battery and engine and cabin air filters, servicing the air conditioning system, and performing an oil change.
Corrosion on underside surfaces is shown in photos below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1999 Shelby Series 1 is #152 of 249 examples produced by Shelby American. It was registered in Florida and New Jersey, reportedly remaining in a Series 1 collection before it was purchased by the seller in 2022 and listed on BaT in May 2023. The composite bodywork is finished in Centennial Silver Metallic over black and gray leather upholstery, and power comes from an Oldsmobile-based quad-cam 4.0L V8 paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes a black soft top, an aluminum chassis, pushrod suspension, 18″ three-piece wheels, Borla mufflers, heated mirrors, air conditioning, and a Delco Monsoon CD/cassette stereo. This Shelby Series 1 has 7,600 miles and is now offered in Naples, Florida, with a clean Montana title in the name of the seller’s LLC.

The Series 1 was designed from scratch by Shelby American and was manufactured at the company’s facility in Las Vegas, Nevada. The aluminum chassis is paired with carbon-fiber and fiberglass laminate bodywork, which is finished in Centennial Silver Metallic on this example. Exterior equipment includes a black soft top in addition to front fog lamps, a front-hinged heat extractor hood, fender vents, heated side-view mirrors, a Le Mans-style fuel filler, and a dual-outlet Borla exhaust.

The three-piece 18″ five-spoke wheels wear Shelby center caps and are mounted with older front 265/40 Goodyear Eagle F1 Supercar tires as well as 315/40 Nitto N1 rear rubber. The Shelby Series 1 features pushrod suspension with inboard-mounted coilovers and remote reservoir dampers. Braking is provided by Shelby-branded four-piston calipers mounted over vented discs at all four corners.

The twin Cerullo bucket seats are upholstered in black and gray leather and feature Carroll Shelby signatures embroidered on the backrests. Additional interior appointments include a carbon-fiber shift knob, power windows, Shelby-branded floor mats, a CD stereo, a Monsoon sound system, and air conditioning. Separation of the dash from the center stack and wear on the driver’s door panel are noted.

The four-spoke steering wheel frames a Shelby-branded instrument panel housing a 170-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline, and auxiliary gauges. The digital odometer shows 7,600 miles, 250 of which were added under current ownership.
A serialized plaque showing serial number CSX5152 is affixed to the dash.

The Oldsmobile-sourced 4.0-liter Aurora L47 V8 features carbon-fiber covers and intake tubing, Borla stainless-steel headers and twin mufflers, and a Shelby-specific engine management system and camshafts. The engine was factory rated at 320 horsepower and 290 lb-ft of torque. A tune-up was performed prior to the seller taking delivery of the car, and the battery was replaced in spring 2023.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle made specifically for the Series 1 by RBT with ZF components.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 1988 Saab 900 Turbo SPG shows 155k miles following ownership history in Washington, New Jersey, and Connecticut. It is powered by a turbocharged 2.0-liter inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transaxle and is finished in Black over Buffalo Gray leather. Equipment includes 16″ three-spoke wheels, a sunroof, fog lights, front and rear spoilers, a Saab/Clarion AM/FM/cassette stereo, R134a-based air conditioning, power windows, and heated front bucket seats. The battery was replaced in preparation for the sale. This 900 Turbo SPG is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve in New York with a clean Carfax report and Connecticut registration.

The car is finished in Black (170B) with aerodynamic lower body cladding and features a sunroof, fog lights, front and rear spoilers, cornering lights, and impact bumpers. Photographs of paint-meter readings are shown in the gallery below.

Silver-finished 16″ three-spoke Aero wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact tires. Factory equipment included power-assisted rack-and-pinion steering, and braking is handled by discs at each corner.

The heated front bucket seats and rear bench are trimmed in Buffalo Gray leather, and interior appointments include a Saab/Clarion AM/FM/cassette stereo, a center console, air conditioning, power windows, and a heated rear window. The air conditioning system was converted to use R134a refrigerant in August 2005.

The padded steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation consisting of a 130-mph speedometer and a 7k-rpm tachometer with an inset clock as well as gauges for boost pressure, engine temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 155k miles.

The turbocharged 2.0-liter 16-valve DOHC inline-four was factory rated at 165 horsepower and 195 lb-ft of torque. The engine is equipped with a “red box” Automatic Performance Control (APC) system that automatically lowers boost pressure when low-grade fuel is detected. The battery was replaced in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the front wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle. Additional photographs of the underside are shown in the gallery below.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or damage.
The vehicle is located in a state that does not issue titles to vehicles of its age. It is being offered on its registration.

This 1991 Honda CRX VTEC 1.6i-VT is a European-market example that was sold new in France in June 1993, and it was acquired by the seller and imported to Canada in 2023. Now showing 91k kilometers (~57k miles), the car is finished in Celestial Blue Pearl over black upholstery. Power is provided by a 1.6-liter B16A1 DOHC VTEC inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transaxle, and features include a sunroof, a hatch spoiler, a rear window wiper, four-wheel disc brakes, 14” alloy wheels, a cabin heater, and a factory Blaupunkt cassette stereo. This CRX is now offered in New Brunswick, Canada, with factory literature, service records, and New Brunswick registration in the name of the seller’s company that describes the car as a 1993 model.
The car is finished in Celestial Blue Pearl (B-53P) with black body-side moldings. Exterior details include a sunroof, a hatch spoiler, a rear window wiper, and power-adjustable side mirrors.

Silver-finished 14″ five-spoke alloy wheels are wrapped in Falken Azenis RT615K+ tires with production date codes from 2021 and 2022. The car was factory equipped with front and rear double-wishbone suspension. Braking is handled by power-assisted discs at all four corners.

The European-market examples received seating surfaces trimmed in black, and embroidered CRX VTEC script accents the backrests of the bolstered bucket seats. Appointments include a cabin heater, a factory Blaupunkt cassette stereo, a rear bench seat, and a rear window defroster along with power windows and mirrors.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 250-km/h speedometer, a tachometer with an 8k-rpm redline, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 91k kilometers (~57k miles), approximately 500 of which were added under current ownership.

The 1.6-liter B16A1 DOHC VTEC inline-four produced 150 horsepower when new, and it drives the front wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle. According to the seller, the timing belt was replaced in 2016.
Additional underside photos can be viewed in the gallery below.
The Carfax report displays a single June 2023 entry in New Brunswick, Canada.
The car does not have a title and is being sold on its New Brunswick registration, which serves as the ownership document in New Brunswick, Canada. The registration describes the car as a 1993 model.

This 1959 Alfa Romeo 2000 Spider was built on December 19, 1958, and delivered new to the US through the Hoffman Motor Company of New York. One of a claimed 3,443 examples, chassis 00072 underwent a multi-year rotisserie refurbishment that was completed in 2010 and was subsequently displayed at the 2021 Concorso Italiano in Seaside, California, where it won Sports Car Market’s Best Tipo 102 award. The car is finished in white with a black Stayfast soft top and an aftermarket black hardtop, while the cabin has been re-trimmed in tan leather and retrofitted with a vintage-style radio and an aftermarket stereo. Power comes from a replacement 2.3L twin-cam inline-four fitted with a custom-fabricated intake manifold, twin Weber 45DCOE carburetors, and modified camshafts. Shifting is through a five-speed manual transmission, and further equipment includes finned drum brakes, Koni shocks, and 400mm steel wheels. The car was sold on BaT in August 2021 and was listed again on the site in March 2022 before being acquired by the current owner later that year. This 2000 Spider is now offered on dealer consignment with a spare 2.0L twin-cam inline-four along with tools and spare parts along with a clean Pennsylvania title.

The 2000 Spider featured bodywork by Carrozzeria Touring of Milan, Italy, and the US-market version can be differentiated by closely-paired hood scoops divided by a single trim piece as well as a single chrome strip along each rocker panel. This example was delivered from the factory in Grigio Biacca (AR 702), and it was stripped, mounted to a rotisserie, underwent rust repair, and fitted with several replacement body panels before it was repainted in its current white finish as part of the aforementioned refurbishment. The car features a black Stayfast soft top shown in the image gallery below and is accompanied by a tan top boot, a black tonneau cover, and an aftermarket black hardtop. A dent on the rear bumper can be seen up close in the gallery.

The 400mm steel wheels feature chrome Alfa Romeo–branded hubcaps and are mounted with Pirelli Cinturato CA67 tires. Koni shocks were added and the hydraulically operated finned drum brakes were overhauled as part of the refurbishment. The steering box as well as the brake master cylinder and shoes were adjusted by Alfaman of Novato, California, in 2021.

The cabin features bucket seats have been re-trimmed in tan Scottish leather, and matching upholstery extends to the shift boot, parcel shelf, and door panels. Anthracite wool carpets line the floors and are protected by rubber Alfa Romeo–branded floor mats. A retro-style AM/FM push-button radio with Bluetooth connectivity is connected to speakers in the kick panels as well as a subwoofer installed below the dash.

A split-spoke steering wheel frames Veglia instrumentation including a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline accompanied by a 140-mph speedometer and auxiliary gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 13k miles, approximately 2k of which have been added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The replacement 2.3L twin-cam inline-four was reportedly built by Fábrica Nacional de Motores in Brazil and features a Conrero-style intake manifold, twin Weber 45DCOE carburetors, and modified camshafts. The engine wears finned valve covers with Alfa Romeo branding, and a Bosch alternator has been installed in place of the factory Marelli generator.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission that was reportedly overhauled by Alfa Parts Exchange of Tracy, California, under previous ownership. The car is further equipped with a stainless-steel exhaust system.

The spare 2.0L twin-cam inline-four is said to have been rebuilt under previous ownership with a .010″/.010″ crankshaft, 85mm forged JE pistons, twin Solex carburetors, and a Marelli generator and starter as well as replacement bearings, valves, and springs. It retains a flywheel and is fitted with a replacement clutch disc and pressure plate.
The Pennsylvania title carries a “Classic Vehicle” brand.

This 2003 Harley-Davidson V-Rod 100th Anniversary is said to have been primarily kept on display in its original owner’s office, and it was acquired from its second owner by the seller in 2024. It is finished in two-tone black and silver with gold pinstripes and is powered by a 1,130cc Revolution V-twin paired with a five-speed transmission. Features include 19″ and 18″ solid alloy wheels, a black vinyl two-up seat, a passenger backrest, a 3.7-gallon fuel tank, forward foot controls, triple disc brakes, a two-into-one CFR exhaust system, a side stand, and fuel injection. The seller purchased the bike in 2024. This VRSCA 100th Anniversary is now offered at no reserve with spare parts and a clean Florida title in the seller’s name.

The bodywork is finished in two-tone black and silver with gold pinstripes and is mounted over a powder-coated double-cradle frame. Features include a black vinyl two-up seat, a passenger backrest, forward foot controls, chrome belt guards, a 3.7-gallon under-seat fuel tank, folding passenger foot pegs, and a side stand. Chrome accessories from Harley-Davidson include light covers, fork headbolt covers, and mirrors.

The 19″ and 18″ solid alloy wheels are mounted with 12/70 and 180/55 Dunlop Sportsmax tires. Showa suspension consists of a 49mm telescopic fork in addition to dual chrome-finished preload-adjustable shocks attached to the polished aluminum swingarm. The dual front and single rear disc brakes each feature a 292mm drilled rotor and a four-piston caliper.

The chrome-finished handlebar is mounted beneath the replacement instrument panel, which contains a 150-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 9k-rpm redline, and a fuel-level gauge. The digital odometer displays 397 miles, and the bike has not been ridden under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The liquid-cooled 1,130cc Revolution V-twin was co-developed with Porsche and is finished in a gray powder coat with polished accents. Additional features include sequential port fuel injection, dual overhead camshafts with four valves per cylinder, and a two-into-one CFR exhaust system. The fluids are said to have been last changed in 2021.
Power is routed to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and a drive belt.

This 2006 BMW M3 coupe is a Canadian-market example that was purchased by the seller in 2023 and now has 93k kilometers (~58k miles). It is powered by a 3.2-liter inline-six linked with a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential and is finished in Titanium Silver Metallic over black Nappa leather upholstery. A Magnaflow muffler, a short shifter, and an aftermarket infotainment system have been added, and additional equipment includes 19″ M double-spoke wheels, a power sunroof, heated power-adjustable front sport seats, a Harman Kardon sound system, and automatic climate control. This E46 M3 is offered in Canada with US and Canadian Carfax reports and Ontario registration.

The car is finished in Titanium Silver Metallic (354) and is fitted with Shadowline trim as well as fog lights, a glass sunroof, rain-sensing windshield wipers, LED tail lights, a trunk lid spoiler, and quad exhaust outlets. The US and Canadian Carfax report lists damage reports from January 2007, August 2010, May 2011, May 2012, June 2016, and November 2017, and the left rear corner and right front corner of the car sustained damage in the aforementioned incidents. Paint correction was performed and an XPEL paint protection film was applied under the current ownership. Touch-up paint has been applied over corrosion around the left front wheel well, hail damage was repaired on the roof, and cracked weather stripping around the left side windows is noted.  close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

The 19″ M double-spoke Style 67 wheels are mounted with Firestone Firehawk Indy 500 tires. The car was factory-equipped with Dynamic Stability Control (DSC), and braking is provided by four-wheel ventilated discs.

The heated power-adjustable front sport seats are upholstered in black Nappa leather, and Brushed Aluminum Shadow trim adorns the dash and door panels. An aftermarket infotainment system has been added, and interior amenities include cruise control, Harman Kardon audio, and automatic climate control. The center cupholders are peeling,  and the stereo intermittently disconnects.

The multi-function leather-wrapped steering wheel features M-color stitching and frames a 300-km/h speedometer and a tachometer with a variable redline along with gauges for coolant temperature, oil temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 93k kilometers (~58k miles), approximately 200 of which were added under current ownership.

The 3.2-liter S54 inline-six was factory-rated at 333 horsepower and 262 lb-ft of torque, which is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. A Magnaflow muffler and aftermarket short shifter have been added.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned damage reports. The Canadian Carfax report is provided in the gallery below.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its Ontario registration, which serves as the ownership document in Ontario, Canada
Head over to our friends at Car and Driver to check out their December 2001 First Drive for the E46 BMW M3 coupe.

This 2006 Aston Martin DB9 Volante has 46k miles, and it was specified in Meteorite Silver over Phantom Gray leather. It is powered by a 5.9-liter V12 paired with a six-speed automatic transaxle, and equipment includes a limited-slip differential, 19″ 15-spoke alloy wheels, a black soft top, rear parking sensors, heated power-adjustable seats, a navigation system, a Linn sound system, cruise control, a MR12Volt Apple CarPlay interface, and automatic climate control. This DB9 Volante is now offered in North Carolina by the selling dealer with the owner’s manual, umbrella, wind deflector, and a clean Florida title.

The DB9 featured a mix of aluminum and composite body panels installed over an extruded aluminum spaceframe. This example is finished in Meteorite Silver with a black soft top and features a Tungsten grille, hood vents, fender vents, rear parking sensors, LED taillights, and dual exhaust outlets. The Carfax report shows that a March 2010 accident resulted in damage to the rear-left corner.
The 19″ 15-spoke alloy wheels were reportedly refinished in January 2024 and are mounted with Bridgestone Potenza RE050A tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel slotted and ventilated rotors.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats trimmed in Phantom Gray leather. Amenities include a retractable navigation screen, a CD stereo, a Linn sound system, cruise control, a wind deflector, and automatic climate control. A MR12Volt Apple CarPlay interface has been added, and a video recorder has been integrated into the rearview mirror.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel features paddle shifters and frames a 220-mph speedometer, a reverse-sweep tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 46k miles.

The 5.9-liter DOHC V12 was factory rated at 450 horsepower and 420 lb-ft of torque, which is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed ZF Touchtronic automatic transaxle and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned accident.

This 1992 Mazda MX-5 Miata was first delivered to Basney Mazda in South Bend, Indiana, and it was optioned with a limited-slip differential as well as the A Package, which added 14″ Daisy alloy wheels, power steering, and a leather-wrapped steering wheel. It shows 39k miles following registration history in Indiana, and it was purchased by the seller from the original owner’s estate in June 2024. Finished in Classic Red with a black convertible soft top over black cloth, the car is powered by a 1.6-liter DOHC inline-four linked with a five-speed manual transmission. Additional equipment includes pop-up headlights, air conditioning, an aftermarket shift knob, and a JVC stereo. This NA Miata is now offered at no reserve with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a spare soft top, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Indiana title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in Classic Red and features a replacement black soft top that was fitted under current ownership. Additional equipment includes pop-up headlights, chrome door handles, painted mirror caps, a convertible top boot, and a single exhaust outlet. The front bumper cover is faded, and photos detailing finish imperfections are included in the gallery. A spare soft top with a glass rear window is included in the sale.

The 14″ Daisy alloy wheels are mounted with Bridgestone Potenza RE960 AS Pole Position tires, which need to be replaced. The car is equipped with variable-assist power steering, an independent double wishbone suspension, front and rear stabilizer bars, and four-wheel anti-lock disc brakes. The brake fluid was flushed in preparation for the sale.

The cabin features bucket seats upholstered in black cloth along with a color-coordinated dash, center console, and door panels. Interior amenities include air conditioning, a JVC stereo, and an aftermarket shift knob.

The leather-wrapped four-spoke steering wheel frames a 140-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 39k miles, approximately 100 of which were added under current ownership.

The 1.6-liter DOHC inline-four was factory rated at 116 horsepower and 100 lb-ft of torque. Work in preparation for the sale included an oil change and replacing the battery. The radiator is discolored.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. The clutch cylinders were replaced and the clutch fluid was changed in preparation for the sale.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Basney Mazda in South Bend, Indiana, along with factory equipment, colors, and a total vehicle price of $17,665.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.
