This 1998 Jeep Wrangler Sport has 40k miles and is powered by a 4.0-liter inline-six linked with a five-speed manual transmission and a dual-range Command-Trac transfer case. The truck is finished in Deep Amethyst Pearl Coat over Mist Gray cloth, and features include full metal doors, a removable hardtop with a rear wiper, 15″ alloy wheels, a fold-and-tumble rear seat, power steering, high-back front bucket seats, an AM/FM/cassette stereo, and a roll bar. The seller purchased the truck in 2024. This TJ Wrangler is now offered at no reserve with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a New Jersey title in the seller’s name.

The truck is finished in Deep Amethyst Pearl Coat, and exterior equipment includes full metal doors, a removable hardtop with a rear wiper, dual side mirrors, and a swing-out tailgate. Areas of sun fading are visible on the hardtop and scratches and dings around the body are shown in the gallery below.

The 15″ cast-aluminum wheels are fitted with 225/75 Goodyear Wrangler SR-A tires, and a full-size spare is mounted to a swing-out rear carrier. Stopping power is provided by front discs and rear drums. The truck came factory equipped with a Quadra-Coil multi-link suspension with live solid axles.

The cabin features high-back front bucket seats upholstered in Mist Gray cloth with color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Interior equipment includes a fold-and-tumble rear seat, a roll bar, a mini-floor console with a cup holder,   an AM/FM/cassette stereo, and a locking glovebox. The carpeting is stained.

The steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for fuel level, battery voltage, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The digital odometer indicates 40k miles, approximately 1k of which were added under current ownership.

The 4.0-liter Power Tech inline-six was rated at 181 horsepower and 222 lb-ft when new. The battery was replaced in January 2024 and in July 2024 the starter was replaced and an oil change was performed.
Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels via a five-speed manual transmission and a dual-range Command-Trac transfer case. Corrosion is visible on the underside.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1980 Pontiac Firebird Trans Am is finished in Nightwatch Blue over blue cloth and is powered by a turbocharged 301ci V8 linked with a three-speed automatic transmission and a Safe-T-Track limited-slip differential. The WS6 Special Performance Package added four-wheel disc brakes along with 15″ cast aluminum wheels, and further equipment includes air conditioning, a Pioneer AM/FM cassette stereo, power windows, and removable t-top roof panels. Acquired by the seller and their spouse in 2007, this Turbo Trans Am is now offered in Canada with an owner’s manual, a car cover, and clean Ontario registration.

The car is finished in Nightwatch Blue and wears contrasting Firebird and Turbo Trans Am graphics. Further details include a front lip spoiler, an integrated rear spoiler, mud flaps, and removable t-top roof panels. The seller notes that various nicks in the paint have been touched up.

The 15″ cast aluminum wheels are mounted with 225/70 BFGoodrich Radial T/A tires and are secured with wheel locks. The vehicle is equipped with power steering as well as the WS6 Special Performance Package, which added a quick-ratio steering box, a larger sway bar, and power-assisted four-wheel disc brakes.

The front bucket seats and rear bench are trimmed in blue cloth with patterned inserts. Amenities include a full-length center console, air conditioning, a Pioneer AM/FM cassette stereo, and power windows.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts an engine turned dash panel housing a tachometer with an inset clock accompanied by a 140-km/h speedometer, and gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and voltage. The five-digit odometer shows 75k kilometers (~47k miles).
The turbocharged 301ci V8 was factory rated at 210 horsepower and 345 lb-ft of torque.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission and a Safe-T-Track limited-slip differential.

This 1948 Chris-Craft Deluxe is a 17′ wood runabout that is powered by an inboard 236ci inline-six driving a single prop through a forward/reverse transmission. A replacement transom, hull framing, and planks are said to have been fitted as part of a refurbishment under previous ownership in 1995, and the boat was subsequently acquired by the seller on BaT in May 2022. Features include a two-row cockpit with red vinyl seating, polished stainless-steel and chrome hardware, a two-piece windscreen, a spotlight, a bilge pump, and an updated electrical system with a battery cutoff switch. The accompanying single-axle trailer features a manual winch, a rolling tongue jack, and guide-ons. Classy Lady was listed on BaT in July 2024 and is now offered at no reserve in Florida with a green boat cover as well as a clean Illinois title for the boat and a bill of sale for the trailer.

The wood hull was reportedly refurbished under previous ownership in 1995 with a replacement transom, framing, and planks, and the seller states a non-soak 5200 bottom is installed. The boat features white upper deck caulking as well as a two-piece windscreen, an aluminum air cleaner cover, a spotlight, and a polished cutwater and other brightwork. A spot of wood rot measuring approximately a half-inch across is noted on one of the ribs.

The cockpit houses two bench seats that were reupholstered in marbled red vinyl in 2014. Further details include a wooden dash, a chrome gear selector, white textured flooring, and gunwale storage pockets as well as front and rear step plates.

The two-spoke steering wheel features a throttle lever and sits ahead of a reverse-sweep tachometer as well as a combination ammeter and oil pressure gauge. A temperature gauge is mounted below the dash. The boat is not equipped with an hour meter, and total runtime is unknown.

The triple-carbureted 236ci Chris-Craft/Hercules KBL inline-six produced 131 horsepower when new. A bilge pump has been fitted along with a 12-volt electrical system featuring a battery cutoff switch.
The engine turns a single propeller via a forward-reverse transmission.

The Chris-Craft data plate is shown above, and a photo of the engine plate in the gallery lists the model, serial number, firing order, and recommended oil viscosity. The Illinois title lists the hull number as R17169 vs. R171769 listed on the data plate.

This 1997 Land Rover Defender 110 is a left-hand-drive example that is said to have been acquired by the selling dealer in 2021 and refurbished in Italy during work completed in 2024. Finished in green over quilted tan leather upholstery, it is powered by a 2.5-liter 300Tdi turbodiesel inline-four linked to a five-speed manual transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a locking center differential. Equipment includes a beige Exmoor Trim Stayfast soft top, LED exterior lighting, and body-color 16″ steel wheels. The truck also has air conditioning, a rearview camera, a Pioneer head unit, Hertz speakers, a wood-rimmed Exmoor steering wheel, teak cargo-area flooring, and inward-facing jump seats. Imported to the US in 2024, this Defender 110 shows 81k kilometers (~50k miles) and is offered by the selling dealer with a clean Carfax report and a clean Florida title that lists the truck as a 1998 model year.

The truck is said to have been disassembled and repainted during the refurbishment, reportedly in Grasmere Green. The previously installed hardtop and rear door have been removed, and a beige Exmoor Trim Stayfast soft top and a drop-down tailgate have been added. Other exterior features include LED lighting, checker-plate trim, black wheel arch flares, mud flaps, fold-down side steps, and a tow ball.

Body-color 16″ steel wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich Trail-Terrain T/A tires, and a matching spare is secured to a swing-out carrier at the rear of the truck. The brake booster was overhauled and the brake vacuum pump was replaced during the refurbishment, at which time the shocks and front brake rotors were replaced according to the seller.

The cabin features front bucket seats and inward-facing jump seats trimmed in tan leather with quilted stitching that extends to the dash, door panels, and shifter boots. The bulkhead behind the front seats has been removed, and custom teak wood flooring has been added to the cargo area. Other details include LED interior lighting, aluminum shift knobs, a Pioneer touchscreen head unit linked with a rearview camera, and a custom sound system with an amplifier, a subwoofer, and 150-watt Hertz marine-grade speakers. Air conditioning was installed in 2024 according to the seller.

The wood-rimmed Exmoor steering wheel fronts a 150-km/h speedometer, a clock, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 81k kilometers (~50k miles), approximately 750 kilometers of which were added under current ownership.

The 2.5-liter 300Tdi turbodiesel inline-four sends power to all four wheels through a five-speed manual transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a locking center differential. Work during the refurbishment is said to have included an oil change and the replacement of the clutch assembly, rear axle, distributor, and water pump.
The frame is said to have been repainted during the refurbishment, and additional underside photos are provided in the gallery below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1972 Husqvarna 125 CR is powered by a 124cc two-stoke single paired with a six-speed transmission and is finished in yellow over a silver frame. Features include a high-mounted expansion-chamber exhaust system, 21″ front and 18″ rear alloy rims, aluminum fenders, a cross-braced handlebar, a side stand, and knobby Pirelli tires. This 125 CR was acquired by the seller in 2021 and is now offered at no reserve in California for off-road use only with a bill of sale.

The bike is finished in yellow with polished fuel tank knee panels and white accents. It also features white number plates, a side stand, aluminum fenders, a black vinyl solo seat, and a silver-painted single-downtube frame. The seller notes chips in the paint and damage on the front number plate, and a photo showing the inside of the fuel tank can be viewed in the gallery.

Wire-spoke wheels with 21″ front and 18″ rear alloy rims wear knobby Pirelli tires. Suspension consists of a conventional fork as well as dual shocks mounted to the swingarm. Braking is from drums at both ends.
The chrome cross-braced handlebar is secured by four-bolt risers. No instrumentation is present, therefore total mileage is unknown.

The 124cc two-stroke single produced 20 horsepower when new and is equipped with an Amal carburetor and an expansion chamber exhaust system. The carburetor and ignition system were serviced in February 2024. One of the engine bolts displays corrosion.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a wet clutch, a six-speed transmission, and a drive chain.
The bike does not have a title or registration and is being sold on a bill of sale only.

This 1976 BMW R90/6 was the subject of a custom build that began in 2018 and involved repainting the bodywork in black with gold pinstripes, powder-coating the frame and related components, fitting a 1,000cc big-bore kit to the air-cooled opposed-twin, and rebuilding the five-speed transmission and cylinder heads. The modified engine features a pair of Dell’Orto carburetors and a two-into-two exhaust system with Hoske mufflers, and the bike is further equipped with a black vinyl two-up seat, an aftermarket upper triple clamp housing motogadget instrumentation, clip-on handlebars, LED turn signals, 19″ and 18″ wire-spoke wheels, dual front disc brakes, Hagon rear shocks, and both center and side stands. The bike was sold on BaT in June 2022 and acquired by the current owner later in that same year. This custom-built R90/6 is now offered on dealer consignment with a clean California title.

The bike was disassembled before the fuel tank and fenders were refinished in black with gold pinstripes and BMW roundel graphics as part of the aforementioned build. The frame and related hardware were powder-coated at that time, and stainless-steel fasteners are said to have been used during the reassembly process. A yellow headlight lens, a modified taillight, aftermarket LED turn signals, and aluminum rear-set foot controls have been added, and additional details include a black vinyl two-up seat, laser-engraved BMW badges on the swingarm caps, and both center and side stands.

Wire-spoke wheels measuring 19″ up front and 18″ out back feature powder-coated rims and hubs as well as stainless-steel spokes and nipples. Dunlop Roadmaster tires are mounted at both wheels and stainless-steel axles are said to have been installed as part of the build. Suspension consists of a leading-axle fork with rubber gaiters that was rebuilt in 2018 as well as twin Hagon shocks mounted to the swingarm on the left and the final drive enclosure on the right. Spiegler stainless-steel brake lines feed a pair of single-piston calipers mounted over cross-drilled discs up front, while a drum provides stopping power at the rear.

Joker Machine clip-on handlebars with bar-end mirrors are secured below the OSHMO upper triple-clamp, which houses a motogadget motoscope tiny 200-km/h speedometer with an inset digital display. True mileage is unknown. Replacement levers and switchgear have been installed. The seller notes that the odometer function resets every time the bike is turned on.

The air-cooled opposed twin was fitted with a Siebenrock 1,000cc big-bore kit before the cylinder heads were rebuilt as part of the 2018 work. The crankcase, cylinders, and heads were painted black at that time, and the modified engine features dual 38mm Dell’Orto carburetors with pod-style air filters as well as an electric starter and a two-into-two exhaust system with heat-wrapped headers, a crossover pipe, and 38mm Hoske black chrome mufflers. The carburetors were cleaned and the battery was replaced in preparation for the sale.
The five-speed transmission was rebuilt and the clutch assembly was replaced as part of the build. Power is delivered to the rear wheel via a driveshaft enclosed within the right leg of the swingarm.
listing_details: Opposed Twin w/1000cc Big Bore Kit

description: This 1972 Honda QA50 is powered by a 49cc four-stroke single linked to a two-speed transmission with an automatic clutch, and the bike is finished in red over a gray-painted frame. Equipment includes a Keihin carburetor, an underslung exhaust system, a kick starter, an inverted fork, drum brakes, white-finished 5″ wheels, a folding cross-braced handlebar, a black solo saddle, and a side stand. This QA50 is offered at no reserve by the selling dealer in Florida for off-road use only with a bill of sale.

The 1.2-gallon fuel tank is finished in red with back and white accents and is accompanied by matching plastic fenders over a gray-painted steel backbone frame. Additional details include a bright fuel filler cap, a black-upholstered seat, a ’60s-themed “QA50” rear fender decal, and a side stand.

White-finished 5″ two-piece steel wheels wear 4.00″ Qing Da Rubber Co. tires. An inverted fork with black rubber gaiters comprises the bike’s only suspension, and braking is handled by a cable-actuated drum at each wheel.

The chrome cross-braced handlebar is equipped with a twist-grip throttle and an ignition-cutoff button, and it is secured in a quick-release riser clamp that allows the handlebar to rotate down for transport or storage. No instrumentation is present, therefore total mileage is unknown.

The 49cc four-stroke single is equipped with a Keihin carburetor, a kick starter, and an underslung black-finished exhaust system with a perforated heat shield and a transverse muffler mounted ahead of the rear wheel.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through an automatic clutch, a two-speed transmission, and a drive chain.
This QA50 does not have a title or registration. It is being sold on a bill of sale only.

This 1978 Ford F-100 Custom was purchased new by the seller’s father and is said to have been kept in storage since 2008. Power is from a 351ci V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission, and the truck is finished in black and silver over black and blue upholstery. Additional equipment includes 15″ American Racing wheels, a LoRider tonneau cover, tubular side steps, a sliding rear window, a receiver hitch, a power sunroof, an Alpine cassette stereo, power windows, and a trailer brake controller. The starter, battery, and fuel pump were replaced in preparation for the sale. This dentside F-100 is offered with the owner’s manual, service records, and British Columbia registration.

The truck received a replacement rear box approximately 15-2o years ago per the seller, and has been repainted black and silver. Equipment includes a tow ball, a LoRider tonneau cover, a two-piece rubber bed mat, a power sunroof, a sliding rear window, and tubular side steps. The seller states a front fender has been replaced.

The 15″ American Racing wheels are mounted with Michelin tires. Braking is handled by front discs and rear drums, and the truck is equipped with power steering. The seller states the tires need to be replaced. The seller states that two additional 15″ American Racing wheels are included in the sale.

The bench seat is trimmed in black vinyl and blue patterned cloth. Amenities include an Alpine cassette stereo, power windows, and a trailer brake controller. The seller notes the truck has a locking hood latch that can be unlocked inside the cab using the ignition key.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 130-km/h speedometer and supplementary gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 83k kilometers (~52k miles) and has rolled over. Total mileage is unknown. The fuel gauge does not work.
The 351ci V8 is equipped with an Edelbrock carburetor and valve covers. The starter, fuel pump, and battery were replaced in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a replacement three-speed automatic transmission. The truck has dual fuel tanks, and the seller recommends that one of them needs replacement due to a leak.
The vehicle is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada. The sale does not include a title.

This 2007 Ford Ranger STX SuperCab Flareside pickup is finished in Redfire Metallic over black and red cloth and powered by a 4.0-liter V6 linked with a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. The truck features a lowered suspension, front disc brakes, 15″ split-spoke alloy wheels, air conditioning, cruise control, a CD stereo, and rear jump seats. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this Ranger has 103k kilometers (~64k miles) and is offered at no reserve in Canada with service records, a Carfax report, and British Columbia registration.

The truck is finished in Redfire Metallic (G2) and features matching bumpers and side skirts as well as dual rear-hinged doors, a Flareside bed, fog lights, windows visors, a drop-in bedliner, and dual exhaust outlets. The Carfax report lists a damage claim amount of CAD $600 in October 2008.

The 15″ split-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with 245/60 Cooper Cobra Radial G/T tires. The truck features a lowered suspension, and braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. The condition of the wheels is depicted in the gallery.

The SuperCab cabin features front sport bucket seats upholstered in black cloth with red inserts. Interior appointments include rear jump seats, air conditioning, cruise control, power windows, and a CD stereo.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 200-km/h speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 103k kilometers (~64k miles), approximately 500 of which were added by the selling dealer.
The 4.0-liter Cologne V6 was factory rated at 207 horsepower and 238 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage claim.
The car does not have a title and is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada.

This 1975 Glastron GT-150 is a 15′ fiberglass runabout that is said to have remained with its original owner until it was purchased by the seller in 2022 following a period of long-term storage. The boat is finished in orange and white over white vinyl upholstery and is powered by a Johnson 75-horsepower three-cylinder outboard. Features include back-to-back seating, a plexiglass windscreen, navigation lights, and a ski locker. This GT-150 is now offered at no reserve in Wisconsin with manufacturer’s literature, a Calkins single-axle trailer, a bill of sale for the trailer, and Wisconsin registration in the seller’s name for the boat.

The fiberglass hull is finished in orange and white with a white bow stripe, and it measures approximately 15′ long with a 6.4′ beam. The boat features rub rails, navigation lights, polished cleats, and two ski eyes. A crack is visible in the gelcoat on the starboard side of the transom.
The cockpit houses back-to-back seats upholstered in beige vinyl. Details include a curved plexiglass windscreen, red vinyl trim, all-weather carpeting, and a ski locker.

The starboard helm features an automotive-style steering wheel along with a hand throttle and shifter. Instrumentation includes a centrally mounted speedometer and tachometer. Total runtime is unknown.
The Johnson 50ci Stinger 75 two-stroke triple was rated for 75 horsepower when new and sends power to a three-blade propeller. The water pump was replaced in 2023.
The single-axle Calkins trailer has white-painted steel wheels, roller hull supports, a manual winch, and a rolling tongue jack.

The boat does not have a title, as it is registered in a state that does not issue titles for boats of its length. It is being sold on its registration. The trailer does not have a title as Wisconsin does not issue titles or registration for trailers of its weight class and intended use. The trailer is being sold on a bill of sale.

This Backdraft Racing Roadster was assembled in July 2007 and acquired by the selling dealer in February 2024. It is powered by a Roush 402R V8 that is linked to a Tremec T56 six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential and finished in black with silver center stripes over gray leather upholstery. Equipment includes 17″ Halibrand-style wheels, power-assisted disc brakes, four-wheel independent suspension, polished bumperettes, a single roll hoop, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, Crow Enterprizes racing harnesses, a Rockford Fosgate Bluetooth head unit, a Boss amplifier, CNC-ported aluminum cylinder heads, MSD ignition, an Edelbrock intake manifold, and a Holley carburetor. This RT3 Roadster is now offered by the selling dealer in Oregon with a copy of the Manufacturer’s Statement of Origin, manufacturer’s literature, service records, and a clean Florida title describing it as a 1965 ROAS.

The fiberglass bodywork is finished in black with silver center stripes and is mounted over a black powder-coated steel frame. Exterior details include polished bumperettes, a hood scoop, fender vents, Raydot-style mirrors, wind wings, a single roll hoop, a LeMans-style fuel filler cap, and side-exit exhaust pipes.

Halibrand-style 17″ wheels are secured with safety-wired three-eared knockoffs and are mounted with Goodyear Eagle F1 tires measuring 235/45 up front and 315/35 out back. The car is equipped with rack-and-pinion steering, adjustable coilovers, and four-wheel independent suspension sourced from an E36 BMW. Stopping power is provided by power-assisted four-wheel disc brakes with drilled rotors and red-finished calipers.

The cockpit features low-back bucket seats upholstered in gray leather that extends to the dashboard and door panels as well as the parking brake and shifter boots. Interior details include an adjustable driver’s seat, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, a dashboard-mounted rearview mirror, tinted sunvisors, Crow Enterprizes racing harnesses, a Rockford Fosgate Bluetooth head unit, a Boss amplifier, and carpeted floor mats with embroidered Backdraft Racing logos.

VDO instrumentation includes a 220-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and supplementary readouts for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, battery voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer shows 6k miles.

The front-hinged hood opens to reveal a Roush 402R V8 that utilizes an iron two-bolt Ford Racing Sportsman block assembled with 10:1 compression ratio forged pistons, H-beam connecting rods, and a forged steel crankshaft. It has an estimated output of 518 horsepower and 500 lb-ft of torque. Additional engine details include CNC-ported aluminum cylinder heads, hydraulic roller lifters, a double roller timing set, MSD ignition, an Edelbrock intake manifold, and a Holley carburetor. Cooling is handled by an aluminum radiator with dual electric fans. Engine documentation outlining the specifications and power ratings is viewable in the gallery below. The starter and battery were replaced in March 2024 along with the carburetor needle and seat for the rear bowl. The valve cover gaskets were replaced in April 2024.

Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a Tremec T56 six-speed manual transmission fitted with an SFI-rated steel bell housing and a limited-slip differential. The transmission was fitted with a replacement 5th gear and carbon fiber synchro rings in June 2024.

An identification tag affixed to the firewall identifies this car as a Backdraft Roadster that was assembled by TR-Tec in South Africa. The current Florida title describes the car as a 1965 ROAS using the VIN AA9BMAAHV71CN1075, shown above.
listing_details: Rockford Fosgate Head Unit w/Boss Amplifier

description: This 1969 Ford Bronco spent more than 50 years in California with its previous owner, and the seller bought it out of storage in 2022. Refurbishment work began in 2023 and included rebuilding the 302ci V8 and installing a C4 three-speed automatic transmission and a twin-stick transfer case. Equipment includes a Weiand intake manifold, a COMP Cams camshaft, and a Holley carburetor. The body was refinished in green, a roll cage was installed, and the interior was refreshed with brown upholstery and two-tone door panels. The truck also has front bucket seats, three-point seat belts, and a Bluetooth head unit housed in the padded center console along with a Bilstein lift kit, Boyd Coddington 17″ wheels, and front disc brakes. This Bronco is now offered on dealer consignment with refurbishment photos, partial records, and a clean California title.
The cab roof was removed as part of the build, and the truck was refinished in green. The roll cage, front grille, tire carrier, and bumpers are finished in white.

Boyd Coddington 17″ wheels are wrapped in 265/65 BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A tires, and a matching spare is mounted to the rear carrier. A Bilstein 2.5″ lift kit is installed. The truck is equipped with manually locking Warn front hubs, power steering, and front disc brakes.

The cabin houses adjustable front bucket seats and a fold-and-tumble rear bench trimmed in brown upholstery, which is complemented by two-tone door panels and a painted dashboard. Three-point front seat belts are installed, and a Bluetooth head unit is housed in the padded center console.

The aftermarket steering wheel is adorned with woodgrain trim and mounted on an Ididit tilting column. Instrumentation includes a 100-mph speedometer surrounded by auxiliary readouts, while a tachometer is mounted to the lower dashboard. The five-digit odometer shows 1,200 miles. Total mileage is unknown.

The 302ci V8 was overhauled and bored .040″ over in March 2024. It is fitted with a COMP Cams camshaft, a Weiand intake manifold, and a Holley 600 cfm carburetor. A Haywire wiring harness is installed.

Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a C4 three-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case with twin-stick shifters. The transmission was overhauled as part of the work that was completed in 2024.

This 2021 Ford Bronco Big Bend is a two-door example that was purchased new by the current owner and has been modified with an RPG Offroad Stage 3 suspension kit, 17″ Bahia Blue Method wheels, and an aftermarket bull bar, auxiliary lighting, spare tire carrier, side steps, and bumpers. The truck is powered by a twin-turbocharged 2.7-liter EcoBoost V6 linked with a 10-speed automatic transmission, electronic locking front and rear differentials, and a dual-range transfer case, and it is finished in Carbonized Gray over Black Onyx and Dark Space Gray cloth upholstery. Additional features include a Ford Performance calibration module, a black hardtop, a receiver hitch, SYNC 4 infotainment, heated front seats, navigation, automatic climate control, and a rearview camera. This Bronco Big Bend has 25k miles and is offered by the seller on behalf of the current owner with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, spare and removed parts, and a clean Michigan title in the owner’s name.

The truck is finished in Carbonized Gray, and modifications include a Reaper Off-Road rear bumper, spare tire carrier, and side steps as well as a Maximus-3 bull bar, Rigid Industries LED auxiliary lighting, and a modular front bumper with an integrated bash plate. An accident with “very minor damage” to “front” is shown on the Carfax report in December 2023.

The Bahia Blue 17″ Method wheels are mounted with Toyo Open Country A/T III tires. The truck is equipped with an RPG Offroad Stage 3 suspension kit, which features King 2.5 remote-reservoir coilovers along with a billet panhard bar, tie rods, and upper control arms. Replacement suspension components were fitted in November 2022, and the front driveshaft was replaced under warranty in August 2023.

The cabin features heated manually adjustable front seats trimmed in Black Onyx and Dark Space Gray cloth. A center console storage safe and a JBL soundbar were added under current ownership, and additional amenities include SYNC 4 infotainment, navigation, automatic climate control, and a rearview camera. A Ford Performance calibration module is included in the sale.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 120-mph speedometer and a configurable digital display. The digital odometer indicates 25k miles, all of which were added under current ownership.
The twin-turbocharged 2.7-liter EcoBoost V6 was factory rated for up to 330 horsepower and 415 lb-ft of torque. The battery was replaced in 2023, and the oil was changed in preparation for the sale.

Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels through a 10-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. The Sasquatch Package added electronic locking front and rear differentials with 4.70:1 gearing.
The roof panel features signatures that are said to have been from members of the Ford Performance Calibration Team at Ford’s 777 Building in Allen Park, Michigan.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned accident.
listing_details: Reaper Off-Road Rear Bumper & Side Steps

description: This 1995 Porsche 911 Carrera coupe wears a Viola Metallic-tinted STEK paint-protection film over black paint, and the interior features Marble Grey all-leather seats. Bilstein dampers and H&R springs have been added to achieve European-specification ride height, and power is from a 3.6-liter flat-six linked with a six-speed manual transaxle and an optional limited-slip differential. Other equipment includes 18″ hollow-spoke “Technology” wheels, a power-operated sunroof, cruise control, air conditioning, and a Porsche Classic stereo with Apple CarPlay. The car remained with its original owner until 2020 and was acquired by the seller on BaT in June 2024. This 993 Carrera coupe shows 25k miles and is offered with a clean Carfax report and a clean Washington title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in Black (L741), and Viola Metallic-tinted STEK DYNOshield paint-protection film was applied to the bodywork in October 2023, at which time the third brake light, mirrors, and door handles were painted to match. Exterior details include headlight washers, fog lights, power-adjustable mirrors, a power-operated sunroof, a speed-activated rear spoiler, and dual exhaust outlets. The rear-window wiper has been removed, and evidence of paintwork under prior ownership is noted.

The 18″ Technology hollow-spoke wheels were added under current ownership, and they are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact Sport tires. Braking is handled by Porsche-branded calipers over cross-drilled rotors at all four corners, and the suspension has been adjusted to European-specification ride height via Bilstein shocks and H&R springs. The brake master cylinder was replaced in 2024.

The Marble Grey all-leather seats have supple inserts and are complemented by a black dashboard and burgundy floor mats. A Porsche Classic stereo with Apple CarPlay was added under current ownership, while cruise control and air conditioning are other features.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a central tachometer with a 6,800-rpm redline, a 180-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, oil level, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 25k miles, a handful of which were added under current ownership.

The air-cooled 3.6L flat-six was factory rated at 270 horsepower and 243 lb-ft of torque. An oil plug was replaced in October 2022 along with the engine-fan air duct. An oil change was performed in March 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a six-speed manual transaxle and an optional limited-slip differential.
Decoding the option sticker reveals the following information:
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The Washington title indicates that use tax was waived as a result of the owner receiving the vehicle as a gift.

This 1982 Yamaha XV920 Virago was acquired out of California by the seller in 2020 and was subsequently built as a custom cafe racer in a project that included resealing the 920cc V-twin, five-speed transmission, and carburetors. The frame was shaved and powder-coated, and custom subframe was fabricated, and additional modifications include a custom leather seat, a stainless-steel exhaust system, a Yamaha R1 front end, an Acewell gauge, rear-set foot controls, and a Motogadget Mo.Unit Blue. This XV920 cafe racer is offered at no reserve with a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The modified XV750 fuel tank in finished in Volvo Denim Blue (723) while the frame was shaved and powder-coated black. Additional modifications include a custom subframe with a frenched-in Revival Cycles LED taillight with integrated turn signals as well as an LED headlight, Motogadget front turn signals, Tarozzi folding rear-set foot controls, and a custom leather seat. Photos showing blemishes on the fuel tank can be viewed in the gallery.

Cast alloy wheels, the front of which is from a Yamaha R6, were powder-coated bronze chrome and are mounted with Dunlop Elite 4 tires during the build. The inverted Yamaha R1 fork was Cerakote-coated, and the front end features a modified triple clamp and dual R1 Brembo disc brakes with wave rotors. The rear end utilizes Triumph Speed Triple suspension components and a drum brake.

Clip-on handlebars are mounted below the top triple clamp and front an Acewell 12k-rpm tachometer and a digital multifunction display. The electronics and wiring have been replaced and the bike has been fitted with a Motogadget Mo.Unit Blue. The ignition and the gas cap use the same key. The digital odometer shows 900 miles, though total mileage is unknown.

The air-cooled 920cc SOHC V-twin is said to have to have been resealed along with the transmission and carburetors during the build. The carburetors were re-jetted to pair with the custom intake and the stainless-steel baffled exhaust system. A lithium-ion battery and an aftermarket CDI box have been fitted.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and an enclosed driveshaft. The clutch and starter were replaced during the build.
The partial frame number is shown above, and the bike is titled in California using the number JYA10L002CA018967.

The motorcycle is titled in California by its 17-character VIN, which contains the nine characters stamped on the frame. However, the label that displayed all characters of the VIN was discarded when the frame was refinished.

This 2013 Fiat 500 Abarth was purchased new by the seller’s parents and now has 19k miles following history in Arizona and Wisconsin. Finished in Grigio over Nero cloth, the car is powered by a turbocharged 1.4-liter inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes an optional sunroof, a rear spoiler, 16″ V-spoke wheels, and a Fiat premium audio system. This 500 Abarth is now offered by the seller on behalf of the original owners at no reserve with a window sticker, 2013 purchase documents, service records, manufacturer’s literature and accessories, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Wisconsin title in the name of the seller’s father.

The Abarth features revised bumper covers and rocker extensions compared to the standard 500. This example is finished in Grigio (PAJ), and exterior equipment includes a sunroof, fog lights, a rear spoiler, Abarth badging, and dual exhaust outlets. The seller notes scrapes on the underside of the front air dam.

The 16″ V-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with 195/45 Yokohama Advan Fleva tires installed in May 2024. The car is equipped with a sport suspension, and stopping power is provided by ventilated front and solid rear discs. A brake fluid flush was performed in May 2024.

The cabin features high-back bucket seats trimmed in Nero cloth with red accents along with a body-color dashboard fascia. Amenities include a Fiat premium audio system, a CD stereo, cruise control, aluminum pedal covers, and air conditioning.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel fronts a 160-mph speedometer, an inset tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level, while a turbo boost gauge with a shift indicator is mounted to the left. The digital odometer indicates 19k miles.

The turbocharged 1.4-liter inline-four was factory rated at 160 horsepower and 170 lb-ft of torque when paired with the five-speed manual transaxle. The seller notes that the battery was replaced in June 2023 and the oil was changed in May 2024.
Additional underside photos are presented in the gallery below.

The window sticker notes initial delivery to Fiat of Scottsdale in Arizona and lists factory equipment, colors, options, and a total price of $23,995. A front license plate bracket, manufacturer’s literature, Abarth-branded merchandise, and two keys are also included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2009 Mercedes-Benz E350 wagon has 61k miles and is finished in Capri Blue Metallic over Cashmere MB-Tex. Power is provided by a 3.5-liter V6 that drives all four wheels via a five-speed automatic transmission. The car is equipped with a sunroof, 17″ multi-spoke alloy wheels, heated power-adjustable front seats, fold-down third-row seating, a Harman Kardon LOGIC7 sound system, a CD stereo, and dual-zone automatic climate control. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this E350 wagon is offered at no reserve with the owner’s manual, a car cover, an accident-free Carfax report, and a New York title.

The car is finished in Capri Blue Metallic (359) and features a sunroof, a rear window wiper, a power-operated tailgate, roof rails, and fog lights. Photos of paint meter readings are shown in the gallery below.

The 17″ multi-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Firestone Firehawk A/S tires measuring 245/45. Stopping power is provided by ventilated discs at each corner, and the car is equipped with a rear Airmatic air suspension.

The heated power-adjustable front seats are upholstered in Cashmere MB-Tex, and interior features include a Harman Kardon LOGIC7 surround sound system, an in-dash six-CD changer, split-folding second-row seats, rear sunshades, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, and COMAND infotainment. The condition of the infotainment screen can be seen in the gallery.
The rear-facing bench seat stows flat into the cargo area floor, and the car is equipped with a cargo-area partition net, a WeatherTech liner, and a retractable cover.

The leather- and wood-rimmed multifunction steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline as well as an analog clock and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 61k miles.
The 3.5-liter M272 V6 was factory rated at 268 horsepower and 258 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in December 2023.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a five-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report shows at least one recall.

This 1957 Chevrolet 210 Sport Coupe is finished in red over black and white vinyl and is powered by a 283ci V8 paired with a two-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes Bel Air–style trim, chrome Cragar S/S wheels, and Edelbrock air cleaner assembly, a dual exhaust system, and an aftermarket cassette player. This 210 is now offered on dealer consignment with a clean Florida title.
The car is finished in red and features twin wind splits, hooded headlights, Bel Air-style trim, a dual exhaust system, and a fuel filler concealed above the left taillight.
Chrome 15″ Cragar S/S wheels are mounted with 215/70 Westlake Radial RP18 tires, and the car is equipped with four-wheel drum brakes.
The cabin is upholstered in black and white and the seats feature black textured cloth inserts. Bel Air badging has been added to the dashboard.

The two-spoke steering wheel features a chrome horn ring and frames a 120-mph speedometer flanked by coolant temperature and fuel level gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 10k miles, though total mileage is unknown.
Originally powered by a 235ci straight-six, the car was fitted with a 283ci V8 at some point. The engine is equipped with an Edelbrock air cleaner assembly.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a two-speed Powerglide automatic transmission. Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery.
The VIN decodes as follows:

This 1967 Pontiac Firebird convertible is finished in burgundy over a black interior and is powered by a 400ci V8 linked with a three-speed automatic transmission. The car is said to have remained with one family for more than three decades prior to the selling dealer’s 2024 acquisition. Equipment includes an Edelbrock Performer intake manifold, a black soft top, dual hood scoops, 14″ Cragar wheels, power steering, power-assisted drum brakes, a Pioneer CD stereo, and trunk-mounted amplifiers. This Firebird is now offered by the selling dealer in New York with a clean Tennessee title.

The car was refinished in burgundy at some point under prior ownership and is equipped with quad round headlights, dual hood scoops, a door-mounted driver-side mirror, and a bright front grille, rear bumper, and trim. The black soft top operates slowly and requires service. Replacement wheelwell moldings were installed in preparation for the sale.

This is a relist after the vehicle was previously sold on BaT in July 2024 and the winning bidder failed to follow through with their commitment to purchase. This was not due to any fault with the vehicle. The winner’s participation on BaT has been restricted.

Cragar 14″ wheels are mounted with Dunlop GT Qualifier tires. Power steering is fitted, and braking is provided by power-assisted four-wheel drums. Multi-leaf rear springs have been installed along with rear air shocks.

The cabin features front bucket seats and a rear bench upholstered in black along with a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. A Pioneer CD stereo is linked to amplifiers housed in the trunk.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 120-mph speedometer and a fuel-level gauge. An aftermarket tachometer is mounted on the steering column, and a trio of readouts are located ahead of the shifter. The five-digit odometer shows 96k miles, approximately 50 of which were added under current ownership.

The selling dealer notes that the 400ci V8 is equipped with a revised camshaft, a Weber carburetor, an Edelbrock Performer intake manifold, an aluminum radiator, and exhaust headers. Three Sunpro readouts are mounted in the engine bay.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a TH400 three-speed automatic transmission.
Decoding the trim tag provides the following information:

This 1967 Pontiac Firebird convertible is finished in burgundy over a black interior and is powered by a 400ci V8 linked with a three-speed automatic transmission. The car is said to have remained with one family for more than three decades prior to the selling dealer’s 2024 acquisition. Equipment includes an Edelbrock Performer intake manifold, a black soft top, dual hood scoops, 14″ Cragar wheels, power steering, power-assisted drum brakes, a Pioneer CD stereo, and trunk-mounted amplifiers. This Firebird is now offered by the selling dealer in New York with a clean Tennessee title.

The car was refinished in burgundy at some point under prior ownership and is equipped with quad round headlights, dual hood scoops, a door-mounted driver-side mirror, and a bright front grille, rear bumper, and trim. The black soft top operates slowly and requires service. Replacement wheelwell moldings were installed in preparation for the sale.

This is a relist after the vehicle was previously sold on BaT in July 2024 and the winning bidder failed to follow through with their commitment to purchase. This was not due to any fault with the vehicle. The winner’s participation on BaT has been restricted.

Cragar 14″ wheels are mounted with Dunlop GT Qualifier tires. Power steering is fitted, and braking is provided by power-assisted four-wheel drums. Multi-leaf rear springs have been installed along with rear air shocks.

The cabin features front bucket seats and a rear bench upholstered in black along with a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. A Pioneer CD stereo is linked to amplifiers housed in the trunk.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 120-mph speedometer and a fuel-level gauge. An aftermarket tachometer is mounted on the steering column, and a trio of readouts are located ahead of the shifter. The five-digit odometer shows 96k miles, approximately 50 of which were added under current ownership.

The selling dealer notes that the 400ci V8 is equipped with a revised camshaft, a Weber carburetor, an Edelbrock Performer intake manifold, an aluminum radiator, and exhaust headers. Three Sunpro readouts are mounted in the engine bay.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a TH400 three-speed automatic transmission.
Decoding the trim tag provides the following information:

This 1977 Honda CB750A Hondamatic was purchased new at Cycle World of Thornhill, Ontario, by the seller’s father who, along with the seller, have ridden it 6,500 miles. It is finished in Candy Presto Red and is powered by a 736cc inline-four paired with a two-speed Hondamatic semi-automatic transmission. Features include 19″ front and 17″ rear alloy rims, a front disc brake, an electric starter, a four-into-two exhaust system, chrome fenders, and a two-up seat in addition to a HondaLine luggage rack, footpegs, passenger backrest, and chrome engine and rear guard. This CB750A Hondamatic is now offered at no reserve in Canada with manufacturer’s literature, initial purchase documentation, historical registration documents, spare parts, a period Shoei helmet, a tool kit, and Manitoba registration in the seller’s name.

The fuel tank and side panels are finished in Candy Presto Red, and the bike features a locking two-up seat upholstered in black vinyl with a passenger grab strap. Brightwork includes the chain guard, fenders, mirrors, engine guard, luggage rack, and rear guard, and the bike is also outfitted with passenger foot pegs, a helmet holder, a HondaLine backrest, an electric starter, and center and side stands.

Wire-spoke wheels with 19″ front and 17″ rear alloy rims were mounted with Continental Attack 2 tires in December 2020, and the wheels were trued at that time. The tires show 2015 date codes. The fork seals were replaced, the tubes polished, and the front brake caliper was rebuilt in July 2007. The bike features dual shocks and a drum brake out back. The seller notes that the parking brake does not work.

Instrumentation includes a Nippon Seiki 130-mph speedometer and a combination unit housing the transmission gear indicator, a fuel-level gauge, and indicator lights. The five-digit odometer shows 6,500 miles. The turn signal relay was replaced in December 2020. There is a dent in the speedometer ring.

The 736cc inline-four featured four Keihin carburetors and a four-into-two exhaust system. It was factory rated at 47 horsepower. The mufflers and fuse box were replaced in December 2020, an oil change was carried out in March 2024, and the carburetors were cleaned and synchronized in July 2024.
Power is routed to the rear wheel through a two-speed Hondamatic semi-automatic transmission and a drive chain.
Records, manufacturer’s literature, a Clymer repair manual, and prior registration documents will accompany the motorcycle.
Also included is a tool kit, a 1975 Shoei helmet, a pair of older tires, and spare and removed parts.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its Manitoba registration, which serves as the ownership document in Manitoba, Canada.

This 1955 Dodge C-3-D truck is said to have been mounted onto the frame of a 1966 Ford Galaxie, which also supplied a 289ci V8 and a three-speed automatic transmission. Other modifications applied under prior ownership include the installation of a wood-plank flatbed as well as a Texaco door graphics, pinstriping, polished wheel covers, power steering, rear air shocks, rear coil springs, aftermarket gauges, lap belts, and an aluminum radiator. The selling dealer acquired the truck in early 2024. Finished in black over gray upholstery, this modified Dodge is now offered at no reserve with a Georgia title.

The truck is finished in black, with hand-painted Texaco logos on the doors and custom pinstriping around the vehicle. Features include a custom wood-plank flatbed with wood side rails as well as a gray front bumper and grille, dual side mirrors, turn signals, windshield wipers, and a cowl vent. Dents, scratches, missing paint, patches, rust, cracked door glass, deteriorated weatherstripping, and other imperfections are shown in the video and photo galleries provided below.

Black 15″ steel wheels with chrome covers are wrapped in 205/75 Hankook Kinergy ST tires. The truck has power steering, unassisted four-wheel drum brakes, rear air shocks, and rear coil springs. The steering wheel is cockeyed when the vehicle is being driven straight, and the seller describes the steering as “touchy.”

The bench seat is upholstered in gray vinyl. The interior offers lap belts and sun visors. The truck lacks a headliner, a dome-light lens, and a glovebox liner. The passenger door has a window crank in place of the interior door handle.

A Ford steering wheel and column sit ahead of a 110-mph speedometer and Equus gauges monitoring fuel level, voltage, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer indicates 60k miles, approximately 10 of which were added by the selling dealer; true mileage is unknown.
The 289ci Ford V8 reportedly was installed by the previous owner. Modifications include a chrome air-cleaner cover and an aluminum radiator. Some parts of the exhaust system have been replaced.

Power is delivered to the rear wheels via a three-speed automatic transmission, which is said to have been sourced from the aforementioned 1966 Ford Galaxie along with that vehicle’s frame and engine. Rust is noted on underbody components as well as the lower cab corners and the bottoms of the front fenders.
The Georgia title carries a notation reading “Conditional title — May not reflect all liens or other encumbrances.”

This 2008 Mercedes-Benz SLR McLaren is a triple-black roadster that has accumulated 10k miles during time in California, Texas, Arizona, and Michigan. Power comes from a supercharged 5.4-liter M155 V8 paired with an AMG Speedshift R five-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes asymmetrical 19″ turbine-spoke wheels, carbon-ceramic disc brakes, butterfly doors, xenon headlights, a gray soft top, side-exit exhaust pipes, carbon-fiber seats, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This SLR McLaren roadster was listed on BaT in January 2024 and is now offered again in New Jersey by the selling dealer with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Michigan title.

The SLR was built with a carbon-fiber monocoque and crash structures. This example is finished in Pure Black and features upward-opening butterfly doors, a gray convertible soft top, integrated fog lights, heated side mirrors, twin side-exit exhaust outlets behind each front wheel, a rear diffuser, and an electronically deployed rear spoiler air brake. The xenon headlights have been modified with black-finished bezels and the Carfax report notes that the windshield was replaced in February 2009. The selling dealer notes chips in the finish on the exhaust outlets.

Asymmetrical turbine-style 19″ alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Super Sport tires measuring 255/35 up front and 295/30 out back. Stopping power is provided by gold-finished and Mercedes-Benz-branded calipers over carbon-ceramic rotors at all four corners, and the car is equipped with a Sensotronic Brake Control system (SBC).

Black leather covers the power-adjustable carbon-fiber seats along with the center console, dashboard, and door panel inserts, while aluminum trim accents the cabin. Additional equipment includes a trunk-mounted CD changer, a Bose sound system, a shift knob-mounted starter button, a wind deflector, and dual-zone automatic climate control. The car was ordered with an XXL driver’s seat and an extra large passenger seat. An aftermarket Kenwood stereo and JL Audio amplifier have been added though the selling dealer states the speakers do not emit sound.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames McLaren-branded instrumentation including a 220-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 10k miles.

The front-mid-mounted 5.4-liter M155 V8 was factory rated at 617 horsepower and 575 lb-ft of torque and features all-aluminum construction, 24 valves, dry-sump lubrication, and a Lysholm-type twin-screw supercharger.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through an AMG Speedshift R five-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 2005 Ford GT is one of 2,022 built for the model year, and it was purchased by the seller in April 2010. The car is finished in Mark IV Red over Ebony leather and was factory optioned with red-finished brake calipers, painted White stripes, and a McIntosh stereo system. Power is supplied by a supercharged 5.4-liter V8 linked with a six-speed manual gearbox and a helical limited-slip differential. Additional equipment includes Brembo brakes, HID headlights, a front splitter, a rear diffuser, and air conditioning. This Ford GT has 1,900 miles and is now offered with a clean Carfax report and a clean Louisiana title in the seller’s name.

The Camilo Pardo-designed GT was styled as an homage to the Le Mans-winning GT40 racing cars of the 1960s and features aluminum body panels over an extruded-aluminum space frame and roll-bonded floors. This example is one of 766 finished in Mark IV Red for the model year and features optional over-the-top white stripes and Ford GT graphics, HID headlights, fog lights, side air intakes, a vented hood, a front splitter, a rear diffuser, and a dual center-exit exhaust system.

Painted cast aluminum wheels measure 18″ up front and 19″ out back and are mounted with Goodyear Eagle F1 Supercar tires. The Brembo braking system features optional red-painted four-piston monoblock calipers with cross-drilled and ventilated rotors that measure 14” up front and 13.2” out back.

The cockpit is trimmed in Ebony leather, and rubber mats cover bare aluminum floors. Manually adjusted seats were designed by Sparco and feature carbon-fiber shells with GT40-style ventilation grommets and harness slots. The console on the center tunnel houses rotary climate controls, and amenities include a McIntosh CD stereo, air conditioning, remote keyless entry, and push-button ignition.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel is affixed to a tilting and telescoping column ahead of the GT40-inspired instrument array consisting of a central tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline and an offset 220-mph speedometer. Toggle-switch controls are positioned under additional gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, voltage, boost, and fuel level. The seller notes that the gauges were replaced in May 2023. The digital odometer indicates 1,900 miles, approximately 700 of which were added under current ownership.

The mid-mounted 5.4-liter DOHC V8 features an aluminum block, cylinder heads, and pistons in addition to a Lysholm screw-type supercharger, a dry-sump lubrication system, and a water-to-air intercooler. Factory-rated output was 550 horsepower and 500 lb-ft of torque, which is sent to the rear wheels through a Ricardo six-speed manual transaxle and a helical limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.
listing_details: Mark IV Red Paint w/White Stripes

description: This 1958 Austin-Healey 100-6 BN6 is a left-hand-drive, two-seat roadster that was built in July 1958 and dispatched to Vancouver, British Columbia in Canada. The car is said to have remained under the care of a single family from the early 1960s through 2017, during which time it underwent refurbishment work in the 1990s and after which it was acquired by the seller’s father. Finished in duotone Pacific Green and Florida Green, the car is powered by a 2.6-liter inline-six mated to a four-speed manual transmission with overdrive. Inside, beige leather trim is accompanied by a Smiths cabin heater, lap belts, and a push-button radio. Additional equipment includes a grey convertible top, a luggage rack, 15″ wire wheels, and four-wheel drum brakes. This BN6 is now offered in Canada by the seller on behalf of their father’s estate with a tonneau cover, sliding-window side curtains, an owner’s handbook, refurbishment records, a British Motor Industry Heritage Trust certificate, and Ontario registration in the father’s name that lists the vehicle’s model year as 1959.

Finished from the factory in duotone Pacific Green and Florida Green, the car was mounted to a rotisserie as part of the aforementioned 1990s refurbishment, during which it underwent bodywork prior to being refinished by Reg Beer Coachbuilder Corp. of Bolton, Ontario, Canada. Exterior details include chrome bumpers with overriders as well as a hood scoop, dual fender-mounted side mirrors, a rear luggage rack, and twin exhaust tips. A grey convertible top is installed, and a grey tonneau cover along with sliding side windows will accompany the vehicle.
Chrome-finished 15″ wire wheels are secured via two-eared knock-offs and mounted with 165-series Vredestein Sprint Classic tires. Braking is provided by four-wheel drums.

The reupholstered cabin houses a pair of low-back bucket seats trimmed in leather with green piping complemented by a color-coordinated dashboard and door panels. Green carpeting lines the floors, and additional appointments include lap belts, a Smiths under-dash heater, a passenger-side grab handle, and a push-button radio. Imperfections in the trim are shown up close in the gallery below.

The banjo-style steering wheel features a 100-6 horn button and fronts Smiths instrumentation that includes a 120-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary gauges monitoring oil pressure, water temperature, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 66k miles, less than 10 of which have been added since 2020.

The 2.6L inline-six was overhauled in the early 1980s and is equipped with twin SU carburetors. Output was rated at 117 horsepower and 149 lb-ft of torque when new. The radiator core has been rebuilt.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transmission with an electrically actuated Laycock de Normanville overdrive unit.

The British Motor Industry Heritage Trust certificate lists factory colors, equipment, and initial delivery to the Austin Motor Company (Canada) of Vancouver, British Columbia, along with a build date in July 1958. The certificate also notes a chassis number of BN6-LO/2065, whereas the chassis plate and the Ontario registration document list the VIN as BN6L92065.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its Ontario registration, which serves as the ownership document in Ontario, Canada.

This 1965 Chevrolet Corvette convertible was purchased by the current owner in 1985 and refurbished in the same decade, which included installing an overhauled 396ci V8 linked with a four-speed manual transmission. Further refurbishments included repainting the car in red, reupholstering the black vinyl interior, and fitting a replacement clutch, flywheel, and clutch release fork. Equipment includes a removable red hardtop, 15″ Rally wheels, four-wheel disc brakes, a Weiand intake manifold, retractable headlights, chrome bumpers, dual exhaust outlets, a Delco radio, and a wood-rimmed steering wheel. This C2 convertible is now offered at no reserve by the seller on behalf of the current owner with service records and a clean California title.

The fiberglass body left the factory finished in Rally Red (UU) and was repainted in 1988, at which time the chrome was re-plated. Additional details include a removable red hardtop, a driver-side mirror, a power-retractable antenna, flip-up headlights, fender vents, split chrome bumpers, and dual exhaust outlets exiting through the rear valance.

The 15″ steel wheels are mounted with 215/70 BFGoodrich Touring T/A tires. The C2 was the first Corvette to offer fully independent suspension, with upper and lower control arms at the front and a three-link setup with a transverse leaf spring at the rear. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs. The suspension was overhauled in 2001, with work consisting of installing KYB shocks and replacing the front-end bushings, U-joints, and lower ball joints.

The cabin was refreshed in 2001 by Javier’s Corvette in Van Nuys, California, and features two bucket seats upholstered in black vinyl joined by color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Amenities include a heater, lap belts, and a Delco AM/FM radio.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for fuel level, amperage, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 70k miles, approximately 30k of which were added under current ownership. The speedometer was repaired in 2001. Total mileage is unknown.

The replacement 396ci V8 was overhauled in 2001 and it is equipped with a Weiand intake manifold and Holley valve covers. Work in May 2021 included installing a new carburetor, replacing the spark plugs and fuel filter, cleaning the fuel tank, and changing the oil.

Power is delivered to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transmission that received a replacement clutch, flywheel, and clutch release fork in 2010. The dual exhaust system is equipped with MagnaFlow mufflers.
Decoding the trim tag reveals the following information:

This 1994 Land Rover Defender 90 is #255 of approximately 2,000 North American-Specification examples imported into the US for the model year. The truck is powered by a 3.9-liter V8 linked with a five-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case and is finished in Alpine White over Charcoal cloth and vinyl. Features include a roll cage, a front brush guard, an aftermarket roof rack, overhead auxiliary lights, 16″ five-spoke wheels, air conditioning, and a CD stereo. The current owner purchased the truck in 2019 and it now shows 92k miles. This Defender 90 NAS is now offered on dealer consignment with a clean Carfax report and a clean Washington title.

Aluminum body panels are finished in Alpine White and accented by black wheel arch flares, and NAS models were equipped with a roll cage from the factory. Additional equipment includes a front brush guard, an aftermarket safari roof basket, auxiliary overhead lights, a rear ladder, side step bars, a tubular rear bumper, a black soft top, and a Yakima Road Shower that has not been plumed. A rear plaque identifies this truck as #255 of approximately 2,000. Paint chips on the front end are noted by the selling dealer.

Factory 16″ five-spoke wheels are mounted with 265/75 BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A tires, and a matching spare is mounted on the swing-out carrier at the rear. Stopping power is provided by power-assisted discs at all four corners. A Bilstein steering damper was installed and the brake pads and pitman arm were replaced in July 2024.

The front bucket seats are upholstered in Charcoal cloth and vinyl and are complemented by a gray dashboard and door panels. Interior amenities include air conditioning, a CD stereo, and rubber floormats. The seatbelt buckles and speaker covers were replaced in July 2024 in addition to missing screws in the right sun visor and the door panels.
The two-spoke steering wheel frames a 120-mph speedometer and a 6k-rpm tachometer as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 92k miles.

The 3.9-liter V8 was factory rated at 182 horsepower and 232 lb-ft of torque. The intake hose, fuel filter, windshield washer pump, and brake master cylinder grommets were replaced in July 2024. Engine compression results taken in July 2024 are shown in the gallery below.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case. An aftermarket muffler is installed. The clutch was replaced in June 2024.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2016 Land Rover Range Rover Sport SE spent time in California, Florida, and Arizona before the selling dealer’s acquisition in 2024, and it now has 42k miles. It is powered by a 3.0-liter turbodiesel V6 linked with an eight-speed automatic transmission and is finished in Santorini Black Metallic over Ebony leather. Equipment includes a panoramic sunroof, xenon headlights, parking sensors, 19″ Style 501 wheels, power-adjustable front seats, a Meridian sound system, dual-zone climate control, and navigation. This L494 Range Rover Sport is now offered in New York by the selling dealer with a clean Arizona title.

The truck is finished in Santorini Black Metallic with a body-color matching roof, and exterior equipment includes a panoramic sunroof, xenon headlights, front and rear parking sensors, heated power-folding side mirrors, a rearview camera, a rear spoiler, and a power-operated tailgate. The Carfax report lists damage in November 2017. Close-up photos of the paintwork and trim are presented in the gallery.

The 19″ Style 501 wheels have been refinished in black and are mounted with 235/65 Pirelli tires with 2014 date codes. The truck is equipped with an adjustable air suspension and a Terrain Response system. Stopping power is provided by anti-lock disc brakes with Cornering Brake Control, Hill Descent Control, Trailer Stability Control, Emergency Brake Assist, and Hill Start Assist.

The seating surfaces are upholstered in Ebony leather and are accompanied by a color-coordinated center console, dashboard, and door panels. Interior amenities include power-adjustable front seats with memory settings along with a Meridian sound system, push-button ignition, dual-zone climate control, navigation, and a touchscreen infotainment system. The right backseat storage net is missing.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a 180-mph speedometer and a tachometer as well as a TFT display. The digital odometer indicates 42k miles.
The 3.0-liter Td6 turbodiesel V6 was factory rated at 254 horsepower and 440 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was completed in 2024.
Power is delivered to all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission and a single-speed transfer case.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage entry and at least one open recall.
