description: This 2007 BMW 650i convertible was first delivered to BMW of North America in Greer, South Carolina, and it has 24k miles. It is finished in Alpine White over Cream Beige Dakota leather and is powered by a 4.8-liter V8 paired with a six-speed automatic transmission. Features include the Sport Package, the Cold Weather Package, the Premium Sound Package, a black soft top, adaptive xenon headlights, Park Distance Control, 19″ Style 121 alloy wheels, heated power-adjustable front sport seats, Comfort Access, a CD stereo, a heated steering wheel, and iDrive with navigation. This E64 650i convertible is now offered in Pennsylvania by the selling dealer with a window sticker, owner’s manuals, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New York title.

The car is finished in Alpine White (300) with the Sport Package, which added Shadowline trim. Additional exterior features include a black convertible top, adaptive xenon headlights, fog lights, Park Distance Control, and dual exhaust outlets.
The 19″ Style 121 alloy wheels are mounted with Bridgestone Potenza RE050A tires. Stopping power is provided by ventilated discs at each corner.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front sport seats upholstered in Cream Beige Dakota leather, which is complemented by light birch wood trim. Interior features include driver-seat position memory along with Comfort Access, a premium sound system, a CD stereo, cruise control, dual-zone automatic climate control, and iDrive with navigation.

The heated leather-wrapped sport steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 24k miles.
The 4.8-liter N62B48TU V8 features double-VANOS variable valve timing and was factory rated at 360 horsepower and 360 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a ZF six-speed automatic transmission.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to BMW of North America in Greer, South Carolina, along with factory equipment, colors, and a total suggested retail price of $86,940.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.
listing_details: Sport, Premium Sound, & Cold Weather Packages

description: This 2016 Ford Focus RS was purchased new by owner at Ray Varner Ford of Clinton, Tennessee, and now has 499 miles. Finished in Nitrous Blue Metallic Quad-Coat over Charcoal Black leather and microsuede, the car is powered by a turbocharged 2.3-liter inline-four linked with a six-speed manual transaxle and a torque-vectoring all-wheel-drive system. Equipment includes 19″ forged alloy wheels, xenon headlights, Brembo front disc brakes, a Sony sound system, SYNC infotainment, Recaro front seats a CD stereo, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This Focus RS is now offered by the seller on behalf of the owner with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, and a clean Tennessee title.

The car is finished in Nitrous Blue Metallic Quad-Coat (DW), and RS models were equipped with a rear wing and revised lower bodywork including a rear diffuser, sill extensions, and bumper covers. Additional exterior details include xenon headlights, a rearview camera, and dual exhaust outlets. The seller states that the car was never driven in rain.

The 19″ forged alloy wheels are mounted with 235/35 Michelin Super Sport tires. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes with Brembo calipers up front. The car is equipped with launch control as well as a sport suspension featuring driver-selectable modes.

The seating surfaces are upholstered in Charcoal Black leather and microsuede, and embroidered RS emblems accent the backrests of the Recaro front bucket seats. Additional appointments include a Sony CD stereo, cruise control, dual-zone automatic climate control, and SYNC 3 infotainment.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel frames a 180-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and a central configurable digital display as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. A trio of instruments for oil temperature, turbocharger boost pressure, and oil pressure are mounted atop the dashboard. The digital odometer indicates 499 miles.
The turbocharged 2.3-liter Ecoboost inline-four was factory rated at 350 horsepower with 350 lb-ft of torque. The head gasket recall was performed in 2020.
Power is delivered to all four wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle and a torque-vectoring all-wheel-drive system.

The window sticker notes initial delivery to Ray Varner Ford in Clinton, Tennessee, and lists factory equipment, colors, options, and a total MSRP of $38,865. Service records are also included in the sale.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 2004 Lincoln Town Car Ultimate is finished in Silver Birch Metallic with a landau half-roof over gray leather, and it is powered by a 4.6-liter V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes 17″ 14-spoke machined aluminum wheels, a keyless entry pad, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, heated power-adjustable front seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, and an AM/FM/CD/cassette stereo. This Town Car has 25k miles and is now offered in Pennsylvania by the selling dealer at no reserve with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Maryland title.

The car is finished in Silver Birch Metallic and features a hood ornament, a keyless entry pad, cornering headlights, dual exhaust outlets, and heated power-adjustable side mirrors. The car also wears an E&G Congressional Town Series landau half-roof, around which bubbling is noted.
Machined aluminum 17″ 14-spoke wheels show curb marks and finish imperfections, and they are mounted with Michelin tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel anti-lock discs.

The heated power-adjustable front seats are trimmed in gray leather, while woodgrain trim accents the dashboard and door panels. Amenities include a rear window defroster, dual-zone automatic climate control, an AM/FM/CD/cassette stereo, and power windows and locks.
The wood- and leather-trimmed steering wheel frames a 120-mph speedometer, auxiliary gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature, and two digital displays. The digital odometer indicates 25k miles.
The 4.6-liter SOHC V8 was factory rated at 239 horsepower and 287 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission with overdrive.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or damage.

This 1985 Ford Mustang LX notchback is a Special Service Package (SSP) example powered by a Roush 347ci V8 crate engine that was fitted in 2003, and it is finished in black over replacement gray cloth upholstery. Equipment includes a five-speed manual transmission, a Centerforce clutch, an MSD tachometer adapter, Holley electronic fuel injection, JBA exhaust headers, a driver-side spotlight, grille-mounted red and blue lights, four-wheel disc brakes, and black-finished 15″ alloy wheels with chrome-finished hubcaps in addition to air conditioning, a JVC CD stereo, a Pilot steering wheel, a police scanner, and a Carson SC-407 radio and siren control unit. The car spent time in Oregon, Washington, California, and Arizona before it was acquired by the current owner in 2022. This Fox-body SSP is offered on dealer consignment with service records and an Arizona title.

The car is finished in black with bright window trim, a driver-side spotlight, quadruple rectangular headlights, grille-mounted red and blue lights, three antennas, and aftermarket fog lights. The roof, decklid, and doors were repainted in November 2004, while the rear bumper cover was repaired and refinished in 2006. Photos show corrosion beneath the fuel filler door.

Black-finished 15″ alloy wheels with chrome-finished hubcaps are wrapped in 225/60 Kumho Ecsta LX Platinum tires. The car is equipped with power steering, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes.

The front bucket seats and the rear bench seat have been reupholstered in gray cloth with patterned inserts, and the cabin features a color-coordinated dashboard and door panels. Appointments include air conditioning, power windows, a JVC CD stereo, and a police scanner. A Carson SC-407 siren control unit mounted beneath the dashboard features a wired microphone, public address and radio functionality, and siren controls.

The Pilot three-spoke steering wheel fronts a 140-mph “Certified Calibration” speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature, amperage, oil pressure, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 33k miles, approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership. The Carfax report lists a potential odometer rollover in October 2000 along with “not actual mileage” and “exceeds mechanical limits” title issuances beginning in June 2003. Total mileage is unknown.

The Roush 347ci V8 crate engine was installed in 2003, and it has been fitted with Holley HP electronic fuel injection in addition to JBA exhaust headers. The selling dealer notes that a replacement distributor and an MSD tachometer adapter were fitted in 2024, at which time a replacement fuel tank was installed.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Centerforce clutch and a five-speed manual transmission.

The Carfax report shows the aforementioned potential odometer rollover and “not actual mileage” and “exceeds mechanical limits” title issuances, and it lists history in Oregon, Washington, California, and Arizona from its initial entry in February 1992.
The Arizona title carries an “Exceeds Mechanical Limits” odometer notation.

This 1976 Cadillac Eldorado Convertible is said to have been purchased new by a member of the seller’s family and is currently owned by the seller’s grandmother. It is powered by a 500ci V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission and finished in red metallic over red leather. Equipment includes a white convertible soft top, 15″ steel wheels, black wheel covers, power steering, four-wheel disc brakes, a power-adjustable front seat, cruise control, power windows, a push-button AM/FM stereo, and a CB radio. This Eldorado Convertible is offered by the seller on behalf of their grandmother with an owner’s manual, a two-piece parade boot, and a clean Montana title.

The car is finished in red metallic with white pinstriping and features a power-operated white convertible soft top, a power antenna, chrome bumpers, fender-mounted light monitors, and a remote-controlled left mirror with a thermometer. The seller notes stains on the soft top, touch-up paint on the rear quarter panels, and paint chips around the body.

The 15″ steel wheels wear black covers and are mounted with 235/75 BFGoodrich Advantage Plus narrow-whitewall tires. The Eldorado featured a torsion bar front suspension and a coil-sprung solid rear axle along with Automatic Level Control and power steering. Braking is handled by power-assisted discs at all four corners.

The power-adjustable front bench seat and rear bench are trimmed in red leather and joined by a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Woodgrain trim accents the cabin, and amenities include cruise control, a push-button AM/FM stereo, a CB radio, a power trunk lid release, and power windows and locks. The seller reports that the air conditioning compressor clutch bearing was recently replaced and notes that the system needs to be recharged.
The three-spoke steering wheel fronts a horizontal-sweep 100-mph speedometer and a fuel level gauge. The five-digit odometer shows 28k miles.

The 500ci V8 features a Rochester Quadrajet four-barrel carburetor and was factory rated at 190 horsepower and 360 lb-ft of torque. The seller states that the carburetor was rebuilt, a tune-up was performed, and the oil was changed at approximately 27k miles.
Power is sent to the front wheels through a Turbo Hydra-Matic three-speed automatic transmission.

This 2012 Porsche 911 Carrera GTS coupe is a Carrara White-finished example that has been modified with an Aerokit front bumper cover, GT3 RS-style side skirts, 19″ center-lock wheels, a European-style rear bumper cover, a GT3 steering wheel, carbon-fiber sport front bucket seats, RS-style door pulls, red seatbelts, a short shifter, and a Shark Werks exhaust system. Powered by a 3.8-liter flat-six paired with a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential, the car is further equipped with a sports suspension, the Sport Chrono Package Plus, a sunroof, black leather upholstery, bi-xenon headlights with PDLS, rear parking sensors, a Bose sound system, and automatic climate control. The current owner acquired the car in 2022 and has since added approximately 2k of the 56k miles. The rear tires were replaced in preparation for the sale. This 997.2 Carrera GTS coupe is now offered in Arizona on dealer consignment with service records, a car cover, spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Montana title.

The 997 GTS featured a revised front apron with larger air intakes, wider bodywork shared with the contemporary Carrera 4S, and a black front lip spoiler, side skirts, and rear diffuser. This example is finished in Carrara White with an Aerokit front bumper cover, a European-style rear bumper cover, GT3 RS-style side skirts, bi-xenon headlights with PDLS, rear parking sensors, a sunroof, a speed-activated rear spoiler, LED taillights, and quad exhaust outlets.

Black-finished 19″ center-lock wheels were reportedly sourced from a GT3 RS and are mounted with 245/35 front and 315/30 rear Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires, the rear of which were installed in July 2024. Braking is handled by red Porsche-branded calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated rotors. The car is equipped with Porsche Stability Management (PSM), an automatic brake differential (ABD), and was optioned with Porsche Active Suspension Management Sport suspension, which lowered the ride height by 20mm when compared with the standard Carrera.

The carbon-fiber sport front bucket seats are trimmed in black leather with red seatbelts, Porsche crests on the headrests, and color-contrasting stitching, while carbon-fiber trim accents the cabin. Porsche-branded floor mats line the footwells, and additional appointments include a Bose sound system, cruise control, PCM with navigation, RS-style door pulls, a short shifter, and automatic climate control. The driver-side door latch assembly was replaced and the passenger-side airbag off warning light were replaced in 2017. A carbon-fiber trim on the right side of the dashboard has deformed.

The GT3-sourced steering wheel frames a central tachometer with a 7,400-rpm redline as well as a 200-mph speedometer and gauges for oil temperature, coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The optional Sport Chrono Package added a stopwatch atop the dashboard. The digital odometer indicates 56k miles, approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership.

The 3.8-liter flat-six was factory rated at 408 horsepower and 310 lb-ft of torque in the GTS, an increase of 23 horsepower over the contemporary Carrera S. Power is sent to the rear wheels via a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. The car has been fitted with a Shark Werks exhaust system, and the seller states that the catalytic converters have been retained. A compression and leak-down test was performed in September 2017 by Auto Tronics in Southampton, Pennsylvania, and the results are viewable in the image gallery below. The clutch assembly was also replaced at this time. Replacement spark plugs were reportedly installed at approximately 50k miles, and an oil change was performed in October 2023.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
There is currently a lien out on the car, and the owner’s lender will need to be paid off before the title can be transferred to the new owner.

This 1971 Volkswagen Super Beetle convertible is finished in red over white vinyl upholstery and is powered by an air-cooled 1.6L flat-four paired with a four-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes a Black convertible soft top, a white top boot, 15″ steel wheels, drum brakes, fender stone guards, and a retro-style radio. The car was refurbished approximately five years ago and was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. This 1302 Super Beetle is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve in Florida with the owner’s manual and a clean Louisiana title describing it as a 1971 Volkswagen Bug.

The car was refinished in red circa 2019 and features a black convertible soft top and a white boot. Additional details include front and rear fender stone guards, a Karmann body tag affixed to the right front quarter panel, dual “pea shooter” exhaust outlets, and chrome bumpers.

Steel 15″ wheels wear chrome VW-stamped hubcaps and are mounted with 165/80 Classic Radial LL800 All Season tires. The car was factory equipped with a MacPherson strut and coil spring front suspension in place of the standard Beetle’s torsion bar setup. Stopping power is provided by drum brakes at all four corners.

The front bucket seats and the rear bench are upholstered in white vinyl and are joined by color-coordinated door panels and charcoal carpeting. Interior elements include a lockable glove box, door map pockets, quarter vent windows, and a retro-style radio.

The two-spoke steering wheel features a chrome horn ring with a Wolfsburg crest center cap and frames a 90-mph VDO speedometer with an inset fuel-level gauge. The five-digit odometer shows 61k miles, a handful of which have been added by the selling dealer.
The air-cooled 1.6L (AH) flat-four is fed by a single downdraft carburetor topped with an open-element air cleaner. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transaxle. Extended studs have been installed in the sump plate.

This 1995 Mercedes-Benz E320 cabriolet was purchased new by the current owner from John Sisson Mercedes-Benz in Washington, Pennsylvania, and it now has 1,600 miles. The car is powered by a 3.2-liter M104 inline-six paired with a four-speed automatic transmission and is finished in Polar White over gray leather upholstery. Equipment includes a black convertible soft top, silver 15″ Alamak alloy wheels, heated power-adjustable front seats, a cassette stereo, automatic climate control, and cruise control. This A124 E320 is offered on dealer consignment with manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Pennsylvania title.

The car is finished in Polar White (149) and features a power-operated black convertible soft top, headlight wipers, a power-telescoping antenna, bright trim, asymmetrical side mirrors, and a single eccentric-sweep windshield wiper. Photographs of paint-meter readings are presented in the gallery
Silver 15″ Alamak alloy wheels are mounted with Continental tires. The car is equipped with Acceleration Slip Control (ASR), and braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats upholstered in gray leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, center console, door panels, and carpets. Burl wood accents the dash, center stack, and doors, while amenities include a cassette stereo, automatic climate control, and cruise control.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline as well as an analog clock and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 1,600 miles.
The 3.2-liter M104 inline-six features four valves per cylinder and was factory rated at 217 horsepower and 229 lb-ft of torque. The engine wiring harness is said to have been serviced in 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1970 Chevrolet Chevelle Malibu Sport Coupe was refurbished under prior ownership approximately 24 years ago, at which time it was refinished in champagne gold with a black vinyl roof and stripes. It is powered by a replacement 454ci V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission, and equipment includes a Positraction limited-slip differential, 14″ Sport wheels, front disc brakes, a cowl-induction hood, a black grille, a driver-side mirror, a horseshoe-style shifter, an AM/FM radio, air conditioning, and a center console as well as an Edelbrock aluminum intake manifold. This Chevelle Sport coupe was acquired by the selling dealer in 2023 and is now offered with a clean Indiana title.

Originally painted green, the car was refinished in champagne gold with black stripes and a black vinyl roof during the refurbishment in 2000. Equipment includes a cowl induction hood, SS badging, a driver-side mirror, and hideaway windshield wipers.
The 14″ sport wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich Radial T/A white-letter tires. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The front bucket and rear bench seats were reupholstered in black vinyl during the refurbishment, and interior appointments include a horseshoe-style shifter, a center console, an AM radio, and air conditioning.

The tilting steering wheel frames a 120-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, and an analog clock in addition to readouts for amperage, fuel level, and coolant temperature. An oil-pressure gauge is mounted below the dash. The five-digit odometer shows 54k miles, approximately 50 of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The car is powered by a replacement 454ci V8 topped with an Edelbrock aluminum intake manifold, a four-barrel carburetor, and a cowl-induction air cleaner assembly. The seller notes oil seeps from the oil pan gasket.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a Turbo Hydra-Matic three-speed automatic transmission and a Positraction limited-slip differential.
Decoding the data plate reveals the following production information:

This 2022 Ford Mustang Shelby GT500 is a Heritage Edition example that was ordered with the Carbon Fiber Track Pack as well as the Technology package. The car is finished in Brittany Blue Metallic with Wimbledon White painted stripes over Ebony leather and suede and is powered by a supercharged 5.2-liter V8 linked with a Tremec seven-speed dual-clutch automatic transmission and a Torsen limited-slip differential. Features include HID headlights, carbon-fiber 20″ seven-spoke wheels, a JLT air-intake system, Brembo brakes, Recaro seats, a Bang & Olufsen 12-speaker audio system, and SYNC 3 infotainment with navigation. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this GT500 has 275 miles and is now offered in California with a digital copy of the window sticker, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean Nevada title.

All GT500 Heritage Edition examples were finished in Brittany Blue Metallic with optional Wimbledon White side and painted over-the-top stripes. Exterior features include a louvered hood, HID headlights, and LED taillights with sequential turn signals. The Carbon Fiber Track Pack added front splitter wickers and a manually adjustable carbon-fiber rear wing.

Exposed carbon-fiber 20″ seven-spoke wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires measuring 305/30 up front and 315/30 out back. The car is equipped with four-wheel independent suspension and a MagneRide damping system. Stopping power is provided by six-piston front and four-piston rear Brembo brake calipers fitted over two-piece ventilated rotors. The Carbon Fiber Track Pack added adjustable strut top mounts.

The Recaro front seats are upholstered in Ebony leather and suede with Dove accents, and the rear seats were deleted as part of the Carbon Fiber Track Pack. Amenities include a SYNC 3 infotainment system with an 8″ touchscreen as well as a Bang & Olufsen 12-speaker audio system, BLIS blind-spot monitoring, dual-zone automatic climate control, Ford Track Apps, and voice-activated navigation.
The passenger-side dashboard plaque identifies this GT500 as chassis N0933.

The Alcantara- and leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel features a gray centering stripe and paddle shifters and frames a configurable 12″ LCD instrument panel. Analog oil pressure and oil temperature gauges are mounted in the center stack. The digital odometer indicates 274 miles.

The supercharged 5.2-liter Predator V8 features an air-to-liquid intercooler, an engine oil cooler, and a cast aluminum intake manifold. Factory-rated output was 760 horsepower and 625 lb-ft of torque. A JLT air-intake system is installed.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Tremec seven-speed dual-clutch automatic transmission and a Torsen limited-slip differential with 3.73:1 gearing. The car features an active dual exhaust system with polished quadruple outlets.
The Carfax report notes at least one recall.

description: This 2006 Porsche Cayenne Turbo is a black-over-black example powered by a twin-turbocharged 4.5-liter V8 paired with a six-speed Tiptronic S automatic transmission. Equipment includes cat-less downpipes, a panoramic sunroof, four-zone automatic climate control, ParkAssist, 20″ Cayenne Sport Techno wheels, heated power-adjustable front seats, a Bose sound system, Porsche Entry and Drive, and an aftermarket touchscreen stereo. The vehicle spent time in New York, Pennsylvania, and Missouri before the selling dealer’s recent acquisition, and it now has under 108k miles. This Cayenne Turbo is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with service records and a clean Missouri title.

The vehicle is finished in black with black trim and features a panoramic sunroof, bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, front and rear parking sensors, a rear window wiper, and sport tailpipes. The Carfax report notes that the rear of the vehicle sustained “minor damage” in an August 2016 accident, and the selling dealer notes evidence of paintwork on a rear quarter panel. Noted blemishes include stone chips on the front bumper cover and dings and scratches around the body.

The 20″ Cayenne Sport Techno alloy wheels are mounted with Cooper tires. The vehicle is equipped with an air suspension and Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM). Stopping power is from red Porsche-branded calipers over ventilated rotors at each corner. The front lower control arms were replaced in January 2021.

The heated power-adjustable front seats have debossed Porsche crests in the headrests and are upholstered in black leather. Other interior features include four-zone automatic climate control, a Bose sound system, cruise control, Porsche Entry and Drive, illuminated Turbo-branded door sill guards, a carbon-fiber shift handle, and an aftermarket touchscreen stereo. The rearview camera is not connected to the navigation screen and the selling dealer notes wear on interior surfaces.

The carbon-fiber- and leather-rimmed multi-function steering wheel features shifter switches and frames a 180-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil temperature, coolant temperature, fuel level, and boost pressure. The digital odometer indicates under 108k miles.

The twin-turbocharged 4.5-liter V8 was factory rated at 450 horsepower and 457 lb-ft of torque. The selling dealer states that cat-less downpipes are installed. Records indicate that the driveshaft flex disc, valve cover gaskets, and camshaft plugs and seals were replaced in January 2021, and the starter was replaced in September 2021.
Power is routed to all four wheels through a six-speed Tiptronic S automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a variable center differential.
The Carfax report notes the aforementioned accident entry and at least one recall.

This 1983 Porsche 911SC coupe was initially sold in Missouri and remained registered in the state through the selling dealer’s acquisition in 2024. Finished in black over black leather, it is powered by a 3.0-liter flat-six paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. The car is equipped with 16″ Fuchs alloy wheels, a steel sunroof, a whale-tail rear spoiler, a MOMO steering wheel, power windows, and a Pioneer CD stereo. This 911SC coupe is offered by the selling dealer with hood and nose masks, a tool kit, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Missouri title.

The car is finished in black with silver Porsche-script side graphics and features headlights with washers as well as a front chin spoiler, power-adjustable side mirrors, an added whale-tail rear spoiler, and rear bumperettes. Paint meter readings from around the car are presented in the gallery.

The refinished 16″ Fuchs wheels with black centers are mounted with 205/55 front and 225/50 rear Hankook Ventus R-S2 tires. Stopping power is provided by power-assisted four-wheel disc brakes with ventilated rotors.

The front sport seats and individual rear seats are upholstered in black leather complemented by a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Appointments include an aftermarket shift knob, power windows, and a Pioneer CD stereo. The air conditioning system has been removed.

The leather-wrapped MOMO steering wheel frames a central tachometer with a 6,300-rpm redline as well as a 170-mph speedometer, a clock, and gauges for oil level, oil temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 126k miles.
The 3.0-liter flat-six was factory rated at 172 horsepower and 189 lb-ft of torque and features Bosch fuel injection. The air conditioning compressor and catalytic converter have been removed.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Type 915 five-speed manual transaxle.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists history in Missouri from new.

This 1954 Chevrolet 3600 pickup is finished in yellow over black vinyl upholstery, and it is powered by a 235ci inline-six paired with a four-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes 15″ steel wheels, a wood bed floor, chrome bumpers, and running boards. The truck was acquired by the selling dealer in 2019, and work under current ownership is said to have included replacing the rear pinion seal and turn signal bulbs. This 3600 pickup is offered by the selling dealer in Wisconsin with a truck cover and a clean Minnesota title.

The truck was repainted yellow under prior ownership, and equipment includes chrome bumpers, running boards, and a wood bed floor. The turn signals and license plate bulbs were replaced in September 2023. A crack is visible on the right side window.
Black-finished 15″ steel wheels wear chrome hubcaps and are mounted with BFGoodrich Silvertown whitewall tires. Braking is provided by drums at each corner.
The bench seat is trimmed in black vinyl, and it is accompanied by a color-coordinated dashboard and door panels. The radio does not work.
The three-spoke steering wheel sits ahead of a 90-mph speedometer and supplementary gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 73k miles.
The 235ci inline-six sends power to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission. The rear pinion seal was replaced in September 2023, according to the selling dealer.
Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery.
The truck is titled using VIN J54J013243, and the partially obscured frame stamp is shown above.

This 1986.5 Porsche 928S is finished in Pastel Beige over brown leather and it shows 68k miles. The car features a modified exhaust system, 16″ flat disc wheels, and adjustable coilovers with Boge dampers in addition to power-adjustable front seats, a sunroof, a 930S-style steering wheel, automatic climate control, and a Bluetooth-capable Blaupunkt stereo. Steinels Autowerks of Twinsburg, Ohio, serviced its 5.0-liter DOHC V8, five-speed manual transaxle, brakes, and climate-control system in preparation for the sale to its current owner on BaT in January 2023, and the tires have since been replaced. This 928S is offered on dealer consignment with a clean Carfax report and a clean Montana title in the owner’s name.

The Pastel Beige finish was covered with paint protection film under previous ownership. Equipment includes pop-up headlights, headlamp washers, integrated fog lights, body-color mirror caps, a sunroof, a rear spoiler, a rear wiper, and dual exhaust outlets.
Anodized 16″ flat disc wheels are mounted with Pirelli P Zero Rosso tires. The suspension has Boge and 928 Motorsport components as well as aftermarket drop links and end links.

The power-adjustable front seats are upholstered in brown leather, and sisal mats line the footwells. Interior appointments include automatic climate control, rear air conditioning, cruise control, a Blaupunkt Bremen SQR 46 DAB stereo, a Hi-Fi sound system, power windows, and a short-shift kit.

The 930S-style steering wheel sits on a raised hub and frames VDO instrumentation. The six-digit odometer shows 68k miles, approximately 400 of which were added under current ownership. The heater control valve was replaced in January 2023. The removed steering wheel is included in the sale.

Factory rated at 288 horsepower and 302 lb-ft of torque, the 5.0-liter DOHC V8 features LH-Jetronic fuel injection and a factory-uprated cooling system, and it sends power to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle. The fuel pressure damper and air mass sensor o-ring were replaced in January 2023 along with the oxygen sensor and its wiring harness, at which time the clutch slave cylinder and hydraulic fluids were also replaced. Seepage is noted from the valve cover gaskets.
The exhaust system has an aftermarket X-pipe and a bypassed rear muffler.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2014 Porsche Panamera GTS is finished in Agate Grey Metallic over Cream and Marsala Red leather and is powered by a 4.8-liter V8 that drives all four wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch automatic transmission. Equipment includes the Premium Package Plus as well as four-zone automatic climate control, soft-close doors, 20″ Panamera Sport wheels, heated and ventilated front and rear seats, PCM with navigation, and LED headlights with PDLS. The car has spent time in Florida, Missouri, California, and Nevada and now has 44k miles. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this Panamera GTS is now offered with a clean Nevada title.

The car is finished in Agate Grey Metallic (M7S) with body-color-painted side skirts and is equipped with LED headlights in black with the Porsche Dynamic Light System (PDLS) as well as a sunroof, soft-close doors, front and rear ParkAssist, and a speed-activated rear spoiler. The Carfax report notes that the rear of the car sustained “minor damage” in April 2018 with no additional information provided.

The 20″ Panamera Sport alloy wheels are mounted with Pirelli Cinturato tires measuring 255/40 up front and 295/35 out back. The car was factory-equipped with adaptive air suspension, Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM), and Power Steering Plus. Stopping power is provided by Porsche-branded calipers over slotted and ventilated discs at each corner.

The cabin features heated and ventilated front and rear seats upholstered in Cream leather complemented by a two-tone Marsala Red and Cream dashboard and door panels. Additional appointments include four-zone automatic climate control, power-adjustable front seats, carbon-fiber trim, a back-up camera, Porsche Entry and Drive, powered rear sunshades, Lane Change Assist (LCA), and Porsche Communication Management (PCM) with navigation.

The leather-wrapped SportDesign steering wheel has a pair of paddle shifters and frames white instrument dials consisting of a central tachometer with a 7,200-rpm redline, a 200-mph speedometer, and a configurable display as well as gauges for oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The standard Sport Chrono Package added a stopwatch atop the dash. The digital odometer indicates 44k miles.
The 4.8-liter V8 was factory rated at 440 horsepower and 384 lb-ft of torque.
Power is delivered to all four wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch automatic transmission.
The Carfax report notes the aforementioned damage entry as well as manufacturer safety and emissions recalls

This Thunder Ranch 550 Spyder replica is powered by a turbocharged and intercooled 2,276cc air-cooled flat-four equipped with dual Dell’Orto DRLA carburetors, MSD ignition, a Turbosmart boost controller, and a Snow Performance methanol injection kit. It is finished in silver over red upholstery and equipped with 15″ steel wheels, four-wheel disc brakes, aluminum drum covers, a four-speed manual transaxle, a hydraulically-actuated clutch slave cylinder, and a Jamar Performance shifter as well as a driver’s helmet fairing, a left GT-style mirror, a Halon fire suppression system, and a dual-grille engine cover with leather hold-down straps. The car was assembled in the 1990s, refreshed in 2009, and acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. This 550 Spyder replica is now offered with service records and a clean Ohio title listing it as a 1955 Porsche.

The fiberglass bodywork is mounted to a tubular steel frame and is finished in silver. Exterior details include a driver’s helmet fairing, gold-finished Porsche and Spyder badging, a GT-style mirror, mesh headlight grilles, Wendler fender badges, a Le Mans-style fuel filler, and a dual-grille engine cover with leather hold-down straps. Images detailing the condition of the exterior are presented in the gallery below.

Steel 15″ wide-five wheels are mounted with 195/50 front and 205/50 rear Yokohama tires. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes with aluminum drum covers. The tires were replaced, the brake fluid was changed, and the front caliper slides were removed and lubricated in June 2024.

The fixed-back bucket seats are trimmed red upholstery and are joined by color-coordinated carpeting and door panel inserts. Interior elements include a height-adjustable rearview mirror, a passenger grab handle, a Jamar Performance shifter, and a 550-style parking brake. A knob for the engine bay Halon fire-suppression system is mounted on the left side of the dashboard.

The wood-rimmed three-spoke steering wheel wears a Porsche crest horn button and frames a central tachometer flanked by a 200-km/h speedometer and a combination gauge, while readouts for boost pressure, oil pressure, oil temperature, and cylinder head temperature are mounted in a stack ahead of the shifter. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 22k kilometers (~14k miles).

The air-cooled 2,276cc flat-four was reportedly assembled by Competition Engineering of Phoenix, Arizona, and installed circa 2009. The engine utilizes an AutoLinea aluminum case and has been fitted with a Garrett turbocharger, an XS Power intercooler, a Turbosmart wastegate and dual-stage boost controller, a Snow Performance methanol injection kit, an external oil cooler, an extended capacity oil sump, dual Dell’Orto DRLA carburetors, and MSD ignition with boost retard. Service in June 2024 included changing the oil, adjusting the valves, cleaning the fuel filter and carburetors, and replacing the pushrod tubes and seals, fuel hoses, valve cover gaskets, spark plugs, and the distributor cap and rotor.

Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transaxle with a Quaife limited-slip differential and a hydraulically-actuated clutch slave cylinder. Urethane transaxle mounts were installed in June 2024.
The car is titled in Ohio as a 1955 Porsche using the California-assigned VIN CA590822, shown above.

This 1987 Buick Grand National was acquired by the current owner on BaT in October 2022 and it now shows 47k miles. The car is powered by a turbocharged 3.8-liter V6 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission and is finished in black over two-tone black and Sand Gray upholstery. Equipment includes a limited-slip differential, a Pypes Performance exhaust system, 15″ chrome wheels, a rear spoiler, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, air conditioning, cruise control, crank windows, and a Delco cassette stereo linked to a Concert Sound audio system. The turbocharger is said to have been rebuilt within the past year. This Grand National is offered on dealer consignment with a clean Florida title.

The car is finished in black (19) and features a sculpted hood, a rear window defogger, sport mirrors, a decklid spoiler, Buick-branded mudflaps, and dual exhaust outlets. The bumpers were painted and replacement fillers were installed under prior ownership.
Factory 15″ wheels with chrome and black accents and are mounted with 215/65 front and 255/60 rear BFGoodrich Radial T/A tires. Braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in black and Sand Gray cloth with Turbo 6 embroidery on the front seat headrests. Grand National-branded floor mats line the footwells, and amenities include air conditioning, cruise control, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, crank windows, a Concert Sound II audio system, and a Delco cassette stereo with a graphic equalizer.

A leather-wrapped steering wheel sits on a tilting column and fronts a horizontal 85-mph speedometer, a digital tachometer, and gauges for boost pressure and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 47k miles, approximately 200 of which were added under current ownership.
The turbocharged 3.8-liter V6 was factory rated at 245 horsepower and 355 lb-ft of torque, and the turbocharger is said to have been rebuilt in the past year.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a 10-bolt rear axle with a limited-slip differential. A Pypes Performance exhaust system has been fitted.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage, and a gap in entries is noted between 1995 and 2022.

This 1974 Ford Bronco was refurbished and modified during a project that was completed in 2022, and it is powered by a 5.0-liter Coyote V8 linked to a six-speed automatic transmission and a Dana 20 dual-range transfer case. The truck was fitted with custom roll pans and bolt-on wheel arch extensions before being refinished in Earl Grey over Tobacco upholstery during the refurbishment. Additional equipment includes 17″ Vision Motorsports wheels, an aluminum 9″ rear axle, a family roll cage, hydroboosted four-wheel disc brakes, body and suspension lifts, power-operated side steps, front bucket seats, Vintage Air climate control, Kicker speakers, and a JVC touchscreen head unit. The truck was previously listed on BaT in October 2023 and was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. This modified Bronco is now offered at no reserve with a clean Arizona title.

Fabricated roll pans and bolt-on wheel arch extensions were installed before the truck was refinished in Earl Grey paint during the refurbishment. Details include a white-finished family roll bar, LED headlights, chrome bumpers, and AMP Research power-operated side steps. Repairs were performed to the side steps under current ownership according to the selling dealer.

Beadlock-capable 17″ Vision Motorsports wheels are mounted with 35×12.50″ BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A KO2 tires that show 2022 production date codes. The truck is equipped with a Borgeson power steering unit as well as a 3″ body lift and a 2.5″ suspension lift with dual shocks at each corner. Braking is provided by a hydroboost system with four-wheel discs.

The cabin features front bucket seats and a rear bench trimmed in Tobacco upholstery that extends to the dashboard, center armrest, and door and side panels. Appointments include Vintage Air climate control, fabricated interior panels, twin transfer case shifters, Kicker speakers, and a touchscreen JVC head unit with Apple CarPlay connectivity.

A woodgrain steering wheel frames Dakota Digital instrumentation consisting of a 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and perimeter gauges for voltage, fuel level, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The digital odometer shows 220 miles. Total mileage is unknown.

The 5.0-liter Coyote V8 was installed during the refurbishment and is fitted with a body-color engine cover and intake piping. Additional equipment includes a Power by the Hour accessory drive, an aluminum radiator, and a PQY adjustable fuel pressure regulator. Repairs were performed to the wiring, air conditioning system, and fan controller in May 2024.

Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels via a 6R80 six-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range Dana 20 transfer case, and a 9″ rear axle with an aluminum housing. The exhaust system features 2.5″ piping and 3″ finishers.

This 1955 Chevrolet 210 two-door Handyman wagon was initially delivered to Washburn Chevrolet of Santa Barbara, California, and was built as a tribute to the current owner’s father, the former proprietor of the aforementioned dealership, which campaigned Corvette race cars driven by Bob Bondurant in the 1960s. Known as the Grey Snapper, the car was refinished in metallic gray during the build and the cabin was trimmed in tan and saddle leather and fitted with BMW-sourced front seats, a custom center console, a Hurst shifter, and AutoMeter instrumentation. Power is provided by a 5.7-liter LS6 V8 linked with a six-speed manual transmission, and further details include electric exhaust cut-outs, an aluminum radiator, rear air springs, four-wheel disc brakes, and 16″ Halibrand magnesium wheels. This modified Handyman wagon is offered on dealer consignment in Oregon with a Washington state title in the current owner’s name.

The exterior was repainted by Corby Auto Body of Santa Rosa, California, reportedly in the BMW shade of Sterling Grey, and the frame was powder-coated during the build. Details include a hood ornament, a horizontal-slat grille, hooded headlights, and chrome bumpers and bodyside trim.

Halibrand 16″ magnesium wheels wheels are mounted with 245/50 BFGoodrich g-Force Comp-2 tires that were installed in preparation for the sale. Air springs are fitted on the independent rear suspension, and braking is provided by four-wheel discs.

The power-operated front bucket seats are said to have been sourced from a BMW sedan, and the seating surfaces were reupholstered in saddle, tan, and brown leather by BK Upholstery of Cotati, California. Further details include bowtie dashboard trim, a Hurst shifter, an AM radio, a heater and defroster, and a center console with cupholders. The cargo area was upholstered to match the cabin.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel sits on a chrome tilting column ahead of AutoMeter instrumentation including 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and readouts for oil pressure, fuel level, and water temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 227 miles, and the total mileage is unknown.

The 5.7-liter LS6 V8 was installed in 2010 and is equipped with a conical air filter, an aluminum radiator, and red fuel rail covers along with electric exhaust cut-outs. Fluid services were performed in preparation for the sale. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential.
The current Washington state title is a duplicate and bears a Classic brand.

This 1964 Porsche 356C is a Karmann-built coupe that was built on October 9, 1963 and originally delivered to California. It was refurbished at Gallery Aaldering in the Netherlands and imported to the US after the current owner’s acquisition in 2023. The car is finished in silver over red leatherette and is powered by a 1.6-liter flat-four and four-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes a Blaupunkt multi-band radio, a Brantz digital tripmeter, VDO instrumentation, 15” wheels, and four-wheel disc brakes. The dual Dellorto carburetors were rebuilt within the last year, and the steering coupler, wheel bearing seals, shocks, and ignition components were replaced. This 356C is now offered on dealer consignment in Arizona with a copy of the Kardex, a tool roll, and a clean Florida title listing it as a 1963 model.

Finished from the factory in Slate Gray, the car was repainted silver during the aforementioned refurbishment. Exterior details include a windshield washer system, a twin-grille decklid, and dual exhaust outlets that exit through the rear overriders.

Silver-finished 15” steel wheels wear polished Porsche-crest hubcaps and are mounted with 165-series Vredestein Sprint Classic tires. Work performed in 2024 included replacing the steering coupler, wheel bearing seals, and Sachs shocks. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs.

The cabin has been retrimmed in red leatherette that extends to the seats, door panels, dashboard pad, and rear bulkhead. Black squareweave carpets line the floors, and a Blaupunkt multi-band radio is accompanied by an analog clock. Discoloration on the left rear jump seat upholstery can be viewed in the gallery along with pitting on the interior brightwork. A Brantz International 2 Pro digital tripmeter has been installed below the dash.

The three-spoke steering wheel fronts VDO green-letter instrumentation consisting of a central 6k-rpm tachometer flanked by a 200-km/h speedometer and a combination gauge for oil temperature and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 434 kilometers (~270 miles), and total mileage is unknown.

The air-cooled 1.6L flat-four is equipped with dual Dellorto carburetors that were rebuilt in 2024. The distributor cap, ignition coil, and battery were also replaced. Compression test results are presented in the gallery.
The engine number P☆711022☆ is shown above, and a corresponding number is listed on the Kardex.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transaxle, production numbers for which can be viewed in the gallery.
A copy of the Kardex report lists factory colors, equipment, identification numbers, and delivery to R.E. Cunningham & Son of Los Angeles, California.
A tool roll will accompany the car.

This 2005 Porsche 911 Carrera S coupe was initially registered in California where it spent much of its time prior to an East coast relocation, and it has 104k miles. It is finished in Black over black standard leather and is powered by a 3.8-liter flat-six paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes the Sport Chrono Package Plus, 19″ aftermarket wheels, a deployable rear spoiler, bi-xenon headlights, a sunroof, heated power-adjustable front seats, automatic climate control, cruise control, a Bose sound system, and Porsche Communication Management (PCM) with navigation. This 997.1 C2S coupe is now offered in Florida by the selling dealer at no reserve with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Delaware title.

The car is finished in Black (041) and features a power sunroof, a speed-activated rear spoiler, a rear window wiper, bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, rain-sensing windshield wipers, quad exhaust outlets. Windshield cowl trim was replaced in August 2021  Photos depicting paint-meter readings are provided in the gallery. There is a scuff in the front bumper cover at the mounting point of the license plate holder.

The 19″ aftermarket wheels are wrapped in Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires measuring 235/35 up front and 295/30 out back. Braking is handled by multi-piston Porsche-branded brake calipers fitted over cross-drilled and vented rotors at all four corners. The car is equipped with Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM) as well as Porsche Stability Management (PSM), an active brake differential (ABD), and Anti-Slip Regulation (ASR). The front struts were replaced in October 2021.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats trimmed in black Standard leather. Features include driver’s seat memory settings, a Bose sound system, a CD stereo with a remote disc changer, automatic climate control, cruise control, and Porsche Communication Management with navigation. A satellite radio receiver is installed at the bottom of the center stack.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a central tachometer and a 200-mph speedometer as well as gauges for oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The optional Sport Chrono Package Plus added a stopwatch atop the dashboard. The digital odometer indicates 104k miles.
The 3.8-liter M97 flat-six features dry-sump lubrication and was factory rated at 355 horsepower and 295 lb-ft of torque. The battery was replaced in May 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle. The clutch and the flywheel were replaced in October 2021.
Decoding the option sticker reveals the following information:
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 1969 Chevrolet Camaro coupe was modified under current ownership with a supercharged 6.2-liter LSA crate V8 linked with a four-speed automatic transmission and a Dutchman 9″ rear end with a Detroit TrueTrac differential. The body was disassembled and refinished in black during the build, and exterior details include a front and rear spoiler, a custom front grille, a vented cowl induction hood, black bumpers, and Ringbrothers mirrors and door handles. The car rides on a coilover suspension and a Speedtech torque arm kit as well as staggered-diameter U.S. Mags wheels mounted over Wilwood disc brakes. The cabin was fitted with TMI Products bucket seats trimmed in red leather and microsuede as well as a Vintage Air climate control unit, a Lokar shifter, a Holley digital instrument cluster, a full-length center console, and a digital media player connected to Focal audio components. This modified Camaro coupe is offered in Canada with build records and Alberta registration.

The body was disassembled before being fitted with replacement quarter panels and repainted in black during the build, and a custom front grille, headlight trim, and hood vents were fitted as well as replacement glass and LED lighting. Additional details include smoothed body-color bumpers, front and rear spoilers, driving lights, a Detroit Speed wiper mechanism, tinted side marker and taillight lenses, and Ringbrothers door handles and mirrors.

The car rides on Speedtech adjustable coilovers and tubular control arms as well as a four-link rear setup, and a Sweet Manufacturing steering rack was installed during the build. Black-finished 19×10″ front and 20×12″ rear U.S. Mags wheels are shod in Nitto NT555G2 tires measuring 235/35 up front and 305/30 out back. A Detroit Speed mini-tub kit was fitted to accommodate the wider rear tires. Braking is handled by black Wilwood calipers over slotted and drilled rotors, and an electric emergency brake system is installed.

The cabin was fitted with TMI Products front and rear bucket seats trimmed in red leather and microsuede and black grommets, and matching upholstery adorns the trunk, center consoles, doors, and Nova-style dashboard. Appointments include Vintage Air climate control, a rearview camera, a Lokar shifter and hood release, power windows, billet door handles, and a Velex digital media center linked with Focal speakers and amplifiers.

The TMI Products steering wheel frames a configurable Holley digital instrument cluster. The odometer shows 474 miles, which is said to represent the mileage added since the completion of the build. Total mileage is unknown.

The supercharged 6.2-liter LSA crate V8 was installed during the build and is equipped with a black anodized billet accessory drive system, an adjustable fuel pressure regulator, custom engine covers, and a Holley wiring harness. The hood opens on billet hinges to reveal a smoothed firewall and an oversized radiator support trim and inner fenders.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a 4L80E four-speed automatic transmission and a Dutchman 9″ rear end with a Detroit TrueTrac limited-slip differential and 31-spline axles. A Speedtech torque arm kit is installed along with a Rick’s fuel tank, a ZL1-specification fuel pump, and Detroit Speed subframe connectors. Stainless-steel headers flow to powder-coated and thermally wrapped 3″ piping, an X-pipe midsection, and chambered mufflers.
Photos taken during the build process are provided in the gallery.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its Alberta registration, which serves as the ownership document in Alberta, Canada.

This 1971 Volvo 1800E was acquired by the seller in December 2022, and subsequent work included a repaint in green as well as overboring and overhauling the 2.0-liter inline-four. Equipment includes a refurbished four-speed manual transmission with overdrive as well as 15″ alloy wheels, tan vinyl upholstery, a heater, and a push-button Motorola radio. Work performed in 2022 consisted of replacing the shock absorbers and assorted brake and fuel system components. This 1800E is now offered with a service manual, repair and refurbishment invoices, and a clean Virginia title in the seller’s name.

Dent repair was performed on the rear end following an incident at a stop sign in 2023, according to the seller, and the body was subsequently repainted in green. The door and trunk seals were replaced along with assorted chrome trim at that time. Exterior details include dual side mirrors, chrome-finished twin exhaust outlets, and chrome-plated bumpers and trim. The high-beam function for the headlights is inoperative, dings are visible in the chrome trim, and pitting and scratches are visible on the headlight rings and bumpers.

The 15″ “Clover” alloy wheels are wrapped in 205/60 Cooper CS3 Touring tires. Bilstein shock absorbers were installed at each corner in 2022, and additional work at that time included replacing the brake master cylinder, brake lines, and rear calipers, rotors, and pads.

The front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in tan vinyl upholstery and are complemented by color-coordinated interior panels. Additional appointments include three-point front seatbelts, woodgrain dashboard trim, a heater, a push-button Motorola radio, and a center console with storage. The front and rear seat support webbing has been replaced along with the front foam seat cushions, according to the seller. The dashboard clock, door locks, and courtesy light are inoperative, the air conditioning compressor has been removed, the driver’s door check is weak, and tears in the left seat base, door panels upholstery, and dash pad are shown in the gallery below.

The three-spoke steering wheel features an aftermarket cover and fronts a Smiths tachometer, a 120-mph speedometer, and supplementary gauges. The six-digit odometer indicates 40k miles, approximately 500 of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 2.0-liter inline-four was overbored and overhauled in 2023, with work including a valve job and installing oversized pistons and a replacement camshaft, timing gear, lifters, bearings, hoses, and assorted gaskets and seals. A used fuel pressure regulator was installed and the oil pressure line, fuel pump, filter, and lines were replaced in 2022. The seller states that the valve cover gasket was replaced along with the fuel level sending unit in preparation for the sale.

Power is sent to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transmission with an electrically actuated overdrive unit. The transmission was refurbished in 2022, and the overdrive switch was replaced at that time. There is a gear oil leak from the speedometer angle drive.
Photos showing the car during various stages of the body repairs and repaint can be seen in the gallery below.

This 1994 Chevrolet Corvette convertible has 49k miles, and it is powered by a 5.7-liter LT1 V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission. It is finished in Black over black leather, and equipment includes 18″ C7-style chrome wheels, a limited-slip differential, an aftermarket exhaust system, a black convertible soft top, fog lights, power-adjustable sport seats, a Delco Bose sound system, a CD stereo, and automatic climate control. The front brakes were serviced, and the brake master cylinder and tie rod ends were replaced in June 2024. This C4 convertible is now offered by the selling dealer with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Illinois title.

The car is finished in Black and features a black convertible soft top, pop-up headlights, integrated fog lights, a Corvette-branded front plate cover, quad tail lights, and quad polished exhaust outlets. The glass is separating from the soft top, and detailed photos of the exterior are provided in the gallery.

Chrome-finished 18″ C7-style wheels are mounted with 315/30 Falken Azenis tires. The car is equipped with traction control, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel ventilated discs with ABS. The tie rod ends, brake master cylinder, brake fluid as well as the front rotors, calipers, pads, and hoses were replaced in June 2024.

The cabin features power-adjustable sport bucket seats trimmed in black leather along with matching door panel inserts and carpets. Amenities include a Delco Bose sound system, a CD stereo, automatic climate control, an onboard computer, and cruise control.

The two-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a central digital speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, and battery voltage. The digital odometer indicates 49k miles.

The 5.7-liter LT1 V8 features sequential-port fuel injection and was factory rated at 300 horsepower and 340 lb-ft of torque. The water pump and serpentine belt were replaced in June 2019, and an oil change was performed in June 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a limited-slip differential. An aftermarket exhaust system was installed in June 2022.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Boyd Chevrolet in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma, along with factory colors, standard equipment, options, and a total vehicle price of $45,644.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 1969 BMW R69US underwent a refurbishment in 2015-16 at Bench Mark Works in Sturgis, Mississippi, with work consisting of over-boring and rebuilding its 594cc opposed twin, resealing the four-speed transmission, and fitting an Earles fork, a 12-volt alternator, an LED taillight, and Oldtimers saddlebags. Finished in Granada Red, the bike received a replacement clutch, valves, valve covers, and pushrods and tubes as well as ignition components, front fender, fork ears, and more as detailed below. The bike is also equipped with 18″ alloy rims, a driveshaft, dual Bing carburetors, a black Pagusa saddle, a chrome handlebar, bar-end turn signals, headlight-mounted mirrors, and both center and side stands. The selling dealer acquired the bike in 2023, and work in December of that year included changing the fluids, lubricating the driveshaft, and replacing the tires. This R69US is now offered at no reserve in New York with a tool kit, a removed fork, service records, and a clean Illinois title.

The bike is finished in Granada Red with white pinstripes, and a pair of Oldtimers Enduro saddlebags were fitted after being painted to match. The Pagusa solo seat received a replacement frame, and the headlight ears, front fender, fork lock, and fuel cap were replaced. Additional bike features include headlight-mounted mirrors, black rubber tank grips, a frame-mounted air pump, an LED taillight, a center stand, and a replacement side stand.

Wire-spoke wheels with 18″ alloy rims and drum-brake hubs were mounted with Heidenau tires in December 2023. Suspension is provided by an Earles fork as well as a pair of shocks mounted to the swingarm on the left and the final-drive housing on the right. The front end was straightened during the 2015 refurbishment, and the wheel bearings and rear brake shoes were replaced.

The chrome handlebar carries bar-end turn signals and Magura grips, and it is secured aft of a chrome adjuster for the steering damper. Instrumentation ahead consists of a VDO 120-mph speedometer and a trio of indicator lights. The five-digit odometer shows 47k miles, approximately 30 of which were added under current ownership.

The 594cc opposed twin features a kick starter, dual Bing carburetors, and a chrome dual exhaust system. A rebuild in 2015 was carried out with a rebuilt crankshaft, over-bored cylinders, and 73.5mm pistons, with a resultant displacement of 619cc. The cylinder heads were also rebuilt, the oil slingers were cleaned, and a 12-volt alternator was fitted. The following components were replaced during the rebuild:
Work in December 2023 consisted of clearing the carburetor jets, lubricating the driveshaft, and changing the oils in the engine, gearbox, and final-drive housing.

Power is sent to the rear wheel through a four-speed transmission as well as a driveshaft enclosed within the right leg of the swingarm. The gearbox and final-drive assembly were rebuilt in 2015 with replacement bearings and seals, and the clutch was replaced at that time.
The headstock plate indicates that this bike is an R69US with serial number 664436, and the matching numbers stamped on the frame and the engine case can be viewed in the gallery.
A tool kit is included in the sale, as are refurbishment records.

This 1963 Chevrolet Corvette split-window coupe is powered by a 327ci L76 V8 linked with a Muncie M20 four-speed close-ratio manual transmission and a Positraction differential. The car is said to have been sold new in Florida before being brought to Canada in the 1970s and underwent a body-off refurbishment in 1988 that involved a repaint in Silver Blue. It features flip-up headlamps and quad tail lamps along with reproduction 15″ turbine-style knock-off wheels. Inside, the bucket seats are trimmed in black vinyl and accompanied by a Delco AM/FM radio, an analog clock, and a split-spoke steering wheel. Acquired by the current owner and returned to the US in 2014, this C2 split-window coupe is now offered in Round Rock, Texas, on dealer consignment with NCRS judging forms, partial service records, and a clean Texas title.

The fiberglass body left the factory finished in Silver Blue (912) and was removed from the frame and repainted as part of the aforementioned refurbishment completed in 1988. The fiberglass underbody panels were also refinished at that time. The car features flip-up headlamps, quad tail lamps, fender vents, chrome bumperettes, and dual exhaust tips that exit through the rear valance. The selling dealer notes that the paint was polished in 2023 and reports a chip on the right-rear quarter panel as well as blemishes on the left-front fender.

The reproduction 15″ turbine-style wheels were produced by Western Wheel Corporation and wear three-eared knock-off spinners. Maxxis MA-1 M+S tires measuring 215/70 are mounted at all four corners . The C2 was the first Corvette to offer fully independent suspension, with upper and lower control arms at the front and a three-link setup with a transverse leaf spring at the rear. Braking is handled by four-wheel drums, which were serviced in March 2023.
The cabin features two bucket seats upholstered in black vinyl as well as color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Amenities include a Delco AM/FM radio, an analog clock, a heater, and lap belts.

The split-spoke steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for amperage, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 75k miles, approximately 2k of which have been added under current ownership.
The 327ci L76 V8 was fitted from the factory with a single Carter four-barrel carburetor and a high-lift camshaft for a factory rating of 340 horsepower.

The engine stamping includes sequence 3120127, which matches the last six digits of the vehicle’s serial number. The RE suffix corresponds with a 340-horsepower, 327ci V8 for use with a manual transmission.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Muncie M20 four-speed close-ratio manual transmission and an optional Positraction differential. The frame is said to have been sandblasted and repainted black as part of the 1988 refurbishment, and the underside of the car was cleaned in 2024 in preparation for the sale.
