This 1971 Norton Commando 750 Roadster is a non-running project that spent time in long-term storage in Ohio before the seller’s acquisition in 2020 from the reported original owner. The bike is finished in black and is equipped with a 745cc air-cooled parallel twin, dual Amal carburetors, a dual exhaust system, a kick starter, a four-speed transmission, drum brakes, 19″ wire-spoke wheels, chrome fenders, street lighting, and a black vinyl two-up seat. This Commando is offered at no reserve with manufacturer’s literature, a tool kit, and a clean Ohio title in the seller’s name.

The fuel tank and side covers are finished in black, and features include chrome fenders, street lighting, dual mirrors, a black vinyl two-up seat, folding passenger foot pegs, and both center and side stands.

Chrome 19″ wire-spoke wheels are mounted with a Dunlop front and Bridgestone rear tire with cracks on the sidewalls. Suspension consists of a Roadholder telescopic fork as well as dual shocks mounted to the swingarm. Braking is handled by drums at both ends, with the front featuring a vented twin leading-shoe design.

Instrumentation consists of a 150-mph Smiths speedometer and a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline. The five-digit odometer shows 17k miles, approximately 1k of which were ridden under current ownership.

The Isolastic rubber-mounted 745cc air-cooled parallel twin was factory rated at 60 horsepower and is equipped with dual Amal carburetors, a kick starter, and a dual exhaust system. The bike does not currently run and corrosion is noted on the exhaust.
The number 145793 stamped on the engine case matches the number stamped on the headstock plate, a photo of which is provided in the gallery.
The bike features a right-side-shifted four-speed transmission and a drive chain with a chrome upper guard.

This 1991 Ford Ranger XLT 4×4 is a regular cab pickup finished in Cabernet Red over Scarlet Red cloth. The truck is powered by a 2.9-liter V6 linked with a five-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case, and features include 15″ five-spoke alloy wheels, power-assisted front disc brakes, a plastic bed floor, a cargo net, power steering, air conditioning, and a radio. This Ranger shows 65k miles and is now offered at no reserve with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Oregon title in the seller’s name.

The truck is finished in Cabernet Red (EH) and features side graphics, towing mirrors, and bright bumpers. The tailgate has been removed, and a net has been fitted in its place. A plastic bed floor has also been added.
The 15″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Ironman tires, and braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. The truck is equipped with power steering.
The bucket seats are upholstered in Scarlet Red cloth, and interior appointments include air conditioning and a radio.
Instrumentation consists of an 85-mph speedometer as well as auxiliary gauges for voltage, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 65k miles.
The truck is powered by a 2.9-liter V6, and fluids services are said to have been performed recently. Then air box has been removed.
Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Wilson Motors in Corvallis, Oregon, as well as factory colors, equipment, and a total price of $14,408.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or damage.

This 1974 BMW 2002 was modified under prior ownership with the installation of a 2.7-liter M20 inline-six paired with a five-speed manual transmission. The car was sold previously on BaT in June 2021 and acquired by the seller on BaT in October 2022. Finished in red over black and houndstooth upholstery, the car is equipped with a sunroof, European-style bumpers, 14″ Panasport wheels, Bilstein shocks and struts, Suspension Techniques sway bars, an Alpina steering wheel, Recaro front bucket seats, VDO auxiliary gauges, and triple Weber carburetors. This 2002 is now offered at no reserve with a clean Wisconsin title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in red and features European-style bumpers, chrome side mirrors, and pop-out rear quarter windows. Work performed under prior ownership reportedly included installing a replacement windshield, repairing the sunroof, removing the rear spoiler, refinishing the front valance and the decklid, and performing a paint correction. Additional bodywork is said to include modifying the rear valance by filling the factory exhaust cutout. The rear license plate light was replaced under current ownership.

Panasport 14″ wheels wear BMW roundel center caps and are mounted with 195/60 Falken Azenis RT615K+ tires. Modifications performed under prior ownership included installing BMW 2002tii-style struts, wheel bearings, and brakes up front, while larger brakes from an E21 320i were fitted in the rear. The suspension is equipped with Bilstein shocks and struts as well as Suspension Techniques sway bars and lowering springs.

The Recaro front bucket seats were trimmed in black cloth and houndstooth inserts under prior ownership, and additional work included refinishing the gauge cluster surround in black, installing a leather-wrapped center console, and replacing the headliner, trunk liner, and square-weave carpets. Equipment includes a heater, a black-vinyl rear bench, a BMW-branded shift knob, and manual-crank windows. A DTechnik air conditioning evaporator was installed behind the center console.

The leather-wrapped Alpina steering wheel fronts a 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and a combination gauge. Additional VDO readouts for coolant temperature, voltage, and oil pressure are located in the center console. The five-digit odometer shows 77k miles, approximately 300 of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The retrofitted 2.7-liter M20 inline-six was installed under prior ownership and is said to be equipped with a 325i-sourced 885 cylinder head. The engine breathes through triple 40mm side-draft Weber carburetors and a tubular exhaust header. A strut bar spans the engine bay, and a Perma-Tune ignition system, a 123Ignition electronic distributor, and replacement spark plug wires were added under prior ownership. An oil change was performed under current ownership.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission. An ANSA exhaust system is fitted. The underside and engine were dry-ice cleaned under prior ownership.

This 1979 Ford Ranchero GT was produced at Ford’s Lorain, Ohio facility, and is said to have remained registered with its original owner until it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. Now showing 28k miles, the truck is finished in blue over blue vinyl and is powered by a 302ci V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. Additional features include white GT body graphics, 14″ steel wheels, power steering, power-assisted front disc brakes, air conditioning, and a push-button AM/FM radio. This seventh-generation Ranchero is now offered at no reserve by the selling dealer with a clean Illinois title.
The truck is finished in blue with GT-specific graphics along the body sides and tailgate. Further details include chrome bumpers, a drop-down tailgate, and a remote-adjustable left-side mirror.

Steel 14″ wheels with polished covers are mounted with 215/70 Uniroyal Tigerpaw AWP II tires. The truck is equipped with power steering, and braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The bench seat is upholstered in blue vinyl and is joined by a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Appointments include air conditioning, a locking glove compartment, and a push-button AM/FM radio.

Instrumentation consists of an 85-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, an analog clock, and auxiliary readouts for monitoring amperage, fuel level, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The five-digit odometer shows 28k miles, approximately 50 of which have been added by the selling dealer.
The 302ci V8 is equipped with a two-barrel carburetor and was factory rated at 140 horsepower.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels via a three-speed automatic transmission.

This 2012 Aston Martin V12 Vantage is finished in Tungsten Silver over Obsidian Black leather with red stitching and is powered by a 5.9-liter V12 paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes carbon-fiber exterior trim, a limited-slip differential, xenon headlights, carbon-ceramic disc brakes, 19″ multi-spoke wheels, parking sensors, heated power-adjustable seats, a 700-watt premium sound system, and a rear-view camera. The car has spent time in New York, Connecticut, Massachusetts, and Texas and now has under 3,600 miles. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this V12 Vantage is now offered in Texas with the owner’s manual, Emotional Control Unit key fobs, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Massachusetts title.

The car is finished in Tungsten Silver and is equipped with a carbon-fiber front lip spoiler, rear bumper inlay, fender strakes, and hood vents as well as xenon headlights, swan-hinged doors, flush-mount door handles, power-folding side mirrors, front and rear parking sensors, and integrated dual exhaust outlets. The seller states that the nose is covered with clear paint protection film that was applied when the car was new.

The 19″ two-tone multi-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Pirelli P Zero Corsa tires. Braking is provided by red-finished Aston-Martin-branded calipers over carbon-ceramic two-piece rotors at all four corners. The car is also equipped with Emergency Brake Assist (EBA) and Dynamic Stability Control (DSC).

The cabin features heated power-adjustable seats upholstered in Obsidian Black leather with red stitching. Interior features include a 700-watt premium sound system, front-seat memory settings, navigation, a rear-view camera, a CD stereo, cruise control, and automatic climate control.

The three-spoke Alcantara-wrapped steering wheel frames a 220-mph speedometer and a reverse-sweep 8k-rpm tachometer as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates under 3,600 miles.

The 5.9-liter DOHC V12 was factory rated at 510 horsepower and 420 lb-ft of torque. Power is routed to the rear wheels via a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. The oil was most recently changed in May 2024.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1970 Porsche 911S was purchased by the owner in Germany in 2019 and restored there in the early 2020s. The restoration included repainting the car, reupholstering the interior, replacing the seals and weatherstripping, rebuilding the engine and gearbox, and overhauling the brakes, suspension, and electrical system. The car is finished in Bahia Red over black leatherette and powered by a 2.2-liter flat-six linked with a five-speed 901 manual transaxle. Equipment includes front and rear bumperettes, 15″ Fuchs alloy wheels, bolstered bucket seats, and a heater. This longhood 911S coupe is now offered on dealer consignment in Germany with German registration.

The restoration included refinishing the car in the factory Bahia Red and replacing the weatherstripping and seals. Features front and rear bumperettes, vent windows, and a driver-side mirror. The selling dealer has supplied a condition report that includes paint meter readings. Photos can be found in the gallery.

The 15″ Fuchs alloy wheels are mounted with 185/70 Fulda tires, and a matching spare is mounted in the front. The brakes and suspension were overhauled during the restoration and Koni dampers were installed.
The cabin has been reupholstered in black leatherette and the headliner was also replaced. Interior appointments include bolstered bucket seats, a locking glovebox, and a heater.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation consisting of a 250-km/h speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, an analog clock, and gauges for fuel level, oil level, oil temperature, and oil pressure. The five-digit odometer has been reset and shows approximately 250 kilometers. Total mileage is unknown.

The 2.2-liter flat-six is equipped with Bosch fuel injection and was factory rated at 180 horsepower and 147 lb-ft of torque. The engine was rebuilt during the restoration, and the dealer-provided condition report in the gallery also includes photos of the engine and transaxle stampings.
The five-speed 901 manual transaxle was also rebuilt.
A photo of the Porsche Certificate of Authenticity is provided in the gallery. It lists the original equipment, colors, and engine number.

This 1989 Dodge Dakota is one of approximately 1,500 built with Shelby modifications including a 5.2-liter V8, alloy wheels, and special interior and exterior trim. Finished in white over a burgundy and grey cloth interior, it also has a limited-slip differential, a sliding rear window, air conditioning, and a cassette stereo. The truck was acquired new by the seller, and it shows 12k miles. This Shelby Dakota is offered with a window sticker, manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Wisconsin title in the name of the seller’s trust.

The Shelby Dakota was offered for the 1989 model year only at a $4k premium over the base truck, and approximately 640 examples were finished in Bright White. Exterior revisions included a lower front air dam with fog lights, black bumpers and fender flares, a windshield visor, and a buttressed hoop over the bed, which has a ribbed plastic liner. The rear bumper has been refinished.
Hollow-spoke 15″ alloy wheels are mounted with 225/70 Goodyear Eagle GT+4 tires. Anti-lock braking was standard, with discs up front and drums at the rear.
The bench seat is trimmed in burgundy vinyl and velour with Shelby-pattern grey cloth inserts, and the cab has air conditioning, a cassette stereo, and a sliding rear window. The headliner is loose.

A racing-style steering wheel with a “CS” horn button frames a tachometer, a 125-mph speedometer, and a six-digit odometer showing 12k miles. A dashboard-mounted plaque notes the truck as number 983 in its series.

The 5.2-liter V8 was sourced from the contemporary Dodge Ram and fitted with an electric fan in order to provide clearance in the engine bay. Factory output was quoted at 175 horsepower with 270 lb-ft of torque when new. A Shelby Automobiles plate with an engine number is mounted on the top of the radiator support.

The four-speed New Process automatic transmission features an overdrive gear, an auxiliary oil cooler, and a high-stall torque converter. It sends power to the rear wheels through a limited-slip differential with 3.90:1 gearing.
The window sticker lists factory colors, equipment, and a total price of $16,670.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2009 Maybach 62 features a rear cabin with an electro-transparent glass roof, reclining and massaging multi-contour heated seats, an intercom system, and a power-operated partition, doors, and curtains. Equipped with a twin-turbocharged 5.5-liter V12, it is finished in white over white leather, and it also has adjustable air suspension, 20″ wheels, adaptive xenon headlights, Distronic adaptive cruise control, and a 21-speaker Bose sound system. The car was sold new to a corporate fleet in Nevada, and it was registered as a commercial vehicle after it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2016. This Maybach 62 has 55k miles and is offered with an accident-free Carfax report and a clean New York title.
The Maybach 62 has a 151″ wheelbase and an overall length of 243″, and curb weight is 6,129 lbs.
The twelve-spoke 20″ wheels are mounted with a mixed set of 275/45 tires. The front brakes feature two calipers per rotor, and the air suspension offers adjustable damping and ride height.

The interior’s white upholstery and paneling are contrasted by a dark headliner, carpets, and piping. Burl walnut inlays, a 6.5″ COMAND infotainment screen, a 600-watt Bose sound system, and a heated steering wheel are additional elements.

The driver is aided by parking sensors, a rearview camera, adaptive cruise control, Keyless Go, a Bluetooth hands-free system, and a voice-control system. A warning light for the tire pressure monitoring system is lit in the instrument cluster. The odometer indicates 55k miles.

With 57.2″ of legroom beneath an electroluminescent roof, the rear cabin has reclining, massaging, multi-contour heated seats in addition to power-operated doors and curtains, a DVD entertainment system with 9.5″ screens and wireless headsets, and a retractable glass partition that was a $30k option from the factory.

Factory rated at 543 horsepower and 664 lb-ft of torque, the twin-turbocharged 5.5-liter V12 sends power to the rear wheels through a five-speed automatic transmission. An oil change was completed in preparation for the sale.
Additional photographs of the underside are shown in the gallery below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
There is currently a lien on the vehicle, and the lender will need to be paid off before the title can be transferred to the next owner.

This 1972 Datsun 240Z was refurbished under prior ownership and is powered by a 2.4-liter inline-six paired with a four-speed manual transmission. Finished in blue metallic over white vinyl, the car is further equipped with dual SU carburetors, 14″ steel wheels, power-assisted front disc brakes, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, a heater, and a Kenwood CD stereo. Work performed in 2023 involved cleaning and adjusting the carburetors, changing the oil, and replacing the fuel pump and ignition components. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this 240Z is now offered with partial service records, refurbishment documents, and a clean South Carolina title.

Finished from the factory in Blue Metallic (115), the car was repainted and the weatherstripping and window seals were replaced as part of the aforementioned refurbishment in 2018. Details include General Electric headlights, a left-side mirror, Z badging on the C-pillars, bright window trim, and a retractable antenna.

Steel 14″ wheels feature five-spoke Z-branded covers and are mounted with 195/70 Ironman Radial RB-12 tires. The car was factory equipped with an independent suspension, a front stabilizer bar, and rack-and-pinion steering. Stopping is provided by power-assisted front disc and rear drum brakes.

The bucket seats were reupholstered in white vinyl in January 2019, at which time the trim, dome light, carpets, seatbelts, door pulls, and shifter and emergency brake boots were also replaced. A Kenwood CD stereo and speakers have been fitted, and additional appointments include sound-deadening insulation,  a center console, a lockable glove compartment, an electric rear window defogger, and a heater.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline. An analog clock and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, amperage, and fuel level are housed over the center stack. The five-digit odometer shows 65k miles, approximately 100 of which have been added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 2.4-liter inline-six was factory equipped with dual side-draft carburetors and was rated at 151 horsepower and 146 lb-ft of torque. Work performed in November 2023 involved cleaning and adjusting the carburetors as well as changing the oil and replacing the spark plugs and wires, distributor cap and rotor, and fuel pump and filter.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission. Spray-on bedliner material was applied to the underside in March 2018.
Partial service records and refurbishment documents are included in the sale.

This 1991 Porsche 911 Carrera 2 Targa is finished in Grand Prix White over black leather upholstery, and it is powered by a 3.6-liter flat-six paired with a five-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. Showing 76k miles, the car is equipped with 16″ Design 90 wheels, a removable Targa roof panel, cruise control, a Blaupunkt cassette stereo, and air conditioning. It was purchased by the selling dealer in 2024, and work performed in preparation for the sale included servicing the fuel injectors and replacing the fuel pump, fuel filter, battery, drive belts, and tie rods. This 964 C2 Targa is offered with the manufacturer’s literature, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New York title.

The car is finished in Grand Prix White and features a removable Targa roof panel and a black satin-finish Targa bar as well as a speed-activated rear spoiler, integrated fog lights, and heated and power-adjustable side mirrors. The selling dealer notes that various panels have been refinished, and close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

Silver-finished 16″ Design 90 wheels are wrapped in Toyo Extensa HP tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs with ABS. The brake fluid was changed and the tie rods were replaced in 2024.

The power-adjustable front bucket seats are upholstered in black leather and are complemented by a color-coordinated dash, center console, and door panels. Amenities include a Blaupunkt cassette stereo, power windows, cruise control, and air conditioning.

The leather-wrapped four-spoke steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a central tachometer with a 6,800-rpm redline as well as a 180-mph speedometer, a Quarz analog clock, and gauges for oil level, oil pressure, oil temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 76k miles.

The air-cooled 3.6L M64 flat-six was factory-rated at 247 horsepower and 228 lb-ft of torque. Work performed in March 2024 included servicing the fuel injectors and replacing the fuel pump, fuel filter, battery, and drive belts.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential.

This 2008 Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor is said to have been used by the Saskatchewan Royal Canadian Mounted Police prior to 2022, and it was acquired by the selling dealer on BaT in June 2024. Police Interceptor models came with a 4.6-liter V8 and a four-speed automatic transmission as well as a 200-amp alternator, a stainless-steel dual exhaust system, heavy-duty shocks, and black-finished 17″ steel wheels. Repainted in silver, the car is further equipped with a push bar, air conditioning, an AM/FM stereo, a power-adjustable driver seat, patterned gray cloth front seat upholstery, and a black vinyl rear bench seat. This CVPI has 8k kilometers (5k miles) is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve in British Columbia, Canada, with spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and British Columbia registration.

The car features body-on-frame construction and left the factory finished in white. It was repainted Silver Birch Metallic under previous ownership, and exterior details include a front push bar, a black honeycomb grille, bright window trim, Police Interceptor trunk badging, and heated power-adjustable side mirrors with color-keyed caps.

Black-painted 17″ steel wheels with chrome hubcaps are mounted with 235/55 Goodyear Eagle RS-A tires. Anti-lock braking is provided by power-assisted four-wheel discs, and heavy-duty shocks came standard on Police Interceptor models along with front and rear stabilizer bars.

The front bucket seats are upholstered in patterned gray cloth, while the rear bench is trimmed in black vinyl. Heavy-duty rubber lines the floors, and amenities include air conditioning, a remote trunk release, a lockable center console, an AM/FM stereo, and a power-adjustable driver’s seat and pedals as well as power-operated windows and locks. The ashtray is missing from the lower area of the center stack.

The airbag steering wheel fronts certified instrumentation consisting of a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as a 220-km/h speedometer and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 8k kilometers (~5k miles).

The 4.6-liter SOHC V8 was factory-rated at 250 horsepower and 297 lb-ft of torque. Police Interceptor variants of the Crown Victoria came equipped with a 200-amp alternator, an oil cooler, and a stainless-steel dual exhaust system. An oil change and coolant flush were carried out in May 2023.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a column-shifted four-speed automatic transmission. The transmission and differential received fluid changes in May 2023.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.
The vehicle is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada. The sale does not include a title.

This 1997 Toyota Land Cruiser HZJ75 is a right-hand-drive crew cab example that was reportedly used by the Tokyo Fire Department in Japan before it was imported to the US and acquired by the selling dealer, and it now shows 6k miles. Powered by a 4.2L diesel inline-six mated to a five-speed manual transmission and dual-range transfer case, the truck is finished in green over gray vinyl upholstery. Additional details include a roof rack with an LED light bar as well as an ARB front bumper, a tubular rear bumper, a bed-mounted roll bar, LED driving lights, auxiliary communication equipment, air conditioning, and a touchscreen stereo head unit. Maintenance in preparation for the sale consisted of replacing the timing belt, drive belt, and valve cover gasket, according to the selling dealer. This HZJ75 is now offered with a clean Georgia title.

The high-roof body is finished in green with yellow “Toyota” lettering on the tailgate, and features consist of a roof rack with an LED light bar as well as side window rain deflectors, fender-mounted mirrors, an ARB front bumper, a tubular rear bumper, a bed-mounted roll bar, a rubber bed mat, LED driving lights, mud flaps, and running boards.

Bridgestone Desert Dueller white-letter tires are mounted on black-finished alloy wheels. Braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. The brake fluid was flushed in preparation for the sale, according to the selling dealer.

The right-hand drive cabin features front bucket seats and a rear bench trimmed in gray vinyl along with a color-coordinated dashboard and door panels. Appointments consist of black rubberized floor coverings, auxiliary communication equipment, air conditioning, and a touchscreen stereo head unit.

A two-spoke steering wheel fronts a 170-km/h speedometer, a tachometer with a 4,500-rpm redline, and supplementary gauges for oil temperature, battery voltage, fuel level, and coolant temperature. The six-digit mechanical odometer shows 6k kilometers (~3,800 miles), approximately 250 kilometers of which were added under current ownership.

The 4.2-liter SOHC 1HZ diesel inline-six features indirect fuel injection and was factory rated at 129 horsepower and 210 lb-ft of torque. Oil and coolant changes were performed in 2024, and the selling dealer states that the timing belt, auxiliary drive belt, and valve cover gasket were replaced at that time.
Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case.

This 2019 Ford Mustang Shelby GT-S coupe is one of a limited number of units modified by Shelby American in Nevada for sale to Pullach, Germany-based rental car company Sixt, and this example served as a rental car in Florida for approximately one year. The car later spent time in Illinois and Washington before the seller’s December 2023 acquisition, and it now indicates 14k miles. Finished in black with orange stripes over black and orange leather, the car is powered by a supercharged 5.0-liter Coyote V8 mated to a ten-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes the GT Performance Package, revised engine management software, MagneRide suspension dampers, Brembo front brake calipers, staggered-width 20″ Shelby wheels, dual-zone automatic climate control, adaptive cruise control, heated and ventilated front bucket seats, SYNC 3 infotainment with navigation, and a Bang & Olufsen stereo in addition to an aftermarket supercharger pulley, drive belt, thermostat, fuel pump, fuel injectors, and spark plugs. This Shelby GT-S is offered with spare and removed parts, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean Washington title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in black with orange stripes, Sixt Supercharged front fender badges, and body-side Shelby GT-S-branded graphics. Exterior details include a decklid spoiler, a front splitter, aerodynamic side skirts, and quad exhaust outlets with polished finishers. Noted blemishes include swirls in the finish along with scratches on the driver-door window.

Staggered-width 20″ Shelby wheels are finished in black and mounted with 275/35 and 305/30 Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires. The fully independent suspension is equipped with MagneRide adaptive dampers. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes, which feature red-finished Brembo calipers at the front corners.

The seating surfaces are trimmed in black leather with orange accents, and embroidered Shelby script accents the backrests of the heated, ventilated, and power-adjustable front bucket seats. Further appointments include dual-zone automatic climate control, adaptive cruise control, a 12-speaker Bang & Olufsen stereo, and a SYNC 3 infotainment system with navigation, Android Auto, and Apple CarPlay.
A plaque affixed to the dashboard identifies this GT-S as #7 produced for the model year.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a configurable digital instrument cluster with a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and readouts for coolant temperature and fuel level. Additional analog gauges measuring oil pressure and boost pressure are mounted in the center of the dashboard. The digital odometer indicates 14k miles, approximately 1,500 of which have been added by the seller.

The 5.0-liter Coyote V8 was fitted with an Eaton TVS R2650 supercharger as part of the Shelby GT-S package, and it drives the rear wheels through a 10-speed automatic transmission and a 3.55:1 limited-slip differential. Further modifications reportedly include an aftermarket supercharger pulley, drive belt, thermostat, fuel pump, fuel injectors, and spark plugs as well as dynamometer-tuned engine management software. The seller states that the oil and the battery were changed in December 2023.
Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery below.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage, displays rental history from May 2019 to August 2020, and lists history in California, Florida, Illinois, and Washington.

This 1970 Oldsmobile Vista Cruiser wagon underwent a refurbishment in 2015 and was acquired by the selling dealer in 2023. It is powered by a 455ci Rocket V8 linked to a three-speed automatic transmission, and it is finished in green over gray and black vinyl upholstery. Features include Aldan American coilovers, Hedman headers, roof rails, tinted windows, a dual-action tailgate, Super Stock II wheels, third-row seats, power-adjustable front bucket seats, an aftermarket stereo, and air conditioning. This Vista Cruiser is now offered by the selling dealer with an owner’s manual, a spare dashboard and air cleaner, and a clean Arizona title in the selling dealer’s name.

The car was finished from the factory in Sherwood Green (48) and was resprayed during the previously noted refurbishment. Exterior equipment includes quad headlights, chrome bumpers, dual side mirrors, white accent stripes, tinted windows, roof rails, “Vista-Roof” raised skylights over the second row of seating and cargo area, and a dual-action tailgate with a power-operated window. Rust repair was performed under current ownership and the paint in those areas was resprayed and blended. Bubbling paint is seen behind the left-rear tire and the roof panels are delaminating.

The 15″ Super Stock II wheels are mounted with Hankook Kinergy ST tires. Aldan American adjustable coilovers have been fitted along with stainless-steel brake lines. The car is also equipped with power steering, and stopping power is provided by power-assisted front disc and rear drum brakes.

The seating surfaces are upholstered in vinyl, and the power-adjustable front bucket seats are said to have been sourced from a later-model Chrysler product. Interior appointments include third-row seats, an aftermarket Kenwood stereo, aftermarket speakers, power windows, and air conditioning. Interior components that were originally green have been dyed black. The left-turn signal and the high beams are not functioning, cracks are seen in the driver door panel and dashboard, and the driver sun visor upholstery is separating.

The steering wheel wears an aftermarket wrap and fronts a 120-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and a fuel-level gauge. Auxiliary gauges have been mounted to the center dash. The five-digit odometer shows 45k miles, approximately 1,500 of which were added under current ownership. The fuel-level gauge does not work.
The car is powered by a 455ci Rocket V8, which the seller notes was refreshed during the 2015 refurbishment. Modifications include an aftermarket chrome air cleaner and Hedman tubular headers.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a three-speed Turbo-Hydramatic automatic transmission. Holes in the rear floor pan are shown up close in photos below.
Decoding the data plate reveals the following production information:
The Arizona title carries an “Exceeds Mechanical Limits” odometer notation.

This 2006 Chrysler Crossfire Limited convertible was first delivered to Steve White Motors in Hickory, North Carolina, and it has 19k miles following registration history in  New York and Florida. Finished in Alabaster White over Dark Slate Gray and Medium Slate Gray Nappa leather, the car is powered by a 3.2-liter V6 paired with a six-speed manual transmission. Features include staggered-diameter seven-spoke alloy wheels, a speed-activated rear spoiler, heated power-adjustable seats, a CD stereo, dual-zone climate control, and cruise control. This Crossfire is now offered in Pennsylvania by the selling dealer with a window sticker, owner’s manuals, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Florida title.

The Crossfire shared its platform with the Mercedes-Benz R170 SLK, and this example is finished in Alabaster White. Features include a black convertible top, a speed-activated rear spoiler, projector headlights, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, a straked hood, fender vents, and dual center exhaust outlets.

The 18″ and 19″ seven-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with GT Radial Champiro UHP1 tires. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes. The car is equipped with a touring suspension, electronic stability control, and traction control.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable seats trimmed in Dark Slate Gray and Medium Slate Gray Nappa leather, while silver-color trim accents the center stack. Amenities include a CD stereo, dual-zone climate control, and cruise control.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 19k miles.
The SOHC 3.2-liter M112 V6 was sourced from Mercedes-Benz and was rated at 215 horsepower and 229 lb-ft of torque. The selling dealer states that the battery was replaced in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transmission.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Steve White Motors in Hickory, North Carolina, along with factory equipment, colors, and a total price of $39,720.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.
listing_details: Dark Slate Gray & Medium Slate Gray Nappa Leather

description: This 2007 Mercedes-Benz SLK55 AMG was first delivered to Phil Long Autohaus in Colorado Springs, Colorado. It has 14k miles following registration history in the state, and it remained in the original owner’s care until earlier this year. Finished in Storm Red over beige Nappa leather, the car is powered by a 5.4-liter V8 paired with a seven-speed automatic transmission. Features include the Premium 2 Package, the Exterior Lighting Package, a retractable hardtop, 18″ polished AMG multi-spoke wheels, bi-xenon headlights, heated power-adjustable seats, an Airscarf neck-warming system, a Harman Kardon sound system, a six-disc CD changer, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This R171 SLK is now offered in Pennsylvania by the selling dealer with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Colorado title.

The SLK55 AMG features deeper valances when compared to the standard R171 in addition to rocker extensions, a rear spoiler, and four polished stainless-steel outlets. This example is finished in Storm Red (541) and is equipped with a color-matched folding hardtop as well as bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, dual roll hoops, and a heated rear window. Photos showing paint-meter readings are included in the gallery.

The 18″ polished AMG multi-spoke wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact tires. The car is equipped with an Electronic Stability Program (ESP) as well as a sport suspension with AMG-calibrated springs and shocks. Braking is handled by AMG-branded six-piston front and four-piston rear calipers fitted over slotted and cross-drilled rotors.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable seats trimmed in beige Nappa leather. Interior amenities include an Airscarf neck-warming system, a Harman Kardon sound system, a six-disc CD changer, an in-dash single-CD player, stainless-steel door sill trim, aluminum pedals, dual-zone automatic climate control, and COMAND infotainment.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer and an AMG-branded tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline alongside an analog clock and a fuel-level gauge. The digital odometer indicates 14k miles.
The 5.4-liter AMG-built SOHC 24-valve V8 was factory rated at 355 horsepower and 376 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Phil Long Autohaus in Colorado Springs, Colorado, along with factory equipment, colors, and a total retail price of $69,195.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.
listing_details: Harman Kardon Sound System w/Six-Disc CD Changer

description: This 1967 Chevrolet Camaro RS/SS coupe was acquired by the selling dealer in 2023 and subsequently underwent rebuilds of the engine and transmission as well as the addition of a custom dual exhaust system with 3″ stainless-steel piping. The 396ci L35 V8 was overbored and fitted with a Holley 700-CFM carburetor and roller rockers. Shifting is through a three-speed TH400 automatic transmission linked with a Positraction differential. The car is finished in Butternut Yellow and features an SS-style hood, concealed headlights, bumper guards, and front and rear spoilers. Inside, the front bucket seats and folding rear bench are trimmed in black vinyl and accompanied by a Bluetooth-capable stereo and a center console with auxiliary gauges. Further equipment includes power steering, power-assisted front disc brakes, and 14″ Rally wheels. Previously listed on BaT in July 2024, this Camaro coupe is now offered at no reserve by the selling dealer in Lindon, Utah, with a Washington State title.

The body is finished in Butternut Yellow with a black nose stripe, tail panel, and pinstripes. Further details include an SS-style hood with raised simulated air intakes as well as concealed headlights, bumper guards, and front and rear spoilers. A replacement windshield was installed, a black vinyl roof was added, and rocker panels were rechromed under current ownership.
The 14″ Rally wheels are mounted with 205/70 BFGoodrich Silvertown redline tires. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The front bucket seats and fold-down rear bench are upholstered in black vinyl, and the car is equipped with lap belts for four passengers. A Bluetooth-capable digital media receiver and aftermarket speakers have been added along with replacement door panels.

The three-spoke steering wheel features an SS-branded horn button and frames a 120-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 5,500-rpm redline. An inoperative clock and two combination gauges are installed within the center console. The five-digit odometer shows 31k miles, approximately 100 of which have been added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 396ci L35 V8 was bored 0.030″ over as part of a rebuild completed by South Valley Machine of Sandy, Utah, and was subsequently installed by Gordon Automotive of Orem, Utah, according to the selling dealer. The engine is fitted with a Holley 700-CFM four-barrel carburetor along with roller rockers. A replacement wiring harness has also been added.
The engine block stamping is shown above. Additional casting and stamping numbers from around the vehicle are shown in the gallery below.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a three-speed TH400 automatic transmission and a Positraction differential. The transmission is said to have been rebuilt in 2024. The exhaust system is comprised of factory exhaust manifolds flowing into 3″ stainless-steel piping with Magnaflow mufflers.
The chassis number is consistent with a 1967 Chevrolet Camaro coupe built at the Van Nuys, California, assembly facility with a V8 engine. Decoding the Fisher body tag reveals:
The Washington State title carries a Classic brand.

This 2005 Dodge Magnum R/T is finished in Mineral Gray Metallic with red hash marks over gray leather upholstery and powered by a 5.7-liter Hemi V8 paired with a five-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes Chrysler 300S 20″ wheels, red-finished brake calipers, a sunroof, dual-zone automatic climate control, power windows, heated and power-adjustable front seats, keyless entry, and a CD stereo with navigation. The car spent time in Oregon and Michigan before being acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. This Magnum R/T has 32k miles and is now offered with the manufacturer’s literature, a spare shift knob, and a clean Michigan title.
The car is finished in Mineral Gray Metallic (PDM) with red hash marks on the hood and front fenders. Details include fog lights, dual exhaust outlets, Hemi 345 badges, and body-colored bumpers.

The Chrysler 300S 20″ alloy wheels are wrapped in 245/45R20 Firestone Firehawk GT tires. The car is equipped with traction control as well as an Electronic Stability Program (ESP). Stopping power is provided by four-wheel anti-lock disc brakes with red-finished calipers.

The heated and power-adjustable front bucket seats are trimmed in gray leather upholstery and are joined by a two-tone dashboard and door panels. Amenities include dual-zone automatic climate control, keyless entry, cruise control, and a CD stereo with navigation.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 32k miles.
The 5.7-liter OHV Hemi V8 features a Multiple-Displacement System and was factory-rated at 340 horsepower with 390 lb-ft of torque. A Chrysler engine cover has been fitted.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a five-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 1955 BMW R25/3 is said to have been imported to the US during the 1970s and it was acquired by the seller in 1998. Refurbishment work performed at Boxerworks of Watkinsville, Georgia, in November 2022 included replacement of the wiring harness, speedometer, horn, throttle assembly, grips, hand levers, and foot peg rubbers, prior to which the exhaust assembly, center stand, luggage rack, tool box lock, and air tube boot were replaced by the seller. The bike is finished in black and is powered by a 247cc OHV four-stroke single paired with a four-speed transmission. Additional equipment includes an exposed driveshaft, a Denfeld saddle, a hinged rear fender, a Bing carburetor, a leading-axle fork, plunger shocks, a steering damper, alloy rims, and drum brakes. This R25/3 is now offered at no reserve with reprints of owner’s and service manuals, a pillion cushion, service records, historical ownership records, and Georgia registration in the seller’s name.

The bike is finished in black and is presumed to have been repainted under previous ownership. Features include a three-gallon fuel tank with an integrated locking storage compartment and black rubber knee grips as well as a black rubber Denfeld solo saddle suspended on a chrome horizontal spring. Additional equipment includes valanced fenders, a luggage rack, and a center stand. A leak in the fuel tank was repaired under current ownership, the fuel tank was sealed under previous ownership, and the seller notes the presence of paint bubbles on the front fender.

Wire-spoke wheels with shouldered 18″ alloy rims are mounted with older Continental front and IRC Grand High Speed GS-11 rear tires. Suspension consists of a conventional leading-axle fork with sliders that were cleaned, straightened, polished, and fitted with replacement seals during the refurbishment. A pair of shrouded plunger shocks are fitted at the rear. Braking is handled by 160mm drums at both ends.

A chrome handlebar equipped with a replacement throttle assembly, hand levers, and grips is clamped by rear-offset risers ahead of the key-handle adjustment knob for a friction-plate damper in the steering stem. Instrumentation consisting of a replacement 140-km/h VDO speedometer with shift points indicated in blue is inset atop the headlight bucket. The five-digit odometer shows 15 kilometers. True mileage is unknown.

The 247cc OHV single was factory rated at 13 horsepower and features a 24mm Bing carburetor, a kick starter, and a replacement exhaust system with a polished slip-on torpedo-style muffler. Additional items replaced during the refurbishment included the air tube boot, intake gaskets, wiring harness, and battery.

Power is sent to the rear wheel through a single-plate dry clutch, a four-speed transmission, and an exposed driveshaft. The engine, transmission, and final drive oils were changed during the refurbishment.
The number 326313 stamped on the frame matches the numbers stamped on the steering head plate and the engine case, photos of which can be viewed in the gallery.
The bike does not have a title, as it is registered in a state that does not issue titles for vehicles of its age. It is being sold on its Georgia registration document.

This Factory Five Racing Mk4 Roadster is finished in white over black vinyl and is powered by a BluePrint Engines 427ci V8 linked with a five-speed manual transmission and an 8.8″ rear axle with a limited-slip differential. Equipment includes a tonneau cover, single roll hoop, a hood scoop, side-exit exhaust pipes, racing harnesses, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, 17″ Halibrand-style wheels, and disc brakes. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this Mk4 Roadster is now offered in New York with a Manufacturer’s Statement of Origin, a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a tonneau cover, spare parts, and a Rhode Island title describing the vehicle as a 2021 RSP 65 Roadster Custom Kit.

The fiberglass bodywork is finished in white with blue stripes, and exterior equipment includes a tonneau cover, single roll hoop, a hood scoop, a windshield frame-mounted side mirror, bumperettes, a LeMans-style fuel filler cap, and side-exit exhaust pipes.

The 17″ Halibrand-style wheels are mounted with Mickey Thompson Street Comp tires with FFR 427 white tire stickers. The car is equipped with power steering and adjustable coilovers at each corner, and braking is handled by Wilwood calipers over drilled and slotted rotors.

The low-back bucket seats are upholstered in black vinyl joined by matching door panels with map pockets. A carbon fiber dash fascia is fitted and interior appointments include Simpson racing harnesses, a lockable glovebox, a dash-mounted rearview mirror, a Wilwood pedal box, and a cabin heater. The FFR President’s and builder’s signatures adorn the glovebox.
A plaque on the dash and firewall states that this car is production #10,000.
The wood-rimmed steering wheel fronts a 180-mph speedometer and an 8k-rpm tachometer as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer shows 9k miles.

The BluePrint Engines 427ci V8 is fitted with a Holley Sniper EFI system, Edelbrock Victor Jr intake manifold, MSD ignition components, long-tube exhaust headers, polished pulleys, and a finned Cobra-branded air cleaner assembly and valve covers.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission, a McLeod clutch, and an 8.8″ rear axle with a Ford Racing differential cover.
A tonneau cover, ignition wires, side pipes, and build records accompany the vehicle.

The car is titled in Rhode Island as an RSP 65 Roadster reconstructed kit using the Rhode Island-assigned VIN of RI02135, shown above. An image of the Factory Five Racing data plate is viewable in the gallery.

This 2005 Harley-Davidson Softail Springer Classic is said to have remained with its original owner before the seller acquired it out of South Dakota in 2024. It now indicates 445 miles and is finished in black with red and chrome accents. Power comes from a fuel-injected 88ci Twin Cam V-twin mated to a five-speed transmission, and equipment includes a clear windscreen, leather saddlebags, a black solo seat, and a matching passenger pillion with a backrest as well as a springer fork, front and rear disc brakes, 16″ wire-spoke wheels, and a chrome-finished dual exhaust system with fishtail-style exits. This FLSTSCI is now offered at no reserve with a clean California title in the seller’s name.

The bodywork is finished in black with a red panel accenting the five-gallon fuel tank. Equipment includes a clear windscreen, a front storage pouch, a black solo saddle, and a matching passenger pillion with a backrest as well as chrome headlight buckets, black leather saddlebags, a chrome rear luggage rack, rider footboards, folding passenger foot pegs, and a side stand.

Chrome-finished 16″ wire-spoke wheels are mounted with Dunlop Harley-Davidson D402 tires that have production-date codes from 2004. Suspension consists of a springer fork with a chrome damper as well as a triangulated swingarm with dual shocks mounted under the frame. Braking is from single cross-drilled discs at each end.

The chrome tank-top console houses a 120-mph speedometer, and it is flanked by a fuel level gauge on the left and a chrome fuel filler cap on the right. The digital odometer indicates 445 miles, a handful of which were ridden by the seller.

The air-cooled 88ci OHV V-twin features Electronic Sequential Port Fuel Injection, an electronic ignition module, an electric starter, and a chrome-finished dual exhaust system with fishtail-style exits. The battery was replaced in July 2024.
Power is routed to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and a drive belt with a black guard.

This 1989 BMW 325i coupe was registered in California and Florida before it was acquired by the current owner in 2023, and it is powered by a 2.5-liter M20 inline-six paired with a five-speed manual transmission. BBS 15″ alloy wheels and Recaro front bucket seats have been installed, and additional modifications are said to include a limited-slip differential with a 2.93: final drive ratio as well as Bilstein dampers, H&R springs, aftermarket rear subframe and engine mounts, polyurethane transmission mounts, and a Condor differential stud kit. Finished in Alpine White, the car is equipped with fog lights, a front spoiler, black kidney grilles, a sunroof, a Pioneer CD stereo, and cruise control. This E30 coupe shows 190k miles and is now offered on dealer consignment with service records, a Carfax report, and a clean Florida title.

The car is finished in Alpine White and features aluminum trim, quad headlights, fog lights, a manually-adjustable sunroof, pop-out rear windows, and a power antenna. A Volvo-sourced front spoiler, black kidney grilles, BMW Motorsport door handles, and window tinting have been added. The Carfax report lists a rear-end collision with another vehicle in September 2018, and the report indicates that the vehicle was not damaged. The selling dealer notes that corrosion on the edges of the sunroof has been treated.

The 15″ BBS lightweight alloy wheels feature 42 Draft Designs spacers and are mounted with a combination of 205/50 Federal, Zeetex, and Dunlop tires. The suspension has been modified with Bilstein dampers and H&R springs. Braided stainless-steel brake lines have been added, and braking is handled by ventilated front and solid rear discs with ABS. The selling dealer states that the wheel bearings were recently replaced, and the brake master cylinder was reportedly replaced in 2023.

Recaro front buckets seats with black cloth upholstery and Recaro-script inserts have been installed, and further interior details include a beige cloth-trimmed rear bench, CD Pioneer stereo, a replacement shift knob, and cruise control. The air conditioning functions intermittently, and there are stains on the rear seat.

A worn three-spoke steering wheel frames a 150-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,250-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature, instant fuel economy, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 190k miles, approximately 600 of which were added under current ownership. There is a crack in the instrument cluster lens, and the Carfax report lists an odometer reading of 192,262 in a March 2024 entry.

The 2.5-liter M20B25 inline-six was factory rated at 168 horsepower and 164 lb-ft of torque. A Mishimoto aluminum radiator, an MSD Blaster SS ignition coil, an oil cooler, and engine mounts have been installed. Photos of service records are viewable in the image gallery below, and the selling dealer states that service in 2023 included replacing the timing belts, water pump, fan clutch, coolant temperature sensor, crankshaft position sensor, battery, fuel filter, belts, ignition wires, coolant hoses, vacuum lines, and exhaust manifold gaskets. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a retrofitted limited-slip differential with a 2.93:1 final drive ratio. Rebuilt rear axles have been installed along with AKG rear subframe mounts, a Condor differential stud kit, and Condor polyurethane transmission mounts, according to the selling dealer.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned accident.

This 2011 Rolls-Royce Phantom Extended Wheelbase is finished in white over beige leather upholstery and is powered by a 6.75-liter V12 paired with a six-speed automatic transmission. It is equipped with a Spirit of Ecstasy hood ornament, power-assisted rear-hinged coach doors, parking sensors, chrome-finished 21″ wheels, self-righting Rolls-Royce monogram center caps, and automatic load-leveling suspension. Other features include heated front and rear seats, burl wood interior trim, a rear-seat entertainment system, and a rotating infotainment screen with navigation. The car was acquired by the seller’s business in 2018 and has 27k miles. This Phantom EWB is offered by the selling dealer with an owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New York title.

The Phantom is distinguished by an aluminum space-frame chassis and body panels along with a Spirit of Ecstasy hood ornament and power-assisted rear-hinged coach doors. This Extended Wheelbase variant is finished in white and has parking sensors and a rearview camera.

Chrome-finished 21″ wheels feature self-righting Rolls-Royce monogram center caps and are mounted with a mixed set of Goodyear and Continental tires. The factory automatic load-leveling suspension is composed of air-sprung double wishbones up front, a multi-link setup in the rear, and computer-controlled dampers.

The cabin is trimmed in beige and black leather with burl wood accents, and it features heated and power-adjustable front seats, automatic climate control, cruise control, and a rotating dashboard panel that plays host to an analog clock and infotainment screen with navigation.

The extended second row has heated outboard seats, seatback entertainment screens, tray tables, vanity mirrors, and deep-pile carpets. Umbrellas stowed within the rear doors are accessible with the doors open.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a power reserve indicator, and auxiliary gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 27k miles, approximately 18k of which were added under current ownership.
The 6.75-liter, 48-valve aluminum V12 was factory rated at 453 horsepower and 531 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in May 2024.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels via a six-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
There is currently a lien out on the car, and the owner’s lender will need to be paid off before the title can be transferred to the next owner.

This 1992 Mercedes-Benz 600SEL was reportedly purchased new by the seller’s spouse, and ownership passed to the seller in September 2023. Now showing 113k miles, the car is finished in black over black leather upholstery. Power is provided by a 6.0-liter V12 paired with a four-speed automatic transmission, and equipment includes a sunroof, gray lower cladding, 16″ Alamak alloy wheels, an electric rear-window shade, dual-zone automatic climate control, heated multicontour front seats, power-adjustable rear seats, a cassette stereo, and a Bose sound system. This V140 600SEL is offered with a clean Carfax report and a clean Ohio title in the seller’s name.

Manufacturer’s literature, a Haynes service manual, a front fender, spare bodywork, and a rear stand will accompany the motorcycle.

Work performed as part of the refurbishment is said to have involved rebuilding the Keihin carburetor, installing a water pump shaft seal kit, and replacing the kick starter, air filter, reed valve, and spark plug.

Power is sent to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and a replacement drive chain, which rolls on replacement sprockets and has been fitted with an Acerbis chain guide and rollers. The seller states that the clutch and the shift lever were replaced under previous ownership.
