The car is finished in maroon with a white Landau partial roof cover, and white pinstriping accents the body. Further details include a receiver hitch, a hood ornament, chrome bumpers, sport mirrors, and front mudflaps.
Steel 14″ wheels wear wire-spoke covers and are mounted with 195/75 American Bronze white-stripe tires. Power steering and front disc brakes were standard equipment.

The seating surfaces are upholstered in burgundy cloth and joined by color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Faux woodgrain trim accents the dashboard, and amenities include a tilt steering column, cruise control, a rear window defogger, a CB radio, and air conditioning. A tape is jammed in the cassette player.

A two-spoke steering wheel frames a horizontal 85-mph speedometer and a fuel gauge. An intermittent service engine light is noted. The five-digit odometer shows 70k miles, nearly all of which were added under current ownership.
The 5.0-liter V8 was factory-equipped with a four-barrel carburetor and rated at 148 horsepower and 250 lb-ft of torque when new.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission. Corrosion is noted on the underbody.

The window sticker lists initial delivery to Merollis Oldsmobile of Lapeer, Michigan, along with factory equipment, options, and a total amount of $14,804. Initial sales paperwork, service records, and the owner’s manuals are also included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage. A gap in entries between 1987 and 2008 is noted.

This 2001 BMW 330Ci convertible remained under the care of a single owner in Connecticut and North Carolina prior to the selling dealer’s acquisition, and it has 60k miles. It is powered by a 3.0-liter M54 inline-six paired with a five-speed manual transmission and is finished in Steel Blue Metallic over beige leather. Equipment includes 17″ Style 79 wheels, a black convertible soft top, heated power-adjustable front sport seats, a BMW Business CD stereo, a Harman Kardon sound system, and automatic climate control. This E46 convertible is now offered in New York by the selling dealer at no reserve with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean North Carolina title.

The car is finished in Steel Blue Metallic and features a black convertible soft top as well as fog lights, power-adjustable side mirrors, and twin exhaust outlets. Detailed photos of the exterior are provided in the gallery.

The 17″ Style 79 wheels are mounted with Kumho Ecsta PA51 tires. The car is equipped with Dynamic Stability Control (DSC) and All Season Traction (AST), and braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front sport seats upholstered in beige leather, while wood veneer accents the dashboard, center console, and door pulls. Amenities include front-seat power lumbar support, driver-seat memory settings, a BMW Business CD stereo, a Harman Kardon sound system, automatic climate control, and cruise control.

The multi-function leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 155-mph speedometer, a tachometer with an inset fuel economy gauge, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 60k miles.
The 3.0-liter M54B30 inline-six was factory rated at 225 horsepower and 214 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 1965 Pontiac LeMans sport coupe remained under the ownership of one couple in California since 1966 until it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. The car has been refinished in metallic copper and is powered by a 326ci V8 linked with a two-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes a black vinyl roof, power steering, power-assisted brakes, and 14″ steel wheels in addition to a center console, cruise control, an AM radio, and air conditioning. This LeMans is now offered by the selling dealer with Pontiac Historic Services documentation, spare parts, and a clean California title.

The car was repainted in its current shade of metallic copper circa 2010 and is equipped with a black vinyl roof. Exterior details include stacked headlights, a driver-side mirror, and chrome bumpers, window surrounds, and trim.
Steel 14″ wheels are mounted with BFGoodrich Silvertown redline tires. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is provided by power-assisted drums at each corner.

The cabin houses front bucket seats and a rear bench upholstered in black vinyl along with a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpeting. Appointments include a center console, cruise control, an AM radio, glovebox storage, and air conditioning.

The steering wheel fronts a 120-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and auxiliary readouts. The selling dealer reports that the speedometer cable is noisy and that the speedometer needle jumps. The five-digit odometer shows 13k miles, a handful of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 326ci V8 was factory equipped with a two-barrel carburetor and was rated at 250 horsepower and 333 lb-ft of torque when new. Service in preparation for the sale involved replacing the battery and ignition components.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a two-speed automatic transmission.
Decoding the trim tag reveals the following information:
Records, documentation from PHS, spare parts, and a car cover are included in the sale.

This 2001 Chrysler Prowler is one of 1,281 Mulholland Edition examples produced for the model year, and it has 25k miles. Finished in Midnight Blue over Agate leather, the car is powered by a 3.5-liter V6 paired with a four-speed automatic transaxle. Modifications include scissor-door hinges, a rear spoiler, a receiver hitch, a mesh grille, an aftermarket grille surround, and LED forward lighting. Additional equipment includes staggered-diameter five-spoke wheels, a dark blue convertible soft top, air conditioning, cruise control, an Infinity sound system, an AM/FM/cassette stereo, and a six-disc CD changer. This Prowler is now offered by the selling dealer with the owner’s manual, spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Virginia title.

The car is finished in Midnight Blue and features split front and rear bumpers with integrated lights as well as cycle-style front fenders, dual exhaust outlets, and a dark blue manually operated convertible top that stows in the rear-hinged trunk. The car has been fitted with scissor-door hinges, and additional modifications include a rear spoiler, a receiver hitch, a mesh grille, an aftermarket grille surround, and LED forward lighting. The exhaust finisher baffle inserts have been removed. Close-up photos of a crack on the front-right fender as well as holes on the soft top are included in the gallery.

Chrome-finished five-spoke 17″ front and 20″ rear wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact tires, which show date codes from 2014. The suspension utilizes coilovers mounted inboard of the narrow front bodywork, and braking is from four-wheel ventilated discs.

The cockpit features bolstered bucket seats upholstered in Agate leather with embossed Prowler logos on the backrests along with color-matching door panels and carpets. The Autostick shifter allows manual gear selection of the automatic transaxle, and additional equipment includes air conditioning, cruise control, an Infinity sound system, an AM/FM/cassette stereo, and a six-disc CD changer.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames an AutoMeter tachometer while a body-color instrument panel in the center of the dashboard houses a 150-mph speedometer and gauges for voltage, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 25k miles.
The 3.5-liter V6 features an aluminum block and was factory rated at 253 horsepower and 255 lb-ft of torque. The water pump was replaced in September 2019.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a torque tube and a rear-mounted four-speed automatic transaxle. Underglow lights have reportedly been added.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.
listing_details: Infinity Sound System w/Six-Disc CD Changer

description: This 2000 Cadillac Escalade remained with one registered owner in Nevada prior to being acquired by the selling dealer in 2023, and it has 97k miles. The truck is powered by a 5.7-liter V8 mated with a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case, and it is finished in Silver Sand Metallic over Neutral Shale leather. Equipment includes a locking rear differential, 16″ six-spoke alloy wheels, front disc brakes, a receiver hitch, fog lights, roof rails, running boards, a Bose sound system, automatic climate control, cruise control, and heated front and rear seats. This GMT400 Escalade is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with a clean Nevada title.

The truck is finished in Silver Sand Metallic (11) and features a receiver hitch, projector-style fog lights, roof rails, a bug deflector, tinted rear glass, and running boards. Paint meter readings are presented in the gallery.
The 16″ six-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with 265/70 Milestar Patagonia A/T and Firestone Destination A/T tires, and braking is provided by anti-lock ventilated front discs and rear drums.

The heated power-adjustable front seats are upholstered in Neutral Shale leather, and amenities include a Bose sound system, a CD/cassette stereo, a rear-seat entertainment system, heated rear seats, automatic climate control, and cruise control.

Instrumentation consists of a 120-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for fuel level, voltage, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The six-digit odometer shows 97k miles, a few hundred of which were added under current ownership.
The 5.7-liter Vortec V8 was factory rated at 255 horsepower and 330 lb-ft of torque. Since the selling dealer’s purchase, the serpentine belt, tensioner, battery, and oil were replaced.
Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a locking rear differential.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 2003 Maserati Coupé has been registered in California from new, and it shows 18k miles. Finished in Blu Nettuno Metallizzato over Beige leather, the car is powered by a 4.2-liter V8 connected to a Cambiocorsa six-speed automated transaxle. Equipment includes fog lights, cruise control, power-adjustable front seats, a remote CD changer, and automatic climate control. This Coupé is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a California title.

The Maserati Coupé was designed by Giorgetto Giugiaro, and this example is finished in Blu Nettuno Metallizzato. Features include fog lights, mesh front and rear grilles,   and quad exhaust outlets. A dent is present on the rear-left quarter panel. Photos showing paint-meter readings are included in the gallery.

The 18″ seven-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Super Sport tires, which show date codes from 2016 and 2017. Braking is handled by black-finished calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated discs at each corner.

The 2+2 cabin features power-adjustable front seats trimmed in Beige leather. Amenities include rear bucket seats, driver-seat position memory, a remote CD changer, navigation, cruise control, and automatic climate control. Sticky buttons are noted by the selling dealer.

The steering wheel sits ahead of column-mounted shift paddles and fronts a 200-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 7,500-rpm redline, and auxiliary gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, battery voltage, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 18k miles.
The 90° 4.2-liter F136 DOHC V8 was jointly developed by Ferrari and Maserati and features dry-sump lubrication and a factory oil cooler for a rated output of 390 horsepower and 330 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed Cambiocorsa computer-controlled automated manual transaxle with column-mounted shift paddles.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.

This 2008 Mercedes-Benz ML63 AMG has 69k miles following registration history in Florida. It is powered by a 6.2-liter V8 that drives all four wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission and a 4MATIC all-wheel-drive system. It is finished in Black over black Exclusive leather, and features include a sunroof, bi-xenon headlights, Parktronic, 20″ AMG five-spoke wheels, heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats, heated rear seats, a rear-seat entertainment system, a Harman Kardon LOGIC7 sound system, and three-zone automatic climate control. This W164 ML63 AMG is now offered by the selling dealer with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Florida title.

The truck is finished in Black (040) and features bi-xenon headlights with Active Curve Illumination as well as headlight washers, fog lights, roof rails, a sunroof, Parktronic, heated power-adjustable side mirrors, running boards, a receiver hitch, a power liftgate, quad exhaust outlets, and AMG-styled lower bodywork.

The 20″ AMG five-spoke wheels are mounted with Continental SportContact 6 tires that show date codes from 2021. The truck is equipped with an Electronic Stability Program (ESP), a four-wheel Electronic Traction System (4-ETS), and an Airmatic air suspension with Adaptive Damping System (ADS II). Stopping power is provided by four-wheel discs with Emergency Brake Assist.

The cabin features seating surfaces upholstered in black Exclusive leather, while burl walnut wood trim adorns the center stack, console, and door panels. Additional appointments include heated and ventilated multi-contour front seats with position memory, heated rear seats, a rear-seat entertainment system, cruise control, Keyless Go, a Harman Kardon LOGIC7 sound system, three-zone automatic climate control, a rear-view camera, and COMAND infotainment with navigation.

The wood- and leather-rimmed steering wheel fronts a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer as well as an analog clock, a fuel-level gauge, and a digital information display. The digital odometer indicates 69k miles. The tire pressure warning light is illuminated.
The 6.2-liter V8 was factory rated at 503 horsepower and 465 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
Power is delivered to all four wheels through an AMG Speedshift seven-speed automatic transmission and a 4MATIC all-wheel-drive system.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 2009 BMW Z4 sDrive35i roadster is finished in Deep Sea Blue Metallic over Ivory White Nappa leather and is powered by a twin-turbocharged 3.0L inline-six paired with a seven-speed dual-clutch automatic transmission. The current owner purchased the car in 2013, and they have since added approximately 24k of the 40k indicated miles. Features include the Premium Package, a power-retractable hardtop, xenon headlights, 18″ Style 293 wheels, power-adjustable seats, and dual-zone automatic climate control. This E89 is now offered on dealer consignment with the owner’s manual and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Deep Sea Blue Metallic (A76) and is equipped with a color-matching power-retractable hardtop as well as adaptive xenon headlights and polished exhaust outlets. The Carfax report notes that the rear and left rear of the car sustained “minor damage” in July 2014, which the selling dealer attributes to the owner scraping the left-rear quarter panel while backing out of a garage. The quarter panel was repainted to address the damage.

The 18″ Style 293 multi-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Bridgestone DriveGuard tires said to have been installed in February 2020 at 35k miles. Stopping power is provided by ventilated disc brakes at each corner. Rear brake pad, rotor, and sensor replacement are noted on the Carfax report in April 2022.

The power-adjustable bucket seats have memory settings and are upholstered in Ivory White Nappa leather along with a matching lower dashboard, center console, and door panel inserts. Interior appointments include anthracite wood trim, a BMW Professional CD stereo, dual-zone automatic climate control, and cruise control.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel features shift paddles and frames a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline as well as gauges for oil temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 40k miles, approximately 24k of which were added under current ownership.

The twin-turbocharged 3.0-liter N54B30 inline-six was factory rated at 300 horsepower and 300 lb-ft of torque. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed dual-clutch automatic transmission. The oil was most recently changed in April 2022.
Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery below.
The Carfax report notes the aforementioned damage entry.

This 2020 Porsche Macan is a white-on-black example that is powered by a turbocharged 2.0-liter inline-four mated to a seven-speed dual-clutch automatic transmission and an all-wheel-drive system. Equipment includes 18″ five-spoke alloy wheels, LED headlights, a panoramic sunroof, a rear spoiler, and heated and power-adjustable front seats as well as dual-zone automatic climate control, a 10-speaker sound system, and a touchscreen infotainment system with Apple CarPlay capability. The car remained registered with one owner in California prior to the selling dealer’s 2024 acquisition and now has 53k miles. This Macan is now offered at no reserve with photos of an AutoCheck report, a Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The car is finished in white with black lower accents and features LED headlights, a panoramic sunroof, rear parking sensors, dual polished exhaust finishers, and a power-operated tailgate with a spoiler, heated glass, and wiper. The Carfax report contains a February 2023 entry that describes “minor damage” to the front of the car. Photos of an AutoCheck report that does not indicate past damage to the vehicle are viewable in the image gallery below.

The 18″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with a mixed set of 235/60 Landspider Citytraxx H/T and Continental ProContact tires. Braking is handled by ventilated discs at each corner, the front of which are paired with Porsche-branded four-piston calipers.

The heated and power-adjustable front seats as well as the rear bench are trimmed in black leather with Alcantara inserts. Amenities include dual-zone automatic climate control, a dash-mounted analog clock, Porsche Entry & Drive, Lane-Change Assist, a 10-speaker sound system, and a 10.9″ touchscreen infotainment system with Apple CarPlay capability.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel frames a central 8k-rpm tachometer flanked by a 175-mph speedometer and a configurable digital display. The digital odometer indicates 53k miles.
The turbocharged 2.0-liter inline-four was factory rated at 248 horsepower and 273 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was most recently carried out in May 2021, per the Carfax report.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a dual-clutch seven-speed PDK automatic transmission.
The Carfax report contains the aforementioned 2023 damage report as well as the details of an open manufacturer voluntary service action.

This 1970 Pontiac Firebird Formula 400 underwent a modification and refurbishment process that was completed in 2019 and involved the installation of a 6.2-liter GM LT4 supercharged V8, a Tremec six-speed manual transmission, and Detroit Speed suspension components in addition to TMI Products bucket seats trimmed in black vinyl, a roll bar, and Vintage Air climate control. Finished in green metallic, the car is also equipped with hood scoops, Boze 18″ alloy wheels, power rack-and-pinion steering, four-wheel disc brakes, power windows, and a retro-style digital stereo. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2022, this Firebird is now offered with a clean Florida title.

The body was refinished in its current shade of green under prior ownership, and details include a Ram Air-style hood, dual side mirrors, a chrome rear bumper, bright rocker panel trim, and tinted windows.

Boze 18″ alloy wheels wear Pontiac-logo center caps and are mounted with 275/35 front and 335/30 rear BFGoodrich g-Force Rival tires. Stopping power is from Baer disc brakes, cross-drilled and slotted rotors, and a Detroit Speed booster. Power-assisted rack-and-pinion steering is fitted, and the car rides on Detroit Speed suspension components including a Quadra Link rear setup, a  front subframe with tubular control arms, anti-sway bars, and coilovers at all four corners.

The cabin was retrimmed during the refurbishment and features TMI Products high-back front bucket seats and a rear bench upholstered in black vinyl with suede-style inserts. The dash pad and roll bar are trimmed in leather, and Lizard Skin ceramic insulation has been applied to the floors. Additional features include woodgrain dashboard trim, a Hurst T-handle shifter, Vintage Air climate control, power windows, front and rear audio speakers, and a retro-style digital stereo with satellite reception and Bluetooth connectivity.

The Formula-style steering wheel fronts a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 5k-rpm redline, and auxiliary gauges. The five-digit odometer shows 64k miles, approximately 1k of which were added by the selling dealer. Total mileage is unknown.

The 6.2-liter GM LT4 V8 crate engine was installed as part of the build and equipped with a 1.7-liter Eaton R1740 TVS supercharger. Additional modifications include a Killer Chiller heat exchanger, an aluminum radiator, a Holley oil pan, ceramic-coated exhaust headers, and a 3″ stainless-steel exhaust system. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a Tremec six-speed manual transmission and a 9″ rear axle assembly. Additional underside photos can be viewed in the gallery below.

This 1972 BMW 2002tii was initially delivered to Helmut’s Small Car Service of Bridgeport, Connecticut, and is said to have been kept in storage between the 1980s and 2008, when a refurbishment was carried out. It was then listed on BaT in November 2021 before subsequently being acquired by the seller. Power comes from a replacement 2.0-liter M10 inline-four mated to a four-speed manual transmission, and the car has been repainted Ceylon Metallic and modified with a PerTronix ignition system, Bilstein shocks, and Ireland Engineering springs and sway bars. Additional equipment includes 13″ steel wheels with chrome-finished covers as well as a cabin heater, a Blaupunkt AM/FM stereo, and front bucket seats that have been reupholstered in black vinyl. The Kugelfischer fuel-injection system was overhauled prior to the seller’s acquisition, and work under current ownership included replacing the fuel tank and engine mounts. This roundie tii is now offered with a window sticker, manufacturer’s literature, service manuals, service records dating to 1972, a car cover, and a clean California title in the seller’s name.

As part of the aforementioned refurbishment, the car was stripped before being repainted in Ceylon Metallic. The bumpers were re-chromed and the bumper impact strips and rocker panel trim pieces were replaced under previous ownership, while the fenders, rocker panels, and various front body panels are said to have been replaced in the 1980s. Additional exterior details include vent windows, dual side mirrors, round taillights, and a chrome exhaust finisher. The trim on the driver’s door is dented.

Silver-finished 13″ steel wheels with chrome-finished covers are mounted with 185/70 Kumho Solus TA11 tires that have production-date codes from 2021. A full-size spare resides in the trunk. Ireland Engineering springs and sway bars were installed under previous ownership along with Bilstein shocks and stainless-steel brake lines. Stopping power is provided by power-assisted front disc and rear drum brakes.

The front bucket seats were reupholstered in black vinyl in 2021, and matching upholstery extends to the rear bench and door panels. Replacement carpeting lines the floor and trunk area, and amenities include a Blaupunkt AM/FM stereo, a dash-mounted analog clock, a heater, and crank-operated windows. The heater box was overhauled under previous ownership. The rear portion of the chrome trim on the passenger door is missing.

The three-spoke steering wheel fronts VDO instrumentation that consists of a 120-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,400-rpm redline as well as gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 5,500 miles, approximately 2,500 of which were added by the seller. True mileage is unknown.

A replacement 2.0-liter M10 inline-four was installed during time with a previous owner. It is said to have been rebuilt prior to installation and features Kugelfischer mechanical fuel injection and a PerTronix ignition system. Work circa 2020 included adjusting the valves and replacing the fuel lift pump, injection pump, injectors, and lines along with the throttle body, water pump, radiator, and various coolant hoses. The engine mounts were replaced under current ownership.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transmission. The muffler was replaced in July 2021 and the fuel tank was replaced under current ownership.

The window sticker shows initial delivery to Helmut’s Small Car Service of Bridgeport, Connecticut, and lists factory equipment and options along with a total suggested price of $4,725.45. Manufacturer’s literature, service manuals, a BMW 2002-branded car cover, and floor mats will accompany the car. Service records dating to 1972 can be viewed in the gallery.

This 2023 Aston Martin Vantage F1 Edition Roadster is powered by a twin-turbocharged 4.0-liter V8 mated to an eight-speed automatic transaxle and finished in Aston Martin Racing Green with a black center stripe over Onyx Black Haircell leather and Phantom Grey Alcantara upholstery. Unique aerodynamic bodywork, 21″ wheels, and a revised Skyhook Adaptive Damping system headline the list of features, which also includes a black soft top, a 360-degree camera system, LED lighting, dual-zone automatic climate control, and an 8″ touchscreen navigation system as well as heated and power-adjustable carbon-fiber sport seats, Satin Twill carbon-fiber interior trim, and a torque-vectoring electronic rear differential. The car was acquired new by the seller and was previously offered on BaT in May 2024. This Vantage F1 Edition Roadster has 70 miles and is offered in Michigan with a clean Carfax report and a clean Montana title in the name of the seller’s LLC.

Created in conjunction with Aston Martin’s 2021 return to Formula One racing, the F1 Edition features a full-width front splitter, front dive planes, and underbody turning vanes. This example is finished in Aston Martin Racing Green with a matte black center stripe and a black soft top. Additioanl exterior details include LED lighting, carbon-fiber fender and hood vents, keyless entry, heated and power-folding mirrors with carbon-fiber caps, and a 360-degree camera system with front and rear parking sensors.

Pirelli P Zero tires sized 255/35 up front and 295/30 out back are wrapped around satin black 21″ wheels that were unique to the F1 Edition, which also specified re-tuned dampers and an increased rear spring rate for the car’s Skyhook Adaptive Damping System. Stopping power is provided by lime green Aston Martin-branded six- and four-piston calipers over slotted rotors at all four corners.

The cabin is trimmed in Onyx Black Haircell leather and Phantom Grey Alcantara upholstery with Satin Twill carbon-fiber trim. Appointments include power-adjustable carbon-fiber sport seats with position memory along with a touchpad gear selector, dual-zone automatic climate control, an 8″ touchscreen navigation system, an Aston Martin Premium sound system, selectable driving modes, and F1 Edition-branded door sill plates.

The Alcantara- and leather-wrapped steering wheel is equipped with paddle shifters and frames a 12″ digital instrument cluster, which has a central tachometer flanked by configurable displays. The odometer indicates 70 miles.
The twin-turbocharged Mercedes-AMG M177 4.0-liter V8 was factory rated at 527 horsepower and 505 lb-ft of torque in F1 Edition configuration, an increase of 24 horsepower over the standard Vantage.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a carbon-fiber propeller shaft, a Touchtronic eight-speed automatic gearbox, and an electronic rear differential with Dynamic Torque Vectoring.
A copy of the window sticker lists factory colors, equipment, and a Total Suggested Retail of $208,486.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1956 Jaguar XK140 MC fixed head coupe is a right-hand-drive example that was reportedly sold new in South Africa and brought to Canada after being acquired by the seller’s family in 1979. It is equipped with a 3.4-liter inline-six paired with a four-speed manual transmission and is finished in green over beige leather upholstery. Equipment includes a C-Type cylinder head, dual SU carburetors, four-wheel drum brakes, 16″ wire-spoke wheels, and chrome bumpers with overriders. The car is no longer in running condition and requires servicing. This XK140 is now offered at no reserve by the seller on behalf of their spouse in Ontario with Manitoba registration.

The car is finished in green and features chrome bumpers and overriders, driving lights, side air intake vents, a split windshield, a locking fuel filler door, and dual exhaust outlets. The paint is faded and worn and pitting is present in the chrome.

Silver-finished 16″ wire-spoke wheels are secured with two-eared knockoff spinners and are mounted with older Dunlop tires that should be replaced due to age. A matching spare is stowed beneath the trunk floor. Braking is handled by four-wheel drums. The seller states that the front and rear brakes require service.

The right-hand-drive cabin features individual front seats and rear seat pads upholstered in beige leather complemented by color-coordinated door panels and brown carpets. Burl wood trim accents the dashboard and door panels and additional amenities include a dash-mounted rearview mirror, a locking glovebox, twin ashtrays, and crank windows. Aftermarket speakers are installed on the rear bulkhead.

The four-spoke steering wheel features a Jaguar horn button and fronts Smiths instrumentation consisting of a 140-mph speedometer and a reverse-sweep 6k-rpm tachometer with an inset analog clock as well as auxiliary gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, amperage, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 65k miles.

The 3.4-liter inline-six was factory rated at 210 horsepower and features a C-Type cylinder head, dual SU carburetors, and a. 6-volt electrical system. The engine cranks but no longer starts. The seller states that the fuel tank requires replacement. A photo of the cylinder head stamping is viewable in the gallery.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold in Ontario on its Manitoba registration, which serves as the ownership document in Manitoba, Canada. The majority of the photos were taken in 2023.

attributes.value: XK140 MC Fixed Head Coupe Project

description: This 1997 BMW 320i Touring was sold new from B&K BMW in Herford, Germany, and was imported to the US in 2022 before it was acquired by the selling dealer later that year. Now with 94k kilometers (~58k miles), the car is finished in Cosmos Black Metallic over black leather and cloth and is powered by a 2.0-liter inline-six paired with a five-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes the M Sport package, 17″ M Contour wheels, a sunroof, roof rails, and fog lights in addition to front sport seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, power front windows, and an aftermarket head unit. Work performed since 2023 reportedly involved replacing the exterior door handle seals, door panel inserts, and steering rack. This E36 Touring is now offered at no reserve by the selling dealer with manufacturer’s literature, partial service records, spare parts, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Georgia title.

The car is finished in Cosmos Schwarz Metallic (303) and features the M Sport Package aero kit, roof rails, a sunroof, fog lights, clear side marker lights, and a rear window wiper. The door handle seals were reportedly replaced in May 2024, at which time a paint correction was performed.

Silver 17″ M Contour wheels are mounted with 225/45 Toyo Proxes tires showing 2022 date codes. A sport suspension was equipped as part of the Sport package, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes with cross-drilled rotors at the rear. The steering rack was replaced in September 2023.

The front sport seats and a rear bench seat are upholstered in black leather with patterned cloth inserts and joined by a color-coordinated dashboard, center console, and door panels. Amenities include dual-zone automatic climate control, power front windows and side mirrors, an onboard computer, a cargo cover, and an aftermarket head unit. The door panel inserts were reportedly replaced in April 2024.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 250-km/h speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, coolant temperature, and fuel economy. The digital odometer indicates 94k kilometers (~58k miles), approximately 1k of which have been added by the selling dealer.
The 2.0-liter inline-six M52B20 inline-six was factory rated at 148 horsepower and 140 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in January 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission. The underside was cleaned using dry ice treatment under current ownership.
Manufacturer’s literature, partial service records, and spare parts accompany the vehicle.
The Carfax report is free of accident or other reported damage with its initial entry in January 2023.

This dune buggy was constructed in a George Barris Mini-T-Style and features a fiberglass body mounted to a modified Volkswagen chassis. The car spent time in California and was refurbished under previous ownership before it was acquired by the seller in 2021. Finished in Nostalgic Maroon Metallic over tan leather, it is powered by an air-cooled 2,109cc flat-four paired with a four-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes a removable tan soft top, dual Dellorto carburetors, a four-into-four exhaust system, a chrome-finished narrowed front beam, chrome rear coilovers, four-wheel disc brakes, 15″ alloy wheels, Mickey Thompson tires, a wood-rimmed Grant GT steering wheel, a CNC pedal assembly, and a Hurst shifter. This dune buggy is offered at no reserve with a build summary and a Connecticut registration listing the car as a 1963 Volkswagen.

The fiberglass bodywork was refinished under previous ownership in Nostalgic Maroon Metallic. Exterior details include a removable tan soft top, a hood ornament, low-profile headlights, billet-aluminum side mirrors, a wine glass-themed rear window, a chrome fuel filler cap, and teardrop taillights.

Polished and staggered 15″ Jegs Performance Sport Star alloy wheels are wrapped in Mickey Thompson tires. The suspension features a chrome-finished 2″ narrowed front beam, 2.5″ drop spindles, and chrome shocks at the front joined by a torsion bar setup with chrome spring plates and preload-adjustable coilovers in the rear. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs.

The individual seats are upholstered in tan leather that extends to the side panels. Additional appointments include a CNC pedal assembly with a hydraulically actuated clutch as well as a chrome-finished top frame, a Hurst shifter, and tan carpets. A spare steering wheel is included in the sale.

The wood-rimmed Grant GT steering wheel fronts a body-color dashboard that houses a Dolphin speedometer while matching auxiliary gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, and voltage are housed in the body-color pod atop the central tunnel. The six-digit odometer shows 3,900 miles.

The air-cooled 2,109cc flat-four features an Eagle 2242 mild street camshaft, dual Dellorto carburetors, a polished four-into-four stainless-steel exhaust system, body-color cooling tins, hex-bar throttle linkage, billet aluminum pulleys, a spin-on oil filter, and an Odyssey battery. An oil change was completed in preparation for the sale.

Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a rebuilt four-speed manual transaxle. Work under previous ownership included media blasting the chassis and adding 2″ steel reinforcement rails to the pan and body before coating the underside with rust inhibitor.
The current Connecticut registration carries an “Antique” designation in the Registered Usage section.

This 1966 Triumph TR4A was acquired by its previous owner in 1996 and subsequently modified. The car was refinished in Signal Red, and its replacement 2,138cc inline-four was rebuilt and fitted with a Moss supercharger. A Moss aluminum head, a Wizard Cooling radiator, and an aluminum flywheel were also installed along with a stainless-steel exhaust system, and the steering and suspension systems were overhauled. The car also has black leather upholstery on the bucket seats, a color-coordinated soft top and tonneau, and 15″ wire wheels, Wilwood front disc brakes, fiddleback walnut dashboard, wool carpeting, and a Lecarra steering wheel. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this supercharged TR4 is now offered in Oregon with the owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, a car cover, and a clean Washington title.

The TR4A was built from 1965 to 1967 and featured a revised grille and a widened chassis compared with earlier TR4 models. The Giovanni Michelotti-designed body has been repainted Signal Red and features a black convertible soft top, a tonneau cover, a Triplex windshield, a driver-side mirror, a flip-up fuel-filler cap, turn signals on the front fender sides, LED tail lights, and chrome bumpers with overriders. There is a dent on the right-front fender.

The 15″ wire wheels are mounted with 165/80 Nexen SB802 tires. Wilwood front disc brakes mounted on alloy hubs were installed in 2021, at which time the springs, trailing arm brackets, and bushings were replaced. A replacement steering rack and Good Parts CV axle joints have also been fitted, according to the selling dealer.

The cabin houses bucket seats upholstered in black leather with white piping, and interior appointments include a locking glovebox, a cabin heater, seat belts, storage pockets, and a rear parcel shelf.

The Lecarra steering wheel sits ahead of a fiddleback walnut dashboard with Jaeger instrumentation. A Smiths boost-pressure gauge and electric clock have been installed. The five-digit odometer shows 57k miles, though total mileage is unknown.

The 2,138cc inline-four was rebuilt in 2002 with an earlier block and a Moss aluminum head, and the Moss supercharger was installed in 2011. A spin-on oil filter, 45-amp alternator, Mallory distributor, and electric fuel pump with an external Fram filter were also installed, and the aluminum radiator is cooled by a SPAL fan. The hood is supported by struts when open and has a redundant release.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission. An aluminum flywheel and a stainless-steel exhaust system have been installed.
The commission plate is a replacement, and the removed tag is included in the sale and presented in the gallery below.
Records are included in the sale along with jacking equipment, a car cover, and a “big-boost” kit that includes a bigger pulley for the supercharger and a longer belt.

This 1929 Ford Model A was refurbished and fitted with boattail speedster-style bodywork under previous ownership before it was purchased by the selling dealer in 2024. The car is finished in white over a green chassis and fenders, and power comes from a 201ci inline-four paired with a three-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes a Stromberg 94 carburetor, an Ansen intake manifold, mechanical drum brakes, red-painted 21″ wire-spoke wheels, a running board-mounted spotlight, and bucket seats trimmed in burgundy upholstery. This Model A Speedster is now offered in Marietta, Georgia, with a conditional Georgia title.

The boattail speedster-style bodywork is finished in white with green and red pinstriping over a green chassis and fenders. Equipment includes a gold miner hood ornament, a top-hinged hood with missing side panels, a tubular windscreen frame, red #59 roundels, running boards with a mounted spotlight and storage boxes, dual taillights, and a chrome exhaust tip.

Red-painted wire-spoke wheels wear chrome Ford-branded covers, and they are mounted with 4.40/4.50–21 Lester whitewall bias-ply tires. A matching spare wheel is stowed under the rear lid along with the fuel tank and battery. The car features front and rear solid axles with transverse leaf springs, and stopping power is provided by mechanical drums.

The cabin features fixed-back bucket seats trimmed in burgundy upholstery with color-matched side panels and carpets. Equipment includes white storage pockets and seat accents, lap belts, a wood floor panel, and a passenger-side grab handle.

The four-spoke steering wheel fronts a dash panel trimmed in alligator leather-style upholstery, and it features a white instrument panel housing a barrel-type speedometer and gauges for coolant temperature and amperage. The five-digit odometer shows under 1k miles, approximately 20 of which were added by the selling dealer. Total mileage is unknown.

The 201ci inline-four features an Ansen intake manifold and a Stromberg 94 carburetor topped with a chrome air cleaner. A fluid service was reportedly performed by the selling dealer in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a three-speed manual transmission.

This 2007 Aston Martin V8 Vantage has 34k miles following registration history in California, and it was purchased by its current owner in December 2016. Finished in Midnight Blue over Caspian Blue and Sandstorm leather, the car is powered by a 4.3-liter V8 paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes 19″ seven-spoke alloy wheels, a limited-slip differential, a back-up camera, heated power-adjustable seats, navigation, and automatic climate control. This V8 Vantage is now offered at no reserve on dealer consignment as part of Mohr Imports’ Monterey Car Week Collection with service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.
The car is finished in Midnight Blue and features an integrated rear spoiler, hood vents, LED taillights, and dual exhaust tips.
The 19″ seven-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact tires. Braking is from Aston Martin-branded red calipers over slotted rotors at all four corners.

The cabin is trimmed in Caspian Blue and Sandstorm leather and features heated power-adjustable seats. Additional features include seat-position memory, a back-up camera, navigation, a CD stereo, aluminum pedals, and automatic climate control.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 220-mph speedometer, a reverse-sweep tachometer, and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 34k miles, approximately 4k of which were added under current ownership.

The 4.3-liter V8 was factory rated at 380 horsepower and 302 lb-ft of torque, which is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.

This 1973 Jaguar E-Type Series III 2+2 is powered by a 5.3-liter V12 linked with a four-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. It is finished in British Racing Green over Biscuit leather, and features include four-wheel disc brakes, power steering, 15” knock-off wire wheels, quadruple carburetors, a leather-wrapped steering wheel, a cassette stereo, and air conditioning. The current owner acquired the car in 2014, and the car has since been repainted. This Series III E-Type is now offered as part of Mohr Imports’ Monterey Car Week Collection on dealer consignment with an Arizona title.

The car is finished in British Racing Green and was repainted under current ownership. Equipment includes uncovered headlights, a forward-hinged louvered hood, US-spec bumpers, pop-out rear quarter windows, and a power antenna.

The 15″ wire-spoke wheels are secured with knock-off spinners and are mounted with 205/70 Pirelli P4000 tires. The Series III E-Type was factory equipped with power steering, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes with inboard-mounted rear rotors.

The 2+2 cabin features front bucket seats and a reach bench upholstered in Biscuit leather as well as color-coordinated door panels. Interior amenities include a cassette stereo, a locking glovebox, and air conditioning.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames Smiths instrumentation including a 160-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline. An analog clock along with auxiliary gauges for voltage, coolant temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level are mounted in the center stack. The five-digit odometer has rolled over and currently shows 2k miles. Total mileage is unknown.
The 5.3-liter V12 was factory equipped with quadruple Zenith-Stromberg carburetors and was rated at 241 horsepower and 285 lb-ft of torque when new.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential.

This 1959 Mercedes-Benz 190SL is powered by a 1.9-liter inline-four paired with a four-speed manual transmission. The car is finished in black over tan leather and is equipped with a black soft top, a tonneau cover, 13″ steel wheels with body-color hubcaps, and an AM/FM radio. The car was refurbished some time ago and was purchased by the current owner in 2019. This 190SL is now offered as part of Mohr Imports’ Monterey Car Week Collection on dealer consignment in California with copies of the data card and production order as well as a clean Montana title.

Originally finished in Graphite Gray (190), the car has been repainted black and features a replacement black soft top as well as a matching top boot and tonneau cover. Additional equipment includes a driver-side mirror and a bright windshield surround, grille, and bumpers.

Steel 13″ wheels wear chrome trim rings, hubcaps with body-color accents, and 6.50.13 Coker Tires tires. The car is equipped with a double-wishbone front suspension, rear swing axles with coil springs, and power-assisted drum brakes.

The cabin features low-back bucket seats upholstered in tan leather as well as matching door panels and dashboard trim. Amenities include a Highway Hi-Fi AM/FM radio, lap belts, an analog clock, and a dashboard-mounted rearview mirror.

The two-spoke steering wheel frames VDO instrumentation including a 140-mph speedometer and a 7k-rpm tachometer as well as gauges for oil pressure, water temperature, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 26k miles, less than 1k of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.
The 1.9-liter M121 inline-four is equipped with dual Solex carburetors and was factory rated at 104 horsepower and 105 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
A photo of the engine stamping is viewable above.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a fully synchronized four-speed manual transmission.
Copies of the data card and production order are included in the sale and show the factory colors and serial numbers.

This 1993 Jaguar XJ220 is one of approximately 280 examples built during two years of production and was manufactured on June 18, 1993. It was delivered to its first owner via Jaguar Deutschland GmbH on January 24, 1994, and placed into storage until 2002. It was sent to Don Law Jaguar in Stoke-on-Trent, Staffordshire, for service that year before it was first imported to the US. It later returned to Don Law Jaguar for additional service in 2016 before it was reimported to the US under a Show or Display exemption in 2017. It won awards at the Jaguar Club of Florida Concours d’Elegance and Hilton Head Island Concours d’Elegance in 2021 and was purchased by the current owner in 2022. The aluminum bodywork is finished in Spa Silver over Charcoal leather, and power comes from a twin-turbocharged 3.5-liter V6 mated to a five-speed manual transaxle with a limited-slip differential. Additional features include a bonded aluminum chassis, a glass roof panel, AP Racing brake, staggered-diameter Speedline wheels, air conditioning, and an Alpine stereo with a trunk-mounted CD changer. This XJ220 shows 1,150 kilometers (~700 miles) and is now offered on dealer consignment in Lancaster, New York, with factory literature, tools, Project XJ220 Limited correspondence, a Jaguar Heritage Trust certificate, import documents, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Florida title.

The XJ220 was developed in collaboration with Tom Walkinshaw Racing based on an all-wheel-drive, V12-powered concept that was shown at the 1988 British International Motor Show. The production version shared the prototype’s bonded aluminum honeycomb chassis but was shortened in wheelbase and overall length. A rally-derived V6 was fitted in place of the concept’s larger engine and powered the rear wheels exclusively. The XJ220 set a production-car record with a top speed of 212.3 mph in stock form during 1991 testing before entering production the following year. An XJ220 with its catalytic converters removed then raised the record to 217.1 mph in June 1992.

Aluminum bodywork was constructed by Abbey Panels, Ltd. of Coventry, England. This example was delivered from the factory in Spa Silver and features a front air dam, retractable headlight covers, louvers at the base of the windshield and rear window to stabilize airflow, underbody venturi tunnels that extend into a rear diffuser, electrically adjustable side mirrors, intake scoops aft of the doors, a glass roof panel, and a trunk-mounted rear spoiler.

Speedline Corse-designed alloy wheels measure 17” up front and 18” at the rear and are secured by center-lock nuts. Bridgestone Potenza S007 tires showing 2017 date codes were reportedly sourced from Don Law and mounted in 2019. The XJ220 rides on a 103.9″ wheelbase and features a fully independent suspension with unequal-length wishbones at all four corners. Stopping power is provided by AP Racing-designed four-piston aluminum calipers mounted over cross-drilled and ventilated discs measuring 13” in diameter up front and 11.8” out back.

The left-hand-drive cabin features manually adjustable bolstered sport seats trimmed in Charcoal leather with perforated inserts as well as a color-coordinated center console, door panels, and roof pillars. Color-matched carpeting covers the floors, while black microsuede accents the kick panels and doors. Additional amenities include air conditioning, power windows, and an Alpine cassette player with a trunk-mounted CD changer.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel sits ahead of a 360-km/h speedometer, a tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline, and gauges monitoring oil pressure and temperature, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The instrument binnacle extends over the adjacent door panel, where a clock, an ammeter, and gauges showing boost pressure and transaxle temperature are housed. The six-digit odometer shows 1,150 kilometers (~700 miles), and approximately 21 kilometers have been added under current ownership.

The 3.5-liter JV6 V6 was developed by Jaguar and TWR based on the Austin Rover V64V used in the MG Metro 6R4 Group B rally car. Shared by Jaguar’s XJR-10 and XJR-11 racing cars, the JV6 features twin Garrett turbochargers with corresponding air-to-air intercoolers, an aluminum block and cylinder heads, dual overhead camshafts on each bank, four valves per cylinder, dry-sump lubrication, multipoint fuel injection with dual injectors, and Zytek electronic engine management. Factory-rated output was 542 horsepower and 475 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle equipped with a limited-slip differential.

The Jaguar Heritage Trust Production Record Trace Certificate lists factory colors and component numbers as well as a June 18, 1993, production date. Correspondence from Project XJ220 Limited, registration documents, service records, and NHTSA import documents can be seen in the gallery along with included factory books and tools.
The Carfax report is free of accidents and damage.

This 1996 Porsche Carrera RS is one of approximately 1,014 examples produced for the 1995 and 1996 model years and was delivered new to Porsche Zentrum Bamberg in Germany. The car is finished in black over black and gray multi-tone leather upholstery, and power comes from a replacement 3.8-liter flat-six mated to a replacement G50/30 six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. RS Clubsport-style spoilers have been added along with a welded-in roll cage, OMP multi-point harnesses, and a fire-suppression system. Further equipment includes a seam-welded body shell, an aluminum hood, 18″ Speedline multi-piece wheels, a front strut tower bar, Recaro seats, air conditioning, power windows, and a Blaupunkt CD stereo. The car is said to have been acquired by the current owner in 2001 from its first owner, after which it was relocated to France. A top-end reseal was reportedly carried out in April 2024, and further work performed since 2022 involved fitting a competition clutch as well as replacing the mufflers and fuel pump. This 993 Carrera RS is offered on dealer consignment in Aubenas, France with a service manual and French registration.

The 993 RS Carrera is a lightweight variant of the Carrera that was introduced for the 1995 model year and featured a seam-welded body shell, an aluminum hood, deleted headlight washers, and thinner glass compared to the contemporary Carrera. This example left the factory in black (L741) and has been fitted with RS Clubsport-style spoilers. Further exterior details include hood and decklid pins, Carrera RS decklid badging, side marker lamps, and dual exhaust outlets. The seller states that the car was involved in a collision with another vehicle in the early 2000s and the right door and rear fender have been refinished. There is a scratch on the driver’s door, and stone chips are visible along the front bumper cover and fenders, hood, and side mirrors. A selection of paint meter readings are provided in the photo gallery below.

Silver 18″ multi-piece Speedline wheels feature RS center caps and are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport Cup tires that measure 225/40 up front and 275/35 out back, the latter of which were installed in May 2024. A factory-optioned strut bar spans the front trunk, which houses a space-saver spare. Stopping power is provided by red four-piston calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated discs at each corner.

The cabin houses replacement fixed-back Recaro seats trimmed in black leather with gray multi-tone centers and fitted with OMP multi-point harnesses that are attached to the partially padded roll cage. Additional modifications consist of a fire-suppression system, TechArt drilled pedals, checker-plate flooring in the driver’s footwell, and a Blaupunkt CD stereo, while factory appointments include air conditioning, power windows, and a front passenger airbag. Wear is visible on the shift knob.

The microsuede-wrapped MOMO steering wheel features a yellow centering stripe and fronts a central tachometer flanked by a quartz clock and combination gauges. The six-digit odometer shows 194k kilometers (~121k miles). The speedometer was removed and repaired in preparation of the sale, and total mileage is unknown. The seller states that the removed factory steering wheel will accompany the sale.

The M64/20 flat-six was enlarged to 3.8 liters for the Carrera RS and features a VarioRam intake system, forged pistons, lightened rocker arms, enlarged intake valves, and Bosch Motronic engine management. It was factory rated at 300 horsepower, and the engine in this example was replaced under previous ownership. The fuel pump was replaced in August 2023 and the seller notes that a top-end reseal was performed in April 2024.

Power is sent to the rear wheels via a G50/30 six-speed manual transaxle that was installed under previous ownership and a limited-slip differential. A competition clutch was installed in July 2022, at which time the clutch pedal stop and release bearing were replaced. A pair of stainless-steel sport mufflers were fitted in April 2024 and the wheel arch liners were also replaced at each corner. Scrapes are visible along the underside.
The maintenance booklet indicates that the car was first sold in Germany in August 1995, and decoding the options sticker provides the following information:

The vehicle is being sold on its French registration, which lists the first registration date as August 1, 1995. The sale does not include a title, as the vehicle is registered in a country that does not issue titles for vehicles.

This 2001 Ferrari 550 Maranello is a Canadian-market example that shows 9k kilometers (~6k miles), and it was registered in Ontario prior to being imported into the United States in June 2020. Finished in Giallo Modena over Nero leather, the car is powered by a 5.5-liter V12 paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. The car is equipped with a limited-slip differential, a Tubi-Style exhaust system, 18″ five-spoke alloy wheels, fog lights, Scuderia Ferrari fender shields, power-adjustable Daytona-style seats, a gated shifter, a CD stereo, and automatic climate control. The tires have been replaced and the oil changed in preparation for the sale. This 550 Maranello is now offered in Florida by the selling dealer at no reserve with the owner’s manual, service records, a car cover, tools, a clean Carfax report, and a Montana title.

The 550 Maranello was styled by Pininfarina, and this example is finished in Giallo Modena. Equipment includes projector-style headlights, fog lights, a hood scoop, a front spoiler, front fender vents, Scuderia Ferrari fender shields, and quad exhaust tips exiting through the rear bumper cover.

The 18″ five-spoke alloy wheels wear 255/40 front and 295/35 rear Pirelli P Zero Rosso tires that were fitted in July 2024. Braking is handled by red-finished Ferrari-branded calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated rotors at all four corners.

The cabin features power-adjustable Daytona-style seats upholstered in Nero leather. Amenities include a gated shifter, automatic climate control, electric windows, a CD stereo, a hi-fi sound system, and rear luggage straps. Sticky surfaces were refinished in June 2020.

The leather-wrapped three-spoke steering wheel fronts a Jaeger gauge cluster with a 340-km/h speedometer and a tachometer with a 7,600-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature and oil pressure, while an analog clock and gauges for oil temperature and fuel level are located atop the center stack. The six-digit odometer shows 9k kilometers (~6k miles).

The 5.5-liter quad-cam F133A V12 features 48 valves, dry-sump lubrication, and Bosch Motronic engine management for a factory-rated output of 478 horsepower and 419 lb-ft of torque. A belt service was performed in June 2020, and additional work at that time included replacing the valve cover gaskets and engine mounts. The oil was changed in July 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. A Tubi-Style exhaust system has been added.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2000 BMW M5 was purchased new by the current owner from Morristown BMW in New Jersey, and it now has 24k miles following registration history in that state since new. The car is powered by a 4.9-liter V8 paired with a six-speed manual transmission and is finished in Titanium Silver Metallic over black Nappa leather upholstery. Equipment includes 18″ Style 65 wheels, a limited-slip differential, a sunroof, xenon headlights, fog lights, heated power-adjustable front seats, dual-zone automatic climate control, and navigation. This E39 M5 is offered in Arizona on dealer consignment with a window sticker, manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carfax report, a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Titanium Silver Metallic with Shadowline trim and features xenon headlights with washers, fog lamps, a glass sunroof, a trunk lid spoiler, rain-sensing wipers, and quad exhaust outlets. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

Chrome Shadow 18″ Style 65 wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact tires. The car features Dynamic Stability Control (DSC) with All Season Traction, and braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs measuring 13.6″ and 12.9″ front and rear, respectively. The brake fluid was changed and the power steering lines were replaced in preparation for the sale.

The cabin features black Nappa leather covering the heated power-adjustable front sport seats, door panel inserts, center console, and lower dashboard, while matte chrome accents the upper dashboard, center console, and upper doors. Amenities include dual-zone automatic climate control, a cassette player, a trunk-mounted CD changer, cruise control, and navigation.

The multi-function leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts an M-branded 185-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a variable redline, along with gauges for coolant temperature, oil temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 24k miles. The instrument cluster pixels were repaired in 2024.

The 4.9-liter S62 V8 is equipped with individual throttle bodies and double-VANOS continuously variable valve timing. It was factory rated at 394 horsepower at 6,600 rpm and 369 lb-ft of torque at 3,800 rpm. The fuel filter, motor mounts, and drive belts were replaced in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Getrag six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. The transmission fluid and differential fluid were changed in May 2024.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Morristown BMW in Morristown, New Jersey, as well as factory colors, equipment, and a total suggested retail price of $72,070.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2009 Honda S2000 was produced for the Canadian Market and 37k kilometers (~23k miles) following registration history in British Columbia, New Brunswick, and Ontario. Finished in Berlina Black over black leather upholstery, it is powered by a 2.2-liter VTEC inline-four linked with a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. The car has 17″ five-spoke alloy wheels, a black convertible soft top, xenon headlights, air conditioning, push-button ignition, bright pedals, a wind deflector, a CD stereo, and cruise control. This AP2 S2000 was purchased by the seller in 2024 and is now offered with the owner’s manual, spare keys and parts, promotional material, handwritten notes, a boot cover, a clean Carfax report, and Ontario registration.

The car is finished in Berlina Black and has a power-operated black soft top with a glass rear window. Additional exterior details include xenon headlights, roll hoops, a boot cover, an aftermarket antenna, clear side markers, and oval-tipped exhaust outlets. Photos of body panel VIN stickers can be viewed in the gallery. A front spoiler was installed under current ownership.

Factory 17″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with staggered-width Michelin Pilot Sport 4s tires. The car features double-wishbone suspension and four-wheel disc brakes. Tire tread-depth measurements are provided in the gallery.

The cabin features seats upholstered in black leather with color-coordinated door panels and carpets. S2000-branded floor mats line the footwells, and appointments include push-button ignition, air conditioning, a wind deflector, bright pedals, cruise control, a CD stereo, and an aluminum shift knob.

The three-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a digital speedometer and a bar-style tachometer with an 8k-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 37k kilometers (~23k miles).
The 2.2-liter VTEC F22C1 inline-four was factory rated at 237 horsepower and 162 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. Additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its Ontario registration, which serves as the ownership document in Ontario, Canada.

This 1967 Volkswagen Beetle was refurbished approximately 20 years ago and acquired by the current owner in 2019. It is finished in Savannah Beige over black upholstery and powered by an air-cooled 1.5L flat-four paired with a four-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes 15″ steel wheels, chrome hubcaps and bumpers, a Solex carburetor, front shoulder belts, and a Bendix Sapphire V push-button AM radio. This Beetle is now offered on behalf of the current owner at no reserve with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a tool roll, spare parts, handwritten service notes, and a Washington State title in the current owner’s name.

Model-year changes for North American 1967 examples included a 12-volt electrical system, revised headlights, and the addition of reverse lights. This example was refinished in Savannah Beige approximately 20 years ago and features polished beltline trim, a left side-view mirror, dual “pea shooter” exhaust outlets, and chrome bumpers with overriders.
Steel 15″ wheels wear chrome hubcaps with Wolfsburg crest logos and are mounted with 165/80 Thunderer Mach I tires. Stopping power is provided by drum brakes at all four corners.

The front bucket seats and rear bench were retrimmed in black basketweave pattern upholstery as part of the refurbishment and are joined by color-coordinated door panels, charcoal carpeting, and a rubber floor lining. Interior elements include front shoulder belts, a passenger grab handle, and a Bendix Sapphire V push-button AM radio.

The two-spoke steering wheel wears a chrome horn ring with a Wolfsburg crest center cap and frames a 90-mph VDO speedometer and fuel level gauge. The five-digit mechanical odometer is believed to have rolled over and currently shows 37k miles. True mileage is unknown.
The air-cooled 1.5L (H0) flat-four is fed by a Solex downdraft carburetor topped with an oil bath air cleaner.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transaxle.

The window sticker shows initial delivery to Jack Feely Motors Inc. of Redlands, California, along with standard equipment, optional equipment, and a suggested retail price of $1,770. Manufacturer’s literature and service notes are also included in the sale.
The Washington State title carries a “Classic” brand.
listing_details: Bendix Sapphire V Push-Button AM Radio

description: This Shelby Cobra is a CSX4000 continuation model that was completed on July 26, 2005, and delivered to S/C Motorsports of Mustang, Oklahoma. Power is provided by a side-oiler Ford V8 that has reportedly been stroked to displace 468ci and paired with a David Kee Toploader four-speed manual transmission. The fiberglass bodywork is finished in Guardsman Blue with Wimbledon White center stripes, and features include Halibrand-style knock-off wheels, four-wheel disc brakes, independent suspension, side exhaust pipes, a chrome roll hoop, latch-and-link lap belts, and a wood-rimmed steering wheel. Acquired by the seller in January 2022, this CSX4000 was previously offered on BaT in June 2023 and is now offered again in Florida with a clean Montana title in the name of the seller’s LLC listing it as a 1965 Shelby Cobra.

The fiberglass bodywork is finished in Guardsman Blue with Wimbledon White center stripes and mounted on a 4″ round-tube steel frame with a 90″ wheelbase. Exterior details include quick-jack bumperettes, a hood scoop, Shelby 427 S/C-badging, fender vents, wind wings, a single roll hoop, a Le Mans-style fuel filler, and side-exit exhaust pipes. Paint chips and scratches are visible on the front end.

Halibrand-style 15″ wheels are secured with safety-wired three-eared knockoffs and are mounted with 26.5×8″ front and 26.5×10.5″ rear Goodyear Eagle Sport Car Special tires with billboard-style lettering. The car rides on four-wheel independent suspension with coilovers and rack-and-pinion steering. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel disc brakes.

The low-back bucket seats are trimmed in black leather and joined by a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpeting. Interior elements include a dashboard-mounted rearview mirror, Crow Enterprizes latch-and-link lap belts, tinted sunvisors, and a battery cut-off switch.

Shelby-branded instrumentation includes a reverse-sweep 180-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for monitoring oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, amperage, and fuel level. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 3,200 miles, approximately 900 of which were added under current ownership. The fuel level gauge has been replaced.

The side-oiler Ford V8 is said to be a 1965 model that was rebuilt and stroked to displace 468ci by Geesford Machine of Hastings, Nebraska. It features dual 540-cfm Holley four-barrel carburetors, Shelby-branded valve covers, MSD ignition components, and an aluminum radiator with an electric fan. Additional equipment reportedly includes a COMP Cams solid-roller camshaft, Edelbrock aluminum cylinder heads, Arias pistons, Dove roller rocker arms, Stelling and Hellings air cleaners, and a Blue Thunder intake manifold. Service performed in 2023 is said to have involved replacing the battery and changing the oil. Images of the engine numbers and casting stamps are viewable in the previous auction gallery.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Ford Toploader four-speed manual transmission that was built by David Kee of San Antonio, Texas. The rear differential is said to be equipped with 3.54:1 gearing.
The chassis number CSX4780 shown above matches the VIN listed on the current Montana title, which describes the car as a 1965 Shelby Cobra.

This 1990 Ferrari 348 TS shows 21k miles following registration history in Colorado, Arizona, and New Mexico. Finished in Nero over Cream Connolly leather, the car is powered by a 3.4-liter DOHC V8 paired with a dogleg five-speed manual transaxle. Features include a Fabspeed exhaust system, a removable roof panel, 17″ five-spoke alloy wheels, a limited-slip differential, a gated shifter, air conditioning, and power windows. This 348 is now offered by the selling dealer with the owner’s manual, service records, a tool kit, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Colorado title.

The 348 was the final V8-powered Ferrari model developed under the direction of Enzo Ferrari, and its design was overseen by Pininfarina chief stylist Leonardo Fioravanti. This example is finished in Nero with black lower-body panels and features a removable black roof panel, pop-up headlights, fog lights, side air intakes, louvered taillights, and quad exhaust tips. Close-up photos of imperfections are included in the gallery.

The 17″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact DWS 06 Plus tires, which were fitted in November 2021. Stopping power is provided by Ferrari-branded calipers over ventilated discs along with an anti-lock system.

The cabin features two seats upholstered in Cream Connolly leather along with a matching center console, lower dashboard, and door panel inserts. Equipment includes a dogleg-pattern gated shifter, a heated rear window, a Boss amplifier, Pioneer speakers, and power windows and door locks. The air conditioning system was converted to R134a refrigerant in June 2020.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames Veglia Borletti instrumentation including a 200-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 7,500-rpm redline, and gauges for coolant temperature and oil pressure. Auxiliary gauges for oil temperature and fuel level are mounted in the center stack. The six-digit odometer shows 21k miles, approximately 300 of which have been added by the seller.

The 3.4-liter quad-cam Tipo F119 V8 features Bosch Motronic engine management and was factory rated at 296 horsepower and 229 lb-ft of torque. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. A belt service was performed in June 2020 by European Auto Service in Palm Desert, California. Additional work at that time included installing a Fabspeed exhaust system and replacing the water pump, fuel sending unit, and valve cover gaskets.
The Carfax report is free from accidents or other reported damage.

This 2011 Subaru Impreza WRX STi remained registered to its original owner until 2023 and was subsequently detailed by Larry Kosilla of AMMO NYC in preparation for sale. Finished in Spark Silver Metallic over black leather and Alcantara, it has 78k miles and is powered by a turbocharged 2.5-liter flat-four that drives all four wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle, a Driver Controlled Center Differential, and limited-slip front and rear differentials. Equipment includes 18″ multi-spoke alloy wheels, a rear hatch spoiler, heated front seats, automatic climate control, and an AM/FM/CD stereo. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2023, this WRX STi is now offered at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a clean Rhode Island title.

The car is finished in Spark Silver Metallic (C3S) and features a hood scoop, a rear hatch spoiler, flared fenders, power-operated side mirrors, and quad exhaust outlets. The lower part of the front bumper cover is cracked and imperfections can be seen in the gallery below. A majority of the seller’s photos were taken in January 2024.

Multi-spoke 18″ BBS aluminum alloy wheels are mounted with 245/40 Dunlop Signature HP tires. Braking is from four- and two-piston STi-branded Brembo calipers fitted over ventilated discs. The car rides on a sport-tuned four-wheel independent suspension that includes an inverted-strut-type setup up front and double wishbones at the rear. Blemishes and flaking paint are present on the wheels.

The heated front bucket seats and 60/40 split-folding rear bench are upholstered in Black Alcantara with Carbon Black leather bolsters, and STi logos are embroidered onto the front seat headrests. Other features include automatic climate control, cruise control, an AM/FM/CD stereo, and aluminum pedals. An SI-Drive control wheel on the center console is used to adjust power distribution from the center differential. The passenger airbag is said to have been replaced in 2020.

A leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel frames a central 8k-rpm tachometer flanked by a 160-mph speedometer and a combination gauge for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 78k miles.
The turbocharged and intercooled 2.5-liter flat-four was factory rated at 305 horsepower and 290 lb-ft of torque. The hood insulation is damaged.
Power is routed to all four wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle, a Driver Controlled Center Differential, and limited-slip front and rear differentials.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

At the conclusion of the auction, a portion of the proceeds from the sale will be directed to The Special Olympics, a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization whose mission is to provide training and competition opportunities for people with intellectual disabilities.

This 2001 Honda Prelude is a Type SH example that is finished in Satin Silver Metallic over black cloth upholstery and is powered by a 2.2-liter inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. Now showing 47k miles, it is further equipped with an Active Torque Transfer System, 16″ alloy wheels, a rear spoiler, a ground effects kit, a power-operated sunroof, air conditioning, cruise control, and a CD stereo. The water pump as well as the timing and clutch components were replaced before the car was acquired by the selling dealer in May 2023, and work performed since then involved changing the oil and brake fluid, repainting various body panels, and replacing the valve cover gaskets. This Prelude Type SH is now offered by the selling dealer in Florida with manufacturer’s literature, partial service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Massachusetts title.

The car is finished in Satin Silver Metallic (NH623M), and the hood, and front and rear bumper covers were reportedly repainted under current ownership, and the seller states that the right rear quarter panel was repainted under prior ownership. Details include black and silver pinstripes, a power-operated glass sunroof, power-adjustable mirrors, a rear spoiler, and a ground effects kit.

Silver-finished 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with 205/50 Evoluxx Capricorn UHP tires. The SH “Super Handling” model featured an Active Torque Transfer System along with firmer springs, shocks, and anti-roll bars than the standard Prelude. Braking is provided by four-wheel discs, and a brake fluid flush was performed in preparation for the sale.

The front bucket seats and a bolstered rear bench seat are upholstered in black cloth with patterned inserts and are complemented by a color-coordinated dashboard, center console, and door panels. Honda-branded floor mats line the footwells, and appointments include air conditioning, cruise control, and an AM/FM/CD stereo.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel is mounted on a tilting column and frames a 150-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 47k miles, approximately 100 of which have been added by the selling dealer.

The 2.2-liter DOHC inline-four features VTEC variable valve timing and was factory rated at 200 horsepower and 156 lb-ft of torque. The water pump, drive belts, and timing belt components were replaced in May 2022, and an oil change was performed and the valve cover gaskets were replaced in preparation for the sale.
Power is delivered to the front wheels via a five-speed manual transaxle. Clutch components were replaced in May 2022, and rust is noted on underside components.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1965 Pontiac Grand Prix is said to have been purchased new by a General Motors employee from Jenny Pontiac of Janesville, Wisconsin and remained in their family until 2015. The car is finished in Iris Mist over Plum vinyl upholstery, and power comes from a 389ci V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes a four-barrel carburetor, power-assisted steering and drum brakes, 14″ eight-lug aluminum wheels, a black vinyl roof, front bucket seats, a center console, and a push-button AM/FM radio with Bluetooth compatibility.
