This Grand Prix Sports Coupe was purchased by the current owner in 2022, and it is now offered on dealer consignment as part of the Mohr Imports’ Monterey Car Week Collection with spare parts, an owner’s manual, a reproduction window sticker, PHS documentation, service records, a set of California black plates, a car cover, and a clean California title.

The car was delivered from the factory in Iris Mist (P), a color offered exclusively on Pontiacs exclusively for the 1965 model year. Features include chrome bumpers and trim, stacked quad headlights, dual side mirrors, a black vinyl roof, rear fender skirts, taillight louvers, reverse lamps, and polished exhaust finishers.

Aluminum eight-lug wheels wear Pontiac Motor Division center caps, and they are mounted with 215/T5R14 Firestone whitewall radial tires. A matching spare wheel with a Uniroyal tire is stowed under a cover in the trunk. The car was equipped from the factory with Wonder Touch power-assisted steering and power four-wheel drum brakes. Three painted steel wheels, five chrome Pontiac Motor Division hubcaps, and four spare finned brake drums are included in the sale.

The cabin features front bucket seats and a rear bench trimmed in Plum vinyl (287) along with a color-coordinated headliner, door panels and carpets. Woodgrain trim accents the dashboard and center console, and additional equipment includes a heater, a push-button AM/FM radio that has been upgraded with Bluetooth compatibility, a center console with cupholders, front lap belts, and a fold-down rear armrest. Corrosion in the trunk is shown in the gallery.

The two-spoke steering wheel fronts a 120-mph speedometer. A clock and gauges for fuel level and battery charge are located in the center of the dash, while a manifold vacuum gauge is mounted on the center console. Additional readouts for water temperature and oil pressure are installed below the dash. The five-digit odometer shows 19k miles, approximately 4k of which were added by the current owner.
The 389ci V8 features five main bearings and a four-barrel carburetor, and it was factory rated at 325 horsepower and 425 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels via a Turbo Hydra-Matic three-speed automatic transmission.
The Fisher body plate partially decodes as follows:

This 1964 Mercedes-Benz 230SL has been refinished in black over red MB-Tex and is powered by a 2.3-liter inline-six paired with a four-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes a black convertible top, a removable hardtop, power steering, 14″ steel wheels with painted covers, Euro headlights, a Becker AM/FM radio, and a heater. The current owner acquired the car in 2016 and the engine was rebuilt in December 2020. Service in August 2021 included replacing the fuel tank and fuel tank sending unit, while a fuel system flush was performed in May 2024. This W113 SL is now offered as part of Mohr Imports’ Monterey Car Week Collection in California on dealer consignment at no reserve with a clean Florida title.

The W113 SL was designed by Friedrich Geiger, Béla Barényi, and Paul Bracq and was introduced to the public at the 1963 Geneva Motor Show. This example came finished from the factory in white and was repainted black over two decades ago. Features include a black soft top, a removable hardtop, dual side mirrors, and European-specification headlights.

The 14″ steel wheels feature covers with painted centers and are mounted with Nexen tires measuring 195/70. The car is equipped with power steering, and braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. Bilstein shocks are fitted.

The cabin houses bucket seats that have been reupholstered in red MB-Tex that extends to the door panels. Interior appointments include an analog clock, a Becker Europa AM/FM radio, a floor-mounted gear shifter, and a heater.

The two-spoke steering wheel features a chrome horn ring and frames a 140-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 32k miles, approximately 1k of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 2.3-liter M127 inline-six was rebuilt in December 2020 by Eurotech of Sante Fe, New Mexico. The work also involved a rebuild of the fuel injection pump and more as detailed in records provided in the image gallery below. The fuel tank and fuel tank sending unit were replaced in August 2021, at which time a valve adjustment was performed. Work performed in May 2024 is detailed in records shown in the image gallery and involved a fuel system flush, a valve adjustment, and replacing the distributor. The oil was also changed.
Power is routed to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transmission.

This 2014 Porsche 911 Turbo S coupe is powered by a twin-turbocharged 3.8L flat-six that drives all four wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle, and it is finished in white over black and Carrera Red leather. Equipment includes the Sport Chrono and Light Design Packages along with 20″ Turbo S center-lock alloy wheels, H&R lowering springs, Porsche Ceramic Composite Brakes, an electronic limited-slip rear differential, LED headlights, Park Assist, Racing Yellow seat belts, carbon-fiber interior trim, illuminated carbon-fiber door sill plates, Bose audio, and PCM with navigation. The car was previously listed on BaT in September 2022 and was acquired by the seller the following month. This 991.1 Turbo S has 13k miles and is offered with a window sticker, an owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Arizona title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in white and has LED headlights, clear side markers, a power sunroof, quarter panel air intakes, a speed-activated rear spoiler, and quad exhaust outlets. Clear paint protection film has been applied to the front end and rocker panels.

The 20″ Turbo S center-lock alloy wheels are wrapped in 245/35 front and 305/35 rear Michelin Pilot Sport tires that were mounted under current ownership. Braking is handled by Porsche Ceramic Composite Brakes (PCCB) featuring yellow-painted Porsche-branded calipers at all four corners. Rear-axle steering and Porsche Dynamic Chassis Control (PDCC) were standard equipment on the Turbo S. The car is also equipped with Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM). H&R lowering springs were installed in January 2023.

The cabin is trimmed in Carrera Red and black leather and features a microsuede headliner, Racing Yellow seatbelts, and carbon-fiber accents on the dash, center console, door panels, and illuminated door sills. Amenities include power-adjustable front seats, cruise control, dual-zone automatic climate control, a Bose sound system, and Porsche Communication Management with navigation.

The three-spoke SportDesign steering wheel frames a central tachometer with a 7k-rpm redline as well as a 225-mph speedometer and gauges for coolant temperature, oil temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. The Sport Chrono Package added a stopwatch atop the dashboard. The digital odometer indicates 13k miles, approximately 1,500 of which were added under current ownership.

The twin-turbocharged 3.8L flat-six features aluminum construction and direct fuel injection. Factory-rated output was 560 horsepower and 516 lb-ft of torque, and the Sport Chrono Package adds an over-boost function that temporarily raises peak torque to 553 lb-ft. The radiator is said to have been replaced in 2022, and an oil change was performed in January 2023.
Power is sent to all four wheels via a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle and an electronically locking rear differential with Porsche Torque Vectoring Plus.

The window sticker lists initial delivery to Porsche of the Fox Valley in Appleton, Wisconsin, along with factory equipment, colors, options, and a total price of $186,695. An owner’s manual and two key fobs will accompany the car.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1986 Porsche 911 Turbo coupe is powered by a turbocharged 3.3-liter flat-six paired with a four-speed manual transaxle and is finished in Garnet Red Metallic over a Champagne leather interior. Equipment includes a sunroof, air conditioning, a Blaupunkt New York AM/FM/CD stereo, power-adjustable front seats, and chrome-finished 16″ Fuchs-style wheels. Additional modifications include a front strut-tower brace, an alarm system, and Euro-style headlamps. The car was acquired by the owner on BaT in March 2021, and subsequent work consisted of replacing the smog pump belt and drive gear and resealing the turbo oil supply pipe at the engine case. This 930 Turbo shows 50k miles and is now offered on dealer consignment with partial service records, a tire inflator, a tool kit, a fire extinguisher, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The body is finished in Garnet Red Metallic and features a sunroof along with front and rear spoilers. Additional equipment includes a rear wiper, Euro-style headlamps, headlamp washers, and integrated front fog lights. The selling dealer reports evidence of bodywork on the rear quarter panel and previous paintwork.

Chrome-finished 16″ Fuchs-style wheels wear Porsche logo center caps and are wrapped in Bridgestone Potenza RE-11 tires. Braking is handled by cross-drilled rotors and four-piston brake calipers at each corner. The brake fluid was flushed under current ownership.

The seats are trimmed in Champagne leather and are joined by matching carpeting and door panels along with a contrasting black dashboard. Additional equipment includes air conditioning, power-adjustable front seats, and power windows. An aftermarket alarm system is installed, and the shifter bushings were replaced in March 2021. A Blaupunkt New York AM/FM/CD stereo is fitted, although the speakers crackle.

The four-spoke steering wheel fronts VDO instrumentation including a 7k-rpm tachometer with an inset boost-pressure gauge as well as a 170-mph speedometer, an analog clock, and combination gauges. The six-digit odometer shows 50k miles, approximately 2,500 of which were added during current ownership.
The front trunk compartment features a strut-tower brace along with black carpeting, a tire inflator, a tool kit, and a fire extinguisher.

The turbocharged 3.3-liter flat-six was rated at 282 horsepower and 289 lb-ft of torque when new. Work in May 2024 consisted of replacing the smog pump belt and drive gear, resealing the turbo oil supply pipe at the engine case as well as performing an oil change.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transaxle. Additional underside photos are presented in the gallery.
The seller notes that the options code sticker is present under the front hood.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 1994 Chevrolet Corvette ZR-1 was initially sold by Ed Morse Chevrolet in Lauderhill, Florida, and it now has 3,600 miles. It is powered by a 5.7-liter LT5 V8 paired with a ZF six-speed manual transmission and is finished in Arctic White over Torch Red leather. The car is equipped with the Selective Ride and Handling Package, a Magnaflow exhaust system, 17″ five-spoke alloy wheels, two removable roof panels, pop-up headlights, power-adjustable sport seats, automatic climate control, a Sony stereo, and an Alpine subwoofer. This C4 Corvette ZR-1 is now offered by the selling dealer with initial sales documentation, the owner’s manual, service invoices, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Pennsylvania title.

The C4 ZR-1 was sold between 1990 and 1995, and it featured a wider tail compared to the standard C4 Corvette and introduced a convex rear fascia with squared-off tail lights. This example is finished in Arctic White and features pop-up headlights, fog lamps, a removable fiberglass roof panel, a removable transparent roof panel, fender aero-vents, and power-adjustable and heated side mirrors.

Staggered-width 17″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Goodyear Eagle F1 tires. The ZR-1 was equipped with the three-mode Selective Ride and Handling package, which was designed in consultation with Lotus and featured Bilstein shock absorbers. Braking is handled by anti-lock disc brakes at all four corners.

The cabin features two power-adjustable sport bucket seats upholstered in Torch Red leather along with matching carpets and door panels. Amenities include cruise control, automatic climate control, an onboard computer, a tire pressure warning system, a Sony touch screen stereo, and power windows and locks. An Alpine subwoofer has been installed in the rear cargo area.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a central digital speedometer and fuel readout flanked by an analog tachometer and gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, and voltage. The digital odometer indicates 3,600 miles.
The 5.7-liter LT5 DOHC V8 was designed by GM’s Lotus Group Division and built by Mercury Marine of Stillwater, Oklahoma. Output was rated at 405 horsepower and 385 lb-ft of torque when new.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a ZF six-speed manual transmission. A Magnaflow exhaust system has been fitted.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 1935 Ford five-window coupe was refurbished and modified under prior ownership with work that included a repaint in two-tone blue, a custom interior re-trim in black cloth, and installation of a Chevrolet 350ci V8 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes an Edelbrock carburetor, intake manifold, and cylinder heads as well as a rumble seat, front disc brakes, staggered-width 15″ steel wheels, Stewart-Warner gauges, a blade-style fuse panel, a tilting steering column, and chrome bumpers and trim. This five-window coupe was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024 and is now offered with a Washington title.

The car is finished in two-tone blue with black running board covers and chrome accents. There is a crack atop the left-rear quarter panel running into the rumble-seat seam. Other paint chips and imperfections are pictured in the gallery below, and bubbling is noted at the lower leading edge of each rear fender.

The car rides on transverse leaf springs front and rear, and braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. Black-finished 15″ steel wheels are mounted with Nexen tires measuring 165/80 up front and 215/75 out back. A spare wire wheel is surrounded by a blue-finished cover and mounted to the rear panel.

The interior is trimmed in black cloth upholstery along with coordinated carpets. A B&M floor shifter is installed along with a tilting steering column and an aftermarket wiring harness with a blade-style fuse panel.
The rumble seat is trimmed in blue vinyl upholstery.

Stewart-Warner instrumentation consists of a 120-mph speedometer flanked by gauges for amps, water temperature, oil pressure, and fuel level. A clock and a transmission-temperature gauge are mounted below the dash. The five-digit odometer shows 16k miles. True mileage is unknown.

The 350ci Chevrolet V8 features an Edelbrock four-barrel carburetor, aluminum intake manifold, and Performer RPM aluminum cylinder heads. A Mallory distributor and ignition coil are installed, and coated headers feed into a dual exhaust system with side outlets ahead of each rear wheel.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission and a 12-bolt rear axle.
The car is titled in Washington using the assigned identification number 181574190. The Washington title carries an Antique brand.

This 2019 Land Rover Range Rover Supercharged is a long-wheelbase example that is finished in Byron Blue Metallic over Navy leather and is powered by a supercharged 5.0-liter V8 linked with an eight-speed automatic transmission and a two-speed electronically controlled transfer case. Features include LED headlights, a panoramic sunroof, 22″ alloy wheels, electronic air suspension, heated and ventilated front seats, heated and reclining outboard rear seats, multi-zone climate control, a Meridian sound system, and touchscreen infotainment with navigation. The truck was first registered in Florida and remained in the state until it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. This Range Rover Supercharged LWB has 35k miles and is now offered by the selling dealer in Wisconsin with a clean Carfax report and a clean Florida title.

The truck is finished in Byron Blue Metallic with a color-matched roof, and exterior features include a panoramic sunroof, LED headlights, rain-sensing windshield wipers, heated power-adjustable auto-dimming mirrors, front and rear parking sensors, dual exhaust outlets, and a power-operated tailgate. Photos of blemishes can be viewed in the gallery below.

Split-Spoke 22″ alloy wheels are mounted with 275/40 Pirelli Scorpion Verde All Season tires. Equipment includes an electronic air suspension with variable ride height as well as selectable Terrain Response driving modes, Adaptive Dynamics stability control, Hill Descent Control (HDC), and Electronic Traction Control (ETC).

The heated and ventilated power-adjustable front seats are upholstered in Navy leather, and Ivory leather and wood trim accent the cabin. Amenities include multi-zone automatic climate control, a Meridian surround sound system, and a 10″ touchscreen infotainment system with navigation.
Long-wheelbase models feature an additional 7.3″ of interior floorspace, and the rear cabin is equipped with power-operated sunshades as well as heated and reclining outboard seats.

The heated wood- and leather-trimmed steering wheel has paddle shifters and frames a digital instrument cluster with an 8k-rpm tachometer and a 180-mph speedometer. The digital odometer indicates 35k miles.

The supercharged 5.0-liter V8 was factory rated at 518 horsepower and 461 lb-ft of torque. Power is sent to all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission and a two-speed electronically controlled transfer case.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1957 BMW 300 was acquired by the seller in 2023 and was subsequently refurbished, including a repaint, a refresh of the interior, and replacement of the canvas top, electrical wiring, and tires. The car is powered by a 298cc single paired with a four-speed manual transaxle and is finished in red with a white roof over beige vinyl. Features include 10″ steel wheels, a parcel rack, a driver-side mirror, chrome-finished nerf bars, sliding side windows, storage pockets, and a rear parcel shelf. This Isetta is now offered with an owner’s manual, service records, a car cover, and a clean Michigan title in the seller’s name.

The car was repainted red with a white roof following the completion of metal repairs in 2024. The windshield wiper motor was rebuilt and a replacement white folding canvas roof was also installed at at that time along with a replacement door seal and hinges, engine cover seal, and headlights. Additional features include a vented door, a parcel rack, chrome-finished nerf bars, sliding side windows, and a driver-side mirror.

The 10″ steel wheels wear chrome hubcaps and were mounted with 145R10 Dunlop SP175 tires under current ownership. The Isetta features a coil-spring suspension up front and leaf springs out back, and stopping power is provided by hydraulically actuated drum brakes.

The cabin is accessed through a front-opening side-hinged door and features a bench seat that was re-trimmed in beige vinyl under current ownership along with storage pockets and a rear parcel shelf. The horn is inoperative.

The steering wheel is mounted on a hinged column and frames a dash pod with a reverse-sweep 60-mph speedometer as well as a shifter on the left. The five-digit odometer shows 21k miles, approximately 30 of which were added under current ownership.

The air-cooled 298cc single is accessed via a panel on the right side of the car and was factory rated at 13 horsepower. Work under current ownership included replacing electrical wiring and rebuilding the Dynastart system.
Power is routed to the rear wheels via a four-speed manual transaxle.
Photos from the repaint can be seen in the gallery.

This 1970 Alfa Romeo 1750 Spider Veloce is a late-run Series I example that was built to US-market specification and then delivered new to Frankfurt, Germany, in May 1970. The car was subsequently brought to the US and spent time in Ohio, where it underwent a multi-year refurbishment by Wedgewood Sports & Imports from 2011 to 2019. Work at that time involved a repaint, suspension and brake overhauls, and rebuilds of the 1.8L twin-cam inline-four and five-speed manual transmission, and a subsequent interior re-trim was carried out in 2023 prior to the current owner’s acquisition. The car is finished in red over tan leather upholstery and wears Carello headlamp covers as well as a Haartz black convertible top and a black vinyl top boot. The engine is fitted with dual Weber DCOE carburetors along with International Auto Parts (IAP) performance camshafts, and further equipment includes KYB shocks, Centerline springs, and 14″ GTA-style alloy wheels. This boat-tail Spider Veloce is now offered on dealer consignment with 2013 correspondence from Automobilismo Storico Centro Documentazione, refurbishment records, and a clean Wisconsin title listing the car as a 1969 model.

The Pininfarina-designed bodywork is said to have been stripped and repainted in red as part of the aforementioned refurbishment. Replacement Carello headlamp covers have been added, and a Haartz black convertible top is paired with a black vinyl top boot. Further details include dual side mirrors, split stainless-steel bumpers, and a single polished exhaust outlet.

The 14″ GTA-style alloy wheels are mounted with 195/65 Vredestein Sportrac 5 Giugiaro Design tires, and a steel spare with an older Goodyear tire is stored in the trunk. The car rides on KYB shocks and Centerline springs and braking is handled by four-wheel discs. Suspension and brake work performed at the time of the refurbishment involved replacing various bushings and rebuilding the brake calipers.

The reupholstered cabin houses a pair of bucket seats trimmed in tan leather accompanied by color-coordinated door panels. A Pininfarina radio blanking plate adorns the dash, and further appointments include a heater, a lockable glovebox, and Alfa Romeo–branded carpeted floor mats.

The wood-rimmed Nardi steering wheel fronts a Jaeger 140-mph speedometer and 8k-rpm tachometer, while a trio of gauges for fuel level, oil pressure, and coolant temperature are located in the center of the dash. The five-digit odometer shows 96k miles. The speedometer was repaired in July 2012, and true mileage is unknown.

The 1.8L twin-cam inline-four sends power to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission, both of which were rebuilt as part of the aforementioned refurbishment. The engine is equipped with dual Weber DCOE  carburetors along with a red-finished cam cover and International Auto Parts (IAP) performance camshafts. A replacement clutch kit was also installed at the time of the engine work.
The underbody of the car is said to have been refinished, and additional underside images are presented in the gallery below.

January 2013 correspondence from Marco Fazio at Automobilismo Storico Centro Documentazione lists factory colors as well as a May 1970 build date. Refurbishment and service records are presented in the gallery below.

This 2005 Mercedes-Benz S55 AMG remained registered to its original owner until 2021 and was acquired by the current owner on BaT in July 2021. It is powered by a supercharged 5.4-liter V8 paired with a five-speed automatic transmission and is finished in Pewter Metallic over Charcoal leather. Equipment includes a sunroof, 18″ AMG double-spoke wheels, bi-xenon headlights, parking sensors, Keyless Go, COMAND with navigation, a Bose sound system, and heated and ventilated multicontour front seats. This W220 S55 AMG has 35k miles and is offered in California by the seller on behalf of the current owner with a clean Carfax report and a clean Nevada title in the owner’s name.

The S55 AMG featured deeper front and rear valances and sill extensions when compared with the standard W220, and this example is finished in Pewter Metallic (723). Equipment includes bi-xenon headlights with heated washers along with a sunroof, door and trunk closing assist, auto-dimming side-view mirrors with integrated signal lighting, front and rear parking sensors, and an AMG Sport exhaust system with quad outlets. Blemishes are visible on the lower front valance.

The 18″ AMG double-spoke wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires measuring 245/45 up front and 265/40 out back. The car is equipped with an Active Body Control (ABC) suspension and AMG-branded multi-piston calipers over cross-drilled brake rotors at all four corners.

The cabin is trimmed in Charcoal leather completed by Burl Walnut trim on the dashboard, center console, and door panels. Amenities include heated and ventilated Drive-Dynamic multicontour front seats along with dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, an electric rear window shade, rear door sunshades, Keyless Go, a Bose sound system, and COMAND infotainment with navigation.

The multifunction steering wheel features gearshift buttons and frames a 200-mph speedometer, an AMG-branded 7k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 35k miles, approximately 12k of which were added under current ownership.
The supercharged 5.4-liter V8 was factory rated at 493 horsepower and 516 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1992 Volkswagen Cabriolet is a Wolfsburg Edition example that is finished in Pearlcolor Green Pearl over white leather upholstery and is powered by a 1.8-liter inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes a white convertible top, a top boot, a roll bar, power-assisted front disc brakes, 15″ aftermarket wheels, an aftermarket head unit with Bluetooth connectivity, power windows, and air conditioning. Acquired by the selling dealer in July 2024, this Cabriolet shows 99k miles and is offered at no reserve with a spare set of wheels, a clean Carfax report, and a Pennsylvania title.

The car is finished in Pearlcolor Green Pearl (LC6V) and features a white soft top with a heated rear glass window as well as a top boot, a black roll bar, round headlights, Wolfsburg Edition badges, and dual remote-controlled side mirrors. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

The 15″ aftermarket wheels are mounted with Hankook Ventus tires. The car was factory-equipped with an independent suspension, and braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums. A spare set of wheels will accompany the sale, photos of which are provided in the gallery below.

The front sport seats and the contoured rear seats are upholstered in white leather, and appointments include air conditioning, power windows, and an aftermarket head unit with Bluetooth connectivity.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a 120-mph speedometer, a 7k-rpm tachometer, a digital clock, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. Auxiliary gauges for voltage, oil pressure, and oil temperature are mounted in the center console. The six-digit odometer shows 99k miles.
The transverse-mounted 1.8-liter inline-four was factory-rated at 94 horsepower and 100 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
Power is routed to the front wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
The Pennsylvania title carries an “Antique” brand.
listing_details: White Convertible Top w/Top Boot Cover

description: This 2002 Chevrolet Silverado 2500HD LT 4×4 pickup has 55k miles and is powered by a 6.6-liter Duramax turbodiesel V8 linked to a five-speed automatic transmission and a push-button dual-range transfer case. The truck is finished in Pewter Metallic over Pewter leather, and in April 2024 a repaint was performed and the front seats were reupholstered. Additional equipment includes a locking rear differential, fog lights, front tow hooks, power-adjustable heated side mirrors, side steps, a tonneau cover, a bed liner, a receiver hitch, 16″ 10-hole polished aluminum wheels, power-adjustable front bucket seats, a CD stereo, cruise control, and air conditioning. This GMT800 Silverado 2500HD is now offered with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Arizona title in the seller’s name.

The truck was finished from the factory in Pewter Metallic and received a repaint in April 2024 that was performed by Watson Chevrolet of Tuscon, Arizona, at which time the lights, emblems, and decals were replaced. Exterior features include 4×4 decals, fog lights, front tow hooks, fender flares, side steps, a body-color tonneau cover, a bed liner, a receiver hitch, and a drop-down tailgate. The left side mirror is cracked and the rear bumper is dented.
Eight-lug 16″ 10-hole polished aluminum wheels are mounted with 245/75 IronMan All Country tires. Stopping power is provided by anti-lock disc brakes at all four corners.

The cabin features seating surfaces upholstered in Pewter leather, and interior amenities include power-adjustable front bucket seats, cruise control, air conditioning, and a CD stereo. The front seats were reupholstered in April 2024. Portions of the headliner show cracks and wear.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer, a 5k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for transmission fluid temperature, fuel level, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and voltage. The digital odometer indicates 55k miles, approximately 500 of which were added under current ownership.
The 6.6-liter Duramax turbodiesel V8 was factory rated at 300 horsepower and 520 lb-ft of torque.
Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels via a five-speed automatic transmission, a push-button dual-range transfer case, and a locking rear differential.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1968 Suzuki TC250 X-6 Scrambler is powered by a 247cc two-stroke parallel twin mated to a six-speed transmission, and it was repainted in metallic blue and silver as part of a refurbishment that took place in 2015. The bike is equipped with a kick starter, a pair of 24mm Mikuni carburetors, Suzuki’s Posi-Force lubrication system, and a chrome-finished two-into-two exhaust system with perforated heat shields as well as 18″ wire-spoke wheels, drum brakes, a friction-type steering damper, a black vinyl two-up seat, and both center and side stands. The seller acquired the bike in 2022, and work in 2024 has included flushing the fuel system, rebuilding the petcock and oil pump, cleaning and synchronizing the carburetors, and replacing the battery, spark plugs, control cables, and tires. This TC250 is now offered at no reserve with an owner’s manual, a service guide, a tool kit, and a clean Texas title in the seller’s name.

The 3.7-gallon fuel tank, fenders, and side covers were refinished in metallic blue and silver as part of the aforementioned 2015 refurbishment. Chrome side panels with rubber knee grips accent the fuel tank, and additional details include a black vinyl two-up seat, a grab strap, a chrome-rimmed headlight bucket, folding passenger foot pegs, and both center and side stands. Decals have been applied to the rear fender just behind the seat, and blemishes on various body panels are identified by the seller in a video provided in the gallery.

Wire-spoke wheels with 18″ chrome-finished rims were mounted with Duro tires and replacement inner tubes in 2024. Braking is handled by drums at both ends, and suspension consists of a conventional telescopic fork with black accordion gaiters as well as a pair of chrome-housed shocks mounted to the swingarm. The fork oil was changed in 2024.

The chrome cross-braced handlebar carries a single round mirror on the left and is situated just ahead of the adjustment knob for the friction-type steering damper. Instrumentation housed in the headlight bucket consists of a 120-mph speedometer and a tachometer with an 8k-rpm redline. The vertical five-digit odometer shows 4k miles, approximately 500 of which were ridden by the seller. The cables for the throttle, clutch, and front brake were replaced in 2024.

The 247cc two-stroke parallel twin features Suzuki’s Posi-Force lubrication system as well as a kick starter, a pair of 24mm Mikuni carburetors, and a chrome-finished two-into-two exhaust system with perforated heat shields. Factory-rated output was 29 horsepower and 20 lb-ft of torque. Work completed since the beginning of 2024 has included flushing the fuel tank, adjusting the timing, rebuilding the petcock and oil pump, and cleaning and synchronizing the carburetors as well as replacing the battery, spark plugs, and fuel lines.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a six-speed constant-mesh transmission and a drive chain. The transmission received a fluid change in 2024.
A tool kit, an owner’s manual, and a service guide will accompany the motorcycle.
The Texas title lists the model year as 1969 and also lists “VIN Certification Waived” under the “Remarks” heading.
listing_details: Black Vinyl Two-Up Seat w/Grab Strap

description: This 2008 Airstream 27′ FB Safari travel trailer is a Special Edition model that was purchased new by the current owner in 2007. The floor plan features a rear lounge area, a kitchenette, a dinette, a bathroom, and a front bedroom with a queen bed. Additional equipment includes an awning, an air conditioner, a ducted furnace, panoramic windows, window shades and curtains, a Sony flatscreen television, and 15″ alloy wheels. This Safari SE is now offered by the seller on behalf of the owner with a clean Carfax report and a clean Texas title in the owner’s name.

The trailer measures 28’0″ long overall and has an aluminum body, a Zip Dee camp-side awning, and front stone guards. Additional details consist of an outdoor shower connection, an extended rear bumper with integrated storage, a retractable boarding step, and connections for electrical service, fresh water, and waste disposal.

Dual axles are fitted with 15″ alloy wheels that wear 225/75 Goodyear Marathon trailer tires, while a spare is secured underneath. The trailer has a 7,600-pound gross vehicle weight rating and is equipped with a 39-gallon freshwater tank, a 37-gallon gray-water tank, and a 39-gallon black tank as well as a house battery, two propane cylinders in a tongue-mounted enclosure, and a power-operated tongue jack.

The interior is outfitted with mosaic-pattern vinyl flooring, woodgrain cabinetry, curtains and privacy shades, halogen lighting, a ducted furnace, and a Dometic Duo-Therm Penguin air conditioner. The dinette has wraparound windows along with beige cloth bench seating that can be converted to a sleeping surface. Other amenities in the lounge area include a 5.5′ sofa, a Sony flatscreen TV, a CD stereo, and Vista View skylight windows.

The kitchenette is equipped with a composite countertop, a stainless-steel sink, an Amana three-burner propane range, and an exhaust hood. A Dometic refrigerator/freezer is located on the opposite wall, and additional features include overhead cabinets, under-counter storage, a water heater, and a residential-style 120-volt power outlet.

The forward bedroom is furnished with a queen bed, built-in nightstands, under-bed storage compartments, a ceiling vent, and panoramic windows with privacy curtains. The adjacent bathroom features a vanity with a composite countertop, a mirror, a stainless-steel sink, and a toilet, while a separate shower room is located across the hallway.
The chassis is equipped with four stabilizer jacks. Additional underbody photos can be viewed in the gallery below.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists events in Texas beginning in 2011.

This 2001 Ford Mustang GT coupe is one of 5,582 Bullitt cars produced for the model year and is powered by a 4.6-liter V8 paired with a five-speed manual transmission. The car is finished in Dark Highland Green over Dark Charcoal leather and features a limited-slip differential, a C&L Performance air-intake system, 17″ Premium aluminum wheels, Brembo front brakes, a hood scoop, a rear spoiler, remote keyless entry, and cruise control. The car has spent time in Missouri and Illinois and now has 76k miles. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this New Edge Mustang is now offered in Wisconsin at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a clean Illinois title.

The car is finished in Dark Highland Green, and features include a hood scoop, a brushed-aluminum fuel-filler door, fog lights, Bullitt badging, power-adjustable side mirrors, polished dual exhaust outlets, and a Mustang script-debossed rear bumper cover. The trunk lid struts were replaced in preparation for the sale. Stone chips are visible on the nose and scratches are visible on the rear bumper cover near the passenger-side tailpipe.

The two-tone 17″ five-spoke Premium aluminum wheels are mounted with older 255/45 Continental DWS Tuned tires. Stopping power is provided by red-finished calipers fitted over 13″ Brembo front rotors and 11.6″ rear rotors with ABS. Bullitt-specific equipment includes re-valved Tokico struts and shocks, revised front and rear stabilizer bars, and a 3/4″ lower ride height when compared to the contemporary SN95. The car is equipped with traction control.

The articulated front sport seats and split-folding rear seats are trimmed in Dark Charcoal leather with perforated inserts. Amenities include a rear window defroster, remote keyless entry, air conditioning, cruise control, power accessories, metal pedal covers, and an in-dash CD changer.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 150-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, coolant temperature, voltage, and oil pressure. The digital odometer indicates 76k miles.

The 4.6-liter SOHC V8 was factory rated at 260 horsepower and 302 lb-ft of torque and is modified with a C&L Performance air-intake system. Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a Traction-Lok limited-slip differential. The selling dealer states that the crankshaft position sensor, drive belt, and battery were replaced in preparation for the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1950 Willys-Overland Jeepster was modified under prior ownership with custom bodywork, a removable hardtop, and a body-color tonneau cover along with a fuel-injected 350ci V8 and a five-speed manual transmission. The truck is finished in metallic blue and rides on Mustang II-style independent front suspension, rear airbags, and staggered-diameter Cragar SS wheels. The interior houses two-tone bucket seats along with a custom dash and center console, a CD stereo, and gauges sourced from a Pontiac Trans Am. Service completed in 2023 included replacing the fuel tank and clutch assembly. This modified Jeepster is now offered by the selling dealer in Idaho with service records and a Washington title.

The vehicle features custom bodywork finished in metallic blue, including a rear roll pan, shaved door handles, and body-color molded fenders and running boards. A firewall was added behind the front seats, and the rear cargo area is topped with a body-color tonneau cover. Rectangular headlights and teardrop taillights were also installed along with a custom grille, wind wings, aftermarket mirrors, and a removable hardtop. Exhaust outlets exit ahead of each rear wheel. Scratches are shown up close in the gallery.

The 14″ front and 15″ rear Cragar SS wheels feature faux-knockoffs and are wrapped in BFGoodrich Radial T/A tires measuring 205/70 and 255/70 respectively. The Mustang II-style independent front suspension incorporates disc brakes, while the rear end features airbags and drums. Maintenance on the rear brakes included replacing the wheel cylinders, shoes, and drums in 2023. The brake fluid was also flushed.

The bucket seats are trimmed in blue vinyl and cloth, and the cabin features fabric door panels, matching carpets, and a custom body-color dash and center console. Amenities include a Sony CD stereo, aftermarket pedals, and a locking glove box. The vehicle is not equipped with seat belts or side windows.

The three-spoke steering wheel frames instrumentation sourced from a Pontiac Trans Am, including a 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary gauges. The six-digit odometer shows 1k miles, and total chassis mileage is unknown.

The fuel-injected 350ci V8 was installed during the build and features finned valve covers, a chrome alternator, and an exhaust system with dual glasspack mufflers. The fuel tank and fuel level sending unit were replaced in 2023, at which time the spark plugs, wires, and the distributor cap and rotor were also replaced.
Power is delivered to the rear wheels via a five-speed manual transmission and a 4.10:1 rear end. Work in 2023 involved replacing the clutch assembly and machining the flywheel.
The truck is titled using the Arizona Assigned Identification Number shown above. The Washington title lists “Antique” under the brands section.

This 1988 Toyota Pickup is a 4×4 example that was purchased in 2017 by the seller who subsequently rebuilt the fuel-injected 2.4L inline-four and installed an L.C. Engineering Pro Torquer camshaft, rocker assembly, and a dual-row timing chain. Repainted green with black Corbeau bucket Seats, the truck features a five-speed manual transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and manually locking front hubs. Additional equipment includes 16″ Toyota wheels, front disc brakes, a tubular rear bumper, a LineX bedliner, a receiver hitch, air conditioning, and an aftermarket stereo. This Toyota pickup is offered with manufacturer’s literature, service records, and a clean Arizona title in the seller’s name.

The truck was repainted green in 2019 and it features a tubular rear bumper. Additional exterior details include a sunroof, a LineX bedliner, and a receiver hitch. A July 2019 entry on the Carfax report lists “minor damage” with no additional information. The right A-pillar is damaged.
Black-finished 16″ wheels are mounted with 245/75 Cooper Discoverer tires. The truck is equipped with manually locking front hubs, and braking is handled by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.
The cabin features Corbeau bucket seats trimmed in black upholstery, and amenities include air conditioning, a fabricated center console with integrated cup holders, and an aftermarket head unit.

The aftermarket three-spoke steering wheel frames a 110-mph speedometer and auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 278k miles, approximately 30k of which were added under current ownership.

The fuel-injected 2.4L 22R-E inline-four was factory-rated at 116 horsepower and 140 lb-ft of torque. The engine was rebuilt in 2017 with an L.C. Engineering Pro Torquer camshaft, rocker assembly, and a dual-row timing chain, and additional work at that time included replacing the water pump, engine mount, spark plugs, thermostat, and coolant hoses. The emissions equipment has been removed and an aftermarket exhaust system and headers have been added.

Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Additional photos showing the undercarriage are provided in the image gallery below.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned July 2019 damage.

This 2016 Ford Mustang Shelby GT350 was purchased new by the current owner at Ford and Lincoln of Smithtown in Saint James, New York, and was subsequently modified with a Whipple supercharger, an ECU tune, aftermarket exhaust, a short-throw shifter, a carbon-fiber driveshaft, and a McCleod Racing clutch. Now with 9k miles, it is finished in Avalanche Gray with black racing stripes over Ebony cloth and Miko suede and powered by a 5.2-liter Voodoo V8 linked with a six-speed manual transmission and a Torsen limited-slip differential. Equipment includes the Track Package, 19″ multi-spoke black wheels, Brembo brake calipers, a rear spoiler, a rearview camera, and Recaro seats. This GT350 is now offered on dealer consignment with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a GT350 ownership box, service records, spare parts, a car cover, a damage-free Carfax report, and a clean New York title in the owner’s name.

The car is finished in Avalanche Gray with optional over-the-top black racing stripes and features HID projector headlights, functional hood and fender vents, a front splitter with the Shelby logo, LED taillights with sequential turn signals, and quad exhaust outlets. The Track Package also added a larger rear trunk spoiler.

The black 19″ multi-spoke wheels are mounted with 295/35 Michelin Pilot Sport 4 S tires in front and 305/35 Mickey Thompson E/T Street S/S tires out back. The car is equipped with six-piston front and four-piston rear Brembo brake calipers. The Track Package added MagneRide magnetically adjusted dampers and performance-tuned front springs.

The cabin features Recaro sport seats trimmed in Ebony cloth and Miko suede along with color-coordinated door panels and carpets. Equipment includes an aftermarket short-throw shifter with a red shift knob as well as a rearview camera, cruise control, air conditioning, and a CD stereo.
The passenger-side dashboard plaque designates this GT350 as chassis G0267.

The Alcantara-wrapped steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer, a tachometer with an 8,250-rpm redline, auxiliary gauges, and a central multi-function digital display. Additional gauges for oil pressure and oil temperature are mounted in the center stack. The digital odometer indicates 9k miles, all of which were added under current ownership.

The 5.2-liter Voodoo V8 features a flat-plane crankshaft and has been modified with a Whipple supercharger, an ECU tune, and aftermarket tubular headers, catalytic converters, and X-pipe crossover exhaust. A commemorative plaque displays the signature of the engine builder, and the car was optioned with the Track Package which includes additional coolers for the engine, transmission, and differential.

Power is sent to the rear wheels via a Tremec TR-3160 six-speed manual transmission and a 3.73:1 Torsen limited-slip differential. Modifications consist of a McCleod Racing clutch, a carbon-fiber driveshaft, and aftermarket rear axles.
The window sticker shows initial delivery to Ford and Lincoln of Smithtown in Saint James, New York, and lists factory equipment, colors, and a total MSRP of $58,040.
Accompanying the car is a GT350 ownership box, manufacturer’s literature, a car cover, a handheld ECU tuner, and spare parts.
The Carfax report lists one open manufacturer recall.
The New York title is listed as a duplicate.

This 2010 Toyota FJ Cruiser is finished in Sun Fusion with a white roof over Dark Charcoal cloth and now has 36k miles. Powered by a 4.0-liter V6 linked with a five-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a locking rear differential, the truck is further equipped with the Off-Road and Convenience Packages, Active Traction Control, 17″ alloy wheels, Bilstein shock absorbers, a roof rack, and a rearview camera in addition to air conditioning, cruise control, and an aftermarket touchscreen head unit. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this FJ Cruiser is now offered at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a clean Gerogia title.

The truck is finished in Sun Fusion with a white roof and features black bumper covers with metallic silver trim. Additional details include a roof rack, running boards, a rear window wiper, and black fender flares with integrated mudguards. Photos in the gallery show body panel VIN decals and paint meter readings.

The 17″ alloy wheels are mounted with 285/70 BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A KO2 tires, and a covered spare is mounted to the swing-away tailgate. The truck is equipped with TRD Bilstein shock absorbers as well as Vehicle Stability Control and Active Traction Control.

The manually adjustable front bucket seats and a 60/40-split folding rear bench are upholstered in Dark Charcoal cloth with gray inserts. An aftermarket touchscreen head unit with USB connectivity has been retrofitted, and additional appointments include air conditioning, cruise control, a rearview camera, and power windows and locks.

Instrumentation includes a 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer with a 5,500-rpm redline, and auxiliary gauges for voltage, coolant temperature, and fuel level. A dash-mounted gauge pod houses a compass, an outside air temperature indicator, and an inclinometer. The digital odometer indicates 36k miles.
The 4.0-liter 1GR-FE V6 was factory rated at 258 horsepower and 270 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was carried out in January 2024.
Power is routed to the rear or all four wheels through a five-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a locking rear differential.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1998 Chevrolet K2500 Suburban LT was initially delivered to Byers Chevrolet of Columbus, Ohio, and now has 321 miles. The truck is finished in Victory Red over gray leather and is powered by a 7.4-liter V8 linked to a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Features include a locking rear differential, roof rails, running boards, a receiver hitch, bucket front seats, a CD stereo, cruise control, and front- and rear-cabin air conditioning. The selling dealer acquired the truck in 2024. This Suburban is now offered with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean Pennsylvania title.
The exterior is finished in Victory Red and features a tailgate, tinted windows, roof rails, running boards, a receiver hitch, and a hood guard.
The 16″ Alcoa eight-bolt wheels are mounted with 265/75 Goodyear Wrangler AT/S tires. Stopping power is provided by anti-lock front disc and rear drum brakes.

The cabin features seating surfaces trimmed in gray leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. Interior amenities include front bucket seats, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, folding second- and third-row bench seats, a CD stereo, cruise control, and air conditioning. Plastic covers adorn the seats.

The tilting four-spoke airbag steering wheel frames a 100-mph speedometer, a 6k-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for fuel level, voltage, oil pressure, and coolant temperature. The six-digit odometer shows 321 miles. An April 2010 Carfax report entry notes the mileage at 100k.
The 7.4-liter Vortec V8 was factory rated at 290 horsepower and 410 lb-ft of torque.

Power is sent to the rear or all four wheels through four-speed automatic transmission, a locking rear differential, and a dual-range transfer case. The truck was optioned with heavy-duty trailering equipment and a heavy-duty transmission cooler.

The window sticker shows initial delivery to Byers Chevrolet of Columbus, Ohio, and lists factory colors, options, and a total vehicle price of $42,148.95. Factory literature, brochures, and supplementary literature are also included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage and lists at least one open recall.

This 1954 Chevrolet Corvette is the 2,101st of 3,640 examples produced for the model year, and it reportedly spent four decades in storage before being purchased by the seller in February 2024. The 235ci inline-six was subsequently serviced and started, according to the seller, and it is mated to a replacement three-speed manual transmission. A damaged black removable hardtop will accompany the car, and a worn black soft top remains along with bucket seats upholstered in black vinyl. This C1 Corvette is now offered as a running project with a clean Michigan title in the seller’s name.

The fiberglass body wears worn and cracked red paint, which was applied at some point under prior ownership. The headlight covers are missing. The black soft top remains, but is worn and damaged. The included black hardtop has damage and wear, and the rear window is broken. A portion of the left-front fender has broken off the car, and the damaged corner piece will accompany the car.

Steel 15” wheels wear polished covers with faux knock-off spinners and are mounted with a mixed set of worn and cracked tires. The C1 was equipped from the factory with an independent front suspension, front and rear hydraulic shocks, a live rear axle with semi-elliptical leaf springs, and four-wheel drum brakes. Condition of the braking system is unknown.

The bucket seats are faired into the rear bodywork, and they are trimmed in black and complemented by a color-coordinated dash pad and door panels. The carpeting has been removed, the dashtop is cracked, and pitting and wear are noted on the dashboard trim and the AM radio.

The worn and cracked two-spoke steering wheel frames a 140-mph speedometer. A central 5k-rpm tachometer is flanked by gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, amperage, and fuel level. The five-digit odometer shows 96k miles.

The 235ci “Blue Flame” inline-six was factory equipped with three Carter YH side-draft carburetors and was converted to a single two-barrel setup under prior ownership. The seller states work was performed to get the engine started in preparation for the sale.

Power is routed to the rear wheels via a three-speed manual transmission, which was installed in place of the automatic transmission under prior ownership. The dual exhaust system has been cut behind the mufflers.

This 2019 BMW R1250GS Adventure HP is finished in blue, white, and red, and it was purchased by the seller on BaT in April 2023. The bike is powered by a liquid-cooled 1,254cc DOHC opposed-twin that is mated to a six-speed gearbox, a quick-shifter, and an enclosed driveshaft. Optioned with a factory alarm and lowered suspension along with the Premium and Option 719 Billet packages, it is equipped with gold-anodized alloy rims, triple disc brakes, a Telelever front end, and a Paralever rear end as well as a clear windshield, two-piece seating, a TFT multifunction display, aluminum box-style panniers, an aluminum skid plate, and a stainless-steel rear rack. The factory ECU tune was restored under current ownership, and the odometer now indicates 5k miles. This R1250GS is offered with owner’s manuals, a copy of the dealer pricing sheet, a BMW GPS navigation unit, oil-change supplies, and a clean Texas title in the seller’s name.

The bike is finished in Racing Blue Metallic, Light White, and N2E Racing Red and features a matte black cockpit trim panel as well as stepped, two-piece, and adjustable-height seating in black. Equipment includes a slipstream deflector, an adjustable clear windshield, LED auxiliary lights, an eight-gallon aluminum fuel tank, a polished stainless-steel rear rack, front protection bars, an aluminum skid plate, both center and side stands, and Motorrad aluminum-box panniers to which Xpel paint protection film has been applied. The Option 719 milled-parts package added silver-anodized aluminum components consisting of covers for the cylinder heads, ignition coil, front engine housing, and expansion tank as well as the hand levers, foot pegs, brake pedal, shift lever, oil-filler plug, and mirrors. There are scratches on the right-side engine guard, and most of the gallery photos and videos were shot in February 2024.

Wire-spoke wheels with rim-edge spoking and gold-anodized alloy rims measure 19″ up front and 17″ at the rear, and they are wrapped in Bridgestone Battlax Adventure A41 dual sport tires. Optional factory-lowered suspension is provided by a Telelever fork with a hydraulic steering damper as well as an adjustable ZF monoshock mounted to a Paralever single-sided cast-aluminum swingarm. Braking is from dual 305mm front discs and a single 276mm rear disc.

The black-finished double-butted alloy handlebar carries heated grips and white plastic hand guards. The 6.5″ TFT color display ahead shows a speedometer, a tachometer, and auxiliary information, and it has Bluetooth media and telephone connectivity. On-screen functions are managed through a multi-controller located inboard of the left hand grip. Additional features include Rain and Road modes, Hill Start Control, switchable ABS, and switchable Automatic Stability Control. The motorcycle was optioned with a factory alarm system, and a BMW Motorrad GPS navigation unit will accompany the motorcycle. The digital odometer indicates 5k miles, approximately 4k of which were ridden under current ownership. The service-due message has been showing since April 2024.

The liquid-cooled 1,254cc DOHC opposed twin was factory rated at 136 horsepower and features ShiftCam variable valve timing, electronic throttle valve control, and a stainless-steel exhaust system. The battery was replaced in March 2023, the oil was most recently changed the following month, and a previously flashed ECU tune was replaced with the stock tune under current ownership.
Power is sent to the rear wheel via a hydraulically operated clutch, a six-speed gearbox, and an enclosed driveshaft, supplemented by the Dynamic package’s Gear Shift Assistant Pro quick-shifter.
The copy of the BMW dealer pricing sheet lists initial delivery to BMW Motorcycles of Escondido in California, factory colors and equipment, and a total suggested retail price of $28,010.

This 2017 BMW M2 was initially delivered to BMW of Greenwich, Connecticut, and was subsequently fitted with carbon-fiber exterior trim, an M Performance steering wheel, and Dinan modifications consisting of a turbocharger, intercooler, ECU tune, intake, exhaust, and coilover suspension. The car is finished in Alpine White over black Dakota leather, and power comes from a turbocharged 3.0-liter inline-six paired with a six-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes the Executive Package, an Active M limited-slip differential, 19″ Style 437M wheels, xenon headlights, Park Distance Control, heated front sport seats, Comfort Access, and iDrive infotainment with navigation, Apple CarPlay, and Harman Kardon audio. The seller purchased the car in 2022 and has since added approximately 31k of the 37k miles. This F87 is now offered with the owner’s manual, service records, a car cover, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Virginia title.

The M2 features bodywork revisions when compared to the contemporary F22 2-Series including flared wheel arches and aerodynamic front and rear bumper covers. This example is finished in Alpine White with Shadowline trim and features a carbon-fiber decklid spoiler, rear diffuser, front grilles, side gills, and mirror covers as well as xenon headlights, a rearview camera, rear Park Distance Control, and quad exhaust outlets. The seller notes damage to the front end was previously repaired as a result of a parking lot incident.

The 19″ Style 437M alloy wheels show curb marks and are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport tires. The car is equipped with Dinan coilover suspension, and braking is handled by blue M-logo calipers mounted over cross-drilled rotors. The adjustable front sway bar end links were replaced in April 2024.

The cabin features seating surfaces upholstered in black Dakota leather with blue stitching, and embossed M2 logos accent the backrests of the heated power-adjustable front sport seats. Amenities include carbon-fiber trim, Comfort Access, a wireless phone charger, a WiFi hotspot, dual-zone automatic climate control, Active Driving Assistant, and an iDrive infotainment system with a Harman Kardon sound system, navigation, and Apple CarPlay.

The M Performance steering wheel frames a 180-mph speedometer, a 7,500-rpm tachometer, and a fuel-level gauge. The digital odometer indicates 37k miles, approximately 31k of which were added under current ownership.

The turbocharged 3.0-liter TwinPower N55B30 inline-six features double-VANOS variable valve timing and Valvetronic variable lift control, and it has reportedly been modified with a Dinan turbocharger, intercooler, carbon fiber intake, and exhaust system as well as a Dinan Stage 2 ECU tune. A coolant exchange and oil change were performed in April 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed manual transmission and an Active M limited-slip differential.
The window sticker shows initial delivery to BMW of Greenwich, Connecticut, and lists factory equipment, colors, and a total suggested retail price of $55,195.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
There is currently a lien on the car, and the seller’s lender will need to be paid off before the title can be transferred to the new owner.

This 1989 Chevrolet K1500 Silverado is a regular-cab Stepside pickup obtained new by a couple in September 1988 from Sexton Chevrolet-Cadillac in Harriman, Tennessee. The truck remained under the care of the original owners until it was acquired by their next-door neighbor and best friend in 2020. The current and third owner, a vehicle collector, purchased the truck in October 2021 and has added approximately 2k of the 16k miles shown. Work under their ownership involved replacing the exhaust system in May 2024. The truck features a Brandywine Metallic finish over Garnet cloth upholstery and is powered by a 5.7-liter V8 linked with a three-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a locking rear differential. Equipment includes a receiver hitch and 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels along with a cassette stereo, cruise control, and air conditioning. This GMT400 pickup is now offered in Texas by the seller on behalf of the current owner with 1988 sales documentation, manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Montana title in the owner’s name.

The truck is finished in Brandywine Metallic with a Stepside bed. It also has a receiver hitch, a sliding rear window, and chrome bumpers. A ceramic coating was applied in 2024, and close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.
The 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with 265/75 Uniroyal Laredo tires. Braking is provided by anti-lock power-assisted front discs and rear drums.
The cabin houses a bench seat upholstered in Garnet cloth. Interior amenities include a cassette stereo, cruise control, power windows, and air conditioning.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames an 85-mph speedometer and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 16k miles, approximately 2k of which were added under current ownership.
The 5.7-liter V8 was factory rated at 210 horsepower and 300 lb-ft of torque. Exhaust components were replaced in March 2024, and an oil change was performed in June 2024.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a three-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a locking rear differential. The transmission fluid and differential fluids were changed in 2023.
Sales documentation from 1988 is included in the sale in addition to manufacturer’s literature viewable in the image gallery below.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 2008 Cadillac DTS is finished in White Diamond Tricoat over Shale leather and is powered by a 4.6-liter V8 paired with a four-speed automatic transaxle. Equipment includes parking sensors, 17″ chrome-finished aluminum wheels, heated and cooled power-adjustable front seats, heated rear seats, navigation, Lane Keep Assist, a six-disc CD changer, cruise control, and tri-zone climate control. The selling dealer acquired the car in 2024 and it now has 51k miles. This DTS is offered at no reserve with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The car is finished in White Diamond Tricoat, and exterior equipment includes xenon headlights, fog lights, heated power-folding side mirrors, parking sensors, quad exhaust outlets, and LED taillights. Touch-up paint has been applied to rock chips around the body. Paint meter readings are shown in the gallery below.

The 17″ nine-spoke chrome-finished aluminum wheels are mounted with 235/55 Uniroyal Tigerpaw tires. The car is equipped with four-wheel independent suspension, Stabilitrak traction control, Magnasteer rack-and-pinion steering, and automatic rear-level control. Stopping power is provided by four-wheel discs. The power steering hose was replaced in June 2024.

The heated and cooled power-adjustable front seats and heated rear bench are upholstered in Shale leather, which extends to the center console lid and door panels. Amenities include navigation, Lane Keep Assist, a six-disc CD changer, cruise control, an electrochromic auto-dimming rearview mirror, and tri-zone climate control.
The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel fronts a 160-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 51k miles.
The 4.6-liter DOHC Northstar V8 was factory rated at 275 horsepower and 295 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was carried out in May 2024 and the air conditioning compressor was replaced in June 2024.
Power is routed to the front wheels through a four-speed automatic transaxle.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
listing_details: Heated and Cooled Power-Adjustable Front Seats

description: This 1965 Ford Mustang fastback was fitted with a 408ci stroker V8 and a Tremec five-speed manual transmission after the seller’s 2020 acquisition. Further equipment includes MSD ignition, a custom aluminum radiator, dual electric fans, underhood bracing, and long-tube headers that flow to a GT350-style side-exit exhaust system, and the car rides on a modified suspension with front coilovers, electric power steering, and a rear leaf spring setup. Black-finished 15″ wheels are mounted over Wilwood front disc brakes. The car wears a black vinyl wrap with an aftermarket hood that features a scoop and retainer pins, and the cabin is equipped with TMI front bucket seats, a Bluetooth stereo, a custom center console, and auxiliary instrumentation. This modified Mustang is now offered with service records and transferable New York registration in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in blue and wears a black vinyl wrap. Details include a fiberglass hood with a scoop and retainer pins along with chrome bumpers, rear window louvers, tinted windows, and front vent windows. A dent in the front-right fender is displayed in the gallery.

Black-finished 15″ wheels are mounted with Dunlop Sport Classic tires. The car rides on a modified suspension with coilovers up front and a Stage 1 leaf spring rear setup. An electric power steering system is installed, and stopping power is provided by front disc brakes and rear drums with Wilwood components.
TMI front bucket seats are trimmed in black vinyl and separated by an aftermarket console with cupholders. Details include a floor shifter, a Bluetooth stereo, and a tilting steering column.

The steering wheel frames a 120-mph speedometer, a column-mounted tachometer, and a fuel-level gauge. Auxiliary readouts are mounted below the dashboard. The five-digit odometer shows 66k miles, approximately 5k of which were added under current ownership. Total mileage is unknown.

The 351ci Windsor V8 is said to have been stroked to displace 408ci, and it is equipped with MSD ignition components, a custom aluminum radiator, dual electric fans, and chrome valve covers. The engine bay was refinished and fitted with an export brace and a Monte Carlo bar.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a T5 five-speed manual transmission with a hydraulic clutch kit. Long-tube headers flow to bullet-style mufflers and a GT350-style side-exit exhaust system.
Photos taken during the build are provided in the gallery.
The car does not have a title, as it is registered in a state that does not issue titles for a vehicle of its age. It is being sold on its transferable New York registration.

This 2009 Mercedes-Benz SL550 has remained registered in California since new and now has 54k miles. The car is finished in Diamond White Metallic over tan Designo leather upholstery and is powered by a 5.5-liter V8 paired with a seven-speed automatic transmission. Equipment includes a power-folding hardtop, a panoramic glass roof, bi-xenon headlights, 20″ multi-spoke wheels, Parktronic, Distronic adaptive cruise control, Keyless Go, heated and ventilated seats, a Harman Kardon sound system, and COMAND with navigation. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this R230 is offered with manufacturer’s literature and a clean California title.

The car is finished in Diamond White Metallic (799) and features a power-folding convertible hardtop, a panoramic glass roof, bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, dual exhaust outlets, and fender air vents. The Carfax report shows undated damage that likely occurred between April 2020 and June 2021, and the selling dealer notes that the rear bumper has been repaired. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

The 20″ multi-spoke wheels are mounted with Falken tires. The car features Active Body Control (ABC) suspension as well as an Electronic Stability Program (ESP) and Automatic Slip Control (ASR). The rear brake pads were replaced in March 2023.

The cabin features heated, ventilated, and massaging multi-contour seats that are upholstered in tan Designo leather. Equipment includes dual-zone automatic climate control, a wind deflector, Parktronic, Distronic adaptive cruise control, Keyless Go, a Harman Kardon sound system, and COMAND with navigation.
The wood-rimmed steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 54k miles.
The 5.5-liter M273 V8 was factory-rated at 382 horsepower and 391 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed automatic transmission.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned undated accident.

This 1986 Porsche 928S is finished in Guards Red over black leather and is powered by a 5.0-liter V8 paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes an aluminum radiator, 16″ seven-hole alloy wheels, a sunroof, a rear spoiler, pop-up headlights, power-adjustable front bucket seats, an Alpine CD stereo, cruise control, and air conditioning. The car was acquired by the seller in December 2022, and subsequent work is said to include replacing the timing belt and the water pump as well as various AC, fuel, and ignition components. This 928S shows 101k miles and it is now offered with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Texas title in the seller’s name.

The car is finished in Guards Red (80K) and features a sunroof, a rear window wiper, a rear spoiler, fog lights, side moldings, and pop-up headlights with washers. The rear window wiper was reportedly repaired under current ownership. The power-adjusting feature of the side mirrors as well as the reversing lights do not work.

The 16″ seven-hole alloy wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport All-Season 4 tires that are said to have been replaced in preparation for the sale. Braking is handled by power-assisted discs at each corner. The seller notes that the axle boots and brake hoses were replaced, a brake service performed, and a power steering leak repaired under current ownership.

The cabin features power-adjustable front bucket seats and folding rear seats trimmed in black leather. The rear seats have been reupholstered and the rear cargo carpet replaced, per the seller. The front seats show signs of wear. Interior appointments include an Alpine CD stereo, aftermarket speakers, cruise control, and air conditioning. The passenger side window motor as well as a scuff plate have reportedly been replaced under current ownership.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 170-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6k-rpm redline as well as auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature, fuel level, oil pressure, and voltage. The six-digit odometer shows 101k miles, approximately 1,200 of which were added under current ownership. The tachometer was repaired in June 2024.

The 5.0-liter V8 was factory rated at 288 horsepower and 302 lb-ft of torque. An aluminum radiator has been installed. Work under current ownership is said to have included replacing the timing belt, water pump, spark plugs, ignition wires, the distributor cap and rotor, and various belts, hoses and lines. The AC compressor, drier, the fan motor, an oxygen sensor, the engine mounts, the hood latch cable, and the battery as well as the fuel pump, relay, the fuel filter, fuel lines, and injectors.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a rear-mounted five-speed manual transaxle.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage. There are multiple gaps in entries.

This 2012 Chevrolet Corvette Grand Sport convertible has 7k miles and is a Centennial Special Edition example produced to commemorate the 100th anniversary of Chevrolet. It is powered by a 6.2-liter LS3 V8 paired with a six-speed automatic gearbox and is finished in Carbon Flash Metallic over Ebony upholstery. Equipment includes a limited-slip differential, the 4LT Premium Equipment Group, 18″ and 19″ satin black alloy wheels, Magnetic Selective Ride Control, a power-retractable black soft top, xenon headlights, navigation, a head-up display, heated power-adjustable seats, a CD stereo, a Bose sound system, and dual-zone automatic climate control. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this C6 Grand Sport is now offered with a recent service invoice, an accident-free Carfax report, and a clean New Jersey title.

All Centennial Special Edition examples were finished in Carbon Flash Metallic and feature 100th Anniversary logos and badging. Additional details include a rear spoiler, a power-retractable black soft top, xenon headlights, fog lights, and polished quad exhaust outlets. The front bumper cover has license plate mounting holes.

The 18″ and 19″ satin black alloy wheels are mounted with staggered-width Michelin tires. The car is equipped with Magnetic Selective Ride Control, and stopping power is handled by four-wheel cross-drilled and ventilated rotors.

The heated power-adjustable bucket seats are upholstered in Ebony leather with microsuede inserts and crossed flags on the headrests. The instrument panel, door panel uppers, and console are trimmed in leather, and additional appointments include a CD stereo, position memory for the driver’s seat, a head-up display, auto-dimming mirrors, a power-adjustable steering column, side airbags, an auto-dimming rear-view mirror, a Bose sound system, Keyless Access, cruise control, and dual-zone automatic climate control. Shrinking in the upholstery is noted on the dashboard, and the seller states the adhesive on the door sill plates is failing.

The three-spoke microsuede-wrapped steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 6,500-rpm redline as well as gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 7k miles.
The 6.2-liter LS3 V8 was factory rated at 430 horsepower and 424 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed and the cabin air filter was replaced in April 2024.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a six-speed automatic gearbox and a 2.73:1 limited-slip differential.
The Carfax report lists at least one open recall.

attributes.value: Corvette Convertible Grand Sport 4LT Centennial Special Edition

description: This Factory Five Racing Mk3 Roadster is a Shelby Cobra replica that was ordered as a kit by the seller in 2005 and subsequently assembled over a multi-year period completed in 2019. It is powered by a side-oiler V8 that has been modified to displace 482ci and mated to a Tremec TKO600 five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. Finished in Guardsman Blue with Wimbledon White stripes over black leather upholstery, the car is equipped with pin-drive 17″ wheels, disc brakes, independent suspension, Edelbrock aluminum cylinder heads, a Comp Cams hydraulic roller camshaft, dual Holley 660-cfm carburetors, MSD ignition, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, a keyed push-button ignition, and a fire extinguisher. Previously offered on BaT in May 2022, this Mk3 Roadster is offered again by the seller with Ontario registration describing the car as a 2005 F5R Kit.

The seller reports that the body edges were rolled and the fender wells were extended before the fiberglass bodywork was finished in Guardsman Blue with Wimbledon White center stripes. Exterior details include polished bumperettes, a hood scoop, fender vents, wind wings, dual side-view mirrors, a single roll hoop, a Le Mans-style fuel filler, and dual side-exit exhaust outlets.

Halibrand-style 17″ wheels are secured with three-eared pin-drive knockoffs and are mounted with BF Goodrich G-Force T/A tires that measure 245/45 up front and 315/35 out back. The car is equipped with four-wheel independent suspension and four-wheel disc brakes with Wilwood calipers, braided stainless hoses, remote fluid reservoirs, and a cockpit-mounted proportioning valve. The seller notes that the tires have less than 500 miles since installed but are approximately 20 years old.

The fixed-back bucket seats are trimmed in black leather and are fitted with Simpson racing harnesses. Additional interior elements include a dashboard-mounted rearview mirror, Wilwood pedals, widened foot boxes, leather door check straps, a keyed push-button ignition, and a fire extinguisher. The seat heaters are inoperative.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel fronts a black upholstered dashboard that houses AutoMeter instrumentation that includes a reverse-sweep 180-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and readouts for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, voltage, and fuel level. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 498 miles, which reflects the distance traveled since the car was assembled.
The seller states that the 427ci V8 was bored and stroked to displace 482ci using a Bear Block Motors FE side-oiler block in addition to the following components:

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Tremec TKO600 five-speed manual transmission reportedly equipped with a Lakewood bell housing and scatter shield, a Ram 11” clutch, and a Torsen limited-slip differential with an aluminum stiffening brace.
The car is registered in Ontario as a 2005 F5R Kit using the chassis stamp F5R100511RD, shown above.

This 1965 Jaguar XKE Series I roadster is a non-running project that was built on November 10, 1964, and it is finished in Pale Primrose over black leather. The car is equipped with a 4.2-liter inline-six, a four-speed manual transmission, a limited-slip differential, a black soft top and boot, enclosed headlights, 15″ wire-spoke steel wheels, power-assisted disc brakes, and a heater. This XKE Series I roadster was acquired by the current owner in 2024 and is now offered at no reserve on dealer consignment with a Jaguar Heritage Trust Certificate, removed parts, and a clean Oregon title.
