The Series I E-Types were equipped with covered headlights and taillights mounted above the chrome rear bumpers. This example came finished from the factory in Pale Primrose, and additional equipment includes a black soft top, a soft top boot, enclosed headlights, a louvered clamshell hood, wraparound chrome bumpers, and dual exhaust outlets. Rust and paint flaking are present throughout the body.
The 15″ wire wheels are secured by two-eared knock-offs and are mounted with older FR70HR15 Dunlop tires. Braking is provided by four-wheel discs with inboard-mounted rear rotors.

The cabin features bucket seats upholstered in black leather along with color-coordinated door panels. The carpets and shift knob have been removed and there are tears in the seats and door panels. An AM radio accompanies the vehicle.

The wood-rimmed steering wheel frames a Smiths 160-mph speedometer and 6k-rpm tachometer, while auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, fuel level, and amperage are located in the center of the dashboard. The five-digit odometer shows 78k miles.

The 4.2-liter inline-six is linked with a four-speed manual gearbox and a limited-slip differential. Three SU carburetors are included in the sale. The engine is not in running condition, and it is unknown when the car was last driven.
The cylinder head stamp reads 7E1616-9.
Additional photos of the underbody are provided in the gallery.
The Jaguar Heritage Trust Production Record Trace certificate shows the original colors and drivetrain numbers as well as the build and dispatch dates.

This 2008 Ford Mustang Roush 428R coupe is one of 200 examples produced for the model year, and it has 14k miles. It is powered by a supercharged 4.6-liter V8 mated to a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential, and it is finished in Vista Blue Metallic with white stripes over black leather. Equipment includes 18″ chrome five-spoke wheels, xenon headlights, fog lights, Roush-specific bodywork, Roush graphics, a hood scoop, quarter-window louvers, a rear spoiler, a lowered suspension, Roush front seats, a short-throw shifter, a Shaker sound system, an in-dash six-disc CD changer, air conditioning, and cruise control. This Roush-modified S197 is now offered with Roush documentation, the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Wisconsin title in the seller’s name.

The bodywork is finished in Vista Blue Metallic (G9) with white racing stripes and Roush graphics, and exterior features include xenon headlights, fog lights, a hood scoop, power-operated side mirrors, and dual exhaust outlets. The Mustang bodywork was revised as part of the Roush conversion including the front fascia, rear wing, and chin spoiler, the latter of which shows imperfections.

The Roush 18″ chrome five-spoke wheels are mounted with Cooper Zeon tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel discs. Handling components have been tuned by Roush, including a lowered suspension with revised front and rear springs and jounce bumpers.

The Roush seats are trimmed in black and gray leather with embroidered Jack Roush signatures. Interior equipment includes a power-adjustable driver’s seat, a short-throw shifter, a spherical shift knob, Roush aluminum pedals and door sill plates, a Shaker sound system, an in-dash six-disc CD changer, air conditioning, and cruise control.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames white Roush gauges including a 144-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary gauges. The digital odometer indicates 14k miles.

The limited-production Roush 428R is differentiated from the 427R by its polished Roush supercharger assembly, which contributes to Roush-rated output of 435 horsepower and 400 lb-ft of torque for the 4.6-liter Modular V8, which also features a Roush intercooler, intake manifold, radiator, and exhaust system as well as a reprogrammed ECM. Fluids services were performed approximately two years ago.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential.
The Roush 428R Certificate of Authenticity lists the VIN and indicates that the car is one of 200 examples converted to Roush 428R specification for the 2008 model year.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or damage.
listing_details: Metallic Blue Paint w/ White Stripes

description: This 2004 Porsche 911 Carrera Targa is finished in Basalt Black Metallic over a Natural Brown leather interior, and it is powered by a 3.6-liter flat-six paired with a six-speed manual transaxle. The car was optioned with red-finished brake calipers, heated front seats, xenon headlights, 18″ Carrera II light alloy wheels, and a Bose audio system. It has been modified with a Fabspeed Motorsport intake assembly, a four-exit exhaust system, Eibach springs, a rear anti-sway bar, and Porsche Classic Communication Management, and it also features a Basalt Black Metallic-painted center console. This 996 Targa is now offered by the selling dealer in New York with a damage-free Carfax report and a clean South Carolina title.

The car is finished in Basalt Black Metallic (LC9Z) and features a sliding panoramic roof panel, an automatically deploying rear spoiler, xenon headlights, integrated fog lights, and polished exhaust outlets. The Targa roof was adjusted, the sunshade was replaced, and a ceramic coating was applied to the bodywork under current ownership.
The 18” Carrera II wheels are mounted with Pirelli tires. The car was optioned with red-painted brake calipers (CRD). Eibach springs have been added along with a rear anti-sway bar.

The cabin features power-adjustable heated front seats upholstered in Natural Brown leather that extends to the dashboard and door panels. A Porsche Classic Communication Management system has been added, and other features include a Bose sound system, automatic climate control, cruise control, an onboard computer, a Basalt Black Metallic-painted center console and dashboard trim strip.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 200-mph speedometer, a central tachometer with a 7,200-rpm redline, and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, battery voltage, and fuel level. Finished in Granito Lucente over Grigio cloth upholstery, the car is equipped with an optional rear spoiler, 15″ steel wheels with full covers, four-wheel disc brakes, a body-color dashboard insert, a CD stereo, and power windows, mirrors, and locks. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this 500 Pop is now offered at no reserve in Canada with a clean Carfax report and clean British Columbia registration.

The three-door hatchback is finished in Granito Lucente and features an optional rear spoiler, projector-style headlights, and a chrome hatch finisher and door handles. There is a scrape on the lower left portion of the front bumper cover, and additional photos of the paint condition are viewable in the gallery below.

The steel 15″ wheels wear silver-finished overs, and they are mounted with 185/55 Firestone Firehawk GT tires. The car is equipped with power steering and four-wheel anti-lock disc brakes. There are curb marks on the right-front wheel cover.

The seats are upholstered in Grigio cloth with black vinyl accents, and they are complemented by a color-coordinated dashboard and door panels. Additional appointments include a body-color dashboard insert, air conditioning, a rear window defroster, a CD stereo, and power windows, mirrors, and locks.

A three-spoke steering wheel fronts a 220-km/h speedometer that features an inset digital display with readouts for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer reads 9k kilometers (under 6k miles), approximately 100 kilometers of which were added under current ownership.
The MultiAir 16-valve 1.4L inline-four was factory rated at 101 horsepower and 98 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in 2024.
The front wheels are driven through a five-speed manual transaxle. Additional photos of the underside are viewable in the gallery below.
The Carfax report lists at least one open recall.
The vehicle is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada. The sale does not include a title.

This 2002 Toyota Land Cruiser has remained registered in California since new and now has 180k miles. It is finished in Riverock Green Mica over Ivory leather and is powered by a 4.7-liter 2UZ-FE V8 linked with a four-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a locking center differential. Features include 16″ five-spoke wheels, a power sunroof, heated power-adjustable front seats, third-row seating, navigation, a JBL CD stereo, cruise control, and automatic climate control. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this Land Cruiser UZJ100 is now offered with the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The truck is finished in Riverock Green Mica and features a power sunroof, a receiver hitch, fog lights, a roof rack, running boards, and a power antenna. The selling dealer notes evidence of paintwork on the right-front fender.

The 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with 275/70 Michelin Defender LTX M/S tires. Braking is handled by four-wheel ventilated discs. The truck features a double-wishbone independent front suspension and a four-link coil spring rear setup. Front axle repairs, wheel bearing repacking, and lower control arm replacement are noted on the Carfax report in November 2021.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats upholstered in Ivory leather along with a two-tone dashboard and door panels. Amenities include navigation, folding third-row seating, a JBL CD stereo, cruise control, and automatic climate control.

The four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 130-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 5,200-rpm redline as well as gauges for voltage, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 180k miles.
The 4.7-liter 2UZ-FE V8 was factory rated at 230 horsepower and 320 lb-ft of torque. The Carfax report notes that the timing belt and water pump were replaced in November 2021.

Power is routed to all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a locking center differential. Additional underside photos are provided in the gallery below.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1970 Chevrolet K10 Custom is a fleetside pickup that was refurbished and modified under prior ownership before being acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. Power is provided by a replacement 350ci V8 linked with a three-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a Positraction rear differential, and it was refinished in green and white with faux wood bodyside trim. The truck rides on a lifted suspension with Fox Performance shock absorbers, and 15″ Rally wheels are fitted over power-assisted front disc and rear drum brakes. On the inside, the bench seat is upholstered in black vinyl and accompanied by Vintage Air climate control, a retro-style push-button radio, and aftermarket audio speakers. Further equipment includes Mile Marker manually locking front hubs, an Edelbrock carburetor, and short-tube exhaust headers. This modified K10 is now offered in Maryland by the seller, a retail dealer in Virginia, with an owner’s manual and a clean Oklahoma title.

Finished from the factory in Medium Olive and White, the truck was repainted and the glass was reportedly replaced in 2022 as part of the aforementioned refurbishment. A later-model grille was retrofitted, and additional details include a fleetside bed, faux wood trim, a sliding rear window, dual side mirrors, side steps, and chrome bumpers.

The 15″ Rally wheels are mounted with 33×12.5″ ProComp Xterrain tires. The truck rides on a lifted suspension that features Fox Performance shock absorbers and is further equipped with power steering and Mile Marker manually locking front hubs. Braking is provided by power-assisted front discs and rear drums.

The bench seat was reupholstered in black vinyl with patterned inserts, while the exposed metal surfaces were finished in green. Rubberized mats line the floorboards, and appointments include Vintage Air climate control, retractable lap belts, and a retro-style digital radio connected to speakers mounted in the kick panels.

The two-spoke steering wheel is mounted to a tilt column and frames a centrally mounted tachometer as well as a 100-mph speedometer and auxiliary gauges for fuel level, voltage, coolant temperature, and oil pressure. The five-digit odometer shows 56k miles, approximately 120 of which have been added by the selling dealer. Total mileage is unknown.
The replacement 350ci V8 was installed under prior ownership and is equipped with an Edelbrock AVS2 carburetor, short-tube headers, and a Chevrolet-branded air cleaner housing and valve covers.

Power is routed to all four wheels through a three-speed Turbo Hydramatic automatic transmission, a dual-range transfer case, and a Positraction rear differential. A dual exhaust system has been fitted, and the transmission and transfer case were reportedly rebuilt as part of the refurbishment.
The service parts identification decal lists factory colors and equipment.
listing_details: Mile Marker Manually Locking Front Hubs

description: This 2000 Porsche 911 Carrera cabriolet was specified in Vesuvio Metallic over Space Gray leather, and it is powered by a 3.4-liter M96 flat-six paired with a five-speed automatic transaxle. Features include a replacement gray soft top, an aftermarket rear spoiler, 18″ Turbo-look wheels, power-adjustable front seats, a Becker Porsche CDR-220 stereo, cruise control, and automatic climate control. The car shows registration history in California beginning in August 2000 and was later relocated to Arizona prior to the selling dealer’s acquisition, and it has 71k miles. The IMS bearing was replaced  with components from LN Engineering in March 2017.  This 996.1 cabriolet is now offered in Arizona by the selling dealer with service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The car is finished in Vesuvio Metallic (L40X) and is equipped with a replacement gray convertible soft top as well as integrated fog lights, an aftermarket rear spoiler, tinted tail lights, and dual exhaust outlets with polished finishers. The soft top hydraulic cylinders were replaced in 2022.

The 18″ Turbo-look wheels show signs of curb rash and are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires. Braking is handled by four-piston Porsche-branded calipers fitted over cross-drilled rotors at all four corners. The front brake pads and rotors were replaced in November 2021, and the rear brake pads and rotors were replaced in March 2023.

The power-adjustable front seats are trimmed in Space Gray leather. Interior equipment includes a Becker Porsche CDR-220 stereo, cruise control, a removable wind deflector, and automatic climate control. The center console was dyed in March 2017.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a 180-mph speedometer, a central tachometer, and gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 71k miles.

The 3.4-liter M96 flat-six was factory rated at 300 horsepower and 258 lb-ft of torque, which is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed automatic transaxle. The IMS bearing was replaced in March 2017 with components from LN Engineering, the battery was replaced in March 2023, and an oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
Decoding the option sticker reveals the following information:
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.

This 2003 Ferrari 575M Maranello is powered by a 5.7-liter V12 and underwent a six-speed manual transmission conversion by European Auto Group of Round Rock, Texas, in 2022. It is finished in Nero with Scuderia Ferrari fender shields and is further equipped with a limited-slip differential, a Skyhook suspension, and 19″ modular wheels. On the inside, the power-adjustable Daytona-style seats are trimmed in black leather with red accents and accompanied by a gated shifter, an automatic climate control system, and a Becker stereo and trunk-mounted CD changer. The car was sold new in California and subsequently spent time in Florida and New Mexico. Now with 23k miles, this 575M is offered on dealer consignment with manufacturer’s literature, a tool kit, a car cover, and a clean New Mexico title.

The Pininfarina-designed aluminum bodywork is finished in Nero with Scuderia Ferrari fender shields and features a hood scoop, a front lip spoiler, front fender vents, and an integrated rear spoiler. Further details include xenon headlights, tinted windows, and quad exhaust tips exiting through the rear bumper cover.

Five-spoke 19″ modular wheels are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires measuring 255/35 at the front and 305/30 at the rear. Braking is handled by red-finished Ferrari-branded calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated rotors at all four corners. The 575M featured a Skyhook suspension system with adaptive dampers.

The Daytona-style seats are power-adjustable and upholstered in black leather with red inserts. A Ferrari-branded Becker stereo is connected to a trunk-mounted CD changer, and a Raytel TellPhone has been added. Further amenities include automatic climate control, electric windows, driver-seat memory settings, and rear luggage straps.

The three-spoke steering wheel is wrapped in leather and paired with a gated shifter. Instrumentation consists of a tachometer with a 7,600-rpm redline as well as a 220-mph speedometer and gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 23k miles, approximately 400 of which have been added under current ownership.
The 5.7-liter quad-cam F133E V12 features 48 valves, dry-sump lubrication, and Bosch Motronic engine management for a factory-rated output of 508 horsepower and 434 lb-ft of torque.

The car underwent a six-speed manual transmission conversion in 2022 by European Auto Group in Round Rock, Texas. A limited-slip differential is also equipped out back. The clutch master cylinder was replaced in 2024.
Manufacturers literature, a tool kit, and a car cover are included in the sale.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.
The New Mexico title is listed as a duplicate. There is currently a lien on the car, and the seller’s lender will need to be paid off before the title can be transferred to the next owner.

This 1981 Yamaha RD350LC is said to have spent time on Vancouver Island before the seller’s acquisition in 2000. Finished in white with blue graphics, the bike is powered by a liquid-cooled 347cc two-stroke parallel twin paired with a six-speed transmission. Equipment includes Autolube oil injection, dual carburetors, a dual exhaust system, a kick starter, dual front disc brakes, 18″ alloy wheels, street lighting, and a two-up seat. Work since 2020 included changing the transmission fluid, coating the inside of the fuel tank, cleaning the carburetors, and replacing the clutch and tires. This RD350LC is offered at no reserve with spare parts, a workshop manual, service invoices, and a British Columbia registration in the seller’s name.

The bike was purchased in 2000 by the seller, who believes that it was imported from Japan to Vancouver Island, Canada under previous ownership. The bike is finished in white with two-tone blue graphics over a black double-cradle steel frame. Details include street lighting, a black two-up seat, folding passenger foot pegs, and both center and side stands. The inside of the fuel tank was coated in 2021, and cosmetic bodywork was carried out before refinishing the fenders and side covers. The tank was coated in POR15 before refinishing. Blemishes in the paint are noted around the bike, and the removed rear grab bar is included in the sale.

Cast-alloy 18″ wheels were mounted with Bridgestone tires in 2021. Suspension consists of a conventional telescopic fork and a monoshock mounted to the swingarm. Braking is handled by dual discs up front and a drum at the rear.

The black low-rise handlebar carries dual mirrors and is mounted aft of a column of indicator lights flanked by a 200-km/h speedometer and a tachometer with a 9,500-rpm redline. The five-digit odometer shows 49k kilometers (~30k miles), approximately 1,700 kilometers of which were ridden under current ownership.
The liquid-cooled 347cc two-stroke parallel twin features Autolube oil injection, a kick starter, and a two-into-two exhaust system. The carburetors were cleaned in preparation for the sale.

This 1966 Plymouth Barracuda was modified in the style of a “gasser” drag racer around 2008, when the car was mounted on a rotisserie, stripped, and refinished and then a replacement overbored 440ci V8 and a four-speed manual transmission were installed. The rear end was tubbed to accommodate 31×18.50″ tires on 15″ Weld Racing wheels, and 26×7.50″ tires, 15″ Jegs wheels, and a straight axle are fitted at the front of the vehicle. Other equipment includes an 8¾” rear end, Moser axles, Richmond 4.10:1 gears, power-assisted Wilwood four-wheel disc brakes, power steering, a wheelie bar, a fuel cell, a cutout-equipped dual exhaust system, an 850-cfm carburetor, a Weiand intake manifold, and aftermarket gauges plus a black-upholstered interior. The current owner acquired the car in 2019. This modified Barracuda—nicknamed “The Gasser Passer”—is now offered in Delaware on dealer consignment with build records and photos as well as a clean Florida title.

The car was stripped and refinished in a shade of metallic red based on a Ford color during the aforementioned refurbishment. A Hemi badge is attached to the grille, and other features include headlamps, taillights, chrome bumpers, bright trim, a hood scoop, a driver-side mirror, tinted glass, and a curved rear window. The car lacks windshield wipers and a wiper motor. Chips and scratches in the paint and other imperfections are pictured in the gallery below.

Bright-finished Jegs 15″ front and Weld Racing 15″ rear wheels are mounted with Mickey Thompson Sportsman M/T tires that measure 26×7.50″ at the front and 31×18.50″ out back. A Wilwood braking system utilizes discs at all four corners and a custom power booster. The front axle has been converted to a straight-axle setup with power steering and leaf springs, and leaf springs and coilovers help locate the live rear axle, which is positioned just ahead of a dual wheelie bar.

The front bucket and rear bench seats are upholstered in black vinyl, which is complemented by black door and side panels, black carpeting, and a black headliner. Wood trim adorns the dashboard, and diamond-plate material is used on the sill covers and kick plates. Other appointments include front lap belts, a Hurst shifter, and a fire extinguisher. An array of switches on the dash operate lights, the fuel pump, and the car’s main power. The vehicle does not have a heater.

A woodgrain-style steering wheel fronts a padded dash top that anchors a Sunpro Supertach II tachometer, and a quintet of Stewart-Warner gauges monitors vehicle speed, water temperature, fuel level, oil pressure, and voltage. The digital odometer is not connected, and true chassis mileage is unknown.
The trunk compartment houses a 15-gallon fuel cell and the vehicle’s battery.

The 440ci V8 is said to have been sourced from a 1970s Dodge truck and was bored .030″ over during the refurbishment for a total displacement of 446ci. Equipment is said to include Keith Black pistons, a Lunati Voodoo camshaft, Crane Cams roller rocker arms, ProComp ignition components, a Weiand aluminum intake manifold, an 850-cfm double-pumper carburetor, oversize valves, heavy-duty valve springs, chrome valve covers, Doug Thorley Headers, and a three-row aluminum radiator with an auxiliary electric fan. The car’s chassis number indicates that it was originally powered by a 273ci V8.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a rebuilt four-speed manual transmission said to have been sourced from a 1970 Plymouth ’Cuda and augmented by a lightweight flywheel, an 11″ clutch, and Hurst linkage as well as a narrowed “742” Chrysler 8¾” rear end, Moser axles, and Richmond 4.10:1 gears. The underside has been strengthened, in part by a driveshaft loop and reinforced frame rails. The dual exhaust system has electrically actuated cutouts that dump just behind the front wheels, and the system continues through dual mufflers and terminates ahead of the rear wheels. Corrosion is visible on underbody components.
Folders containing service and build records as well as images documenting the refurbishment will accompany the car and are shown in the photo gallery.
listing_details: Narrowed Rear Axle & Tubbed Rear Wheel Wells

description: This 2018 Porsche 911 Carrera 4S cabriolet has 9k miles and was optioned from the factory with the X51 Exclusive Powerkit in addition to the Sport Chrono Package and a sport exhaust system. It is powered by a twin-turbocharged 3.0L flat-six that drives all four wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle and is finished in Carrara White Metallic over Espresso and Cognac Natural leather. The car is further equipped with 20″ Carrera Classic alloy wheels, a red convertible soft top, LED headlights with PDLS+, a back-up camera, a Burmester sound system, mahogany interior trim, Lane Change Assist, and heated and ventilated power-adjustable front sport seats. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this 991.2 C4S cabriolet is now offered with the owner’s manual, two keys, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New York title.

The car is finished in Carrara White Metallic and has LED headlights with Porsche Dynamic Light System Plus (PDLS+) as well as a red convertible soft top, LED taillights, front and rear parking sensors, dual exhaust outlets, power-folding mirrors, and a speed-activated rear spoiler. Paint meter readings are provided in the gallery below.

The 20″ Carrera Classic alloy wheels are mounted with 245/35 front and 305/30 rear Pirelli P Zero tires showing 2017 and 2018 date codes. Braking is handled by red-painted Porsche-branded calipers over cross-drilled and ventilated discs, and the car is equipped with Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM). The brake fluid was flushed in July 2023.

The heated and ventilated power-adjustable front sport seats are upholstered in Cognac, while Espresso Natural leather covers the upper portions of the dashboard and door panels. Porsche-branded floor mats line the footwells, and additional appointments include mahogany interior trim, PCM with navigation, a CD stereo, a back-up camera, Lane Change Assist, a Burmester sound system, dual-zone automatic climate control, and cruise control.

The heated leather- and mahogany-trimmed steering wheel frames a central tachometer with a 7,400-rpm redline as well as a 200-mph speedometer and gauges for oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The optional Sport Chrono Package added a stopwatch atop the dashboard. The digital odometer indicates 9k miles.
The twin-turbocharged 3.0L flat-six was rated at 444 horsepower when equipped with the X51 Exclusive Powerkit. A replacement drive belt was installed in July 2023.

Power is sent to all four wheels through a seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transaxle and Porsche Torque Vectoring Plus with an electronically locking rear differential. The car is equipped with a sport exhaust system, and additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.
listing_details: Heated and Ventilated Power-Adjustable Front Sport Seats

description: This 1954 Chevrolet 3100 five-window pickup was modified around 2010. Riding on a boxed frame with a Plymouth Volare-sourced front end, the truck is powered by a 383ci ZZ V8 linked to a 700R4 automatic transmission and a Ford 9″ rear end with 3.70 gears. The exterior was refinished with red paintwork, a mahogany bed, and chrome trim, and Cragar SS wheels were installed along with 11″ front disc brakes, an Ididit column, Vintage Air climate control, power windows, and an Alpine stereo. This 3100 pickup was acquired by the current owner in 2011 and is now offered at no reserve on dealer consignment with records and an Arizona title.

The rear fenders, box, running boards, and floorboards were replaced before the truck was repainted by Color Works Auto Refinishing in Denver, Colorado. The headlights, chrome front bumper, weather seals, and glass were replaced, and the rear bumper is a customized 1978 El Camino component that was narrowed and re-chromed.

The tailgate has bowtie pinstriping and hidden latches and cables. The mahogany bed is separated by chrome strips and has a flush fuel filler for the stainless-steel fuel tank. A battery jump post is located under the right-side running board, and there is a battery disconnect behind the right seat.

The front end was sourced from a Plymouth Volare, the frame was boxed, and Chassis Engineering rear springs were installed along with Bilstein shocks, power steering, 11″ front disc brakes, and stainless-steel lines. The 15″ Cragar wheels wear BFGoodrich Radial T/A tires.

The bucket seats have inner armrests, and the custom console with an emergency brake and Alpine stereo are mounted between them. Vintage Air climate control, custom carpeting, and power windows were added.

The Lecarra steering wheel is mounted on an Ididit column that has been painted to match the dashboard. The 27k miles on the replacement odometer represents the mileage driven since completion, with approximately 11k miles added by the current owner.

The 383ci ZZ V8 is topped by a polished-aluminum intake manifold and a Holley carburetor. The exhaust manifolds have been powder-coated and are linked to a dual exhaust system with Flowmaster mufflers. A Zoops front-runner serpentine kit, an Afco aluminum radiator, a Haywire wiring harness, and chrome accessories have been installed. The spark plugs and valve cover gaskets were replaced in 2023.
The 700R4 automatic transmission is linked to a Ford 9″ rear end with 3.70 gears that was installed in 2020. The truck also has a transmission cooler.
A build summary and records in the gallery are included in the sale.
The Arizona title carries a Not Actual Mileage odometer code.

This 2013 Audi Allroad Quattro Premium Plus is powered by a turbocharged 2.0-liter inline-four that drives all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transaxle and a Quattro all-wheel-drive system and is finished in Moonlight Blue Metallic over Velvet Beige leather upholstery. Equipment includes 18″ five-arm-Allroad alloy wheels, a sunroof, a power-operated liftgate, self-leveling xenon headlights, LED daytime running lights, fog lights, Parking System Plus parking sensors, roof rails, a Bang & Olufsen sound system, a rearview camera, heated power-adjustable front seats, Audi MMI Navigation, cruise control, and automatic climate control. The car was acquired by the current owner in May 2017, and it now has 90k miles. This B8 Allroad Quattro is now offered on dealer consignment at no reserve with a Carfax report and a clean Florida title.

The car is finished in Moonlight Blue Metallic (LX5R) and features a sunroof, a power-operated liftgate, self-leveling xenon headlights, headlight washers, LED daytime running lights, Parking System Plus parking sensors, heated power-folding side mirrors, roof rails, and fog lights. An October 2016 entry in the Carfax report lists an accident reported as a result of contact with a deer. There is a chip in the windshield, there are paint chips on the front end, there are scratches on the top of the rear bumper cover, and scuffs are shown on the right-front wheel arch and behind the left-rear wheel.
The 18″ five-arm-Allroad alloy wheels are mounted with 245/45 Toyo Celcius tires, and braking is handled by ventilated discs at each corner.

The heated power-adjustable front bucket seats are trimmed in Velvet Beige leather, and amenities include a Bang & Olufsen sound system, a rearview camera, Audi MMI Navigation, HomeLink, Voice Control, Bluetooth connectivity, automatic climate control, dark brown walnut wood trim, and cruise control. There is a crack in the veneer trim to the left of the Quattro dashboard badge.

The multifunction steering wheel frames a 160-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 90k miles, approximately 30k miles of which were added under current ownership.
The turbocharged 2.0-liter EA888 inline-four was factory rated at 211 horsepower and 258 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.

Power is sent to all four wheels through an eight-speed Tiptronic automatic transaxle and a Quattro all-wheel-drive system. The transaxle, transfer case, and differential were serviced in February 2023.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned accident.

This 2017 Land Rover Range Rover is a standard-wheelbase SVAutobiography example that is finished in SV Premium Palette British Racing Green over two-tone red and black leather upholstery and is powered by a supercharged 5.0-liter V8 linked to an eight-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range electronically-controlled transfer case. Equipment includes Dynamic air suspension, 22″ wheels, a panoramic sunroof, adaptive xenon headlights, a 360° camera system, heated and ventilated seats, and four-zone automatic climate control as well as center console cooler compartments, adaptive cruise control, active Park Assist, navigation, and a rear-seat entertainment system with dual monitors. The truck has remained registered in California since new and was acquired by the selling dealer in 2022 before it was offered on BaT in March 2023. This Range Rover SVAutobiography has 74k miles and is offered with manufacturer’s literature, rear entertainment headsets, two keys, a Carfax report, and a clean California title.

SV Premium Palette British Racing Green paint finishes the bodywork, and features include a contrasting black roof and window trim as well as a panoramic sunroof, a solar-attenuating windshield, a power-operated split tailgate, adaptive HID headlights, LED taillights, fog lights, and soft-close doors. The truck is equipped with a surround-view camera system and Park Assist as well as automated driver-assist functions for parallel parking and perpendicular parking. The Carfax report lists damage reported in a May 2024 entry, though no additional information is provided.

Diamond-turned 22″ style 514 wheels are wrapped in 275/40 Continental Extreme Contact Tires showing 2022 date codes. Standard equipment included electronic air suspension with Terrain Response 2 as well as Hill Decent Control (HDC), Roll Stability Control (RSC), and reactive grounding response, while the Dynamic package added revised steering knuckles, links, springs, and dampers. Braking is handled by four-wheel anti-lock discs with Electronic Brake Assist (EBA), Cornering Brake Control (CBC), and red-finished calipers. The front and rear brake pads, rotors, and wear sensors were replaced in November 2021, and the selling dealer states that the rear brake rotors were surfaced and the rear brake pads and wear sensors were replaced along with the control arms in June 2024. There are curb marks on the right-rear wheel.

Red and black leather upholstery covers the heated and ventilated seats, and it extends to the armrests, doors, lower pillars, and dashboard. Amenities include four-zone automatic climate control, navigation, massaging front seats, a center console cooler compartment, a leather-trimmed headliner, and a rear-seat entertainment system with dual monitors. The seat inserts feature diamond stitching with Autobiography-script embroidery.

The multifunction heated steering wheel features red paddle shifters and frames a configurable digital instrument screen that displays a 180-mph speedometer and an 8k-rpm tachometer. The digital odometer indicates 74k miles, approximately 24k of which were added under current ownership.

The supercharged 5.0-liter V8 in Dynamic specification was calibrated to produce 550 horsepower and 502 lb-ft of torque. According to the selling dealer, the alternator and battery were replaced in 2023. An oil change was performed and the air filter was replaced in preparation for the sale, according to the selling dealer.
Power is sent to all four wheels through an eight-speed automatic transmission, a dual-range electronically-controlled transfer case, and a locking rear differential.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned damage report.

This 2001 Porsche 911 Carrera 4 cabriolet was specified in Slate Grey Metallic over Natural Brown full leather, and it was optioned with the Technic Package, dark maple wood trim, heated power-adjustable front seats, and 18″ Sport Classic wheels. It is powered by a 3.4-liter M96 flat-six that drives all four wheels through a replacement six-speed manual transaxle, and equipment includes a speed-activated rear spoiler, a black soft top, xenon headlights, fog lights, a Becker Porsche CDR-220 stereo, and automatic climate control. This 996 C4 cabriolet has 37k miles, and it is now offered in Florida by the selling dealer with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Florida title.

The car is finished in Slate Grey Metallic (23F) and features a black convertible soft top as well as a speed-activated rear spoiler, xenon headlights, integrated fog lights, heated mirrors, and polished exhaust outlets.

The 18″ Sport Classic wheels are mounted with Continental ExtremeContact tires. The car is equipped with Porsche Stability Management (PSM) and an Automatic Brake Differential (ABD). Braking is from silver calipers over ventilated and cross-drilled rotors at all four corners.

The cabin features heated power-adjustable front seats upholstered in Natural Brown leather that extends to the dashboard and door panels. Dark Maple wood trim accents the center stack, and additional features include driver-seat memory settings, a Becker Porsche CDR-220 stereo, cruise control, a removable wind deflector, and automatic climate control.

The wood- and leather-rimmed steering wheel frames a central tachometer with a 7,200-rpm redline and a 180-mph speedometer as well as gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 37k miles.
The 3.4-liter M96 flat-six was factory rated at 300 horsepower and 258 lb-ft of torque. The seller notes that the IMS bearing was replaced in June 2022 with components from LN Engineering.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a replacement six-speed manual transaxle. An entry in the Carfax report states that the transmission was replaced in January 2005.
The window sticker lists delivery to Brandywine Porsche in Newtown Square, Pennsylvania, along with factory colors, standard equipment, options, exclusive options, and a total price of $99,540.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other damage.
The Georgia title is listed as a replacement.

This 2006 Porsche Boxster is finished in Dark Teal Metallic over Sand Beige standard leather and now has 11k miles following history in Pennsylvania and Maryland. It is powered by a 2.7-liter flat-six paired with a five-speed manual transaxle, and equipment includes the Preferred and Sound Plus packages as well as a black soft top, 17″ wheels, a deployable rear spoiler, heated seats, and cruise control. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this 987.1 Boxster is now offered in Pennsylvania with a photocopy of the window sticker, manufacturer’s literature, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Maryland title.

The car is finished in Dark Teal Metallic and features a power-operated black convertible soft top. Additional equipment includes silver-accented quarter panel intakes, roll bars, a speed-dependent rear spoiler, a central exhaust outlet, and auto-dimming mirrors with a rain sensor.

The 17″ multi-spoke alloy wheels feature full-color Porsche-crest center caps and are mounted with 205/55 front and 235/50 rear Michelin Pilot Sport tires. The car is equipped with Porsche Stability Management (PSM), and braking is handled by four-piston Porsche-branded calipers over cross-drilled rotors.

The cabin features heated seats upholstered in Sand Beige leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard and carpets. Amenities include the Sound Package Plus, cruise control, and a CD stereo. The driver’s seat outer bolster and climate adjustment switches are worn.
The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a central 8k-rpm tachometer, a 175-mph speedometer, and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 11k miles.
The mid-mounted 2.7L flat-six is located ahead of the rear cargo area and was factory rated at 236 horsepower and 199 lb-ft of torque.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transaxle.
A photocopy of the window sticker lists factory equipment, colors, options, and a total price of $50,855. Manufacturer’s literature and service records are also included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2015 Audi RS5 cabriolet was acquired new by its current owner, and it was optioned with the Comfort, Technology, and Black Optic Plus packages. Finished in Panther Black Crystal Effect (LZ9Z) with a black soft top over black Milano leather, it features an Audi crown-gear center differential, a torque-vectoring rear differential, titanium-finished 20″ wheels, adaptive xenon headlights, heated and ventilated front seats, a Bang & Olufsen sound system, blind-spot monitoring, a rearview camera, and Audi MMI infotainment with Navigation Plus. Power comes from a 4.2-liter V8 that drives all four wheels through a seven-speed S tronic dual-clutch automatic transaxle. This RS5 has 35k miles and is offered on dealer consignment in New York with two keys and a clean Connecticut title.

The RS5 features a model-specific front end, rear diffuser, and wide wheel arches, and its convertible top folds at speeds up to 31 mph. The Black Optic Plus Package added a gloss-black Singleframe grille, a carbon-fiber rear lip spoiler, body-color mirror caps, and black finishers for its sport exhaust system. Damage to the right side and right front is listed in an August 2018 entry on the Carfax report, which also lists damage to the rear in a June 2023 entry, and damage to the left rear and rear in a January 2024 entry.

The 20″ rotor-design wheels are mounted with 275/30 Michelin Pilot Sport A/S 3+ tires. The car is equipped with an RS sport-tuned suspension and scalloped cross-drilled brake rotors, and its four Audi Drive Select modes can adjust the car’s throttle response, shift points, steering, damping, and rear differential.

The Comfort Package front seats are heated and ventilated, equipped with a neck-level heating system, and upholstered in black Milano leather. Carbon-fiber trim and a 12-speaker Bang & Olufsen sound system are additional appointments.

The flat-bottom steering wheel has shift paddles, and the driver is aided by a Bluetooth hands-free system, a rearview camera, parking sensors, blind-spot monitors, push-button start, and Audi MMI Navigation Plus. The odometer indicates 35k miles.

Trimmed with a Black Optic Package carbon-fiber engine cover, the 4.2-liter FSI V8 was factory rated at 450 horsepower and 317 lb-ft of torque, and it sends power to all four wheels through a seven-speed S tronic dual-clutch automatic transaxle and a Quattro all-wheel-drive system with a torque-vectoring rear differential.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage entries.

This Ford Mustang race car was built in 2021 by Capaldi Racing of New Baltimore, Michigan for competition in National Auto Sport Association (NASA) Sport Touring events, winning the 2023 Great Lakes Region ST2 Championship. The car was built around a 2017 Ford Mustang FP350S caged body and is powered by a 5.2-liter DOHC V8 linked to a Tremec six-speed manual transmission. The bodywork is finished in white with racing livery and a carbon-fiber roof and hood. Features include a carbon-fiber front splitter, a Verus rear diffuser, a Xineering Downshift Blip Module, an AIM Solo DL datalogger, a QA1 carbon-fiber driveshaft, and AP Racing calipers. The race-prepped cabin features an MSA-spec roll cage, a window net, a fire suppression system, a Sparco quick-release steering wheel, and a Momo seat with a Schroth Racing six-point harness. This Mustang race car is now offered in Michigan for off-road use only with a spare set of wheels and a bill of sale.

The bodywork is finished in white with racing livery, and features include a custom side-exit exhaust, an Anderson carbon-fiber hood, an Anderson carbon-fiber roof, a front splitter, and a Verus rear diffuser. The seller notes that a door, a fender, and rear facia were damaged and have been replaced.

Forgeline 18″ GS1R monoblock aluminum wheels with I-beam spokes are finished in pearl gray and wear Hoosier rain tires, while a matching set of wheels are mounted with Hoosier R7 tires. Stopping power comes from AP Racing’s six-piston Endurance front and four-piston rear calipers over two-piece vented and slotted rotors measuring 372mm and 340mm, respectively. The suspension utilizes JRi shocks with custom valving at all four corners.
The cabin features a black Momo racing seat with a Schroth Racing six-point harness as well as a fire suppression system and a roll cage.

The three-spoke Sparco quick-release steering wheel fronts a 200-mph speedometer, a tachometer with an 8,250-rpm redline, and an AIM Solo DL datalogger. Toggle-switch and push-button controls are housed in the center stack. The seller notes that a used gauge cluster was installed and set to 10k miles when the car was built. The odometer now reads 17k miles.

The 5.2-liter DOHC V8 was recently rebuilt and features a billet oil pump, Watson Racing motor mounts, a Braille lithium battery, and an ATL fuel cell. Receipts for the engine work can be viewed in the photo gallery below.
Power is sent to the rear wheels through a Tremec 3160 six-speed manual transmission, a QA1 carbon-fiber driveshaft with a heat shield, and a 3.55 rear differential.
listing_details: Spare Set of Matching Wheels w/Hoosier Wets

description: This 1957 Ford Thunderbird was modified in 2023 with a 5.0-liter Coyote V8, which is linked to a 4R70W four-speed automatic and a Strange Engineering 9″ rear end. Finished in metallic blue and white over a color-coordinated interior, the car rides on an Art Morrison chassis and also has a removable fiberglass hardtop, Truespoke stainless-steel-spoked wheels, a Wilwood master cylinder, a wood-rimmed steering wheel, power windows, a Retrosound stereo, and Classic Auto air conditioning. It was titled in California for approximately 40 years before relocating to Arizona in 2015. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this modified Thunderbird is now offered in New York with a clean Arizona title.
The car is finished in metallic blue with a white fiberglass hardtop with porthole windows. The selling dealer states the paintwork was performed in 2023.
Truespoke stainless-steel-spoked wheels wear BFGoodrich Silvertown whitewalls. The car rides on an Art Morrison chassis and has a Wilwood master cylinder along with four-wheel disc brakes.

The Dial-O-Matic power-adjustable bench seat is upholstered in light blue with white pleated inserts and is accompanied by a color-coordinated dashboard and door panels. Power windows are present and a RetroSound stereo and a Classic Auto air conditioning system have been installed.
The wood-rimmed steering wheel frames Classic Instrument gauges. The 1k miles shown on the odometer represents the mileage driven since completion.
The battery has been relocated to the trunk.

The 5.0-liter Coyote V8 is said to have been a crate motor that was installed in 2023. It has an Airraid intake, an aluminum radiator, and a dual exhaust system with MagnaFlow mufflers. Power is routed to the rear wheels via a 4R70W four-speed automatic transmission and a Strange Engineering 9″ rear axle.

This 2000 Saab 9-5 wagon has remained with a single owner in California before being acquired by the selling dealer in 2024. Subsequent work consisted of replacing the tensioner, water pump, spark plugs, and front brake pads and rotors. Finished in Frost Grey Metallic over grey leather upholstery, the car is powered by a turbocharged 2.3-liter inline-four paired with a five-speed manual transaxle. Equipment includes a roof rack, dual-zone automatic climate control, power-adjustable front seats, power accessories, and a CD/cassette stereo. This 9-5 Wagon has 91k miles and is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve with a clean Carfax report and a clean California title.

The car is finished in Frost Grey Metallic and details include a power sunroof, roof racks, and headlights with a wiper system. Paint and body blemishes are displayed in the gallery along with paint meter readings.

The 16″ 10-spoke alloy wheels are wrapped in 215/55 General Altimax RT43 tires. The car is equipped with a traction control system and four-wheel disc brakes with ABS. The front brake pads and rotors are said to have been replaced in preparation for the sale.

The seating surfaces are upholstered in grey leather and wood trim accents the instrument panel and center console. Additional appointments include a CD/cassette stereo, power-adjustable front seats, and dual-zone automatic climate control.

The four-spoke steering wheel frames a 155-mph speedometer flanked by a tachometer and auxiliary gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer shows 91k miles, approximately 150 of which were added by the seller.

The turbocharged 2.3-liter inline-four was factory rated at 168 horsepower and 207 lb/ft of torque. Work under current ownership is said to consist of replacing the tensioner, water pump, and spark plugs.
Power is sent to the front wheels through a five-speed manual gearbox.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or damage and lists registration history in California.

This 1978 Yamaha SR500 is said to have spent three decades in Arizona before it was relocated to Kansas, where it was acquired by the seller in April 2023. Finished in red with gold graphics, the motorcycle is powered by a 499cc SOHC single that was reportedly refurbished under current ownership. It is also equipped with a five-speed transmission, a Mikuni carburetor, front and rear disc brakes, alloy wheels, aftermarket rear turn signals, a two-up seat with a passenger grab strap, and both center and side stands. Additional work under current ownership is said to have involved servicing the brakes as well as rebuilding the engine and replacing the camshaft, camshaft sprocket, and steering stem bearings. This SR500 is offered at no reserve with a Haynes workshop manual and a clean Colorado title in the seller’s name.

The motorcycle left the factory finished in Star Red with gold graphics. Additional details include a 3.2-gallon fuel tank, a two-up seat with a passenger grab strap, and both center and side stands. The seller states that aftermarket rear-view mirrors and turn signals have been fitted to the bike. Close-up photos of blemishes are presented in the gallery below.

Alloy wheels measuring 19″ up front and 18″ out back were reportedly mounted with Shinko tires under current ownership. Suspension consists of a telescopic fork in addition to a pair of preload-adjustable shocks attached to the swingarm. Stopping power is provided by front and rear disc brakes. The seller states that the steering stem bearings and were replaced and the brakes were serviced in preparation for the sale.
The handlebar frames a 120-mph speedometer and a tachometer. The five-digit odometer shows 13k miles. The Colorado title lists a mileage reading of 29,700 miles.

The 499cc SOHC four-stroke single is equipped with a kick starter, a 34mm Mikuni carburetor, and a single exhaust. Factory-rated output was 33 horsepower and 28 lb-ft of torque. According to the seller, the engine was completely rebuilt under current ownership. Additional work is said to have included replacing the camshaft and camshaft sprocket along with various gaskets.
The number 2J2022519 stamped into the engine case matches the number stamped into the frame, a photo of which can be viewed in the gallery.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a five-speed transmission and a drive chain.

This 2018 Mercedes-AMG GT R has 9k miles and is powered by a twin-turbocharged 4.0-liter V8 linked with a seven-speed dual-clutch automatic transaxle and an electronically controlled limited-slip differential. Finished in Brilliant Blue Metallic over black upholstery, the car has carbon-fiber exterior and interior accents, rear-axle steering, 19″ and 20″ AMG forged wheels, Parktronic, a carbon-fiber roof panel, power-adjustable heated seats, AMG illuminated door sill plates, TIKT Performance carbon-fiber brake ducts, steel-braided brake lines, an adaptive sport suspension, the Exterior Carbon Fiber Package, and COMAND infotainment with navigation. Purchased by the owner in 2023, this AMG GT R is now offered on dealer consignment with partial service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Virginia title.

The car is finished in Brilliant Blue Metallic with carbon-fiber accents, and additional details include a front splitter, a fixed rear wing, a carbon-fiber roof and fenders, front and rear Parktronic, and LED headlights and taillights. XPEL paint protection film has been applied to the front end and mirror caps, per the seller.

The 19″ and 20″ black AMG forged twin five-spoke wheels are mounted with 275/35 front and 325/30 rear Michelin Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires. Braking is handled by yellow-finished calipers over cross-drilled and slotted rotors, and the car is equipped with steel-braided brake lines, an adaptive sport suspension, TIKT Performance carbon-fiber brake ducts, rear-axle steering, and a larger rear anti-roll bar compared to the standard AMG GT. A brake fluid flush was carried out in April 2023.

The heated power-adjustable AMG Performance seats are trimmed in black upholstery with AMG logos on the backrests, yellow seatbelts, and color-contrasting stitching that extends to the center console, dashboard, and door panels. Carbon-fiber trim accents the cabin, and additional appointments include aftermarket floor mats, a rearview camera, AMG illuminated door sill plates, dual-zone automatic climate control, and COMAND infotainment with navigation.

The Dinamica-wrapped AMG Performance steering wheel frames a 220-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and a central configurable digital display. The digital odometer indicates 9k miles, approximately 4,500 of which were added under current ownership.
The 4.0-liter V8 features revised twin-turbochargers, exhaust ports, and throttle mapping for a factory rating of 577 horsepower and 517 lb-ft of torque. A carbon-fiber shroud covers the engine.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a seven-speed dual-clutch automatic transaxle and an electronically controlled limited-slip differential. The car is equipped with a carbon-fiber driveshaft. The rear differential and transaxle fluids were replaced in April 2023. Additional photos of the underside are provided in the gallery.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1986 Nissan 300ZX Turbo was initially delivered to Tom Harrigan Datsun in Dayton, Ohio, and it now shows 9k miles following registration history in Michigan and New Jersey. Finished in Dark Pewter Metallic over gray leather upholstery, the car is powered by a turbocharged 3.0-liter V6 paired with a five-speed manual transmission. Features include removable roof panels, a rear spoiler, 16″ turbine-style alloy wheels, a power-adjustable driver’s seat, a cassette stereo and graphic equalizer, and cruise control. It was acquired by the selling dealer in 2023, and work performed since has included replacing the tires, timing belt, water pump, battery, spark plugs, distributor cap and rotor, fuel filter, and clutch slave cylinder. This Z31 300ZX Turbo is offered with a window sticker, manufacturer’s literature, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean New Jersey title.

The car is finished in Dark Pewter Metallic, and exterior features include removable T-top roof panels, pop-up headlights, fog lights, a hood scoop, a rear window wiper, a rear spoiler, and a power antenna. Paint correction and paintless dent removal were performed in preparation for the sale. Close-up photographs of the exterior finish and trim are shown in the gallery below.

The 16″ turbine-style alloy wheels were refinished and fitted with Yokohama Advan Sports tires in preparation for the sale. Stopping power is provided by ventilated discs at each corner. The brake fluid was changed in 2023.

The two-place cabin features bucket seats upholstered in gray leather. Interior equipment includes a power-adjustable driver’s seat, air conditioning, cruise control, and a cassette stereo with a graphic equalizer.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames digital instrumentation consisting of a speedometer, a tachometer, and readouts for fuel level, coolant temperature, oil pressure, and voltage. The digital dash power supply was replaced in preparation for the sale. The six-digit odometer shows 9k miles.

The turbocharged 3.0-liter VG30ET V6 was factory-rated at 200 horsepower and 227 lb-ft of torque. Work performed in 2024 has included replacing the timing belt, water pump, battery, spark plugs, fuel filter, and distributor cap and rotor.

Power is routed to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission. The transmission fluid was changed and the clutch slave cylinder was replaced during the selling dealer’s ownership. The underside was treated with dry ice in May 2024.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Tom Harrigan Datsun in Dayton, Ohio, as well as factory colors, equipment, and a total manufacturer’s suggested retail price of $23,159.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2005 Toyota Celica GT has remained registered in Pennsylvania through the selling dealer’s acquisition in 2024 and now has 17k miles. Finished in Silver Streak Metallic over black and gray cloth, the car is powered by a 1.8-liter inline-four paired with a four-speed automatic transaxle. Equipment includes 15″ alloy wheels, a sunroof, projector-style headlights, fog lights, a hood scoop, and a rear wing in addition to air conditioning, cruise control, and a CD stereo. This Celica GT is now offered at no reserve by the selling dealer with manufacturer’s literature, two key fobs, a Carfax report, and a Pennsylvania title.

The car is finished in Silver Streak Metallic (1E7). Details include a power-operated sunroof, projector-style headlights, fog lights, a hood scoop, a rear window wiper, and a rear wing. The Carfax report lists a damage report in November 2016 with “minor damage” occurring.

Silver-finished 15″ alloy wheels are mounted with 195/60 Goodyear Eagle RS-A tires. The car rides on MacPherson struts up front and double-wishbone suspension out back. Braking is provided by front discs and rear drums.
The front bucket seats and fold-down rear bench seat are upholstered in black and gray cloth. Appointments include air conditioning, cruise control, a center console, and an AM/FM/CD stereo.
The three-spoke steering wheel frames a 150-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and digital gauges for coolant temperature and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 17k miles.
The 1.8-liter inline-four features dual overhead camshafts with variable valve timing and was factory rated at 140 horsepower and 125 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the front wheels via four-speed automatic transaxle.
Manufacturer’s literature and two key fobs will accompany the vehicle.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned damage report.

This 1995 Eagle Vision TSi spent time with a single owner until the selling dealer’s acquisition in April 2021. Subsequent work consisted of installing tires, recharging the air conditioning, repainting the lower cladding, and replacing the timing belt, water pump, coolant hoses, and front brake pads and rotors.  Finished in Bright White over Agate and Quartz leather, the car is powered by a 3.5-liter V6 paired with a four-speed automatic transaxle. Equipment includes lower body-side cladding, fog lights, traction control, and a theft alarm. The cabin is outfitted with automatic climate control, eight-way power-adjustable front seats, power windows and door locks, an Infinity sound system, and a cassette stereo. This Vision TSi shows 29k miles and is offered at no reserve with a window sticker, literature, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The car is finished in Bright White with gray lower cladding. Exterior details include fog lights and body-color mirrors, door handles, and side moldings. The lower cladding is said to have been repainted under current ownership.

The 16″ alloy wheels are wrapped in 225/60 Douglas All Season tires that were installed in 2022. The car rides on a four-wheel independent suspension, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel anti-lock disc brakes. The selling dealer is said to have replaced the front brake pads and rotors.

The eight-way power-adjustable front bucket seats and rear bench are upholstered in Agate and Quartz leather. Amenities include cruise control, automatic climate control, a theft alarm, an Infinity sound system, and a cassette stereo. The air conditioning is said to have been recharged since 2021. The passenger airbag cover is warped.
The two-spoke airbag steering wheel frames a 120-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and supplementary gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The six-digit mechanical odometer shows 29k miles.

The 3.5-liter SOHC V6 was factory rated at 214 horsepower and 221 lb-ft of torque. Work since 2021 is said to have consisted of replacing the timing belt, water pump, radiator hoses, and serpentine belt and performing an oil change. The car most recently passed a Smog Check in August 2024.
Power is delivered to the front wheels via a four-speed automatic transaxle.
The window sticker shows equipped options and a total price of $25,578.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage and lists vehicle history in California.
The vehicle is registered as Planned Non-operation in the state of California.

This 2008 Mercedes-Benz CLK63 AMG Black Series is finished in Arctic White over black Nappa leather and is powered by a 6.2-liter M156 V8 paired with a seven-speed automatic transmission. The car has spent time registered in Arizona, Florida, and Montana, and it now has 8k miles. Equipment includes a limited-slip differential, 19″ AMG multi-spoke wheels, an AMG adjustable coil-over suspension, bi-xenon headlights, carbon-fiber trim, Keyless-Go, and a Harman Kardon sound system. Recently acquired by the selling dealer, this CLK63 AMG Black Series is now offered in Florida with a window sticker, a VMI report, manufacturer’s literature, service records, a car cover, a battery tender, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Montana title.

DTM-inspired flared fenders, carbon-fiber-reinforced front and rear aprons, and a carbon-fiber decklid spoiler were added to the CLK63 Black Series. This example is finished in Arctic White (650) and features bi-xenon headlights with Active Curve Illumination as well as heated side mirrors, fender vents, and quad polished exhaust outlets. Clear paint protection film covers the front bumper cover, hood, fenders, and rear wheel arches, and the selling dealer notes chips in the finish. Photos of paint meter readings are provided in the gallery below.

The 19″ AMG multi-spoke alloy wheels are mounted with Continental tires installed in June 2024. Adjustable coilovers and an AMG Electronic Stability Program (ESP) were standard. Stopping power is provided by multi-piston AMG-branded calipers over cross-drilled and slotted rotors at all four corners.

The cockpit features bolstered bucket seats trimmed in black Nappa leather along with a color-coordinated dashboard, door panels, and carpets. The rear seats were deleted in Black Series models, and appointments include aluminum and carbon-fiber trim, Keyless-Go, dual-zone automatic climate control, cruise control, a Harman Kardon LOGIC7 sound system, and COMAND infotainment with navigation. The carbon-fiber center console storage lid was repaired in September 2023 and the air-conditioning system was recharged in June 2024.

The flat-bottom leather-wrapped AMG steering wheel is equipped with paddle shifters and frames a 200-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, an analog clock, and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 8k miles.

The hand-assembled 6.2-liter M156 V8 was factory rated at 500 horsepower and 465 lb-ft of torque. Power is sent to the rear wheels through an AMG Speedshift seven-speed automatic transmission and a limited-slip differential. Work in September 2023 included changing the engine oil and transmission and differential fluids as well as replacing the air intake pipe and air filters.

The window sticker notes initial delivery to Sigma Motors in Chandler, Arizona, and lists factory equipment, colors, options, and a total retail price of $138,375. A car cover, a VMI report, a battery tender, manufacturer’s literature, and service records are also included in the sale.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 2007 Saturn Sky was modified in 2008 by Mallett Performance Cars of Berea, Ohio. Work included installing a 7.0-liter LS7 V8 with ported cylinder heads, long-tube exhaust headers, and a custom-grind camshaft as well as a Tremec T56 six-speed manual transmission, a LUK Pro Gold clutch, a big brake kit, 18″ Forgeline wheels, Penske coilover suspension, a Corsa Performance exhaust system, custom interior components, flared rear quarter panels, and a heavy-duty differential, axle shafts, and sway bars. Finished in Black Onyx over black leather upholstery with alligator inserts the car is further equipped with a manually retractable black convertible soft top, fog lights, a rear spoiler, air conditioning, cruise control, and a Kenwood touchscreen infotainment system. The seller purchased the car in 2017 and has since added approximately 4k of the 21k miles. This modified Sky is now offered with Mallett Performance Cars invoices and a clean Illinois title in the seller’s name.

The Sky was built as a twin to the Pontiac Solstice, with both vehicles riding on the General Motors Kappa platform. This example is finished in Black Onyx and features a manually retractable black convertible soft top in addition to a front-hinged hood, bright hood vent trim, fog lights, a rear spoiler, and a polished aluminum exhaust outlet. Mallett modifications include functional front fender vents and fabricated flared rear quarter panels. There is staining on the soft top and there are scratches in the paint. A 2007 Carfax report entry notes minor damage resulting from a front-end collision with another vehicle.

Black Forgeline wheels are mounted with Continental Extreme Contact Sport tires measuring 275/30 up front and 325/30 out back, that were installed recently. This example is fitted with Mallett’s big brake kit, which added 13″ slotted rotors, SSBC calipers with Mallett-branded covers, and front brake ducting. Suspension modifications include adjustable Penske coilovers and aftermarket front and rear sway bars.

The bucket seats were reupholstered in black leather with alligator pattern inserts and feature Mallett-embroidered headrests. Interior appointments include stainless-steel pedal covers, metallic door sill covers, power windows, air conditioning, cruise control, and a Kenwood touchscreen infotainment system.

The leather-wrapped multifunction steering wheel fronts a 140-mph speedometer, an 8k-rpm tachometer, and a fuel-level gauge. The digital odometer indicates 21k miles, approximately 4k of which were added under current ownership.

The 7.0-liter LS7 V8 was installed by Mallett Performance Cars and is modified with an upgraded camshaft, ported cylinder heads, an aluminum radiator, carbon fiber ignition covers, and long-tube exhaust headers.

Power is routed to the rear wheels through a Tremec six-speed manual transmission and an iron 8.8″ rear center section with 3.73:1 gears. A LUK Pro Gold clutch, an upgrade shift fork, and a custom driveshaft and half shafts have been fitted.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage report.
The Illinois title lists a “Corrected” remark.

This 1986 Suzuki RG500 Gamma was acquired new by the seller who has ridden it approximately 18k kilometers (~11k miles). It has been modified with a Lance Gamma clutch, a Fox shock with a ride-height adjuster, carbon valves, and a shift shaft support, and it has been repainted in white with blue with red graphics and is powered by a 498cc two-stroke square-four paired with a six-speed transmission. Additional equipment includes an aluminum twin-spar frame, a four-into-four expansion -chamber exhaust system, triple disc brakes, Enkei wheels, clip-on handlebars, and rear-set foot controls. This RG500 is now offered in Canada with spare parts, an owner’s manual, a bike cover, and an Ontario registration in the seller’s name.

The fully-faired bodywork was refinished in white, and the blue and red graphics were replaced before the bodywork was clear-coated. A number of components have been powder-coated. Details include a rectangular headlight, NACA ducts, a 5.8-gallon fuel tank, a removable rear cowl, a side stand, rear-set foot controls, and fairing-mounted mirrors and indicators. The lower nose cone has a crack.

Black-finished Enkei six-spoke wheels measuring 16″ up front and 17″ out back are mounted with Metzeler tires. Braking is handled by dual discs with four-piston calipers up front as well as a single disc with a twin-piston caliper out back. Suspension consists of a refurbished telescopic fork with an anti-dive function as well as a Fox monoshock and a ride-height adjuster mounted to the boxed aluminum swingarm.

Clip-on handlebars are mounted below the top triple clamp and frame a 260-km/h speedometer, a tachometer with a 10k-rpm redline, and a coolant temperature gauge as well as a bank of indicator lights. The five-digit odometer shows 18k kilometers (~11k miles), all of which have been ridden by the seller.

The liquid-cooled 498cc two-stroke square-four factory-rated output was 95 horsepower and it features a kick starter, carbon rotary disc valves, and two crankshafts geared to a central pilot shaft as well as a four-into-four expansion-chamber exhaust system that features Suzuki’s Automatic Exhaust Control (SAEC) system and two under-tail outlets. The exhaust system has been ceramic-coated, and the spark plugs and battery were replaced in 2023.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a Lance Gamma wet clutch, a six-speed transmission, and a drive chain. The transmission oil was changed in 2023.

This 1973 BMW 3.0CS was originally delivered to Georgia Pacific Motors of Victoria, British Columbia, Canada, and was acquired by the seller and their sister in 1984 before being stored in 1990. The car is finished in Baikal Metallic over blue cloth and is powered by a 3.0-liter M30 inline-six linked with a four-speed manual transmission. Equipment includes a sliding steel sunroof, 14″ light metal wheels, power-operated windows, a cassette stereo, and a heater. This E9 is now offered as a non-running project in Canada at no reserve with the owner’s manual, service records, spare parts, and British Columbia registration in the names of the seller and their sister.

The car came finished from the factory in Baikal Metallic (42) and was repainted in the early 1980s, at which time rust remediation was performed on the firewall, front shock towers and fenders, and right front floor. Exterior features include a sliding steel sunroof, dual side mirrors, bright window trim, and chrome-finished bumpers with rubber impact strips. A replacement windshield and a right mirror were installed in the mid-1980s. The antenna is missing and the seller notes prior accident damage behind the front bumper. Rust is visible around the fenders, rear quarter panels, passenger-side rocker panel, trunk lid, and lower doors.

The 14″ light metal wheels are mounted with older 205/70 BFGoodrich Comp T/A tires up front and 195/70 Toyo Radial Snow & Rally tires out back. Stopping power is provided by discs at all four corners.

The cabin houses front bucket seats and contoured rear seats trimmed in blue cloth with vinyl sides and backs. Interior appointments include front seat head restraints, a Concord cassette stereo, power-operated windows, a heated rear window, Coco floor mats, a Momo shift knob, and a heater. There are tears on the driver’s seat and door panels, an area of the stereo housing has broken off, the passenger vent window does not close all the way, and the lower right corner of the windshield is delaminating.

The three-spoke steering wheel fronts a 150-mph speedometer, a tachometer, an analog clock, and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The five-digit odometer shows 85k miles, approximately 3,200 of which were added under current ownership.
The 3.0-liter M30 inline-six was fitted with a replacement cylinder head in 1984 and is linked with a four-speed manual transmission. The car was last driven in 1990 and no longer runs.
Additional underbody photos are provided in the gallery.
The vehicle does not have a title and is being sold on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada.

This 1997 Lexus LX450 is powered by a 4.5-liter inline-six linked with a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case, and it has been modified with an Old Man Emu suspension lift kit, a Prinsu roof rack, and an ARB front bumper with a winch and auxiliary LED lights. It is finished in Dark Emerald Pearl over Ivory leather and features 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels, a powered sunroof, power-adjustable front seats, three rows of seating, automatic climate control, and a Pioneer CD stereo. Acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, this 80-Series LX450 shows 217k miles and is now offered at no reserve with an owner’s manual, two keys, one key fob, spare parts, a Carfax report, and a clean New Jersey title.

The truck is finished in Dark Emerald Pearl with gray lower cladding and features a Prinsu roof rack and an ARB front bumper equipped with a Traveller winch and LED auxiliary lights. Additional details include a powered sunroof, sliding rear windows, tubular side steps, and a rear window wiper. The Carfax report lists accidents reported in December 2003, January 2005, and September 2013 that resulted in damage to the front and right side of the vehicle. Scuffs are present on the right side of the front bumper, bubbling paint is noted below the rear glass, scratches are shown on the rear bumper, and there are scrapes and a dent on the left-rear door. Additional photos of fading paint on the roof and exterior imperfections are viewable in the gallery below.

The truck rides on a modified suspension with an Old Man Emu lift kit and dampers as well as an Old Man Emu steering stabilizer. The 16″ five-spoke alloy wheels wear 295/75 BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A K02 tires, and a full-size spare is mounted to an under-chassis carrier. Braking is handled by ventilated discs at each corner. Corrosion is shown on the wheels.

The seating surfaces are upholstered in Ivory leather, while wood veneers accent the door panels and center console. Interior amenities include power-adjustable front seats, side-folding third-row jump seats, a Pioneer CD stereo, cruise control, and automatic climate control. There are splits and wear on the driver’s seat and second-row bench, the nets on the back of the front seats are stretched, there is a crack on the top of the dashboard above the instrument cluster, and wear is shown on the left-rear door panel.

A four-spoke leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a 130-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for oil pressure, coolant temperature, voltage, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 217k miles, a handful of which were added under current ownership. There is wear on the top of the steering wheel.
The 4.5L 1FZ-FE inline-six features electronic fuel injection and was factory rated at 212 horsepower and 275 lb-ft of torque. An oil change was performed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a four-speed automatic transmission and a dual-range transfer case. Areas of rust are present on portions of the underside.
The Carfax report lists the aforementioned accidents.

This 2004 Porsche 911 Carrera 4S cabriolet is a non-running project whose 3.6-liter flat-six suffered an undiagnosed failure in November 2023. Finished in Carrara White over Metropol Blue full leather, the car is equipped with a six-speed manual transaxle, an all-wheel-drive system, a speed-activated rear spoiler, a Metropol Blue soft top, 18″ GT3 alloy wheels, xenon headlights, power-adjustable heated front seats, a Bose audio system, and automatic climate control. This 996 C4S cabriolet project has 85k miles and is now offered by the selling dealer at no reserve in Canada with service records and British Columbia registration.

The car is finished in Carrara White (LB9A) and features a Metropol Blue convertible soft top. It is fitted with xenon headlights, headlamp washers, a speed-activated rear spoiler, integrated fog lights, heated mirrors, and polished exhaust outlets. The Carfax report lists an accident in a May 2012 entry. The car was declared a total loss in Canada in January 2023, and invoices shown in the gallery below detail approximately C$20k in repairs performed at that time.

The 18″ GT3 alloy wheels show finish imperfections and are mounted with Michelin Pilot Sport tires. The car is equipped with Porsche Stability Management (PSM) and an Automatic Brake Differential (ABD). Braking is from red calipers over ventilated and cross-drilled rotors at all four corners.

The Metropol Blue full leather interior features heated power-adjustable seats with supple center inserts. Options include a Bose sound system, self-dimming mirrors, and rain-sensing wipers, and the cabin is also equipped with automatic climate control, cruise control, and a Becker-Porsche CDR23 head unit.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel frames a central tachometer with a 7,200-rpm redline and a 200-mph speedometer as well as gauges for coolant temperature, oil pressure, voltage, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 85k miles.

The 3.6-liter flat-six experienced a failure in November 2023. It does not run, and it does not turn over smoothly. The camshaft plugs, clutch, flywheel, and intermediate shaft cover have been removed prior to the car’s acquisition by the selling dealer, who notes that further disassembly is required for diagnosis. The IMS bearing was replaced in January 2021, and related invoices are shown in the gallery below.
