Power is sent to all four wheels through a six-speed manual transaxle. Corrosion is noted underneath the car, including in the right rocker panel area.
Decoding the option sticker reveals information including:
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned May 2012 accident and January 2023 total loss declaration.
The vehicle is being offered on its British Columbia registration, which serves as the ownership document in British Columbia, Canada.

This 2015 MV Agusta Brutale 800 Dragster RR is powered by a 798cc DOHC triple linked to a six-speed transmission and is finished in red and white with carbon-fiber accents. Equipment includes white, black, and red wire-spoke wheels, a Tail Tidy license plate bracket, a red Marzocchi fork, triple Brembo disc brakes with ABS, bar-end mirrors, and a quick-release fuel filler cap. This Brutale 800 Dragster RR is now offered at no reserve by the selling dealer in Florida with removed parts, manufacturer’s literature, and a clean Ohio title.

The 4.4 gallon fuel tank is finished in red and white and the bike also features a black-finished steel trellis frame, a flyscreen, a quick-release fuel filler cap, and a side stand as well as a carbon-fiber exhaust heat shield, engine covers, fenders, and body panels.

White 17″ rims laced with black spokes and red-anodized hubs and nipples are mounted with 120/70 front and 180/55 rear Pirelli Rosso II tires. Adjustable suspension consists of an inverted 43mm Marzocchi fork as well as a progressive Sachs monoshock mounted to a single-sided aluminum alloy swingarm. ABS braking is provided by a pair of Brembo radial four-piston calipers mounted over 320mm floating drilled discs up front along with a two-piston caliper mounted over a single disc at the rear. The brake fluid was flushed in preparation for the sale.

Aluminum individual handlebars feature bar-end mirrors. A monochrome LCD screen displays a 17k-rpm bar-style tachometer and readouts for speed, gear, engine-map selection, coolant temperature, and time of day. The digital odometer indicates 2,200 miles, approximately 100 of which were ridden under current ownership.

The liquid-cooled 798cc DOHC inline-three features Mikuni electronic fuel injection and was factory rated at 138 horsepower and 63 lb-ft of torque. The battery was replaced and the oil changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is sent to the rear wheel through a six-speed transmission with MV Electronically Assisted Shift (EAS).
Removed parts are included in the sale along with manufacturer’s literature.

This 1953 Silver Dome travel trailer is a double-axle model that is finished in tan and burgundy. A refurbishment under prior ownership is said to have involved replacing the flooring, propane system, plumbing, and electrical system as well as repainting the body and installing a water heater, refrigerator, and microwave oven. The floor plan features a forward lounge area, a kitchenette, a bathroom, and an unfurnished rear bedroom. Amenities include wood paneling, a sink, a range, hinged windows, and overhead lighting. This Silver Dome travel trailer was acquired by the seller in 2016 and is now offered at no reserve with a Utah title in the seller’s name.

Silver Dome began offering travel trailers in 1932, and production continued until 1961. The body of this example was repaired and refinished in tan and burgundy under prior ownership. Details include two entry doors with porthole windows, boarding steps, LED taillights, and hinged windows. The coating on the roof is perforated and has deteriorated, and the seller notes dents in the trim and bodywork.

Steel wagon-style wheels are painted red and mounted with Hi Run black wall tires. Stopping power is from electrically activated drum brakes, and equipment includes a tongue jack, a seven-pin trailering harness, and dual tongue-mounted propane tanks. The trailer measures approximately 25′ long and is configured as a park model with connections for water, waste disposal, and electrical service.

The interior is outfitted with varnished wood paneling, bamboo flooring, wall sconces, and residential-style power outlets. The forward lounge area houses a daybed with a floral cover, two folding tables, corner shelves, and an overhead storage cubby. The kitchenette is equipped a refrigerator, a microwave oven, and a four-burner propane range in addition to a double-basin sink, a slide-out work surface, overhead cabinets, and under-cabinet drawers. The wood trim is separating from the paneling in places, and water damage from a roof leak is visible in the lounge area on the floor, on the ceiling, and on a cabinet top. The seller recommends replacing the daybed mattress.

The unfurnished sleeping area is located at the rear and has a dedicated exterior entry door, hinged windows, a mirror, and overhead storage. The adjacent bathroom has a toilet room with a Dometic commode as well as a wet room with a porcelain sink and a shower.
Rust is visible on the underside, and one of the belly panels has separated from the underbody. Additional photos can be viewed in the gallery below.
The current Utah title is listed as a duplicate.

This 1974 Volkswagen Thing is powered by an air-cooled 2,007cc flat-four that utilizes an aftermarket engine case modified for a full-flow oiling system and fitted with a 78mm crankshaft, 90.5 mm pistons and cylinders, an Engle camshaft, dual Weber carburetors, a Bosch 009 points-type distributor, high-flow heater boxes, and a modified A-1 Sidewinder exhaust system. It was acquired by the current owner out of Oregon and brought to California where it received over $40k in service before spending approximately a year in Hawaii. Additional details include 15″ aftermarket steel wheels, BFGoodrich All-Terrain tires, drum brakes, a four-speed manual transaxle, a chromoly lightweight flywheel, a 1700-lb pressure plate, and a 200mm clutch disc in addition to a hood rack, running boards, a receiver hitch, a fold-down windshield, removable doors, perforated rubber floor mats, duckboards, a Custom AutoSound head unit, and Memphis Audio speakers. This Type 181 is now offered on behalf of the current owner at no reserve in California with service records and a clean Hawaii title.

The body is finished in beige with a black convertible soft top and removable side curtains. Exterior details include a hood rack, running boards, and a receiver hitch in addition to a fold-down windshield, fender-mounted turn signals, and removable doors. The tires rub the front fenders under hard braking.

Aftermarket 15″ steel wheels have been powder-coated black and are mounted with 215/75 BFGoodrich All-Terrain T/A KO2 tires. The brake drums were machined and the master cylinder, wheel cylinders, hoses, shoes, and wheel bearings were replaced in February 2023.

The front bucket seats and folding rear seats are trimmed in black vinyl upholstery. Interior elements include perforated rubber floor mats, duckboards, lap belts, and cupholders mounted to the ashtray receptacle. The audio system is reported to consist of a Custom AutoSound head unit linked to Memphis Audio speakers.

The four-spoke steering wheel has been wrapped in leather and frames a 100-mph speedometer with an inset fuel-level gauge, while readouts for oil pressure and temperature are housed in a custom-fabricated pod in the center of the dashboard. The five-digit mechanical odometer shows 54k miles, approximately 1k of which have been added under current ownership.

The air-cooled 2007cc flat-four was built by Wolfgang International in November 2021 using a replacement aftermarket magnesium engine case modified for a full-flow oiling system and clearanced for a 78mm stroker crankshaft. Additional engine details include 90.5mm pistons and cylinders, EMPI GTV-2 40×35.5 cylinder heads, an Engle W110 camshaft, a Bosch 009 points-type distributor, and dual Weber 40 IDF carburetors. In February 2023 the engine was removed and steam cleaned, the tins were powder-coated, the carburetor linkage was modified, and the oil cooler was replaced. Additional work performed at that time included installing a battery tender and adjusting the valves. Photos of engine compression readings are displayed in the gallery.

Power is delivered to the rear wheels through a four-speed manual transaxle with a chromoly lightweight flywheel, a 1700-lb pressure plate, and a 200mm clutch disc. The gear oil was replaced in February 2023 along with the installation of high-flow heater boxes and modification of the A-1 Sidewinder exhaust system.
listing_details: Black Convertible Soft Top & Side Curtains

description: This 1999 Toyota Corolla VE sedan remained registered in California with its original owner until it was acquired by the selling dealer in 2024, and it now has 22k miles. Finished in Sandrift Metallic over gray cloth, the car is powered by a 1.8-liter inline-four paired with a three-speed automatic transaxle. Equipment includes 14″ steel wheels, front disc brakes, aftermarket window tint film, air conditioning, a digital clock, and an AM/FM/cassette stereo. This Corolla is now offered at no reserve by the selling dealer with manufacturer’s literature, a clean Carfax report, and a clean California title.

The car is finished in Sandrift Metallic (3M5) and features black mirror caps and door handles. Additional details include halogen headlights, aftermarket window tint film, and a retractable antenna mounted on the A-pillar.
Silver-finished 14″ steel wheels were mounted with 185/65 Advanta ER-800 tires under current ownership. Braking is handled by front discs and rear drums.

The front bucket seats and rear bench seat are upholstered in gray cloth with patterned inserts are joined by a color-coordinated dashboard and door panels. Corolla-branded floor mats line the footwells, and appointments include air conditioning, a dash-mounted digital clock, a rear window defroster, and an AM/FM/cassette stereo.
The four-spoke steering wheel frames a 110-mph speedometer and gauges for fuel level and coolant temperature. The digital odometer indicates 22k miles.
The 1.8L 16-valve inline-four was factory rated at 120 horsepower and 122 lb-ft of torque. The oil was changed in preparation for the sale.
Power is delivered to the front wheels via a three-speed automatic transaxle.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage.

This 1994 Porsche 911 Turbo S 3.6 was produced in January 1994 and is one of 39 examples delivered in the US market with the factory X85 Flachbau (flat nose) option, which featured a revised front fascia and pop-up headlamps similar to the contemporary 968. Finished in Midnight Blue Metallic over Cobalt leather and patterned cloth upholstery, the car is powered by a turbocharged 3.6-liter flat-six mated to a five-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. It rides on polished 18″ Speedline wheels and is further equipped with an electric sliding roof, a rear spoiler, heated and power-adjustable front seats, Dark Rootwood interior trim, and a factory cassette stereo. This 911 Turbo S Flachbau is now offered by the selling dealer in New York State with a Porsche Certificate of Authenticity and a rebuilt Indiana title.

Commanding a $60k premium over the $99k base price for the Turbo 3.6 in 1994, the X85 flat nose option featured a front fascia and pop-up headlamps similar to the contemporary 968, along with RS-style front air inlets, rear fender air intakes, and dual paired exhaust tips. This example left the factory finished in Midnight Blue Metallic (F8) and is equipped with an electric sliding sunroof, a rear window wiper, and a body-colored rear spoiler. The Carfax report notes a salvage title issued in 2002, a total loss damage report in 2009, and severe damage reported in 2013. According to the seller, the aforementioned reports are related to a collision that occurred in 2002 and resulted in replacement of the hood, front bumper cover, front-left fender, and left side skirt, as well as a repaint of the body apart from the rear decklid.

Polished 18” Speedline Cup wheels with Turbo-script center caps are wrapped in staggered-width Michelin Pilot Sport Cup tires. A spacesaver spare is stored in the front trunk compartment. Braking is provided by cross-drilled rotors and red-finished calipers with white Porsche script at all four corners.

The cabin houses heated and power-adjustable front seats trimmed in Cobalt Blue leather with patterned inserts that extend to the rear jump seats. Dark Rootwood trim accents the dash, parking brake handle, and shift knob, while blue carpets line the footwells. Porsche crests adorn the front headrests, and additional amenities include air conditioning, power windows, and a factory cassette stereo.

The four-spoke airbag steering wheel is wrapped in blue leather and frames a central tachometer, a 180-mph speedometer, combination gauges, and an analog clock, while a boost gauge sits ahead of the shifter. The six-digit odometer shows 30k miles, approximately 350 of which were added by the selling dealer.

The 3.6-liter M64/50 flat-six came equipped with the X88 power kit from the factory, which added modified cylinder heads and camshafts, altered timing, larger-capacity fuel injectors, and a larger turbocharger and intercooler. Output was rated at 380 horsepower and 384 lb-ft of torque when new.

Power is sent to the rear wheels through a G50/52 five-speed manual transaxle and a limited-slip differential. Turbo S models were fitted with a stronger flywheel and clutch compared to the contemporary Turbo. A quad-exit exhaust system with modified heat exchangers was also standard on the Turbo S.
The Porsche Certificate of Authenticity lists a production completion date in January 1994 and notes the factory colors and equipment.
The Carfax report shows the aforementioned damage reports and total loss declaration.
The Indiana title lists a Rebuilt Vehicle brand.
listing_details: One of 39 US-Spec X85 Flachbau Models

description: This 1992 Lamborghini Diablo was sold new in California and remained with the first owner for over 20 years before being sold to the second owner in 2013 and acquired by the current owner in 2015. The car is finished in Nero and features 17″ OZ Racing wheels, retractable headlights, scissor doors, and a rear wing. Inside, the fixed-back bucket seats are trimmed in black leather and accompanied by a gated shifter, automatic climate control, and an Alpine stereo linked to a CD changer. Power is supplied by a 5.7-liter V12 linked with a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential, and test pipes have been installed in place of the catalytic converters. Now showing 34k kilometers (~21k miles), this Diablo is offered on dealer consignment in Sheridan, Colorado, with an owner’s manual, a tool kit, one vehicle key, the removed catalytic converters, and a clean Colorado title.

The Marcello Gandini-designed Diablo debuted in January 1990 and featured composite and aluminum bodywork. This example is finished in Nero and has been repainted. Details include retractable headlights as well as fog lights, scissor doors, a vented engine cover, a rear wing, and quad exhaust outlets. The selling dealer notes that the finish on the doors does not match the rest of the car.

The 17″ OZ Racing multi-piece alloy wheels were mounted with 245/40 front and 335/35 rear Pirelli P-Zero Asimmetrico tires in May 2023. Stopping power is provided by ventilated disc brakes at each corner.

The cockpit houses fixed-back bucket seats trimmed in black leather, which extends to the dash and doors. An Alpine cassette stereo is linked to a CD changer, and further amenities include automatic climate control as well as power windows, mirrors, and door locks. The selling dealer notes that the leather on the dash has shrunk.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel wears an embossed Raging Bull insignia and is paired with a gated shifter. VDO instrumentation consists of a 220-mph speedometer and a tachometer with a 7,500-rpm redline as well as auxiliary gauges for oil pressure, oil temperature, coolant temperature, fuel level, and voltage. The six-digit odometer shows 34k kilometers, approximately 3k of which have been added under current ownership.

The 5.7-liter V12 was factory rated at 485 horsepower and 428 lb-ft of torque. Power is routed to the rear wheels via a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. The engine was removed in order to service the clutch fork in 2014. Work in 2023 involved replacing the clutch slave cylinder, battery, radiator fan blade, and coolant hoses along with the clutch fluid, engine oil, and coolant.
Aftermarket test pipes have been installed in place of the removed catalytic converters, which will accompany the car.
A tool kit and other accessories are also included in the sale along with an owner’s manual and one vehicle key.
The Carfax report notes a lien on the car, though the Colorado title indicates that the lien was released in March 2020.

This 1989 Lamborghini Countach is one of approximately 658 examples of the 25th Anniversary variant built during a three-year production run and is finished in Nero Tenebre over Champagne leather. Power is from a 5.2-liter quad-cam V12 equipped with CIS fuel injection and mated to a five-speed manual gearbox. Equipment includes a limited-slip differential, scissor doors, a rear wing, fog lights, 15″ OZ Racing multi-piece wheels, a gated shifter, an Alpine CD stereo, and electronic climate control. The car was built in April 1989 and it was listed on BaT in March 2019 before being acquired by the Arizona-based selling dealer in 2023. This Countach shows 10k kilometers (~6,200 miles) and is offered with manufacturer’s literature, service records, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Arizona title.

Originally penned by Marcello Gandini, the Countach’s bodywork was updated by Horacio Pagani for the 25th Anniversary edition that debuted in 1988. This US-market example was built in April 1989 and is finished in Nero Tenebre. A rest-of-world front bumper has been fitted, and there are cracks on the rear bumper cover as well as stone chips on the front bumper and side rocker panels. Imperfections are presented in the gallery below.

OZ Racing 15″ multi-piece alloy wheels are mounted with 225/50 front and 345/35 rear Pirelli P Zero tires. The Countach features a fully independent suspension with coil springs and telescopic shock absorbers, and stopping power is provided by four-wheel ventilated disc brakes. The brake lines were replaced in 2016 and the fluid was most recently flushed in November 2023.

The power-adjustable bucket seats are upholstered in Champagne leather with black piping. Interior appointments include a gated shifter, an Alpine CD stereo, electronic climate control, and power windows. The right door strut and the door seals were replaced and the dash was reupholstered in November 2023, after which the rear decklid upholstery was replaced. The driver seat motor and seat belt reels were replaced in preparation for the sale, and the passenger window switch was repaired.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel fronts a 320-km/h speedometer and a tachometer with a 7,500-rpm redline along with gauges for voltage, oil temperature, oil pressure, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The six-digit odometer shows 10k kilometers (~6,200 miles).

The Bizzarrini-designed 5.2-liter V12 features a 60° cylinder bank angle, four valves per cylinder, and Bosch K-Jetronic fuel injection. Revised intakes on the 25th Anniversary Countach allowed for the radiators to be mounted vertically for improved cooling. Output was factory rated at 420 horsepower and 369 lb-ft of torque, which is sent to the rear wheels through a five-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip differential. A $49k engine-out service in September 2016 involved overhauling the fuel injection system, refurbishing the engine externals, and replacing the hoses, mounts, and gaskets as well as installing a Kevlar clutch. Work since November 2023 included replacing the battery, expansion tank cap, fuel pump fuse, and spark plug boots along with changing the engine, transmission, and differential oils. Compression test results are presented in the gallery.
Additional underside photos are shown in the gallery.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 2009 Alfa Romeo 8C is one of a planned 500 Spiders built between 2008 and 2010 and one of approximately 35 examples designated for the US market. The car is powered by a 4.7-liter F136 V8 mated to a six-speed semi-automatic transaxle with a limited-slip differential, and it is finished in Rosso Alfa over black leather upholstery. Equipment includes cloverleaf-style 20” alloy wheels, ceramic-composite brakes, bi-xenon headlights, a power-operated black soft top, and a carbon-fiber windshield frame along with carbon-fiber sport seats, a Becker CD stereo, and dual-zone automatic climate control. The car was previously offered on BaT in March 2022 and December 2022, and was acquired by the selling dealer in 2023. Now with 2,200 miles, this 8C Spider is offered with manufacturer’s literature, a trickle charger, tools, a clean Carfax report, and a clean Florida title.

Designed by Wolfgang Egger at Centro Stile Alfa Romeo, the production 8C Competizione was introduced at the 2006 Paris Motor Show. It revived the 8C name originally used for Alfa Romeo’s eight-cylinder racing cars of the 1930s and featured styling cues from the company’s post-war sporting cars across its carbon-fiber body panels, which are supported by a steel space frame. The 8C Spider was unveiled at the 2008 Geneva Motor Show.

This example is finished in Rosso Alfa and features a power-operated black soft top, bi-xenon headlights, fog lights, fender vents,  a carbon-fiber windshield frame, and quad exhaust outlets. The front bumper was repaired and refinished in 2024, at which time the carbon-fiber trim and hood latch were also repaired.

The cloverleaf-style 20” alloy wheels are mounted with 245/35 front and 285/35 rear Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires. Stopping power is provided by black Alfa Romeo–branded Brembo calipers over cross-drilled carbon-ceramic rotors at all four corners.

The cockpit features carbon-fiber seats trimmed in black leather with red stitching and basketweave accents, which extend to the matching door panels. The dashboard and center console feature brushed aluminum and carbon-fiber trim, and additional appointments include dual-zone climate control, a Becker CD stereo, and dual roll hoops. The sticky buttons were refinished in March 2024.

The leather-wrapped steering wheel features aluminum spokes ahead of paddle shifters, and the center console wears a Limited Edition badge. Instrumentation consists of a tachometer with a 7,500-rpm redline accompanied by a 210-mph speedometer and digital readouts for oil temperature, coolant temperature, and fuel level. The digital odometer indicates 2,200 miles.

Designed by Ferrari and Maserati, the 4.7-liter F136 YC V8 featured a 90° bank angle and a cross-plane crankshaft. It produced 444 horsepower at 7,000 rpm and 354 lb-ft of torque at 4,750 rpm when new. The head cover, spark plug, and solenoid gaskets were replaced along with the battery in preparation for the sale.

Power is sent to the rear wheels via a six-speed semi-automatic transaxle that can be operated in five different modes of automatic or paddle-controlled shifting. A limited-slip differential was standard.
The Carfax report shows no accidents or other damage.

This 2003 Lamborghini Murciélago is finished in Nero Aldebaran over Nero Perseus leather and is powered by a 6.2-liter V12 that drives all four wheels through a six-speed manual transmission. Now showing 23k miles, the car is equipped with a limited-slip rear differential, 18″ Speedline Corse alloy wheels, a front-axle lift system, a speed-activated rear spoiler, xenon headlights, automatically deploying rear intakes, automatic climate control, and a CD stereo. The car was sold new by Platinum Motors, LLC of Santa Ana, California, and spent time in Europe and Canada before being brought back to the US in 2024. This Murciélago is now offered in New York by a retail dealership in Canada with a window sticker, the owner’s manual, service records, a Carfax report, and an Ohio title.

The Murciélago was designed by Luc Donckerwolke and was publicly unveiled in 2001 at the Frankfurt Motor Show as the replacement for the Diablo. This example is finished in Nero Aldebaran and features a speed-activated rear spoiler, a pantograph windshield wiper, xenon headlights, scissor doors, rear fog lights, dual exhaust outlets, and automatically deploying rear intakes to aid in cooling. The front bumper was repainted in 2022.

Staggerd-width 18″ Speedline Corse alloy wheels are mounted with Pirelli P Zero tires measuring 235/35 up front and 335/30 out back. Stopping power is provided by Lamborghini script calipers fitted over cross-drilled two-piece rotors at each corner. The car is equipped with active dampers and a front-axle lift system.

The manually adjustable seats are trimmed in Nero Perseus leather, which extends to the dashboard, door panels, center console, and headliner. Interior elements include automatic climate control power windows, a gated shifter, and inboard shoulder restraints. Scratches are present on the center console and wear is visible on the driver’s seat boltsers and the soft-touch coating near the Kenwood head unit.

The leather-wrapped three-spoke steering wheel frames a 220-mph speedometer, a tachometer, and gauges for fuel level, coolant temperature, oil pressure, and oil temperature. The digital odometer indicates 23k miles, a handful of which have been added under current ownership.

The mid-mounted 6.2-liter V12 has been fitted with an aftermarket exhaust system. An oil change was performed in April 2022, the starter was replaced in November 2022, and fuel lines were replaced in April 2024.
Power is sent to all four wheels through a six-speed manual transmission and a limited-slip rear differential.
The window sticker lists initial delivery to Platinum Motors of Santa Ana, California, along with equipment, options, and a manufacturer’s suggested retail price of $281,100.
The Carfax report is free of accidents or other reported damage up to the most recent entry in May 2023. A gap in entries can be seen between May 2003 and July 2022.
